<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-AIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP GIULIANI AIDE LEAVING T BECOME A LAW PARTNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Randy Mastro deputy mayor who for the last five
years has served as both aggressor and peacemaker for Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, will resign next month to become a partner in the New
York office of a Los Angeles law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Mastro, 41, denied this weekend that internal politics or an
interest in elective office had played a role in his decision to
step down. He said he wants to spend more time with his wife, Dr.
Jonine Bernstein, and their 2-year-old daughter, Arianna, and to
rejoin his former law firm, Gibson, Dunn &AMP; Crutcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first love is the practice of law,'' he said. ``And now is
the right time to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, Dunn, with about 100 lawyers in its Park Avenue office,
is one of Manhattan's largest law firms. The Los Angeles-based firm
has a total of more than 600 lawyers, including 230 partners.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani will announce Mastro's resignation soon, perhaps as
early as Monday. ``The mayor enjoys a very close personal
friendship with Randy Mastro and understands that he's leaving for
family reasons,'' said Colleen Roche, the mayor's spokeswoman, who
recently announced that she, too, would soon leave the
administration. ``His departure creates a very big void which will
be difficult to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   In public, Mastro has often been the voice of the
administration, whether shouting over budget matters in televised
debates or standing in his office, baseball bat in hand, to explain
to reporters the details of the city's assault on the sex industry.
He was so identified with the city's mission to crush organized
crime _ in the Fulton Fish Market, at the San Gennaro Festival, and
in the private carting industry _ that for many months, he and his
family were accompanied by police bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   In private, he has been a key strategist, entrusted to negotiate
with elected officials, curry favor among unions and other special
interests, and persuade members of the Democrat-controlled City
Council to see things the mayor's way. A registered Democrat in a
Republican administration, he engendered suspicion among some
colleagues and loyalty among others.
</P>
<P>
   He has no clear successor as the deputy mayor for Operations,
responsible for day-to-day management of government and for
negotiating the city budget.
</P>
<P>
   Mastro began working for Giuliani more than a decade ago, as an
assistant U.S. attorney in the Southern District of New York, where
he specialized in organized crime. After several years in private
practice, he provided legal advice to Giuliani's campaign in 1993,
and then worked on the mayor-elect's transition team. When Giuliani
took office, he chose Mastro to be his chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   When the mayor's close friend, Peter Powers, resigned as first
deputy mayor in 1996, Giuliani made Mastro a deputy mayor _
although not first deputy mayor _ because, according to widespread
speculation, Mastro did not have the necessary political skills.
</P>
<P>
   Several people now say that assessment was way off mark. Fred
Jacobs, the chief counsel for Sheldon Silver, the Democratic
speaker of the State Assembly, said that he and Mastro had
negotiated several political compromises, even though their bosses
have a frosty relationship. ``Our closest moments have been when
our bosses have been firing the biggest missiles at each other,''
Jacobs said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
