<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-TEEN-DRIVING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS TURN OUT FOR FESTIVE EXPRESSION OF GAY PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MELISSA SCHMITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES -- Teen-agers across the San Fernando Valley are
scrambling to get their driver's permits before Wednesday, the day
California will dramatically change a rite of passage teens live
for -- obtaining a driver's license.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joining 21 other states across the country, California is
toughening teen driving laws in an attempt to cut roadway
fatalities caused by exuberant young drivers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Motor Vehicles, motorists 15 to
19 years old make up only 4 percent of California's drivers. But
that 4 percent was involved in 8.8 percent of all fatal collisions
in the state in 1996 and 9.9 percent of all injury collisions.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to slash the number of teen-agers dying due to
avoidable traffic collisions, the state is putting into effect a
new licensing program that will extend from 30 days to six months
the amount of time a 16- or 17-year-old driver will have to hold a
permit before obtaining a full-fledged license.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen and 17-year-olds who obtained their permits before
Wednesday are not affected by the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Those who fall under the new law will have to get in 50 hours of
supervised driving time, including 10 hours at night.
</P>
<P>
   For the first year they hold a driver's license, minor drivers
will have to be accompanied by a parent or guardian when driving
between midnight and 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most painful to the teen-ager, the law says teen
drivers cannot transport passengers under 20 years of age for the
first six months, unless supervised.
</P>
<P>
   That's a major bummer in the eyes of most teens, who see the
driver's license as their personal emancipation proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Koscielny, 16, of Saugus High School in suburban Santa
Clarita, is one of those not greeting the new laws with open arms,
even though she received her learner's permit in the 11th hour of
the July 1 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good that we have a little more time,'' Koscielny
said, referring to the 50 hours of training and the extended
learner's permit. As for the law prohibiting teens from driving
their friends around: ``I don't like that part,'' she said. ``I
don't think that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sally Reed, director of the California Department of Motor
Vehicles, said the restrictions are in place to keep young people
like Koscielny, and others driving on the road with them, safe
until they get their bearings behind the wheel of a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are common-sense restrictions that affect the times and
situations when teens are in the most danger,'' Reed said. ``They
make good sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Western Insurance Information Service, a nonprofit consumer
education organization, said a similar program in Canada proves
they make good sense. That program has been credited with a 55
percent reduction in fatalities involving 16-year-olds, a Western
Insurance spokesman said. The other 21 programs in the United
States are too new to evaluate.
</P>
<P>
   Judi Umeck of Santa Clarita is friends with Koscielny's mother.
And Umeck, like her friend, has worried for months about the safety
of her daughter on the road. The two women, like many others they
know, have their own rules for their driving daughters.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the alarming statistics of crashes and collisions
involving teen-age drivers are much more than numbers to mothers of
16-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Umeck's daughter has lost friends at the rate of one per year
for the last three years to traffic crashes, numbers that simply
hit too close to home.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three fatal crashes would have been directly
prevented by the new restrictions governing teen drivers. They
didn't occur during the restricted hours or with other young people
in the car. Nevertheless, to Umeck and her 16-year-old daughter,
they are a painful symbol of why restrictions are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they're doing something,'' said Umeck, who is on
staff at Providence High School in Burbank. ``It's fine to have
more restraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us have already implemented that anyway. My daughter
isn't allowed to take more than one friend at a time. When I see
five or six kids in a car with a teen driver at one time, it scares
me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Umeck's daughter Erin, 16, agrees with her mother _ to some
extent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways it's good,'' said Erin, who also got her license
just under the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people go out partying, but say you're coming home from a
party or the movies, and you're going straight home instead of out
cruising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point of my getting my license was so I could run
errands for my parents,'' she said. ``I'm a baby-sitter. And I take
this little girl to Magic Mountain. The new laws would be just like
having a permit instead of having a license.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have my license, it doesn't affect me,'' she said.
``I knew and that's why I took my classes over spring break.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to beat Wednesday's deadline, Erin also took her
driver's education through the DMV instead of school, where the
program takes place over the summer. ``When I finished I had just
turned 16. I practiced every chance I had,'' she said, explaining
the sense of urgency she felt.
</P>
<P>
   But the teen said she understands the need for the laws, as
frustrating as they are.
</P>
<P>
   When young people like her classmates die, it's a tragedy Erin
said she could live without. More so than living without the
privilege of driving her friends around.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I feel I kind of agree with them. I do think we
all need to understand the responsibility, and we shouldn't be
abusing it,'' Erin said. ``Accidents can happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
