<HEADLINE>
THAT'S THE TICKET _ A FREE HOUR WITH MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As tough as it was to get a seat at the Forum when
Magic Johnson played, the converse is true for scoring passes to
``The Magic Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of tickets to TV show tapings are given out all the
time to shoppers at Farmer's Market, next to the CBS' Television
City at 3rd Street and Fairfax in Hollywood. But one of the
toughest to !ital!get rid of on this particular day last week was
the big yellow admission cards to Magic Johnson's weeknight talk
show, taped up the street at the Paramount Studios.
</P>
<P>
   A typical sales pitch from the guy paid to hand these out went
like this:
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``Want a free ticket to a TV show?''
</P>
<P>
   Customer: ``Uh, OK, which one.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``How about The Magic Hour?''
</P>
<P>
   Customer: ``What else do you have?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``Howie Mandel... ''
</P>
<P>
   Customer: ``Jerry Springer?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``No, he doesn't tape his shows here.''
</P>
<P>
   Customer: (Walking away) ``No, I guess not.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``Not even Magic Johnson?''
</P>
<P>
   Customer: ``Well... do I have to use the pass today?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``It's good !ital!every day!''
</P>
<P>
   Customer: ``Can I have more to take some friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``You can take as many people as you like _ on this one
pass!''
</P>
<P>
   Customer: ``And it's free?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``I'm giving them out! Complementary!''
</P>
<P>
   Customer: ``Can I get Magic's autograph?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy: ``Like I said, the tickets are (begin ital)free(end
ital)!''
</P>
</TEXT>
