<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT YANKEES, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It took everything the Mets could muster to salvage
one game of their three-game series with the Yankees. And even
then, they needed an umpire to reverse a call to win.
</P>
<P>
   In the most bizarre moment of this weekend, pinch-hitter Luis
Lopez's fly ball to medium right field off Yankee reliever Ramiro
Mendoza with one out in the bottom of the ninth gave the Mets a 2-1
victory at Shea Stadium on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But for a moment it appeared that the Mets might have to go to
extra innings. When Paul O'Neill ran down Lopez's ball with runners
on first and third, making an over-the-shoulder catch, even he
thought the game was over. Carlos Baerga could have walked home
from third base with the winning run and O'Neill would have had no
chance. So O'Neill disgustedly responded with a no-look throw back
to the infield.
</P>
<P>
   But when Derek Jeter gathered in O'Neill's throw to the right of
second base, the Mets' Brian McRae _ who had been on first _ was
already past Jeter and almost on second base. Jeter turned and
quickly threw to first baseman Tino Martinez, who fumbled the ball
as he stumbled over first base, but then appeared to touch first
base with his bare hand, having possibly doubled McRae off with the
final out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Dreckman, the first base umpire, immediately ruled McRae
out. Mets Manager Bobby Valentine then rushed to the umpire to
argue. So did Baerga, all while the Yankees rushed off the field,
thinking they were headed for the 10th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Dreckman conferred with the home plate umpire, Frank
Pulli, who apparently ruled that Baerga had crossed home plate
before Martinez made the tag at first, something confirmed by the
video replays. The Mets celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   The final play overshadowed an incredibly taut pitching duel
between Orlando Hernandez and Masato Yoshii, each of whom pitched
hitless ball for the first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez allowed two hits in eight innings _ and only a
third-strike wild pitch prevented him from taking a no-hitter into
the seventh. Yoshii, meanwhile allowed two hits in seven innings
and struck out a career-high 10 batters before Dennis Cook pitched
two perfect innings to pick up the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga started the winning rally by chopping a second-pitch
single over a leaping Martinez at first for a lead-off double.
Butch Huskey then sacrificed Baerga to third, before Mendoza
intentionally walked McRae. On a 1-2 count, Lopez sent the fly to
right that ended the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost the series, but they salvaged something
nonetheless amid the strange ending on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   After a relatively quiet Saturday afternoon, the electricity was
back in force at Shea on Sunday night as Yoshii and Hernandez threw
hitless ball through the first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   But both struggled with their control early.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who walked four in three and two-thirds innings
against the Braves last Tuesday night, walked Edgardo Alfonzo and
Bernard Gilkey to open the game. Still, Hernandez was able to
strike out Mike Piazza on a 3-2 pitch and, with the runners in
motion, Yankee catcher Jorge Posada easily nailed Alfonzo at third
for the second out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez walked John Olerud to give the Mets runners on first
and second. But Baerga meekly tapped up the first base line to
Hernandez, who kept right on going to record the third out at first
base.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii had made easy work of the Yankees in the top of the
first. But after retiring Darryl Strawberry on a routine fly to
left to open the second, Yoshii walked Martinez and Posada before
striking out Chad Curtis and Scott Brosius to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   After Hernandez walked McRae with one out in the bottom of the
second and saw him erased when Posada threw him out on an attempt
at a delayed steal of second, both pitchers settled down.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the fourth, O'Neill rifled a hard smash to Alfonzo's
right at third base. Alfonzo tried a backhanded stab at the ball,
but could not come up with it, and O'Neill reached first on the
error. While Strawberry struck out swinging on a 1-2 pitch, O'Neill
stole second. But Yoshii had enough poise to strike out Martinez on
three pitches, the last one looking. And, after issuing an
intentional walk to Posada, Yoshii was able to coax Curtis to hit a
two-hop bounder to Alfonzo, who stepped on the bag at third for the
final out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the fifth, someone recorded a hit. With two out and
Chuck Knoblauch on first after a four-pitch walk, Jeter lined
Yoshii's first pitch to him to right for a single.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the pressure was on Hernandez. The Mets finally got to him
in the sixth. The Cuban right-hander struck out Piazza, but the
ball skipped past Posada, and Piazza hustled to first before the
catcher could even throw, safe on the wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Olerud, who responded with one of the best at-bats of
the game. Ahead 3-1 in the count, the struggling first baseman
fouled four consecutive pitches off before lining the ball to right
field. O'Neill tried a shoestring catch, but the ball short-hopped
his glove.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's no-hitter was gone. Five pitches later, so was his
shutout when Baerga lined a 2-2 pitch past the pitcher's extended
glove and into center field for a single. Curtis's throw was cut
off, and Piazza scurried home without a slide. The Mets led, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees turned around and tied the game in the seventh
on Brosius' eighth homer of the season, which landed deep in the
visiting bullpen in left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
