r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-     06-29 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUELAS NOW TRAINS WITH RIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Twice, they've engaged in dramatically intense
battles.
</P>
<P>
   The first time was in Mexico City, when Gabriel Ruelas narrowly
lost a decision and a chance to win the WBC super featherweight
title against legendary Azumah Nelson in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The second time was in Indio, two years later, when Nelson
scored a brutally easy knockout over a Ruelas, who wasn't himself
shortly after he delivered the blows that killed Jimmy Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's interesting how things evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's long-time trainer was killed in a car accident last
year, and he had to find someone else to work with. Who does he
choose? Joe Goossen _ Ruelas' trainer.
</P>
<P>
   The rivals now train together in Goossen's Van Nuys gym and
ultimately will spar with one another.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas, who beat James Leija to win the WBC title but lost it to
Nelson in their second meeting, admits it's a strange arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was comfortable with it, he shot a glance over
at Nelson as the Ghanan was preparing to spar, as if he was
checking to see whether he was imagining all this.
</P>
<P>
   However, he can appreciate the situation after thinking about
it: He has the unusual opportunity to work with one of the greatest
fighters of his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably a little weird,'' said Ruelas, who exchanged
friendly words with Nelson when they saw each other last week.
``Obviously, it's a positive thing if I learn something from him in
the ring. Especially now that I don't fight that often.
</P>
<P>
   ``...I'm sure that when we start sparring every day, I'll get
used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who lost his title to Genaro Hernandez last year, got to
know the close-knit Goossen family _ including promoter Dan
Goossen, Joe's brother _ as a result of the two fights with Ruelas.
</P>
<P>
   And he liked what he saw. He considers the Goossens and Ruelas
his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have something important. They have love,'' said Nelson,
who is listed as 39 but might be older. ``And those who have love,
have a fear of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about working with Ruelas?
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Nelson, who started fighting professionally in 1979,
has seen it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand the boxing game,'' he said. ``We
fought each other, yes. But it's a business. You don't have to
think bad about anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``...For everyone in this game, I have friendship. These are my
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas and Nelson are in the same position: Former champions
positioning themselves for another title shot.
</P>
<P>
   They fight separate opponents on an America Presents card in San
Antonio on July 11, featuring eight former champions. Ruelas, who
has moved up to the lightweight division, fights tough but limited
Troy Dorsey. Nelson takes on Leija, with whom he has a 1-1-1
record.
</P>
<P>
   Both are favored and, assuming they win, they could fight for
titles soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Said Nelson, ``After I knock out Leija, bring on anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Ruelas will fight anyone, but he likes the prospect
of facing rising star and fellow L.A.-area resident Shane Mosley,
the IBF lightweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a daunting challenge: Mosley, who is unbeaten,
looks almost unbeatable at the moment. But Ruelas has a little
something extra now; he has Nelson there to help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I have a legend as a sparring partner and I don't even
have to pay him. That's a good deal,'' Ruelas said with a chuckle,
obviously tickled over his good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Good news: The fact Felix Trinidad has signed an eight-fight
contract with Main Events and HBO could pump life into a
talent-laden, but stagnant welterweight division.
</P>
<P>
   HBO now has under contract the three champions in the division:
Trinidad (IBF), Oscar De La Hoya (WBC) and Ike Quartey (WBA).
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, apparently free from the grip of Don King, is expected
to face Quartey in November. Seth Abraham, president of
Time-Warner/HBO Sports, said Trinidad could finally step into the
ring with De La Hoya between May and September of 1999 _ assuming
Trinidad beats Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has been under tremendous media pressure to fight
Trinidad, Quartey or Jose Luis Lopez _ possibly the best of the
bunch _ and in turn reportedly has pushed his promoter, Bob Arum,
to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey has a mandatory defense against Andrei Pestriaev before
the Trinidad fight.
</P>
<P>
   Changing times: De La Hoya is 25 and has fought no Hall of
Fame-level fighter in his prime.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Sugar Ray Leonard was 25, he had fought Wilfredo
Benitez, Roberto Duran (twice) and Thomas Hearns.
</P>
<P>
   Times sure have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like it was back in the '70s and early '80s, when
champions fought champions,'' Leonard said. ``...It's more about
business now. I'm not saying that's wrong, to get top dollar. But
you also have to prove your worth fighting top fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You owe it to the public to accept challenges from anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Leonard doesn't blame De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Oscar is afraid of any fighter. I think it's his
promoter protecting him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Mosley, who destroyed Wilfrido Ruiz on Saturday
in Philadelphia, is rapidly becoming one of the top pound-for-pound
fighters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   We'll know more when he faces an Arturo Gatti or Angel Manfredy.
</P>
<P>
   David Reid, who knocked out Simon Brown on the same Philadelphia
card, also was impressive. He, Fernando Vargas and Floyd
Mayweather, all 1996 Olympians, are future millionaires....
</P>
<P>
   Bert Sugar, a veteran boxing writer and historian, has launched
a bi-monthly boxing magazine: ``Bert Sugar's Fight Game.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine has articles written by some of the nation's top
writers. It is lively and has credibility with Sugar in charge. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
