<HEADLINE>
HOMER IN NINTH SINKS MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Jamie Moyer is a cruel example that things even out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner left-hander won 17 games last season and probably
should have lost more than five. But this season he doesn't win
games he should win, and the list of should-haves keeps getting
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer pitched seven solid innings Sunday against the expansion
Arizona Diamondbacks, departed for a pinch-hitter in the eighth
when the Mariners tied the game and wound up with a no-decision in
a 3-2 Seattle loss before 47,965 at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr., slugged his 32nd homer of the season, but just
like 12 of his past 13 home runs, it came in a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The latest loss, Seattle's 19th in the past 27 games, came
suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Bobby Alaya, who tossed a quick and perfect eighth
inning, fed Diamondback left fielder Yamil Benitez a first-pitch
fastball leading off the ninth, and the ball landed in the picnic
area above the 413-foot sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moyer had gotten me out with changeups early in the game, but
against (Ayala), I was looking for a fastball,'' Benitez said.
</P>
<P>
   While it was the first time the Diamondbacks have won a game on
the final pitch, it's not a new experience for the Mariner bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the lack of offense in games Moyer pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was the exact antithesis of this year,'' said
shortstop Alex Rodriguez, comparing Moyer's back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In Moyer's 30 starts a year ago, the M's scored fewer than three
runs for him only once. He won by scores of 9-0, 9-7, 13-4, 8-2,
15-4, 12-9, 8-1, 11-1, 10-6, 10-0 and 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is this season. In 18 starts, Moyer has lost games
5-0, 2-0, 6-0 and 5-2. Add no-decisions in the six games he has
surrendered three or fewer runs, and you know why the veteran is
5-6 despite having a better earned run average this year (3.53)
than a year ago (3.86).
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't banging his head against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been shut out three or four times, but sometimes the
luck of the draw comes into play,'' he said. ``All you can do is
try to control what you can control. For me to sit here and
complain about the offense not scoring runs is ludicrous. My job is
to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   He actually had two jobs Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With the three-game series being played in a National League
ballpark, eliminating the designated hitter, Moyer had a chance to
help himself with a bat in the fifth inning, when he stepped into
the batter's box with runners on first and second, two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed starter Brian Anderson retired Moyer on a force out
at second.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had gotten a basehit there and got us to the top of the
batting order and put the pressure on the Diamondbacks,'' Moyer
said. ``It would have been nice to get a hit somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you know why I didn't like the National League.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, trailing 2-1, were looking for a come-from-behind
win when Dan Wilson singled to lead off the eighth and
pinch-hitting David Segui reached base on shortstop Jay Bell's
error. Joey Cora's sacrifice bunt advanced both runners into
scoring position, but the best Seattle could do was get a
run-producing infield out from Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The M's had another shot to go ahead in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez led off with a single, but Jay Buhner, attempting
to sacrifice pinch-runner Jeff Huson to second, popped out.
Left-handed reliever Alan Embree then picked Huson off base before
a full-count delivery to Glenallen Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't execute, that's for sure,'' manager Lou Piniella
said. ``Jay is a pretty reliable bunter, and I've used him (to
sacrifice) before. He just popped that one up.''
</P>
<P>
   Huson's ensuing overanxiousness cleared the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's basically a hit-and-run situation, and the only thing
you have to concern yourself with is getting picked off,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Huson, ``I read him (Embree's pickoff move) right the first
time and wrong the second time. I was running on the pitch and
wanted to make sure I didn't get thrown out at second (if Hill
struck out). I guess I probably should have waited a little
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill walked on the next pitch, but Russ Davis flied out to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The game's next pitch, thrown by Ayala, was the final one of the
game and ended a terrific pitching duel.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer scattered seven hits. Anderson checked the Mariners on
five.
</P>
<P>
   Embree got the win. Ayala took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to get beat, it's going to be with my best
pitch,'' Ayala told Rodriguez, who walked side-by-side with the
pitcher in the visiting clubhouse, offering encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the ball well,'' Rodriguez said. ``There's not much
you can say about a guy hitting a first-pitch, 92-mile-an-hour
fastball out. Can't do anything but tip your hat to the hitter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
