<SLUG> BC-LA-BENDERS-FUND-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER (AND SON) KNOWS BEST FOR INVESTMENT SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA CANADA FLINTRIDGE -- Their office is on a quaint, residential
road, not Wall Street. They work out of a charming home overlooking
the Angeles National Forest, not a sleek building in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But while they may be far from the nation's financial capital,
the father-son team of Robert and Reed Bender are making their own
waves in this suburb northeast of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Their money management firm, Robert Bender &AMP; Associates, has
outperformed the majority of its peers. Since the firm opened in
1972, it has garnered an average annual return of 22 percent among
its managed accounts, beating the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, a
benchmark of the U.S. stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Bender &AMP; Associates currently manages $173 million from 330
clients -- minimum to join is $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, they were tapped by the Santa Barbara Group of
Mutual Funds in Los Angeles to manage the Bender Growth Fund, a $10
million mid-cap fund. Though its fees are higher than the average
fund, its no-load shares have returned a respectable 41.5 percent
since 1996; good, but not quite the S&AMP;P 500's 51 percent return.
</P>
<P>
   Their portfolios perform in part because they're aggressive
managers, unafraid to take greater risks with investments, said
Peter Walker, publisher of Money Manager Review, a San Francisco
publication that tracks manager performance.
</P>
<P>
   Money Manager ranks the company first among balanced (stocks and
bonds) managers with a 59.64 percent return for the 12 months ended
March 31, and third among equity managers with a 76.51 percent
return over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Their success stems from Robert Bender's nit-picky investment
strategy. Only a handful of stocks a year pass enough muster to be
added to their portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find investments,'' said the 61-year-old former
aerospace executive. ``We're extremely particular.''
</P>
<P>
   They are so picky that they only have 34 stocks in their mutual
fund and 22 among their individually managed accounts. Almost half
of the Bender fund is invested in tech stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike managers who chase the latest trends, the Benders like to
pick stocks they hope will perform in the long-term regardless of
stock market swings. For instance, while financial services stocks
are currently popular because of the mergers within the industry,
the Benders won't buy any that don't meet their investment model.
</P>
<P>
   They are strictly fundamental analysts, judging companies on
market factors as well as company performance and management.
Technical analysis, on the other hand, looks at a stock's volume,
momentum and other quantifiable factors before making a buy or sell
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most money managers, they also have a remarkably low 10
percent turnover, meaning that only one-tenth of their holdings on
the average are bought or sold each year. Fewer trades means less
capital gains, resulting in less taxes to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Most mutual fund managers change their holdings more frequently,
some with a 100 percent turnover or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You buy good companies, you stick with them,'' said co-manager
Reed Bender, 30. ``They can't do it every quarter but they can do
it in the long-term.''
</P>
<P>
   Their strategy is to hold stocks for five to seven years _
almost an eternity among fund managers. They're not concerned with
the vicissitudes of the market at any given moment, since they
believe they've picked good companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the No. 1s and No. 2s in the industry, not the 10s and
12s,'' said the senior Bender.
</P>
<P>
   They start with a close examination of the economy's growth to
identify promising industries in which to invest, such as computer
networking. They then identify the companies they consider to be
top players in that market.
</P>
<P>
   The Benders prefer firms in ``pure play,'' or those that derive
about 90 percent of their business from growth within the industry
they're studying. As the market grows, so will the firm, they
reason.
</P>
<P>
   They only buy companies that are profitable, with at least a 20
percent growth in earnings per share. Profit growth should come
with revenue increases from the core business, to make sure that
bottom-line boosts are a result of operations, not from
cost-cutting or acquisitions. The company also can't be saddled
with too much debt and must be a leader in its industry.
</P>
<P>
   Their painstaking research includes not only analyzing company
operations and marketability of products, but chats with key
executives, customers and visits to headquarters and stores. They
take analysts' reports with a grain of salt, since most analysts
work for companies that have investment banking divisions, which
can have a financial stake in a company.
</P>
<P>
   However, profit increases still are key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks go up on earnings growth. That's the bottom line,''
said Reed Bender, relaxing in his den office. ``I don't care what
the market does.''
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1172 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-BENDERS-FUND-2nd-t     06-29 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-BENDERS-FUND-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
 
LA CANADA FLINTRIDGE, Calif.: the market does.'' 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Such thinking led them to Cisco, now a high-flier in the
computer networking field, which they first bought in 1990 for 80
cents a share, adjusted for splits. The company closed at $89~ on
Friday. Cisco is the best maker of routers, and Lucent and Nortel
are chasing it, the younger Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   They also bought Microsoft for as low as $3 a share and Home
Depot for $4, adding to their positions as the companies grew.
</P>
<P>
   The Benders do buy companies in slower-growing industries such
as retail. But their strategy is to buy the best-managed ones.
</P>
<P>
   However, they don't like cyclical industries, such as
semiconductors where firms can be dependent on product
introductions. Intel is one such company. Even if it has most of
the world's personal computer chip market, it's languishing now
because of problems with its new chip. Years ago, it rose high with
the Pentium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a boom and bust cycle,'' Reed Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   They sell if they feel the firm can't meet their stringent
criteria anymore, such as Wal-Mart. Robert Bender identified
Wal-Mart as a good stock in 1980 and it performed well for them
over the years. But they dumped the stock in 1994 when growth
started slowing down. This year they sold Sun Microsystems, the
developer of the Java computer language, because the company's
growth is expected to slow.
</P>
<P>
   But they're holding onto Microsoft, despite its antitrust
problems. There's no threat to its operating system dominance and
it's well-positioned in the Internet marketplace as well, Reed
Bender said. Netscape, whose browser is Microsoft's chief
competitor in the Internet marketplace, is bound to be overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't (buy) companies that compete with Microsoft,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   They also steer clear of many Internet companies, such as search
engine makers, since many aren't profitable. Most foreign stocks
are a no-no as well, because there are too many factors a money
manager has to watch for, such as currency risks, political
stability and adequate regulatory oversight.
</P>
<P>
   They prefer companies that supply infrastructure to a growing
industry. One such favorite is Quintiles Transnational, a contract
research company.
</P>
<P>
   The Benders don't like biotechnology stocks, since they are
dependent on FDA approvals. But they favor a company like
Quintiles, which provides FDA testing and application support for
biotech and pharmaceutical companies. Whether or not a company
receives FDA approval, Quintiles still gets the business.
</P>
<P>
   But they've bought into some dogs as well. One loser was
Versatility, a company whose systems help customer service
representatives identify products purchased, computers used and
details of the last service call when a customer phones in. But
business did not develop as they had hoped. They bought the stock
several times at an average price of $10 and bailed out at $6 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   As for future plans, Robert Bender does not intend to open more
offices than the one he has at home in La Canada Flintridge and a
marketing office in downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more peaceful and I don't want to waste time traveling,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
