<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A SUMMER SMASH 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ My 10-year-old son, Sam, isn't much of a newspaper
reader yet, but finally he has something to check every morning
when the Globe is plopped on our walkway.
</P>
<P>
   Did McGwire hit another one? How many is that?
</P>
<P>
   If you are a baseball fan, it is the first thing you look for
when the morning paper arrives. And it is often the lead story of
the day when ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' loops back at the top of the
hour.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it's going to go for the rest of the baseball
season, right up until some time in September when _ barring
injuries, of course _ Mark McGwire hits home run No. 62, shattering
Roger Maris's record set in the asterisk summer of 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, 1961. As it was then, it is today ...
</P>
<P>
   ... John Glenn is preparing for a space flight, there's a young
singer named Dylan making noise, the Green Bay Packers are the most
feared team in the NFL, there's a Democrat in the White House who
vacations on the Cape and Islands ... and someone's on pace to set
the major league single-season home run record.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals played their 80th game Sunday and are off Monday.
They reach their official midseason Tuesday night at home against
the Kansas City Royals. McGwire already has 36 homers, which means
he'll project to at least 72 when the St. Louis halftime whistle
blows.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lurking not far behind we have Chicago Cub Sammy Sosa
with 32 home runs, including a big-league-record 19 (and counting)
in the month of June. And then there's Ken Griffey, who Sunday hit
his 32d for the Seattle Mariners in their 82d game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, Sosa, Griffey. Three guys with a legitimate shot to
beat Maris. There have been threats in the past, but never this
many this far into the season, with these kinds of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   It's incredible when one realizes that Maris's record has stood
longer than Ruth's. The Babe hit 60 in the summer of 1927 and it
was 34 years later that Maris hit No. 61. The much-maligned Maris
never again reached those heights, never made the Hall of Fame, and
died of cancer, but his record has lasted 38 years, four more than
the Babe's.
</P>
<P>
   Back in '61, the Red Sox were part of homer history because it
was a Boston rookie righty, Tracy Stallard, who served up the final
meatball in the Yankees' 162d game of the season (Tom Zachary
surrendered No. 60 to Ruth in '27). All good New Yorkers know that
the Maris homer ball was caught by Sal Durante, a truck-driving
teenager from Coney Island. Durante collected a $5,000 reward put
up by a Sacramento restaurateur and happily gave the ball to Maris.
When Cal Ripken homered in his 2,131st consecutive game in 1995,
the fan who caught the ball wanted more money than Bill Gates has.
</P>
<P>
   Stallard lives in Virginia and will need an unlisted phone
number when McGwire gets near 60. The Red Sox this time will be a
safe distance from history: Boston finishes with Seattle in August
and the Sox don't play the Cardinals or Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The Babe's widow was interviewed regularly during Maris's '61
chase and told reporters that she didn't want Maris to hit 60. She
said it was the record her husband loved best. Maris was forever
haunted by the chase, and by the charges that his record was
tainted because he did it in a 162-game season, as opposed to
Ruth's 154-game slate.
</P>
<P>
   Maris in '61 played 10 more games than Ruth in '27, but came to
the plate only six more times. Like McGwire this year, Maris had
the advantage of hitting in an expansion season against plenty of
pitchers who would have been in Triple A or retired if not for the
addition of two new rosters.
</P>
<P>
   We are reminded that Reggie Jackson had 37 homers at the
All-Star break in 1969 and wound up with ``only'' 47. The second
half is harder.
</P>
<P>
   But this time it's really going to happen. One or two of the
above sluggers could be stopped by injury or slump, but it's highly
doubtful that all three will come up short. McGwire hit 58 last
year. Griffey was on a pace to smash the mark when the strike hit
in '94.
</P>
<P>
   This is the year Maris's record falls. Just ask Sam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
