<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOX-MARLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX HIT LOW SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Red Sox pitcher Derek Lowe wasted a splendid opportunity
to lift whatever curse is dogging him during this season of no
wins.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in the one American city that has more in common with the
Caribbean than the Corn Belt, your neighbors don't look twice if
you sacrifice pigs, chickens, goats, or the nearest household pet
as an appeal to the gods for relief from ill fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe passed on the voodoo, however, and elected to shoulder the
burden for Sunday's 5-1 loss to the Florida Marlins, which dropped
his record to 0-7 and threatens to leave the 6-foot-6-inch
righthander with a permanent stoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is killing me,'' Lowe said after once again pitching just
well enough to lose, this time to Ryan Dempster, a 21-year-old
rookie who was making just his sixth start and hadn't won yet,
either, until holding the Red Sox to four hits and a run in seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every time I go out there somebody with an 0-3
record and a 9.00 ERA goes out there and throws by far his best
game,'' Lowe said. ``I don't know if it's bad luck, or whatever.
It's a strange game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the last game of an odd bit of scheduling in which the
Red Sox endured a 19-game stretch in which they were home for two
short sets totaling five games while playing 14 on the road. They
actually survived quite well, winning 12 of the 19, batting .294,
and compiling a staff ERA of 4.07.
</P>
<P>
   After an off-day Monday, they go into the All-Star break with
six games at home, beginning Tuesday with a three-game set against
Montreal, but it will be a short respite. After the break, they
play 12 of their next 14 and 24 of their next 30 on the road before
unpacking their suitcases for any length of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day off will probably be good for us,'' manager Jimy
Williams said. ``We've got a few guys banged up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are starting to show signs of attrition. With Mo
Vaughn down with a strained hamstring and Reggie Jefferson
recovering from a beaning, Williams started an infield that
featured four guys who have all played shortstop, including Mike
Benjamin, who was at first base, the firmest sign yet that the Red
Sox fancy newcomer Billy Ashley as a DH and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   The regular shortstop, Nomar Garciaparra, batted cleanup and
doubled and scored in the second inning on Benjamin's single. The
hit extended Garciaparra's streak to 20 games, matching Larry
Walker for longest streak in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know him from Adam,'' Marlins manager Jim Leyland said
of Garciaparra, who had seven hits and was on base nine times in
three games against Floirida, ``but he's a real ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks to me like he's lived before. Does Jimy (Williams)
room together with m? They ought to. You don't let that guy get
away. He's a trophy bass.''
</P>
<P>
   But that second-inning uprising was the best the Red Sox could
muster Sunday. Rookie Lou Merloni struck out with runners on the
corners in the sixth. Pinch hitter Damon Buford and Darren Lewis
were retired with a runner on third in the seventh. Darren Bragg,
facing reliever Antonio Alfonseca, struck out with the bases loaded
in the eighth, an inning in which Garciaparra also whiffed against
the Marlins' six-fingered man, who is called ``El Pulpo'' (The
Octopus).
</P>
<P>
   Lowe put himself in a 2-0 hole in the first inning, when he gave
up a single, a walk, and Cliff Floyd's two-run triple. He fell
behind, 3-1, in the third when his wild pitch allowed Edgar
Renteria, who had doubled, to walk home from third. He was gone in
the fifth, when he loaded the bases after two were out with a
single and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hurt myself by walking (Todd) Zeile after I had him down 1
and 2,'' Lowe said. ``It could have been a very easy inning. I got
two quick outs on five pitches, and then turned it into a
marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins seemed intent on sparing Lowe some agony when Mark
Kotsay, the runner on first, broke for second after he saw Edgar
Renteria, the runner already occupying that base, make a move
toward third. But Renteria was merely bluffing, which should have
made Kotsay a pigeon for catcher Scott Hatteberg.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatteberg, after taking a few steps toward second, threw to
second baseman Merloni, allowing Kotsay free passage back to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was terrible,'' Hatteberg said. ``All my fault. I ran out
there but I should have kept running toward first. Lou didn't have
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally screwed up. It was totally my fault that Derek
didn't get to stay in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Lowe has any evidence to suggest the outcome would have
been any different had he lingered on the scene. He has allowed
three runs or fewer in each of his last five starts, of which this
was the briefest, and nothing to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm going out there thinking I have to throw a
shutout every time, but in the back of my mind I don't want to give
up too many runs, so I'm trying to make the perfect pitch and it's
backfiring,'' Lowe said. ``I'm getting into too many high pitch
counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know what else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And on he went to the plane. Too late to stop at the chicken
coop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 0047EDT &QL; 
