<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART GOES DISTANCE IN N.E. 200 
</HEADLINE>
 ENGLAND 200-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Eighteen laps remained in Sunday's Indy Racing
League event at New Hampshire International Speedway when Tony
Stewart said he began his countdown. It was, after all, only two
years ago in the inaugural IRL race at NHIS that Stewart was in the
midst of a runaway victory _ he led for 165 laps and was five
seconds from putting the field three laps down _ when his engine
quit 18 laps from the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an electronic crank trigger,'' Stewart recalled. ``It's
right in the heart of the engine and when it quit, it just shut the
motor off.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart experienced no such problems Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was difficult for him not to keep a keen ear on his
engine as he counted off the final 18 laps en route to victory in
the New England 200 at NHIS before a crowd estimated by track
officials to be 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he experienced any false alarms in his final 18-lap
tour of the 1-mile oval at NHIS, Stewart said, ``No, but I heard
every little thing that happened. I could tell you every time a
valve closed, I could hear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chimed in car owner John Menard, ``I could hear it in the
pits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Larry (Curry, team manager for Team Menard) in the last
five laps I probably created more noises in my head that probably
weren't happening,'' said Stewart, who led twice for 93 laps and
inherited the lead for good from teammate Robbie Buhl, last year's
winner, on Lap 163. ``I was counting laps. From 18 down, I was
counting 'em. I had my spotter and Larry both tell me how many laps
we had. They both said 20, so two laps later I started counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even act like we won the race until I knew we could
coast across without getting passed,'' he added. ``I didn't want to
even think that, coming off of (Turn) 4, we had it won, because I
didn't know if I could coast that far and still win. So, until we
got there, I wasn't counting anything in the bag yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In recording his second IRL triumph of the season, and second in
a row at NHIS for Team Menard, Stewart finished ahead of a pair of
Great Scotts _ runner-up Scott Goodyear and third-place finisher
Scott Sharp, who entered the race tied with Stewart in the IRL
points standings at 115 but now trails by 17 (167-150).
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who earned $122,950, will not likely be back to defend
his title next year since he will be driving for Joe Gibbs on the
NASCAR Winston Cup circuit. But, even if he weren't, it's likely he
would not have returned to NHIS with the IRL, whose three-year
contract with the track expired with Sunday's race. Because of
sagging attendance figures, which experienced a decline Sunday for
the third year in a row, it's not likely that the IRL will be back
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great race track,'' said Menard, who has had two of
his four career IRL triumphs at NHIS. ``We really enjoy it. I feel
bad that more spectators don't share my enthusiasm for this
track.''
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't blame Billy Boat if he wasn't eager to return to
NHIS. After winning the pole position Saturday in record fashion
with a lap of 162.146 miles per hour, Boat twice experienced
calamity in Turn 2. The A.J. Foyt driver spun there on Lap 32 then,
on Lap 95, was involved in a four-car crash and suffered a broken
left thigh when his car was broadsided by Raul Boesel. Boat was
transported to Concord Hospital, where he remained Sunday night
under observation. He will be transferred Monday to Methodist
Hospital in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main focus right now is on Billy and his family,'' said
Tommy LaMance, team manager for A.J. Foyt Enterprises. ``When we
are clear about his condition then we'll go back and evaluate
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat's accident wound up being the worst mishap of the race,
which was marred by six caution periods totaling 50 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Twice this season, Stewart has failed to reach the finish line
of a race, including the Indianapolis 500. But Sunday Stewart
seemed to put all those frustrations behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope so,'' he said. ``I mean, this is definitely a momentum
booster just like I said after we won Orlando and after we ran
second at Phoenix. It just proves that if we don't break, we can
win races and finish on the podium. This team is capable of winning
races everywhere we go, it's just a matter of getting a little luck
on our side, and today we really had the luck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
