<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRANCE-PARAGUAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERTIME SUCCESS FOR FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENS, France _ Tout le monde will be jumping on the France
bandwagon now. Les Bleus officially captured the imagination of
their own country Sunday with a 1-0 overtime win over Paraguay,
their fourth in succession, setting up a quarterfinal meeting
against Italy Friday at Saint-Denis.
</P>
<P>
   The French have become a team worth embracing _ the most solid
of defenses, able and willing attackers, propelled by the momentum
of the enthusiastic support of a crowd of 41,275 at Stade Felix
Bollaert, which sang the most serious of ``La Marseillaise'' after
a good-natured ``Joyeux Anniversaire'' salute to goalkeeper Fabian
Barthez.
</P>
<P>
   If any team can unite France, it could be this one. Only the
most xenophobic of Front National members could be unimpressed by
this team's diversity. Coach Aimee Jacquet's team is composed of
first-generation immigrants from Africa and the Caribbean,
offspring of Argentinians, Armenians, Basques, and Portuguese, plus
some stereotypical Gallic descendents of Vercingetorix, such as
Laurent Blanc, author of the 117th-minute goal Sunday. And they are
about to be reinforced by their best, the suspended Zinedine
Zidane, the most famous Algerian-French footballer since Albert
Camus.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been difficult to imagine France failing against
Paraguay, but the French were less than four minutes away from a
penalty kick showdown against Jose Luis Chilavert, one of the most
dominating figures in this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Chilavert almost controlled the pace of the game from the goal
by his sheer presence. Chilavert's intimidating demeanor is
palpable. He is built like a heavyweight boxer _ 6 feet 2 inches,
204 pounds _ and he has punched out everyone from journalists to
opponents to the bodyguards of presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Chilavert punched away French chances in regulation time
but was a gracious villain as he helped up Youri Djorkaeff after a
second-half collision.
</P>
<P>
   But, though Chilavert was prepared to go a few more rounds, his
teammates wearied, and France reinforced the attack with Stephane
Guivarc'h and Robert Pires, plus midfielder Alain Boghossian, then
brought Blanc up from deep central defense.
</P>
<P>
   France kept the ball in the air, and when Paraguay finally
appeared tired of heading out of danger, Pires and David Trezeguet
combined to set up Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very difficult match,'' Jacquet said. ``We
dominated the match, but in a match like that, where everything is
closed down, you never know what will happen. We were lacking some
confidence, and that is what happens when you play a team like
Paraguay that seals itself off like an impenetrable wall.''
</P>
<P>
   The Paraguayans made life difficult for both France and referee
Ali Mohamed Bujsaim of the United Arab Emirates. They delayed and
attempted to frustrate the French, who have their own
self-destructive tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Though France's players were supposed to be the more
sophisticated, the Paraguayans took better advantage of an
incredibly underqualified refereeing crew, which consisted of
linesmen from Sri Lanka and Vanuatu, countries that are oceans away
from the high-level professional leagues. In the first half,
Djorkaeff actually grabbed a linesman's arm in attempt to force him
to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Chilavert and central defenders Celso Ayala and Carlos Gamarra
kept the goal area secure. And Paraguay's swarming tactics stifled
the creativity of Djorkaeff and highlighted the absence of Zidane.
</P>
<P>
   Lilian Thuram provided some powerful penetrations from the back,
and France had several near misses in the run of play in regulation
time, the best by Thierry Henry off the far post in the 38th minute
and Djorkaeff's drive that was headed over the bar by Julio Cesar
Enciso 32 minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Late in regulation time, with the crowd chanting ``Youri,''
Djorkaeff nearly decided the contest. He directed a free kick
toward the far post, curling away from Chilavert, who dove to clear
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``France got a little desperate, but we were really tired,''
said Paraguay's Brazilian coach, Paulo Cesar Carpeggiani. ``But
it's normal to get tired at the end of a game like that. We thought
we would have a better chance of winning if it went to penalty
kicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay went to a fifth defender midway through the second
half, as Denis Caniza replaced Carlos Paredes, a 21-year-old
midfield creator from Olimpia in Asuncion who has been among
Paraguay's most impressive performers in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The insistent pressure and strength of France caused the
Paraguayans to visibly tire. Several collapsed after Blanc's shot
hit the back of the net, leading to a moving scene in which
Chilavert consoled and encouraged his teammates while pulling them
to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   France has never advanced past the semifinals, and if any of the
French are withholding their support, it is because they are wary
of being let down again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a great matchup with Italy,'' Jacquet said. ``They
are our dear friends, and we have a lot of players playing there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
