<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HALLOFFAME-BIRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL BECKONS BIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Larry Bird will get the word Monday. The Hall of Fame
will announce that its panel of 24 anonymous voters has deemed that
Bird, having waited the minimum five years, has been inducted.
</P>
<P>
   It is as close to a lock as one can find. Bird retired at the
end of the 1992 season and became eligible for consideration this
year. The results will be announced Monday, with the induction
ceremony scheduled for Oct. 2.
</P>
<P>
   It's never easy to predict how the vote will go, but this one
isn't in doubt. Bird will become the 19th Celtic player to be so
honored, although some, such as Bill Walton, Tiny Archibald, Pete
Maravich, and Dave Bing, established themselves as stars long
before joining the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of soup-to-nuts Celtics, Bird will join K.C. Jones, Tom
Heinsohn, Frank Ramsey, Sam Jones, John Havlicek, and Bill Russell
as honorees (Bob Cousy played seven games with the 1969-70
Cincinnati Royals, Dave Cowens played 40 ill-advised games with
1982-83 Milwaukee Bucks, and Bill Sharman played 31 games for the
1950-51 Washington Caps.). Red Auerbach was inducted as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Of the above players, only Russell and Havlicek were inducted in
their first year of eligibility. Heinsohn, for instance, retired in
1965 but was not selected until 1986. Ramsey was selected in 1981,
17 years after he retired.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the Hall of Fame admits at least three nominees from
the regular category and one each from the women's, veterans, and
international categories. Bird is one of four first-time nominees
in the regular category, along with Adrian Dantley, Chet Walker,
and former Harlem Globetrotter Marques Haynes. The others are Larry
Costello, Artis Gilmore, Gus Johnson, Sidney Moncrief and coaches
Alex Hannum, John Thompson of Georgetown and Tex Winter, the man
behind the world champion Bulls' triple-post offense.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, Gilmore had a cup of coffee with the Celtics in the
1987-88 season, while Thompson played 74 games for the Celtics in
1964-66 before going on to bigger and better things with the Hoyas.
</P>
<P>
   Two women are nominated: Jody Conradt, the head coach at Texas
the past 22 seasons, and Harley Redin, who coached at Wayland
Baptist. Nominated in the veterans category are Grady Lewis, a shoe
company executive, and Arnie Risen, who ended his 13-year NBA
career in 1958 with the Celtics. The nominees in the international
category are Yugoslavian coach Aleksandar Nikolic and Ubiratan
Pereira Maciel of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Bird needs no introduction to Boston fans and will likely be
joined next year by Kevin McHale, his running mate for most of his
Boston career. McHale retired after the 1992-93 season.
</P>
<P>
   Bird joined the Celtics in 1979 and was the near-unanimous
choice for Rookie of the Year, well ahead of Magic Johnson. He
earned three consecutive Most Valuable Player titles in 1984-86 and
led the Celtics to three world championships, gaining the Finals
MVP in two of those years (1984, 1986.) He was a 12-time All-Star
and still holds or shares 27 Celtics records.
</P>
<P>
   His final two years were cut short by back pain which forced his
retirement. But before retiring, he was a member of the first (and
true) Dream Team at the 1992 Olympics, winning a gold medal. He was
retained by the Celtics as a consultant following his retirement,
but grew disenchanted with his role in the organization. He left
last year to accept the head coaching job and part ownership of the
Indiana Pacers and guided the team to the Eastern Conference
finals, earning Coach of the Year honors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
