u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SELES-B     06-29 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-SELES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELES FACING TOUGH TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ She's hardly a household name on the WTA Tour, with
just one tournament victory to her credit, but Monica Seles is more
than familiar with Sandrine Testud.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, who plays Testud in her fourth-round match Monday at
Wimbledon, lost to the Frenchwoman in the third round here last
year and again in the Italian Open in May. That was just before
Seles lost to Arantxa Sanchez Vicario in the final of the French
Open.
</P>
<P>
   So Seles didn't take Sunday off. She hit for about 30 minutes,
trying to keep her game sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both of us are playing better,'' said Seles, the No. 6
seed. ``I'm definitely playing better, but I also feel Sandrine has
improved, too. So maybe the better one of us will win. I'm just
going to go out there and take it a ball at a time and do some
things differently than I did the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very good fighter, she's good from both sides, and she
has a good serve. So I'm just going to have to play my game at a
higher level. I'm going to have to attack, serve well, and go for
my shots. I'm just going to have to attack and attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Testud, seeded 14th and ranked 13th in the world, has won
$177,887 this season. Seles, who hasn't won a tournament, is fifth
ranked and has earned $353,303.
</P>
<P>
   Testud, who earned $417,753 last year while having her best
season (44-23 record), made it to two finals, winning at Palermo
and losing at Atlanta. She also made the quarterfinals in seven
other events, including the US Open as well as the Lipton
Invitational. She has not lost a set in three matches at Wimbledon.
But neither has Seles.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly even matchup between Seles and Testud symbolizes
the depth of women's tennis. With close to a dozen top players,
there is plenty of talent for fans to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing of players also has never been better. Martina
Hingis, Anna Kournikova, Venus Williams, and Lindsay Davenport are
among the younger players who have made headlines and captured the
imagination of the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's such a great point that if we don't really
take advantage of it, we never will,'' Seles said. ``I think our
new CEO (Bartlett H. McGuire) is doing a great job, so hopefully it
will continue. I just think the variety is so much better on the
court, off the court, and terms of personalities and games, too.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest names ever in women's tennis was knocked out
of the tournament last Friday when Steffi Graf lost in straight
sets. Seles saw only the final game of Graf's 6-4, 7-5 loss to
Natasha Zvereva.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always hard to say what will happen because I didn't see
the match,'' Seles said. ``We all watch the final game in the
locker room and I thought she just played some great tennis. But I
was just really happy for Natasha because I know it's tough when
you play somebody like 15 or 16 times in a row and you lose to
them, and I always thought Natasha has some of the best hands in
world, and it was just nice to see that she put it all together and
in a really good place, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf, who has been plagued with knee injuries, has thought
seriously about retiring. It's something the other tour players
discuss often.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Steffi, it's going to be tough for her to come back to the
level that she was, obviously, but, knowing her, she is such a
perfectionist that she'll try,'' Seles said. ``So I really think
that she's still going to keep on playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles doesn't believe that not having Graf in her draw will mean
very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's always the match. I mean, gee, if I can get
through the Testud match, that's the biggest, before I start
thinking about Steffi,'' Seles said. ``The way Natasha played
(against Graf), she could beat any of us. So you don't look that
far ahead. I can just see what the players are saying, but until I
see it with my own eyes, I would just prefer not to say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Seles is hoping that her game will say it all this
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
