<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-DENMARK-NIGERIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA CAN'T COPE WITH GREAT DANE ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ Even after they did it, they couldn't say
how they did it or where it came from. Denmark (yes, that Denmark)
4, Nigeria 1?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why it should be like this suddenly, it is impossible to
say,'' shrugged coach Bo Johansson, after his lightly regarded side
had ripped the wings off the favored Super Eagles in the Stade de
France Sunday night and won a date with defending champion Brazil
in the World Cup quarterfinals. ``You never know. You can't really
say such things.''
</P>
<P>
   How did a team that had managed only three goals in its first
three matches score two in the first dozen minutes? By doing what
most people are reluctant to do against the fleet Nigerians: Go
straight to their goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes went right at the Nigerians and it paid off almost
immediately, as Peter Moller (third minute) and Brian Laudrup
(12th) put the ball in the back of the net. The Super Eagles, in
shock, never regrouped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose concentration after 2-0 and it was very difficult to
do something different,'' said coach Bora Milutinovic, after
Nigeria had gone out in the second round for the second straight
time. ``I am not happy to finish the World Cup in this way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thought the Super Eagles would, not after beating seeded
Spain and 1994 semifinalist Bulgaria in their group. They were the
team nobody wanted to play, the team the French were delighted to
avoid. Everyone this side of Copenhagen (and most folks there)
figured Denmark was just a speed bump on the way to a shootout with
Brazil on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes had come slouching into the second round after tying
South Africa and losing to France. After a dozen years away from
the tournament, that seemed to be enough for them. So Johansson had
let them relax over the weekend, working them lightly.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the Danes took the field Sunday night, they were
brisk and bold. As soon as they saw the Nigerian defense playing
loose, they lofted a long ball to captain Michael Laudrup, who
dashed past two defenders and tapped the ball across to Moller, who
blasted it past keeper Peter Rufai.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't figure to be a problem for the Super Eagles, who
usually play with more urgency and muscle and invention when
they're a goal down. But before Nigeria could crank up the war
chariot, it was 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   After Moller blew a free kick through the wall and off Rufai's
hands, an unmarked Brian Laudrup pounced on the rebound and slammed
it by. No question _ and no fluke. ``Those goals were from
fantastic attacks,'' said Johansson. ``It wasn't luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaken awake, Nigeria came calling again and again. Nwankwo Kanu
sprinted in on a break, but keeper Peter Schmeichel smothered his
bid. Okechukwu Uche kneed one over the crossbar. Kanu misheaded a
lovely cross from Jay-Jay Okocha. Okocha launched a shot just wide,
then put another over the bar. Twenty-five shots Nigeria took, and
all but eight were off target.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Eagles were in a tailspin. Fifteen minutes into the
second half, Denmark's Ebbe ``Sudden Impact'' Sand hurled them to
earth. Sand, who'd been on the pitch for only 22 seconds (and only
16 while the ball was live), took a looping pass from Michael
Laudrup, dropped it from head to right foot, and drilled it through
for 3-0. It was the fastest goal by a substitute in Cup history and
it finished Nigeria for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a little bit of the old, famous Danish way of
playing, and it is enormously nice to see,'' mused Johansson, after
Thomas Helveg had made it 4-0 in the 76th minute. ``We played a
couple of fantastic games in 1986. This was a little bit like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the last, and only other time, the Danes were here.
They destroyed Uruguay by five goals, shut out West Germany, then
were blown to bits, 5-1, by the Spanish in the second round. So
their expectations were modest this time _ and still are. ``Beat
Brazil? We have to try,'' Johansson said. ``Nigeria can't try any
more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
