<SLUG> BC-CAR-NE200-GOODYEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIR OF SCOTTS COME UP SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Tony Stewart took off.
</P>
<P>
   The Scotts gave chase.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Goodyear and Scott Sharp took turns leading Sunday's New
England 200. But at the end they and the rest of the Indy Racing
League field were left to follow winner Stewart around New
Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   And when the race _ perhaps the last IRL race to be held here _
was over Goodyear had pulled down a season-best second place and
Sharp was third.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp grabbed the lead from Jeff Ward on Lap 19 and then gave it
back when he pitted early on Lap 28.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, driving for a first-year team that includes Baltimore
Raven quarterback Jim Harbaugh, moved in front when Ward went out
with engine problems on Lap 55 and then led twice more for a total
of 44 laps.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, Goodyear ran out of gears.
</P>
<P>
   He lost fifth gear early, but he said that was not a big problem
because he could use sixth gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then we came out of the pits with 82 or 88 laps to go and
we only had fourth gear,'' Goodyear said. ``We went in fourth gear
the rest of the way. That cut us down a second or a second and a
half a lap. That dumps so much speed. And I was waiting for the
thing to blow up, but it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear managed to make one last run at Stewart late in the
race, shaving his lead to 1.3 seconds with 14 laps to go. Still
running in fourth gear, Goodyear hoped one more round of traffic
might appear in front of Stewart to keep the race at Goodyear's
pace. No such luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good race car and was catching up mainly in traffic,''
Goodyear said. ``I didn't need the fifth and sixth gear in traffic;
fourth gear was perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   So he looked for more Sunday afternoon cars on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping for a big gaggle of traffic at the end to give me
a chance to catch him,'' Goodyear said. ``But I didn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Sharp felt it was traffic _ specifically the car of
defending champion Robbie Buhl _ that kept him from getting at
Goodyear and let Davey Hamilton close on him near the end of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie Buhl wouldn't get out of the way,'' Sharp said. ``If
someone is slowing you down a second a lap, someone else is going
to come up on your tail.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp figured he wasn't going to catch Stewart, but he might
have had a shot at Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a chance,'' Sharp said. ``But once I had that traffic
problem, I had no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear's previous best finish this year was a fourth in the
last race at Texas. He was third in the first IndyCar race here in
1992 behind Bobby Rahal and Michael Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, who won the second race of the season at Phoenix, lost a
little ground to Stewart in the point standings. The two came into
this race tied for first.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Sharp won here when Stewart developed electrical
problems late after nearly running away with the race. Sharp, a
Babson College graduate and native of Norwalk, Conn., missed last
year's race while he recovered from a couple of concussions.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp pulled away from Ward with a nice restart on Lap 19. He
held the lead until the next caution flag on Lap 28 when he dropped
into the pits for four tires and fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had entered our pit-stop window and we knew we had to do
three pit stops,'' Sharp said. ``Sometimes if you do it early, you
can get ahead of the curve. That was David's (team manager David
Cripps) call. His strategy won one for us at Phoenix and I'm not
going to question that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp was back to second behind Stewart with another restart on
Lap 110. And for much of the rest of the race, he and Goodyear
chased Stewart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 0102EDT &QL; 
