<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-HERNANDEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALM HERNANEZ WORKS WONDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With BBO-YANKS-METS) (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez was about two hours away from his
first pitch, which is a time when most major league starters have
an imaginary wall around them. It is usually anathema to starters
to be interviewed before they pitch, but Hernandez ignored that
policy on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees' first-base coach, Jose Cardenal, as an
interpreter, an animated Hernandez talked about everything from the
likelihood that Cuban President Fidel Castro would watch Sunday
night's series finale between the Mets and the Yankees to how
Hernandez's grandfather was such a weak baseball player that he was
only used as a pinch-runner.
</P>
<P>
   If Hernandez is superstitious, he might assemble the same 10
reporters for another chat before his next start. Although the
Yankees eventually lost, 2-1, Hernandez followed his pre-game
session by silencing the Mets without a hit into the sixth inning.
He kept throwing, and dominating, while uncorking an astounding 142
pitches, the most thrown by a Yankee this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to pitch the same way that I've been pitching,''
Hernandez said in the visiting clubhouse at Shea Stadium before the
game. ``I want to do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked. He had a stunning bout with wildness, in
which he walked four of the first seven Mets, but was saved when
catcher Jorge Posada gunned down runners at second and third on
attempted steals. Hernandez went on to retire 12 of 13 batters at
one point.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped the Mets on one run and two singles over eight
innings, striking out nine, walking five and throwing one damaging
wild pitch in his fifth major league start, and was out of the game
when the Mets won on Luis Lopez's sacrifice fly in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Pulli, the plate umpire, may have unnerved Hernandez in
the first inning by telling him he was finished with his warmup
tosses before he thought he was. Yankee Manager Joe Torre met with
Pulli before the second, and the umpire used hand signals to tell
Hernandez the number of warmup pitches he had left in subsequent
innings. Hernandez walked just one batter after the second. In the
one inning the Mets scored against him, though, Hernandez was too
tricky for Posada.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the sixth and Hernandez still working on a
no-hitter, he threw a nasty 3-2 breaking ball that Mike Piazza
waved at for strike three. But Posada also waved at the ball, and
it rolled by him for a wild pitch, allowing Piazza to hustle to
first. Giving the Mets a fourth out was an ominous sign during a
no-hit attempt.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud followed by also working Hernandez to a 3-2 count.
Finally, Olerud looped a shot to right that landed inches in front
of a charging Paul O'Neill for the Mets' first hit. O'Neill
short-hopped the ball, but no one was fooled. The no-hitter was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the shutout was history, too, as Carlos Baerga also worked
Hernandez deep in the count before smacking a single over the mound
for a 1-0 lead. Hernandez struck out Butch Huskey to strand men on
first and third and whiffed Edgardo Alfonzo with McRae on second to
end the seventh. He had thrown 134 pitches through seven innings,
and it was somewhat surprising when he came back out for the
eighth. All Hernandez did was pump eight pitches for a 1-2-3
inning. Ramiro Mendoza replaced him in the ninth with the score
tied, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez compared the Mets-Yankees rivalry, with its fervor, to
the one in Cuba between Industriales, his former team, and Metro,
the team Rey Ordonez played for. He and Masato Yoshii, who gave up
just two hits himself in seven innings for the Mets, contributed to
a rowdy atmosphere on Sunday night. Before the game, Hernandez did
cite one big difference in the conduct of Cuban spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of fights in the stands,'' he said. ``In
Cuba, if you fight, you go to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Hernandez smiled, which he did often during the 15-minute
exchange with reporters. The pitcher defected from Cuba on Dec. 26,
1997, with seven others on a 17-foot raft, and signed a four-year,
$6.6million contract with the Yankees in March. He has not stopped
smiling since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castro will be watching this game,'' Hernandez said of the
ruler who banned him from the Cuban national team in October 1996
because he thought the pitcher would follow his brother Livan and
defect. ``He knows everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Castro should know that Hernandez was outstanding on Sunday
night. Before the game, he charmed reporters and bopped to Bruce
Springsteen's ``Glory Days.'' He was probably unaware that the song
is about a former high school pitcher who cannot stop reminiscing
about his high school days and the terrific fastball he once had.
Hernandez, though, has made it to the United States and will not
have to rely on his glory days in Cuba for memories. He will have
nights like Sunday night to create more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to win,'' Hernandez said when asked about
opposing the Mets before more than 53,000 fans and a national
television audience. ``The other stuff, I don't care about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
