<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1197 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF--MIDSEASON-HNS &LR;      06-29 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF--MIDSEASON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
PGA Tour's older players coming back strong in 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JAYNE CUSTRED
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   It was the young guns' game in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four major championships were won by golfers who
were 20-something, and the new blood on the PGA Tour continued to
dominate week in and week out for much of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now consider the scene for the first half of 1998. Mark O'Meara,
41, triumphed at the Masters. Fred Couples, 38, came through with
two wins and three other top-three finishes. And Tom Watson, 48,
reconsidered his plans to head to the Senior circuit after besting
a stellar field at the Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the young players continue to turn in their stunning
performances. No one has been more consistent than David Duval, 26.
Tiger Woods is not having the same season he had last year, but he
has spent a good portion of his time at the top of the leader
board.
</P>
<P>
   But at the midway point in the 1998 PGA Tour season, the
``veteran'' golfers have proved they should not be taken lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember four or five years ago when the European players
won all the majors,'' Tom Lehman said. ``The media were writing off
the U.S. players, saying there were no good U.S. players. Then, of
course, the U.S. players have won almost every major since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, some of these younger guys started stepping up, and
now it is the young guys that are in control of the tour. That
happens for a season, and then Tom Watson wins and Couples wins a
couple of times, and suddenly, it is the old guys again.
</P>
<P>
   ``So things kind of go in cycles. And great players are great
players period, no matter how old they are. The old guys never went
anywhere. It is just that the younger guys played a little better
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But this year there has been a rebirth for some. Couples, who
hadn't won since the 1996 Players Championship, got on the board
early, winning the second event of the year, the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic. He won again at the Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Scott Simpson, 42, picked up his first victory in
five years, winning the Buick Invitational. Then came O'Meara's
green jacket at Augusta National. With most of the attention on
Couples and Duval, O'Meara sank a curling 20-footer for birdie on
the 72nd hole to steal the Masters title.
</P>
<P>
   Six events later, it would be Watson's turn.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, like most of the seasoned golfers on tour, wasn't
surprised by the change in fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many good players now in the world, and a lot of
them happen to be young,'' O'Meara said. ``They have burst onto the
scene with high expectations, and they have lived up to those
expectations. There is just so much talent that it is very
interesting to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact is, I have actually played some of my best golf
over the last three, four years. I am now 41 years old. Tom Watson
has been playing some extremely good golf. Obviously, his putting
touch has returned because we saw that at Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's nice to have a good mix. And I have said
this before: The golf ball is sitting out there on the ground. It
really doesn't know how old you are. It doesn't know if you are 20
or 30 or 50 or 60 or 70. It just kind of sits there waiting to be
struck. That is what makes this game so special.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the young golfers must be given their due. If asked
who is the most dominant player of the moment, most would point to
Duval. He won the Tucson Chrysler Classic and the Shell Houston
Open, and has contended nearly every week. Duval has missed just
one cut and finished in the top 15 seven times, most recently at
the U.S. Open, where he was tied for seventh on the treacherous
Olympic Club course.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from when Duval first joined the tour and
seemed unable to win. In his first three seasons on tour, he was in
the top 10 18 times before winning his last three events in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt that I could succeed out here,'' Duval said.
``Now, I think it is a big jump and a big assumption to expect to
win that many golf tournaments that quickly and in that short of a
span of time. But it just happened to work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as you do it and the more you do it, the more
confidence you get because you realize that there are many
different ways to win. So then comes Sunday when you have a chance,
and you might not be quite doing or playing the way you had
envisioned, but you realize that there is more than one way to go
about it, and there is more than one way to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Other younger golfers joining Duval in the winner's circle this
season are also household names. Defending British Open champion
Justin Leonard captured a big victory at The Players Championship.
Phil Mickelson began the year by winning the Mercedes
Championships, and Ernie Els was in the winner's circle at the Bay
Hill Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Woods. Last year, he was the dominant golfer. He
started with a win at the Mercedes Championships in 1997, followed
it up with an unbelievable performance at the Masters, then added
two victories down the stretch. He was the 1997 Player of the Year
and the leading money winner.
</P>
<P>
   Tigermania has not calmed, but Woods doesn't seem to have the
same flash as he did a year ago. He got his first win of the season
in May at the BellSouth Classic. But his all-out assault on the PGA
Tour appears to have hit a few snags.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Meara, for one, believes it is only a matter of time
before Woods dominates again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger is really hitting the ball well,'' said O'Meara, perhaps
Woods closest friend on tour. ``He is swinging as good as I have
seen him swing. And if Tiger is not the best, he is right there.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps now is the time for the golfers in their 30s to make
their noise. Lee Janzen, 33, hadn't won since he captured three
tournaments in 1995. With the new players on the scene and the
veterans making a splash, Janzen was all but forgotten. He proved
at the U.S. Open that he is anything but gone.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen's even-par effort at the Olympic Club was superb. He
refused to let the pressure of the event, or of the course, get to
him. And he gave a demonstration in patience that was inspiring.
That's why it was Janzen who cradled the U.S. Open trophy, tears in
his eyes, when the second major of the season came to a close.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, heading into the British Open, it's anybody's guess
who will have an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at anybody as a young guy or an old guy,''
Leonard said. ``Golf isn't really a sport where age makes a huge
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it depends on the individual. I mean, sure, the
difference between a 15-year-old and a 30-year-old is a big
difference. But once you are a professional on the PGA Tour, I
don't think age is as great a factor as people make it out to be.
The way the tour is these days, anyone can win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
