<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MERCURY-MYSTICS-A     06-29 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-MYSTICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MERCURY WINS, MILLER SEES FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``It's only two points!'' someone in the crowd of
15,191 at the MCI Center yelled at Cheryl Miller on Sunday as she
leaped off the bench to celebrate a brilliant coast-to-coast play
by 6-foot-8 Maria Stepanova.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, two ``big'' points,'' the Mercury coach shot back, and
not just because it capped a 14-3 run that put away the Washington
Mystics in an 86-69 victory.
</P>
<P>
   What Stepanova did _ block former American Basketball League
Most Valuable Player Nikki McCray, then race downcourt to convert a
layup _ was huge because of the long-term implications. If the
Russian, a 19-year-old just off the injured list with only seven
minutes of prior playing time, can play like that now, how much
more is possible in the years to come?
</P>
<P>
   Miller turned to Stepanova with 9:46 remaining and the Mercury
(6-1) unable to finish off the expansion Mystics (1-6), much like a
game in Phoenix on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Mystics got two points closer, 60-52, before Stepanova
triggered the killer run with 11 points, six rebounds, two blocks
and an assist in 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That after learning in the morning she would play for the first
time in almost two weeks, swapping places with Brandy Reed
(patellar tendinitis, right knee) on the 11-player active list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice seeing Stepanova come in and play well,'' Miller
said of her first-round draft pick. ``The crowd was kind of getting
on me a little bit because she blocked a shot and scored two
points, I'm like, `Yeah, but she's 19 years old.' There is this
huge future for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was neat to see her respond to being thrown into that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller speaks limited Russian and supplements her vocabulary
with the help of interpreter Yelena Badalyants, telling Stepanova
to run, be aggressive and take it to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very helpful to have your coach not only to tell you
when you're doing something bad, but when you're doing something
good as well, and that's what Cheryl does,'' Stepanova said through
the interpreter. ``It is very helpful for morale and makes you want
to go out and play more and prove to your coach that you can do it
and to not let her down.
</P>
<P>
   ``She communicates with her team, I have learned, not just as a
coach but as a good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller could well throw Stepanova into the WNBA's highest
profile arena, Madison Square Garden, on national television
against the New York Liberty at 4:30 p.m. today. The back-to-back
games are the second of the season for the Mercury, which swept Los
Angeles and Washington at home on the first occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even (if) she has (only) a minute to play on the court, she'll
set out to prove herself,'' the interpreter said of Stepanova's
comments. ``The more time she has, the more excited she gets.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as Stepanova was in the second half, 6-5 Marlies Askamp
was equally effective in the first, recording 12 points and four
rebounds in 10 minutes. It was the biggest contribution of the
season for Askamp, the first player off the bench last year, who in
the middle of April was on crutches and relegated to aqua jogging
for five weeks because of a torn foot tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Askamp's steal from LaShawn Brown and layup started the Mercury
on a 13-2 run for a 28-18 lead that grew to 36-22 before the
Mystics got within 38-25 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important for me to make my first layup, I didn't do
that last game,'' Askamp said. ``Then, that's my game, get the
offensive board and run the floor. That's my type of game.''
</P>
<P>
   While Askamp and Stepanova picked up the slack for Jennifer
Gillom, held to a season-low eight points, Bridget Pettis remained
on fire from the perimeter. She had a team-high 23 points, her
third 20-point game in the past four. It was her eye-popping moves
_ not McCray's _ that drew the ooohs, especially a behind-the-back
drive that was so good no one cared that the layup rimmed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching Mike too long,'' said Pettis, the East
Chicago, Ind., native of her Bulls idol. ``That was shaking and
baking.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettis' backcourt mate, Michele Timms, had a pair of
three-pointers and 10 points on her 33rd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Murriel Page (18 points), McCray (15) and Penny Moore (15)
reached double figures for the Mystics, who take a three-game
losing streak to Houston today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to step it up,'' said McCray, held below her 21.5
average. ``It's a trying time for our team. None of us are used to
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix and defending league champion Houston are tied for first
in the Western Conference. Eastern Conference Charlotte (7-1) is a
half-game ahead for the league's best record. Conference champions
and the two teams with the next best records regardless of
conference qualify for the playoffs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
