A1205 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DBACKS-MARINERS-A     06-29 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DBACKS-MARINERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWER PLAY  
 BENITEZ'S HR LIFTS D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - One pitch. One swing. One run. One victory.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, the Diamondbacks defeated the Seattle Mariners,
3-2, on Sunday at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Yamil Benitez wasted little time in deciding the
outcome. His solo home run into the picnic area in left-center
field on the first pitch of the ninth inning from Mariners
right-hander Bobby Ayala sent the Diamondbacks onto the road for a
six-game trip to Chicago and Houston on a positive note.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona took two of the three games in the weekend series,
finishing interleague play with a 5-8 record. Arizona's overall
record is 28-54. Seattle (34-48) goes home to face the Colorado
Rockies in a three-game interleague series.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second home run in as many games for Benitez, who has
played primarily against left-handers and has been used as a pinch
hitter the rest of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I hit it, it was gone,'' Benitez said of his sixth
homer of the season. ``That's the first home run I've hit to win a
game since . . . well, I can't remember. It's been a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter knows Benitez's potential,
but rookie David Dellucci has been playing very well, and that has
limited Benitez's playing time. Dellucci started in center field
Sunday in place of Devon White, who was given the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good for Yammy,'' Showalter said. ``He answered the
bell and has done what it takes to be ready to play this season.
He's worked hard at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez acknowledged that he wants to play every day, ``but I
don't make those decisions. What I'm trying to do is stay focused
and patient, be ready for every chance I get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks jumped to a 1-0 lead in the first inning.
Leadoff batter Andy Fox singled off left-hander Jamie Moyer _ it
was the seventh straight plate appearance in which he reached base
_ and scored on Matt Williams' one-out single to left field.
Williams increased his hitting streak to 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks left-hander Brian Anderson nursed the lead until
two outs in the sixth, when Ken Griffey Jr. ripped his 32nd homer
into the stands in right. It was the 21st homer allowed by Anderson
this season, tying Cleveland's Charles Nagy for the major league
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona quickly regained the lead in its half of the sixth.
Williams led off with a single and was forced on a grounder by
Dellucci. After a groundout by Benitez for the second out, right
fielder Karim Garcia hit a triple off the yellow line on top of the
right-field fence to score Dellucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it would be a home run, but I'll still take my
triple and RBI,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson pitched to one batter in the eighth, giving up a single
to leadoff batter Dan Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson gave way to another left-hander, former Cleveland
Indians teammate Alan Embree, acquired last week in a trade with
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter David Segui hit a grounder to shortstop Jay Bell,
who bobbled the ball. Segui was ruled safe at second as the result
of an error, and Segui reached first on the fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Cora moved both runners up with a sacrifice, and Alex
Rodriguez's grounder to short allowed pinch runner Rich Amaral to
score the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was disappointed that he couldn't hold the lead,
Anderson said, ``Of course, you'd like to have the `W' put next to
your own name, but the bottom line is, our team won. My first goal
is to keep us in the game and give us a chance to win, and I did
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In seven innings, Anderson gave up five hits and two runs, one
earned, walked one and struck out one.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, it was decision time for Mariners Manager Lou
Piniella. Should he leave Moyer in? He was pitching well. Or should
he go to his volatile bullpen? At the Kingdome, the fans begin to
boo when the bullpen phone rings, or they tack up banners that say,
``Refuse to Use.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella went with Ayala, who retired Travis Lee, Williams and
Dellucci in order. Then came the quick encounter in the ninth with
Benitez, who gave Embree his second victory.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Benitez was wearing his batting helmet,
because he was mobbed by his teammates and slapped on the head
after crossing the plate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
