<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TRADE-TALKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES CHASE PREDATORS IN DEAL FOR CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB McManaman  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes hope to complete a trade with the
expansion Nashville Predators today that will bring them one of two
centers, either Craig Darby or veteran Mike Sullivan, in exchange
for a late-round pick in next year's draft, according to NHL
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville acquired Darby from the Philadelphia Flyers and
Sullivan from the Boston Bruins in the NHL expansion draft Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, the 6-foot-3, 200-pound Darby appears to have the
most up-side and attraction. A four-year pro from Oneida, N.Y.,
he's played only 35 regular-season games in the NHL but pumped in a
team-high 42 goals and 87 points last season for the Flyers' minor
league affiliate in the American Hockey League, the Philadelphia
Phantoms.
</P>
<P>
   Darby, 25, also has scored at least 20 goals each of the
previous two years in the AHL. He had one goal in three games with
the Flyers in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-2, 190-pound Sullivan, meanwhile, is a decent two-way
player who can create some offense and help shut down opposing
lines defensively. The seven-year pro from Marshfield, Mass.,
scored five goals and added 13 assists in 77 games last season for
Boston. He has played 453 career NHL games.
</P>
<P>
   One of them will be brought in primarily for depth, specifically
on either the third or fourth lines. The Coyotes risk losing two of
their centers in those roles, Bob Corkum and Mark Janssens, to free
agency. Sullivan, 30, also has played left wing, where he could
challenge Darrin Shannon's spot on the third line. Shannon also
becomes a free agent on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Bobby Smith had been trying to finalize the deal
for the past few days. Initially, it hinged on the Coyotes picking
a prospect in Saturday's NHL draft and then shipping his rights to
Nashville. That plan fell through, however, and Smith later
confirmed Phoenix now will trade one of next year's picks to the
Predators. ``Hopefully, he'll play on our team next year, and it'll
be for a draft pick in '99,'' Smith said, declining to identify the
player. &QL; 
Note
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld underwent emergency surgery last
week to repair torn tendons in his left arm and hand after it was
sliced during a freak accident on the skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing a game of (three-on-three) shinny with some of
our coaches and some other guys a couple of weeks ago, and there
was a crash in the corners and someone's blades ran through me,''
said Schoenfeld, who is wearing a cast up this elbow.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of blood, but that didn't seem to bother the
former rough-and-tumble NHL defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things will happen when older guys still try to play a
young man's game,'' the 46-year-old Schoenfeld said, laughing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
