<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S MAGIC: POUNDS MELT IN VEGAS ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Las Vegas is known for impersonators, but that was no Elvis on
the scale a couple of weeks ago before a bout with Phoenix
middleweight
 &UR; Fidel Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   In another chapter of boxing burlesque (won't these follies ever
end?), Hernandez lost to a Philadelphia's  &UR; Aaron Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   We think.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the fighter could have been  &UR; Eric Mitchell, Aaron's
twin.
</P>
<P>
   The unfortunate Hernandez can't really be certain. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   At a weigh-in the night before the June 19 fight at The Orleans,
Hernandez and Mitchell, presumably Aaron, were supposed to be at no
more than 158 pounds each.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was a couple of pounds below the agreed-upon weight.
But Mitchell was 162{ pounds. Mitchell was given 12 hours to lose
the excess. Another weigh-in was scheduled for 7 a.m. the next day.
</P>
<P>
   That morning, a Mitchell stepped on the scales.  &UR; Jenny Craig
would have been proud. This Mitchell weighed 156{.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird, because I saw his trainer bring food to his room
the night before,'' said Hernandez, a tough-minded young prospect
from
 &UR; Michael Carbajal's Ninth Street Gym. ``I thought, `He's got to lose
weight, and he's eating?' I figured he'd be out jogging or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   After this Mitchell stepped off the scale, he was asked to sign
a standard contract. He didn't. Instead, he ran out the room before
promoter  &UR; Robert Gonzalez could offer him a pen.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long to identify a problem. Gonzalez suspected
that the slimmed-down Mitchell was in fact Eric.
</P>
<P>
   Eric, a good welterweight, fights at 147. Aaron, a good super
middleweight, is comfortable at 168. But, hey, they look like each
other, so what's a few pounds between twins?
</P>
<P>
   For Hernandez, plenty.
</P>
<P>
   After the apparent bait-and-switch, Hernandez was told the fight
was off. He spent the next several hours at buffet tables, the pool
and casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even went bowling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had gone from warrior on the eve of battle to Las
Vegas tourist within a few hours. That evening, he walked to the
ballroom, site of the night's card. Suddenly, he was told the bout
was back on at 165 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there was no doubt about Mitchell's identity. It was
Aaron, super middleweight, against Hernandez, junior middleweight.
Hernandez was knocked out in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, I wasn't ready,'' said Hernandez, whose star-crossed
career includes a nasty managerial battle and a victory over a
fighter who was in the ring for the second time in as many nights.
``All day, I was thinking I wouldn't fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I was cheated. They did something that wasn't right,
that was wrong from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez co-managers  &UR; Joe Joseph and  &UR; Danny Carbajal are
planning to file a protest with the Nevada State Athletic
Commission, which already is facing double trouble after July 9
when  &UR; Mike Tyson is eligible to reapply for the license he lost
last year for dining on
 &UR; Evander Holyfield's ears. Both of them. &QL; 
 &QL; 
On the road again &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Oscar De La Hoya and  &UR; Julio  &UR; Cesar Chavez are scheduled to
arrive at the Valley's Celebrity Theater on July 16 in the second
stop on a tour to sell their Sept. 18 rematch at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption is that Chavez will be available. He was arrested
in Mexico on tax charges two days after he was badly bloodied last
week in a victory over  &UR; Ken Sigurani. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Briefly. . .  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Valley card is scheduled for July 14 at Midnight Rodeo.
Phoenix bantamweight  &UR; Homero Sierra, national Golden Gloves
runner-up, will make his pro debut.
</P>
<P>
   And guard  &UR; Roy Jones  &UR; Jr. is shooting only 29 percent from the
floor for Jacksonville of the United States Basketball League.
Defenders fear him, anyway. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Norm Frauenheim can be reached at 602-444-8259 or
norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
