<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1210 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SUMMIT-2NDLD-     06-29 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SUMMIT-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs 3rd-18th grafs to correct quotes from Clinton's speech and
add further material from question-and-answer session; also subs
for minor re-editing throughout) 
 (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton proclaimed personal freedom the
``mandate of the new century'' in a broad defense of human and
economic liberty on Monday in a speech at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   In his last public appearance in the Chinese capital, the
president said the United States did not seek to impose its vision
of society on China or any other nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are convinced that certain rights are universal,'' the
president said, ``not American rights or European rights or rights
for developed nations, but the birthrights of people everywhere,
now enshrined in the United Nations Declaration on Human Rights _
the right to be treat with dignity, the right to express one's
opinion, to choose one's own leaders, to associate freely with
others and to worship, or not, freely, however one chooses.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials called Monday's speech, which was
carried live on Chinese television, a philosophical discourse
addressed directly to the Chinese people, after a weekend that
featured a remarkable series of public and private discussions with
President Jiang Zemin, and a visit to Beijing's largest Protestant
church.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to several hundred students and faculty members in a
freshly painted auditorium at China's most prestigious university,
Clinton sought to broaden his audience from the Chinese leadership
to a new generation that will shape the future of the most populous
country on earth. Beijing University, which is celebrating its
centennial this year, has been the nurturing ground of successive
movements for political change in China.
</P>
<P>
   He said liberty was not a luxury to be enjoyed only by wealthy
nations, but a necessary element of human and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging China's centuries-old fear of internal
disintegration, he said all societies craved stability.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, personal freedom strengthens a nation's security,
rather than undermining it, as the Communist government has
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe, and our experience demonstrates, that freedom
strengthens stability and helps nations to change,'' Clinton said.
``China's greatest source of strength resides in the minds and
hearts of its citizens. It is therefore profoundly in your
interest, and the world's, that young Chinese minds be free to
reach the fullness of their potential. This is the message of our
time and the mandate of the new century and the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   He hailed the rapid economic growth that has swept across China
in the last decade, as the government has loosened controls on
private entrepreneurship and begun to close down inefficient
state-owned enterprises. He said growing incomes brought more
options to the Chinese people: foreign travel, access to cable
television and the Internet, new career opportunities, a higher
standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``But true freedom includes more than economic freedom,'' the
president said. ``In America, we believe it is a concept which is
indivisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke for 30 minutes, then took questions for another
half hour.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the United States sought to isolate China through
security agreements with Japan and arms sales to Taiwan, he
answered: ``It is not fair to say that either Japan or the United
States have a security relationship that is designed to contain
China,'' and added that American policy posed no obstacle to the
peaceful reunification of China and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Another student followed up with one of many surprisingly
challenging questions, this one about whether the president,
despite his smile, intended to pursue a policy of containment of
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is no,'' Clinton said. ``I'm not hiding another
design behind the smile. That's what I really believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Another questioner asked whether there remained problems in the
United States in realizing it ideals of democracy and human
liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton replied that the United States is still plagued by
violent crime and racial and sex discrimination. ``So we Americans
need to be sensitive not only to preserve the freedoms that we hold
dear, but also to create an environment in which people can build a
truly good and free life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared somewhat taken aback by the students'
suspicions about American motives in engaging the Chinese
leadership in discussions while continuing to support Taiwan and
maintaining a strong strategic alliance with Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing University speech offered a coda to a series of
weekend meetings with Jiang and other top government leaders here.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening, Clinton and Jiang continued their dialogue at
a private dinner, exploring in greater depth the growth of the
United States-China relationship and possible paths of China's
future.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was the last meeting of the two presidents on
Clinton's nine-day, five-city visit to China, which has seen a
significant step forward in relations both between the two nations
and between their leaders. Aides called the evening ``very casual
and very lively.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday began with a service at Chongwenmen Church and ended with
the dinner, attended by the presidents' wives and a few top
advisers. The day also included an afternoon of touristic
diversions to the Forbidden City and the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner, in the Zhongnanhai compound for Beijing's political
elite, included discussion of the Asian financial crisis,
development of an independent judiciary in China and American
movies. Jiang recalled enjoying ``Gone with the Wind'' several
years ago in Shanghai, according to an American official who
attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went way beyond what people thought were the
possibilities of having this kind of discussion,'' Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said of the two days of meetings between
the two presidents. ``We have moved the relationship into a
qualitatively and quantitatively different direction.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
