<HEADER>
A1212 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-2NDLD-2N     06-29 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-2NDLD-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BEIJING: different direction.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Albright and other American officials were still clearly elated
by the news conference on Saturday in which Clinton and Jiang
engaged in an animated debate on topics that for years were not the
subject of public discussion _ religious freedom, Tibet and the
role of the individual and the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press conference was a truly remarkable event and one that
is going to have long-term repercussions _ positive ones,''
Albright said in a session with reporters at the Diaoyutai state
guest compound here. But in a reminder that not everything has
changed in China, American security officials had posted a notice
on the wall of the room where Albright spoke, reading, ``The walls
have ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright and two other American officials _ Sandy Berger, the
national security adviser, and James Sasser, the ambassador to
China _ said on Sunday that 600 million Chinese had seen the news
conference, carried live on China Central Television, the state
network.
</P>
<P>
   That number seemed a significant exaggeration, given that there
are an estimated 300 million television sets in China and there was
no advance notice that the news conference would be carried live.
It was difficult to find Chinese who had seen the live broadcast,
and state television rebroadcast only selected portions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Sunday, the president and his wife, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, attended services at Chongwenmen Church, the largest
officially sanctioned Protestant church in Beijing, with more than
2,000 members. The congregation gave Clinton a bilingual Bible and
asked him to speak to the overflow crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrate with you the growth of the practice of our faith
in China,'' Clinton said in remarks that lasted less than five
minutes. ``I believe our faith calls upon us to seek unity with
people across the world with different backgrounds and races and
creeds.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I believe Chinese and Americans are brothers and
sisters as children of God. We come here in that spirit today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and their daughter, Chelsea, spent Sunday afternoon
touring the Forbidden City and the section of the Great Wall at
Mutianyu. The authorities cleared the Forbidden City complex for
the Clintons, only the third time they have done so, American
officials said. The previous times were for a tour by President
Richard Nixon and for the making of the film ``The Last Emperor.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the wall ``quite unbelievable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
