<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-EMBREE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS DUO DOMINATE MARINERS  
 REUNITED MATES SHINE ON MOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The (comedy?) team of Brian Anderson and Alan Embree has been
reunited. Look for more yuks in the clubhouse. Practically
speaking, the Diamondbacks would prefer more of what transpired
Sunday, when Anderson and Embree combined on a 3-2 victory over the
slugging Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Embree was acquired Tuesday from Atlanta for Russ Springer. The
somewhat flaky left-handers (there is probably a redundancy in
that) were teammates with the Cleveland Indians in 1996. Embree was
already with the club when Anderson reported from the minors.
According to Anderson, this is the first thing Embree said to him:
``You wish you threw as hard as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson recalls thinking, ``That's a real jerk. But impressive,
nonetheless.''
</P>
<P>
   Embree further endeared himself when the two were playing catch,
separated by a short distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He uncorks an 0-2 fastball off my chest,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Embree said, ``I didn't do it on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Embree said, ``He had that cocky strut, that
gung-ho (expletive) catching flies. I just wanted to knock him down
to size.''
</P>
<P>
   The two parted after that season. Anderson stayed with the
Indians in 1997, went 4-2 and pitched brilliantly in the playoffs
and World Series. Then he was the Diamondbacks' No. 1 pick in the
expansion draft. Embree, meanwhile, was traded to Atlanta as part
of the big Kenny Lofton-Marquis Grissom-David Justice deal. He had
a 3-1 record, and appeared only briefly in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are teammates once more. Against the Mariners, Anderson
pitched seven strong innings before coming out after giving up a
lead-off single to Dan Wilson in the eighth. The Diamondbacks were
up, 2-1. Embree came in and yielded an infield hit to pinch-hitter
David Segui. Joey Cora sacrificed the runners to second and third,
and Alex Rodriguez grounded out, scoring Wilson to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   Embree got through the ninth inning and then got his first
Diamondbacks victory when Yamil Benitez led off the bottom of the
ninth with a home run off Bobby Ayala. Anderson has yet to win at
Bank One Ballpark, although his last two home starts have been good
enough to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you want that win, you want to see that `W' next to
your name,'' said Anderson, who was charged with two runs in his
seven innings. ``But we won. The day I start to bitch and moan when
I think I should have won is the day I quit. The bottom line is,
don't give up a hit leading off the eighth inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson gave up just five hits. The only other run off him was
a solo home run by Ken Griffey Jr. in the sixth. It was Griffey's
32nd homer of the year, which leads the American League. Griffey
golfed a low change-up into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say?,'' Anderson said. ``He's a great hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson continued to help himself by picking off base runners.
He nailed Rodriguez in the fourth for his seventh pick-off of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Embree also picked off a runner, getting pinch-runner Jeff Huson
in the ninth. That happened after slugger Jay Buhner popped out to
Embree trying to sacrifice. Buhner hadn't sacrificed since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised,'' Embree said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the effectiveness of the Atlanta starters, Embree was
a bit player with the Braves. Here, he already has assumed a major
role, coming in with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I'm most effective,'' he said. ``Blow-out
situations are no fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And he still throws harder than Anderson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
