 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2459 - JUNE 29, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. SMASHING THE IRON RICE BOWL The preeminent symbol of the
Chinese Communist Party's economic policies has been an unbreakable
iron rice bowl, standing for cradle-to-grave social security. But
with Beijing unable to keep its state enterprises - behemoths that
employ about 76 million workers - afloat, China is teetering
between economic reform and social unrest. At the last count, 15
million workers were officially estimated to be redundant, and the
real number may be higher. Beijing must cushion their fall to avoid
a second Tiananmen Square uprising. The iron rice bowl is cracking
and may soon shatter. By Neil C. Hughes. From Foreign Affairs
magazine. 3,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
CHINA WILL BE ASIA'S NEW SOURCE OF ECONOMIC STABILITY Stephen S.
Roach, chief economist and director of global economics for Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, writes that China, not Japan, is now the
economic and geopolitical leader of Asia - a shift that will also
have a lasting and profound impact on world financial markets. New
York Times Op-Ed. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
INDONESIA COULD TRAVEL THE PATH OF THE RUSSIAN
</P>
<P>
   AND IRANIAN REVOLUTIONS Indonesia may be facing a two-stage
revolution, with the worst yet to come. In Stage 1, the old emperor
goes out. In Stage 2, an ineffectual transitional regime is
overthrown by a more permanent, extremist successor. In the case of
Indonesia, that move could be toward an anti-Western radicalism
with Islamist overtones. By Walter Russell Mead. The New York Times
Magazine. 1,300 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
A MATTER OF HONOUR It wasn't publicly announced, but the U.S. Navy
has ruled that the late Admiral Mike Boorda was entitled to wear
two combat award designations that were being called into question
when he committed suicide two years ago. Boorda, the Navy's
highest-ranking officer as chief of naval operations, shot himself
on May 16, 1996. He was the target of a Newsweek probe, by writers
including defence reporter John Barry and Army Colonel David
Hackworth. By Nick Kotz. From Washingtonian Magazine. 2,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
WE ARE FAMILY The family is facing the future in better shape than
statistics about single-person households and high rates of divorce
suggest, says Christina Hardyment. Family ties remain strong, but
the shape of the family is changing as we find new solutions to
suit changing times. From Prospect magazine. (N/A U.K.) 3,000
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
THE BLACK AND THE RED A French book on communism ('Le Livre Noir Du
Communisme : Crime, Terreur et Repression' by Stephane Courtois,)
equates Hitler's 'genocide of race' with Stalin's 'genocide of
class.' Timothy Garton Ash considers the implications of comparing
Nazism and communism. From Prospect magazine. (N/A U.K.) 2,000
words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
THE CAUCASIAN WAR Two books chronicle Russia's disastrous
intervention to quash the Chechen uprising. Review by Bill Keller.
From The New York Times Book Review. 1,500 words. (Bill Keller,
managing editor of The New York Times, was the paper's Moscow
correspondent from 1986 to 1991.)
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
DO FLAME-RETARDANTS EXTINGUISH SEA LIFE? Brominated flame
retardants are used in products as diverse as cars, computers,
textiles and TV sets. The chemicals have turned up in the body
tissues of whales and dolphins, showing that they may be polluting
the oceans. By Helen Phillips. Nature News Service. 500 words. (N/A
France and Spain.) Embargo 18h00 GMT Wednesday, July 1.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
From MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE :  &QR;  INTERFERON COULD HALT
PROGRESS OF EARLY MELANOMA: Treatment with the natural
immune-system protein interferon may help prevent one type of skin
cancer from turning deadly. By Merritt McKinney. 500 words.  &QR;  HELP
YOUR BODY MANAGE THE HEAT THIS SUMMER: Summer sun spells fun for
many people, but for some it may prove deadly. Here's how to stay
safe in the heat. By Saralie Faivelson. 500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
SMALL WILL BE BEAUTIFUL : Early next century, your friends will be
calling you on your wristfone as you watch the TV on your glasses.
David Pescovitz looks at the first steps in this incredible
shrinking feat. From New Scientist magazine. 1,500 words. (N/A
Australia, New Zealand, Brazil.)
</P>
