<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STUDENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FINDS CHINESE NATIONALISM ALIVE AND WELL ON CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
   A News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ Questions posed to President Clinton by Chinese
university students Monday reflected nationalistic sentiments that
recall China's historic fear of foreigners and foreign culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have asked me some very good questions today that have an
element of criticism in them,'' Clinton told students and faculty
at Peking University before flying to the fabled port city of
Shanghai, the commercial hub at the mouth of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
   Five of seven questions posed to Clinton by students at Peking
University reflected undercurrents of nationalism or anti-foreign
sentiment. Many Chinese still resent the foreign intervention that
began in the early 1800s with Europeans' forced creation of trading
enclaves followed later by Japanese occupation that didn't end
until allied victory in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   THe hour-long nationally-televised appearance with the students
saw Clinton challenged by questions about U.S. weapons sales to
Taiwan and U.S.-Japanese security arrangements that some Chinese
worry is aimed at China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the students' sharp-edged questions will help him
``understand how what I say is perceived by others'' and enable him
to tailor his approach so that he can ``be a more effective
president for my people and for the things we believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his team urged greater democratic reforms, saying
the changes promise more prosperity for a nation with a paltry per
capita annual income of $750 _ barely 3 percent of citizens of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want China to be successful, secure and open,'' Clinton
said. ``Our two nations will be far better off working together
than apart.''
</P>
<P>
   One student, seeking to defend China's indignation over U.S.
weapons sales to nearby Taiwan, asked whether Clinton would allow a
foreign nation to sell missiles to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said U.S. sales of defensive weapons to Taiwan should
not impede reunification negotiations between Beijing and Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   The students' questions won greater applause than Clinton's
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask me: `Do I really want to contain China?''' Clinton
told one student. ``The answer is no. I want partnership. I'm not
hiding another design behind a smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Students and faculty members said they welcomed Clinton's visit
to China _ the first by an American president since the 1989
crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators that left up to 800 dead
and hundreds more imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Meng Zhaorong, a Peking University faculty member in her
mid-60s, called Clinton's overtures ``very necessary because they
help our two nations understand each other.'' But Meng complained
that Clinton is spending too much time with China's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope President Clinton comes back to China to talk to the
masses and the average people,'' Meng said.
</P>
<P>
   Jian Yi, 22, one of 24,000 students at the elite university,
said Clinton's visit is merely a beginning. ``Relations will be
even better if the next president after 2000 comes to Beijing,''
Jian said.
</P>
<P>
   A 19-year-old junior from Harbin near the Russian border who is
majoring in business management said Clinton's foray shows ``quite
a different attitude than other U.S. leaders who view China through
the past. The student, who declined to be identified, said
Clinton's ``attitude will help our generation in the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Yun, a student who heard Clinton's remarks on a radio,
said Clinton misunderstands China's record on human rights. His
critiques ``do not suit the conditions in today's China,'' Zhang
said. ``His understanding of China is not very deep or complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang Yushi, 20, a computer major, said that China ``can't go in
one step from a stable socialist country to everyone having freedom
of speech, freedom of assembly.'' Yushi added: ``It would lead to
chaos. We need to go slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Roth, assistant secretary of state for East Asian
affairs and a Clinton adviser, said China's next generation of
leaders reflects ``some real friendship'' for the United States
offset by ``the growing nationalism'' of current leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that we have to deal with in the future,''
Roth added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton carefully couched his appeals for greater democratic
freedoms with the promise that ``freedom strengthens stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, on a nine-day visit to five Chinese cities, did not
mention the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre, Taiwan or Tibet during
a 31-minute address to more than 500 students and faculty members
that was broadcast across this nation of 1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The freest possible flow of information, ideas and opinions
and a greater respect for divergent political and religious
convictions will actually breed strength and stability,'' Clinton
said. ``It is therefore profoundly in your interest and the world's
that young Chinese minds be free to reach the fullness of their
potential.''
</P>
</TEXT>
