<SLUG> BC-R-JERUSALEM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
29.) 
 THE NEW FEAR IN ISRAEL: NEXT YEAR IN JERUSALEM
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating for all needing. Originally file on Saturday, June(The Week in Review) 
(duplication warning: also sent with `i' code) 
(bl) 
By SERGE SCHMEMANN c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEVASSERET ZION, Israel _ Through the centuries of dispersion,
Jews affirmed the faith that they would eventually return to Zion
by declaring, ``Next year in Jerusalem!''
</P>
<P>
   But the ancient vow has taken on an unwelcome new meaning for
residents of this sylvan suburb, and others scattered through the
hills west of Jerusalem, that Israel's government wants to annex to
the Holy City.
</P>
<P>
   Having established themselves in Zion's secular prosperity, the
suburbanites here want no part of the Holy City's politics, taxes _
and, most of all, its increasing emphasis on religion.
</P>
<P>
   Their passions were fired last week by the announcement of a
government plan ``for strengthening of Jerusalem's status'' by
expanding city limits far into Israeli territory to the west, and
by extending Jerusalem's ``municipal umbrella'' to Jewish towns and
settlements in disputed territories to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the eastward reach was promptly assailed by
Palestinians, Europe and the U.S. State Department, which have a
strong interest in reviving the stalled progress toward a final
peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But a far greater outcry came from a less expected quarter: the
Israeli suburbanites to the west. Their story explains a lot about
how intricately tied up the peace process is with the internal,
often byzantine, politics of Israelis themselves.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the plan was not a thumb in Yasser Arafat's eye, but
one in their own _ a blatant bid by Mayor Ehud Olmert to solve
Jerusalem's demographic and financial problems with the flick of an
administrative pen, simply by gobbling up suburbs to which
prosperous and secular Jerusalemites have been fleeing, with their
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Olmert effectively told the defectors, you will be in
Jerusalem, like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   And they do not. Shlomo Kanyas, a resident of a nearby hamlet
who owns a garden supply shop here and is a prime mover behind the
bitter resistance to Jerusalem's expansion plan, put it this way:
``I support Jerusalem. I believe Jerusalem is a holy place for the
Jewish people. I'd do anything to keep it like that. But that
doesn't mean I have to live in Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is simple. Even as Israel is fiercely battling for
international recognition of Jerusalem as the united and eternal
capital of the Jews, the city's Arab population is growing at a
rate four times as fast as the Jews. At the same time, secular
Israelis are steadily being squeezed out by ultra-Orthodox Jews,
who have far larger families _ and far lower incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Arabs currently account for 30 percent of the total population
of 620,000, and Israeli planners have not been reticent to declare
that this is their preferred limit. According to a recent study by
the Jerusalem Institute for Israel Studies, keeping the rate at
current levels would mean that Arabs will account for 45 percent of
the population in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that more Jewish residents were leaving
Jerusalem than were moving in, largely because of the high cost of
housing and a dearth of jobs. Another significant statistic was
that while the ultra-Orthodox accounted for only 30 percent of the
Jewish residents of Jerusalem, their children accounted for 58
percent of all children in Jewish kindergartens.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that Jerusalem is the second poorest city in
Israel after Bnei Brak, an ultra-Orthodox city adjacent to Tel
Aviv, and stands to get poorer. Another is that a majority of the
population in Jerusalem do not share the Zionist zeal to affirm it
as the capital of Israel _ the Arabs because they support the
Palestinian claim to Jerusalem, and the ultra-Orthodox because
their feelings for Jerusalem are more religious than political.
</P>
<P>
   The plan adopted by the government, which must still be worked
out by experts, seeks to resolve these various problems by
instantly boosting the Jewish population and tax base of Jerusalem,
and giving the city control over large tracts of vacant land east
and west where attractive housing can be built to lure young
couples _ and to house the rapidly swelling religious population.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as the popular columnist Nahum Barnea wrote in the
newspaper Yediot Ahronot, is that the plan is undemocratic:
``Jerusalem, which is steadily growing more ultra-Orthodox, and has
been deserted by tens of thousands to the suburbs, now pursues
those who have left, along with their property taxes, and forcibly
brings them home.''
</P>
<P>
   Yisrael Kimche, a researcher at the Jerusalem Institute for
Israel Studies, argued further that moving the center of the city
westward would only weaken the old center, and would erode the
green areas between Jerusalem and Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all such practical and political concerns, there is the
sad irony that people whose ancestors yearned so ardently for
Jerusalem are now so upset at living there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I forget thee, O Jerusalem, let my right hand forget her
cunning,'' mourned the psalmist from exile by the waters of
Babylon.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Mevasseret Zion may not have the ancients' way
with words, but the placard outside the local council headquarters
had some of the same ardor: ``Annexation of Mevasseret Zion equals
political violence.'' Those residents who battled the police and
tried to block traffic on the main Jerusalem-Tel Aviv highway last
week were not sparing their right hands, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in Jerusalem for five years,'' said Yoram Sason, head
of special events in the Mevasseret Zion council. ``I felt there
was nothing there for me, no community life, no entertainment.
People here left Jerusalem because Jerusalem was not developed, it
had no community services, the education was lacking.'' Here, he
said, the schools were better, property values were higher, taxes
were lower.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sason and Kanyas, whose home is in Beit Zayit nearby,
seemed especially put off that they were members of Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's Likud party, and had voted for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What upsets me is that I voted for Likud, and the government
was supposed to build on the eastern side of Jerusalem,'' said
Kanyas, unwittingly suggesting that his notion of ``political
violence'' did not extend to building on predominantly Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't want to live in Jerusalem,'' he quickly
added. ``Jerusalem is very important for us. But we don't have to
live in Jerusalem to feel that Jerusalem is important for the
Jewish people. Not the whole country should live in Jerusalem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
