<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-COLOMBIA-WAR-REVIEW     06-29 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-COLOMBIA-WAR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
27.) 
 IN COLOMBIA, ACCORD COMES WITHOUT PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, June (The Week in Review)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `i' code)  
 (bl)  
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ A clamor is rising on all sides for an end to
decades of political violence here, so a weekly news magazine,
Cambio 16, had the novel idea of asking each of the parties to
state its goals for waging war.
</P>
<P>
   In their separate wish lists, all of the players _ the assorted
leftist groupings, the right-wing paramilitaries, the government _
spoke of land reform, of opening the political landscape for new
movements, of investing more in education and health, and of
Colombians gaining greater benefits from the country's natural
resources. Even the right-wing paramilitaries questioned the value
of an unfettered free market.
</P>
<P>
   So striking were the similarities that the magazine's cover that
week featured head shots of the main actors. ``So Then, Why Are
They Fighting?'' it asked.
</P>
<P>
   That question has become more pressing with the election last
Sunday of Andres Pastrana as the next president of Colombia, on a
platform in which the top priority was negotiating an end to the
political violence that has claimed more than 31,000 lives so far.
</P>
<P>
   It has also become more relevant in Washington, where the
administration is growing more involved in Colombia in activities
that could intensify war and in measures that could bring peace.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, the Pentagon has been aiding the Colombian military in
the name of fighting drug trafficking, though it acknowledges that
the training and equipment may be used to fight insurgents
unconnected to the drug trade. At the same time, the State
Department has been sponsoring informal seminars that bring the
parties to the Colombian conflict into contact with veterans of
peace negotiations in Guatemala and El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Over nearly four decades, the conflict in Colombia has come to
resemble nothing so much as the old commercials for Timex watches
that, strapped to a horse's hoof or the wheel of a car, just kept
on ticking. In the rest of Latin America, rebels have laid down
their weapons, as in Guatemala; tried their hand at government, as
in Nicaragua, or been crushed by government forces, as in Peru. But
in Colombia, the gruesome conflict keeps on plumbing new depths of
horror.
</P>
<P>
   Eerily, Colombia still betrays the language, suspicions and
reflexes of the Cold War. Senior military officers contend the
rebels are out to take power and establish a narco-communist state,
and they brand human rights workers as guerrillas. The rebels seem
unconvinced by communism's defeat in Europe, insisting there must
be something better _ a post neo-liberal, post-Cuban model for
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious and frequent reason experts cite for the
continued fighting here is drug trafficking, which bankrolls both
the rebels and the most important paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence analysts estimate that the rebels collect some $100
million a year in commissions for protecting landing strips, crops
and labs in zones they control, while two major paramilitary
leaders in Colombia have become drug dealers ``involved in all
aspects of the drug trade,'' according to one U.S. intelligence
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has ever portrayed the insurgents as enjoying an easy
life thanks to drug funds. Their fighting forces live in the
mountains, rise by dawn and change camps every few days to elude
detection, said Daniel Garcia Pena, who heads the Colombian
government's peace commission. The funds have, though, provided all
sides with the means to wage a war that has become a way of life,
ideological declarations aside.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the declarations do not tell the whole story. What does
talk about a future, scaled-back role for the military say about
the resentment that seethes and multiplies when whole villages of
peasants are forced from their homes by one side or the other?
</P>
<P>
   One member of the leading guerrilla group, the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia, said he had been active in his church as
a young man but joined the rebels after the military murdered his
wife because of his leftist sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Castano tells a brutal story of how his brother Fidel
created the right-wing paramilitaries after their father died in
the custody of guerrillas who kidnapped him for ransom nearly 20
years ago. The father was tied to a tree and, perhaps mad with fear
and confinement, he stretched the tether to its limit and ran
headlong into the trunk, crushing his head, said an educator with
close ties to the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   These are intimate hatreds, whose ghosts fly across generations
and borders.
</P>
<P>
   And even within the public lists of their goals, the same words
_ agrarian reform, political reform _ have different meanings on
different lips. In some cases, they have no meaning at all.
</P>
<P>
   For some rebels, land reform is a way of distributing large
estates that are not personally worked by their owners. At the
other end, Castano, the paramilitary leader whose death squads
commit about 70 percent of all the political murders, runs a banana
cooperative in Uraba that, he says, is a model of agrarian reform.
Skeptics say the cooperative is only an effort by the
paramilitaries to establish political credentials, and a way to
repopulate areas they have emptied of other peasants.
</P>
<P>
   Now, people here are wondering whether this grinding conflict
has really reached a turning point, given an emerging public
consensus that government forces have not managed to defeat the
rebels on the battlefield. No cease-fire is required for peace
talks to begin, so analysts here expect conflict and dialogue will
intensify at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia may well move toward peace as it has through war,
bloodily and tangled in contradictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1510 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-CHINA-REVIEW-NYT     06-29 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
27.) 
 CHINA AND AMERICA: FRIENDS IN NEED OF HEARING AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, June (The Week in Review)  
(duplication warning: also sent with `i' code) 
 (bl)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ About the last thing President Clinton wanted to hear
during the first day of his visit to China was that the authorities
had rounded up several dissidents in Xian, the city where he landed
Thursday evening. Yet keeping naysayers away when any big public
event occurs is pretty much the way things work in China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip was carefully planned to show as much of the
nonpolitical side of China as possible _ villagers, business
executives and teachers are on the itinerary _ and part of the
intention was evidently to keep from being swamped in debates over
human rights. The President could not avoid speaking about human
rights altogether, but he evidently wanted to avoid dwelling on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   But there it was anyway, and it arguably made sense, as Clinton
did, to speak about his country's own beliefs rather than to
lecture his hosts about their own shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights is one of those issues, like self-determination for
Taiwan, that so fundamentally divide the United States and China
that no amount of summitry can bridge the difference. And the U.S.
and Chinese presidents, despite all the reasons they may have to
improve relations and cooperate on security and economic issues,
are almost permanently vulnerable to unexpected and unpredictable
flare-ups over these questions.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions about schemes by the Chinese military, or campaign
financing scandals, are likely to come and go like other political
fads in Washington. Yet on a deeper level officials and the general
populace in China and the United States still have fundamentally
different ways of looking at the same issue, and that's where the
problem lies. Often the problems can be set off not by some
centrally organized plan, but by some local potentate or
institution taking initiative on its own, in an act that the other
side nevertheless sees as having import far beyond the local scene.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the dissidents in Xian is a telling example of how
the basic points of view can differ. To the American news media,
any story about a harassed dissident is newsworthy on the day the
president arrives, because human rights in China is a live
political issue in Washington. More important, any whiff of human
rights violations speaks directly to American convictions about
political freedom, so this kind of report can often have a deep
resonance in an American audience.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Chinese response to the story, as relayed to U.S.
officials, was honest: The officials did not want the dissidents to
disrupt the proceedings of the president's arrival. And that kind
of thinking is not limited to Chinese leaders; it also reflects
what ordinary Chinese people say. Whatever these people may think
about the broader value of free expression, Clinton's arrival is so
important an event, in the Chinese view, that anything that
interferes with it even in a peripheral way is best discouraged .
</P>
<P>
   A more serious incident occurred when Harry Wu, the Chinese-born
human rights advocate, was apprehended trying to enter China in
1995 to try to document abuses in China's prison system.
</P>
<P>
   To the vast majority of Americans, China's two-month detention
of Wu was reprehensible and violated any humane standard of
decency. To the vast majority of Chinese, who typically care little
for the rights of prisoners, Wu was a self-serving hype artist who
was only poking about to draw attention to his cause. There was
precious little overlap in the two views.
</P>
<P>
   In one day, Wu's arrest came out of nowhere to cause a serious
rift in U.S.-Chinese relations. Each government was limited by
strong domestic pressures, and it took two months to reach an
acceptable diplomatic solution _ China sentenced Wu to 15 years in
prison for spying, but then released him _ because the views of the
two governments were so far apart.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan, a similarly intractable thorn between Washington and
Beijing, is also prone to producing unexpected problems in
U.S.-Chinese relations.
</P>
<P>
   When Cornell University invited Taiwanese President Lee Tung-hui
to commencement in 1995, so many Americans supported Lee's visit _
which he had skillfully portrayed as a simple request for a U.S.
visa by an alumnus to his alma mater, when it actually meant far
more _ and so many Chinese opposed it, that it set the stage for
what happened in March 1996, when the United States and China came
close to military confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most comic recent example of U.S.-Chinese
differences, or perhaps the most tragic, occurred in Shanghai last
week.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Lincoln Center Festival, having commissioned a
classic Chinese opera to be performed in a modern interpretation in
New York next month, was suddenly told that Shanghai's Bureau of
Culture had blocked the opera troupe's elaborate sets, costumes and
props _ all paid for and technically owned by Lincoln Center _ from
being shipped at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Although the director of the Bureau of Culture argued that
artistic concerns were at issue, it became evident in negotiations
with Lincoln Center that petty political motives _ power over
artistic troupes, professional jealousy, the right to censor _
played an even more powerful role. This was no central Chinese
government decision; it was a local official wielding authority.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans can simply not accept the idea that ! government
official might block an artistic project for no good reason, or
might dictate what is legitimate art or might simply make himself
the sole arbiter of artisitic taste. To most Chinese, even ones who
care about art, succumbing to officialdom is a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, what might ordinarily have been an arcane dispute
about a classic Chinese opera, hardly an art form that draws much
popular attention outside China (or inside, for that matter), took
on an unexpectedly political element because it occurred in the
days prior to Clinton's arrival in China.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to Lincoln Center's expectation, it finally had to
cancel plans to stage the opera in New York, because negotiations
were going nowhere. It remains conceivable that Clinton could
intervene at the last moment, to try to save what had been called a
shining example of U.S.-Chinese cultural exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if he does, it won't be the last time that relations
between the United States and China are strained by the unexpected
emergence of an issue that cuts to the core of feelings and
concerns on separate sides of the Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
