u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-CO     06-29 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Students and Clinton put on dubious show
 &HT;    (For release, July 1, 1998.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Jefferson Clinton may be faster on his feet, and able to
duck a jab, better than was Muhammad Ali in his prime. He showed it
the other night while answering questions from students at Peking
University, the birthplace of student dissent that led to the
horror at Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   But how much of what he had to say in response to the students'
unanticipated tough questioning was a smoke screen; condescending
language while working his way offstage?
</P>
<P>
   One could go over the text of the questions, and the responses
of the president, and apply it to general U.S. policy. Substitute
Libya or Cuba for China and you have some interesting
ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the United States do not trust the Chinese communists.
I'm not limiting that to Clinton's political antagonists in the
Congress _ they'll say they're appalled by anything he says or does
_ but there is little since China's intercession in the Korean War
that gives us any reason to trust them.
</P>
<P>
   While we place nations such as Syria and Iran on a list of
pariahs for selling arms to what we perceive to be our enemies, we
do not cast China in that same light. And China is serving up a lot
of hardware to terrorist groups and nations.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton was confronted by one student who questioned our
continued military support of Taiwan, an island the Chinese have
historically considered to be a part of China, he double-talked for
diplomacy's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's response was that we sell arms to Taiwan for defensive
reasons only. That's cute language, but hopefully the translators
sent the real meaning back to the students. That would have been
that the U.S. believes Taiwan remains under continuous military
threat from Mainland China, and we'll stop selling arms to Taiwan
when China stops rattling its sabers in that direction, stops
holding intimidation-based naval maneuvers off Taiwan's coast.
</P>
<P>
   Curious to me throughout the televised question-and-answer
period was that all the questions came from the same side of the
auditorium, from that section of the room to his right.
</P>
<P>
   This, alone, makes me suspicious that either the Clinton people
agreed to pre-arranged questioners or that the Chinese authorities
hand-selected the questioners and placed them in the same area for
convenience. Spontaneity and truth may have suffered.
</P>
<P>
   If one really expected one of the students to say something
critical of the Chinese government, he was fooling himself. The
last thing the Chinese would want would be for such a display to
appear on worldwide TV.
</P>
<P>
   It would be my assumption that everyone in that audience was
there because Chinese government officials wanted them there. And
Chinese government officials certainly did not want dissidents in
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton really meant his ``we're all God's children''
analogy, both in the auditorium and at the Protestant church
service the day before, then we would not be dealing with
embargoes, boycotts and sanctions throughout the world. Whatever
reasons those smaller countries gave us to inflict sanctions
against them pale when compared to what the Chinese communists have
done, both within its borders and without, since taking power a
half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton was meaning but not saying is that the United
States doesn't want to mess with a huge country like China, that
we'll put up with the Chinese arming the rogues of the world
because we, too, arm nations and rogues that other nations and
other rogues think are despicable, that we'll put up with human
rights abuses by China because so many of our allied nations still
have dirty hands when it comes to human rights _ as do we.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, the only real relationship the United States
has with China is colored green and is spelled m-o-n-e-y. It can
make for strange bedfellows.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
