<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes: It's foreign policy, stupid
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   China has been working 50 years to get over its revolution, and
still hasn't figured out how. Bill Clinton, discovering the bracing
effect a little foreign policy has on presidential humor, zipped
off to beguile the Chinese into being nicer. A little free speech
here. A little less jail time there. The Chinese are cautious.
Students, journalists and artists alone can drive even the most
accommodating oligarch half off his or her rocker.
</P>
<P>
   It's all scripted. Clinton gets to lecture the Chinese on human
rights. The Chinese get to ignore him. Critics back home get to say
he hasn't done enough. The Chinese leadership will do what it cares
to keep the bucks flowing, insisting they won't be pushed around by
McDonald's and Coca-Cola. In the end, we'll gripe and sell them
whatever they'll buy. That's our nature.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing all that wrong with revolution; some serve good
purposes. It's the post-revolutionary period that's dangerous. We
held two, the American Revolution and the Civil War. The first
worked out. We haven't gotten over the second one. Mao, Stalin and
Hitler made careers out of proposing ever more radical upheavals.
Revolution is addictive.
</P>
<P>
   As you look around, you don't see much New World Order. You do
see a lot of countries in the revolutionary intensive care unit.
Our solution so far has been to kill a few people, then sell them
stuff. Or, when we're peeved, not sell them stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E:mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
