<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN01-COX     06-29 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: We're for big government, GOP declares
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One way to hold down the crime rate is to stop passing laws
against stuff that isn't crooked. Congress is off on two such
toots.
</P>
<P>
   To cover their tails after killing comprehensive anti-smoking
legislation for the tobacco lobby, Republicans are proposing a bill
that would ticket youths caught smoking, take away their license to
drive if they have one and force them to do community service.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier bill pushed by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., would have
held the tobacco companies to costly account if they continued to
pitch children. McCain's GOP colleagues instead want to make kids
liable for falling for the companies' advertising. House Speaker
Newt Gingrich has declared the new approach just right. He would.
</P>
<P>
   And the House has passed legislation that would make it illegal
for an adult in a state that requires parental consent for an
abortion to accompany a girl to a non-consent state. Thus a short
drive across a state line would become a crime _ abetting a minor
in the commission of a lawful act!
</P>
<P>
   The bill is just one more hammer blow in the endless labor of
the Republican Party to build barriers to abortion until all that's
left is an unreachable right encased in impediments. And that is of
a piece with the accumulating assault on women's reproductive
rights in general.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives are planning to keep federal health insurance from
covering contraceptives for government employees, and the House has
voted to forbid U.S. approval of RU-486 and similar, so-called
morning-after drugs. Thus are American women to be denied access
that is common in Europe to a safe, uninvasive means of early-term
abortion. (Incidentally assuring a contraband market and thus
_presto! _ still more crime.)
</P>
<P>
   All of this retrograde energy is by way of placating the
religious right, several of whose eminences have spoken sharply to
Republican leadership of late.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the GOP seems permanently stuck on the down side
of the gender gap _ a big reason it has been unable to nail the
durable majority that it believes it ought to have by rights. What
counts is that the Christian Coalition, James Dobson's Focus on the
Family and Gary Bauer's Family Research Council be kept in at least
sullen lockstep with GOP candidates.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the GOP curia, Pat Robertson, has announced that
the lightning and wildfires in Florida are God's punishment for
Disney treating gays and lesbians as it treats everyone else.
(Perhaps Robertson will in time explain just what sin the farmers
and ranchers of the Southwest committed to be visited, as they are,
by drought and a plague of grasshoppers.)
</P>
<P>
   It is dutifully, then, that the Senate leadership is blocking
approval of a qualified gay as ambassador to Luxembourg. (Actually,
who isn't qualified to be ambassador to Luxembourg?) What's a
little human sacrifice in the cause of intraparty amity?
</P>
<P>
   Has the silly season just come early this year? Is it becoming
permanent? Does El Nino twist human affairs as it does
meteorological ones?
</P>
<P>
   Or are we suffering the double whammy of an election year and
the incoming millennium? If so, 2000 doesn't even bear thinking
about.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
