<HEADLINE>
27.)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, June The Week in Review  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIDS Now Rivals Historic Epidemics
</P>
<P>
   AIDS has spread so widely around the world that it now compares
with the great epidemics of history, the United Nations reported.
In parts of Africa, one in four adults is infected with the AIDS
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 30 million people were infected with the virus, HIV,
and 21 million of them were in Africa, according to the United
Nations report, the first to provide a country-by-country analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The report paints the gloomiest pictures of the HIV epidemic
since it was first recognized in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Death of the Middle Ages killed 20 million people in
four years and the influenza pandemic of 1918-1919, after World War
I, killed 20 million.
</P>
<P>
   High Court Broadens Grounds For Harassment Suits
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled that an employee who resists a
supervisor's advances can pursue a sexual harassment lawsuit even
if he or she suffered no career setbacks because of the harassment.
</P>
<P>
   But such a lawsuit cannot succeed, the court said, if the
company has an anti-harassment policy with an effective complaint
procedure and the employee has unreasonably failed to use it.
</P>
<P>
   In a 7-to-2 decision, the court said Kimberly Ellerth, of
Belvidere, Ill., should have an opportunity to prove to a court
that her former employer, Burlington Industries, violated her civil
rights even though she was neither fired nor demoted. Ms. Ellerth
quit her job about two months after she was recommended for a
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Court Calls HIV a Disability, And Rules on Arts Grants  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court also ruled that people with HIV infections need not
have any symptoms of disease or obvious impairment in order to be
covered by the federal law that bars discrimination on the basis of
disability. It was a major victory for people with the virus that
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Voting 5-4, the justices agreed with a federal appeals court's
ruling that a woman with asymptomatic HIV infection, who was
refused care in a dentist's office, met the definition of
disability under the Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   In a case involving the National Endowment for the Arts, the
court upheld a congressional decency test for awarding grants, but
only after a majority interpreted a 1990 law as containing only
``advisory language'' that did not actually prohibit subsidies for
indecent art. In fact, the court strongly suggested that the law
could violate the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   White House Renews Contract Preferences
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Supreme Court held that many of the
government's programs granting preferences based on race or sex
were unconstitutional. The Clinton administration began searching
for an approach that retained affirmative action in government
contracts while satisfying constitutional requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Now the White House has come up with a new policy.
Minority-owned businesses will be given an advantage in bidding in
industries like trucking where statistical surveys show they are
underrepresented. But in industries like food processing where they
seem to be getting a fair share, there will be no affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID ROSENBAUM
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T in Cable Merger
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T announced that it had agreed to acquire the nation's No. 2
cable television company, Tele-Communications Inc., for $31.8
billion. But unlike other big communications mergers, which have
drawn concern from regulators, AT&AMP;T's latest deal elicited
initially favorable reviews from officials who hope the new company
could compete more aggressively in local phone markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH SCHIESEL
</P>
<P>
   Ruling Goes to Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft scored a major legal victory when a U.S. Appeals Court
ruled that the software giant could bundle anything it wanted with
its Windows operating system, as long as the combination benefited
customers.
</P>
<P>
   That issue was at the core of the Justice Department's
longstanding lawsuit against Microsoft _ and the new suit, filed
last month by the Department and 20 states. The Justice Department
vowed to press on.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOEL BRINKLEY
</P>
<P>
   Molinari Leaves CBS
</P>
<P>
   Susan Molinari's bid to transform herself into the next Katie
Couric fell apart, in part because she didn't want to be the next
Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months after Ms. Molinari, the former congresswoman from
New York, began a new career as co-host of ``CBS News Saturday
Morning,'' she and CBS News have split.
</P>
<P>
   Her side says CBS _ leery of criticism that a neutral news
program would become a forum for a partisan politician _ tried to
steer the cheery Republican into home-and-garden chat and away from
important issues. CBS News president Andrew Heyward said she would
fare better as a political commentator, but had no such job to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Schroder Replaces Smits on `NYPD Blue'
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of tall, dark and handsome actors auditioned to replace
tall, dark and handsome Jimmy Smits on ``NYPD Blue,'' the ABC
police drama.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was Rick Schroder, of the blond hair and bubbly
smile, who is best remembered as Ricky Stratton from the mid-1980s
NBC sitcom ``Silver Spoons.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 28, Schroder will play partner to Detective Andy Sipowicz
(Dennis Franz). . Executive producer Steven Bochco saw ``great
chemistry'' between Schroder and Franz in auditions.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   McDougal Released
</P>
<P>
   Susan McDougal, who was jailed for refusing to testify before a
grand jury about her dealings with Bill and Hillary Clinton, was
freed because of a spinal problem. A federal judge in Little Rock
said he was motivated by ``compassion and mercy.'' Mrs. McDougal
had spent 18 months in jail for contempt of court and another three
for her conviction on mail fraud and other charges stemming from
the Whitewater real estate deal.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges Losing To Computer Companies
</P>
<P>
   The computer industry is raiding universities for faculty,
graduate students and even undergraduates, creating an
unprecedented shift in talent away from the academic world into
start-up companies offering good salaries and stock options.
Professors say basic research will suffer and dropouts will be
jobless when the demand cools.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ETHAN BRONNER
</P>
<P>
   Secret Missing in China  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials faced questions from Congress
over whether China stole a sensitive encoded circuit board from the
wreckage of the failed launching of a U.S. satellite in China in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon insists the loss of the encoded chip, which tells
an orbiting satellite which way to point, would have minimal impact
on national security.
</P>
<P>
   But government officials could not say whether China has ever
given an accounting of the missing circuit board.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   Hey! I'm Trying to Sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Try, if you can, to recall the olden days of train travel.
Passengers read or slept, laughed or wept, conversed softly,
perhaps wrote novels. They may have yearned to call home or office,
but, they survived.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the cell phone, and a simple trip became a minefield of
little emergencies. The train's late, the dinner's cold, the
meeting's canceled, Junior has the flu. On New York's Metro-North
recently, a man engaged in oh-so-solemn discussion of the evening's
wine choice.
</P>
<P>
   And for some reason that modern science has yet to fathom,
callers send these vital bulletins in booming, resonant tones.
</P>
<P>
   Now some riders, understandably, balk at having their cocoon
invaded. A group called the Long Island Rail Road Commuters Council
has started a campaign to promote greater courtesy, featuring a
contest for cartoons or slogans to make the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be viewed as disciplinarians,'' said Larry
Silverman, the council's chairman. ``Often it's not a lack of
courtesy so much as a lack of awareness'' _ awareness that you
don't have to yell into the things. Whatever it is, it's a growing
nuisance; the council said cell-phone abuse was a top complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the answer is a modern-day echo of the no-smoking car:
the no-phone car. Just as you used to pass from clear air to
choking haze, now you could go from a sea of serene readers into a
cacophony of ``Sell 300 shares!'' ``The '92 cabernet, of course!''
and ``The kids did what??!!''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Taking a Stand for the Ultra-Rich
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer has used his influence as chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee to preserve an inheritance tax break for a
few wealthy people that no one, not even Archer, intended to be in
the law in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   He makes no apologies. ``Death taxes,'' says Archer, a Texas
Republican who represents one of the country's wealthiest
districts, are confiscatory and unfair. Just because a tax cut got
on the books accidentally is no reason to get rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   The word in Republican circles is that Archer was encouraged,
perhaps instructed, to take his stand by House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, another opponent of estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The only beneficiaries of the mistake are the heirs of a few
hundred people who die each year and leave estates worth more than
$17 million. Each of those estates will be spared more than
$200,000 in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to the government in lost revenue: $880 million over
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The tax break resulted from an error by someone on Congress'
technical staff in the drafting of last year's balanced-budget and
tax-cut law. Drafting mistakes are commonplace in big, complicated
tax bills. When they are caught, they are normally corrected in the
next tax bill without much opposition.
</P>
<P>
   That is what everyone expected to happen this time. But Archer
blocked the correction. Since no one felt as strongly about fixing
the error as he felt about leaving it uncorrected, a few rich
families are even richer.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM
</P>
</TEXT>
