<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday June 30, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Bill Clinton, discovering the bracing
effect a little foreign policy has on presidential humor, zipped
off to beguile the Chinese into being nicer. It's all scripted.
Clinton gets to lecture the Chinese on human rights. The Chinese
get to ignore him. Critics back home get to say he hasn't done
enough. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   XIN-COMMENTARY _ In many of my homesick dreams in the States,
Xi'an stayed as still and as solid as the thousand-year-old stone
city wall. But I would return to find a much different Xi'an, just
as Xi'an would find a much different me. Xin, Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Disclaimer: The following
material contains nothing of political or social significance and
carries a rating of GG (Good Grief!). Elizabeth Schuett, a teacher
and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio, is a regular contributor to the Cox
News Service. (Schuett, Cox News Service) (k)
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ She was captivating, inspiring. From time to
time I listened to the tape of Patricia Smith's speech, rejuvenated
by her creativity and passion for language. So it was with a sense
of betrayal bordering on the personal that I heard that Smith
resigned last week, admitting she made up quotations and even
people in her twice-weekly column. Thursday, for the first time in
its history, the American Society of Newspaper Editors withdrew the
1998 Distinguished Writing Award it had given to Smith. (McCarty,
Dayton Daily News.)
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ Airline executives respond to questions about
government regulation the way the Scarecrow gave directions to
Dorothy after she landed in Oz. They point in two opposite
directions at once. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
