</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Airlines always keep an eye on their bottom line
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Airline executives respond to questions about
government regulation the way the Scarecrow gave directions to
Dorothy after she landed in Oz. They point in two opposite
directions at once.
</P>
<P>
   When airline honchos think regulations might help consumers,
they point vigorously toward libertarianism. But if the regulations
help their profits, they point toward legislation.
</P>
<P>
   This month, industry leaders displayed their schizophrenic
tendencies while trying to influence Congress. Their libertarian
side came out as they fiercely lobbied the House Transportation
Committee to kill government guidelines to curb predatory pricing.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines, proposed in April by Transportation Secretary
Rodney Slater, would allow the government to levy fines whenever it
finds a major airline trying to snuff out a small carrier by
flooding the market with cheap seats.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20 years since airlines were deregulated, the government
has not been involved in determining fares. But Slater said his
department needs the power to stop big airlines from ``dumping''
unfairly priced seats.
</P>
<P>
   But his proposal got the major carriers complaining that the
guidelines would limit their pricing flexibility and be a step
toward re-regulation. Republican leaders agreed and last week
pushed the House Transportation Committee to delay implementation
of the guidelines for months while the matter is studied by the
National Academy of Sciences' Transportation Research Board.
</P>
<P>
   The major carriers' anti-DOT position was in keeping with a
grand pronouncement made by Carol Hallett, president of the Air
Transport Association, the industry's trade group. Last year, in an
address to hundreds of Wall Street analysts, Hallett attacked
regulations, saying, ``Everywhere we turn, we face the government's
heavy hand.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if the major airlines could get that heavy hand to help
them with the luggage? Well that's another matter.
</P>
<P>
   This month Delta Air Lines testified before the House Aviation
Subcommittee, urging Congress to pass the ``Carry-On Baggage
Reduction Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Should Congress be in the business of telling individuals how
big their purses can be or whether a diaper bag is baggage?
</P>
<P>
   Yes sir, according to Delta. But why is this a job for
government? The Atlanta-based carrier already has instituted a
two-bag limit to prevent travelers from hauling on board their
steamer trunks. The policy is a good one: Overstuffed bins are
dangerous and they slow the boarding process.
</P>
<P>
   But some of Delta's less-prosperous competitors don't have such
tough carry-on policies. They have emptier planes and therefore
more room in their overhead bins. On slow days, they might allow a
business traveler to hop onto a plane with a garment bag, a
carry-on suitcase and a laptop computer and a purse.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way a free market is supposed to work: Each carrier
does what it can to attract customers. Delta, which has problems
with flight delays, needs a strict carry-on rule to speed up
boarding. Small carriers, which have fewer occupied seats, may need
a relaxed carry-on rule to please customers.
</P>
<P>
   But why face competition when you can get government to
eliminate the pressure for you? If Congress were to pass the
``Carry-On Baggage Reduction Act,'' then small airlines would lose
an advantage they have over big ones.
</P>
<P>
   The major airlines may seem confused about government's role in
their industry, but their position actually is quite consistent:
Any regulation that protects consumers is a violation of the free
market, and any regulation that protects them from start-up
carriers is good public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
