</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Much ado about nothing most of the time
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Here and there in the news with occasional
commentary, and a story of my own:
</P>
<P>
   ``I read, therefore I am amused ... and occasionally dismayed.''
_ Socrates (loose translation because I don't read Greek).
</P>
<P>
   Disclaimer: The following material contains nothing of political
or social significance and carries a rating of GG (Good Grief!).
</P>
<P>
   Local newspaper: Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan when asked if
Pakistan had carried out additional nuclear tests: ``Yes, by the
grace of God.''
</P>
<P>
   God is in the bomb business?
</P>
<P>
   West Coast reader: ``It used to be called brainwashing'; now it
has a different name _ rap.' ''
</P>
<P>
   East Coast reader: ``My 11-year-old came home from school with
this joke. He thought it was hilarious:
</P>
<P>
   Question: ``What do you do when your mother staggers out onto
the porch?''
</P>
<P>
   Answer: ``Shoot her again.''
</P>
<P>
   This is humor?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but only to the generation who will be running the country
in our Social Security years.
</P>
<P>
   Local newspaper headline: Mooning threatens Navy officer's
career. ``A would-be career officer with a Ph.D. could be dismissed
from the Navy because he mooned a buddy while jogging at the
Pensacola Naval Air Station.'' The lieutenant, an aerospace
physiology instructor, was ordered to undergo two psychological
evaluations and was charged with indecent exposure and conduct
unbecoming an officer.
</P>
<P>
   Can't help wondering: If he'd done it in a bar, would that have
come under the heading of acceptable military behavior?
</P>
<P>
   Psychological evaluations? Because a guy bared his butt? Come
on, Navy, he's probably getting ready to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Story time: Year _ 1981. Place _ sidelines of a soccer field at
a small, private school in west Georgia. The team (coed) is at
practice; my son is goalie. The headmistress and I sit in the shade
and watch.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, a county school bus rolls by on the road above the field.
Kids hang out the windows yelling insults at our players,
questioning their sexual orientation because they have girls on the
team. This has been happening daily for a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Next day, same place: ``Look at Denise run!'' the headmistress
cheers as a gangly girl of 13 charges down the field, controlling
the ball the whole way. ``You know,'' she exults, ``we just might
win that game tomorrow.'' We exchange odds on the possibility, and
then the conversation wanders away from the playing field and onto
other things. Suddenly, we notice the quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are all of the boys up on that hill next to the road? What
is that they're doing?'' she asks, squinting at the distance.
``Where are the girls?'' Seconds later, we spot the three girls
behind a big old tree, out of sight of the road. ``What's going
on?'' a now highly suspicious headmistress asks.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is just rounding the bend in the road. As the big
yellow school bus comes alongside our practice field with heads
hanging from every window yelling insults, the entire Oak Mountain
Academy soccer team bares their butts in a perfectly orchestrated
response to the abuse they have been enduring for days.
</P>
<P>
   The headmistress gasps. The girls behind the tree gape. I
giggle. The boys are too far away from all of us for any details to
be noticed. In other words, we can't see much, but the county bus
is getting an eyeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God!'' the headmistress chokes out, ``did you see
that?''
</P>
<P>
   I raise my eyebrows, widen my eyes and answer: ``See what?''
</P>
<P>
   She turns, studies my fibbing face for a moment, and tests the
waters. ``Quite right. Yes, of course. We saw nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of seconds, the girls are out from behind the tree
and everyone is back on the practice field hard at work, kicking,
defending, and glancing our way to see what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   After a few moments of thought, in an aside, the headmistress
says to me, ``They handled the timing rather well, don't you
think?'' I assure her it was the most efficiently choreographed
mass mooning I had ever witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   End of discussion. It became a non-event.
</P>
<P>
   As is 90 percent of the daily news.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
