<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XIN-COMMENTARY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: My China, my mother and me
 &HT;    By Liu Xin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ I am home. From the descending airplane I can see
the loess-covered landscape of the Yellow Earth Plateau, winding up
and down. As we approach, I see the city wall and moat, ringing
Xi'an in brick and water.
</P>
<P>
   In many of my homesick dreams in the States, Xi'an stayed as
still and as solid as the thousand-year-old stone city wall.
</P>
<P>
   But I would return to find a much different Xi'an, just as Xi'an
would find a much different me.
</P>
<P>
   I land in Xi'an on a steaming, hazy June afternoon. Within
minutes, I am surrounded by tour guides, hotel receptionists and
taxi drivers waiting to solicit the arriving tourists.
</P>
<P>
   I am also surrounded by silk: silk blouses, silk pants, silk
dresses, some colorful, some patterned. They are wrinkled, sopping
wet, sticking to the bodies of men and women busy talking on
cellular phones or waiting for departures or arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   I wave to the city tower as the taxi drifts among the cars,
motorcycles and bicycles. Women pedal by, steering with one hand,
clutching a corner of their skirts in the other, saving their
dresses from the turning wheels. Their shoulders and arms are
covered with silk scarves, protecting their fair skin from the
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very trendy this year,'' the taxi driver says, nodding
at the silk scarves fluttering by, making beautiful waves in the
hot summer sun.
</P>
<P>
   As I drag myself _ in soaking cotton shirt and shorts _ out of
the taxi, I see my mother and brother looking at me, hesitating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that you?'' my mother asks, reaching her arms out. ``You
are so dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair skin is very important to women in China. I was very fair
when I left home several years ago. It took me almost a year to get
a nice tan after I moved to Florida to work for The Palm Beach
Post.
</P>
<P>
   I don't defend myself this time. After 31 hours on a sleepless
journey from West Palm Beach, Fla. to Los Angeles to Tokyo to
Beijing, I only want to rest.
</P>
<P>
   The sun rises over the city wall, the cold gray stones standing
against the misty sky like a huge backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp, high female voice blares from speakers, counting from
one to four in Mandarin: ``yi, er, san, si.''
</P>
<P>
   I am watching morning exercises in the park outside the wall,
where men and women gather in front of an instructor who commands
them to bend, twist and stretch in unison. Nearby, others sway,
turn and push into the air in slow motion, working through tai chi.
Some inhale deeply and tighten their muscles as they practiced kung
fu. A few thrust swords into the air while others play badminton
across nets suspended between trees.
</P>
<P>
   Across the moat, packed buses lurch along the streets and black,
chunky, unstylish bikes mix with trendy newer models. I notice that
Fei Ge _ Flying Pigeon brand bicycles _ are not the status symbols
they were a decade ago. These days, Raleighs dominate the market.
</P>
<P>
   On a red Yong Jiu (``Forever'') brand bike, with my camera bag
placed in the basket in the front and my pony-tail loosely bound, I
look more traditionally Chinese than most of the young women on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   They wear brightly colored short skirts and tights, even making
a tentative effort at applying make-up, trying foreign lipsticks
and eye-shadows. Some have their hair permed in the latest styles;
a few even have reddish hair. This would have been unthinkable in
the Xi'an I knew.
</P>
<P>
   But so much is new in Xi'an: Outside the city walls, a high
technology zone sprawls into countless tall apartment buildings,
each with personal satellite dishes gathered on top. Highway
bridges snake this way and that.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the walls, fancy stores have opened, some with imported
shiny Italian leather shoes and fashionable French silk dresses.
Mercedes-Benzes and Cadillacs navigate through the traffic. Miller
Lite sells in bars. McDonald's, Coca-Cola, Marlboro cigarettes are
popular.
</P>
<P>
   Designer goods are snapped up by cash-rich Chinese. It didn't
take me long to figure out that it cost only two dollars to buy a
Calvin Klein T-shirt on the street in Xi'an, while in the States
they cost $12. I wish I had known that when I spent all of that
money buying CK shirts as gifts for friends in China.
</P>
<P>
   But more than tangibles have changed. MTV brought Mary Chapin
Carpenter's Passionate Kisses to Chinese teens as soon as their
American counterparts heard it. Politics, once a national
obsession, no longer holds young people's interest. Instead, it is
money. I found out two of my best friends from high school had
become roly-poly millionaires among the hundreds of thousands of
young nouveau riche throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While the T-shirts may have failed to impress my family and
friends, something quite unexpected caught their interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa, look at this!'' my mother says, staring at the plastic
bag I kept my film in to avoid airport X-ray checks. ``Look at the
colors, one side yellow, one side blue, and when it is fully
zipped, it turns green!'' Her mouth and eyes are wide, as if she
were Columbus spotting the New World. It was a gallon-size Ziploc
freezer bag I got from the Publix supermarket on Southern Boulevard
in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Days after that, whenever we had visitors at home, she would go
to the kitchen to get the bag and explain patiently how the color
changed. Everyone tried their hand at ``the color trick'' over and
over again. ``How smart the Americans are!'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   When I grew up, there was a saying: Even the moon is rounder in
America. Foreign products in the ``Friendship Store'' downtown were
sold only to foreigners. And outside the American embassy, there
was always a line of young people anxious to leave their motherland
for American dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the tinted windows of the old Friendship Store have
been replaced with bright, transparent glass. ``Everybody
welcome,'' a sign says.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody with money.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get rich is glorious,'' Deng Xiaoping announced in 1978.
And the people responded.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in purchasing power has resulted in a phenomenon called
the ``three hot buys'' - san da jian.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1960s and 1970s, the three items a Chinese family
desired were bicycles, watches and radios. In the 1980s, households
saved to buy color televisions, refrigerators and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1990s, all these had become passe. The China Daily
speculated on the three hot buys for the 1990s in 1993 _ some
people said cars, houses and telephones _ but, the paper reported,
the Chinese had yet to reach consensus on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the hot item on the market for family entertainment
is the VCD, a combination VCR and CD player.
</P>
<P>
   One day, my mother and I stood with a crowd of men in the
electronics department of a giant local department store, examining
more than a dozen brands of VCD machines. Colorful banners hung all
over the store: Bloody Sale! Suicide Sale! On the Chinese market,
trends come and go quickly. Retailers often sacrifice some profit
to make a sale.
</P>
<P>
   After the persistent salesman promised to give us a free
``virtual pet'' bonus, my mother took out her wallet to buy a VCD.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese Tamagotchi, the egg-sized computer critters that beep
at all hours to be fed, cleaned, amused and educated, are so hot
they are constantly out of stock. My 21-year-old sister had been
looking for one for a week. I was not sure whether my mother was
more interested in the VCD or the digital pet.
</P>
<P>
   My mother pulled out a bright red plastic card from her wallet
and extended it to my nose. ``Have you ever seen this?'' she asked,
giggling. ``It's an xin yong ka. You can take money out of the
machine in the giant stores just like this.'' She shrugged her
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   An ATM card. She was showing me an ATM card.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dan wei started direct deposit this year,'' she said,
smiling proudly. ``Do you Americans have this?''
</P>
<P>
   I laughed. Not because of the card or her question. She was
calling me an American.
</P>
<P>
   So the Xi'an I'd returned to had changed.
</P>
<P>
   But during my stay, I found comforting constants: the smell of
garlic and charcoal barbecue, the laughter and conversations
outside small restaurants, men and women strolling leisurely down
the street with fans in their hands. The bird market, banned during
the Cultural Revolution, had returned, with colorful parrots
greeting me in Mandarin _ ``Gong Xi Fa Cai,'' congratulations for
making good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   My mother cooked all of my favorite foods, feeding me zong zi
(glutinous rice and dates wrapped in a bamboo leaf), jiao zi (meat
dumplings) and various stir fries. As much as I complained about
putting on weight, I'd stuff myself at every meal.
</P>
<P>
   And at night people brought out stools and fans and met up with
friends under the city wall, where they chatted and joked, while
the moon's reflection twisted in the moats.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, my mother is scrubbing to prepare for dinner. A
woman is singing on the VCD in her deep voice.
</P>
<P>
   Love is a lock,
</P>
<P>
   I could never find the key.
</P>
<P>
   It is the end of July and I am preparing for my trip back to the
United States. My mother has helped me pack, but she has been
quiet. Several times I think she wants to tell me something
important.
</P>
<P>
   I know my mother is proud of me. She's kept my articles and
photographs from newspapers and magazines even though she worries
about my carrying more than 30 pounds of photo equipment and going
to strange places, meeting strangers every day.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I had told her I wanted to be a traveling photojournalist.
I could sense she knew what this would entail; we would see each
even less than we have been; infrequently, at best.
</P>
<P>
   I grew up the oldest of three children, yet my mother and I
never had a heart-to-heart conversation. A famous regional folk and
opera singer, her experience of being sent to the countryside to
work during the Cultural Revolution scared her so much she made me
stop my piano lessons when I was 6. She changed her career for good
_ working as an office manager at a construction company _ soon
after she divorced my father, whom she met at age 18. She stopped
singing.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce was very rare in China then. I worked hard to keep the
highest grades at school so that my teachers and classmates
wouldn't point at me and spread gossip about my family.
</P>
<P>
   Love is a lock,
</P>
<P>
   why do you keep me waiting.
</P>
<P>
   On the VCD, the woman is singing in her twanging voice.
</P>
<P>
   I open the door to the small kitchen and heat rushes out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you OK, Ma? Can I help you with anything?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   On the cutting board, colorful ingredients are spread out like a
beautiful garden: finely cut tomatoes, green peppers, black
mushooms, soft tofu, bamboo shoots, dried yellow flowers and
chopped ham. My mother is making my favorite dish: hot and sour
soup.
</P>
<P>
   Water has started boiling in the pot. I help my mother add the
colorful ingredients. Steam rises between us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to divorce your stepfather,'' she says calmly,
tears welling in her eyes. ``I decided to tell you this before you
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   I am stunned, speechless. I'd never thought she would leave my
stepfather. I knew she wasn't happy with her life after she married
him 18 years ago. He was a nice person but could never figure out
why my mother was unhappy with her comfortable secretary's job, or
why she would get mad at him for turning up the radio to listen to
those boring officially permitted operas, which had ruined her
first career.
</P>
<P>
   Many times in the past, she wanted to get a divorce. ``You can't
divorce again!'' her friends and my grandmother would gossip. ``One
woman divorces two husbands _ what would people think?!''
</P>
<P>
   I never imagined that my mother, who had swallowed the
traditional moral and social values - and her passions - all her
life, would spew them out at age 53.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why this time, Ma?'' I ask through the steam. The ingredients
swirl in the boiling water as colorful as a kaleidoscope. The girl
on the VCD finally finishes her love song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life was so quiet in the past several years,'' she says, ``and
I started to think about my own life. I realized what big mistakes
I'd made. I could have given you, your sister and brother a better
family life if I had been stronger. I blame myself all the time and
always think that you might hate me and that's why you stay so far
away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   The soup is steaming between us, distancing my mother from me,
blurring her face, and then pulling us together by circling around
us. Suddenly, I feel that I want to tell her many things that I've
never told her simply because I was not used to sharing my thoughts
with her.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never told her that the more I learned from life without
her, the closer I felt to her.
</P>
<P>
   I choke back sobs as I tell her how my cameras have taken me to
such places! Through tiny towns of Florida and to smoky cigar bars
in Havana. I could cover the news without waiting for the
Propaganda Department to tell me what to think. I'd lived in six
cities and worked for five American newspapers, even taking a
two-month solo camping trip through the States.
</P>
<P>
   I tell her how much joy and freedom I derive from my new
experiences: so much so that I now have enough confidence to go
around the world and work. I tell her that I had been afraid to
share these feelings with her because she always wanted me to
settle down.
</P>
<P>
   But wherever I go, I tell her, I owe who I am to her: Really,
she had taught me everything, about love, and, indirectly, about
following the heart and its passions. And because my siblings and I
had left her for the world, she finally had the chance to listen to
her own heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine and I are thinking about starting our own
choir group,'' my mother says. A big smile lights up her face. ``I
have not sung a complete song for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, we are conversing as two women. We may never
have been a perfect mother and daughter. But mothers and daughters
don't have to be perfect. For the first time, we are laughing as
two friends who had been apart for years, only to be reunited in my
mother's kitchen in Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
   My mother slowly drops in the sesame oil as a finishing touch.
We eat our soup like a communion.
</P>
<P>
   It is hot and spicy, just as I like it, and I know I will miss
it wherever my life takes me next.
</P>
<P>
   As the taxi takes me out the city gate on my way to the airport,
a funeral procession - beating drums and gongs - makes its way
slowly through the empty fields. People in white shrouds - white is
the Chinese color of mourning - carry round, colorful paper
wreaths, like archery targets.
</P>
<P>
   I think about my grandma, who is 90 this year.
</P>
<P>
   My grandma is among the last generation of Chinese woman who has
3-inch bound feet, once called ``lotus petals.'' Her toes curve
around the sole of the foot until they touch the heel. She walks
stiff-legged and sway-hipped. I always found excuses to avoid
walking with her on the street when she visited my family. She
would tease my size seven feet in return: ``Who dare to marry a
girl with big feet like you?''
</P>
<P>
   I said my feet would take me around the world.
</P>
<P>
   I look back to the city. The tall city wall is disappearing in
the distance.
</P>
<P>
   From far away in the taxi, I see the paper wreath burn and the
smoke soar to the sky. Wind carries along the ash and dust and good
wishes from the mourners, swirling in the air above the land where
ancient emperors were buried with a piece of jade placed in their
mouths.
</P>
<P>
   In the silence, an ancient poem plays its notes in my heart:
</P>
<P>
   Endless is my longing _ longing for Chang'an (Xi'an).
</P>
<P>
   High is heaven, wide is earth;
</P>
<P>
   Neither can my spirit fly,
</P>
<P>
   Nor my dreams carry me over the firm mountain pass.
</P>
<P>
   Long is the longing that crushes my heart.
</P>
<P>
   Liu Xin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
