<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOGS30-COX     06-29 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book aims to help future dog owners find compatible breeds
 &HT;    (EDS: May run with DOGS-TIPS30-COX)
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's midmorning on a shaded nature trail that tracks
the Chattahoochee River, and the scene is funny enough to make a
dog laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny women in skin-tight togs lurch and stumble, jerked along at
full gallop by huge, hard-charging dogs on long pastel leashes.
Tall men slow to a trot to keep from outpacing panting, sad-eyed
miniature schnauzers.
</P>
<P>
   Such places can be great laboratories to examine the love people
have for their pets _ and also man's inhumanity to dog, says
Stanley Coren, a psychologist and canine authority whose avowed
mission is to slash the human-dog divorce rate. He hopes to do that
by helping people make better choices when selecting a pet. A lot
of psychology and a little common sense can make a difference, he
counsels.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Why We Love the Dogs We Do: How to Find the
Dog That Matches Your Personality'' (Free Press, $24), Coren spells
out why 40 percent of all dogs that are adopted each year end up at
the pound, abandoned or dead. He blames psychological
incompatibility for most mismatches, and he advocates picking dogs
based on personality traits _ yours and the animal's.
</P>
<P>
   It's not brain surgery: If you're laid back, you don't want a
high-strung dog, he says. And you don't want a friendly dog like a
golden retriever unless you're sure you'll have the time and
patience to love it and enough space for it to romp.
</P>
<P>
   Coren's recommendations differ from others who give advice on
selecting dogs in that he stresses the importance of analyzing your
own behavior, not just the reputed personality or physical traits
of the animal.
</P>
<P>
   His last book, ``The Intelligence of Dogs'' (Bantam, $13.95),
made dog lovers howl by rating 133 breeds from dumbest to smartest.
The new book is likely to be less controversial, though it is sure
to raise the hackles of breeders who disagree with his assessment
of their dogs' personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it like I see it, and we put them where we thought they
should be,'' he sniffs.
</P>
<P>
   Coren wrote his latest book out of disgust at what happens to
dogs that are abandoned or traded in for a new model. It upsets
them, can make them neurotic and, in some cases, might cause them
to die of a broken heart, Coren says. Thousands are turned in at
shelters that try to find owners, but are forced to put dogs that
are not adopted to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Separation also can be traumatic for dog owners. They often feel
like failures or just plain dumb and may shy away from giving pets
another try.
</P>
<P>
   A University of British Columbia professor who judges dog
competitions and shows his own dogs, Coren used scientific methods
to come up with the tests outlined in his book.
</P>
<P>
   After studying the personalities of 6,149 dog owners, scores of
breeds and thousands of dogs, he devised simple psychological tests
for people in four areas _ extroversion, dominance, trust and
warmth. Based on the answers to those tests, the book recommends a
breed category. Once you choose a group, any of a dozen or more
dogs in that listing will do.
</P>
<P>
   Coren came up with those groups _ friendly, protective,
independent, self-assured, consistent, steady and clever _ after 96
veterinarians, breeders and psychologists rated 22 dimensions of
dog behavior.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't test mutts, which can be just as smart and sweet as
purebreds, Coren says. But the tests can help pick mixed breeds,
too _ just choose one that looks most like one of the dogs that
best fit your personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the tests say you'd fit well with a poodle and you see a
litter of pups that are part poodle, pick the poodliest one in the
bunch,'' he says. ``Even mutts behave predictably if you can tell
what kind of dog they look like.''
</P>
<P>
   Coren's book is the most recent to offer tips on selecting a
canine companion, but there are many other places to get advice,
from the Internet to animal shelters. Most any veterinarian can
help you pick a dog, based on factors such as your age, the size of
your home and how often you're away, says Bill Garrett, head of the
Atlanta Humane Society. He avoids recommending specific dogs
because the personalities of canines can vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   The American Kennel Club simply urges people to educate
themselves. This year, the AKC recalled the latest edition of its
``Complete Dog Book'' and apologized after complaints over its
classification of some popular breeds, including rottweilers and
Dalmatians, as not being good with kids.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sharon Crowell-Davis of the University of Georgia, one of
only 16 certified dog psychiatrists in the country, also suggests
people should do more homework before obtaining dogs, such as
asking veterinarians and friends for advice and observing the
behavior of the parents of potential adoptees.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of disastrous experiences with pets, Allen Bower
did some homework before buying a bichon frise.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's playful. She's laid-back. She's always glad to see you,
and she's not high-strung like a cocker spaniel we had once,''
Bower says. ``She's a perfect match.''
</P>
<P>
   Getchel Caldwell did the same, talking to breeders and reading
anything he could find on Chinese shar-peis before shelling out
$1,800 for a pup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always liked the way they looked, but I had no idea of their
traits,'' he says. ``He's strong-willed but very personable. We
have a soothing relationship. He's a great companion, like the
people I talked to said he'd be.''
</P>
<P>
   Coren stresses the importance of adopting dogs ``not for what
they'll do for your ego or image, but for your peace of mind.''
He's particularly critical of celebrities who he believes buy dogs
to fit their public image.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson's bull mastiff, a mean, aggressive breed that could
bite the ear off any rottweiler, may well be a good match for him,
Coren says. Evander Holyfield's Akitas _ which, like bull mastiffs,
are in the ``protective'' breed group _ jibe with his image as a
muscle-bound fighter, but not with his Mr. Nice Guy persona.
</P>
<P>
   But people who can't afford the full-time trainers that tend
celebrities' pets shouldn't buy dogs for image. A golden retriever,
which Coren places in the ``friendly'' category, will go bonkers if
it's not petted and loved enough. And no amount of hounding or
scolding can make a dog like a golden retriever crave solitude or
independence, Coren adds.
</P>
<P>
   Other advice: Don't buy a ``fad'' dog unless it fits like your
personality. For example, Jack Russell terriers, hot dogs because
of their exposure on the popular TV series ``Frasier,'' are too
temperamental for most folks, Coren says.
</P>
<P>
   Max Falls, who owns a furniture repair business, wanted an
even-tempered dog to work with his horses. So he bought an
Australian cattle dog, which Coren classifies as clever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's well mannered. Very smart. He works real well with my
horses, and he's got a lot of spunk. And like my rat terrier, he's
feisty,'' Falls says, chuckling. ``I guess that makes us good
buddies, 'cause I can be feisty, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
