   GREIG _ Answers to consumers' questions. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE3_ ATLANTA _ It's not going to happen, but wouldn't it
be nice if all pickups came with extended cabs and a third door? Of
course, there'll always be buyers for two-door, regular-cab models,
but it's amazing how much convenience and utility the extra space
and door add, particularly to a compact like the Chevrolet S-10.
(DeValt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE30 _ Just about the coolest thing a person can do on
the Internet at this time of the year is to find ways to get out of
the heat. There are plenty of Web sites that suggest ways to stay
cool during the hot summer. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
(f, l)
</P>
<P>
   MACNEWS30 _ For the uninitiated, Microsoft's Excel spreadsheet
program has always been an 800-pound gorilla _ powerful and
intimidating. That's too bad, because the program can be very
useful if you're not scared off by its impenetrable appearance and
seemingly endless list of features. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH30 _ Tomorrow is another day. It's also another day to
see the 1939 classic ``Gone With the Wind'' on the big screen the
way it was meant to be seen. A generation of mothers and
grandmothers will be taking their teenage daughters and
granddaughters off to see their generation's ``Titanic.''
Meanwhile, a generation of daughters and granddaughters can take
the opportunity to check out ``GWTW'' on the World Wide Web and
maybe teach mom and grandma a little bit about cybersurfing at the
same time. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY30 _ Once upon a time, folks sat open-mouthed at
their first sight of a television set. When radio was first
invented, some people seriously thought it might be the work of
devils. And nowadays we have computers that can read handwriting,
understand human speech and translate more languages than a platoon
of U.N. translators. So _ compared to all that _ I have my work cut
out for me when I tell you that the most magical technological
device that I know is an antenna. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS30 _ This column is dedicated to the literati among you
who run computers despite an innate loathing of them; consider it
your reward for reading this column even when it bewilders you. And
now...Computer Haiku. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-WATCH30 _ The federal Cooling-Off Rule, passed by
Congress in 1972 to protect vulnerable consumers from unscrupulous
door-to-door salespeople, is one of the nation's best consumer
laws. But it still remains one of the most misunderstood, which
often causes problems. Rarely a week passes that we don't receive
calls from readers who say they have purchased some item, usually a
car, and they want to return it. ``Don't I have three days to
change my mind?'' they ask. Usually the answer is no _ and nearly
always no with the purchase of a car, unless the seller agreed to a
return period. (Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   THARPE-COLUMN30 _ Fraudulent credit card offers are the kudzu
vine of consumer cons. They keep coming back, despite constant
efforts to eradicate them. Kudzu will thrive almost anywhere where
there's a little bit of dirt. Fraudulent cards thrive on the need
for credit _ and consumers who have difficulty obtaining credit are
prime targets for the bogus offers. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT30 _ Dueling formats _ you know the story.
</P>
<P>
   It could be VHS against Betamax. Or compact discs against vinyl.
Fax vs. e-mail, vs. the Postal Service. Among wireless phones, it
could be traditional cellular against personal communications
services, or analog against digital. In connecting to the Internet,
there is a coming battle between phone lines called Asymmetric
Digital Subscriber Lines, known as ADSL, and cable modems running
over cable lines. And for them to succeed, they must both overcome
the slower but more entrenched modems. The formats clash. Sometimes
one dies, and sometimes they coexist. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
