</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Theory on veterans' benefits unsubstantiated
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
288-6291 or (800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During a recent conversation about the erosion of veterans'
benefits, a friend told me he thought it was because less than 30
percent of U.S. Congress members are veterans. I have been unable
to find support for these statistics. This would be interesting
information for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   _Carl M.
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the American Legion's National Legislative
Commission, 46 percent of the Senate members are veterans, compared
with 32 percent of the House. Remember both are disproportionately
male.
</P>
<P>
   How does this compare with the adult male population of the
United States? Roughly 25 percent are veterans.Q: I have been
trying to locate a paperback book, ``Lavender Blue,'' by Parris
Afton Bonds. I tried several resale book stores last year and have
resigned myself to the fact that it is nowhere to be had.
</P>
<P>
   _Mary Ann A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't give up on resale shops and garage sales; the stock
changes frequently and unpredictably. As an alternative, why not
write the prolific (35 novels, 15 languages) Bonds in care of the
Southwest Writers Workshop, 1338B Wyoming Blvd., NE, Albuquerque,
N.M. 87112.Q: I just saw ``The Truman Show'' (which I loved), and I
noticed the ushers wearing ``Save Truman!'' pins. Is there any
``Truman Show'' merchandise like that available? I'd especially
love a bumper sticker.
</P>
<P>
   _Brett A.
</P>
<P>
   A: Best I could do is a Truman hat and T-shirt from the
Paramount Store ... unless you can cop one from an usher at the
theater. Call (800) 699-1085 to order from Paramount. To order a
custom-designed bumper sticker, call Sign Effects at 990-5564.Q: I
would like to know the rules about buying Beanie Babies in Canada
and how many I can bring back to the United States. If my friends
give me envelopes to put one in and I mail it from Montreal, is
that legal?
</P>
<P>
   _Kathy Cobbs
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't you think this whole thing has gotten out of hand?
</P>
<P>
   According to customs import specialist Joseph Wechman, a
``traveler can import one item bearing a recorded trademark'' for
personal use. This means one Beanie (not one bear, lobster, etc.)
per person every 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   I would not advise mailing it. You run the risk of having the
Beanie Baby confiscated. The problem has become so acute that
Beanie biggie, Ty Inc., has a hot line for people whose Beanies
have been confiscated by U.S. Customs. Call (888) 317-5488 with all
the details about your seizure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have heard cruises are available on freighters as opposed
to the higher-class cruise ships. Do you have names and addresses
of those that sail the Caribbean out of Texas or Louisiana ports?
</P>
<P>
   _Bob K.
</P>
<P>
   A: Many freighters depart New Orleans for Houston before heading
for Central and South America or the Caribbean. Egon Oldendorff,
Ivaran Lines and Reederei Bernhard.
</P>
<P>
   To book passage, contact a service such as TravLtips of the
Cruise &AMP; Freighter Travel Association, P.O. Box 580188, Flushing,
N.Y. 11358 or by phone at (800) 872-8584.
</P>
<P>
   The positives of freighter travel? Passengers enjoy the extended
time at sea without large crowds of Kathie Lee Gifford clones. The
negatives? Freighters' main concern is cargo, not passengers, so
you must be flexible regarding time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read bilberry is beneficial to the eyes. I inadvertently
purchased some bilberry leaf instead of the fruit. Does the leaf
have similar benefits?
</P>
<P>
   _S. Tomkins
</P>
<P>
   A: Check with your doctor before taking any medication.
</P>
<P>
   World War II flyers reported increased night vision as a result
of munching on bilberry jam. Current bilberry boosters say it
decreases the effects of computer screen-induced eye strain. The
Herb Bar, 200 W. Mary St., stocks the leaves and reports some help
is available from both leaves and fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Author Shannon Quinn agrees and advises beginning gradually (one
cup of bilberry tea a day). Remember to pulse herbs _ three weeks
on and one off _ for best results.Q: We are selling a garage that
has about 500 cans of very old paint. How can we dispose of this
paint for a nominal fee?
</P>
<P>
   _C. Reece
</P>
<P>
   A: Glad you are disposing of this paint before you sell the
property. Many buyers find out too late that hazardous waste on the
property is conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred cans exceeds the household quantity of 30 gallons
at the City of Austin Hazardous Waste Collection Facility, 4411
Meinardus Drive (416-8998). If the paint is latex (and latex only),
remove the lid and let the paint dry. Put the lidless can in your
pay-as-you-throw City of Austin trash collection.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I ever get lucky enough to meet Dame Judi Dench, I need to
know protocol. How would I address her? Do I curtsy? To avoid a
severe faux pas, how does she pronounce her last name? Where can I
write her?
</P>
<P>
   _Tania Blanton
</P>
<P>
   A: Loved ``Mrs. Brown''!
</P>
<P>
   Dame Judi Dench (rhymes with ``trench'') is addressed as ``Lady
Dench'' in conversation and on paper as ``Dame Judi Dench,
D.B.E.,'' Dame of the British Empire _ one of the top rungs of the
Order of the British Empire. (Glad we don't have to remember
peerage!)
</P>
<P>
   Helen Mann of the British Consulate says Americans are not
really expected to curtsy and in England one curtsies only to royal
family members. Write Dame Dench in care of Julian Belfrage
Associates, LTD, 46 Albemarle St., London W1X 4PP England.Q: I
would like to know the average cost per prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   _T.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: In Texas the average institutional cost per day per inmate
(general population) was $38.64 in fiscal 1996, says Larry
Fitzgerald, Department of Criminal Justice. ``The Corrections
Yearbook'' by the Criminal Justice Institute estimates the national
average cost per day per inmate (state and federal prisons) is
$54.25.Q: In February I ordered painted daisies, English primroses
and dwarf daylilies from Michigan Bulb Co. I finally received the
daisies and English primrose, which were dead.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the shipment was to be sent separately. I waited
three weeks; nothing arrived. After three letters the company
finally sent me part of the money. So I sent another letter with a
copy of my cashed check explaining I had not received the rest of
my shipment _ to no avail. I've been sending mail to: Michigan Bulb
Co., 1950 Waldorf N.W., Grand Rapids, MI 49550.
</P>
<P>
   _Bonnie C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Customer service spokeswoman Gina Snyder said the address is
correct. Follow up with a phone call to (616) 735-2100. But it's
easy to run up a phone bill trying to get money back. I sent your
letter to the company and Snyder said you should have your money or
bulbs within two (tops three) weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend in Minnesota collects skulls and skeletons of
various animals, mostly those found locally. He runs a summer camp
and I would like to give him a bit of Texas for his collection.
</P>
<P>
   Who sells armadillo skeletons/armor? This would be a great gift
and a constant reminder of his transplanted friends.
</P>
<P>
   _Colleen Huey
</P>
<P>
   A:The best selection of skulls _ alligator to warthog _ is
available from Wildlife Skulls of Texas at (713) 465-8088.
Armadillo skulls run $45. Seems steep since ranchers frequently
find these skulls.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A favorite food, Stouffer's frozen rarebit, has disappeared
from the supermarket freezer. What is the story? I asked three
different people and got three different answers: 1) What's
rarebit?; 2) Didn't know we stocked it; and 3) Dunno, used to be
around some.
</P>
<P>
   _J.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: Welsh rarebit is a common British dish usually made of
cheese, ale or milk, and spices served over toast. Some call it
Welsh rabbit but there is no hare in it.
</P>
<P>
   Stouffer's still makes Welsh rarebit, so speak to the manager of
your supermarket. If your pleas are not answered, call customer
service at (800) 225-1180.Q: My husband is responsible for the
meditation at our church. We recently heard Dr. Laura Schlessinger
read an article written by a father about the time he has with his
children. Can you get a copy?
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Lyday
</P>
<P>
   A: Requests for tapes (no transcripts) are obtained by calling
the office of the poohbah of pop psychology at (818) 461-5403.
Tapes are $40 per hour and are only available for the two weeks
after the airing. prior to a request. On her Web site,
www.drlaura.com, recent monologues and letters are posted. Nothing
matched your request, but I found letters from listeners such as
``Great truths about life that little children have learned,''
which includes ``You can't trust dogs to watch your food.'' Q: My
daughter bought a bread machine at a garage sale. It has a cookbook
referring to the manual (not included, of course). Can you help
find a manual for a Welbilt, model ABM-100?A: To purchase a manual
($7.50) call Welbilt customer service at (800) 872-1656. Grab the
paper when you dial. I was on hold for 10 minutes.Q: If you
withdraw money from an Individual Retirement Account for a
first-time home purchase, are you excused from the penalty for
withdrawing from an IRA? What forms are needed?
</P>
<P>
   _M.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Generally you are excused from the withdrawal penalty but
not from the taxes,'' says IRS spokesman Kenneth Vargas. Other
guidelines regarding this withdrawal include a $10,000 cap and use
of the money for qualified costs within 120 days of distribution.
For more information, ask for IRS publication No. 553 by calling
(800) TAX-FORM or check the IRS Web site at www.irs.ustreas.gov.
</P>
<P>
   The form you need is No. 8606, which is available by calling the
above number.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I notice an abundance (inside and out) of small
centipede-like creatures _ brown, about an inch long and maybe 1/8
inch wide. What are they?
</P>
<P>
   _Jake L.
</P>
<P>
   A: Millipedes, probably.
</P>
<P>
   Millipedes love piles of wood chips or mulch. ``They are more or
less scavengers and can build up in high numbers. They are probably
entering your home to seek shelter, like a lot of other things
right now, looking for moisture,'' says Texas A&AMP;M's critter wizard
John Jackman.
</P>
<P>
   Millipedes have two or more pairs of legs per body segment;
centipedes, one pair. Reduce the millipede invasion by removing any
leaves or organic debris from your home's exterior. Once inside,
you can sweep away millipedes or crank up the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is Kenneth Starr's mailing address?
</P>
<P>
   _Dante C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Send your missive to: The Honorable Kenneth W. Starr, Office
of the Independent Counsel, 1001 Pennsylvania Ave., N.W.,
Washington, D.C. 20004. The salutation? ``Dear Judge
Starr.''Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
