<HEADER>
A1564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING30-COX     06-29 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer job changed young man's life and Mercedes-Benz, too
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the greatest challenges facing any automaker
today is bringing the right product to market.
</P>
<P>
   Few would argue that Mercedes-Benz is doing an exceptional job:
the E-Class, sporty SLK and M-Class sport-utility vehicle are all
blessed with exceptional customer demand.
</P>
<P>
   Just how does a carmaker make the right decision at the right
time? Many rely on research groups, previous sales data and
managerial skills.
</P>
<P>
   Often it is just a gut feeling. Sometimes they are right,
sometimes wrong. Recently, wrong hasn't appeared in the
Mercedes-Benz vocabulary. Its secret weapon may well be its North
American president, Mike Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is not a typical auto executive, and neither is his
background. After graduating from college, Jackson planned on a law
degree. The purchase of a Mercedes 190 SL in need of repairs
changed his life and, possibly, too, the corporate face of
Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   With few mechanical skills, Jackson took a summer job at a
Maryland Mercedes dealer. He found he not only had a knack for
things mechanical, he actually liked the work.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months later, he was the shop foreman. His affinity for
the job did not go unnoticed. He soon became a factory
trouble-shooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a service department couldn't resolve a problem, I'd
better,'' Jackson recalled.
</P>
<P>
   From his dealing with customers on this job, he realized he
enjoyed interaction with people and made a move to corporate
marketing. His family realized a law career was not in the cards.
Jackson had cars, and especially Mercedes-Benz, in his blood.
</P>
<P>
   The chance arose to buy the Mercedes dealership where he had
originally started, and Jackson took it. But he kept telling the
guys in Germany, ``You've got a great product, but you've got to
change the way you do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Mercedes tired of hearing this, responding, ``If you
know so much, come back to corporate and see if you can do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson could hardly believe the German automaker was ready to
accept change. ``Then I found out that their idea of change was in
Germany and mine might as well have been on the moon. We were
worlds apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Little by little, Jackson won out, providing a fresh personal
focus on how a luxury carmaker can do business.
</P>
<P>
   Sales figures don't lie. For the first time, in 1997, Mercedes'
sales in the United States topped 100,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many domestic automakers are considering the
death of coupes and niche hot-rod offerings, Mercedes has brought
to market the slick CLK coupe to compete with 3-Series BMW and
Lexus SC 300 and 400. It has stuffed a potent 302-horsepower V-8
into a subtle C-Class sedan, the AMG C-43. With 0-to-60 mph in 5.9
seconds, Jackson and company realized the C-43 isn't for everyone.
With the help of super tuner AMG, they are bringing in only 500
units per year for the next three years to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't contend to have one car for all people, but we
believe Mercedes-Benz has one model or another that can personally
fit most drivers' needs, desires and wishes,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
