<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Test Drive: In the Chevy S-10 truck, three's not a crowd
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not going to happen, but wouldn't it be nice if
all pickups came with extended cabs and a third door? Of course,
there'll always be buyers for two-door, regular-cab models, but
it's amazing how much convenience and utility the extra space and
door add, particularly to a compact like the Chevrolet S-10.
</P>
<P>
   Comparison drives between the bright red test vehicle with
optional V-6 engine and four-speed automatic transmission and a
black regular cab with the standard four-cylinder engine and
five-speed manual transmission were conclusive: Both are useful and
practical, but the extended cab and third door significantly
improve everything but the price (roughly $11,000 base price for
the standard truck; about $15,000 for the larger cab).
</P>
<P>
   Compared with most other options offered, Chevrolet's
driver's-side third door is a bargain at $295. Other option prices
on the tester, which totaled $21,167, included $710 for power
mirrors, locks and windows and $395 for a tilt wheel and cruise
control. Load some work-related items, haul a few groceries or put
a third occupant on the extended cab jump seat, and you'll
understand why more than half of the plus-cab S-10s sold have a
third door.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison drives also proved that, yes, the 175-horsepower
V-6 engine is preferable to the 120-hp four-cylinder, but is the
extra power worth the loss of 3 to 5 miles per gallon in fuel
economy? Remember, most buyers don't make serious beasts of burden
of compact trucks. They're for what the industry calls ``personal
use,'' not for some other use, whatever that might be.
</P>
<P>
   When put to personal use, the S-10 is not carlike in its ride,
handling and overall comfort level, but both versions were
reasonably quiet, had excellent ergonomics because of a dash
redesign for '98 and sported adequate seating. Minuses include the
leg- and ankle-bumping seat adjustment handle that sticks straight
up on the outboard front of the bottom cushion and a shifter-clutch
pairing on the four-cylinder that demands familiarity. Unloaded,
both trucks entertained occupants with wheel hops on bumps and
other irregular pavement, and there's no reason to expect the
extended cab S-10's optional sport suspension package ($455) to do
anything but harden the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Positives include good visibility, drink holders molded into the
door pockets, not-so-cheap-appearing plastic and cloth in the cabin
and good headlamps (also new for '99) that automatically go from
daytime running lights to full-beam status as visibility vanishes.
The new passenger-side air bag is switchable, and all S-10s come
with power anti-lock disc brakes.
</P>
<P>
   As the sales numbers (expected to be about 240,000 units this
year) and average price ($16,300) of the S-10s sold indicate,
Chevy's neat little compact has a lot going for it, and all of it
is far more enjoyable and useful when there's an extended cab and a
third door.
</P>
<P>
   Chart:
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1998 Chevrolet S-10 rear-drive, extended-cab
pickup
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $21,167 (includes discount not always
available; base price: $15,230)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: Dual front air bags with switchable
passenger's, side-impact beams, power anti-lock brakes, daytime
running lights
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: Optional 4.3-liter V-6 engine (175 horsepower),
optional four-speed automatic overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: LS trim package with V-6 engine, air
conditioner, aluminum wheels, upgraded stereo with cassette player,
$2,588; automatic transmission, $1,070; power locks, windows and
mirrors, $710; sport handling package, $455; tilt steering wheel,
cruise control, $395; driver's side third door, $295; CD player,
$189; tachometer, $59; floor mats, $25
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 17 mpg regular unleaded city; 22 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Russ DeValt test drives for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
