<SLUG> BC-THARPE-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beware: Bogus offers aplenty for credit cards
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fraudulent credit card offers are the kudzu vine of
consumer cons. They keep coming back, despite constant efforts to
eradicate them.
</P>
<P>
   Kudzu will thrive almost anywhere where there's a little bit of
dirt. Fraudulent cards thrive on the need for credit _ and
consumers who have difficulty obtaining credit are prime targets
for the bogus offers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Federal Trade Commission announced a settlement
with SureCheK Systems, an Atlanta-based firm that allegedly assured
consumers they would receive a credit card, regardless of their
credit history, if they paid $129 upfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``In almost all cases, they failed to provide the cards, and in
others they failed to disclose additional processing and annual
fees,'' the FTC said.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 500 million major credit cards, such as Visa
and MasterCard, circulating in the United States, and tens of
millions of consumers annually receive offers for credit cards. The
vast majority are legitimate, but fraudulent ones keep appearing
around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic ways to spot the real offers from the bogus
ones:
</P>
<P>
   _ With rare exceptions, legitimate offers will be made by a bank
or credit union, not some firm of which you've never heard. Look
out for copycat names that might imply the firm is a bank or credit
union when it's not.
</P>
<P>
   _ There is never a requirement to pay an advance fee to receive
a regular bank credit card. In a few cases, a bank or credit union
offering a secured credit card _ a card for which you establish a
savings account as collateral _ will charge a small application
fee. But never pay an application fee to any firm other than a bank
or credit union for a secured card.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Tharpe writes about consumer-related topics for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
