<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cyberscene: Get informed about heat-related ills
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just about the coolest thing a person can do on the
Internet at this time of the year is to find ways to get out of the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of Web sites that suggest ways to stay cool
during the hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop is at the Atlanta-based Weather Channel site at
http://www.weather.com. That organization has a special site at
http://www.weather.com
</P>
<P>
   /safeside/heat/ devoted to dealing with the heat.
</P>
<P>
   You'll learn right away that staying cool in the extreme heat is
more than just a way of being comfortable. It can save your life.
You are reminded, high up on the page, that: ``In 1995, extreme
heat contributed to the deaths of almost 500 people in Chicago. And
that same year, it killed more people in the United States than all
other natural disasters combined.''
</P>
<P>
   So pay attention as you follow the well-thought-out links on
this page. At the click of your mouse, you can be whisked to areas
that tell you what you can do to stay cool (and safe) during a heat
wave; how to determine if your age or physical condition put you at
special risk; and how to prepare for a heat emergency.
</P>
<P>
   While sunburns aren't as serious as a heatstroke, they are very
common in the South. And since long exposure to the sun can
increase your risk of skin cancer, it's worth your time to learn
about protecting your skin from serious burns. So before we leave
the excellent Weather Channel site, let's drop in at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .weather.com/health/sunpro
</P>
<P>
   .html.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find out about sunscreens and lotions, but _ for those
who want to be really scientific about fighting the sun _ you can
also follow a link from this page to learn how to read the Weather
Channel's ultraviolet forecast maps that show the intensity of
these rays in different parts of the country. The UV ratings _
which start at zero and go to levels beyond 10 _ can call for
protection as simple as wearing a hat (at levels of 2 or below) to
staying inside if you can (when levels are 10 or higher).
</P>
<P>
   Our next site also originates in Atlanta. It's from the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention. The page, called ``Extreme Heat
_ A Prevention Guide to Promote Your Personal Health and Safety''
can be found at http://www.cdc
</P>
<P>
   .gov/nceh/programs/emergenc
</P>
<P>
   /prevent/heat/heat.htm. While the information isn't as
well-organized as what's offered by the Weather Channel, you will
find links from this page to topic areas that offer the same sort
of common-sense advice you got from your mother. For instance, you
are told to drink plenty of fluids, pace yourself when working in
the heat and to wear appropriate clothing. While most people who
have enough sense to come in from the heat already know these
things, you'll find plenty of details and tips that may come as a
surprise. For instance, it's smart _ on a really hot day _ to avoid
extremely cold beverages since the contrast in the temperatures can
actually produce a harmful shock to your system in some instances.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Federal Emergency Management Agency site, the last
heat-related page on our tour of hot sites says that even a cool
shower after coming inside from hot temperatures can ``result in
hypothermia, particularly for elderly and very young people.''
</P>
<P>
   So even common sense can fail you in hot weather. But, as long
as you're inside in air-conditioned comfort surfing the Web, you're
safe from even the hottest day.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
