<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: What's wrong is wrong, in deed and journalistic word
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The subject was the intoxication of language. ``We don't know
where it begins,'' Boston Globe columnist Patricia Smith said at a
conference in San Diego last year. ``It could begin when a toddler
holds a wooden alphabet block up to the light and the letters find
their backbones and become real . . . It could be when two
beautiful and nappy-headed girls jump double-dutch so feverishly
that it sends electric jolts through the muscles in their calves,
and the spark moves through their hearts and into their mouths and
they give birth to a rhyming song they didn't know they had . . .''
</P>
<P>
   She was captivating, inspiring. From time to time I listened to
the tape of Smith's speech, rejuvenated by her creativity and
passion for language.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with a sense of betrayal bordering on the personal
that I heard that Smith resigned last week, admitting she made up
quotations and even people in her twice-weekly column. Thursday,
for the first time in its history, the American Society of
Newspaper Editors withdrew the 1998 Distinguished Writing Award it
had given to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been a banner month for journalism. In late May,
Stephen Glass, a 25-year-old associate editor of The New Republic,
fabricated at least a portion of two-thirds of the 41 articles he
had written for the political journal.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's inventions included a cancer patient named Claire who
reacted to therapies that showed promise in mice: ``Right away, I
said, 'Rub it on my skin, pop it to me in a pill, shoot me up with
it.' If I could find a way to steal it, I would. Hell, if I could
get my hands on it, I'd swallow the whole . . . mouse.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe allowed Smith to write an ``apology'' that read more
like an apologia. Excuse after hollow excuse. She had never gone to
journalism school, so ``I set out to be 10 times as good by doing
10 times as much. Write columns. Author books. Write and perform
poetry. Make films. Pen and star in plays. Gig at Scullers with a
jazz band.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you don't need to graduate from journalism school to
understand that it's wrong to lie. As for her other excuses _ she
was too busy to tell the truth? Too much of a hotshot?
</P>
<P>
   After anger subsided, I simply felt baffled. Why would you ever
need to make something up when there's such amazing material in
real life?
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons I love my job is that people always surprise
me. You could sit around all day and ponder, and you'd never come
up with stories that are as compelling, quotes that are as
profound, funny, moving or appalling.
</P>
<P>
   People tell you things you know you wouldn't tell your mother or
your best friend. Humbled by the trust they have placed in you, you
pray that you can bring them to life, do their stories justice.
Invariably you fall short _ your failures a daily reminder that the
writing is in service to the subject matter, not the other way
around.
</P>
<P>
   I went back to Smith's speech. ``We don't know where it
begins,'' she said. ``It could begin when a fourth-grader discovers
the word 'anemone,' and rolls it around and around in her mouth
simply because it feels so good and that day maybe she says it
1,000 times.''
</P>
<P>
   What a sad contrast with the words of Globe ombudsman Jack
Thomas: ``What Smith had done was to take the language she says she
loves and twist it into something grotesque. She had manipulated
readers, betrayed colleagues and made a burlesque of what is the
soul of not only journalism, but all writing, and that is to write
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how gifted the writer, or how seductive the words,
that is where it begins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
