<HEADER>
A1574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH30-COX     06-29 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Netw(at)atch: franklymydear.com complements movie
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tomorrow is another day.
</P>
<P>
   It's also another day to see the 1939 classic ``Gone With the
Wind'' on the big screen the way it was meant to be seen. A
generation of mothers and grandmothers will be taking their teenage
daughters and granddaughters off to see their generation's
``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a generation of daughters and granddaughters can take
the opportunity to check out ``GWTW'' on the World Wide Web and
maybe teach mom and grandma a little bit about cybersurfing at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   The official ``Gone With the Wind'' Web site has an easy address
to remember, http://www.franklymydear.com. ``GWTW'' buffs know this
is Rhett's (Clark Gable) parting shot to Scarlett (Vivien Leigh) at
the movie's end and one of the most memorable and classic lines
ever uttered in film (next to DiCaprio's ``I'm king of the world,''
of course.).
</P>
<P>
   New Line films, the distributor of the newly restored film, has
created a beautiful site, filled with classic photos and trivia. A
special treat is the time line, which gives an amazing
month-by-month account of the making of the movie. Visitors learn
about casting problems, costume problems and the insistence of
African-American cast members that certain words be deleted from
the script. In the '90s, its very trendy for movie companies to put
up Web sites for their films, but this site for the 1939 classic
has to be one of the richest, most informative and beautiful Web
sites ever done to complement a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the film are also fascinated with Margaret Mitchell and
her best-selling novel, on which the movie is based. While visitors
to Atlanta won't be able to find Scarlett's fictional homestead of
Tara (not that this stops them from asking directions), they can
visit the Margaret Mitchell House in person or on the Web at
http://www.gwtw.org. Here, visitors can read up on the woman who
penned the novel.
</P>
<P>
   The house, which is located in Midtown Atlanta, was one of
Mitchell's many homes and the one where she wrote most of ``Gone
With the Wind.'' Mitchell's story is also an interesting step back
into what the world and the South was like in her time. The design
is simple, and there is a lot of reading, but it's good reading.
</P>
<P>
   The Gone with the Wind Online Exhibit (http://www.lib
</P>
<P>
   .utexas.edu/Libs/HRC/HRHRC/DOS/GWTW/GWTW.html) is a project of
the Harry Ransom Humanities Center at the University of Texas at
Austin. It's a wonderful repository of ``GWTW'' memorabilia,
historical documents such as producer David O. Selznick's memo to
Louella Parsons, and pictures of the original costumes, including
the famous ``curtain rod'' dress. The site is elegantly designed
and a fascinating look behind-the-scenes at the making of ``Gone
With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
