<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-JOBS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer jobs mean more than cash
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the cool artificial air of Barton Creek
Square Mall, somewhere between the Food Court and The Gap,
17-year-old Sabrina Villasana sits on a stool at an ice cream kiosk
watching shoppers meander by.
</P>
<P>
   A customer strolls up and Villasana springs into action, smiling
and asking in her best saleswoman's voice, ``May I help you,
ma'am?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a phrase she speaks a hundred times an afternoon, just one
part of the 23-hour-a-week ritual known as the Summer Job at the
Mall. More than 3 million teens nationwide work summer jobs _ and
this year, with the nation's lowest unemployment rate in a
generation, more teens may have a better pick of the jobs they want
and it already looks as if more teens are working. In April the
national teen unemployment rate was 13.1 percent, lower than the
15.6 percent unemployment rate of April, 1997, according to the
Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of that elusive freedom that only money brings, older
teens will do everything from peddling Gap jeans and ice cream to
lifeguarding and mowing lawns. But there's more to a summer job
than just money, and several experts say teens can walk away from a
summer job with valuable experience in addition to cash.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Brain, author of ``The Teenager's Guide to the Real
World,'' advises young workers to ask lots of questions _ get to
know the business from the inside out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't simply stand at the register looking bored,'' he said.
``Actively try to learn about the different aspects of the
business. There are millionaires who own their own restaurant
franchises, but it isn't easy to run a restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Gossett, director of development at Junior Achievement
of Central Texas, a nonprofit organization that teaches students
from kindergarten through 12th grade about business, says her
organization encourages teens to find summer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any opportunity you have to learn is beneficial for your
future,'' she said. ``You may not want to flip burgers for a living
forever, but the skills you learn here _ responsibility and
teamwork _ can parlay into other jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Labor, on average, 51.3 percent
of teens work retail summer jobs and 33.8 percent work service
summer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Teens covet mall jobs, since they pay just above minimum wage,
the workplace is air-conditioned, and the hours are never too early
or too late, said Henry Nguyen, 19, who works at the Sunglass Hut
at Barton Creek Square Mall in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very stressful, like when I waited tables last
summer,'' he said. ``And I think you can learn a lot, especially if
you ask questions and really try to understand how things work.''
</P>
<P>
   Teens not yet old enough to work at the mall might try being
entrepreneurs _ perhaps starting a lawn mowing or babysitting
service, or learning how to create Web sites, Brain said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Quattrociocchi, a national speaker and consultant on work
issues, said teens should be wary of settling for just any job.
</P>
<P>
   ``While working can be helpful, it can also be harmful _ earning
should be connected to learning or it's a bad,'' she said. ``Teens
should look for a job that's the closest to where they want to end
up. If you're not interested in the food business, then don't get a
fast-food job.''
</P>
<P>
   Quattrociocchi said teens can look for fields that interest
them, such as car repair or the record industry, and then seek out
gofer-type jobs or volunteer positions in related companies. That
way, teens are exposed to the career fields they're most interested
in, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now a teen might say, how does a volunteer job help me earn
money?'' Quattrociocchi said. ``Well, you get connected to everyone
working in that field by volunteering. These are the people who
will tell you where the jobs are. Once they can see you care and
have skills, they'll start recommending you for jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing, the experts agree, is not to waste a
summer doing something you hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible to spend a whole summer being miserable,'' Brain
said. ``And money doesn't make up for misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Tanamachi writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
