<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-ONLINE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth wedded to phone lines for its Net access
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth.Net and its sister telephone companies
offering Internet access have unique problems to deal with as
technology slowly but steadily advances toward cable modems and
high-speed access. Their options are limited by reliance on the
telephone network. Whether that will help or hurt long term is
still uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, AT&AMP;T, which also operates Internet service
provider WorldNet, had no choice but to place its bets on the
high-speed promises of ADSL (asymmetric digital subscriber line)
telephony technology. However, the merger with Tele-Communications
Inc. provides it with cable modem technology as well as potential
access to 67 million homes. But because AT&AMP;T is also a
telecommunications provider, it can also continue developing an
ADSL strategy.
</P>
<P>
   As MindSpring President and Chief Operating Officer Michael
McQuary notes, it's important for an ISP to be light on its feet.
``I think you've got to constantly be on a course for multiple
strategies,'' he says. ``You've got to stay light on your feet and
be able to change directions on a moment's notice.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it's not possible for BellSouth.Net, the region's
second-largest ISP, to change directions in the same manner.
Because of its connection to BellSouth, it is firmly tied to ADSL.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth.Net president Ray Smets believes when consumers begin
to make decisions about high-speed Internet access, they'll want
the phone company to provide that service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fair amount of good public response to the kinds of
goods and service we are planning to deploy,'' Smets says. ``In
fact, the response has astounded us.''
</P>
<P>
   Smets calls BellSouth's plans for ADSL ``very aggressive.'' He
says there are 1.8 million homes currently qualified for high-speed
access and that the company will market the service to those homes
throughout 1999. ``Broadband will definitely impact our business in
the future,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Smets agrees with analysts and others in the ISP business and
says the marketplace has to mature before consumers will actively
seek out high-speed access. ``First you have to get them online,
then you have to graduate them to the advantages of high-speed
access.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the main advantage of BellSouth.Net in the long run is
its ability to provide all kinds of access from telephone dial-up
to high-speed ADSL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will graduate people into ADSL,'' he says. ``Not everybody
needs broadband when they first go online. Over time, we will see a
migration toward broadband. ADSL has an incredible amount of
industry backing. Customers can buy ADSL modems packaged in their
computers and it has a lifespan of decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Smets says he wants to keep his options open, those
options are limited to broadband or dial-up phone service. The
future of BellSouth.Net and other ISPs operated by phone companies
depends on the success of ADSL.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
