<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waco bat maker etches out Heisman for Williams
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ricky Williams returns this fall as the nation's
leading rusher in college football, but his chances of winning the
Heisman Trophy are hardly etched in stone.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, no. Ash hardwood, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Sellers is the guy doing the etching. According to the Waco
pharmacist, a part-time maker of baseball trophy bats, Williams
will win the Heisman. Says so right there in black and white. Black
script and white ash on a 33-inch, 27- ounce bat that has Williams'
authentic signature laser-engraved alongside a Longhorns logo. The
words ``1998 Heisman Trophy winner'' will be emblazoned on the
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Peyton Manning was supposed to win the 1997 Heisman
and Notre Dame's Ron Powlus one or two before that, so it might not
be a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, no bat would have a sweeter spot than Williams'
custom-made model. For now, the University of Texas senior-to-be is
working more on his .347 batting average and eight-game hitting
streak for the Philadelphia Phillies' Class A baseball club, the
Batavia Muckdogs of the New York-Penn League, than he is his
football skills.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is certainly Sellers' favorite to become the first
running back to win the Heisman since Eddie George in 1995. But
that's because Sellers, a 37- year-old graduate of the UT School of
Pharmacy, is a longtime Longhorn fan, whose citizens band handle
was ``Bevo'' until it was recently converted to ``Batman'' for
obvious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers called former Texas running backs coach Bucky Godbolt to
get in touch with his protege and actually spoke to Williams, who
was thrilled to have his own personalized bat. Williams wasn't the
least bit worried about being jinxed, maybe because he thinks he'll
be allowed to carry it with him out of the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sellers is an unabashed Williams fan, he did gig the
Longhorns back about switching jerseys from No. 11 to No. 34
because his three kids had to have both souvenir jerseys. ``He's
going to break me,'' Sellers said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' special order is one of more than 100 trophy bats that
Sellers has fashioned since December 1995. He plans to present the
light-colored bat with the natural grain finish to Williams at an
August football practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is quite a coup for me,'' beamed Sellers, who in November
will officially petition major-league baseball to become a licensed
bat maker and would love to win contracts from some marquee
major-leaguers. ``I'm not trying to put anybody out of business.
I'm small-time. My wife always reminds me, `Rob, you're a
pharmacist.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the higher-profile Louisville Slugger and Easton
manufacturers, it might become a case of Sellers, beware. However,
at this point, Sellers even orders some of his wood from the
Kentucky bat maker.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers, a Little League catcher from Conroe, has been adept at
woodworking since his high school days. Some 12 years ago, he
started making furniture such as coffee tables and a roll-top desk
for his family but graduated to bat making 2 1/2 years ago after a
friend got him a great deal on a mint-condition wood lathe for $175
at a Houston Independent School District auction.
</P>
<P>
   The roll-top took him 11 months. Bats, he can turn around more
quickly. He has become so accomplished, he has cut in half the time
it takes to cut, groove, sand, rub and polish a bat and can turn
out a finished product in two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers has even taken to naming his bats like the 37-ounce
``Big Bertha'' that he can barely pick up. Where's Mark McGwire
when you need him?
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Uncle Sam,'' born on July 4. It has an added
patriotic touch of a red, white and blue stripe. ``Billy Bob,''
named for Sellers' father, William Robert Sellers, was created on
July 7, his dad's birthday. He's even re- created the red-stained
Pete Rose model to replace his buddy's favorite bat that Sellers
broke in high school.
</P>
<P>
   The artist has been featured in newspaper stories as well as the
``Texas Tales'' television show. But his disappointment was
palpable when one reporter showed up for an interview and never
once picked up, swung or even sniffed the aroma of one of Sellers'
bats. Guy probably liked the DH, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers has sold about 55 of his specialties, almost as many as
he has given away to friends. Corey Bush, the Robinson
pitcher-outfielder who was named player of the year on a Super
Centex team, has one. So does Chase Mann, Rosebud-Lott's rookie
coach and coach of the year in the Waco area.
</P>
<P>
   What baseball fanatic wouldn't want one? I can still remember
the soothing feel of the amber-colored Henry Aaron model my parents
brought me from their summer trip to Sioux City, Iowa. Some things
you just don't forget.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers' works of art are showing up everywhere from sports bars
to the office of the business editor of the Waco Herald-Tribune. It
is such a labor of love that he has difficulty putting a price on
his creations. Nevertheless, they go for $99.95, plus tax. Batting
tips not included.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls' column appears in the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
