<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ConsumerWatch: Cooling-Off Rule often not what buyers believe it
is
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The federal Cooling-Off Rule, passed by Congress in
1972 to protect vulnerable consumers from unscrupulous door-to-door
salespeople, is one of the nation's best consumer laws. But it
still remains one of the most misunderstood, which often causes
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely a week passes that we don't receive calls from readers
who say they have purchased some item, usually a car, and they want
to return it. ``Don't I have three days to change my mind?'' they
ask.
</P>
<P>
   Usually the answer is no _ and nearly always no with the
purchase of a car, unless the seller agreed to a return period,
which some dealers have begun doing in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooling-Off Rule gives you three business days to cancel
many purchases made at your home, apartment, dormitory or
workplace, or a location that's not the seller's permanent place of
business, such as convention centers, fairgrounds, restaurants and
temporarily rented hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   But there are numerous exceptions. The Cooling-Off Rule does not
cover sales that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Are under $25.
</P>
<P>
   _ Are made entirely by mail or telephone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Are the result of previous negotiations at the seller's
permanent place of business where the goods are regularly sold.
</P>
<P>
   _ Are made as part of your request to do repairs or maintenance
on your home.
</P>
<P>
   Also exempt from the Cooling-Off Rule are sales that involve:
</P>
<P>
   _ Real estate, insurance or securities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Autos, trucks and other motor vehicles sold at temporary
locations, provided the seller has a permanent place of business.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arts or crafts sold at fairs or locations such as shopping
malls and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Cooling-Off Rule, the federal Truth-in-Lending Law
gives borrowers a three-day ``recision period'' to cancel a
personal loan for which their home is collateral. In addition, some
states mandate cancellation periods for certain purchases
regardless of where they are made. Georgia, for example, requires
health club contracts to have a seven-day cancellation period.
</P>
<P>
   But as many shoppers have learned to their dismay, no federal
law regulates the merchandise return policies of retailers. What
items stores accept for return, refund or exchange is pretty much
up to each store to decide. Fortunately, most retailers usually
accept returns to keep customers happy.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Tharpe writes about consumer-related topics for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
