<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mac News: Excel makes better use of Mac's innovations
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the uninitiated, Microsoft's Excel spreadsheet
program has always been an 800-pound gorilla _ powerful and
intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad, because the program can be very useful if you're
not scared off by its impenetrable appearance and seemingly endless
list of features.
</P>
<P>
   In Excel 98, the latest version, Microsoft's programmers wisely
switched strategy. Instead of adding yet more functions, they
focused on making Excel easier to use and understand.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a program that, while still at times overwhelming,
is greatly improved. Here's a look at some of the more important
changes.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of my list is 16 levels of undo and redo. Many users
have long been reluctant to try Excel's powerful functions, fearing
a mistake would mess up their stock portfolio or home finances. Now
you can go back or forward 16 steps at a time. Nearly any misstep
can be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Excel now also lets you quickly check a formula analyzing a set
of numbers. For starters, there's a feature called AutoCorrect,
which automatically identifies and corrects 15 of the most common
formula errors.
</P>
<P>
   You can also double-click a spreadsheet cell with a formula, and
Excel will highlight any data involved in it. That way you can
quickly check to see if you've included the right numbers for the
calculation.
</P>
<P>
   Another nifty improvement is the ability to name in English a
cell or range of cells. You can, for example, name a row of figures
``June sales.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes work easier yet, because then you can use that named
range of cells in a formula instead of typing in an arcane list of
cell addresses. For example, you could write a formula that says
``June sales minus June expenses.'' Now isn't that easier than
typing A4:B6 - C3:C8?
</P>
<P>
   Excel now includes lots of formula templates, easily accessible
from the upper left corner of any spreadsheet. Select one of these
templates and plug in your own cells or numbers. You can also cut
and paste parts of the templates to form formulas of your own.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, Microsoft had ignored Apple Computer's
innovations in the Mac versions of its software. Excel 98 reverses
this practice. It reflects the new look of OS 8 and its
improvements, including contextual menus, drag-and-drop and sticky
menus. You can also easily link data between documents.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy Excel as a stand-alone product for $399 (the upgrade
is $149) or get it as part of Office 98. It's a suite of programs
that includes Word, Outlook and Proponent in addition to Excel.
Office retails for $499 (the upgrade is $299).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
