<SLUG> BC-MARTINEZ-BROTHERS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dominican Republic's favorite sons give nearly as much as they
get
 &HT;    By Cheryl Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jesus Martinez is jealous of his
brothers not because they are famous big-league pitchers but
because of the money success brings them.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a greedy young man. The millions he craves are not for
himself. He doesn't want a fancy car or diamond jewelry or a
stylish wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he sees what his older brothers contribute to their
hometown of Mano Guayabo in the Dominican Republic and he feels
left out.
</P>
<P>
   When Pedro, 26, and Ramon Martinez, 30, return home, they are
celebrated like the prodigal sons. It is a holiday. They are tugged
and pulled as every child wants just to touch, to get a piece of
the brothers for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the older brothers have given more than simply time.
They have built a church and their next project is to build a
school.
</P>
<P>
   They wear their fame like a comfortable sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great about them, but I'll feel better if I could help
a little bit,'' said Jesus, a 24-year-old who is with the
Cincinnati Reds' Class AAA team. ``I can be there, because I'm
their brother, but I can't (contribute) because I have nothing.
That sometimes gets me a little upset, not because of what they do,
but because I can't give what they give.'' Pedro Martinez won his
first Cy Young Award last season with the Montreal Expos. He was
then traded to the Boston Red Sox after the expansion draft, and
signed a six-year, $75million deal.
</P>
<P>
   He is 10-2, with a 3.02 ERA and 137 strikeouts in 119 innings
after Friday's win against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   It is the third major-league team for Pedro. All three began
their professional careers with the Los Angeles Dodgers, with whom
Ramon still pitches, although he will miss the rest of the season
after he has rotator cuff surgery Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Pedro insists he's the same person who grew up in a wooden
house, with nothing but food to eat and the shoes he needed to wear
to school. That is why he pours so much of his time and money back
into his home. He wants to celebrate, not forget, where he came
from.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in the footsteps, literally, of Ramon, who is 3 1/2
years older. Pedro would follow him to the Dodgers academy in Campo
Las Palmas when Ramon signed in 1984. He would carry Ramon's bags,
but he really went just to see the fields, to be part of the game.
Sometimes, he'd catch Ramon. Then Ramon would catch him, and
eventually, that's how Pedro got noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro would challenge everyone and anyone to throw from center
field to home plate. He wanted to be on those fields every minute
of every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a crush on baseball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Pedro was 14, his fastball was in the high-70s. Two
years later, he was signed by the Dodgers. He owes everything to
Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the open door for us to pass through,'' Pedro said.
``He did everything for us. I have a lot to appreciate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon won 20 games in a season and threw a no-hitter during his
eight full seasons with Los Angeles. He always felt responsible for
setting a good example for his family. One of his lessons was
teaching his brothers how to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro embraced competition with a bear hug. He wanted to win
every race, every fight, every moment. He also always was the
instigator in the family. He'd hoist his mother, Lopoldina, on his
back and run around the house. He'd pull Ramon's ears.
</P>
<P>
   He loves music and dancing and joking and laughter. Ramon and
Jesus are much more quiet. There is only room for one clown. But
there is more than enough space for more than one star.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon and Pedro used to talk when they were little kids about
what they would do if they ever made it to the major leagues. Their
first plan was to buy a big house for their family.
</P>
<P>
   Family means the most.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro brought everyone together this spring for Ramon's 30th
birthday March 22. Ramon pitched that day, and afterward received a
call from teammate Ismael Valdes _ who said he needed Ramon to bail
him out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon, obviously concerned, drove down to the courthouse in Vero
Beach, where the Dodgers train. He realized the hoax when there,
among his entire family and good friends, was a sweet red Ferrari,
a gift from Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just buy what I need and I help my family,'' Pedro said.
``I'm very, very normal.''
</P>
<P>
   They always knew they'd give back to the community. They
distribute discarded shoes from their teammates and give food and
toys to families at the holidays. They figure if other players see
what they do, they'll want to give, too.
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of people in the town who knew Ramon had
ability when he signed. They were happy for him, but also said
money would change him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably I changed a little,'' Ramon said. ``But I haven't
changed the way I treat them.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers believe more in people than in money. They built a
church first because it was the way to show their town God helps
and if you believe strongly, dreams can come true like theirs did.
</P>
<P>
   They have lived both lives, of the rich and of the poor, and if
they are not a bridge, then at least they can be messengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps me understand how people think and how they feel,''
Pedro said of experiencing poverty and wealth. For Jesus, baseball
</P>
<P>
   was almost an afterthought. He wasn't a field rat like Pedro, he
wasn't leading the way like Ramon. He really got into the sport
when Pedro signed. That could be why his progress appears slower.
</P>
<P>
   He signed with the Dodgers in 1990 when he was 16. But he never
made it above Class AAA and was chosen by the Arizona Diamondbacks
in the expansion draft before being traded to the Florida Marlins
for Devon White. He was then traded as the player-to-be-named to
the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little tough for him,'' Ramon said. ``It makes him feel
a little pressure because the expectations are very high. Maybe
he's rushing. I told him, `Your time will come.' Besides, lefties,
they survive longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. It was great early in spring training this season, with
Jesus at big-league camp with the Marlins in Melbourne, and Ramon
not too far away in Vero Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Jesus wanted anyone's help. It was just nice to have
family near. All three had to learn English when they came to
America, and all were confused and a bit lonely. Pedro was
devastated when he was traded to Montreal after the '93 season. But
he's learned it is part of the game: as much as following Ramon
taught him, it was time to make it on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus is ready for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want me to be the same as they are,'' Jesus said.
``That's what anybody would like for their brother. I just want to
be as good as I can be. I want to be myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Rosenberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
