<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THARPE-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beware: Bogus offers aplenty for credit cards
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fraudulent credit card offers are the kudzu vine of
consumer cons. They keep coming back, despite constant efforts to
eradicate them.
</P>
<P>
   Kudzu will thrive almost anywhere where there's a little bit of
dirt. Fraudulent cards thrive on the need for credit _ and
consumers who have difficulty obtaining credit are prime targets
for the bogus offers.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Federal Trade Commission announced a settlement
with SureCheK Systems, an Atlanta-based firm that allegedly assured
consumers they would receive a credit card, regardless of their
credit history, if they paid $129 upfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``In almost all cases, they failed to provide the cards, and in
others they failed to disclose additional processing and annual
fees,'' the FTC said.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 500 million major credit cards, such as Visa
and MasterCard, circulating in the United States, and tens of
millions of consumers annually receive offers for credit cards. The
vast majority are legitimate, but fraudulent ones keep appearing
around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic ways to spot the real offers from the bogus
ones:
</P>
<P>
   _ With rare exceptions, legitimate offers will be made by a bank
or credit union, not some firm of which you've never heard. Look
out for copycat names that might imply the firm is a bank or credit
union when it's not.
</P>
<P>
   _ There is never a requirement to pay an advance fee to receive
a regular bank credit card. In a few cases, a bank or credit union
offering a secured credit card _ a card for which you establish a
savings account as collateral _ will charge a small application
fee. But never pay an application fee to any firm other than a bank
or credit union for a secured card.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Tharpe writes about consumer-related topics for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWO-PLAYERS30-COX     06-29 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWO-PLAYERS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One player provides team with double trouble
 &HT;    By Ron Jackson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For a natural left-hander, learning to throw
strikes right-handed is about as simple as shooting a basketball in
a strait jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Except, if you are Matt Witt, the 13-year-old who throws a
baseball ambidextrously. One young man, two pitching arms. It's no
mirage.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sight to see when Witt carries around two matching
Rawlings gloves _ one a left-hander's glove, the other a
right-hander's. Some days he is a southpaw pitcher, other days he
is a right-handed pitcher or a right-handed shortstop or
outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of the more amazing things I have ever seen,'' said
coach Bill Begley of the Troy, Ohio-based Brown's Bombers who play
in the Dayton Amateur Baseball Commission Class C (16-and-under)
League. ``Matt has a unique ability. In one inning he throws BBs
from the shortstop hole with his right arm; then the next inning he
strikes out batters and closes the game out as a left-handed
pitcher. It's a trip watching how opponents react.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been our problem to figure out how to use him best,''
Begley continued. ``He's a talented kid and he's full of savvy
already.''
</P>
<P>
   Witt of Bethel Twp., who will be a freshman at Bethel High
School, writes, drinks and eats lefthanded, bats lefthanded, plays
golf lefthanded and shoots baskets lefthanded. He currently plays
point guard on the Dayton Metro 14-and-under basketball team that
is headed to the Amateur Athletic Union nationals July 3-10 in
Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-9, 150-pound Witt has almost pitched exclusively
lefthanded this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more comfortable pitching left handed,'' Witt said. ``I
throw basically the same pitches with both arms _ fast ball, curve
and a change. There's a little mental adjustment moving from the
left to right side and it's a little awkward. But I have no
problems with it now. It's still weird, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching mostly in relief, Witt has earned a save with five
strikeouts in three innings. His earned-run average is 2.33 and
opponents are batting .111 against him. He is hitting .576 as a
left-handed batter.
</P>
<P>
   Witt remembers when Montreal Expos pitcher Greg Harris made
history in 1995 against the Cincinnati Reds, throwing both
left-handed and right-handed in the same game. Harris used a
special six-finger, two-thumbed glove that now resides in the
Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   The young switch-pitcher would like to purchase a custom-made
six-finger, two-thumbed glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go out to the mound to switch gloves, it costs me a
conference call,'' Begley said. ``Umpires will not allow him to
warm up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt's father Harold, a one-time third baseman in the St. Louis
Cardinals organization, remembers once when his son went from
left-hander to right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposing coach asked, 'What is the new kid's name
pitching?' I said it's the same kid,'' the elder Witt said. ``He
still didn't comprehend what I said. He asked me again and I told
him. He left shaking his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Jackson writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
