<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1637 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT     06-29 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: QUESTIONS THAT DEGRADE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating for all needing to fix category code)   (fb) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sidney Blumenthal, assistant to the president, made his third
appearance before Kenneth Starr's grand jury in Washington last
Thursday. He was asked a question that unwittingly defined the
character of what Starr and his colleagues are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever discussed with Mrs. Clinton whether the
president has a sex addiction?'' a prosecutor asked. Blumenthal
answered no, adding that the question was outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time Starr's assistants had asked him a
sexual question. Blumenthal decided to tell me about the
experience, as a grand-jury witness may do. (I sought a comment
from the independent counsel's office; but Starr's spokesman,
Charles Bakaly, did not return a call.)
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal was first called before the grand jury on Feb. 26. He
was asked what he had told reporters in various news organizations
and what they had said to him about Starr and his assistant
prosecutors. He answered those questions.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was asked what President Clinton had said to him about
the Monica Lewinsky matter. Blumenthal declined to answer,
asserting executive privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The White House claim of executive privilege was rejected in the
courts over the next several months, and finally abandoned.
Blumenthal was then called to testify the second time, on June 4.
</P>
<P>
   Hours passed without his being asked the question he had
declined to answer on Feb. 26. Instead the two prosecutors who
questioned him _ Jackie Bennett Jr., Starr's deputy, and Solomon
Wisenberg _ asked about imagined White House meetings to plot
strategy against the independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:30 p.m., in their last 10 minutes, the prosecutors asked
Blumenthal the previously unanswered question about what the
president had told him on the Lewinsky matter. Blumenthal replied
that the president had said the same thing he had publicly, that he
did not have a sexual relationship with Lewinsky and had not told
anyone to lie. Blumenthal added that Clinton was a man of
compassion, rooted in his temperament and his religious
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   At that point the prosecutors asked Blumenthal to leave the room
so they could consult. After five minutes he was called back, and
Wisenberg asked him: ``Does the president's religion include sexual
intercourse?''
</P>
<P>
   There was another sexual question in last week's grand-jury
session, conducted by two new prosecutors. It was, ``Does the
president believe that oral sex is sex?'' It was just that _ a
general question not tied to any particular matter.
</P>
<P>
   We have become coarsened in this country. We are too often
indifferent to the claims of privacy, which Justice Brandeis called
``the right most valued by civilized men.'' But have we really gone
so far that prosecutors can appropriately ask an assistant about
his boss' religion and sex life?
</P>
<P>
   I do not think so. I think most prosecutors would regard those
questions with contempt. It is sneering, smart-aleck stuff, the
tone of Clinton-haters on cable television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not a joke. Blumenthal's lawyer, William McDaniel, who
has 20 years of experience as a defense counsel in Washington and
elsewhere, put it: ``This is a serious matter. These men and women
(on the independent counsel staff) represent the prosecutorial
power of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have enormous power. Inside the grand jury room,
with no judge or defense lawyer present, they can ask questions
without regard to the usual rules of evidence, limited only by
their own sense of responsibility and decency.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of abuse is especially great in the case of an
independent counsel, who has no limits of budget or time. That is
why I decided to write about the question put to Blumenthal. In a
republic based on law, degradation of the legal process is
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here, I think, is third-rate prosecutors full of
hubris and obsessed by sex. I am sure they have pursued that
obsession with other grand-jury witnesses who have so far been too
scared or too embarrassed to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be brave enough to take on this abuse of power? Starr
is renting more office space, evidently ready to go on indefinitely
looking for some way to bring down President Clinton. Who will cry
hold, enough?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
