<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     06-29 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, June 27, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   E-COLI-POOLS (Undated) _ The water is fine. That's the message
from health and pool experts who say you're more likely to get E.
coli from contaminated food than from a chlorinated swimming pool.
Concerns about contaminated pool water surfaced after a severe
outbreak of E. coli bacteria sickened at least 10 children at a
Georgia waterpark earlier this month. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   HORSE-MEAT (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California every year supplies
the world's restaurants with thousands of pounds of horse meat for
cold cuts, sausages, steaks and stews. An initiative slated for the
ballot this fall would outlaw the export of California horses for
human consumption. The campaign's slogan: ``Just Say Neigh.'' By
ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   D'AMATO-CAMPAIGN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Two of the three times Alfonse
D'Amato has won elections for the U.S. Senate, he has eked by with
less than 50 percent of the vote. If the latest poll numbers hold
up, he's headed for a similar squeaker in November. By HARVY
LIPMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-VIDEO (Laredo, Texas) _ Infrared scopes and helicopters
haven't scared undocumented immigrants from entering South Texas,
but officials hope images of rattlesnakes, dead bodies and broiling
summer temperatures will. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BAR (San Francisco) _ Californians who feel cheated or
neglected by their lawyer now have only one recourse: Get another
lawyer. Because of a political fight in Sacramento, the State Bar
of California on Friday axed all but 20 of the 283 employees who
investigate complaints against attorneys and who prosecute bad
lawyers. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GILLETTE-MARKETING (Undated) _ This is a friendly warning. We
will be bombarded by an all-out media blitz for the new Mach 3
razor in the weeks to come. Gillette, which is to razors what Bill
Gates' Microsoft is to computer software, has vowed to flood the
marketplace with the Mach 3 beginning in July. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   SFO-RUNWAYS (San Francisco) _ As San Francisco International
Airport officials scurry to come up with a publicly acceptable plan
to extend runways into San Francisco Bay, many passengers are
demanding to know why the facility launched a massive growth
project for passengers and planes that now seem to have nowhere to
land. By ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   FTC-ADS (San Francisco) _ Cigarette ads aimed at ethnic
communities have been printed in Vietnamese or Chinese or Spanish,
except that the surgeon general's warning was in English. On
Friday, the FTC ordered that advertising disclosures like the
surgeon general's warning be in the language of the ad's target
audience. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   OFFICE-RENTALS (San Francisco) _ It's a distinction that will
make businesses cringe and landlords secretly rejoice. A portion of
the Bay Area has edged out New York City for having the most
expensive office space in the country, according to a new survey.
By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES (San Francisco) _ July looks like a
winning month for fans of mysteries and thrillers, with offerings
from such well-known writers as Patricia Cornwell, Lucian Truscott,
Carl Hiaasen and Philip Shelby. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-AFFLECK-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ Last fall he roamed among
us almost unnoticed. Now he's starring in a blockbuster, dating
actress Gwyneth Paltrow, sporting an Oscar and posing shirtless for
the cover of GQ magazine. For Ben Affleck, it's been ``one weird
transition.'' Affleck stars in ``Armageddon,'' which opens
nationwide Wednesday. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Arborvitae plants are beautiful
evergreens that like full sun and must have excellent drainage.
Unfortunately these plants are susceptible to spider mites and
bagworms, as well as leaf and stee clight. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ The newest strategy, or gimmick, if
you prefer, in the airline fare game is an Internet site that
invites travelers to name the price they are willing to pay for a
round-trip ticket. Forget published fares. If an airline with
unsold seats determines that your price is right, that's what you
pay. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-HOMERS (Undated) _ Mark McGwire might feel like a caged
animal, but Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr. feel as free as birds.
That's because McGwire is doing all the dirty work, drawing
unprecedented attention to his pursuit of Roger Maris. Sosa and
Griffey are keeping within striking distance of Maris without the
pressure and headaches that seem to plague McGwire. By JOHN SHEA.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-GIANTS-HISPANICS (San Francisco) _ Peter Magowan became a
Giants fan during the days when such Latin luminaries as Orlando
Cepeda, Juan Marichal, Jose Pagan and the Alou brothers populated
the team's roster in the late '50s and early '60s. He hired Luis
Rosa to talent spot in Latin America. Yet 5 1/2 years later, the
Giants still haven't developed a front-line Hispanic player. By
JORGE L. ORTIZ.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WYNALDA (San Jose, Calif.) _ Eric Wynalda, after much
prodding, finally said what anyone who followed the U.S. national
team during the World Cup already knew: ``It was just miserable.
The whole World Cup experience was miserable. We just felt so
helpless.'' By JILL R. DORSON.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (Portola, Calif.) _ The continuing saga of Davis
Lake has turned into a giant monkey that the California Department
of Fish and Game just hasn't been able to shake off its back. But
the word is that the DFG will try to shed the nemesis over the July
4 weekend with the first in a series of trout plants. By TOM
STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ In the race for Texas
lieutenant governor, voters will have to choose between a name
dropper and a ticket dodger. Republican Rick Perry has no problem
mentioning Gov. George W. Bush's name during campaign speeches,
while Democrat John Sharp hardly even hints at the name of the
gubernatorial nominee at the top of the Democratic slate. By CLAY
ROBISON.
</P>
