<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-NAZI-LOOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS GOLD OFFER IS LESS GENEROUS THAN IT SEEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The recent offer by Switzerland's banks to pay nearly
$600 million to Nazi victims whose plundered wealth wound up in
their vaults looks more generous than it is.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish organizations last week spurned the offer, holding out
for at least $1 billion _ a demand that on its face seems
excessive.
</P>
<P>
   But the offer and counter-offer need to be explained. Pre-World
War II currency values were about 20 times greater than those of
today's inflation-ravaged money. Several historians, including some
Swiss, have calculated the Nazi loot that found its way to neutral
Switzerland from 1939 to 1944 at $60 million, or $1.2 billion at
present-day values.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't include funds transferred by European Jews and
others for safekeeping before the war started _ an estimated $25
million to $30 million, which would be $500 million to $600 million
today. Some Swiss officials have acknowledged that many of these
accounts were not handed back to survivors or their descendants
after the war.
</P>
<P>
   According to several economists, the withheld accounts helped to
fund Switzerland's own notable postwar expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, some right-wing Swiss politicians and a number of
newspapers in that country charged that the banks' latest proposal
to repay victims of Nazi persecution or their descendants was so
lavish that it threatened to undermine the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some leading Swiss banks face legal action in the
United States following rejection of the $600 million bid to end
the controversy, which has gone on for three years. New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani has warned that the city may try to stop Swiss
financial institutions from doing business there, including dealing
on Wall Street. At issue is whether New York possesses the
constitutional right to do so since America's relations with other
countries are controlled by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   But the struggle, with its deep emotional overtones, won't go
away. The Swiss claim they are now the victims _ as much as
anything else, they say, of domestic U.S. politics and of lawyers
trying to generate hefty fees for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   However, suspicion of the Swiss runs deep and not only in
America. ``The Swiss continue to give an impression of dragging
their feet and of not really seeing any reason to make up for their
past malpractices,'' declared the French news magazine Le Point.
``For this reason, they get little sympathy from the rest of the
world and do not deserve much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
