r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALABAMA-GOVRACE-SFCHR     06-29 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-GOVRACE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NECK-AND-NECK GOP RUNOFF IN ALABAMA  
 BY MARC SANDALOW 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OPELIKA, Ala. _ The defiant chords of Lynyrd Skynyrd's ``Sweet
Home Alabama'' blare over a small tent's loudspeaker as Governor
Fob James strides to a small podium in this God-fearing hamlet
between Montgomery and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is sweating heavily and the sleeves of his white
shirt are rolled up to his elbows. The sun has set, although it is
still 95 degrees and muggy. A supporter hands him an Auburn
University baseball hat, which he triumphantly places on his head
with his palm.
</P>
<P>
   Using no notes, the governor begins a colorful 20-minute tirade
against the ``monkeys'' and ``elitists'' who oppose him. He mocks
his rival's use of ``po-lit-i-cal op-e-ra-tives,'' drawing out each
syllable to accentuate both his drawl and his contempt. He
ridicules the Supreme Court for trying to deprive his constituents'
children the right to worship in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The scene, observed by two dozen cows in a field less than 100
yards away, is as Alabaman as the pulled pork barbecue and
sweetened iced tea being devoured by the all-white crowd of about
300. It conjures up memories of George Wallace and Kissin' Jim
Folsom, who dominated this state's politics in earlier decades.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also the stuff of derisive Yankee stereotypes _ and to
a growing number of residents, a statewide embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   James is being challenged in a close runoff election Tuesday by
Winton Blount III, an Alabama version of a country Republican.
Although James' drawl, focus on religious issues and evangelical
righteousness have proven popular among the state's good ol' boys,
Blount insists that James' style is standing in the way of
progress.
</P>
<P>
   The race has evolved into one of the most closely watched _ and
colorful _ in the nation. At one point in the campaign, the portly
Blount recalled a when James ``danced around the stage like a
monkey'' to publicly mock the theory of evolution. James responded
by saying, ``(at least) I'm not a fat monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican runoffs used to be meaningless in the South, where
Democrats ruled for the 100 years after the Civil War. But for the
first time in history, more Republicans than Democrats voted in
primaries earlier this month, and the race between tomorrow's
winner and Democratic Lieutenant Governor Don Siegelman in November
is expected to be close.
</P>
<P>
   It is another pivotal moment in the evolution of a region where
civil rights and Civil War monuments stand side by side, and which
many of the nation's political leadership _ including the
president, speaker of the House and the Senate majority leader _
call home.
</P>
<P>
   The contest also reflects a nationwide struggle among
Republicans over whether social issues _ such as school prayer and
abortion or economic issues such as taxes and spending _ should be
the party's top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the simplest way to understand Alabama's politics is to
think of San Francisco _ Alabama is the opposite. Few destinations
on this planet are as politically and culturally distant from
Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Bible coloring books and gospel cassettes can be found in
Alabama's Piggly Wiggly supermarkets. Opposition to abortion, gun
control and gay rights are a given. Political candidates routinely
quote Scripture and complain that House Speaker Newt Gingrich is
too moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in a curious way, Alabamans are experiencing a struggle
familiar to many San Franciscans _ in reverse. Just as moderate
liberals, like former Mayor Frank Jordan, have argued that the
city's liberal image scares off business, moderate conservatives in
Alabama insist that their own right-wing image keeps them in the
backwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time we had a leader who understood the language of
business,'' said Mobile roofer Jerry Lathan, using words remarkably
similar to those used in San Francisco campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image Fob (James) projects is that of an intolerant,
prototypical, southern redneck,'' added Lathan, who is working for
Blount's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   James has become the darling of the religious right for his
defense of of school prayer, at one point offering to lead prayers
in defiance of a court order and appealing a school prayer ruling
to the Supreme Court over the objections of his own attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fired both barrels,'' he said unapologetically when the
court refused to consider the case last week. ``If I had another,
I'd fire it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a much publicized statement that reminded some of former
Governor George Wallace's use of troops to keep blacks out of the
University of Alabama in the early 1960s, James threatened to use
the national guard to prevent the federal government from removing
a plaque of the Ten Commandments from an Alabama Courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's city newspapers have endorsed Blount, whose
father was the postmaster general under President Richard Nixon and
whose supporters say is the candidate who can attract investment
into the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't carry us back to the kind of stereotype that James
evokes,'' Blount said in an interview. ``I'll be talking about the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't threaten to call out the national guard in a futile
attempt that takes us back to those images of yesterday. I won't be
a governor who will say the Bill of Rights don't apply. We need a
governor who understand that our image is important to this
state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuts'' responds James.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard there are some Southern Californians who are
embarrassed by y'all,'' he told a Chronicle reporter. ``I
understand your governor's race was an embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not more an embarrassment than Mayor Daley was to Chicago.
What you are listening to is an opponent who doesn't have an
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   James, like many southern politicians before him, seems to revel
in the charge that he is subject of Yankee scorn. Just as San
Francisco politicians are not ashamed to call themselves liberal,
James contends he is just a ``plain, old-fashioned conservative,''
in a radio commercial. ``And the big city newspapers never met a
liberal they didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   James, like many Alabamans, is a Democrat who switched parties.
Whatever the label, there can be no mistaking the conservative and
religious leanings of this state, whose population of 4.3 million
people is slightly smaller than that of the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   A poll conducted earlier this month by the Mobile Register found
that nearly 3 out of 4 voters said a candidate's religious
background is an important factor, and 2 out of 3 respondents said
the Bible ``is the actual word of God and is to be taken
literally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very conservative place,'' said Lorie Johnson, the
head of the Auburn College Republicans, a born-again Christian and
an avid James supporter. ``Students here are very conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson exemplifies the struggle between the old and the new,
saying she aspires to become a sportswriter for a national magazine
but feels it is inappropriate for women to work outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a mother is the most important job a woman can do,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest polls show the race is a dead heat. Regardless of who
wins, it is clear that Alabama is going through some changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Alabama doesn't get a progressive governor to lead us into
the 21st century, we're all in trouble,'' said Guy Hunt, who was
removed as Alabama's governor in 1993 for diverting campaign
contributions to his inaugural fund and is supporting Blount.
</P>
<P>
   A progressive governor for Alabama?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking liberal,'' he said. ``In Alabama, progressive
means using good common horse sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
