r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON WINS IN HOME STRETCH 
BY NANCY GAY
</HEADLINE>
   Chronicle Staff Writer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Jeff Gordon hasn't called California home since
he was 13 years old, but those Vallejo roots maintain a strong hold
on the thousands of NASCAR fans who packed Sears Point on Sunday
for NASCAR's annual Winston Cup stop here, the Save Mart/Kragen
350.
</P>
<P>
   They came out en masse _ crowd estimates were between 100,000
and 110,000 _ in part to worship the sport's most dynamic young
star, and Gordon did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   He cut his racing teeth on the dirt tracks at the Solano County
Fairgrounds in a quarter-midget, and 13 years later Gordon returned
to the North Bay and dominated an intimidating road race he had
always enjoyed but never conquered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to win this race for a long time and it's
always special when you've got that many people pulling for you,''
said Gordon, the pole-sitter who picked up a winner's purse of
$160,675 in his fourth Winston Cup victory this season. He also
regained the NASCAR Winston Cup points lead from Jeremy Mayfield,
who started fifth and finished 18th in the wild race.
</P>
<P>
   Stealing the lead late from surprise front-runner Bobby Hamilton
by sneaking inside on the tight Turn 11 hairpin curve, Gordon
pulled in front for good with only 10 laps remaining in the
217.56-mile race. He survived more bumping with Hamilton in the
same treacherous turn and eventually pulled away with a 3.11-second
advantage in the final lap as Hamilton's tires finally wore out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove the tires and the car right into the ground. I just
ran 'em plumb to death,'' said Hamilton, who drove his No. 4 Kodak
Chevrolet to second place.
</P>
<P>
   The brushes between the two drivers down the stretch were so
close that NASCAR officials radioed both drivers and their crews,
telling them to ``cool it a little,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   But it all made for brilliant racing, and a thrilling finish.
``He was putting up a fight,'' said Gordon, who passed No. 43 John
Andretti, No. 7 Geoff Bodine and No. 10 Ricky Rudd between laps 90
and 100 to get right behind Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I caught him, I drove real hard into Turn 11 and I got
underneath him,'' Gordon said. ``We were both kind of locking the
tires up. We bumped a little bit. I got by him, and he bumped me
back a little bit. Then he got by me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun racing him. It was real aggressive racing
that late in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was a crazy day, with five yellow caution flags flying
and eight drivers failing to finish, two of them going out because
of accidents (rookie Jerry Nadeau and veteran Terry Labonte).
</P>
<P>
   Nadeau, 27, vying for NASCAR Winston Cup rookie-of-the-year
honors, showed his wildness as early as Lap 1, when he slid off the
course and ran across the grass at Turn 2 before charging back onto
the track.
</P>
<P>
   He spun off the course a final time in Lap 14. Nadeau came wide
out of Turn 7 at The Chute, lost control in the beginning of the
swerves at Turn 8 and drove straight up the side of the hill,
plowing over the grass and burying the front end of his car into
the soft dirt bank.
</P>
<P>
   That mishap, which knocked Nadeau out of the race, brought out
the first caution. The nose of Nadeau's No.13 FirstPlus Ford _
co-owned by driver Bill Elliott and Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan
Marino _ was stuck in the soft earth and several attempts to
restart the engine proved futile.
</P>
<P>
   There was more concern about the condition of Nadeau, who may
have blacked out briefly upon impact. Clearly frustrated after the
accident, he also complained of some neck pain. As a precaution,
Nadeau was transported to Sonoma Valley Hospital for a CT Scan. He
was examined and released.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first corner was pretty exciting, that's for sure,'' said
Gordon, who held the lead for 43 laps but dropped back in the
middle of the race when his team lost valuable time in the pits.
``Jerry is an aggressive guy. He was just a little too aggressive,
so we were happy to make it through that.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gordon, there was reason to rejoice in his first career win
at Sears Point, one of only four tracks on the Winston Cup circuit
where he had never posted a victory. He had always loved racing the
road courses and did well on them, winning at Watkins Glen in 1997
and finishing in the Top 10 in his previous three races at Sears
Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream come true for me. I never really raced out
here at Sears Point when I was a kid growing up here,'' said
Gordon, who makes his home in Mooresville, N.C., but had a
battalion of family and friends at Sears Point cheering him on.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he had truly come home. ``It's just a little bit
special, a little bit extra, plus it's a track that's tough to win
on and we wanted to win out here,'' Gordon said. ``It's just an
unbelievable feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
