<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEWS-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING MYSTERIES, THRILLERS FOR SULTRY JULY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ July looks like a winning month for fans of
mysteries and thrillers, with offerings from such well-known
writers as Patricia Cornwell, Lucian Truscott, Carl Hiaasen and
Philip Shelby.
</P>
<P>
   Among the best of the crop:
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas Detective Romulus Poe investigates the horrific murder
of a show girl in Faye Kellerman's ``Moon Music.''
</P>
<P>
   In Philip Shelby's ``Gatekeeper,'' a young and beautiful foreign
service officer at the U.S. Embassy in Paris becomes a target of an
international assassin known as the Handyman and a cabal plotting
to create a new world order.
</P>
<P>
   A drop-dead gorgeous tabloid TV reporter tries to track down a
mysterious chemical called Adam One in the comedic mystery ``The
Last Manly Man'' by Sparkle Hayter.
</P>
<P>
   In Patricia Cornwell's 11th thriller featuring Dr. Kay
Scarpetta, ``Point of Origin,'' Virginia's chief medical examiner
faces a killer who masks his crimes with fire.
</P>
<P>
   Working for her bail-bondsman cousin, Stephanie Plum goes
hunting for waitress Maxine Nowicki, accused of bail jumping, theft
and extortion in Janet Evanovich's ``Four to Score.''
</P>
<P>
   A female cadet collapses and dies on the parade grounds at West
Point in Lucian Truscott's ``Full Dress Gray.'' When an autopsy
reveals that she had sex with multiple partners the night before,
the new superintendent must determine whether there was a gang rape
or a cadet orgy.
</P>
<P>
   After Louisa Shilder, an aide to a vice presidential candidate,
finds an envelope addressed to her at a party at his house, her
daughter is kidnapped and Shilder moves to unravel an international
bribery scheme in ``The Betrayal,'' by Sabin Willett.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Hiaasen teams up with Bill Montalbano to create the
mysteries ``Trap Line,'' in which a Key West fishing boat captain
is being forced by drug lords to smuggle their wares, and ``Powder
Burn,'' in which a Miami architect sees his ex-girlfriend hit by a
car full of hit men for the drug lords.
</P>
<P>
   In 1908, Fremont Jones and her lover, Michael Archer, return to
San Francisco, set up a private investigation agency and get
involved in the murder of two mediums in Dianne Day's ``Emperor
Norton's Ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   A stalker goes after Iditarod racer Jessie's sled dogs, then her
in ``Deadfall'' by Sue Henry.
</P>
<P>
   As illegal dogfights plague Moscow, Inspector Porfiry Rostnikov
investigates the murders of some of the most powerful Mafia bosses
in the Russian capital in Stuart M. Kaminsky's ``The Dog Who Bit a
Policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Picture of Innocence'' by Jill McGown, Detective Chief
Inspector Lloyd and Detective Inspector Judy Miller investigate the
murder of East Midlands farmer Bernard Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   After the bizarre deaths of several well-known criminals,
Chicago Police Commander Larry Cole must confront scientist Johnny
Gault, who runs a security service that booby-traps properties with
high-voltage electricity and snake venom injection devices in Hugh
Holton's ``Red Lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   In H. Michael Frase's ``The Last Goodbye,'' Josh Mitchell and
Pamela Morrow meet on a flight from New York to San Francisco.
However, the next morning Morrow is found murdered on a beach in
California, and Mitchell becomes the prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   New York Police Capt. Jim Donovan, awaiting the birth of his
first child, is called back from leave to investigate the murder of
a high-society Manhattanite while shopping for jewelry with his
fiancee in Michael Jahn's ``Murder on Fifth Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dan Oran's ``Ulterior Motive,'' the billionaire chairman of
Seattle-based Megasoft, who is running for president, is gunned
down by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Still reeling from the death of his wife and unborn child,
Shanghai Homicide Detective Zhong Fong is assigned to investigate
the Dim Sum murders _ a New Orleans policeman and an African
diplomat, both of whom had been dismembered _ in David Rotenberg's
``The Shanghai Murders.''
</P>
<P>
   In Janet Lawrence's ``Canaletto and the Case of the Westminster
Bridge,'' the Italian artist travels to London to paint the newly
built Westminster Bridge. However, he is attacked and robbed twice
in one day, left for dead in an alley, then rescued by apprentice
engraver Fanny Rooker. Together, they must figure out who wants
Canaletto dead and why.
</P>
<P>
   After his lover makes a public announcement that he is gay, high
school teacher Tom Mason starts the new school year amid a push by
conservative parents to rid the school of gays. When one of the
conservative parents is murdered in the school library, Mason must
prove that his best friend is innocent in ``Are You Nuts?'' by Mark
Richard Zubro.
</P>
<P>
   In Jeremiah Healy's ``The Stalking of Sheilah Quinn,'' litigator
Quinn gets wealthy Arthur Ketterson acquitted of the murder of his
girlfriend, only to have him stalk her.
</P>
<P>
   When the body of a headless female is found in the well of
remote Irish monastery, Sister Fidelma is sent to investigate. En
route, she discovers a crewless and cargo-less merchant ship under
full sail off the Irish coast in Peter Tremanye's ``The Subtle
Serpent.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Rattlesnake Crossing'' by J.J. Jance, Cochise County
(Ariz.) Sheriff Joanna Brady must stop a wave of murders after a
militia group invades historic San Pedro Valley.
</P>
<P>
   As a cholera epidemic plagues New Orleans in 1833, surgeon and
teacher Benjamin January tries to clear a runaway slave accused of
murdering her master and trying to poison his wife in Barbara
Hambly's ``Fever Season.''
</P>
<P>
   In James D. Brewer's ``No Escape,'' the setting is New Orleans,
the year 1873 and the plague yellow fever. And Big River Detective
Agency must investigate the murders of two men who would have died
of the fever anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In Charles McCarry's political thriller ``Lucky Bastard,'' John
Fitzgerald Adams, who believes he is the illegitimate son of JFK,
wants two things in life _ the presidency and women. But some dark
dealings in his past may halt his rise to the top.
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. Now pick out your favorite reading spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
