<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIES' RALLY MEANS WILD WIN 
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
     Chronicle Staff Writer 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Sunday's mess of a game between the A's and the Rockies
offered a direct demonstration of why the designated-hitter rule
should be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   A's manager Art Howe did not enjoy playing under National League
rules very much, because his team lost an 11-10 game it should have
won. But when it comes to sheer craziness, the kind of stuff that
makes fans and everyone else grin and shake their heads, it was
hard to top watching the pitchers take their hacks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be great to get back to our league where we can get
the ninth hitters out more easily than we've been getting the
pitcher out here,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   A's starter Tom Candiotti got things started. He came up in the
third inning and doubled to right, the first extra-base hit by an
A's pitcher since Ken Holtzman doubled against Texas on Sept. 15,
1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fastball, middle away,'' Candiotti said. ``When I hit
it, I just tried to get to first as fast as I could. I saw the
right fielder stop and I said, `Oh, man, (he's) going to catch it,'
then it fell and I turned on the afterburners. I looked over and
saw four starters in the other dugout all standing up and clapping
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The A's wasted that leadoff double, but rallied for four runs in
the fourth to take a 5-3 lead. The Rockies countered that with
three runs off Candiotti in the bottom of the inning, helped by
errors by rookies Miguel Tejada and A.J. Hinch.
</P>
<P>
   The big hit? The A's walked No.8 hitter Jeff Reed to get to
Rockies starter Jamey Wright, who came up with two outs and runners
at the corners. Wright got all of a Candiotti knuckleball and
belted it into the left-center gap for a double to score both
runners.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the A's were in position to win the game. They broke
out for four runs in the top of the seventh, a rally highlighted by
Rickey Henderson's dancing off of third base to trigger a
run-scoring balk, and Matt Stairs' pinch-single to score two runs.
That made it 9-6 A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those games where you say, `We should have won
12-4,' '' Candiotti said.
</P>
<P>
   The errors kept the Rockies in striking range, and they beat up
on the bullpen the way the A's had the day before. T.J. Mathews and
Mike Fetters (0-2) were in and out of there almost before you knew
it. Henderson's error in left on Dante Bichette's sinking line
drive made matters worse, but the key was Todd Helton's two-run
homer to right off left-hander Mike Mohler.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Rockies an 11-9 lead and made it harder for the
A's to take over again. Ben Grieve came through in the eighth with
his second double of the day, scoring Rafael Bournigal, but that
rally fizzled when Mike Blowers struck out looking with two runners
on base to end the inning. Replays showed the ball was well
outside, despite home plate umpire Jerry Meals' verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when he called it a strike,'' Blowers said. ``I
couldn't even believe it. That was a huge call. All the guys told
me it was pretty close to a foot outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, not getting a call from a National League umpire was
hardly the key to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was our downfall,'' Howe said. ``We don't make a
play to start the fourth inning, and we wind up giving up three
unearned runs. In the seventh, we couldn't get anyone out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Rockies manager Don Baylor did not enjoy the game as much
as he might have, despite celebrating his 49th birthday. ``I hope
no one stresses on their birthday like I did,'' he said. ``It was
back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
