<SLUG> BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR FANS SEE THRILL RIDE 
BY TIM KEOWN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SONOMA, Calif. _ Once a year they show up, more than 100,000 of
them, acres and acres of humanity stretching across the Sonoma
hills. They come early and stay late, with the goal of catching
occasional glimpses of colorful cars going at remarkable speeds.
</P>
<P>
   To some of us, the appeal can be puzzling. The assumption _ born
out by unscientific, walking-around research _ is that the majority
of NASCAR fans root for wrecks and some view the Civil War as a
temporary setback.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, Jeff Gordon showed why so many people are willing to
battle sun, wind, dust and infernal traffic congestion to witness a
Winston Cup race. In a way, Gordon let everybody in on the secret.
It took awhile, but the allure of NASCAR became apparent in the
final few laps of the Save Mart/Kragen 350 at Sears Point.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon pulled off what amounted to a perfectly executed
two-minute drill. You want excitement? There was Gordon, busting
his way past six cars in 14 laps to take the lead on a course that,
by his estimation, allowed drivers just one logical spot for safe
passage.
</P>
<P>
   For his crowning achievement, Gordon passed the leader, Bobby
Hamilton, on the 102nd lap. He turned Hamilton inside out with a
run to the inside of a hairpin turn _ Turn 11 to the believers _
and then jammed it hard on the straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't know your front end from your rear, you could
appreciate the talent _ and the guts _ it took for Gordon to make
that move. Even if you walked in cold from a lifetime of
nonmechanical sporting pursuits, you immediately would have known
that Gordon's move into the lead was something that separates
regular guys from phenomenal performers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in, the first car you think about outrunning is the
24,'' Hamilton said, referring to Gordon. ``They're champions.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon usually doesn't receive such ungrudging support from his
fellow racers. He is, of course, the fairy-tale prince in the world
of the self-proclaimed frogs. He's 26, photogenic and well-spoken,
and he races with an aggression usually reserved for I-80 on a
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   He also wins, which adds to the gall. Yesterday was his fourth
win of the Winston Cup season. It earned him and his crew more than
$160,000 and puts his race earnings at close to $1.7 million this
year. He also leads the series in points, which he won last year.
</P>
<P>
   (As evidence of Gordon's status, one of the ancillary amusements
provided to race fans Sunday was the chance to be photographed _
free of charge _ with a life-sized cardboard figure of Gordon that
just happened to be adorned with pink lace panties and lipstick.
Ancillary amusements, presumably, are also a big part of NASCAR's
allure.)
</P>
<P>
   Gordon doesn't seem to reflect the good-ol'-boy spirit of
rebellion, and auto racing has always been a rebel's pursuit.
NASCAR, however, is the great straddler; it has managed to gain
widespread appeal while retaining a portion of the politically
incorrect spirit. For one thing, where else in the world is
nicotine so gloriously exalted?
</P>
<P>
   Gordon does milk ads and appears on cereal boxes. He's also a
Westerner _ born up the road in Vallejo, where he lived until he
was 13. At that point, his father decided his son had outgrown the
limited racing opportunities in California. It was either
child-labor laws or safety laws, but the Gordons made the move to
the Midwest and it paid off.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, Jeff raced in places such as Rio Linda, Fremont and
Sunnyvale, but he never had a reason to visit Sears Point. Since he
turned pro and began dominating the circuit, he has circled this
race as one he'd like to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dream come true,'' Gordon said. ``We've been trying
to win this race for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Hamilton jousted into that same Turn 11 through the
final laps, with Hamilton trying to make it work on rapidly
deteriorating tires. They bumped a few times, nothing too nasty,
and the NASCAR officials sent down word that the 24 and the 4
needed to calm it down.
</P>
<P>
   The news never made it to Gordon. It somehow got hung up between
Gordon's crew chief, Ray Evernham, and his driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know nothing of that,'' Gordon said, shooting a curious eye
toward Evernham. ``That was just good racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining himself, Evernham said, ``I got kind of busy, I
guess. I wasn't worried about either one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton wasn't bothered by any of it, and he offered this
pinpoint assessment: ``That's what makes our sport what it is _ we
got fenders.''
</P>
<P>
   The racers traditionally give the bulk of the credit to the
sponsors and the pit crew and the race promoters and the engineers
and the inventors of asphalt, but Gordon's contribution couldn't be
discounted. He thanked all the right people, but in the end, he was
the one making the tough decisions and having them work out.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the infinite number of racing T-shirts suggests, he
was driving it like he stole it. In this neighborhood, there is no
greater compliment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
