<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDNER'S THREE-HITTER, SNOW'S SLAM PROPEL S.F.
</HEADLINE>
  By Henry Schulman 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last year's Giants were easy to figure out. They
were a merry band of castoffs from other teams that finally were
given a chance to prosper in a friendly environment under a
benevolent manager, who convinced them they were better than anyone
figured they were. Consistency was their byword: only one big
winning streak, no big losing streaks.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Giants are a puzzle. They are almost exactly where
they were at this time last year (48-35 now, 47-36 then), yet they
arrived here by winning 11 in a row and then losing 11 of their
next 18 when one of their big bats disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Which way do they go now that they face a tough week against the
Southern California teams, with three at Anaheim and three at home
against Los Angeles? If their past two games are a good barometer,
they must like their chances.
</P>
<P>
   After coming from behind to beat the Texas Rangers on Saturday,
they presented 36,664 fans at 3Com Park a neat little package
Sunday: seven runs in the first two innings, including a J.T. Snow
grand slam, a three-hit shutout by Mark Gardner against the
best-hitting team in the majors and a 7-0 victory that moved them
within 51/2 games of the first-place San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of us have been disappointed with the way we've
been playing,'' Gardner said after tossing his seventh career
shutout. ``We haven't pitched well, we haven't hit well. It's been
the total package. We need to look at where we're going and see
what we need to do. We could easily be 10 games back at the
All-Star break with the teams we've got coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not if they play like they did yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The first three Giants reached in the first inning _ Darryl
Hamilton on a single, Bill Mueller on an error and Barry Bonds hit
by a pitch _ before Charlie Hayes drilled a fastball from 11-game
winner Aaron Sele past the pitcher's ear for a two-run single. Snow
followed with a sacrifice fly for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later, Hamilton walked, Mueller singled and Hayes
walked to load the bases for Snow, who with two out, skied a 1-1
Sele pitch high into the jet stream in left field that carried into
the bleachers for a grand slam. Snow had his 100th career homer and
a career-high five RBIs, and the Giants had a 7-0 lead that killed
the Rangers' spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that broke their backs,'' Gardner said. ``I don't
think they thought they were out of the game after the first
inning. To them, 3-0 is nothing. But 7-0 is a tough mountain to
climb.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow has been a revelation in the last week. He returned from
his mother's funeral on Monday not rusty after a wrenching ordeal
that caused him to miss five more games, but hot as a fireplace
poker. He has six hits in 20 at-bats since, including two doubles
and two homers.
</P>
<P>
   Snow believes that his many absences this season have yielded a
paradoxical benefit now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're halfway through the season, but I still feel like it's
April or May because my season has been so choppy,'' he said. ``I
was gone four days in May, and then my shoulder was banged up, and
that cost me five or six starts. I was gone the last week for five
games. That all adds up to a chunk of a half a month or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus is on the game again,'' Snow said. ``Not that it
wasn't before, but this game is hard enough when there's nothing
else on your mind. When your mind is clouded, I don't think you see
the ball and concentrate as well as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Concentration and focus also defined Gardner's start. He had a
one-hitter through seven innings and finished by facing just two
batters over the minimum. None of the three singles he allowed were
scorched. He walked none, struck out five and threw two double-play
balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a groove from the first inning, which has been his
nemesis inning,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``He was ready
from the time he got out there. We got three runs, which is an
instant cushion, but not a huge cushion against their lineup. After
the grand slam you saw Gardy more relaxed and determined.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates agreed that the slam helped
Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   ``After J.T. hit his grand slam, this was the flattest our team
has been in four years,'' Oates said. ``I'm not taking anything
away from Mark. He pitched a superb ballgame, but I don't think he
saw us at our highest intensity today.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded like a backhanded compliment, but Gardner will take
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be right,'' the seven-game winner said. ``I don't
know. We'll never know. Maybe it did take the wind out of their
sails.'' &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
