<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREETSMARTS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL INVESTORS MISS OUT ON CONFERENCES' JUICY NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK VEVERKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
It may be time for the securities industry to break from the
tradition of holding ``breakout sessions'' at stock conferences,
where most of the juicy stuff on companies is disclosed.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Equal access to information on public companies, or the lack
thereof, continues to be a thorn in the side of small investors.
</P>
<P>
   And well it should. There are inequities everywhere you look
when it comes to how news and information is disseminated about
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, stock conferences orchestrated by investment
banks and brokerages. Usually held at posh hotels and swank
resorts, these forums are frequented by fund managers and buy-side
analysts who can afford to pay the hefty prices of admission.
</P>
<P>
   These gabfests have become ubiquitous during the current bull
run, especially in San Francisco. Mayor Willie Brown, for one,
should be thankful for the boon to San Francisco's already robust
tourism business.
</P>
<P>
   These conferences usually feature three or four salons
(partitioned banquet rooms, really) filled with CEOs and CFOs
telling attendees how their companies are doing. They usually run
through their boilerplate presentations in a half-hour or so, while
number-crunchers in dark suits and skirts munch on muffins and
granola bars.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, the attendees adjourn to so-called breakout
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists currently are banned from the breakouts where most
of the news, essentially, breaks out. As you might imagine, the
financial press isn't thrilled with this policy. Nor should
investors be.
</P>
<P>
   The practice amounts to a two-tiered system for disseminating
important, if not technically ``material,'' information. You know,
tidbits like missed shipments, high inventory levels, a glitch at a
factory or a potential strike at a plant.
</P>
<P>
   It's stuff that can lead to bad quarters, missed earnings
targets or long-term performance problems. Stuff that you and I
might like to know, especially if you're a shareholder. (By the
way, I wouldn't be a shareholder because I don't invest in
individual stocks.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the investment banks and brokerages that host these
conferences say they can't allow the press inside these sessions
because the folks that run the companies wouldn't be as candid. Nor
would they be as specific when pressed about their operations and
income statements.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, isn't that the point? Why does a fund manager who owns
500,000 shares get preferential treatment over the investor who
owns 500 shares?
</P>
<P>
   Even if part-time investors can afford to pay the freight, they
aren't likely to be able to take time from their jobs to hang out
at the Ritz for four days.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should they have to. They shouldn't have to attend stock
conferences just to stay even with the big boys and girls from
fundland. Just let the journalists attend the breakouts or
eliminate them altogether. At least by letting reporters in,
whether they are from Dow Jones, Bloomberg News, The Chronicle or
the moon, they would have access to all of the company news, which
they in turn could deliver to Jane and Joe investor.
</P>
<P>
   This fair and sane approach would help level the playing field
between big and small investors, and it should improve the quality
of information that eventually hits the street.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the juice spilled during breakouts is often done so
informally, which sometimes lends itself to muddled messages. (OK,
I admit. I've managed to sneak into one or two of these on
occasion.)
</P>
<P>
   Fund managers and analysts who attend these sessions often give
accounts of the breakouts to journalists anyway, which creates room
for interpretation by the source. And sometimes, it results in
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   A real-life case in point: A hedge fund source says that he
attended a recent stock conference held by Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in
Boston at the Ritz-Carlton (naturally). The analyst says he
attended the breakout session for Preview Travel, an online travel
service based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   According to the source, someone at the session asked if the
company would become profitable in line with analysts' predictions
(which are usually based on guidance from management).
</P>
<P>
   The answer, as reported by the source, was no. ``They sounded
like they were backing off from earlier targets for
profitability,'' the source says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that would be a pretty important bit of news. If it
were true.
</P>
<P>
   But for his part, Preview Travel chief executive Ken Orton says
he didn't utter any such thing at the breakout session.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Orton told me that he thinks the source ``slipped into
the wrong room.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In addition, Wall Street analysts anticipate that Preview
Travel will climb into the black in the third quarter of the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And Orton says he ``is comfortable with the analysts'
projections.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it. Straight from the horse's mouth. But
wouldn't it have been easier if journalists were allowed to report
what is revealed during all presentations at these stockfests?
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the practice of holding breakouts should simply be
banned altogether. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
