<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1821 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMAGEDDON-MOVIE-LA &LR; Q     06-29 2205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMAGEDDON-MOVIE-LA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROID + STARS   HIT?
</HEADLINE>
 Q  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Producer Jerry Bruckheimer likes to refer to his
new exploding-asteroid movie, ``Armageddon, as `The Dirty Dozen' in
outer space.'' However, indie-film actor Owen Wilson (``Bottle
Rocket'') might have come up with a better description.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like the Village People than `The Dirty Dozen',''
Wilson says, laughing. ``You've got the cop, the construction
worker, the motorcycle guy ... something for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Something for everyone'' certainly has been the guiding
principle behind the making and marketing of ``Armageddon''
(opening WeQesday), the second asteroid movie to hit theaters this
summer. Longtime action hero Bruce Willis is joined by ``Good Will
Hunting'' heartthrob Ben Affleck and a host of indie film actors,
including Wilson, Billy Bob Thornton, Steve Buscemi and Peter
Stormare. MTV poster child Liv Tyler is also on hand, playing
Willis' daughter and Affleck's lover while trying to make the movie
remotely palatable to female audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think just about everyone will find something to like in
this movie,'' Tyler says. ``Men, women, boys, girls, dogs, cats,
trees ...''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we're not completely sure that trees will appreciate
``Armageddon.'' We'll have to check with our Druid friends on that
and get back to you. And dogs and cats will have to wait until the
film comes out on video to enjoy its finer points. But there is no
disputing that all the other demographic bases are covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie's aspirations are so clear,'' Wilson says. ``It
wants to be the BIG summer movie. It will accept nothing less.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only place ``Armageddon'' might not play is France.
Audiences at the Cannes Festival were heard snickering during a
poignant late scene between Willis and Tyler when 50 minutes of the
film was shown there in May. After the movie, Willis sarcastically
told the crowd: ``Thank you for enjoying the comical aspects of the
film. I'm glad to see that you take the end of the world so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Michael Bay was a little more forthright in his
assessment when we asked him about his Cannes reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Americans are the ones who always save the world,''
Bay says. ``You don't see `Francois' landing a space shuttle on an
asteroid, do you?''
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't. That job is left to Willis and Affleck. (Note:
These interviews took place before Willis and wife Demi Moore
announced their breakup.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Having done three ``Die Hard'' movies and a few other
shoot-'em-ups, do you ever get tired of the action genre?
</P>
<P>
   Willis: They're still fun. I know a lot of actors labor over
what project to do next and how it's going to affect their careers.
But I just go with the fun thing to do. Fortunately or
unfortunately, that seems to be my criteria: Am I going to enjoy
myself?
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about being the father of a teen-age girl (Liv Tyler)?
That's a little twist compared to past roles.
</P>
<P>
   Willis: It was right on the edge of being mathematically
correct. But that's Hollywood. They stretch the truth a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Kind of like landing a space shuttle on an asteroid and
blowing it up?
</P>
<P>
   Willis: I don't know about landing on an asteroid, but there was
a giant asteroid that passed between the Earth and the moon four
years ago and if it had hit the Earth, it would have killed
everyone. No more newspapers. No more TV. No more movies. Just a
few survivors looking for a can of Chef Boyardee.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In my book, that would be the apocalypse. Doing this
interview must be a sign of the end of the world for you.
</P>
<P>
   Willis: I don't do many interviews any more. I was asked very
pointedly by the studio to help promote this film. That's why I'm
here.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is promotion and marketing now part of the territory for you?
</P>
<P>
   Willis: It's all commerce. But it's not part of my job. My job
is to be interesting in the film and to be entertaining. That's
all.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sounds pretty simple.
</P>
<P>
   Willis: I have a really low threshold for b-------. I've seen
too much in my time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has that made you a cynic?
</P>
<P>
   Willis: I have a really cynical attitude about the world. And I
say cynical because it's the easiest thing to say. Because don't
you think the government is b-------? Don't you think they're all
lying to you and just taking the money? Well that's just one
example of all the things I think are screwed up in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sounds like you've got a list.
</P>
<P>
   Willis: The government could feed everybody in this country
tomorrow if they wanted to. They pay farmers not to grow food.
Please. There are people who are starving, and they could solve it
by pushing one button _ and they don't do it. I don't know why.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've often come out and supported Republican causes. Are
you still in that camp?
</P>
<P>
   Willis: I'm a Republican insofar as I believe in smaller
government, less government intrusion and lower taxes. I also
believe in a lot of Democratic principles like feeding people who
are hungry and taking care of old people who can't take care of
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some might say that those things could pose some
contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   Willis: Not necessarily. There are a lot of great ideas in the
U.S. government that have been around for a long time. They're just
not taken advantage of because people are making money from
special-interest groups. And until that changes, the government is
never going to be anything more than politicians taking money from
people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Actors often get a hard time for expressing political
beliefs. You don't seem to have any problem going public with your
ideas, though.
</P>
<P>
   Willis: I have a point of view as a taxpaying citizen. I pay the
highest tax rate there is. So I have every right to a point of
view.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As long as we've completely abandoned talking about the
movie, are there any other things in our society that irk you?
</P>
<P>
   Willis: Don't you think the media's out of control? I'd say
we're about five years away from televised executions on
pay-per-view. Right now, there are shows where people regularly
beat each other up and people tune in to see that. That's not that
far from killing people.
</P>
<P>
   You hear, too, all this talk about, ``We can't stop the drug
problem.'' Let me tell you something. Someone is making money off
the drug trade in the United States. They could stop it as soon as
they wanted. Declare war on drugs. I mean, really declare war and
go to Colombia and say, ``It stops now, or we're going to make you
the 51st state.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I could see that happening in a movie _ probably in one where
you're the star. But in real life ...
</P>
<P>
   Willis: Why not? Or why not take all the things that are killing
people _ all the poison, all the trash _ and just put it in a big
rocket and aim it at the sun? No more nuclear radiation, no more
waste. And yet they bury it in the ground in 55-gallon drums.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And yet, many politicians seem more concerned about the
content in movies and television than they do about a lot of the
issues you've raised. What's your response?
</P>
<P>
   Willis: I don't think anybody who goes to see films thinks
anybody in the movies is really dead or got hurt. But when you
watch the news and you see that chalk outline on the ground and you
see pools of blood or dead people stacked up like cordwood, that is
the most terrifying thing that exists in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you can't seem to switch on the TV these days without
seeing those images or some car chase down the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Willis: ABC is competing with CBS who's competing with NBC to
see who is going to have the most sensationalistic story so you'll
watch their version of that plane tumbling down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Like I said before, it's all about commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After ``Chasing Amy'' and ``Good Will Hunting,'' audiences
might be scratching their heads wondering what you're doing in an
asteroids movie.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: I know. It sounds like I'm selling out. The funny thing
is, I was never the guy who wanted to do indie films. I grew up
loving the ``Star Wars'' movies, ``Indiana Jones'' and ``Back to
the Future.'' You'd never catch me watching a boring foreign film.
I was Mainstream Man. On the set, I kept asking Michael Bay where
my NASA light saber was.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you look at ``Armageddon'' as your big break, since you
were hired for that film before ``Good Will Hunting'' came out?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: Yeah, I always thought this would be the first movie
that a lot of people would see. My highest ambitions for ``Good
Will Hunting'' were that maybe a few critics would like it and it
would do break-even business because Robin (Williams) was in it. I
kept saying, ``Matty (Damon), if we just do $25 million, maybe
they'll let us do another movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: And now you've got an Oscar to show for it and everyone knows
who you are.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: It's weird, the whole fame thing. People are interested
in my personal life and I'm not even that interested in it. I guess
because you project this exciting, romantic life on the screen,
people presuppose you must have this dashing, exciting life at
home. And really, I'm just there sitting around watching TV with my
gut hanging out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since you're calling yourself Mainstream Man, do you plan on
taking your career in a pretty commercial direction?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: I'd like to do a bunch of different things. Maybe
that's impossible, but I'm going to try. After ``Armageddon,'' I
did Kevin Smith's next movie, ``Dogma,'' which cost all of $4
million. Then I did ``Shakespeare in Love,'' a period movie with
Geoffrey Rush, Dame Judi Dench and Gwyneth Paltrow. And now I'm
doing ``Forces of Nature,'' a romantic comedy with Sandra Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any desire to direct someday?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: Definitely. And when I do, it will probably be more
like ``Good Will Hunting'' than ``Armageddon'' because that's what
I know about _ relationships between young people trying to make
their way through life. I know very little about meteor showers and
space ships.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Being a relatively unknown actor at the time, were you a
little intimidated when you walked on to the ``Armageddon'' set?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: Are you kidding? I was extremely intimidated for the
first six weeks. I was intimidated by the scope of the movie, by
the money they were spending, by Jerry Bruckheimer, by Michael Bay,
who's very loud and brash until you figure him out ... And then
there's Bruce Willis, Billy Bob Thornton, Peter Stormare, Steve
Buscemi. I felt like the absolute scrub rookie player on a veteran
all-star team.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So how'd you manage to come out of that?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: I just tried to figure out how these movies work. Since
you're competing with all these visual and audio histrionics, you
have to simplify and choose one thing that's going to be the
centerpiece of your performance. For me, I made this character a
guy who has something to prove, so he was willing to take enormous
risks. And when they diQ't pay off, he'd feel hurt and want to take
even bigger risks just so Bruce's character would like him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did Willis offer any advice?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: Bruce had some pearls of wisdom. (Laughing) I taught
Bruce a lot about acting and he taught me a lot about the benefits
of Viagra. So it worked out well.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's hard to picture you being intimidated. You seem pretty
outgoing.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: My mother always accused me of being in love with the
sound of my own voice. We'd be on road trips and she'd be like,
``STOP SINGING! Be quiet! You're talking just to hear yourself
speak!'' Which is probably true because I tend to like to
pontificate and ramble on about stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Matt Damon is much the same way. How'd you ever write that
``Good Will Hunting'' script together?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: We have a thing where we'll both have an idea at the
same time and it's just a matter of which one of us talks louder,
that's whose idea wins out. Being around us when we write is tough.
You need earplugs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have plans to write together again?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: We'll be writing some stuff this summer. Matty's in
Italy making a movie, so in our spare time, we'll write.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sure, you will.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: I know. It sounds bad. It's like I needed an excuse to
go to Italy, so I called up Miramax and said, ``Look. Send a
ticket. Matty and I are going to be working. Really. Don't worry.
And make sure you cover all our expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you guys ever compare notes or shake your heads in
disbelief over your new status as sex symbols?
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: (Laughs) You know, I don't see myself as a sex symbol.
Sex symbols tend to be blond, sexually ambiguous ... you know, that
David Cassidy kind of thing. In a weird way, it's the 13-year-old
girls who define who's a sex symbol because they're the ones who
show up at events shrieking. You need a certain kind of
innocuousness to appeal to that. I don't think I have it. Matty, on
the other hand, might, with his blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So you'll leave the Teen Beat audience to him.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck: Yeah. If I'm going to be a sex symbol, I'd rather be
one for mature, 30-year-old women. In my opinion, they have better
taste anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
