<SLUG> BC-ONECONOMICS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERATION XERS' FORTUNES FALL ON HARD TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Never before in history have so many twentysomethings made so much
money, so fast. Young luminaries of the digital revolution such as
Marc Andreessen of Netscape Communications, David Filo and Jerry
Yang of Yahoo, and Michael Dell of Dell Computer have become richer
than most kings and corporate titans of old.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But many of their generation, and a majority of men, are
slipping behind the economic status of young adults in previous
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Unless middle age unexpectedly revives their fortunes, many of
today's Generation Xers may be doomed to a standard of living worse
than their parents _ even though they are the most educated group
of young adults in America's history.
</P>
<P>
   The median (middle-ranking) worker aged 25 to 34 made $20,909 in
1996, according to the Census Bureau. But 20 years earlier, the
average Baby Boomer in that same age bracket made $23,123 (in 1996
dollars) _ 11 per cent more.
</P>
<P>
   (Some college grads this year are enjoying big salaries and
signing bonuses, but it's too soon to say how much young workers
overall are benefiting from the tight labor market.)
</P>
<P>
   Most forecasters didn't expect this pay decline. With the end of
the Baby Boom in 1964, birth rates declined. As the ``Baby Bust''
generation entered the labor market, the smaller supply of workers
was expected to boost their wages.
</P>
<P>
   Business Week predicted in 1979, ``Over the next 25 years (the
Baby Bust generation) will enjoy better entry-level jobs, higher
relative income, and faster promotions because of sparser
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Generation Xers also should be earning more money thanks to
superior educational credentials. In 1996, 27 percent of adults
ages 25 to 29 had completed college, compared with only 19 percent
of that age group in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   But two recent studies by economists at the Bureau of Labor
Statistics demolish those optimistic scenarios with sobering
statistics:
</P>
<P>
   _ Real (inflation-adjusted) median earnings for young adults, 25
to 34, fell from $545 per week in 1979 to $463 per week in 1996, a
15 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   _ Young adults also lost ground relative to older workers. The
earnings of young adults fell from 95 percent of what all adults
earned in 1979 to 89 percent by 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many of the fastest growing occupations for young adults
between 1979 and 1996 were low-paying ones such as sales, service
and laboring jobs.
</P>
<P>
   With hardly any exceptions, ``members of Generation X appear to
be worse off by every measure'' than their Baby Boom predecessors,
concluded BLS economists Geoffrey Paulin and Brian Riordan in
Monthly Labor Review, a publication of the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
   These trends might not be so worrisome if young workers could
count on fat pay raises as they become older and more experienced.
But the evidence strongly suggests that the rewards of maturity
won't make up for youthful deprivation.
</P>
<P>
   Men who were 25 to 34 years old in 1956 enjoyed a 67 percent
jump in median income over the next 20 years. But young men in 1966
saw only a 37 percent rise in earnings as they aged over the
following two decades.
</P>
<P>
   And young men in 1976 went on to make a mere 17 percent more by
the time they reached middle age in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown in pay growth ``raises the issue of whether the
most recent cohorts will ever achieve incomes equal to those of the
earlier postwar cohorts,'' said Jared Bernstein, an economist at
the Economic Policy Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given continued slow income growth and falling real wages, it
is very possible that the recent (and some future) cohorts will
have lifetime incomes inferior to those of their parent's
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   But now we come to a paradox: National surveys actually seem to
show an improvement over time in the happiness of young Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The General Social Survey, conducted by the University of
Chicago, shows little change in reported well-being of Americans
overall. But for those under the age of 30, the number saying they
were ``not too happy'' fell from 14 percent in the 1970s to 10
percent in the 1990s. The number calling themselves ``quite happy''
rose from 58 percent to 63 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   British economists David Blanchflower and Andrew Oswald called
this change ``a large movement'' compared to the generally glacial
trends in such surveys.
</P>
<P>
   One possible explanation is that government income statistics
understate the economic advances of workers.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists claim official figures overstate inflation and
thus understate real pay gains by all workers, old as well as
young. But there's no consensus on just how far off the official
numbers are, or whether appropriate corrections would turn apparent
pay losses into pay gains.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible answer is suggested by the fact that the
growing happiness among young adults is confined almost entirely to
those who are not married.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that young men and women have benefited from
society's recently increased tolerance of those living outside
marriage, and from their consequent ability to live in less formal
relationships,'' Oswald and Blanchflower speculate.
</P>
<P>
   Oswald admits that their research raises more questions than it
answers. But it does confirm that income has only a small effect on
reported happiness. Were it otherwise, most twentysomethings would
be in a real funk today.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; Jonathan Marshall can be reached by e-mail at marshall &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
