<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1826 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-29 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     BETWEEN THE NORTH AND THE SOUTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   The corps of skilled workers who toil in Silicon Valley and live
in San Francisco are ``changing the City by the Bay from the cradle
of counterculture to a cybergeek suburb,'' writes &UR; Romesh &LR; 
 &UR; Ratnesar &LR;  in this week's New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Hi-techies ``drawn by the neighborhood's close proximity to the
freeways'' have particularly infiltrated Potrero Hill, says the
author, and in the Marina district, Chestnut Street ``has become a
yuppie strip mall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is becoming a suburb of Palo Alto,'' says
Marina-district resident  &UR; Candace Tavernas &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Mary Etta Moose &LR;  writes that her niece, househunting in
San Francisco, rejected one property after consulting an internet
site that informed her there were only nine restaurants in a
half-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COUNTER CULTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Personals' weekend reading was highlighted by a stroll through
the garage sale classifieds in Saturday's Chronicle:
</P>
<P>
   Is your dungeon dingy? A ``Dungeon Close-Out'' in Tracy offered
``Adult toys and equipment. Featured in international videos.
Stock, rack, suspension devices and cages.'' A Russian Hill garage
sale included the come-on, ``Aren't gay garage sales the best?''
</P>
<P>
   And apparently, ``The Antiques Road Show'' is getting some
competition. A ``new appraisal TV show'' is searching for a
``garage sale/flea market/treasure hunting fanatic with a
flamboyant/unique personality.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LIES THAT BIND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on the ``Tonight Show'' a few months ago,
 &UR; Fran Drescher  &LR; told  &UR; Jay &LR;   &UR; Leno &LR;  about cutting her finger while
slicing a muffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``As millions of wincing viewers looked on,'' says a report in
the latest Allure magazine, ``Drescher described in graphic detail
how blood had gone everywhere and how when paramedics rushed to the
scene, she made them wait until she'd showered and changed clothes
before going to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Daily Variety said she had made up the
anecdote so that she'd have something interesting to say. Drescher
admitted the story wasn't true, but rejected any negative
implications. ``I feel totally victimized,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Grateful Dead archivist, journalist and radio personality
 &UR; David Gans  &LR; and the Broken Angels have cut their first CD,
`` &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; ,'' which includes the lyrics: ``Clintonian
moments in your head / The people of America have been misled/
Inquiring minds are overfed. ...'' More information at
 &LR; www.trufun.com &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Sidney Mobell &LR; 's gold-and-diamond Monopoly set is not the
most expensive game ever made, writes  &UR; John Joss &LR; . ``Sid's a piker.
Politics and war have him beat by billions.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Mare Winningham &LR;  revealed at a New York premiere party for
``Everything That Rises,'' a TNT movie directed by  &UR; Dennis Quaid &LR; 
and set to be broadcast on July 12, that ``Lonesomer,'' an album of
her singing ``folk pop,'' will be released this week. Winningham
was nominated for an Oscar for her performance as a folk singing
star in the 1995 movie ``Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Doug Hayward &LR;  says that  &UR; Jerry Brown &LR;  didn't know the
microphone was still on when he patted himself on the back after
panning the new Bay Bridge design on KTVU-TV Tuesday night. ``Now
 &LR; that  &LR; sent them a message they can understand,'' said Brown. The
design he hated was approved on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHINNY YOUR WAY TO BEAUTY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   First hoof creams became popular hand creams for humans; then
mane conditioners became popular for hair. Then came ``The Horse
Whisperer.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, says New York magazine, Awake Cosmetics is producing an
Equestrian Color Collection, including such Bridle and Stirrup eye
shadow, and Pirouette and Canter lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Miraval Spa in Arizona offers an ``Equine
Experience'' package that lets clients ride, touch and whisper to
the horses, thereby enabling them to ``capture some of the horse's
strength and nobility and embody it'' themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And at the highest end, Hermes told New York that ``sales for
equestrian-themed items have definitely increased since the film.
Everyone wants that look, if not necessarily that lifestyle. Too
much manure, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
