r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Telecom Rivals Say Pac Bell's FCC Plea Part of Hidden Agenda   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Pacific Bell made a plea to the Federal Communications Commission
this month: Ease up on some of rules blocking it from deploying
ADSL (a fast, new Internet service that runs over plain old phone
lines).
<TEXT>
<P>
   But rivals say Pac Bell has a hidden agenda _ sneaking into the
long-distance market before it opens its local telephone monopoly
to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This application is part of a plan to circumvent the
requirements they are subject to under the Telecom Act,'' said MCI
spokesman Richard Severy.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell spokesman John Britton said that criticism is
misplaced. Although three other Baby Bells _ Bell Atlantic, US West
and Ameritech _ have asked the FCC for permission to carry ADSL
over long-distance, Pac Bell didn't make that same request.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said all Pac Bell wants is freedom from certain rules
that hinder it from competing with ADSL startups like Covad and
North Point Communications, which are cherry-picking business
customers who want high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``Data has become the king of the network,'' Britton said. ``We
can't meet the data needs of our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   But rivals are suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   They fear that if Pac Bell expands its current ADSL pipeline, it
could start serving long-distance customers who talk instead of
type _ by taking advantage of new technology that can turn voice
traffic into digital bits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same facilities (Pac Bell) wants permission to install
could, with minor adaptations, be used to complete long-distance
calls,'' said AT&AMP;T spokesman Wayne Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   But Britton said, ``Pacific Bell isn't going to try to sneak
voice into packets and make it look like data.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC will consider ADSL petitions against the backdrop of
last week's AT&AMP;T-TCI merger _ which has been billed as a way for
AT&AMP;T to buy the wires into your home.
</P>
<P>
   And you thought deregulation made things simpler!
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Irrelevant? &LR;  Ensemble Information Systems in San Rafael sells
a $10,000 software package that creates custom Web pages on the
fly, so each time you visit a site, you only see information
relevant to your user profile _ hence the product name, Relevant.
</P>
<P>
   Led by President and chief technologist Jean Christofferson, the
Ensemble team includes financial whiz Cyndi Goddard, sales chief
Vicy Van Meter and Web designer Sarah Baron  &LR; (www.ensemble.com). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Goddard contacted me after I wrote about politicians using Web
sites in campaigns. She said Ensemble had offered Jane Harman a pro
bono dose of Relevant to power the Web site for her failed
gubernatorial bid.
</P>
<P>
   Harman ignored the offer. Fortunately for Ensemble's balance
sheet, the firm has paying clients like Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes
&AMP; Lerach, the law firm that files class-action lawsuits against
high-tech firms.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Mapmaker: &LR;  Ten years ago, Fern Greene gave up a career in New
York network television to get on the mommy track in Novato. But as
her sons reached school age, she itched to segue from part-time
multimedia designer to full-fledged entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   So three years ago, she set out to create a CD-ROM game that
teaches kids how to read and make maps. With help from San Jose
multimedia consultant Mark Bunzel, Greene spent two years hunting
for a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Makoto Morise of Panasonic Interactive Media in Santa
Clara finally agreed to publish Make-A-Map 3D. The Associated Press
named the $30 Mac/PC title one of the Top 10 tech products of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Persistence and tenacity were my best attributes,'' said
Greene, who now is working on a series of children's adventure
games.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Postindustrial chic &LR; : Several hundred people gathered under
the freeway Thursday night at Fourth and Harrison streets in San
Francisco to watch a battle among remote-controlled robots.
</P>
<P>
   Welded from pieces of backhoes and other machines, the robots
looked like giant mutant toys. The spectators, largely
leather-garbed twentysomethings, stood silhouetted on rooftops and
cars and in phalanxes around the combatants.
</P>
<P>
   The event was organized by San Francisco performance artist Mark
Pauline, who has spent the past 20 years putting military and
civilian technologies to weird uses _ to show that technology has a
mind of its own. His philosophy and exploits are explained at the
Web site of Survival Research Laboratories  &LR; (www.srl.org) &LR; , the
organization he founded in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at
sign)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1833 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AURORA-SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AURORA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Investors Don't Bite at Aurora Foods IPO   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Wall Street had a tepid reaction to yesterday's initial public
offering of Aurora Foods Inc., the San Francisco maker of such
well-known supermarket products as Duncan Hines cake mixes and Aunt
Jemima frozen waffles.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of the highly leveraged company ended the day at $21,
exactly the price at which they began trading. They peaked at a
lackluster $21.13 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of 14.5 million shares by a syndicate led by Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co. raised $304.5 million for Aurora and its owners. The
company also completed a $200 million debt offering yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Schaadt, a food industry analyst with Fourteen Research
Corp. in New York, attributed the stock's unenthusiastic reception
to the fact that Aurora carries $700 million in debt from its
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Packaged food is also a highly competitive business, Schaadt
said. ``There is a lot of competition for shelf space in the
supermarket, so it could be investors are saying, `Let's wait and
see''' how the company performs.
</P>
<P>
   The economy may also be a factor. Food stocks tend to perform
better in down economies, while during boom times ``there are other
things that are more exciting'' such as technology and retailing
stocks, Schaadt said.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora was created in a recent deal that united the seven
branded food lines of two predecessor companies: Aurora Foods
Holdings and VDK Foods Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The new company's strategy is to continue buying and reviving
underperforming, non-core food lines, according to a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora's predecessor companies showed significant progress in
turning around brands within a year of acquiring them from larger
food companies, the filing said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Celeste frozen pizzas, for example, rose 8.6 percent
after dropping 16.8 percent in the year prior to the acquisition,
when the line was owned by Quaker Oats, the filing said.
</P>
<P>
   And Sales of Mrs. Paul's frozen seafood products, formerly owned
by Campbell Soup Co., rose 7.1 percent after falling 9.2 percent
the prior year.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora's other brands include Log Cabin, Mrs. Butterworth's and
Van de Kamp's. All of the lines, which have been acquired since
September 1995, occupy the No. 1 or No. 2 position in their
categories, the filing said.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the products last year generated net income of $25.3
million on sales of $874.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora's principal pre-IPO stockholders include three investment
firms that had stakes in Aurora's predecessor companies: San
Francisco-based Dartford Partnership LLC, New York's Fenway
Partners Inc. and McCown De Leeuw &AMP; Co. of Menlo Park and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Wilson, a Dartford partner, is Aurora's chairman and chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Aurora Vice Chairman Jamie Ardrey also a Dartford
partner,declined to comment on the offering yesterday, saying the
company remains in a quiet period for the next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
