<HEADER>
A1844 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIANTS-BBN-GIANTS-SFC     06-29 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANTS-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A'S HOSE OFF OVERHEATED GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY SCHULMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Two San Francisco police officers stood guard outside the
umpires' locker room after Thursday's game, which is all you need
to know about the state of Giants' relations with the men in blue
right now.
</P>
<P>
   A's closer Billy Taylor stood on the mound after the last out,
mocking Barry Bonds' ``raise the roof'' hand gesture, which is all
you need to know about the state of the Giants' game right now.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland won 5-2 to complete an unusual split in the transbay
interleague series. The Giants won the two games at the Oakland
Coliseum, while the A's took the two at 3Com Park. While the A's
left for Colorado after Thursday's finale, the umpiring crew of
Mike Winters, Hunter Wendlestedt, Larry Poncino and Steve Rippley
stuck around to work this weekend's Giants' series against the
Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   It should be an interesting weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Rippley ejected Giants catcher Brian Johnson for
arguing balls and strikes, Winters tossed pinch-hitter Charlie
Hayes for the same offense in the eighth inning Thursday. Hayes did
not take it well. In fact, he charged Winters and needed to be
wrestled to the ground by manager Dusty Baker, who ended up on the
turf himself, along with first-base coach Carlos Alfonso and
several others who rushed over to restrain Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   A clump of players and coaches, including Barry Bonds and Orel
Hershiser, had to drag a screaming Hayes to the dugout, which is no
easy task. He's a big guy. When Hayes walked to his car 40 minutes
later, he was still steaming about Winters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to go f_ myself,'' Hayes said. ``The next one who
says that to me, I'm hitting in the mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Winters' response: ``I don't think I said that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were trailing 4-2 and had two runners on and two out
when Baker sent Hayes to pinch-hit for Ramon Martinez. Taylor was
called in to face Hayes and fell behind 2-1. The big right-hander
then threw a slow bending slider that Hayes thought was inside.
Winters called it a strike, drawing an incredulous look from Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   On the next pitch, Hayes hit a meager pop-up to third to end the
inning. Baker sent Hayes out to play third base, and on his way
there he began arguing with Winters. That's when the chaos began.
Winters ejected Hayes, who then went after the umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was popping off, and he continued to pop off after he
popped up,'' Winters pointed out. ``He continued it long enough to
where he was ejected. It was simple. I had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Winters might have had too much of Hayes' body on him had Baker
and Alfonso not restrained the player. Baker and Alfonso were
losing the battle when the manager finally dragged Hayes to the
ground as the crowd of 23,069 began chanting, ``Charlie! Charlie!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a guy go after an umpire like that,'' Taylor
said. ``It was a good pitch, a late breaker on the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said that Hayes' actions were not premeditated, but a
reaction to Winters saying something he was not supposed to say.
``That's when Charlie went off,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   As Hayes walked to his car after the game he insisted that he
merely engaged Winters in ``normal conversation about balls and
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he made a bad call,'' Hayes said. ``The balls he
was calling were strikes, and the strikes he was calling were
balls. He said, `Go f_ yourself,' and that's when I snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never disrespected him. For some reason, the umpires think
they can disrespect us. I've been thrown out of four games, and
that guy has thrown me out of three of them. I just want right to
be right, and wrong to be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who was right and who was wrong in the Johnson
/Rippley and Winters/Hayes affairs, the Giants will have to find a
way to coexist with the crew this weekend. The Rangers are the
American League's best-hitting team, with a .294 average, and
though umpires are pretty good about not holding grudges, they are
human.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day is different,'' Johnson said. ``You hope everybody
can be professional enough to do our jobs. We are, as players, you
hope the umpires can too.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was still upset about his ejection a night earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, there are no checks and balances as far as the
umpires are concerned. They're able to do whatever they wish,'' he
said. ``It's very similar to the depiction of the cop twirling his
baton and saying, `I can do anything I want.' If we fail to do our
jobs, we get demoted or fined. There's nothing comparable for the
umpires. You never see them get fined.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hayes episode breathed life into what had been a dull game.
The A's took a 4-0 lead in a bizarre fourth inning in which Shawn
Estes threw two wild pitches and walked three A's, including
pitcher Jimmy Haynes with two out, while catcher Brent Mayne
committed a passed ball and made his second wild throw to second in
as many games.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes was the first A's pitcher to draw a walk since Ken
Holtzman in 1973. Rickey Henderson followed with a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell asleep in the middle of the third inning and woke up in
the Twilight Zone,'' Estes said. ``Balls were falling all over the
place. It was just like pinball.''
</P>
<P>
   Good pinball, maybe, but bad baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants scored on J.T. Snow's double, a wild pitch and Bill
Mueller's sacrifice fly in the fourth, and singles by Snow, Stan
Javier and Mayne in the eighth. But Taylor struck out Bonds looking
for the second straight game to end it. Taylor then mocked Bonds'
hand gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what anybody says,'' the pitcher said. ``There
has always been a rivalry here. When two teams from the same area
play, it always means a lot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1845 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON-W     06-29 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON-WARRIORS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNTRODDEN TEAM TOUCHED BY AN ANGEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM KEOWN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's presume the Warriors have a plan. Let's presume Garry St.
Jean and P.J. Carlesimo know more than we do. Let's presume they
understand the importance of employing men who can dribble
competently and shoot the ball from outside the key.
</P>
<P>
   Working under this presumption, Antawn Jamison will be a fine
addition to a team that needs several more.
</P>
<P>
   There has to be something else coming. The Warriors can't go
into the season with a backcourt of Bimbo Coles and Tony Delk and
team it with a frontcourt of Jamison, Erick Dampier and Donyell
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you can say about that lineup: Jamison would be able
to perfect his specialty _ offensive rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   The key to this for anyone who cares about the Warriors is
ignorance. Ignore history. Ignore the pang of anxiety that hit when
you saw them hand Jamison the No.4 jersey _ Chris Webber's old
number. Ignore the past two Warriors No.1 picks, static forwards
Todd Fuller and Adonal Foyle. Ignore the memory of Joe Smith, who
was on hand the last time the Warriors were surprised by the
outside shooting of a 'tweener forward in predraft workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Because if you leave history out of it _ and if you let your
mind leap ahead to a Terrell Brandon-for-Latrell Sprewell trade _
it's impossible not to like Jamison.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors unfurled Jamison to a mostly unsuspecting lunchtime
crowd at the Oakland City Center on Thursday, and it was
immediately apparent why the Warriors fell all over themselves to
get this guy.
</P>
<P>
   He says he wants to be here, and he looks sincere when he says
it. He wants Carlesimo to get in his face, because he is used to
that and respects a coach who will not accept losing and
lackadaisical play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not one of those coaches who kisses your butt because
you're making this much money or because you can shoot a
basketball,'' Jamison said.
</P>
<P>
   If P.J. wants more mustard on the passes, that's what he'll get.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all. When he heard about Sprewell's choking of
Carlesimo, Jamison says his first thought was, ``How can a player
do this to a coach?''
</P>
<P>
   When he was a kid, Antawn and his father used to play
one-on-one, and the loser had to cut the grass. ``I've been cutting
the grass for some time,'' Albert Jamison said Thursday. His tone
was more begrudging than joking. You get the feeling the old man _
he's only 41, but still _ wouldn't mind another crack at the kid,
and that's a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, it's hard to presume the Warriors are going to
do anything right. For a long time, we have been conditioned to
think the worst of the Warriors. It's Pavlovian: If the Warriors
did it, it must be wrong. This habit came about after years of
practice, and one unfortunate discovery: Thinking the absolute
worst about the local NBA entry didn't come close to matching
reality. Our imaginations simply weren't big enough.
</P>
<P>
   Forgive the digression, but the best comparison comes from a
bridge-construction project in Iowa. The project was well under way
when a worker went to his supervisor recently and said, ``Yo, boss,
this is one fine project we got going, but this here bridge isn't
going to make it all the way across that water.'' The worker was
right; the bridge was being built over the wrong stretch of river.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Warriors _ always building something that stands no
chance of reaching land.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back to Jamison, let's agree on one thing: It's best not
to get caught up in the tender psyche of Donyell Marshall. What
does Jamison's presence mean for Marshall? Who cares? Not to cast
aspersions on Marshall _ he improved drastically, played hard, all
that _ but there isn't anything there to convince the Warriors
they're set in the frontcourt for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   After all,  &LR; somebody &LR;  had to score last year, and it just so
happens that a lot of the scoring fell to Marshall. He did it, and
congrats to him, but the respective talents of Marshall and Jamison
are not mutually exclusive. They can play together, and if Marshall
ends up being the first guy off the bench, then the team has
improved.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison came to town wearing a sharp four-button suit with an
angel pendant pinned to the right lapel. Asked to explain the
importance of the angel, Jamison got passionate:
</P>
<P>
   It reminds him of the bad times his family has endured, the
hardships and trials. It reminds him of his grandmother, who died
about five years ago. He used to wear it everywhere, even pinned to
his shoes on the court. That proved impractical _ it kept coming
loose and falling off on the court _ so he began holding it in his
hand until it was time to put it in his locker and take the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The angels are watching over me every day _ they were
definitely watching over me (Wednesday night),'' Jamison said. ``I
wear it everywhere. It signifies a lot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what the Warriors are counting on _ angels. Lord
knows they need them, and maybe they found one. In fact, let's
presume that, too. Sometimes it beats trying to figure out the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
