r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIN98-SFCHRON-WINDOWS     06-29 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIN98-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN 98 GETS TEPID RESPONSE  
 BY JULIA ANGWIN AND JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - WINDOWS 98   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Windows 98 got a lukewarm response at many Bay Area computer
stores when it hit store shelves at 12:01 a.m. yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   A few die-hard techies lined up at stores to buy the
controversial software. But most midnight shoppers saved their real
enthusiasm for $98 computers that CompUSA stores around the country
were offering in limited supply as Windows 98 promos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good deal but I don't know if it's worth it,'' said
Nicole Wright, a stockbroker who waited in line for 12 hours at
CompUSA in San Francisco to buy a $98 computer.
</P>
<P>
   She was one of the lucky ones _ each CompUSA store only sold 10
cheap computers. The rest of the crowd had to console themselves
with steeply discounted modems, CD-ROMS and armfuls of the $89
Windows 98 software.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came because I thought it would be sold out tomorrow,'' said
Doc Casey, who spent part of his vacation from Taiwan at the San
Bruno CompUSA store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to install all of them as soon as I get home,'' he
said, balancing a stack of Windows 98 boxes under his arm.
</P>
<P>
   However, the software rush was a pale imitation of the frenzy
surrounding the launch of Windows 95 _ when customers around the
country lined up just for the software and 1 million copies flew
off the shelf in the first day.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft would not predict sales of Windows 98 _ an update to
Windows 95, which runs most of the world's personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nowhere near the demand for Windows 98 (as for
Windows 95),'' said Al Thoman, owner of Friendly Software in San
Carlos. ``Computer users aren't as pressed to upgrade their
software this time.'' Analysts predict Windows 98 sales will lag in
comparison to Windows 95, which gave the Windows operating system's
``look and feel'' a dramatic face-lift.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, much of the hype around Windows 98 has nothing to do
with technology _ but is driven by the government's antitrust case
against Microsoft that focuses on Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   `If it weren't for the Justice Department, this would be the
nonevent of the year,'' said Jeff Tarter, editor of Softletter, an
industry publication in Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put this under the get-a-life file,'' he said. ``Are you sure
that half the people in line weren't Justice officials?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the two dozen midnight customers at Fry's
Electronics in Palo Alto _ which was not offering any cheap
computer promotions _ were there to gawk, not to shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was curious about what the turnout was going to be,'' said
Denver Lough. ``But there's no one here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lough showed up at 11:30 to make sure he got a place in line
after hearing about the expected crowds on the radio. He also was
trying to escape the construction noise outside his house. He was
the first person in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is it is a tempest in a teapot,'' said Lough, a Los
Altos consultant who bought Windows 98 to fix some bugs on his home
PC.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Devore, who works next door to Fry's, said he was drawn to
the store by the big searchlights that lit up the sky. But when he
got there, he saw an empty parking lot and few shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to see the hype but I didn't see any hype,'' said
Devore, a 25-year-old self-proclaimed Macintosh user.
</P>
<P>
   While it was practically a ghost town at Fry's, it was like the
``The Rocky Horror Picture Show'' for nerds at CompUSA stores,
vying for the $98 PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a light drizzle, stiff wind and temperatures in the low
50s, a crowd of 400 people lined up outside the San Bruno store.
Several hundred also showed up at the San Francisco store.
</P>
<P>
   Although the twenty-something crowd in San Bruno was quiet and
well behaved, two policemen and store employees lurked nearby to
make sure no one cut in line.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Louie of San Francisco spent his time in line leafing
through a computer manual.
</P>
<P>
   Louie said he wanted the modest software upgrade because of
improvements such as being able to run DVD drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear it's also a lot faster and more efficient for booting
my system up,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Others in line had different things on their mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good place to pick up computer chicks,'' joked Brian
Beaver of San Francisco. ``I would buy (Windows 98) one way or
another, but I came here mainly because it's an event.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft shares fell $3.38 to $101.56 in trading of 22.1
million, making it the second most active U.S. stock. Earlier, the
shares climbed to a record $106.88.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;
</P>
