<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAGS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE PASSENGERS FEEL A CARRY-ON SQUEEZE  
   
   
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - BAGS   By Kenneth Howe  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
U.S. airlines are starting to crack down on excess carry-on
baggage, but so far their policies are only being selectively
enforced.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On crowded flights, passengers are likely to be limited to no
more than two carry-on bags _ with briefcases, laptop computers and
large purses counting as one. But on less crowded flights, the new
two-bag limit may be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines say they need to limit carry-on bags to ensure
safety and speed up boarding and exiting on increasingly crowded
flights.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, United Airlines plans to take stronger action,
strictly limiting the size of any carry-on bag to 45 linear inches,
a measurement derived from adding the height, length and width of a
bag.
</P>
<P>
   United is testing at least two devices to screen for oversized
bags. At San Francisco International Airport, it is using a
laser-beam that measures bags as they exit the X-ray machine.
</P>
<P>
   The lasers work, but psychologically, they should go in front of
the X-ray machine so that a bag can be rejected as too big before
it passes security, said Greg Couper director of airport services
for United.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unconsciously, passengers feel if the bag goes through
security screening, it has passed some rite of validation and
they're hanging on to it,'' said Carol Holmes, assistant to the
president of the Association of Flight Attendants.
</P>
<P>
   United said it has been more successful with a low-tech device
being tested in Los Angeles International. A plexiglass template is
bolted to the front of the X-ray machine with a 10-inch by 15-inch
hole cut in it. If the bag fits though it can be carried aboard. If
not, it must be checked.
</P>
<P>
   The new policies pose a problem to some travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real drag,'' said musician Erik Torjeson, who had a
guitar damaged when he was forced to check it as baggage on a Delta
Air Lines flight.
</P>
<P>
   Torjeson is a guitarist with Starship Featuring Mickey Thomas, a
spin-off of the rock group Jefferson Starship. Yesterday, he was
allowed to carry his $1,000 guitar onto a United flight. ``These
are delicate instruments and we travel all the time,'' he said. ``I
can't check this as baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration ordered airlines to come up
with their own &UR;  &LR; carry-on baggage policies 10 years ago, but until
recently, the airlines had little incentive to write detailed rules
or enforce them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, carry-on baggage has become a big problem.
``It's like weeds in the garden _ it's just kept growing on us,''
said Couper.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the growing popularity of rolling carry-on
luggage, or ``wheelies.'' Luggage-makers discovered the wheel about
four years ago. They have made carting carry-on to the gate much
easier, especially for the old and the very young, who may have
lacked the strength to sling much baggage over their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the carry-on glut is that there are simply
more passengers on each flight. The average flight today is 70 to
75 percent full, up from 60 to 65 percent just a few years ago,
according to the Association of Flight Attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Couper said United is concerned about the issue for three
reasons. Too many carry-on bags leads to chaos in the aisles. The
added time spent finding extra space for too many bags also delays
flights. Finally, there is the safety issue.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA, a flight attendants union, estimated in 1996 that as
many as 4,500 passengers and 3,600 flight attendants a year are
injured by falling carry-on bags.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference on carry-on bag injuries last year, a passenger
recounted how a laptop computer fell on her head, resulting in a
compressed spine. Another told of being struck by a piece of metal
luggage, which left the victim needing a cane to walk for the next
two-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
   ``And these are only the reported accidents,'' said the AFA's
Holmes. ``We don't know how many injuries go unreported.
</P>
<P>
   Couper said leisure and business travelers are equally likely to
carry on too much. But he said that oversized carry-ons are a
bigger problem than too many bags.
</P>
<P>
   United studies have shown that 16 to 17 percent of passengers
bring carry-ons that are too big.
</P>
<P>
   But only 3 to 4 percent of travelers bring more than two
carry-ons. United said it has reduced that figure to 1 to 2 percent
since it started enforcing its two-bag limit in May.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, carry-on constraints could ease as reconfigure
some of their craft to allow for bigger bins, and start flying
bigger planes with roomier overhead compartments. But those
solutions will take time.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants would like the FAA to come up with a
standard rule for carry-ons.
</P>
<P>
   But the FAA has no plans to do so. ``Our regulations say that
bags must be properly stowed,'' said FAA spokeswoman Kathryn
Creedy. ``But there needs to be flexibility between airlines.'' She
noted that different carriers use different aircraft, which have
more or less space in the cabin. Moreover, each carrier can
configure the same aircraft in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   One Congressman is taking the issue into is own hands.
Representative William Lipinski, D-Ill., has introduced H.R. 3064,
which, among other things, would prohibit passengers from bringing
more than a single carry-on bag on board a commercial aircraft.
However, neither the FAA, the airlines nor the flight attendants
support the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
