<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ONLY CHINA LISTENED TO ZHAO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Those needing a metaphor for President Clinton's
travails in China have been obliged by a 78-year-old guy who could
have been more than a contender, and still has more guts than the
typical pols inflicted on citizens from both ends of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Zhao Ziyang was in public view as a big shot, he
was in tears, but he was also still the general secretary (as in
Big Enchilada) of the Chinese Communist Party. Zhao was in
Tiananmen Square on the evening of May 19, 1989, pleading with the
leaders of the young democracy demonstrators (whose cause he had
both cynically and genuinely championed) to declare victory and go
home. He failed, lost his power, lost his effort to avoid martial
law, and lost in his attempt to prevent the horror and outrage that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Even in impotence and house detention, however, Zhao has never
quite shut up, as was apparent last week when a letter he wrote his
former comrades in the Chinese leadership earlier this month
surfaced in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   What was remarkable about the letter was not the criticism of
his successors that was emphasized in news accounts. What was
remarkable was its confidence and its optimism as Zhao publicly
urged today's leaders to use an acknowledgement of the colossal sin
that Tiananmen represents to reap great benefits for China's
future, internally and externally.
</P>
<P>
   Follow his train of thought, keeping in mind that his intended
audience is mostly Chinese and that the letter was addressed to the
party's Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
   This onetime economic modernizer and Deng Xiaoping underling
thinks Clinton's visit is a decided ``turn for the better'' in
Sino-US relations at the beginning of what he also thinks will be a
period of even more enormous scientific and economic progress in
China.
</P>
<P>
   In this exciting era, Zhao is without any doubt that additional
personal and political freedom is simply inevitable, or, as he put
it, ``The trend of democracy cannot be blocked.''
</P>
<P>
   So, if it's inevitable, if it's also in China's interest, what
is the point, Zhao wonders, about clinging to an official version
of the mass killing that began on June 4, 1989, that is wrong,
known to be wrong by the people, a blot on China's international
image, and an obstacle to its future progress? Or, as he wrote last
month:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past the Communist Party of China has rectified many
historical mistakes. Now we are facing the arrival of a new, open,
democratic, and information-age era. What reason do we have to
reject the will of the people, cling to the June 4 problem, and
block our road to democratic politics?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't drag June 4 into the next century to resolve. The time
is ripe now to resolve the problem. We should give it a fair
appraisal. We should not carry a historical burden into the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more to the point, Zhao argued that expiation in the form
of reversing the official line about Tiananmen, namely that it was
a proper response to a ``counter-revolutionary'' threat, would
``bring 100 benefits and no harm'' and get rid of most of the
``factors'' abroad that are ``restricting China economically,
politically and culturally.''
</P>
<P>
   One clue that he is right can be found anytime Chinese
officials, big-shot or little-shot, are asked about the massacre.
They go on auto-pilot, the official line being that the verdict was
correct and is reaffirmed in party and government gatherings all
the time. They simply cannot handle the followup: If the verdict is
so solid, how come it keeps coming up?
</P>
<P>
   This suggests two courses of action for now. One, recommended by
smart dissidents, is that Americans from Clinton on down make sure
they tell the Chinese how they feel about the massacre. What is
requested is not mindless confrontation but skillful
identification.
</P>
<P>
   The other is for Clinton and other top officials to make sure
they inquire about Zhao's health, with obvious implications. My
guess is the Chinese will be anxious to assuage any concern.
</P>
<P>
   After all, before Zhao, the party boss was a guy named Hu
Yaobang, another economic modernizer with democratic tendencies who
got bounced when Deng Xiaoping yanked the leash.
</P>
<P>
   In April of 1989, Hu died. As the news was released, some young
people gathered to pay tribute to him and to his progressive ideas
_ in a corner of Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   We all know what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
