<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET FIRMS FIXING ACHILLES' HEEL IN SOFTWARE  
 BY JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - ATTACK   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
A group of Internet companies led by Netscape Communications,
Microsoft and RSA Data Security are expected today to announce
software programs to correct a potentially dangerous flaw in their
computer products.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a pre-emptive strike, the companies are posting free
``software fixes'' on their Web sites so that corporate users of
their server-software products are immune from the so-called
Million Question Attack.
</P>
<P>
   The server products contain cracks in their design that
conceivably make them susceptible to complex attacks from crafty
hackers. A successful break-in would make encrypted, or specially
coded, software on computer systems vulnerable to theft.
</P>
<P>
   A Bell Labs researcher discovered the security threat, which the
firm immediately deemed ``theoretical'' with no evidence of
reported virus attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Cryptographer Daniel Bleichenbacher said it would be nearly
impossible to exploit the security flaw. He said a successful
hacker attack would have to send up to 1 million messages to a
targeted Web server over several days to crack a computer system.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Netscape and others say they are taking the
cyberthreat seriously. Netscape, IBM and Microsoft are slugging it
out for corporate accounts in the lucrative server-software
business, and none of them wants to lose a customer to a security
threat _ no matter how obscure.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Meredith, Netscape's senior vice president of customer
satisfaction, said the Mountain View company has notified all of
its major customers about the potential attack. She added that
Netscape's Communicator and other Web browsers are not affected by
the ``Million Question Attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith said security software patches on Netscape servers
already have been tested successfully and deployed on its Netcenter
Web site, as well as on Internet sites for customers Charles Schwab
and Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and RSA officials had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
