</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ENGLAND-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TRADITIONAL INDUSTRIES FADE, NEW ENGLAND SEEKS IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New England is hot.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is a booming industry, and President Bill Clinton and
his family are returning to Martha's Vineyard for another summer
vacation. Several recent polls indicate that Massachusetts
residents and those of the other five states feel good about
themselves (well maybe not the Rhode Islanders, who were the most
pessimistic in a recent Roper poll) and the region.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee magazine, the publication that celebrates New England,
has a circulation that has risen through the years and now rests
comfortably at 700,000, with 62 percent of that heading out of the
region.
</P>
<P>
   But for the tourists who come here, as well as for those who
live here, much of what we traditionally identify with New England
has faded. And much of what remains is preserved in boutique
industries and museum exhibits. Fishing, farming, and textiles,
lifestyles of a region that produced Herman Melville, Robert Frost
and Jack Kerouac, have all declined.
</P>
<P>
   Want to see a textile mill? Go to a museum in Lowell. If Clinton
watches the sunset at Menemsha as vacationers do on a clear evening
on the Vineyard, he will peer across a harbor once filled with
working fishing boats, but now jammed with pleasure yachts from all
along the East Coast. And many farms across the region are growing
subdivisions, or turning to niche produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are moments in history when you can tell the former
values and culture of a society are leaving you, when the amount of
nostalgia begins to build up, along with the legends and stories
about the Good Old Days,'' says American historian Thomas H.
O'Connor, the Boston College professor and author of several books
on Boston and New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I teach a course on the age of Jackson, and that was a period
in New England where old New England _ of churchyards, town greens,
cemeteries and town meetings _ was leaving and the new New England
_ of textiles, machinery and mill girls _ was coming in. It was at
that point where New England writers, Longfellow, Emerson, Thoreau
and Hawthorne created the folklore and legends of New England,
recreating the old New England at the very moment it was becoming
the new New England. And something like that is happening now _ a
longing for the '20s, '30s and '40s, when textiles, maritimes and
the port of Boston were big.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the city debates the future of its waterfront, it is
clear that whatever the future of the harbor is, most of it will be
far removed from its maritime past. At one recent conference on the
harbor, an MIT economist suggested that actors be hired to dress up
as longshoremen and fishermen for tourists to look at, as hotels
and office towers sprout up around the warfs.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Fish Pier, which was so busy 60 years ago that police
were required to direct pushcart traffic on the warf, is now
anchored by the Exchange Conference Center, a $7 million
Massachusetts Port Authority makeover of the building where fish
auctions once ruled. Now, the building is designed to showcase the
city to prospective businesses and can be leased for corporate
functions. Massachusetts products for the Millennium, such as
computers and razors, are displayed under glass cases inside.
</P>
<P>
   While the pier still smells of fish and the fish-processing
industry is doing well, 90 percent of the money it generates comes
from fish caught elsewhere _ flown in from around the world or
trucked in from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Tied up at one end of the pier is the Captain Sam. The 75-foot
fishing boat, built in 1979, is for sale. The windows of the
wheelhouse are covered with signs that notify anyone interested in
buying the boat that ``this vessel has sold its rights and permits
to fish to the US Government under the Department of Commerce's Buy
Back program.'' A potential owner can use the boat only for
``research, education, training, humanitarian, safety or law
enforcement purposes.'' Fishing is prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing will get a memorial nod at the 21st century gateway to
New England _ Logan International Airport. The airport is
undergoing a $1 billion renovation, but the new structures will
have little inside or out to let travelers know they are in New
England instead of Atlanta or Denver. One exception will be the new
parking garage. Instead of numbers or colors designating each
floor, the garage will use old New England icons. One will be the
statue of the Gloucester fisherman. (The others will be the USS
Constitution, the Boston Marathon, and the Swan Boats.) They could
have added a tractor plowing a field by a stone wall.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, Massachusetts has lost 100,000 acres of
farmland, and now only 10 percent of the land in the state is used
for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Chileans pay a buck an hour to pick apples, you can get
an apple air-freighted into Logan &UR;  &LR; (International Airport) at the
cost to grow it in New England,'' says Jay Healy, commissioner of
the Massachusetts Department of Food and Agriculture. As a result,
New England farmers are trying to add value to their produce by
turning apples into pies, milk into blue cheese, and tomatoes into
salsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wrestle with this every day,'' says Healy. ``We want to
help the agriculture businesses stay in production and not sell out
to the highest bidder for development.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmland, says Healy, is important psychologically as well as
economically. If they all disappear and ``we turn into New Jersey
we will miss the boat on things that make us unusual and make us
want to visit and live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite efforts to make farms more productive and give more
value to the food they produce, the largest cash crop in the state
is nursery products. Some of those trees and shrubs were purchased
to landscape the former farmland that is now subdivisions and
condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   New England towns that were not built along harbors, for
transport and fishing, were built around mills, for transport and
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
