<SLUG> BC-STREET26-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET SMARTS/ MARK VEVERKA 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - STREET SMARTS   AOL CHIEF STEVE CASE WON'T BE BANNED FROM TCI-AT&AMP;T PARTY c.1998 
 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
What exactly is Steve Case trying to tell us?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buried amid the mountains of coverage on the blockbuster AT&AMP;T
Corp. buyout of Tele-Communications Inc. was an intriguing response
to the deal from the America Online chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to entering into a broadband reseller
agreement with AT&AMP;T once the merger with TCI is complete,'' said
Case in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: AOL has no intention of being held hostage to
narrowband phone lines while the fatband cable guys get their acts
together. Broad bandwidth can improve the speed and performance of
online services, plus cable television offers the potential for
millions of new AOL subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tries to paint these things like they're Deathwatch
2000, where there is only one winner. But I don't think that AOL is
going to get shut out of the (cable) game,'' says financial analyst
Paul Noglows of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Case still wants to join the party. And while not invited
to this week's soiree, AOL already has been dancing with AT&AMP;T and
apparently would like to go for another whirl with the bigger,
badder AT&AMP;T/TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Why it was just last week (how time flies when suits are racking
up advisory fees) that the Financial Times in London reported that
AOL rebuffed a takeover bid by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Neither firm dignified such reports with on-the-record comments,
natch. But where there's smoke, there's often fire, and more than a
couple of analysts and money-runners think that AOL had been trying
to hammer out some sort of deal with AT&AMP;T. Albeit, it might not
have been a full-on buyout or even the purchase of a minority
stake.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, some analysts and investors speculate that AOL of
Dulles, Va., and AT&AMP;T of New York had been trying to hatch a
partnership agreement in anticipation of an AT&AMP;T-TCI merger.
</P>
<P>
   One reason AT&AMP;T may have cooled on this idea is that AT&AMP;T, while
knee-deep in talks with TCI, grew concerned about possible
antitrust challenges to its marriage with TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Why? TCI owns a 42 percent stake in At Home, an Internet portal
company that connects televisions to the Web using cable television
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the market loved the proposed AT&AMP;T/TCI deal when it
came to At Home. The stock market darling's shares soared about $12
to close around $51 on the merger news Wednesday. But sentiment has
shifted swiftly. At Home shares plunged about $3.50 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   And that price drop may be an early warning sign for At Home
shareholders. Because if they listen closely to what AOL's Case is
saying, At Home is going to have to share its pole position as the
primary gateway to Web users via cable.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the AT&AMP;T/TCI announcement, At Home was the master of
its universe. TCI boasts 10.5 million cable television subscribers
and At Home was pegged to be its cable customers' primary portal to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But that won't be the case if AOL and other content-driven
Internet services gain access to the wide, wide world of couch
potatoes with their cable boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime an Internet-based business gets into a cable-based
business, it definitely perks up the ears of the folks of At
Home,'' says Internet consultant Grady Hall of I.spy in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, AOL shareholders had reason to cheer yesterday. AOL
closed up more than $4 to around $108. While some investors may
have picked up on the pragmatic statements by Case, the shares were
also boosted by yet another Wall Street bull hanging out a ``buy''
sign on AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analyst Dawn Simon of Brown Brothers Harriman in New
York initiated coverage on AOL yesterday, forecasting that the
stock could rise as high as $123 a share over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Simon says that she didn't base her optimistic assessment on
AOL's future partners, but on the strength of the company's many
diversified revenue streams, ranging from subscription fees to
advertising to e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider all of the (price run-up based on) merger and
takeover speculation as gravy,'' Simon says.
</P>
<P>
   If so, AOL's Case may be telling shareholders to get a hold of
one whale of a gravy boat before it's all over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at The Chronicle, 901 Mission
St., San Francisco 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail
at mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
