<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTES EXPECTED AT BELFAST ASSEMBLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ When the new Northern Ireland Assembly holds its
inaugural meeting on Wednesday in the same room where the agreement
that created it was reached, the fights will begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
   There will be arguments over where the Assembly should sit
permanently, over whether the selection of Cabinet ministers should
be held now or put off until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But in a place where disputes are traditionally settled by
violence, the prospect of people attacking each other armed only
with their words and their mandates is considered remarkable
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, after all the votes were counted _ and under the
complicated proportional representation system it took two days _
the prospects for the Assembly appeared good, despite what is
expected to be a raucous beginning.
</P>
<P>
   About three-quarters of the 108 members of the Assembly
supported the Good Friday agreement, but it is the presence of
about 30 others who vehemently oppose it that will make Northern
Ireland's experiment with democracy a contentious affair.
</P>
<P>
   Things were looking much better for the Ulster Unionist leader
David Trimble, who fended off a mutiny as he led a badly divided
Protestant community to the Assembly. Trimble's party ended up with
the most seats, at 28, which virtually ensures his election
Wednesday as the first minister of the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trimble has passed all the big tests,'' said Finnoula
O'Connor, a political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democratic and Labor Party, which represents moderate
Catholics, took 24 seats and became the first nationalist party to
win the most votes in a Northern Ireland election, capturing 22
percent of the first-preference votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Unionists, led by Trimble's nemesis, the Rev. Ian
Paisley, made a strong showing with 20 seats, and will lead the
opposition within the new Assembly. But other dissident unionists
did not capture enough seats to obstruct the workings of the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Elliott, a political scientist at Queen's University,
said the election results showed that more unionists voted for
candidates opposed to the agreement, but that the overall vote for
pro-agreement candidates rose from 71 percent in last month's
referendum to about 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout in the referendum was a record 81 percent, but only 69
percent on Thursday, when the election was held. Turnout among
Catholic nationalists, however, did not drop, something analysts
attribute to nationalist confidence and unionist angst. While
unionists are divided over the Assembly and the agreement,
nationalists see both as favorable to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein, the party that is close to the Irish Republican Army,
improved its vote for the third consecutive election, taking 18
seats, one more than it expected. Sinn Fein's electoral success is
crucial to reassuring the IRA that it was wise to let politics take
precedence in their campaign for a united Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists will use their new bully pulpit in the Assembly to
demand that the IRA say the war is over and begin turning in some
of its weapons, a subject that will be raised regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The middle-of-the-road Alliance Party, which attracts voters
from across the sectarian divide, took six seats. Alliance members
could emerge as the swing votes in an Assembly that is likely to be
frequently divided along lines of religion and national identity.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Coalition, which has only been in existence for two
years, took two seats, including one for the party leader, Monica
McWilliams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good day for democracy,'' said McWilliams, whose party
was credited with bringing a good deal of civility and common sense
to the negotiations that led to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes Saturday suggested new possibilities in politics. When
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams learned that Billy Hutchinson, a
convicted loyalist killer, had won a second seat for the
Progressive Unionist Party, he burst out, ``Well done, Billy!'' at
the City Hall counting center.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and other republicans were at war with loyalists like
Hutchinson for nearly 30 years, but now Sinn Fein and the
Progressive Unionists are among those most anxious for the Assembly
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Kelly, a former IRA bomber, won a Sinn Fein seat in the
same North Belfast constituency as Hutchinson. Kelly said that
while the two would never agree on the question of whether Northern
Ireland should remain part of Britain or be united with the Irish
Republic, they share common views on economic and social policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly is likely to make strange political bedfellows. One
who won't be getting into bed with anyone, however, is Paisley. He
has vowed to prevent the creation of cross-border authorities that
will oversee areas of mutual interest on the island, such as
agriculture and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   But those authorities are a crucial element in the Good Friday
accord, which says that the Assembly will be suspended if there is
not agreement by Oct. 31 on establishing the cross-border bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Paisley says they are part of an eventual slide into a united
Ireland. Mainstream unionists don't like them, but are prepared to
put up with them in exchange for the Assembly and nationalists
accepting that Northern Ireland will remain part of the United
Kingdom until a majority living there want otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another sign of the changed times, Adams and other
leading republicans said they regretted that Gary McMichael, leader
of the Ulster Democratic Party, did not win a seat in the Assembly.
McMichael's party is the political wing of the Ulster Defense
Association, a loyalist paramilitary group that has killed hundreds
of Catholics, including Sinn Fein officials.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the IRA killed McMichael's father, John, who
wanted to take the Defense Association into the political arena.
Now, former killers from both sides of the divide here are heading
into a new political arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
