<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO, EVERYBODY DOESN'T KNOW THAT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that,'' I heard the woman say when the train
pulled to a stop. Her tone was dismissive. Her manner distracted.
She went back to her magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting next to her was a girl of about 7 or 8 whose face seemed
to reflect a variety of emotions. Disappointment. Anger.
Bewilderment. Or maybe I was projecting my own feelings onto the
child.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what she'd said to the woman, who may have been her
mother, but it didn't deserve that response.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to cross the aisle and tell the girl I had no idea what
she'd said, but that whatever it was, I was sure that everybody
doesn't know it, and that even if they do, it doesn't matter. All
that matters is that she knows it, and that she wants to share it
with someone else. That's what's important. She shouldn't let the
woman's careless remark hurt her.
</P>
<P>
   Of course I didn't speak to the child for fear she and the woman
would think I was a nut. And maybe I am, because I get nutty when I
hear somebody say that, especially when they say it to a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody goes through that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels the same way when they're your age.''
</P>
<P>
   I've heard these and similar things said so many times, and so,
I imagine, have you. I've probably said them myself, although I try
very hard not to. Usually these phrases are just blather, the kind
of thing people say without thinking. Have a nice day. Be good.
How's it going?
</P>
<P>
   But these thoughtless remarks can hurt. Because when somebody
says, ``Everybody thinks that,'' what they're really saying is, ``I
can't be bothered to listen to you,'' or ``You don't know
anything,'' or ``You're no different than anybody else. Your
thoughts, your feelings, your experiences aren't unique. I don't
want to hear about them. So shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   I hear those words and I'm back in the eighth grade, in English
class, and the teacher has acknowledged my raised hand and I am
standing up, because in those days, in that school, you always
stood up to speak. I don't remember what I said, nothing very
brilliant I'm sure. But I remember what she said, ``Everybody knows
that.''
</P>
<P>
   I sat down. I sat down for the rest of the year. I never raised
my hand again. I never volunteered to speak. I waited until I was
called upon. At a parent-teacher conference the same teacher told
my mother, ``I'm afraid your daughter isn't college material.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother was devastated. And furious. At me. At the teacher. At
the school. At life, because her kid had suddenly turned into a
knucklehead. I was fascinated by the phrase ``college material,''
which unfortunately for me became part of our daily vocabulary at
home. I imagined some sort of fine, silky fabric from which
intelligent people were cut, while the rest of us were made of
burlap.
</P>
<P>
   The next year I was lucky, and drew a wonderful English teacher.
Things improved. But I never forgot that eighth grade teacher. And
I never forgot what she said to me. ``Everybody knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought of her again the other day, when I saw one of those
billboards advertising Macintosh computers, a big picture of Jim
Henson, with Kermit the Frog, and the words, ``Think different.''
My eighth grade teacher wouldn't have gotten the point. She would
have corrected the grammar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
