<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T UNDERESTIMATE `RIDICULOUS' 401(K) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We would like to retire in 10 to 12 years. I have absolutely
no money saved. My company offers a ridiculous 401(k), matching no
portion of contributions. My husband contributes approximately $400
to $500 a week to a company stock savings plan and 401(k). We are
37 and 41 years old and have little or no knowledge of investing.
Where should we start?
</P>
<P>
   M.C., San Diego &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I suggest you start by rethinking your company's
``ridiculous'' 401(k) program. A 401(k) has considerable value even
if the company doesn't match contributions or offer any other
incentives. One virtue is that it makes it very easy for people who
are not in the saving habit to save _ once you sign up, the funds
are automatically deducted from your paycheck and are accordingly
sheltered from the myriad attractive nuisances that American
marketers dream up. A more substantial advantage of a 401(k) is
that it provides deferral of taxes on both the money contributed
and the earnings it generates. The thinking is that in retirement
most people will be in a lower tax bracket than they are during
their earning years, and accordingly they will save by paying the
taxes later at a lower rate.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem for you is that funds in a 401(k) are difficult
or expensive to get at before age 59 1/2. If you simply withdraw
money before that age, you face a 10 percent premature withdrawal
penalty, as well as the tax. (It is also possible to withdraw funds
before that age through a sequence of equal payments designed to
last through your life expectancy, but once you embark on such a
plan you are locked into it until age 59 1/2, and accordingly you
lose a lot of flexibility in your financial planning.)
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion for a person in your situation is to use the
401(k), but not for all your savings. You might decide to put half
of your retirement savings in the 401(k) and keep the remainder,
which you will mentally earmark for those years before you reach
age 59 1/2, in a taxable mutual fund account. Most of the major
fund families _ Fidelity, T. Rowe Price, and so forth _ offer
excellent information packets describing mutual funds in general,
how to select funds to meet your objective, and their offerings in
particular. If you simply get 800 numbers for the funds from
information, they will be happy to fill your mailbox to overflowing
with their literature. If you want to get a more fundamental primer
on investing, the investment equivalent to Doctor Spock's baby book
is How To Buy Stocks, by Louis Engel and Brendan Boyd, continuously
in print for 55 years and currently available in mass market
paperback.
</P>
<P>
   To a certain extent your fund choices will probably be dictated
by the menu of investments available through your 401(k) plan. For
example, if your plan offers a solid growth and income offering
such as a fund tracking the Standard and Poor's 500 Index, you
might select that as your core position, diversifying the 401(k)
program by adding a balanced fund and maybe, since your anticipated
time frame isn't all that long, even a small position in a bond
fund. But many 401(k) menus have limited offerings among small-cap
or sector funds, and you can accordingly hone in on those with your
taxable positions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My daughter will start college this fall at a private school
that costs $15,000 in addition to a scholarship she received. Among
our assets is $42,000 in mutual funds and stocks in custodial
accounts for her. She has been offered a 2 percent loan that would
cover her entire education with no principal payment for 10 years.
I believe the money is better left in those accounts, to be used
for eventual repayment of the loans. What do you think of that
idea?
</P>
<P>
   M.M., Beaumont, Texas
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds like a great idea to me _ so great, in fact, that
it seems likely there's something wrong with it. On most
application for financial aid for college, parents and students are
required to list their income and assets separately. This is
because they are treated very differently. In the basic formula,
students are expected to commit 50 percent of their income and 35
percent of their assets to educational costs; parents are expected
to be willing to commit 47 percent of their income, but only 5.65
percent of their assets. Now even though you or your wife are
custodians of that $42,000, it belongs to your daughter, and it
should be listed as her asset.
</P>
<P>
   Under the typical formula for student aid, the assumption would
then be that she should be willing to spend $14,700 of it for her
first year of college, and thus be eligible for only $300 in loans
for the first year. In later years, her presumed contribution would
decrease as her assets are consumed, and loan eligibility would
increase accordingly. Following the numbers through (and assuming a
6 percent return from her investments), after four full years she
would have spent all but $9,218 of that $42,000, and have borrowed
a total of $23,387.
</P>
<P>
   My suspicion is that the custodial accounts were listed on the
wrong place, and that was why your daughter was offered this very
attractive loan program. If I'm wrong, of course you're right _
it's a terrific deal, and your daughter would not only be able to
pay the interest during the first ten years and then repay the
principal, but also would have about $30,000 left over. But
remember the old investment rule _ if it sounds too good to be
true, it likely is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 26 and work for a mutual fund company. I have a balance
of $10,500 in my 401(k) plan, of which 30 percent is in company
stock, 30 percent in Evergreen fund, 25 percent in a Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fund, and 15 percent in Evergreen Balanced fund.
My company matches 100 percent of the first 6 percent of salary I
contribute, and I add a further 3 percent. Two additional options
have recently been added to your 401(k) menu _ Evergreen
International Growth and Mentor Growth. I plan to retire around age
65, and want to know what allocation would work best to maximize
returns. I do not wish to reallocate the existing money, but would
rather like to change the selection of funds for new money. How
would you position this portfolio among these six options?
</P>
<P>
   A.D., Boston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a little difficult, because a balanced fund has no
place in a portfolio that has 39 years to grow. If you insist on
keeping Evergreen Balanced _ which is a solid enough fund _ I
suggest you stop contributing to that account for ... oh, make it
about 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But I would much rather see you move out entirely, into a more
growth-oriented portfolio. Allocation might run along these lines:
30 percent company stock, 25 percent in the index offering, and 15
percent each in the mid-cap growth fund (Evergreen fund), the
international offering (Evergreen International Growth), and the
small-cap growth fund (Mentor).
</P>
<P>
   If you are unwilling to make any transfers, you'll have to
juggle your allocations of new money to reach those levels. Thus,
you might begin by dividing all new money to Evergreen
International Growth and Mentor funds until each account is 15
percent of the total portfolio, and then dividing contributions
evenly among company stock, the index fund, the international fund,
and the small-cap fund.
</P>
<P>
   Continue this until you have brought the Evergreen position down
to 25 percent. At that point, you can allocate money among the
various funds according to the target positions, rebalancing
annually. As for the balanced fund position, I would leave it out
of the calculations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
