<HEADLINE>
IN ALABAMA RUNOFF, A FERVOR OVER RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ As Governor Fob James and his challenger,
Winton Blount, tumble toward Tuesday's runoff election, they sound
as though they are running for deacon rather than Alabama's
Republican gubernatorial nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In their final debate Thursday night, James mused about America
as ``a Christian nation'' while Blount, embracing the principle of
forgiveness, assured a statewide television audience that he still
considered the governor ``a good Christian'' even though he had
earlier accused James of lying and cheating in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they are not talking about race,'' said Bradley
Moody, a professor of political science at Auburn University in
Montgomery, referring to the theme that has poisoned state politics
since the days when George C. Wallace ruled Alabama 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   James has been mixing church and state since he threatened to
call out the National Guard last year to defend a county judge's
display of the Ten Commandments on a wooden tablet in his
courtroom. He then defied a federal judge by arguing that the Bill
of Rights did not apply to an Alabama law authorizing voluntary
prayer in schools. James likes to say that ``God has been
blackballed'' by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Blount is running radio spots quoting the
Bible and declaring that only ministers have a higher calling than
public servants. If elected, Blount promises to serve with
``reverence'' and ``devotion.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a bizarre campaign, rooted in an incident several years
ago when James displayed his contempt for the theory of evolution
by emulating an ape, waddling across a meeting room of the Alabama
Board of Education. When Blount recalled James's performance this
month and criticized the governor for ``dancing around like a
monkey,'' James retorted: ``Well, I'm a monkey that's in good
shape. I'm not a fat monkey.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's wife, Bobbie James, who is said to have banished
portraits of Robert E. Lee and former first ladies from the
governor's mansion because she felt they were possessed by demons,
joined the fray by calling Blount ``a big, fat sissy.'' She later
apologized.
</P>
<P>
   A star running back for Auburn in the 1950s, the 63-year-old
James has grown rumpled and overweight since he made a fortune
manufacturing plastic barbells and went into politics. Blount, 54,
is a Montgomery businessman whose prosperity rivals his girth. His
father, one of Alabama's earliest Republicans, served as postmaster
general in the Nixon administration.
</P>
<P>
   Their contest is nip-and-tuck. In the first primary on June 2,
James won 48 percent of the vote while Blount, who ran
unsuccessfully for governor four years ago, took 41 percent. Three
other Republican also-rans, whose total vote denied James a
majority, endorsed Blount following the first primary.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of Tuesday's runoff will face Lieutenant Governor Don
Siegelman, a Democrat, in the general election in November.
</P>
<P>
   But in a bid to knock off the conservative incumbent on Tuesday,
Richard Arrington, the black mayor of Birmingham, has promised to
deliver thousands of black votes for Blount in the Republican
showdown. Crossover voting is permitted in Alabama, which has no
formal party registration.
</P>
<P>
   Giles Perkins, executive director of the state Democratic Party,
said the party is discouraging Democrats from taking part in the
GOP race, and political analysts predict that few blacks will
actually take a Republican ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Moody describes Tuesday's election as a battle between the
governor, a champion of the white working class, and a challenger
who represents the interests of the ``chamber of commerce, country
club Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   In his campaign, Blount has charged that Alabama lags behind
other Southeastern states because of James's lack of vision and
personal eccentricities. He has also said that a landfill owned by
James's family has reaped unseemly profits from state business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people might agree that James is crazy and does
unconventional things,'' said Moody, ``but they don't think he's
dishonest.''
</P>
<P>
   However, James's opponents say the governor is hypocritical.
When James recently signed a bill requiring silent meditation by
schoolchildren, he was heard muttering curses over an open
television microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial writers in Alabama are scornful of the governor. The
Birmingham News pronounced James an ``embarrassment.'' A columnist
for the Montgomery Advertiser, Bob Ingram, wrote that James's ``fat
monkey'' remark ``was another example of Fob putting his foot in
his mouth, which he has done so often his face may soon have
stretch marks.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandt Ayers, editor and publisher of the Anniston Star, said
James has failed to maximize the state's potential during a period
when other states in the region are thriving economically. ``He's
involved in all these crazy crusades,'' Ayers said. ``He's devoted
so much energy to defend the Ten Commandements you'd think somebody
was out to repeal them.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell Raines, an Alabama native and editor of The New York
Times editorial page, said this month that James is the latest in a
long line of embarrassing Alabama governors, running from Kissin'
Jim Folsom's public drunkenness to Wallace's tolerance of ``racial
violence and a culture of endemic corruption in Montgomery'' to the
``hayseed machinations'' of Guy Hunt, who was drummed out of office
following a conviction for state ethics violations in 1993.
Alabama's lack of progress, Raines wrote, ``can be linked directly
to its penchant for electing buffoons.''
</P>
<P>
   In the face of criticism, James used a state plane this past
week to fly to Dallas to address several hundred followers of the
Christ for the Nations Institute, an evangelical mission. He told
the crowd he would join an organized resistance to the federal
government if marshals are sent to DeKalb County, Alabama, to
enforce a court order against practicing religion in public
schools. ``The people in DeKalb County are brave people, and they
will resist, and I will support them,'' James vowed.
</P>
<P>
   During their debate the next night in Birmingham, Blount said
James had exploited the issue of religious freedom and ``terribly
confused the people of this state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
