u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TANGLEWOOD-BOS &LR;      06-29 1592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TANGLEWOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLE RETURNS TO TANGLEWOOD IN A SIGNATURE ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vinson Cole was a promising young American singer when he made
his Tanglewood debut as Jacquino in Beethoven's ``Fidelio'' in
1982. This week the tenor returns to Tanglewood to open the season
in one of the signature roles of his distinguished career, Faust in
Berlioz's ``La Damnation de Faust.'' It's a part he has sung more
than 70 times and to the satisfaction of some of the world's most
eminent conductors, including Seiji Ozawa, with whom he has taken
the role part in performances with the Berlin Philharmonic and the
New Japan Philharmonic. Friday night's performance will be Cole's
first with the Boston Symphony Orchestra; he will be singing
opposite the celebrated Marguerite of Frederica von Stade.
</P>
<P>
   Cole also is probably the ranking African-American male opera
singer. Since Leontyne Price, many African-American women have been
prominent presences on the world operatic stage, but men have had a
harder time of it. George Shirley was Cole's only predecessor in
leading tenor roles in major international contexts. At 47 and at
the peak of his career, Cole is in a comparably lonely position
today, with no successor in sight. ``Race seems to be less of an
issue in Europe,'' Cole says. ``I've had a larger operatic career
in Europe than in the United States, but what that's due to, I
really can't say. I basically go where I am wanted _ why would I go
someplace where I wasn't wanted?''
</P>
<P>
   For a singer of his stature, Cole has appeared infrequently at
the Metropolitan Opera. Whatever the reasons for that, it's not
because the Met has a roster full of tenors who sing better than
Cole. This is not a subject Cole wants to get into, although he
says he enjoyed singing some outdoor performances of ``Carmen''
with the Met in the parks recently, and a tour of ``La Damnation de
Faust'' with the Met orchestra under the direction of James Levine.
</P>
<P>
   Cole grew up in Kansas City, Mo., and he's been singing most of
his life. ``I sang in church choirs ever since I can remember, and
when I was 9, a woman heard me and took me to her voice teacher at
the Kansas City Conservatory. I started taking lessons, and at 10 I
sang in my first opera _ I was Amahl in `Amahl and the Night
Visitors.''' Before long, Cole was singing for every organization
in Kansas City, including the Lyric Opera, where he sang in ``La
Boheme,'' ``Tosca,'' and ``Rigoletto.''
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Cole's voice changed. ``It was a late drop, and it
happened overnight. My first voice teacher always said, `When your
voice changes, do not stop singing, but continue to work,' so
that's what I did. It was his belief that many tenors became
baritones because they stopped singing when their voices changed
and waited for them to settle. But if you're using the voice, the
possibility of singing as a tenor is there. I have reason to thank
him for that advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole attended the University of Missouri and then went on to
Philadelphia. At the Philadelphia Music Academy he worked with the
great Met star of the 1940s, Licia Albanese (``a lovely lady'');
the next year, at the Curtis Institute of Music, he began working
with another Met veteran, Margaret Harshaw, with whom Cole studied
right up until her death at age 88 earlier this year. ``We were
extremely close. The day before she died, she said to her son,
`Tell Vinson when he goes down to the low voice ...' I said to him,
`She's going to go to her grave working on my voice,' and that's
exactly what she did. She spoke her mind totally, but that's what
you want from a teacher. I can't tell you how grateful I am to
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole spent two summers as an apprentice in Santa Fe, and made
his official operatic debut in the title role of Mascagni's
``L'Amico Fritz'' in the spring season of the San Francisco Opera
in 1976, appearing opposite Leona Mitchell. Cole was still a
student at Curtis at the time. The next year he won the national
auditions of the Metropolian Opera. Shirley Verrett was one of the
judges; she fumed at some colleagues who felt that Cole wasn't
singing loudly enough. ``Are we talking loud,'' Verrett said
pointedly, ``or are we talking good?''
</P>
<P>
   Cole's career was launched. He made his Boston debut singing the
Steersman in Sarah Caldwell's Opera Company of Boston production of
``The Flying Dutchman,'' and soon he found himself a regular guest
of major American orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   An underremarked aspect of Seiji Ozawa's music directorship of
the Boston Symphony Orchestra is his belief in young American
artists like Cole and his loyalty to them over the years; those
artists in turn have been remarkably loyal to him. Cole has been a
regular guest of the Boston Symphony, memorably participating in
the orchestra's Berlioz festival and tour in 1993 and in the
tribute to his great predecessor Roland Hayes in 1996. (Hayes was
the first African-American soloist to be engaged by a major
American orchestra.) ``It is always a joy to work with Seiji, which
I have done at La Scala, in Berlin, and in Japan, as well as in
Boston,'' Cole says. ``Like Herbert von Karajan, he is a wonderful
accompanist because he is a wonderful listener _ you feel you are
being carried through the piece on a pillow, so you can really
enjoy the experience. That's rare as far as conductors go. I also
love singing with the Boston Symphony; it is such a wonderful sound
it makes. I've been listening to a broadcast recording from 1955
when my teacher, Margaret Harshaw, sang Wagner's `Immolation Scene'
from `Die Gotterdammerung' with the orchestra under the direction
of Charles Munch; all the facets of the music are there, and it's
really fantastic. To sing with this orchestra means something
special to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most colleagues in the musical world, Cole adores Von
Stade. ``She's one of the nicest people in the entire world, and
she brings such a wonderful, vibrant life to whatever she does. I
recently heard her in a recital for the first time _ it was in
Munich and I was bowled over. From song to song she could change
moods in a matter of seconds; the changes were utterly natural _
there was nothing phony or showy about them. She gives of herself
and she's honest; when she sings with you, you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Karajan was one of Cole's major mentors. ``The patronage of
Karajan had two edges: People adored him and immediately accepted
you because Karajan had. But there were people who didn't like him,
and if you sang with him, they wanted nothing to do with you.
Nevertheless, I would not give up one second of the experience of
working with him _ these were the greatest musical experiences of
my life. It wasn't anything he actually said or told me; it was
what took place in performance and rehearsal. It was
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   With Karajan, Cole sang the Italian Singer in ``Der
Rosenkavalier,'' Beethoven's ``Missa Solemnis'' and Ninth Symphony,
the Mozart and Verdi Requiems, and the Bruckner Te Deum. ``There
were other things too that were scheduled, but he died. Florestan
in Beethoven's `Fidelio' would have been the next thing; he wanted
to get back to the old Viennese tradition of a lyric tenor like
Julius Patzak or Anton Dermota in this part, which comes out of
Gluck, Mozart, and Haydn rather than leading directly to Wagner.
Then we were going to do Stravinsky's `Oedipus Rex' and Mahler's
`Das Lied von der Erde.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Cole's projects with Ka-rajan were recorded, and he also
has made recordings with Vladimir Ashkenazy (Mendelssohn's
``Lobgesang''), Giuseppe Sinopli (Liszt's ``Faust'' Symphony),
Carlo Maria Giulini (Verdi Requiem), and Bernard Haitink (Bruckner
Te Deum). Next season he will record Berlioz's ``L'Enfance du
Christ'' in Leipzig. There are also some recordings Cole is not on.
</P>
<P>
   Cole makes his home in Seattle. ``I'd been in New York and
Florida a long time, but I really wanted to go somewhere where I
could have a different quality of life. I enjoy it in Seattle _ you
can go from the mountains to the water within 35 minutes, and the
fish is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Another attraction is a remarkable 10-year association with the
Seattle Opera, where Cole has sung 11 roles, including Gluck's
``Orfeo'' in a production directed by Mark Morris, Romeo, Werther,
Rodolfo, Pinkerton, Nadir, Don Jose, Ferrando, Nemorino, and Percy
in ``Anna Bolena.'' ``Over the years I've sung everything from
Monteverdi to Stravinsky, with everything in between; I feel
particularly comfortable in French roles. There isn't much I could
sing that I haven't yet, although I'm excited that I'm going to
sing Cavaradossi in `Tosca' again _ I haven't done that since I was
20 and still in college. I would also love to sing Lohengrin, in
the right theater and under the right circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of a possible glass ceiling to his career is clearly
not one Cole enjoys discussing, but he does speak forthrightly
about prejudice. ``What just happened in Jasper, Texas, proves that
prejudice does still exist. These things have existed and will
exist. People are not born with prejudice, but they are taught it,
and as long as people continue to teach it, to expose little
children to it, it will continue. My job is to do what I know how
to do. If I run into problems, I try to work around them. What I
try to do is try to overcome what's there, do my job, and keep
striving to do my best, to be the best I can be. That's the only
advice I can offer anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
