<HEADLINE>
DECIPHERING THE CRUELTY OF ARGENTINA'S REIGN OF TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A LEXICON OF TERROR 
Argentina and the Legacies of Torture 
By Marguerite Feitlowitz 
Oxford University Press, 302 pp., illustrated, $30 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Argentine president Carlos Menem has been described as a
``post-modern president,'' one who ``does not feel bound by words,
especially not his own words.''
</P>
<P>
   The description has come from analysts trying to reconcile
Menem's past promises with his policies, as he has shifted away
from populism during his nine-year presidency. But the assessment
cuts much deeper, to the core of his nation's powerful relationship
with language, which dates as far back as the Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite Feitlowitz sheds new light on this relationship in
``A Lexicon of Terror,'' a chronicle of the so-called Dirty War of
the late 1970s, in which as many as 30,000 suspected leftists were
secretly ``disappeared'' by the military, many of them raped and
executed. The book is a painstaking study of the terror, a
dissection of the regime's sinister manipulation of language and
rhetoric. But it is hardly a dry or academic study.
</P>
<P>
   Through the horrifying narratives of dozens of kidnapped
survivors and their families, Feitlowitz, who teaches writing and
translation at Harvard, builds a compelling argument that the
military regime irrevocably altered the Argentine vocabulary and,
in turn, its psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Each chapter introduces prison camp survivors tortured by warped
usage of ordinary words: ``parilla,'' the traditional Argentine
meat grill, came to mean the metal table where victims were laid
out for torture; ``fish food'' was slang for corpses thrown from
military planes into the sea. Juxtaposed are the chilling official
speeches denying that there was any torture at all. Reprinted in
the book, along with clippings from newspapers that accepted the
double talk at face value, the speeches expose a tradition of an
officialdom ``not bound by words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It made you psychotic,'' says one Argentine mother who, like
hundreds, kept vigil for her lost child in the central government
square. ``We could barely `read' let alone `translate' the world
around us. And that was exactly what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The regime rose to power in 1976, after the ousting of Isabel
Peron, whose two-year presidency following her husband's death left
Argentina in a state of mayhem. To restore order, the new military
leadership laid strict ground rules, demanding the eradication of
anyone considered ``a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   The broad interpretation of danger led to the November 1977
kidnapping of physicist Mario Villani, to whom Feitlowitz devotes
nearly 20 pages. ``Disappeared'' as he drove through downtown
Buenos Aires, Villani was spirited away to a secret torture prison
named ``the Athletic Club.'' He remained imprisoned for the next
four years.
</P>
<P>
   During more than six hours of interviews, Villani recalled the
unimaginable physical torture of lying blindfolded on the
``parilla'' while guards seared his skin with a 220-volt electric
prod. But it is the dialogue inside the prison that makes up the
bulk of his account.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnap victims were constantly told they ``did not exist.'' When
they were scheduled for torture, or ``physical therapy,'' they were
brought to an ``operating theater.'' A prisoner on his way to die
was told he was ``being given his ticket,'' a cruel phrase that
over time became used as a commonplace threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after they disappeared me, I didn't understand a lot of
what was said to me,'' Villani said. ``And then when I got out,
people didn't understand what I said to them. I realized I was
still thinking _ and talking _ in camp terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Such interviews _ and there are dozens in the book _ are the
result of the many years the author spent in Argentina, both as a
Fulbright research scholar in 1990 and with a Mary Bunting
Fellowship in 1992-93. Almost all the interviews are recounted in
the present tense; Feitlowitz is careful to frame each survivor in
the world of the living, a forceful reminder of the legacy that
remains in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Politics is treated similarly; the last quarter of the book is
devoted to the ``Scilingo Effect,'' the national reawakening that
began in March 1995, when retired Navy Captain Adolfo Scilingo
publicly confessed to his role in dumping ``fish food'' into the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   The book ends in 1997, with Menem's refusal to address new
revelations about the terror on the very last page. With that,
Feitlowitz underscores her point. ``The past is a predator,''
Feitlowitz says, quoting the Argentine adage. And it is one that
still requires a ``popular volition to meet the danger at its
source.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1330EDT &QL; 
