<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-AFT-BEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN FILM INSTITUTE'S TOP 100 LOSES SIGHT OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Top 100 list)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even more fun than looking at a list is second-guessing it.
That's what was fun about the American Film Institute's
much-bruited list of what it deemed America's 100 greatest movies.
First, however, full disclosure: This writer was one of the voters,
although not one of those who put together the list of 400 films
from which the 100 came. Further, this writer is affiliated with
the National Film Preservation Board, which helps nominate each
year's batch of 25 films added to the National Film Registry of the
Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   My own list, drawn up for a forthcoming anthology, remains in
constant flux. This film is dropped, that film is added, others are
reassessed. Although the AFI list contains great films, it's tilted
as much to popularity as merit, with too many great older films
crowded out by contemporary films of debatable quality. At the risk
of seeming a bad loser, griping about personal favorites that
didn't make the final cut, it seems obvious that the voting was
dominated by pleasurable recollection of films seen within the
voter's lifetime, not from any real sense of film history.
Otherwise, how does one explain the omission of the great silent
films that gave film its language and grammar?
</P>
<P>
   Only four silents were named. D.W. Griffith was represented by
``Birth of a Nation.'' It can be argued that ``Intolerance'' is
greater. What &UR;  &LR; of Erich von Stroheim's ``Greed''? Victor Seastrom's
``The Wind''? Chaplin, of course, deserves a place on any list. But
three Chaplin films _ ``The Gold Rush,'' ``City Lights,'' and
``Modern Times'' _ were named, while none by Buster Keaton was.
``The General'' was the only Keaton feature on the ballot. But it's
a big one that shouldn't have been overlooked. The silent
``Ben-Hur,'' with its assimilationist subtext conveying in veiled
fashion the story of Hollywood's moguls, is miles better than the
later and barely watchable Oscar-winning version that made the cut.
``The Big Parade'' and ``The Crowd'' stand up handsomely today,
too. So does ``Wings,'' the first Oscar winner, still remarkable
for its aviation sequences.
</P>
<P>
   The omissions are just as puzzling when sound enters the
picture. ``Footlight Parade,'' the best black-and-white musical
ever, didn't even make the preliminary list. ``42nd Street,'' the
Busby Berkeley musical that did show up on the ballot, was denied a
place on the final 100. Similarly, it's ridiculaous that the list
should contain no Fred Astaire-Ginger Rogers musical, even though
``Top Hat'' was an option. What about gangster icon Jimmy Cagney?
He just made the cut, coming in at No. 100 with ``Yankee Doodle
Dandy.'' Cagney began as a dancer and was a good one, but how can a
list of American classics omit the man who made the gangster movie
what it was, from the jolting ``Public Enemy'' to my favorite, the
even wilder and surprisingly tender ``White Heat''?
</P>
<P>
   The director of ``White Heat,'' Raoul Walsh, was denied entry,
too, even though his career practically spanned the history of
movies, of which he directed a couple of hundred, including ``The
Big Trail,'' ``High Sierra,'' ``They Drive by Night,'' and ``The
Man I Love.'' William Wellman, whose career includes ``Wings'' and
``Public Enemy'' and extended to ``A Star Is Born,'' ``Nothing
Sacred,'' ``Beau Geste,'' and ``The Ox-Bow Incident,'' also was
passed over. Still, directors of Westerns and action films fared
better, predictably, than directors of comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Hawks, who moved easily between genres, barely made the
list with his screwball comedy ``Bringing Up Baby,'' which came in
97th. But Hawks's ``His Girl Friday,'' the best newspaper comedy of
them all, is nowhere to be found (nor is Hawks's classic Western,
``Red River''). Moreover, there isn't a single film by Preston
Sturges, who perfected comic anarchy on film, or Ernst Lubitsch,
whose so-called Lubitsch touch set the standard for sophisticated
comic battles between the sexes, but was ignored by voters. W.C.
Fields came up empty-handed, too. Subgenres fared even worse.
Independent films were non-starters. Sci-fi barely caused a blip on
the screen after ``Star Wars.'' Not even ``Blade Runner'' made it.
Except for the great ``Double Indemnity,'' film noir was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   When you consider what was left off the list, you wonder at some
of the titles that were given a shot. If ``Blade Runner,'' ``Top
Hat,'' ``The Magnificent Ambersons,'' ``Atlantic City,'' ``The Bank
Dick,'' ``The Awful Truth,'' ``The Lady Eve,'' and ``Trouble in
Paradise'' were shut out, so, at least, were ``Pretty Woman,''
``Beverly Hills Cop,'' ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off,'' and ``The
Fugitive.'' But what were the last four doing on a list of 400
greatest American films in the first place? Maybe what they were
doing was sending a message that all films were winners. Someday,
``Beverly Hills Cop'' will need to be preserved or transferred to
new stock, and why not?
</P>
<P>
   The late Andre Langlois, founder of the Cinema-theque in Paris,
a man who stored cans of film in his bathtub until they could be
housed safely elsewhere, said he felt he had no right to discard
any film, that all should be saved and that posterity should be
given the same chance to judge them that we were. It's an argument
I wouldn't dream of trying to refute. If the AFI list, and the
Library of Congress selections later this year, lead to an
increased awareness of older films, that many more will be saved _
and rediscovered and enjoyed. And that many more lists will be
possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
