<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO AIRPORT OFFICIALS FACE DEBATE OVER RUNWAY EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Five years ago, as San Francisco leaders planned
one of the biggest airport makeovers in local history, they made a
promise to environmental regulators: no new runways until well
beyond 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the steel and concrete outlines of $2.4 billion in new
terminal buildings begin to rise above the airport construction
zone, the mantra has changed.
</P>
<P>
   With the airport's on-time service among the worst in the nation
and weather causing thousands of flight delays and cancellations,
officials say the airport desperately needs to expand its runways
just to handle the traffic it has today.
</P>
<P>
   As airport officials try to come up with a publicly acceptable
plan to extend runways into the San Francisco Bay, some passengers
are demanding to know why airport directors launched an expansion
without being able to accommodate more planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have this gorgeous, multibillion-dollar airport
that is one of the worst in the nation for delays,'' said San
Francisco lawyer James Woods, adding that his flights have been
delayed so often that he now takes pains to avoid using San
Francisco International Airport. ``Somebody's not thinking here.''
</P>
<P>
   But current and former airport planners say public demands have
changed. Nearly a decade ago, when city leaders discussed
modernizing the airport's 1930s-era runway system to reduce noise
and prepare for the future, they say the environmental opposition
to filling the Bay was so fierce the idea died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been one to tie my hands behind my back, go out
into the political ring and let myself be hammered to bits,'' said
former Airports Director Lou Turpen, who commissioned a 1990 study
of how the airport's runways could be improved. Turpen said he
dropped the idea when it became clear that environmental opposition
might kill chances of any airport makeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a political football,'' said Turpen, who left San
Francisco in 1995 to become the director of Toronto's airport. ``It
wasn't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead airport planners focused on building a new international
terminal to address the predicted boom in world travel _ a trend
expected to bring more passengers in larger airplanes, but not
necessarily an increase in the number of flights coming to the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   The number of passengers using the airport is expected to jump
67 percent between 1990 and 2006 _ to a total of nearly 51 million
per year. But the number of take-offs and landings at the airport
is expected to rise only 3 percent in the same time period.
</P>
<P>
   The terminal expansion now under way is the largest single
public works project ever in the San Francisco Bay area. It
includes a new international terminal with 26 flight gates, an
expanded customs facility, new long-term parking lots, a garage for
rental cars, and a light rail system around the airport _ all paid
for with airport revenues.
</P>
<P>
   As plans for this development were being approved, the Bay
Conservation and Development Commission, which must approve any
construction that intrudes on Bay waters, has said the project
should be subject to their review because it would inevitably lead
to the need for runway expansion.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1993 letter to the commission, Turpen vehemently denied
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Current runway configurations will adequately handle projected
airline operations well into the next century,'' Turpen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, congestion on the airport's runways has grown from
an occasional annoyance to an all-out crisis, particularly with
recent weather problems blamed on the El Nino weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stockwell, who commutes weekly between his home in Napa
County and his publishing job in San Diego, said missed connections
and airport delays have made his travel nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``My company can't afford to send me through San Francisco
Airport anymore,'' he said. ``It just takes too much time.''
</P>
<P>
   At peak travel times, the airport's parallel runways are booked
to capacity _ about 60 landings per hour in clear weather, when two
planes can land side-by-side.
</P>
<P>
   Since San Francisco's runways are only 750 feet apart, all it
takes is a few clouds to knock the whole system into chaos. When
visibility drops, the airport can land planes on only one runway,
cutting in half the number of planes that can get to San Francisco.
The Federal Aviation Administration requires runways be 4,200 feet
apart for dual landings in inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   The delays in San Francisco creates a domino effect, keeping
planes on the ground at airports around the country. In San
Francisco, it has regularly caused dozens of flight cancellations
and left terminals packed with angry, stranded passengers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Expanding the runway system is likely to mean building out into
environmentally sensitive Bay waters.
</P>
<P>
   The airport has offered to do some sort of massive Bay
restoration project as a trade-off for the environmental damage
that might be caused by the new runways.
</P>
<P>
   Under one proposal, the airport would buy 29,000 acres of South
Bay salt ponds and restore them to their original wetlands state,
in what would be one of the largest mitigation efforts in U.S.
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they're dangling the carrot of major wetlands
restoration in the South Bay has sweetened the pot for some
people,'' said Will Burns of Save the Bay, acknowledging that
environmentalists might be more open to the project now than 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns said he believes the airport has known all along it
would need to expand its runway system and simply broke the project
into two pieces to stymie the environmental opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The terminal expansion is worth nothing without taking the
next step,'' he said. ``They knew that when they started.''
</P>
</TEXT>
