<SLUG> BC-HAIR-SALON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIR SALON STRIVES FOR SOMETHING DIFFERENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By TERESA TALERICO  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Flip through an Elle magazine at Vain and you realize
this isn't your grandmother's beauty salon.
</P>
<P>
   Someone has taken a black Magic Marker and scrawled ``SEXISM
HARDCORE'' across Christy Turlington's bra-and-panty-clad torso in
a Calvin Klein ad.
</P>
<P>
   You look up and see Hannah Levin, a 27-year-old rock band
manager, admiring the platinum-blond stripes that now race through
her dark tresses.
</P>
<P>
   But then Jeanne Barrett, who is a bona-fide white-haired
grandmother from Leschi, pops in for a quick trim on her short,
``wash-and-run'' style.
</P>
<P>
   Both women feel at home at Vain, a Belltown mecca of magenta
hair dye, industrial-strength gel, grass-roots activism and
post-punk urban chic.
</P>
<P>
   That's the point, says owner Victoria Gentry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people to walk in and feel like they're going to
be ridiculed if they want something different,'' she says. ``(But)
I also want people who want something more conservative to feel
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentry, 34, has created some waves in the beauty industry with
her 2-year-old Seattle salon, quirky hair-care products, unorthodox
business practices and vow to celebrate ``alternative visions of
beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Vain, at 2222 Second Ave., has been featured in magazines such
as Redbook, Jane and Siren and in The New York Times lifestyles
section.
</P>
<P>
   Clients include band members of the Posies and Screaming Trees,
and the salon has its own Web site at www.vain.com
</P>
<P>
   Gentry's philosophy? Give the people what they want, whether
it's access to ``professional-only'' hair dyes or purple mohawks.
</P>
<P>
   Her customers leave Vain with glossy Marlo Thomas flips. Streaks
of fire-engine red. Spiky punk looks. And, yes, even conservative
bobs and crew cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of it is people looking for a transformation,'' she says.
``They don't like fluffy hair. They want hair that has texture.''
</P>
<P>
   To achieve it, Gentry developed her own line of Vain products
with tongue-in-cheek slogans. They include ``2nd Day Hair: Shampoo
for marginally clean hair'' and ``Dirty Boy, Dirty Girl: Hair goo
for the rumpled masses.''
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey native, Gentry has streaks of ``cherry bomb'' red
in her own dark, shag-cut hair. She started cutting locks as a
punk-rock teenager when she experimented on friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of my brother's tracked me down on the Internet the
other day,'' she says. ``He said, `You gave me the most ridiculous
haircuts I've ever had.'''
</P>
<P>
   At 21, she enrolled in the Artistic Academy of Hair Design in
Fair Lawn, N.J. Her instructors were wide-eyed, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just upset at what my vision of beauty was,'' she
says. ``I only knew how to do mohawks.''
</P>
<P>
   To gain experience, she worked at a New Jersey mall salon and
perfected the ``big hair'' popular with customers there. But Gentry
soon tired of cookie-cutter styles and crossed the Hudson River for
liberation.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, she worked at an East Village salon in
Manhattan and amassed a loyal following of rock musicians, record
producers and artists. She also served as a hairstylist on
Lollapalooza tours.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she moved to Seattle and opened Vain. Her mission? One,
do something about the lackluster long hair that dominated the
grunge scene. And two, open a beauty shop that wasn't stuffy or
pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   The city also seemed perfect for her activist spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was a very good demographic,'' she says. ``It
was a growing city. I wanted to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   At Vain, Gentry keeps a kiosk stocked with American Cancer
Society brochures, free condoms, a list of organizations that do
animal research and information on Home Alive, a Seattle group that
offers self-defense classes for women.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry is a Home Alive advisory board member, has volunteered
with campaigns to free a Pennsylvania death row inmate and is
planning ``Hero Sisters,'' a conference to introduce girls to women
in non-traditional careers.
</P>
<P>
   She also wants to change an industry notorious for sticking it
to women _ narrow-minded beauty standards for exorbitant prices.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbing her nose at other salons, Gentry sells
professional-use-only hair dyes and supplies to do-it-yourselfers.
Usually such products are not available to clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's garbage,'' Gentry says. ``I want this to be
like a laboratory environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Among her peers, some are encouraging, others skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   One Belltown stylist, who wouldn't give her name, praised Gentry
for breathing life into the snooty world of upscale hair salons.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does that very edgy kind of thing,'' she said. ``You know,
a lot of crazy, fun colors. It's really great.''
</P>
<P>
   But another wondered if Gentry could be held legally liable,
say, if a customer buys professional-only dye and then damages her
hair or burns her eyes while using it at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not supposed to do that,'' said Joevir Morada, a
stylist at Fernando's Salon in Belltown. ``They will be held
responsible for whatever happens to their client. The coloring says
for professional use only.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gentry says she instructs customers interested in dying
their hair at home with salon-quality products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to be excited about creating their own styles,''
she says. ``Not `I want to be Cindy Crawford.' I want them to be
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Vain's red walls are not plastered with photos of models and
movie stars. And customers are encouraged to develop their own
styles with the help of staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Her clients are mostly music industry types, but they also
include lawyers, doctors and people with more conservative looks.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, the 72-year-old grandmother, settled into a chair at
Vain. She said she had just finished modeling for a photographer
friend who was shooting a magazine ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know for what,'' she teased. ``It might be an HMO. It
might be `Depends.' '
</P>
<P>
   Gentry giggled.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, the band manager, thumbed through a Rolling Stone. She's
been a customer for six months and couldn't be happier with the
Vain philosophy _ and the prices (cuts start at $28 and include
free trims).
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to go to an insanely expensive salon downtown where the
stylists were all very elitist,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a salon that feels feminist _ where you can be
interested in how you look, but not a slave to Mademoiselle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
