<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MCDOUGAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CLINTON BUDDY MCDOUGAL'S REVELATIONS NOT TOTALLY BELIEVABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hell hath no fury like a business partner scorned. Jim McDougal
vowed to become Bill Clinton's ``worst nightmare'' two years ago,
when he abandoned his longtime defense of the president and started
telling Ken Starr what the Whitewater special prosecutor wanted to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal died in a prison hospital early this year, just as he
was wrapping up ``Arkansas Mischief: The Birth of a National
Scandal,'' a book co-written with Boston Globe reporter Curtis
Wilkie.
</P>
<P>
   The two Deep South populists have produced a book that is
immensely readable but not always believable.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in part, a modern political history of Arkansas, seen
through the eyes of a country boy who set out to do good and then
tried to do well. McDougal depicts a factionalized, one-party state
in which public and private business were freely intermingled.
</P>
<P>
   In one incident, powerful Sen. John McClellan, Congress' leading
prober of organized crime, pulls eight dollars from his billfold
and asks a lobbyist buddy to buy him a pair of alligator shoes back
in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goddamn, senator,'' the lobbyist replies, ``They cost
sixty-four dollars. And besides, that's the first time I ever saw
you pull anything besides a handkerchief out of your pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   McDougal has an initial knack for real estate deals, and makes a
bundle for such employers as Sen. J. William Fulbright. He has
spotted what seems like a sure-shot deal on the White River when
McDougal and his wife, Susan, run into the Clintons in a Little
Rock restaurant. It's 1978 and Bill Clinton will soon be elected
America's youngest governor. After a five-minute conversation, Bill
and Hillary Clinton were signed on as partners in the venture
called Whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   McDougal presents a familiar view of Clinton. The future
president is charming, vastly intelligent and full of himself.
Clinton signs on as Fulbright's driver when the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee chairman is fighting a tough 1968 re-election
battle. But he promptly gets into arguments with Fulbright and is
banished from the car.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Hillary Clinton is compared to Lady Macbeth. It is
her cold, harsh treatment of Susan McDougal that helps persuade
ex-hubby Jim to start spilling the beans to Jeff Gerth of The New
York Times in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Once he told Clinton's 1990 gubernatorial opponent Sheffield
Nelson that there were beans to spill, McDougal was quickly passed
up the conservative food chain. ``Arkansas Mischief'' reveals a
high degree of collusion among Clinton's enemies, and extensive
cooperation between those enemies and dirt-digging Washington,
D.C., reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arkansas Mischief'' starts out as an entertaining tale, and a
clear-eyed look at how political decisions really get made in a
backwater state. But _ like Jim McDougal's career _ it comes
unglued.
</P>
<P>
   Through all the bitterness comes a basic point. If the Clintons
had reciprocated the loyalty and favors shown to them, a bitter man
would never have set in motion the scandal that has bedeviled an
otherwise successful presidency for more than five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whitewater case unfolded because I wanted Bill Clinton to
feel my pain,'' writes Jim McDougal. In that assertion, at least,
he is wholly believable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arkansas Mischief: The Birth of a National Scandal
</P>
<P>
   By Jim McDougal and Curtis Wilkie. Henry Holt, 320 pages, $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
