u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUCLEAR-MILLSTONE-BOS     06-29 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-MILLSTONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTARTING CONNECTICUT REACTOR REFUELS ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERFORD, Conn. _ Sometime this week an operator deep inside
the Millstone 3 nuclear reactor will throw a switch that ends one
of the darkest periods in the history of the US nuclear industry.
</P>
<P>
   After a 27-month shutdown, a record fine for safety violations,
and a staggering $1.3 billion in costs to the owners, New England's
largest power plant will begin splitting atoms again, in time for
the summer season when electricity demand is highest.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Millstone officials still face immense challenges.
Like a nuclear Rip Van Winkle, Millstone 3 will wake to a changed
world that is getting tough on nuclear power. Growing pressure for
utilities to compete, coupled with aging parts, forced two of the
region's eight reactors to close permanently while the three
reactors at Millstone were out, and Millstone 1, the oldest reactor
at the site, could be next.
</P>
<P>
   But, after what they've been through, it's hard to blame chief
nuclear officer Bruce Kenyon for planning a celebration on the
nuclear plant's lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from thousands of issues down to a handful and it's
starting to sink in to everyone'' that start-up is imminent, said
Kenyon, the orderly troubleshooter who came in 1996 to turn around
what regulators then regarded as America's worst-run nuclear plant.
``I'm starting to get excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the Nuclear Regulatory Commission approves Millstone's work
on a few minor problems, operators can begin to ``pull rods,''
removing the control rods inside the reactor that act as a brake on
nuclear reactions. Then, over the next four to six weeks, workers
will gradually bring Millstone 3 to full power.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Millstone 3 will boost New England's power supply,
which has nearly run short the last two summers due to problems at
nuclear plants. With only two of the region's reactors running on
Friday, utility officials appealed for conservation throughout New
England to avoid shortages.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the people of southeastern Connecticut, a bastion of
pro-nuclear sentiment with its nuclear submarine base and submarine
manufacturing plant, the last two years have been disillusioning.
Though Millstone has a community support group, many residents are
wary of their nuclear neighbor and a local citizens group believes
the restart is too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company still has a lot of work to do in regaining the
trust and confidence of people ... because its record of
mismanagement under previous leadership gives no cause for great
confidence,'' said Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal,
a critic of Millstone owner Northeast Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the steam clouds rising from tests inside Millstone 3
underscore a striking turn from early 1996 when troubles at the
plant made the cover of Time magazine and forced a shutdown. Dozens
of workers said they had been harassed by management for raising
safety concerns, and regulators were accused of looking the other
way as managers cut sometimes-dangerous corners.
</P>
<P>
   Workers said Northeast Utilities, New England's largest utility,
had become gripped by ``megawatt fever,'' a term for managers
obsessed with the huge cost of idling a nuclear plant for a single
day. They pushed workers to undertake risky repairs while the
reactor was running and store radioactive fuel in an inadequate
cooling tank to save time.
</P>
<P>
   By September 1996, when Kenyon arrived, Millstone was on the
lowest rung of the NRC's ``watch list'' of troubled plants,
requiring a formal vote of the commissioners to restart. So low was
NRC trust in plant officials that they took the unprecendented step
of hiring a contractor to double check virtually every significant
reform plant managers undertook.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon, a respected senior executive with South Carolina
Electric and Gas and former chief of Millstone 2, immediately
replaced the whole Millstone management team _ mainly with
outsiders _ but he discovered that the job was much more difficult
than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found an organization that was demoralized, struggling to
find a direction ... wanting to do what's right, having lost
confidence in the leadership,'' said Kenyon, sitting by his window
overlooking the sprawling industrial complex on the edge of Niantic
Bay. As a result, he had to repeatedly push back his goals for
starting up the reactors.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other long nuclear plant outages, where the biggest
problems were broken equipment, Kenyon had to fix a broken
workplace culture. Millstone officials have spent more than $500
million on improving the nuclear reactors, almost none of it on
construction, and a good amount of it on convincing workers to
speak their minds again.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I found the hardest to do is to rebuild a climate of
trust in an atmosphere of distrust,'' said Kenyon, his tanned face
deeply lined as he smiles. ``There was a segment of the employee
population whose sense of trust was so damaged that it was really
digging out of a deep hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to prove his sincerity, Kenyon even hired one of the
harshest Millstone critics, former Millstone engineer Paul Blanch.
Northeast Utilities had been fined $100,000 in 1993 to settle
Blanch's harassment charges and Blanch had gone on to organize the
Citizens Regulatory Commission to publicize Millstone safety
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Blanch, a consultant who helps resolve employee concerns before
they become a crisis, believes that Kenyon has made Millstone safe
enough to generate power again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people are comfortable that they can raise issues
without the fear of retaliation,'' said Blanch, a claim backed up
by the fact that Millstone now responds to more employee concerns
than any other nuclear plant.
</P>
<P>
   But others feel that the old Millstone, and the old cozy
relationship with the NRC, is just below the surface. Ernest
Hadley, attorney for the employee whistleblower who hurt Millstone
managers the most, believes neither the company nor NRC officials
learned their lessons because no one was punished. Senior managers
for Northeast Utilities and the NRC escaped with honors, profit or
both, while a criminal investigation into a possible coverup of
violations by the US Attorney in Connecticut has languished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was held personally accountable. They can't fine these
people enough'' to make them change behavior, said Hadley, who is
based in Massachusetts. ``The way you hold people accountable is...
you send them to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   NRC officials, who found their credibility challenged as never
before in the wake of the Millstone scandal, counter that they have
taken unprecedented steps to make sure Millstone is safe. The
agency has spent more time at Millstone, measured in the hundreds
of thousands of hours, than anywhere else in the country, and fined
Northeast Utilities a record $2.1 million last December.
</P>
<P>
   Millstone officials say they have learned their lesson also,
fixing at least 20,000 problems at Millstone 3 alone, and
consistently choosing to delay the restart when faced with
difficulties. Now, they feel, the only thing to do is start the
reactor, expected to get NRC approval any day.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is far less rosy for Millstone 1, a 1970 vintage
reactor that provides a quarter of the 2,680 megawatts at
Millstone. Work on the reactor halted last year after a company
study showed a relatively small $70 million advantage to keeping
the reactor open. If a study next month is even more unfavorable,
as many expect, Northeast Utilities could decide to close the
reactor for good.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Utilities is bullish on Millstone 2, which managers
hope to restart by year's end. And the startup of Millstone 3 gives
the company much-needed income to reduce the $30 million that
Millstone's owners pay for replacement power.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate fate of the reactors at Millstone may have as
much to do with the competition as anything Millstone officials do.
Dozens of efficient facilities that burn natural gas have been
proposed for New England, based partly on the belief that the
owners can charge less for electricity than existing plants,
driving some of them out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, construction began on a new gas plant in
Charlton, Mass., a project that owner PG&AMP;E Corporation called ``a
model... for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   But Northeast Utilities, unique among New England utilities,
will live or die by its nuclear plants. As the owner or part-owner
of five reactors, all of which would be hard to sell, Northeast has
little choice.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon is aware of the challenges. ``It is not time to sit back
and rest on our laurels,'' he said. ``Our performance is solid
enough for restart, but we have not reached excellence and ...
that's where we need to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
