<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1891 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-ENGLAND-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     06-29 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ENGLAND-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... and manufacturing.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Virtually every city or town in New England had at least one
small mill or shop, and they really have disappeared,'' says
Richard Candee, a Boston University professor and director of
Preservation Studies, though a few soldier on in the area's mill
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few textile companies that are still doing well by
developing a specialty product and holding on hard to it,'' says
Candee. He added that some other mills, like the Schwamb Mill in
Arlington, Mass. that makes oval picture frames, have been kept
alive as working museums.
</P>
<P>
   New England's great industries and its natural beauty spawned
great literature. And now that they are vanishing, so too may be
the literary opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will not have someone writing about the whaling industry,
and you will not have people writing about the old customs house in
Salem, (Mass.) or camping on the pond,'' says Peter Davison, a
Boston editor and poet.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe that the next great wave of literature
might be about spreadsheets and e-mail. But even if it is, the
venue could just as easily be Silicon Valley or Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Even regional accents and colloquialisms _ the linguistic stamp
of who we are _ are starting to slip, says Maine humorist Tim
Sample.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a verbal shorthand and has a very pragmatic role of
identifying someone as being from your tribe, or from away,'' says
Sample, who grew up in Boothbay Harbor and now lives in Bath. He
says there has been a dilution of the Downeast accent, caused by
the ``influx of people and the morphing of demographics along the
coast of Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that, sadly but inevitably, happens as these
cultural and social touchstones diminish is it falls to people in
the arts, writers and performers to preserve them.''
</P>
<P>
   That this is happening in Maine is remarkable, Sample says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mainers have a long tradition of resisting change, and it has
stood us in pretty good stead. Maine would be a lousy place to
start a new religion. If you go to California, you could get 100
devotees in the first month. After six years in Maine, you might
get one person coming to your meeting. `New' is not a good
adjective to use when pushing something in Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Green, a Boston university English professor, says that
many local terms in use as recently as 50 years ago, are
disappearing. ``I'm not sure people say `dropped eggs' anymore
instead of poached eggs; I'm not sure people say `tonic' instead of
soda. Do you know what a jug-o-rum is? It's a bullfrog. `Peepers'
are spring frogs. People used to say bellybunt for bellyflop. The
second crop of hay was called a `rowen.'''
</P>
<P>
   William Kretzschmer, a professor of English and linguistics at
the University of Gerogia, where he directs the American Linguistic
Atlas Project, says the perception is ``that there is more and more
speech that does not sound like it comes from anywhere is true.''
But the suppression of regional accents, he says, still occurs
mostly in college-educated, upper-middle-class people. Dialects
still thrive in many middle- and lower-class families.
</P>
<P>
   The postcard New England of pristine mountain forests and
endless beaches is harder than ever to find, especially in the
summer or during foliage season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is manufactured and artificial,'' says Judson D.
Hale, the editor of Yankee magazine. ``And when you do go to the
icon places where so many Europeans and Americans go, you will be
surrounded by places that are cheap and shabby. If you go to where
Paul Revere lived, you might end up buying some T-shirts, but Paul
Revere really did live there.''
</P>
<P>
   New England, says O'Connor, is becoming ``multicultural,
multilingual, highly technically industrialized, overpopulated and
over polluted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are wonderful oceans out there. But instead of the lone
white sailboat, there are jet skis careening at 80 miles an hour.
But we still like to think of it the old way ... It might be that
we are in a period of nostalgia, choosing to ignore the realities
of the present and future, preferring instead to dream our dream of
what Cape Cod and Boston was like _ small winding streets and
little shops. But Boston is a multinational city of finance and
real estate that bears very little relationship to what we like to
think it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Hale is far from ready to abandon New England as Anyplace USA,
despite the Wal-Marts at the edge of many rural towns, the Red
Lobster Restaurants in Maine, and the myriad outlet stores _ from
Manchester, Vt., to Freeport, Maine _ that have become a late
20th-century version of the New England country store.
</P>
<P>
   ``The human condition is to regret what is passing by,'' says
Hale. ``But I think there is a great effort across New England to
strengthen its image. People are working hard to keep that image
and our culture autonomous. The mountains always stay the same.''
</P>
<P>
   He notes that New England sensibilities still run strong. During
the 1980s, for example, when the Celtics were battling the Los
Angeles Lakers for basketball supremecy, ``we did not mind the
Lakers team so much, but we hated the hoopla, the cheerleaders, the
movie stars along the sidelines. It was so different in Boston
Garden, it was really New England.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the Garden is gone and in its place is the Fleet Center,
a cookie cutter arena that could be a major league sporting venue
in any other major city. The building has no obstructed-view seats,
but it also _ at least so far _ has no soul.
</P>
<P>
   If the six states of New England have one sports team that binds
them together, it is the Red Sox, with their century-old tradition.
But even the Red Sox of today are blur of players who are unlikely
to spend a career here. Since Dwight Evans _ who spent 17 years
patroling right field _ left in 1990, the team has had 33 players
in that position. Jerry Seinfeld's schtick about fans rooting for
laundry has some truth to it. Many fans pay to see the team in
large part to experience venerable Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, it appears, will soon be gone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
