<HEADER>
A1895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIVERSE-DISCOVERY-BO     06-29 1671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSE-DISCOVERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS ARE BEGINNING TO SEE HOW THE UNIVERSE WILL END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  How old is the universe? How will it end? What is it all made
of? After centuries of wondering, and decades of painstaking and
frustrating research, scientists may be close to answering those
fundamental questions.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes down to the search for three numbers: The key
measurements that will reveal the universe's past, its present, and
its future _ including its ultimate fate. Scientists have startled
themselves with the recent progress they've made toward figuring
out what those numbers are.
</P>
<P>
   The three numbers that will describe what scientists refer to as
the ``shape'' of the universe _ whether it is ``open'' and will
expand forever, or ``closed'' and will eventually come crashing
back together, or something in between _ are these: The speed of
the universe's expansion, called the Hubble constant; the amount of
matter in the universe, called the density parameter; and a
peculiar number called the cosmological constant, which describes
whether, and if so how much, empty space exerts a pressure of its
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The degree of precision that we now have in determining''
these basic measurements ``would have been deemed inconceivable a
decade ago,'' said John Bahcall, an astrophycisist at the Institute
for Advanced Study in Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, several groups carrying out different
kinds of research _ some looking at neutrinos, the tiniest, most
lightweight objects known to exist; some looking at supernovae, the
most colossal explosive events known; and others looking at aspects
of the vast realm in between _ are pinning down the answers to what
scientists consider some of the biggest puzzles of all.
</P>
<P>
   As Peter Coles of the University of London wrote in the current
issue of the journal Nature, ``the standard ideas of the 1980s
about the shape and history of the Universe have now been
abandoned,'' leading to a ``new model universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few months ago, most astronomers acknowledged that they
only knew what made up less than 10 percent of the universe. The
new findings remain controversial, and a massive influx of data
expected over the next few years could change everything, but now
it is just possible that virtually all of the stuff of the cosmos
has finally been identified.
</P>
<P>
   The new data suggest some intriguing conclusions. One is that
the ``shape'' of the universe lies poised exactly in between the
theoretically possible extremes, eternal expansion and ultimate
collapse: In the parlance of physics, it is perfectly ``flat,''
although with an unexpected acceleration. And, even more
surprisingly, about two-thirds of the ``stuff'' that makes up the
universe may consist of neither matter nor energy; it may be,
instead, a mysterious phenomenon that produces a universal push out
of pure nothingness. It is this phenomenon that is measured by the
``cosmological constant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really weird result,'' conceded Robert Kirshner of
the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics, a member of one of
the teams whose research has produced this revolution in cosmology.
``You thought we were telling a fairy tale before!''
</P>
<P>
   The weird result emerged from his group's study of very distant
exploding stars, or supernovae. They found that the more distant
supernovae _ up to 5 billion light years away _ are moving more
slowly than those closer to us. Because we see those galaxies as
they were 5 billion years ago, this suggests that the expansion of
the universe _ the rate at which all the galaxies in space are
flying apart _ is actually speeding up.
</P>
<P>
   Theorists have long known that because everything in the
universe exerts a gravitational pull on everything else, the
expansion should be slowing down. So what could explain this
paradoxical acceleration? Most scientists now think that _ assuming
the supernova findings are correct _ this implies that there really
is a ``cosmological constant,'' a kind of pressure exerted by sheer
vacuum that pushes everything apart; it's sort of like the
science-fiction notion of ``antigravity.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept was first suggested, and then hastily retracted, by
physicist Albert Einstein in the 1920s. Einstein found the idea
disturbing because it implied that the universe was expanding _
scientific heresy in an era when everyong thought that it was
static and unchanging. But just a few years later, astronomer Edwin
Hubble's observations of the motions of distant galaxies proved
once and for all that the universe really is expanding; that
discovery, in turn, gave rise to the Big Bang theory, and modern
cosmology.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, many scientists are still troubled by the idea of a
cosmological constant, which suggests, as Kirshner put it, ``that
space has this spongy quality to it.'' Until the new supernova
evidence came along, the idea had almost disappeared from
scientific discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is strong, but not yet conclusive. As Kirshner and
others on the supernova team readily acknowledge, there may be some
other explanation. For example, what they observed was a difference
in the brightness of nearby and distant supernovae, which they
attributed to a difference in their velocity. Maybe, instead, it is
the supernovae themselves that differ in some way.
</P>
<P>
   Bahcall is one of those who takes the cosmological constant
interpretation with a grain of salt. Theoretical calculations, he
said, suggest that if it exists at all, it should be much, much
bigger than the supernova data indicates.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a right to be skeptical,'' Kirshner said, ``but
not infinitely skeptical.'' And his group is continuing its search
for clearer evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The supernova evidence so far, widely reported in the field but
not yet formally published, comes on top of other recent major
finds that also have helped to close in on some of these key
numbers that shape our fate: First, the discovery by five
independent teams, reported in January, that there is not nearly
enough matter in the universe to produce the gravitational pull
needed to halt its expansion and eventually make the universe
collapse upon itself in a ``big crunch,'' or even to make it
``flat.'' Then, the discovery reported a few weeks ago that tiny
particles called neutrinos do have mass. It had long thought likely
that they had none.
</P>
<P>
   The minuscule mass of the neutrino may account for some of the
missing, or ``dark matter'' in space _ matter that is not visible
by any ordinary means. But because the neutrino mass is apparently
so tiny, it adds to the evidence that there's not enough matter out
there to cause a big crunch or a flat universe.
</P>
<P>
   The neutrino discovery was made by an international team using a
detector in Japan called Super-Kamiokande _ a huge underground
cavern filled with water to detect faint flashes of light that show
the passage of a neutrino. The experiment proved that these tiniest
of all subatomic particles are not weightless, as light is, but
have some measurable mass. But it did not reveal just what that
mass is; it only showed that there is a third type, in addition to
the two previously known, and measured the differences in their
mass.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists say the finding suggests that, at most, neutrinos
might account for about 10 percent of the matter needed for a
``flat'' universe. That's not enough to make any difference in the
basic Big Bang theory, but it could turn out to be enough to make a
big difference in explaining how galaxies formed, said theoretical
physicist Alan Guth of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
``It would change the theories quite a bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But all the recent findings suggest that the universe contains
only about 20 to 30 percent as much matter as most theories,
including Guth's, predicted there must be _ an amount called the
``critical density.''
</P>
<P>
   That shortcoming could have been fatal to those widely accepted
theories _ except that, as luck would have it, along came the
evidence for a cosmological constant, just what was needed to fill
the critical density gap.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In the equations that describe the birth and growth of the
universe, the cosmological constant is equivalent to matter, even
though it has no physical substance. And the measurement of the
cosmological constant derived from the supernova research is just
the amount needed to account for the 70 percent or so of the
critical-density mass that was missing.
</P>
<P>
   That provides the amount needed to produce the ``flat'' universe
that most theories say exists _ including Guth's ``inflationary
universe'' theory, which has become the prevailing cosmological
paradigm. It holds that the universe underwent a brief flash of
enormously accelerated expansion during a tiny fraction of a second
after the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these observations are right, then we've found the critical
density,'' said Guth. But, he added, ``it's certainly a surprise,''
because nobody had been expecting a cosmological constant to be the
thing that would fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly changes our view of cosmology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there's much more to come. New surveys of the entire sky,
including the massive Sloan Digital Sky Survey that reported its
first observations three weeks ago, and new satellites, including
one called the Microwave Anisotropy Probe, designed to find ripples
in the cosmic background radiation _ the echoes of the Big Bang _
are expected to produce reams of data in the next few years that
could pin down once and for all the three numbers that describe the
universe's shape and its fate.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, said Guth, the basic numbers that describe
the universe may be nailed down to within about 10 percent _ which,
in theoretical physics, counts as astonishing precision.
</P>
<P>
   As the astronomer Coles put it in his article in Nature, ``a
data explosion is about to engulf cosmology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
