<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIEVING PARENTS FAULT PRODUCT RECALL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, Linda Ginzel and Boaz Keysar thought it was a freak
accident last month when a portable crib at their toddler's
day-care center snapped shut and killed their son.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, however, the couple from Chicago discovered his
death fit a pattern. The crib, called Playskool Travel-Lite and
made by Kolcraft Inc., had been recalled by the government and the
company five years ago after three children had died in the units.
And since the 1993 recall, two more children, including Daniel
Keysar, died in the cribs.
</P>
<P>
   As the couple endures the loss of their 17-month-old child, whom
they described as ``a pudgy, happy little bundle of enormous
potential,'' the boy's death raises questions about the
effectiveness of the nation's recall process.
</P>
<P>
   Do the government and manufacturers act swiftly enough to
identify dangerous objects? And when they do, is enough done to get
the word out about recalls?
</P>
<P>
   The couple said the recall system failed them, as they and their
day-care provider had no idea that the portable crib used by their
son was defective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an effective system,'' said Keysar, 40, a psychology
professor at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Kolcraft and federal officials insist that they acted
responsibly during the 1993 recall of the Playskool Travel-Lite
crib, spreading the word through press releases and notifying
pediatrician and childrens' groups.
</P>
<P>
   But there is tangible evidence their efforts fell short.
According to Kolcraft's own attorney, Charles Risch of Chicago,
just 3,500 of the 11,000 defective cribs (model numbers 77101 and
77103 sold between 1990 and 1992) have been returned.
</P>
<P>
   With only a 30 percent return rate on such a dangerous crib,
Keysar said the company should have stepped up efforts to get more
of them back. Aggressive recall campaigns often include bounties,
such as double your money back, or company-paid ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company should spend at least as much money to retrieve
these cribs as they spend marketing them,'' Keysar said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say all of the youngsters were killed in a
similar manner: The upper horizontal railings, which should remain
taut while the crib is in use, suddenly collapse into a V-shape
because of a faulty locking device at the center of the railing. A
child's neck gets trapped at the bottom of the V-shaped bars,
causing suffocation.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, who also have a 5-year-old son, have filed a lawsuit
against the crib maker, but do not blame the family day- care
center, Sweet Tots in Chicago, in their son's death, said their
attorney, Steve Senderowitz. The center had apparently received the
crib as a hand-me-down gift.
</P>
<P>
   Ginzel, 39, who is also a university professor, pointed out that
in the last several years, Evenflo, Century, Draco, and Baby Trend
have joined Kolcraft in recalling 1.5 million portable cribs or
playpens of different models. Federal officials said 12 children
have died from collapsed playpens and cribs.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Schoem, director of recall and compliance for the US
Consumer Product Safety Commission, defended the agency's work in
identifying hazardous products, saying that about 300 products are
recalled a year. He said the average recall prompts a return rate
of about 30 percent. He said some big-ticket items, such as cars
and refrigerators, have return rates of 90 percent, perhaps because
more money is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   He said immediate action was taken in 1993 when regulators
identified a problem with Kolcraft's Playskool model, and the
government required the company to play a major role in spreading
the word about the defects. Kolcraft offered a full refund for all
returned cribs.
</P>
<P>
   If there is blame about lack of publicity of recalls on these
cribs and other products, Schoem places some with the media for
failing to devote enough space or air time to recall information.
In contrast, he said, ``Newspapers almost on a daily basis run
lottery results.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid future tragedies, commission officials point out that
parents should be careful when receiving hand-me-down products,
which may have been recalled without them knowing it. (For
information on these cribs and other recalls, check the
commission's Web site at www.cpsc.gov or call its hotline at
1-800-638-2772.)
</P>
<P>
   The commission also urges parents to fill out registration cards
when they make the original purchase. These cards help the
manufacturer contact owners when a problem arises. No such card was
made available in the Playskool Travel-Lite crib.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Keysar and Ginzel have started a nonprofit group to
warn parents about dangerous products for juveniles. The group has
its own Web site (www.kidsindanger.org). Keysar and Ginzel are also
pursuing a wrongful-death suit against the company. State
authorities in Illinois have yet to complete an investigation of
the day-care center, a routine move when a death occurs at a
licensed facility.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois officials are giving all licensed day-care centers a
copy of the portable crib recall lists. At the Massachusetts Office
of Child Care Services, which licenses day-care centers here,
spokesman Doug Pizzi said all centers will be given a list of the
recalled cribs.
</P>
<P>
   Ginzel said more information has to be made available about such
products. Many parents have called her saying they were ignorant
about the hazards of foldup cribs, even though they are widely
used. ``Everyone always says, `We had no idea.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
AT&AMP;T misdelivers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T may be trying to turn around its reputation for giving out
wrong numbers, but Sue Marsh says it has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh, executive director for the Massachusetts Coalition for
the Homeless, said she is being driven mad by AT&AMP;T operators who
keep giving out the coalition's phone number to people seeking
numbers for other Massachusetts groups.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, she said she has gotten from two to five
phone calls a day intended for groups ranging from Massachusetts
General Hospital to Massachusetts Electric. When she called to
complain, she said an AT&AMP;T representative explained that some
overworked operators hear a request for an organization beginning
with the word ``Massachusetts,'' and simply give the number of one
of the first Massachusetts groups on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh said she was infuriated when the AT&AMP;T worker suggested, as
a possible solution to this problem, that she might want to get the
coalition's number unlisted. ``AT&AMP;T is asking the victim to be
taken out of directory assistance!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokeswoman Robin Sayre said she has yet to hear of a case
when so many wrong numbers went to one group. While she is
convinced the coalition's experience is an isolated case, perhaps
an odd linking of random mistakes, she has sent a message to all
directory assistance oeprators to ``probe carefully'' when asked
for a listing beginning with the word, ``Massachusetts,'' and pay
close attention when giving out the coalition's number.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
