<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 (FR)!! ``Dr. Dolittle''  Eddie Murphy talks to the animals, and
they talk back to him, ``Babe''-style, reasonably engagingly. But
this bland remake, set in contemporary San Francisco, suffers from
a weak script and is smothered under a pall of uplift and
heavy-handed self-empowerment messages. (PG-13)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! ``Cousin Bette''  &LR; Jessica Lange is a lot of fun to watch as the
revenge-dispensing poor relation in a family of witless aristocrats
in Balzac's Paris. But Des McAnuff's lack of trust in the material
leads him into crude underlinings and italicizings that wrench the
comedy of revenge. Elisabeth Shue's appropriately vulgar burlesque
queen, breaking the hearts of lechers, and McAnuff's mirroring of
the era's political upheaval in the world of the theater complement
Lange worthily, but little else does. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el-.2 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! 1/2 ``Insomnia''  &LR; Impressively edgy police thriller from
Norway. The real twistiness begins after big-city cop Skellan
Skarsgard is dispatched to a small coastal town on the Arctic
Circle and uncovers the identity of the murderer. He finds himself
compromised, stressed, and unable to sleep when the murderer
reveals his knowledge of the cop's guilty secret and threatens to
expose him if he doesn't frame somebody else for the crime.
(Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``Out of Sight''  &LR; Finally George Clooney looks like a movie
star, roguish and relaxed as a career bank robber lining up his
exit heist. But he has to make it past a crew of killers determined
to elbow him out of the payoff, and also elude Jennifer Lopez's
smart, tough, sexy cop he almost wishes would catch him. He knows
that falling for her would be a bad career move, but he does it
anyway in this playful riff on Elmore Leonard's novel. (R)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
