<HEADER>
A1906 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SUMMER-BOS &LR;      06-29 1610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOOKS OF SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An old friend and I have been having our annual argument about
what each of us will read this summer. A passionate but careful
reader, he is committed to Trollope; I rather sniffily countered
that I thought George Eliot would be a better bet. Late one evening
we were roaming around WordsWorth, where a spirited discussion was
taking place in the mystery aisles about Chinese culture. Like
Harvard Book Store, it is the kind of haven where one might gladly
be locked in overnight. My friend, grumpy at me for having messed
with his decision, clutched copies of both Eliot's ``Middlemarch''
and Trollope's ``Can You Forgive Her?''; I, stuck in the ``B''
section and the 20th century, grabbed a new edition of British
writer Pat Barker's brilliant novel of the First World War,
``Regeneration,'' and forced it upon him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, read this,'' I said, sure he would love the
fictionalized relationship between poet Siegfried Sassoon and his
wartime psychiatrist. My friend smiled politely, pretended to scan
the jacket copy, and put the novel back on the shelf. ``You know
me,'' he shrugged. ``I'm basically a drawing-room kind of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   I, on the other hand, was drowning in war novels by the time I
was 11 or 12, happily immersed in ``Mila 18'' and ``The Naked and
the Dead'' in the basement of an air-conditioned Texas library.
What makes some of us gravitate to the elegant quiet of the drawing
room, others to the thrilling horror of the front lines, regardless
of gender or age or other telling traits of sensibility? I remember
taking solace during one August heat wave in Henry James's ``The
Portrait of a Lady,'' just on the heels of John le Carre's ``The
Little Drummer Girl''; I'm not at all sure the James made me a
better person, but I know it made me work a lot harder. One reader
will reach for Tolstoi every July; another insists upon nothing
more demanding than a Stephen King or John Grisham. All of us have
the same cross-genre goal: to leave behind the tragedettes and
self-delusions of our own lives for a time, and to find respite or
wisdom or comic relief in, God willing, an imaginary someone
else's.
</P>
<P>
   The Tolstoi of the summer of '98, according to some hyperbole,
is Richard Price's ``Freedomland''; the novel is neither that good
nor that wide, but it does deliver a story of dark intrigue _ the
search for a missing child _ with technicolor mega-realism. This
has been a heavy hitter's season for serious fiction, most notably
with Toni Morrison's exquisitely realized ``Paradise,'' her
incantatory vision of two colliding cultures _ an insular black
community and a women's retreat _ in a small Oklahoma town. Robert
Stone's ``Damascus Gate'' delivers Jerusalem in all its mad
splendor; the novel is vastly intelligent, but it's a tough
mountain trail, and newcomers to Stone might want to try the recent
reissues of his best novels: ``A Flag for Sunrise,'' ``Dog
Soldiers,'' or ``Outerbridge Reach.'' Cormac McCarthy finishes his
Border trilogy, set in a mythic, mid-century West, in ``Cities of
the Plain.'' The previous two volumes, ``All the Pretty Horses''
and ``The Crossing,'' are better: richer, deeper, more rhapsodic.
Writing from within the moral ambiguities of post-apartheid South
Africa, Nadine Gordimer takes on individual responsibility in a
violent society in ``The House Gun.'' And in ``My Heart Laid
Bare,'' Joyce Carol Oates, waxing overly Gothic as ever, traces the
threads of family mendacity and betrayal through two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Frazier's grits 'n' gunpowder Civil War saga, ``Cold
Mountain,'' continues its nearly yearlong perch on the best-seller
lists, though I still contend that Ruby's Southern cooking is the
most compelling aspect of the novel. Russell Banks and Jane Smiley
took on the same historical era with similarly mixed results _
Banks's ``Cloud-splitter'' is a weighty fictionalized account of
John Brown's life, and Smiley's ``The All-True Travels and
Adventures of Lidie Newton'' is a picaresque abolitionist tale set
in antebellum Kansas. Anne Tyler produced another Mary Poppins
feel-good novel in ``The Patchwork Planet,'' while John Irving
continues his comic Dickensian chest-pounding with ``A Widow for
One Year.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickens figures in an even more direct way for Peter Carey, who
pays homage to ``Great Expectations'' in his deftly imagined ``Jack
Maggs.'' Such intellectual fiction has been enjoying a mini-revival
of late, kicked off last year with Thomas Pynchon's hefty ``Mason &AMP;
Dixon'' _ many have traveled there, but few have survived to tell
the whole tale. Recent spinoffs from that school of cerebrum-lit
include Australian writer Janette Turner Hospital's surrealistic
``Oyster,'' Maureen Howard's ``A Lover's Almanac,'' which is as
clever and au courant as dim sum, and Richard Powers's ``Gain'' _ a
daunting history of American commerce, which newcomers are advised
to put second to his previous novel, the brilliantly cyber-poetic
``Galatea 2.2.''
</P>
<P>
   Less showy but more emotionally rewarding are a few elegantly
literary novels from recent months _ particularly Irish writer
Colum McCann's ``This Side of Brightness,'' a resonant and deeply
moving story set in the subway tunnels of New York. Alice McDermott
provides a sweet melancholy with ``Charming Billy,'' which delivers
her central character by opening at his wake. In ``The Antelope
Wife,'' Louise Erdrich returns to her signature territory of Native
American myth and emotional legacy on the high Northern Plains.
Dorothy Allison fans will appreciate the easy-listening tone of her
rock 'n' roll novel, ``Cavedweller,'' which is hip and emotionally
candid, a long, old-fashioned story about going home. Jane
Hamilton, Oprah-ized for ``The Book of Ruth'' and appreciated for
``A Map of the World,'' has written a lovely novel in ``The Short
History of a Prince.'' Critic David Gates, who wowed a select band
of happy nihilists with his Holden Caulfield-like ``Jernigan,'' has
maintained that voice of ironic despair in ``Preston Falls.''
Another quiet victory of the season has been that of Ian McEwan,
whose hot-air-balloon send-off at the beginning of ``Enduring
Love'' transports readers in every way.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy analysands, limping through August while the docs are in
Truro, might want to draw succor from Daniel Menaker's ``The
Treatment'': You may be temporarily at sea, but at least you don't
have the demonic Dr. Morales for a shrink. An even wiser
contribution to the Art of Neurosis is Julie Hecht's sleeper story
collection from last year, ``Do the Windows Open?'' Laconic,
deadpan, and brilliantly charming, it's one of the funniest books
I've read in ages.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Two from 1997, now both in paper, were Don DeLillo's
``Underworld'' and Philip Roth's ``American Pastoral''; DeLillo's
vast and visionary epic looms like Idaho next to Roth's impeccably
structured Perfect Village. Arundhati Roy's gauzily sorrowful
novel, ``The God of Small Things,'' broke a lot of hearts in a
minor way last year; it's available in paper as well. A few other
books from 1997, well-received but half-neglected by the numbers,
deserve mention again: Rilla Askew's Faulknerian first novel, ``The
Mercy Seat,'' is a beautifully somber story about a family in the
19th-century West. Canadian poet Anne Michaels wrote a lovely ode
to prose in her story of a young Jewish refugee hiding during the
Second World War in ``Fugitive Pieces.'' And Francisco Goldman, in
his spooky, Conradian ``The Ordinary Seaman,'' took us aboard a
ghost ship in Brooklyn that never leaves port.
</P>
<P>
   Now on to the chips 'n' dips section, where pulp and whodunits
will take care of those tired brain cells that worked so hard all
year. The bimbette novel getting all kinds of press this summer,
much of it undeserved, is British former journalist Helen
Fieldings' ``Bridget Jones's Diary'' _ rhymes with Gidget, just
about as retro, but seems to be amusing Neanderbabes. Jacquelyn
Mitchard wrote a death-row love story in ``The Most Wanted,''
though her 1996 first novel, ``The Deep End of the Ocean,'' is much
better. Brad Meltzer, a lawyer who wowed bestseller lists last
summer with ``The Tenth Justice,'' has just turned out another
legal thriller about a husband-and-wife prosecutor-and-defense
pairing, ``Dead Even''; like his first novel, it's emotionally
clunky, but he's got the courtroom-suspense momentum down pat.
</P>
<P>
   In the mystery realm, P.D. James reigns supreme, as usual, with
last winter's ``A Certain Justice,'' which opens with a dead
barrister wearing a powdered wig. Her fellow Brit Martin Amis tried
to expand his repertoire by writing an existential whodunit,
``Mystery Train''; this little novel has left most literary readers
going ``huh?'' (shorthand for ``Why did I bother?''). More
rewarding and less pretentious is Carol O'Connell's spooky, awful
scare-novel, ``The Judas Child.'' On the local hero front: Susan
Conant, whose Alaskan malamutes save the day in her canine capers,
has added to her dog-friendly mystery series with ``The Barker
Street Regulars''; due any day from the presidentially adored
Dennis Lehane (Clinton read him on the Vineyard, of course) is the
Bean-town P.I. mystery ``Gone, Baby, Gone.''
</P>
<P>
   And leave us not forget the old standbys, who are to the bookish
in summer as essential as peach pie: Graham Greene, Edith Wharton,
E.M. Forster, Evelyn Waugh, Dickens, naturally, and, oh, maybe
Anthony Powell. (Woolf? Eliot? No, Trollope, dammit, Trollope!)
</P>
<P>
   If you find something magnificent, let me know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
