<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1910 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-AFFLECK-2TAKES     06-29 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-AFFLECK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN AFFLECK'S NEXT FRONTIER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The craziness started, of course, right after this
year's Oscars. The parties and hugs and goodbyes didn't stop until
the night after Ben Affleck and Matt Damon raised the Oscarcast
energy level with their exuberance at being named
best-original-screenplay winners for ``Good Will Hunting.'' Then
Affleck and Damon climbed on a red-eye for Pittsburgh to shoot
their next movie, ``Dogma,'' a religious satire by ``Chasing Amy''
filmmaker Kevin Smith. That's when the surrealism began in earnest,
Affleck says. ``The captain said, `Congratulations,' and the movie
on the plane was `Good Will Hunting,' and then we land and there
were hundreds of people at 6 in the morning at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how weird it is,'' Affleck continues,
stretching out in a suite in the kind of hotel that offers a view
of yachts bobbing in a marina. ``It was the first time we really
hung out together since the Academy Awards, and there were these
extras (for the film), and one lady was standing behind me and she
was like brushing up against me and she was like, `I'm touching
him, I'm touching him.' I thought, `This is insanity.' Then I
overheard Matt talking to someone who had walked up to him and
said, `God, I can't believe I'm talking to Matt Damon.' And I
thought, `You know, talking to Matt Damon used to be as pedestrian
as walking the dog. And now it's something people can't believe
they're doing.' But I guess it's the same process with anyone who
becomes famous.''
</P>
<P>
   At 25, Affleck knows he's up to his neck in paradox. At
precisely the moment when Hollywood stands ready to shove him into
a box labeled ``hunk'' or ``genius,'' he sees the danger of being
mythicized into something unreal. So he's playing the Hollywood
kind of Russian roulette young talent always has played, dancing
with the system, but also dancing away from it. That's why he made
``Dogma,'' in which he and Damon play fallen angels exiled to
Wisconsin, and ``200 Cigarettes,'' with Courtney Love, Paul Rudd,
and his brother, Casey. But he's here today to talk about his role
in ``Armageddon,'' the summer's gonzo action movie opening
Wednesday. In it, Affleck plays a trouble-shooter saving Earth from
a Texas-size asteroid, along with Bruce Willis, and providing the
love interest opposite Liv Tyler as Willis's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of rejoicing in taking the Hollywood plunge, Affleck is
a little worried about what he's getting into. ``It's a concern to
me, being cut off from real life,'' he says. ``I've seen it happen
to people's careers who I don't know really well, but I hear about
how their lives changed. You see their work and it becomes less and
less something you can relate to. It's less and less about real
life because you stop having real experiences to draw upon. It's a
real danger. In addition, it's a danger to your personality if
you're surrounded by people who just want to be around you for
sycophantic reasons or because they think it makes them look cool.
I realize in a poignant way that our world is only what's in our
immediate perception. And if that reality becomes corrupted, then
your perception of the world can be corrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   So Affleck has learned to soft-pedal exchanges like the one he
recently experienced at LA's Tower Records, when a guy came up to
him and told him, in effect, that the house where Affleck and Damon
and another roommate recently lived had become a Hollywood pop
shrine, on a par with the apartment where Quentin Tarantino wrote
``Pulp Fiction'' or the house where Sylvester Stallone wrote
``Rocky.'' A fabled site, in other words, where Hollywood lightning
struck and could rub off on other hopefuls if they stood there
soaking up success vibes.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum, ``Armageddon'' producer Jerry
Bruckheimer says, ```Good Will Hunting' wasn't out, but we'd seen
`Chasing Amy,' and thought he was very interesting. We tested him
in my office. Every secretary and assistant wanted to know who he
was, which reaffirmed my thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Affleck is sensitive enough and idealistic enough to
worry about his friendship with Damon being commercialized into a
commodity. Besides, he says, it doesn't reflect the current
reality. ``It's such a weird thing that the very same time that our
friendship became so public, we never spent any time together
because we were so busy working on different pictures, except for
`Dogma.' Before we were successful, we lived together and hung out
together with a bunch of other guys from Cambridge. Now that we're
busy, I don't see him enough. That's one of the things that make it
hard to keep writing. We're working on a new script, but `working'
is the operative word, and to say that it's unfinished is an
understatement. Ironically, the success of the first project is
what makes it difficult to actually do the same thing again. I
thought the whole point of being successful is that you get the
opportunity to keep doing it. I didn't think it would be as much a
preventative device as an opportunistic one.''
</P>
<P>
   All Affleck is prepared to say about the upcoming script is that
it will be a romantic comedy. ``I love working with my friends, and
it's good to actually have this happen to both of us at once
because then we can bounce the strangeness of it off someone that
it's also happening to. But sometimes, I gotta tell ya, it's
mind-bendingly bizarre what we're turned into. There's maybe a
danger in being seen as a kind of Frick and Frack, Heckle and
Jeckle kind of thing. Which is why we went out and did separate
stuff. Matt did `Saving Private Ryan.' I went and did `Shakespeare
in Love.' Then we did `Dogma,' I did this one, now I'm going off to
do a romantic comedy, very commercial, called `Force of Nature,'
with Sandra Bullock. And Matt is doing `The Talented Mr. Ripley.'
There's no shortage of people who want us to make another movie
together. But you know what? It took five years to make `Good Will
Hunting' happen, and I'm pretty sure the next one will happen in
less than five years.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1914 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-AFFLECK-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     06-29 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-AFFLECK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LOS ANGELES: ... five years.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love,'' still filming in London with a script
by Tom Stoppard, didn't yield the usual tidbits to the tabloid
press, partly because, Affleck says, he and his girlfriend, Gwyneth
Paltrow, don't have any scenes together. ``Joseph Fiennes, Ralph's
brother, plays Shakespeare, Judi Dench plays Queen Elizabeth,
Geoffrey Rush plays the play's producer, and Gwyneth plays the
woman he falls in love with. She disguises herself as a boy in
order to act because women weren't allowed onstage in Shakespeare's
day. The story is about Shakespeare getting writer's block as he's
writing `Romeo and Juliet.' I play this big star and I'm like a
huge pain. I have this enormous ego and I'm very demanding, but
Shakespeare has to have me in the play in order to get it produced.
He doesn't want to cast me as the lead, so instead he casts me as
Mercutio, and when I ask him what the name of the play is, he
thinks a minute and says, `Uh, ``Mercutio,''' and I say, `Oh, OK.'
It's like `Bullets Over Broadway,' except that it's `Swords Over
Shakespeare.'''
</P>
<P>
   Affleck's mother, Chris Affleck, and Damon's mother, Nancy
Carlsson-Paige, are both educators who work in Cambridge. Affleck,
who bought his mother a car from his ``Good Will Hunting'' payday,
still feels weirded out from his last visit home when he slept on
the fold-out sofa in her apartment. ``It's been really incredible
to go home and be totally thrown out of context. The people in
South Boston were very hospitable, showed us a lot of details, like
how people in Southie wore their pants as opposed to the way they
wore them in (Boston's Dorchester neighborhood). I haven't been
back to South Boston since we shot the movie. I wonder what it
would be like to walk down the street now. I kind of want to go
back to the L Street Bar. I'm glad South Boston will now be known
for something besides the busing crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cambridge, it's strange to be in places where you grew up
and you were always treated a certain way, like if you went to this
pizza place and they gave you a hard time. Now all of a sudden,
it's like the pizza's free and they want to take your picture and
put it on the wall. ... If we had any impact, I think it's because
Matt and I came across as guys, not, like, celebrities. ... I
didn't have a sense that we were the front-runners. I didn't dare
imagine it. When I heard my name, it was stunning and shocking and
overwhelming. I felt like dissociated from myself. It's like when
you get in a car accident and you feel you're watching yourself in
slow motion. It was that kind of feeling, but it was a good car
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   When he signed to do ``Armageddon,'' Affleck thought it would be
the movie that meant, for the first time, big exposure. ``But when
`Good Will Hunting,' came out and was so high-profile, it staved
off the questions of, like, who you are. At least going in I felt I
had some kind of credibility and didn't feel like a complete
impostor.'' Still, Affleck says, he initially stumbled over the
differences between this, his first big-budget production, and the
indepdendent films he had done. ``Coming from the `Star Wars'
generation, I always wanted to do one of these movies,'' Affleck
says, ``and I loved the chance of working with Billy Bob
(Thornton), Steve Buscemi, and Owen Wilson. ... Billy Bob is like
my hero, so rather than be obsequious about it, I had to try and
make fun of him. I would kid him about being a hillbilly with an IQ
of 30. But Billy Bob has a much crueler sense of humor than I do.
He got back at me by saying Matt and I were lovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was uncomfortable the first month and a half of the
shooting. We started in August, but Bruce (Willis) was still
filming `Mercury Rising' and couldn't show up until September. So
they did a lot with Peter Stormare (the Swedish actor plays a
Russian astronaut) and me on the Mir. We served essentially as the
guys on whom they tested the suits to see if they would be suitable
for movie-star wear, you know? Of course, they weren't, and they
had to make a bunch of modifications. Bruce was our leverage. We'd
say, `Bruce is going to go crazy if you keep it like this, so you
better fix it. We know you'll trot all over us, but Bruce will go
nuts.' Once he showed up, he was funny and self-deprecating and he
cared. Still, it was difficult for me to adjust. I felt intimidated
by the scope of the movie, and by the company I was keeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, the director (Michael May) was involved with the
pictures, making it look great. But the good news was that he'd let
you do your thing. Once I figured out that I had to draw a little
more broadly to compete with the kind of histri-onics and cacophony
that were going on, it became easy. ... At first, I felt like a
reject from `Lost in Space.' It was only because I had the luxury
of a long shoot that I had the chance to make some adjustments and
eventually grew comfortable and relaxed a little bit and became
ultimately proud of my performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Affleck laughs when asked if making a big studio film like
``Armageddon'' will cause him to be perceived as a sellout in
Cambridge. ``They already think we sold out with `Good Will
Hunting,''' he says. ``It can be very much the People's Republic. I
mean, Cambridge is a very interesting town with a lot of smart
people, but they don't necessarily understand exactly how this
particular business works. And it's a business like any other
business. You couldn't very well go into the shipping business
without dealing with UPS. I mean, big universities are corporate
entities. So ultimately, if you want to do some kind of
professional work, you end up in bed with large corporations. But
there's also a conservative kind of working-class sensibility in
Cambridge that doesn't say that you've gone and switched sides from
labor to capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Affleck, who keeps his Oscar on a bookshelf in his one-bedroom
digs, says his mother's well-documented wariness of Hollywood has
lessened. ``If anything, she's probably more resigned to the fact
that it's just gonna sort of happen and she's gonna let me do it. I
think she's less worried that I'm gonna end up panhandling and
brokenhearted. I think her chief concern was that I would get swept
away by Hollywood. Failure in this business can be very crushing
and debilitating and that's her concern. It's a concern I would
have about my kids. But I guess she feels like even if it all goes
downhill, I would have achieved some modicum of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I enjoyed about the Oscars is that I was able to
share it with her. It wasn't just my experience or my and Matt's
experience. Bringing our moms made it seem more real.... She met a
lot of people out there, but, you know, my mom is not star-struck.
She's star-struck by political people or activists. She spent most
of her time saying, `You know, I thought he was kind of sleazy.'
And I said, `Well, guess what, Mom? They're all sleazy. You're not
visiting a monastery. You're visiting, you know, Sodom and
Gomorrah. This is, uh, the sleaze center of the universe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
