<SLUG> BC-THIS-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURREAL VOYAGE TO `THIS WORLD' OF PERVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THIS WORLD, THEN THE FIREWORKS 
Directed by: Michael Oblowitz 
Screenplay by: Larry Gross, based on Jim Thompson's story 
Starring: Billy Zane, Gina Gershon, Sheryl Lee, Rue McClanahan,
Seymour Cassel, Will Patton, Richard Edson 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: R (strong violence, sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This World, Then the Fireworks'' is lurid and over the top,
even by Jim Thompson's standard. Michael Oblowitz's film
enthusiastically embraces Thompson's perverse story of murder,
brutality, incest, whoring, and lies that the spiritual father of
pulp fiction couldn't get published in his lifetime, even in
Playboy. The result is a heavily stylized and thoroughly surreal
excursion that makes truer contact with the amoral darkness of
Thompson's metaphysical world than several more technically
accomplished films have. It also knows its way around noir (see if
you can winkle out the homage to Dashiell Hammett in the name of a
murder victim).
</P>
<P>
   The film's very disjointedness seems an integral part of the
chaotic world prowled by a feline, predatory brother and sister
team. Their lives were defined when they were children in 1926 and
their father blew the head off a cuckolded husband after a July 4
celebration and was sent to the electric chair for it, trigger
finger and all. Thirty years later, the older brother _ played by
Billy Zane with a rancid cool that convinces us he's just barely
keeping the lid on his demons _ flees Chicago, where he has done
too good a job as a reporter exposing police corruption, and joins
his sister and mother in a seedy California coastal town.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a welcome sight to his mother, played by Rue
McClanahan with a whiny aspiration toward the respectability that
has so far eluded them. McClanahan's baleful look when he goes
upstairs to reunite with his sister says all that's needed. Gina
Gershon, continuing to inch her way back to credibility after
``Showgirls,'' delivers the film's most complex performance as a
tough survivor who has terrorized the local mob into allowing her
to operate as an independent prostitute, yet who also lives at home
and believes in family values, insofar as she can.
</P>
<P>
   The proof of the expertness with which the film threads its way
through Thompson's hellish parody of American values is that, by
the end, the incestuous brother-sister scam team turns out to be
the most innocent in the film. This is despite Zane's
enthusiastically callous abuse of a repressed and masochistic
policewoman all too eager to become his sex slave, and whose beach
house he covets. Sheryl Lee's resourcefully layered performance as
the willing victim is her best in some time. The film is a bit too
stylistically self-conscious to fully hand itself over to the
lunacy in the writing, but never so much so that it fails to apply
an ironic fillip to its gruesomeness. ``This World, Then the
Fireworks'' rises to Thompson's kinky depths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
