<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MCKENNITT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SECRETS OF LOREENA MCKENNITT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loreena McKennitt's star has been gently rising in the new-age
and world-music fields for more than a decade, to the point where
her albums have been turning gold in America, signifying sales of
500,000 copies, and selling well in other parts of the world. The
Canadian singer-songwriter-harpist, comfortable with both ancient
tribal instruments and computers, built her audience by increments,
via public radio airplay, song placement in movies and television
shows, word-of-mouth, reviews _ ``brick by brick,'' as she often
puts it.
</P>
<P>
   The steady trajectory of her sales spiked upward earlier this
year when a remix of her lilting song ``The Mummers' Dance'' was
given a modern-rock dance pulse by England's Nick Batt under his
moniker DNA. (He previously had done something similar for Suzanne
Vega and ``Tom's Diner.'') McKennitt didn't know much about the
remix game but asked that it satisfy her ``creative needs ...
retain the idiomatic bits.'' The surprise hit did for her what
``Orinoco Flow (Sail Away)'' did for Enya years ago. It swept
people away. And it gave her a vast crossover audience, boosting
the song's album, ``The Book of Secrets,'' to the platinum level (1
million sales).
</P>
<P>
   Which caused two problems.
</P>
<P>
   She worried some people might feel ``burned'' by hearing ``The
Mummers' Dance'' remix on radio, only to buy the album and find the
original, non-beat-and-synthesizer-inflected song. ``It almost
appeared to some (people) that they were duplicitously lured into
buying the CD,'' she says, ``and for some people ... the other
music was not their culture and they didn't even get the version of
`The Mummers' Dance' they heard on the radio. It's an example where
the industry can be rather callous with the public. And I'm quite
concerned how the industry is treating the public these days.''
</P>
<P>
   The other problem was the need to tour more extensively than
planned. Speaking recently from her office in Stratford, Ontario,
McKennitt admits she's glad she's finally finished touring,
sighing, ``I just kind of tuckered myself out.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ``The Mummers' Dance'' remix was released
commercially. At present, she is getting some rest, having a
semblance of a private life. ``It's starting, slowly,'' she says.
``What I call my private life means just being able to go to city
council meetings or go out to dinner with friends. Last week, I
went to a club in Toronto for the first time in three years. Last
night, I went to the theater for the first time in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   McKennitt, 41, works closely with her manager, and says they
sometimes disagree about the approach, the intensity, the balance
of work and downtime. Says the manager: ``She wants to do so many
things. Her mind never ceases. She has her own ideas and notions,
and, of course, she never accepts the conventional way of doing
things. I try to analyze when that's good and healthy and
appropriate and when it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, the manager is McKennitt. Yes, she answers, she does
drive herself crazy sometimes, sharing those two jobs. But wait,
there's more: McKennitt is also her own producer. She writes
detailed liner notes for her songs. (Somewhat ironically, in the
booklet accompanying ``The Book of Secrets'' she reveals many
secrets of her process.) She has two offices, one in Stratford near
her farmhouse home and one in London, and 12 full-time staffers.
The businesswoman part of her deals in ``budgets and timelines.''
</P>
<P>
   She's a musical anthropologist. When she does interviews in
countries where English is not the native language, she pays for a
translator. She thinks it's insulting to expect people in every
country to speak English. ``I just go, `The hell with it,''' says
McKennitt, which is about as profane as she gets, ``and spend my
own money and do it because it's proper.''
</P>
<P>
   What is she not? ``Some would say I'm a workaholic,'' McKennitt
says, ``and that can't be further from the truth. It doesn't take
me two seconds to change gear, and I'm always trying to find ways
of divesting myself of responsibility. But at the same time, I've
set a certain standard for myself and it does end up involving more
of my participation.''
</P>
<P>
   You can think of McKennitt as a Canadian Ani DiFranco, a prime
example of the DIY (do-it-yourself) mentality forged during the
early punk years and articulated by her pal Peter Gabriel in the
song ``D.I.Y.'' All of the work, of course, is done to better serve
the needs of the artist.
</P>
<P>
   The spectrum of today's pop music is as broad _ and as extreme _
as it's ever been. There's assaultive heavy metal, punk, and rap
out on one wing; the sort of music made by Enya, Brian Eno, Robert
Fripp, Dead Can Dance, and McKennitt out on another. This latter
style was pioneered by Fripp and Eno in the 1970s, but took hold in
a semi-commercial sense during the next decade with the music
recorded on England's 4 A.D. label, particularly that of the
Cocteau Twins and their spinoff This Mortal Coil.
</P>
<P>
   McKennitt creates gorgeous, ethereal, multi-layered musical
tapestries. She terms her style ``eclectic Celtic,'' for its Celtic
basis and its wide range of world-music influences: Middle Eastern,
Russian, music that sounds as if it sprang from the mystical Dark
Ages, music rooted in a time and place and yet beyond time and
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all pretty much created from my eclectic range of
interests and trying to re-articulate that within a music form,''
she says. ``Categorization is an unfortunate necessity that the
industry has gotten into for what I would like to think are the
most honorable reasons, to be helpful to the public. But it's been
taken far beyond a filing system _ nor does it reflect the
diversity or complexity of things going on. Even Celtic music, what
are we talking about? Is it the traditional repertoire or is it a
kind of music that is derivative of it? What about music with a
non-Celtic repertoire, but one with Celtic instruments? I think
what we're seeing _ and I would certainly put myself as a symptom
of it _ is that we're living in a time where affluence and
technology have allowed us to either physically travel or be
exposed to such a wide range of musical expressions, particularly
cultural or ethnic expressions.''
</P>
<P>
   Put another way: If you put Shane MacGowan &AMP; the Popes and
McKennitt in the same Celtic bin, you're talking about artists who
are worlds apart.
</P>
<P>
   McKennitt discusses music with a scholarly mien, as well as
considerable passion. But the woman who once hoped to be a
veterinarian and started her musical life as a folk singer never
graduated from high school. Rather, she has assumed control of her
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music and vehicles of my career have afforded me the
opportunity to go around studying various subjects and geographical
places that I would have been interested in anyway,'' she says,
``and then have forged that into a kind of personal document.'' Her
songs, she adds, feel to her like fictionalized travel writing,
which allows fans ``to vicariously plug in through this prism of
their own perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``The Book of Secrets,'' her journeys _ literally or
figuratively _ took her to Greece, Turkey, Italy, Siberia, England,
and, as always, to Ireland. She's used words by Tennyson and Yeats
and fashioned songs for them. On this latest album, she was
inspired by the writings of a sixth-century monk, by Alfred Noyes,
by Sufism, by Dante's ``The Divine Comedy.'' She integrates the
modern and the ancient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I feel like I'm a Luddite,'' McKennitt says, ``I'm
not frightened of the technology, but want to learn enough about it
to use it with discretion. I've always found synthesizers very cold
and crude, but at the same time if they're treated in a particular
way, blended, they're actually rather invisible, supporting other
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Like David Byrne, Paul Simon, and Peter Gabriel, she considers
it her joy and duty to explore other cultures. When she travels,
she keeps binders, recording what she hears and feels. It's to her
credit that there are few accusations of cultural larceny; she
makes the world's music her own. ``You're always to some degree an
outsider,'' she says, ``and there's danger in that because your
perceptions might be awry.''
</P>
<P>
   If McKennitt's music has a soothing, calming effect, she
understands. Still, she notes, the intent is more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music can be complex or it can be simple in its architecture,
its intent, its message, its personality, and its
characteristics,'' she says. ``I think that it's great music is so
versatile, there are so many forms, causes, so many feelings, and I
find it very interesting in the broader subject of the
psychological impact of sound ... similar to the psychology of
color. In that way, I can see there are many aspects to my music _
or more than one character _ but one of the characters I recognize
is that there are many poeple who find it soothing; (it works) for
those who are looking for the music to function and support their
mood in that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel there is a lot more than just providing a soothing
sound environment, which I feel is the primary mandate of new-age
music. It's not to provoke; it's not to disturb; it is there to
provide a pleasant environment that is not intrusive. I think there
is a place in the world for that kind of music and that kind of
sound. Where I get a bit concerned is having my music reduced to
just that function because there is a lot more going on in terms of
the subject matter and even the arrangement. It's not
(itals)necessarily(unitals) designed to be soothing. When I go into
the studio, it's not like: ``Oh, what can I play to be the most
soothing?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
