<HEADER>
A1925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DOWN-BOS &LR;      06-29 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING WRONG GOES RIGHT FOR PETER MCDONALD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``I Went Down,'' Peter McDonald plays a brooding introvert
who, in his own way, is eloquently inarticulate. Just released from
a Dublin prison for an unidentified petty crime, he finds himself
enmeshed in a group of low-life gangsters, setting off on a crazy
mission with a thug who fashions himself as an Irish John Wayne but
is really just another two-bit bungler. Throughout this wild
misadventure, McDonald walks tentatively and stares sullenly, but
beneath the steady, silent gaze of his emerald eyes, it's clear his
mind is always working, the brain muscles cranking complex thoughts
the character can't manage to express.
</P>
<P>
   When things go wrong, all he can manage to spit out is a certain
four-letter word that, in working-class Dublinese, almost rhymes
with ``talk.'' He says it a lot because things go wrong a lot. The
situation is hilariously absurd, but not to McDonald's character:
He's deadly serious, and that's why it's so funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing goes smoothly for these two guys,'' says McDonald, a
26-year-old Dublin native making his film debut in the independent
feature. ``They can't open doors. They can't steal a proper car.
They don't really know how to work guns. They make noise when they
shouldn't make noise. They always get it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But everything seems to be going right for McDonald, who is
poised at the beginning of what has the potential to be a brilliant
career. Just four years ago, he was a student acting in the Drama
Society at University College Dublin, and until he was cast as Git
in ``I Went Down,'' he was performing in &QC; 
pubs with Fly By Night Productions, a theater company he started
with several college mates including playwright Conor McPherson.
The only thing fly-by-night about the troupe, however, is its name.
McPherson, who wrote the screenplay for ``I Went Down,'' will make
his Broadway debut this year with his acclaimed play, ``The Weir.''
Another company member is now an assistant director at Dublin's
Abbey Theatre. McDonald is signed up for other films, including the
screen version of McPherson's play ``The Lime Tree Bower.''
</P>
<P>
   There's something refreshing about the actor at this incipient
stage: He exudes a natural confidence that isn't cocky. He's hardly
the reticent naif he plays on screen; he chats easily, with calm
self-assurance and unaffected warmth. But this is also a man who is
all too conscious that marketing is part of the business, and
marketing he does on a recent visit to Boston. And he does it well.
The award-winning independent film opens Wednesday, and it's
literally up against the end of the world, as in ``Armageddon,''
the big-bang flick with the big-bucks marketing budget.
</P>
<P>
   ```Armageddon' has so much screen space and such overpowering
marketing that people are going to see it,'' McDonald says. ``We're
going out with 100 prints or something for starters, and it's our
job to let people know that if they come to see it, they're going
to have a good time. It mixes art house and entertainment, that's
the point we're trying to make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I Went Down,'' which was shot in 35 days on a budget just
under $3 million, has a wacky sensibility; it crosses genres faster
than you can cross a Boston street. It's part Western, part buddy
film, part gangster flick, part adventure story. McDonald's
onscreen cohort, played by Brendan Gleeson, is a gangster-wannabe
who reads cowboy novels and munches chocolates while he should be
paying attention to the task at hand. The two characters bicker
constantly over trivial issues, but their bond solidifies
organically.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald says the relationship grew out of a deadly-serious
approach to acting. ``We didn't corpse while we were on the set,''
he says, explaining that ``to corpse'' means to make each other
crack up. ``We knew that we had to play it totally straight,
because if we were trying to achieve comic performances, it would
go over the top and backfire. These characters are oblivious to the
fact that any of this might be funny. They straddle seriousness and
situation comedy just naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   The film attempts to do that, too, at every step of the game. It
is broken up by subtitles out of an old melodrama; it opens with a
quote from Plato's ``Republic'' that includes the title phrase ``I
Went Down,'' which has multiple meanings here. McDonald's character
``went down'' _ that is, he went to prison for a crime he didn't
commit. But in the end, Plato's lofty reference fades to a lewd
joke, based on the more vernacular meaning of the term. ``At the
end of this rough-and-tumble journey, the title is taken to a
different place, if you know what I mean,'' McDonald explains. We
know what he means.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's own journey has been the storybook actor's tale.
Growing up in Dublin, he made his stage debut as one of the Three
Kings in a Nativity play; he always felt the urge to act, and it
became stronger when he went to college. His mother, Brenda
Costigan, is a ``cookery writer'' for an Irish newspaper _ ``I do
try to get home on a Sunday'' for the traditional family meal, he
says. His father, Richard McDonald, had a business selling baler
twine and rope. &UR;  &LR; There were no actors in his immediate family,
although he has an auntie-in-law who is a performer.
</P>
<P>
   He came of age at a time when Ireland was experiencing economic
prosperity for the first time in decades; the old, repressed ways
of the past were fading, especially in the cosmopolitan centers.
``There was a sense of opportunity and more confidence in the
country,'' he says. ``It was a good time to grow up in Dublin.''
</P>
<P>
   His generation was weaned on American film and television, and
there is nothing tweedy or quaint about McDonald and his fellow
filmmakers. ``I Went Down,'' McDonald says, consciously avoids all
the cliches associated with Oirish films. It's not about Catholic
guilt; it's not about the Troubles; and there's not a saintly Irish
mother or a priest in the plot. Plus, it's shot in the flat peat
bogs of the Midlands: Director Paddy Breathnach deliberately didn't
trot cast and crew out to Yeats territory, with all those gorgeous
yet familiar scenes of rolling green pastures shot in the Celtic
twilight. ``The middle of our country is a great location, but no
one films there,'' McDonald says. ``One day we shot and the sun was
streaming through, and the peat almost looked red; it looked like
Arizona. We went back another day and got clouds, and it looked
like the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald himself is more influenced by the call of America,
though, than the pull of the moon. Like many of his fellow young
citizens, he spent four months in San Francisco on what's called a
J-1 visa, which allows Irish students to come to the United States
to work, have a grand old time, and sometimes camp out with
long-lost cousins. He traveled a bit while he was living here and
has a particular affinity for the American South. He's proud of his
ability to put on an American accent: ``It all depends on where you
wanna go, girl,'' he says, demonstrating a twangy voice that is
part Bill Clinton, part Jed Clampett.
</P>
<P>
   But his tastes run more to independent art films than to
situation comedies. He admires films like Steve Buscemi's ``Trees
Lounge,'' Stanley Tucci's ``Big Night,'' and Alan Taylor's
``Palookaville.'' He lists the Coen brothers and Ang Lee as his
favorite filmmakers. But during this marketing tour, he'd prefer to
remain on the qt about one Quentin Tarantino; he flinches at any
attempt to compare ``I Went Down'' with ``Pulp Fiction,'' even
though they both explore the buddy relationships of quarrelsome
hired guns. ``I think Tarantino is very good, but we're very
conscious that this film is not associated with his name,''
McDonald says politely. ``I don't think it's a reference point.
Ta-rantino puts genre characters in front of you, whereas in `I
Went Down,' the characters only think of themselves as genre
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reference points, the statistics are already
impressive. ``I Went Down'' is the highest-grossing independent
Irish film in history, and it won four awards at the 1997 San
Sebastian Film Festival. McDonald is hoping for similar acclaim
here, but that's not to say he's salivating at the chance for Matt
Damon-esque fame. ``I'm not in it to become a star,'' he says.
``I'm well aware that I could become ...'' He pauses, briefly.
``I'm well aware that I've achieved a certain amount of fame at
home, and that's one of the prices you pay to have clout as an
actor. The more people see your work, the more people will want to
see it again. But if you're going around acting like you're some
new big thing, it will come back to you. Plus, I haven't felt any
serious sense of fame at all. People don't bother you much in
Dublin,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, he hopes he can continue to straddle the worlds
of film and theater gracefully. A role on Broadway would be a good
thing, preferably in one of McPherson's plays. After all, in the
end of ``I Went Down,'' two of the characters do head off to the
States. ``It was a running joke on the set that if there is a
sequel, it would be called `And While You're Down There,''' he
says. ``We used to say that when (one of the characters) gets over
to America, he sets up a chipper _ you know, a fish and chip shop _
in New York or somewhere. And then some gangster comes in to try to
extort money and the whole adventure begins again.'' McDonald
laughs, heartily. Now that would be good fun. ``But,'' he adds,
``there's no talk of a sequel.'' Not yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
