<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-MARKETING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSE SHAVE: GILLETTE GEARS UP TO LAUNCH ITS FUTURISTIC RAZOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a friendly warning. We thought you might like to brace
yourself for what's to come: the Mach 3.
</P>
<P>
   We will be bombarded by an all-out media blitz for the new razor
in the weeks to come. It will be unavoidable, with images of Top
Gun-style fighter jets and their macho pilots pushing a product
that belongs in medicine chests.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, which is to razors what Bill Gates' Microsoft is to
computer software, has vowed to flood the marketplace with the Mach
3 beginning in July.
</P>
<P>
   The company did not give birth to the first three-blade razor
without some serious labor pains. Almost a billion dollars worth of
labor pains.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, the one that promises to be painful to anyone
with symptoms of TV commercial-intolerance, is the $300 million
advertising deluge that will be upon us throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   Most men may not believe their shaving routine needs
fine-tuning. Every morning we shower and shave, if we shave at all,
without giving much thought to either activity.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you're already using a Gillette product, most likely
the Sensor or Sensor Excel if you are given to permanent-handle
products.
</P>
<P>
   Even Benedetto Fusco, a barber in Schenectady, N.Y., since 1954
and a man who prefers the long-handled straight razor, admits to
using a Gillette at home. Why? Because it's convenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are in a hurry you don't want to use a straight
razor. You might take a piece of skin off if you do,'' Fusco said.
``With a Gillette you can go fast. You may have to go over lots of
areas two and three times, but you can go fast.'' Fusco figures he
belongs to the last of a breed, barbers who still offer
straight-edge razor shaves. There are fewer requests for them every
day, but Fusco doesn't think it's the $6 fee that makes men shy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has changed and the straight razor is like an
antique,'' he mused. ``We've got too many people in a hurry, too
many people who don't know what a really good shave is like.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as he's concerned, a good shave cannot be had with a twin
or triple-blade razor, not to mention a disposable product.
Observed Fusco, ``There's no comparison, none whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, the company whose patented slogan is ``the best a man
can get,'' so dominates the wet-shave industry it's a surprise the
competition isn't crying foul.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Boston, Gillette reported $2.9 billion in blades and
razors sales for 1997, earning $1.2 billion profit on them. Schick,
with $739 million in sales last year, is No. 2 and not gaining
ground. Schick is a division of the Morris Plains, N.J.-based
Warner-Lambert Co.
</P>
<P>
   In a fawning story about Gillette and the Mach 3 in the June 15
New Yorker, business writer James Surowiecki writes, ``shaving has
become perhaps the only business in the world where the most
popular product is also the best: Gillette is simultaneously the
Porsche and the General Motors of shaving.''
</P>
<P>
   If the company's predictions are on target, by the turn of the
century the high-tech Mach 3 (Gillette's design team was required
to watch ``Terminator 2'' to get the look just right) will be the
most popular razor in the country and Americans will be buying 1.2
billion Mach 3 blades a year.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of razors, as well as a lot of greenbacks, for a
blue-chip company.
</P>
<P>
   The Mach 3 is the result of seven years of research and
development, a product the company started working on almost as
soon as it introduced the Sensor in 1989. The Sensor, the first
razor with twin blades individually mounted on responsive springs
that continuously sense and automatically adjust to the face, and
its upgraded sister product, the Sensor Excel, are the most popular
razors in Gillette's history.
</P>
<P>
   But they failed to take blade technology to the next level,
employing the same twin-blade setup that the company debuted in
1971 with the Trac II. Then the R&AMP;D folks came up with a
three-blade concept employing a new substance called diamond-like
carbon, DLC.
</P>
<P>
   This new product comes with a new price, of course. The Mach 3
razor set will retail for approximately $6.50, with a four-pack of
replacement blades, or cartridges, setting you back another $6.50.
By comparison, a Sensor Excel costs $4.49 and 10 cartridges sell
for just under $10.
</P>
<P>
   Schick's top product, the Protector featuring a pivoting blade,
costs $5.39 and $5.99 for five refill blades.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the Mach 3 to truly dominate the men's shaving market, it
must also make inroads on the disposable blades. More than half the
people who use razors buy disposables, according to a Consumer
Reports study two years ago. Disposables, while less ecologically
sound, cost between 20 to 50 cents each, and there's no blade to
pop in when the razor gets dull.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette is a viable competitor with its Custom Plus and Good
News disposables, but Schick, Bic and even drugstore brands are
priced lower than Gillette's disposables.
</P>
<P>
   If quality influences choice, though, more men will be turning
to cartridge razors. The Consumer Reports survey, which measured
razors for closeness, cuts, drag (how easily the blade glides over
the skin) and ease of use, found that overall men thought cartridge
razors performed better than disposables, that they gave a closer
shave and were easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   And the top two rated razors? Gillette's Sensor Excel and
Sensor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the Mach 3 makes its debut, the Gillette
braintrust is busy trying to come up with the company's first new
razor of the next millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
