   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA-MAIN _ BEIJING _ At the Beijing train station
Monday morning people were playing pool, tending fussy kids, buying
snacks. And a few dozen followed a very abnormal pursuit, listening
raptly to President Clinton talk about freedom and democracy. What
they and potentially half a billion other Chinese heard was
Clinton's unprecedented argument on behalf of freedoms never
enjoyed here and change that is seldon even whispered about today.
Some Chinese enthused. Many thought Clinton was meddling. But even
among those, thoughts lingered that some good might come of his
words. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA-SHANGHAI _ SHANGHAI _ Clinton talks about China in
the 21st Century. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Clinton is not expected to begin speaking until almost 10
p.m. EDT. Story will move when he concludes.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA-HONGKONG _ For many Chinese, President Clinton's
meanderings around Shanghai Wednesday will be eclipsed by a daylong
gala here marking the first anniversary of Hong Kong's return from
British colonial rule. Clinton's decision to bypass the anniversary
of the handover of Hong Kong _ a celebration he reportedly was
entreated to attend _ denied China a gazzling public relations
ornament to perk up recession-racked Hong Kong's spirits. (Kunstel,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HISTBOX _ Hong Kong history. (Albright, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-FIRES _ Vice President Al Gore headed to fire-scorched
Florida with the promise of more federal aid and attention, but the
vice president can't bring what residents here need most _ rain.
Scattered thunderstorms were predicted for this afternoon, but
officials said it wouldn't be enough to douse flames and ease the
threat of more fires. (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA:
8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MLK _ Janet Reno is expected to announce a limited
re-investigation of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s assassination.
(Brice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-EDUCATION _ The South is making steady progress in a
number of areas of education, but is still clearly behind other
states in the nation, according to a report by the Southern
Regional Education Board released Monday. Georgia is in the middle-
to upper portion of southern states on 11 benchmarks that include
children in pre-k, immunizations, dropout rates and National
Assessment of Education Progress tests. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HIGHWAYS _ Now that there's a new transportation bill that
brings lots of extra money to Texas, what should the state do about
priorities? Senator Phil Gramm meets with Texas Transportation
Commission Chairman David Laney and other transportation leaders to
talk about what the state needs to do. This develops from a 12:30
p.m. meeting/press conference. (Hiott, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
