<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-RENTALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAND HILL ROAD, THE NEW CORPORATE ADDRESS OF CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's a distinction that will make businesses
cringe and landlords rejoice. A portion of the San Francisco Bay
area has edged out New York City for having the most expensive
office space in the country, according to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
   The highest of the high-rent honors goes not to downtown San
Francisco, but to a half-mile strip of Sand Hill Road in Menlo Park
that has become the pricey capital of venture capital. The survey
quotes rents in that area reaching $70 per square foot, higher than
the most exclusive towers of Midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists ``all want to be within walking distance of
each other, and that little stretch of Sand Hill Road is where
you've got to be,'' said Richard Podos, vice president of New
York-based Equis Corp., the real estate services company that
conducted the research.
</P>
<P>
   New York City received the top spot in the previous two years of
the survey. Podos attributed Menlo Park's new ranking to the
booming high-technology industry and the desire of venture
capitalists to stick close together to be near Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the companies that occupy the estimated 600,000 square
feet of office space on Sand Hill Road include investment firm
Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts &AMP; Co.; Goldman Sachs; venture capitalists
VC Institutional Venture Partners; Kleiner Perkins Caufield and
Byers and Venture Law Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are ascribing a lot of prestige to that address,
and they're willing to pay for it,'' said Larry Hendrix, a senior
vice president in Equis' office in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate officials were not surprised by the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Peninsula has been the tightest office market in the
country, and it has been for the past couple of years,'' said Kurt
Houtkooper, a broker with Grubb &AMP; Ellis Commercial Real Estate in
San Francisco. ``(Venture capitalists) have the money to pay the
high rents.''
</P>
<P>
   While real estate experts say the buildings are fairly modest,
the cachet of the address has gained national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across the country, if you say you're on Sand Hill Road,
people know where you are, and they know what that means,'' said
Monica Finnegan, senior vice president and managing director of CB
Richard Ellis, a commercial real estate company in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Bay area, on average, is still considered more
affordable than New York City.
</P>
<P>
   According to Equis, 15 midtown Manhattan properties are going
for more than $60 per square foot, and eight of those are asking
more than $65.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
