<SLUG> BC-HUTCHESON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLINT STRIKE NOT A MATTER OF SIMPLE ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Having spent the better part of a week with the
folks on the picket line in Flint, Mich., it comes as no surprise
to me that the strike against General Motors shows no signs of
ending.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the kind of dispute that can be settled by splitting
the difference. It isn't about money. It isn't about benefits. It's
a fight over big issues, issues like: Where do U.S. factory workers
fit in the global marketplace? Can U.S. companies stay competitive
and stay in the United States? Do companies have a moral obligation
to remain in company towns that they have helped create?
</P>
<P>
   As the birthplace of both GM and the United Auto Workers union,
Flint has been dealing with these issues for at least 20 years. But
the passage of time has only increased the desperation on both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   GM, which has eliminated about 44,000 jobs in the city, is still
struggling to cut costs and boost productivity. The workers, who
believe that they have done their share to help the company, feel
as vulnerable as ever. They are not trying to hold on to the past _
they are just trying to hold on to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the strikes by 9,200 workers at two Flint parts
plants have idled nearly 150,000 other GM employees. The list of
innocent victims includes about 1,400 at the GM assembly plant in
Arlington, Texas, which needs parts from Flint to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the striking workers are quick to concede that they have
to adapt to the new realities of global trade. Just as GM doesn't
make your father's Oldsmobile anymore, the UAW doesn't turn out
your father's assembly worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that times have changed. We need to be
competitive,'' one 12-year plant veteran told me. ``It's a two-way
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone shares the we're-all-in-this-together
attitude. Every workplace has malcontents who have nothing but
complaints about the organization that pays their salary. Flint
worker Kim McKinnis suggested that GM executives should be
subjected to Nuremberg-type trials for ```crimes against the
American people.'' He said that free-traders in Washington should
be carried away in shackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that sounds radical,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, maybe a little.
</P>
<P>
   Striker Chris Szafran showed up on the picket line wearing a
10-year-old T-shirt from a previous dispute with GM. ``I'm about to
develop an attitude,'' the shirt announced. ``Enough is enough.''
Szafran, who has worked at GM for 21 years, said he votes to strike
every chance he gets.
</P>
<P>
   But McKinnis and Szafran were the exceptions. The vast majority
of the workers I met realize that their future is inextricably
linked to GM's. They know that if GM can't compete, they won't have
jobs. At the same time, they fear that nothing they do will stop GM
from seeking cheaper workers in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an irrational fear. GM already operates nearly three
dozen foreign plants, and no one expects that trend to turn around
soon. In a vivid example of how little national borders matter in
the global marketplace, the Flint strikes have triggered more than
25,000 layoffs in Mexico. About 240 workers were sent home in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The sad truth is, stopping the flow of jobs out of Flint may be
like trying to stop a tidal wave. A debilitating strike doesn't
help.
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Hutcheson is chief of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's
Washington bureau. You can e-mail him at
rhutcheson(at)krwashington.com or call him at (202) 383-6101. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
