<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1973 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     06-29 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK CAREFULLY ABOUT CHINA, TRADE AND HUMAN RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The frantic haste of President Clinton's detractors to attack
everything he says or does is trivializing what ought to be a
serious discussion concerning our relations with China. The
suggestion that the American president has sneaked military secrets
to the communist nation in exchange for election-year contributions
is ridiculous, bordering on paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   And the insistence that Clinton should not set foot anywhere
near Tiananmen Square would be like a foreign president's shunning
a White House reception because it's adjacent to the Mall where
Army troops once clubbed and dispersed peaceful bonus marchers.
Such distractions obscure several consequential questions on which
a public dialogue ought to focus. Here are a few:
</P>
<P>
   What responsibilities do we have for domestic policies of
political leaders in countries with which we trade? Is
international trade principally a matter of commerce, undertaken
for financial return, or is it a means for conferring political
approval upon nations with which we feel an ideological affinity?
Is trade something we encourage for mutual economic benefit, or a
carrot to induce compliance by others with our political
principles?
</P>
<P>
   Some well-meaning people want Clinton to begin by giving China a
strong tongue-lashing to prove his own bona fides as a champion of
human rights. State Department spokesmen respond that constructive
engagement is more effective than lectures. They point to the
patient conversion of South Africa, once an international pariah
for its history of human-rights abuses. Several points need
mentioning in this regard.
</P>
<P>
   As ardently as we wish to bring others around to our way of
thinking on questions of individual rights, there is a realistic
limit to how swiftly we can influence fundamental change when it
runs contrary to entrenched traditions. China is the world's
largest nation, maybe the oldest; it is conscious of its power and
jealous of its sovereign prerogatives. From 1949 to 1973, it lived
within walls of self-imposed isolation, impenetrable as those
physical walls that its ancestors built in the third century B.C.
</P>
<P>
   China has been changing for the better _ not as fast as we'd
like, but faster than some Chinese find comfortable. Its official
attitude toward our country has improved greatly. Chinese leaders
acted responsibly to help ease the Asian financial crisis, and
recently to help calm nuclear passions in India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts think we rushed the Soviet Union into a too-quick
transition to free-market capitalism from a totally state-managed
economy. Mikhail Gorbachev argued for a more gradual
transformation, but tides of change swept swiftly over Russia, with
mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   These have included steep increases in prostitution and black
marketeering, as well as ruinous interest rates that stifle
individual enterprise in its crib and bleed the public treasury.
The six-month bond rate jumped to 72 percent this month. Markets
are freer, but it's an open question whether Russia is better off
financially.
</P>
<P>
   The principal purpose of a trade agreement is economic, not
political. Asked privately why Clinton would promote free trade
with China but not with Cuba, a White House spokesman answered
matter-of-factly, ``I can think of at least a billion reasons.''
Each is a potential customer. China could become the world's
biggest market. With one-fifth of the world's people, it makes
American exporters salivate at the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   But, obviously, people can't buy goods without money. The
average Chinese lives on cents, not dollars, a day. He'll be a
customer only when he has a job that pays him a living wage. In the
past, some investors in China have engaged prison labor through the
government. Others have sold goods on our markets made by Chinese
labor at daily wages as low as 50 cents. If Clinton's negotiators
approve trade of this type, they'll be selling out the American
working family.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cherished human rights is the right to a livable wage.
On that question, American interests are clearly at stake. The
quality of Clinton's statesmanship may be measured by the level at
which he draws the line against Asian goods produced by
destructively low wages.
</P>
<P>
   Another point concerning human rights is our own continuing need
to set an example. We are the self-professed light on the hill. Our
country began as a haven and refuge from persecution. Here, we
declared that all were created equal and endowed with inalienable
rights. We engraved the most basic of these rights into our
Constitution as its first 10 amendments before ratifying it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for 80 years thereafter, we tolerated slavery while
virtually exterminating American Indians. We experienced the Alien
and Sedition laws, the Ku Klux Klan, the arbitrary imprisonment of
American citizens solely because of their Japanese ancestry, and
the ignominious phenomenon of McCarthyism.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom is not free, or necessarily self-perpetuating. Its
premiums must be kept up-to-date. Our country, made up of fallible
human creatures, must continuously guard against temptations of
self-interest, unreasoning hysteria, self-righteousness, or
political ambitions that would lead us astray from the
constitutional liberties we publicly espouse.
</P>
<P>
   Prejudice is a powerful and pernicious vice, the more so when it
wears the clever disguise of patriotism or religion. We cannot
always rely solely upon elected officials to protect us from it.
However brave and enlightened, they're occasionally tempted to the
sin of silence when speaking out seems an instrument of political
suicide. If we love liberty, we must guard it zealously for the
most unattractive, unpopular minorities among us.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth, a Democrat, is a former speaker of
the U.S. House of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box
1413, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
