<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN30-COX     06-29 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Telling the stories one more time
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could have called it a convention of storytellers. It
actually was my parents' 50th wedding anniversary party.
</P>
<P>
   I love hearing stories. I grews up on them. One of my favorite
pastimes as a young girl was to spend the night with my
grandmother, MeMe. As I snuggled into bed beside her, enveloped by
the heady aroma of Avon night cream, I'd beg her, ``MeMe, tell me
the story about the time you put Uncle Frank into the rain barrel
to bring his fever down ...'' ``Tell me about the time you walked
to school through the woods and a wolf chased you ...''
</P>
<P>
   MeMe was an ace storyteller. It was a trait she passed on to her
son, my father.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy is renowned for his storytelling. He's also renowned for
never letting the truth slow down a good yarn. As he often says,
``If I forget a fact or two, well, I just smooth right over it and
nobody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows, and nobody cares. It's an art, and Dad has
perfected it.
</P>
<P>
   At my parents' anniversary party, the room was filled with their
cohorts and partners in jest from the last 50 years. Men with whom
Dad had been boyhood friends recalled childhood pranks,
coming-of-age stories, first loves and last loves.
</P>
<P>
   Laughter ricocheted off the walls of that room for a solid two
hours as stories were shared one more time. I would have given
anything to hear each one of them. Back-slapping and knee-slapping
were the order of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The stories were more than a remembrance of good times. They
were a testament to lives well-lived. These are people who had
great fun, did outrageous things, took chances. They had pulled
pranks, concocted elaborate jokes, waited patiently for the right
opportunity to good-naturedly sucker in a pal. They made memories
that lived through the decades.
</P>
<P>
   As I moved throughout that room at the party, I found myself
wondering, ``What stories will I remember at my 50th anniversary
party? How am I spending my days, and will any of them be worth
recalling after 50 years of marriage? Am I having fun? Am I
creating wonderful memories with friends and family and
neighbors?''
</P>
<P>
   My folks lived all those years in a rural community, which by
its nature pulled folks together. They worshiped in the same small
country church, went to the same PTA and 4-H gatherings, the same
elementary school Christmas plays, the same Saturday night VFW
dances.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of us live isolated lives in urban societies,
sequestered behind shut doors and windows in air-conditioned homes,
offices and schools. We pop out just long enough to pop into a car
and busily go on our way. Little time is allotted for lingering,
loitering or lounging _ and even less time, I fear, for making
memories. Or telling stories.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 people attended my parents' open house, and each
one came with a story or a recollection. Each one in some way had
been touched or enlivened by my parents and had come to pay respect
and to celebrate knowing them. As their daughter, I felt incredibly
blessed to see this outpouring of love for two people I hold so
dear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember when we hot-wired the passenger seat of your '40 Ford
and gave the high school principal a good jolt?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Duke, now there was a hunting dog _ always hunting for a
nice, quiet place to take a nap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember when we sprinkled black gunpowder into Old Man
Smith's pipe tobacco? He got a charge out of that one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that fishing trip to Canada? We all slept in that
little camper in the middle of the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   While we were busily recording the memories of that anniversary
party on videotape, my parents were replaying memories recorded in
their minds and hearts. The stories of a lifetime. A wonderful
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
