<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2022 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-29 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSE A NAME DROPPER OR A TICKET DODGER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the all-important race for Texas lieutenant
governor, it has become obvious that voters will have to choose
between a name dropper and a ticket dodger.
</P>
<P>
   School administrators who heard from both candidates at an
Austin conference last week surely must have noticed the difference
in approach between Republican Rick Perry and Democrat John Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Perry mentioned Gov. George W. Bush's name three or four times
in his 20-minute speech, not-so-subtly reminding everyone that he
is a Republican eager _ as are other GOP nominees _ to cash in on
the governor's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week we were in Washington, D.C., with Gov. Bush. I had
the great honor for him to introduce me,'' Perry began.
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea, and, Perry hoped, so did his audience.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, by contrast, avoided partisan references and never even
hinted at the name of the gubernatorial nominee at the top of the
Democratic slate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats pooh-pooh polls showing Bush with as much as a
53-point lead over challenger Garry Mauro, and everyone knows the
chasm will narrow before election day.
</P>
<P>
   But a conservative-to-moderate Democrat like Sharp, who is still
competitive in what many expect to be a strong Republican year,
dares not wave the Democratic banner too boldly. Sharp has refused
to endorse Mauro or any other statewide Democratic candidate. He is
too busy running his own campaign, he says.
</P>
<P>
   This is a different year, Sharp senses, than when he won three
previous statewide elections for the Railroad Commission and state
comptroller as a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp and other Democrats blasted the recent Scripps Howard
Texas Poll, which not only showed a huge lead for Bush over Mauro
and leads for most other Republican statewide candidates but also
indicated Sharp's support for lieutenant governor among likely
voters had plunged 10 percentage points since March.
</P>
<P>
   The race between Sharp and Perry, according to the survey, is a
toss-up with about one-third of likely voters undecided. But the
poll leaves the strong impression that Sharp is slipping, a message
that could discourage would-be financial contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the survey was flawed because Democrats were
underrepresented in the polling sample. It remains to be seen
whether that was a polling glitch or simply a sad (for the
Democrats) sign of the times. But the Sharp campaign drew
encouragement from another result of the same poll, which showed
the Democratic candidate leading Perry among independent voters, 30
percent to 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Independents, who accounted for 26 percent of the polling
sample, will decide the lieutenant governor's race, as they do most
statewide races. And according to the survey, 43 percent of them
were undecided between Sharp and Perry, the current state
agriculture commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to school administrators, Sharp called for the
state to spend part of its tobacco settlement money to build new
classrooms and the Legislature to find new ways to soften the blow
of the Robin Hood school finance law, issues close to home for most
school leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Perry advocated two of Bush's priorities, a greater emphasis on
teaching reading in the public schools and a pilot voucher program
that would let students in low performing schools transfer to other
public or private schools and use tax dollars for tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Bush strongly supports Perry and not just because Perry is the
Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp once considered challenging Bush for re-election, and 10
years ago he was Texas chairman of Democrat Michael Dukakis'
presidential campaign against the governor's father, then-Vice
President George Bush, and said a couple of tacky things about the
elder Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that the governor's father has starred at two Perry
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   As presiding officer of the Texas Senate, the lieutenant
governor has a major role in the state's lawmaking process.
</P>
<P>
   Should the younger Bush win re-election and then follow in his
father's footsteps and get promoted to the White House _ a race the
governor is expected to make in 2000 _ the Sharp-Perry race will
become even more important.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will become the next governor.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sharp is keeping his distance from his ticket leader,
he isn't abandoning the Democratic Party altogether. He has been
endorsed by key Democratic constituencies, including organized
labor and minority groups, and is hoping for Democrats' grassroots
support.
</P>
<P>
   And Sharp prominently features on campaign literature the name
of his honorary campaign chairman, the state's top elected Democrat
and current lieutenant governor, Bob Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, who isn't seeking re-election, is backing Sharp to
succeed him. But Bullock, in another signal of distress for the
Democrats, has endorsed Bush in the governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
