<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2024 &Cx1f; tad-z
a t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-ASIA-TRAVEL     06-29 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-ASIA-TRAVEL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THOUGHT A TRIP TO ASIA WAS WELL OUT OF YOUR BUDGET? WELL, THINK
AGAIN
 &HT;    With ASIA-TRAVEL-BOX.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, July 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It wasn't just the country's exotic flavor _
Bangkok's snake farms or elephant riding in Chiang Mai _ that
attracted Eric Pipkorn to Thailand. It was also the price.
</P>
<P>
   Pipkorn, of Atlanta, snatched up a package deal that included
roundtrip airfare, hotel costs and a day trip to Laos. The cost for
the weeklong trip? Just over $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we saw the package, we decided to go,'' said Pipkorn, who
went with his wife to the southeast Asian country last month.
``Normally, it costs that much just to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocked by a debilitating financial crisis that has plagued the
region since last fall, travel and booking agents on both sides of
the Pacific Ocean are scrambling to attract U.S. travelers by
slashing prices on airfares, hotel rooms and tour packages to just
about anywhere in southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in two more recent , yet memorable events _ a bloody
uprising that led to the downfall of Indonesia President Suharto
and a thermonuclear tit-for-tat between India and Pakistan _ and
some of these agents sound downright desperate as they look to U.S.
travelers to rejuvenate hurting Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, contrary to some earlier forecasts that the region
would have rebounded by now, currencies continue to lose value.
Since mid-June of last year, for example, the Thai baht has lost 72
percent of its value against the dollar. The Philippine peso and
Malaysian ringgit are down 55 percent and 57 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   What started with the collapse of the Thai baht last summer has
spread to other Asian countries ``like the flu,'' said Dan Dabney,
a professor of economics at the University of Texas in Austin. The
International Monetary Fund, which stepped in to stabilize the
economic decline, ``acted too little and too late,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the bargains are not limited to southeast Asia. In
Australia, where the currency has tumbled to a 12-year low, travel
providers are looking to fill up half-empty planes and hotels. In
the past, they would have been full of Asian travelers.
</P>
<P>
   But what's been summarily bad for southeast Asia has in turn
become a major savings boon for U.S. travelers _ particularly those
going to Thailand, Malaysia and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia is not seen as a once-in-a-lifetime destination
anymore,'' said Cynthia Scott Severns, spokeswoman for Northwest
WorldVacations.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she said a four-night travel package in July and August
leaving from Atlanta to Bangkok _ including air, hotel and a
sightseeing tour _ would cost $855 per person. Last year's price:
$1,240.
</P>
<P>
   Similar savings abound. A five-night package to Singapore
departing from Austin _ including hotel, roundtrip transfers, and a
half-day city tour _ will cost $1,009 beginning this September.
Last year the trip would have cost $1,499, according to United
Vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Travel and booking agents also are tossing in extra incentives,
ranging from free meals to permitting an extra piece of luggage on
the way home to allow for shopping excursions.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one example: roundtrip airfare to Malaysia at $950 is
already 30 percent off from last year, according to World
Connections Travel of Atlanta. But toss in five free nights of
hotel accommodations, and you can see why the operating words for
agents when it comes to the depressed region are ``sell'' and
``market.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the countries and cities are getting into the act, say
industry spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Hong Kong: City of Life,'' is the slogan of a campaign
launched by the Hong Kong Tourist Association this month to spark
interest in visiting the Special Administrative Region (SAR), as it
has become known.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Hong Kong's currency is pegged to the U.S.
dollar _ which provided some immunity to the continuing regionwide
devaluations _ the SAR has suffered a severe decline since the
Chinese handover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The successful transition of Chinese sovereignty has taken
Hong Kong out of the world media headlines and away from its
leading position in potential traveler's minds,'' said Lily Shum,
HKTA regional director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reactivate consumer interest globally and convert
that interest into firm travel plans for 1998,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So travel providers are cutting prices on hotel rooms and
airfare to Hong Kong. A roundtrip ticket there via Japan Airlines
from Atlanta is $800 _ 30 percent less than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers will also find terrific deals when shopping in Hong
Kong, where merchandise has been slashed up to 80 percent,
according to travel industry spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   The same is true in Thailand, where everything from meals to
souvenirs has been cut drastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get there, it's a heck of a bargain,'' said Marilyn
Staff, spokeswoman for Colorado-based Asia Transpacific Journeys.
</P>
<P>
   In Bangkok, a room at the Bel-Aire Princess, a four-star hotel,
costs travelers $65, down about 30 percent from last year,
according travel agents. And the rate at Bangkok's Royal Orchid
Sheraton is $120, down from $190 last year.
</P>
<P>
   The bargains have transcended the region's borders as well.
</P>
<P>
   In Australia, tourists will find shaved prices on everything
from Sydney Opera House tickets, which have dipped from $48 to $34
since last year, to a night at the Coconut Beach Rainforest Resort,
which has fallen to $124 from $172 since last year, according to
the Australian Tourist Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Fish, president of Absolute Asia, a New York-based
travel firm, warns that bargains may expire as countries convert
their rates to U.S. dollars or inflate their local currency-based
rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that southeast Asia represents a good travel bargain
is not necessarily a compelling reason to go,'' Fish said. ``(But)
if you ever wanted to visit Asia, this is the best time to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
