<HEADER>
A2027 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-29 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARBORVITAE PLANTS SUBJECT TO MITE DAMAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have four bushes in my back yard that were 3 feet tall when
I first moved to Texas in 1988, and during the years they had grown
tall and well-shaped.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1992 I noticed a brown spot in one of the trees; the next
year it was larger, and two more trees showed the same damage. Now
all four are at least half-brown. This year they also seem to have
some sort of hard cap on most of the top branches.
</P>
<P>
   A: The plants you have are arborvitae. These evergreens do like
full sun as yours get, but they must have excellent drainage.
Unfortunately these plants are susceptible to spider mites and
bagworms, as well as leaf and stem blight. Your plants probably
have spider mite damage _ the hot, dry conditions are certainly
favorable for this pest _ but I think blight is also involved. I'm
sorry, but based on the photos you sent, I would remove the plants.
</P>
<P>
   The hard caps are berries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A trunk began to grow from the middle of my cactus about two
months ago. I would like to know the name of this plant, how long
it lives after it flowers and other information.
</P>
<P>
   A: That is a giant flower stalk rising from your agave, or
century plant. This succulent can take 10 years or so for the plant
to flower, and it blooms only once. After that, the rosette of long
leaves dies, but often you will see ``pups'' sprouting around the
mother plant.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully dig the mother plant out and any young plants you wish
to have. You don't want the sharp points on the foliage to puncture
you. As you probably noticed with your mother plant, agaves
generally require little attention. Sun and good drainage will do
it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a fig tree that has grown quite high but does not
produce figs. Do I need to pollinate?
</P>
<P>
   I have a kalanchoe. It has not bloomed since I bought it. It has
grown in a pot and been transplanted, and it looks great, but no
blossoms. Any help will be appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your fig does not need a pollinator. Figs are parthenocarp
fruit, which means they do not require sexual fertilization. Figs
may show vigorous vegetative growth at the expense of fruiting. So
once your fig slows, it should produce figs. However, stress can
slow or prevent fruit production. Keep your tree well-watered and
heavily mulched.
</P>
<P>
   Kalanchoes generally flower in winter. The blooms are triggered
by short days. These succulents like good light but prefer not to
be exposed to harsh sunlight. They'll tolerate it but prefer bright
light. Provide a porous potting soil and water spring to fall. Then
decrease watering in winter. Allow the soil to dry between
waterings. Fertilize monthly during the growing season and avoid
air conditioning and heating drafts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a plant that is 30 years old and produces red blooms
profusely. What is it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The photo you sent is of a fireman's cap or coral tree,
``Erythrina crista-galli.'' This small tree/large shrub will mature
to nearly 20 feet in height. It is subject to freezes and may lose
its top in cold weather but is usually root-hardy. It is also heat-
and drought-tolerant. The fireman's cap likes full sun and a
well-draining soil. This fast grower produces reddish-coral waxy
flowers in spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which grasses will a cat eat?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have seen our cat munch on various ornamental grasses such
as Mexican feather grass, Japanese silver grass and purple fountain
grass. I've also heard that some cats will even eat a little
liriope. Although primarily meat eaters, cats sometimes seek the
nutrients in vegetation. They, of course, also love catnip. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
