<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-29 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR-FARE WARS HAVE NEW BATTLEGROUND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our cable-television franchise added several new channels this
month, and while traveling around the dial, I came upon the Game
Show Network and ``The Price Is Right.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the modern-day version, in which everyone screams and plays
the fool. No, these were the original black-and-white episodes with
Bill Cullen addressing each well-dressed, seated participant as
``Mr.'' or ``Mrs.'' and conducting a serious, sedate bidding
process.
</P>
<P>
   A forerunner, I thought, of http://www.priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   The newest strategy, or gimmick, if you prefer, in the airline
fare game, is an Internet site that invites travelers to name the
price they are willing to pay for a round-trip ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Forget published fares. Erase advance-purchase and
Saturday-night-stay-over requirements. If an airline with unsold
seats determines that your price is right, that's what you pay.
</P>
<P>
   Those not attuned to online shopping can play the game by
calling 800-774-2354.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works:
</P>
<P>
   You pick the dates you want to travel. Your trip must begin in
the United States or Puerto Rico. You set the price you'll pay, and
Priceline will let you know within an hour via e-mail whether an
airline accepts your bid for domestic travel. A response to a bid
for international travel may take 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   You won't be surprised to learn that a few not-so-teensy-weensy
other details are involved.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, you get only one free bid _ for as many as eight
people traveling together _ per week per route, a restriction
designed to prevent extremely low bids. A second request incurs a
nonrefundable $25 fee.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you have no say as to which airline you fly. Priceline
guarantees only that you will travel on a major airline or its
affiliate. You have no say, either, about times of departure or
arrival other than to insist that flights depart between 6 a.m. and
10 p.m., or about whether you'll fly nonstop or via a connection.
Once tickets are issued _ all in coach class _ no refunds or
changes are permitted. And you accrue no frequent-flyer mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Industry reaction has been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Smart, a consumer-oriented monthly newsletter, cites
several travelers whose bids were accepted and concludes: ``Our
advice? Give Priceline a try. You have little to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But the June Consumer Reports Travel Letter details an
exhaustive test marked by delays and rejections and says of
Priceline: ``The bidding system it uses poses some serious hidden
risks to consumers who use it. Travelers who aren't careful may
wind up paying more than they would have if they'd just called an
airline or travel agency. Perhaps travelers will become savvy
enough to figure out the right price for their first bid. As the
system works now, however, we're inclined to forget about Priceline
and find some other way to buy a cheap air ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Several large U.S. airlines have said they are not involved in
Priceline. But would an airline admit to selling tickets for less
than a published price? Indeed, why would any airline participate
in such a wholesale distributorship? Simple reason: Airplanes flew
with more than 200 million empty seats last year.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued travelers can access the Web site and follow
instructions to take a ``tour,'' offered with no obligation. The
Web site is more consumer-friendly than the automated telephone
message; besides, you'll pay a small fee for services rendered by
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Online instructions are clear, and you can progress through most
steps with no commitment. You are informed that you can increase
your chances of a bid acceptance by agreeing to use alternate
airports. For instance, when I inquired about a Houston-San
Francisco round trip, I was asked whether I was willing to fly out
of either Bush Intercontinental or Hobby and into San Francisco,
Oakland or San Jose. I also was told that if I would agree to make
more than one stop or connection and/or to take an overnight
flight, my odds would improve.
</P>
<P>
   Since I had no immediate travel plans, I stopped short of
supplying a credit-card number required for finalizing the process.
(For those hesitant to give this information online, a phone number
is provided.)
</P>
<P>
   But if I were making a price bid for real, I'd do considerable
research in advance. I'd check individual airline Web sites and
large multipurpose sites for any published specials. I'd access
http://www.bestfares.com to check out last-minute deals. I'd peruse
newspaper advertisements for tour packages that include air
discounts. I'd consult a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   And I'd carefully weigh the value of scheduling convenience and
frequent-flyer mileage.
</P>
<P>
   I'll be interested to hear from any readers who submit bids. My
gut feeling is that spur-of-the-moment leisure travelers may reap
more savings from Priceline _ since a participating airline would,
in effect, be waiving all advance-purchase restrictions _ than
those who plan ahead and study all options or those with
last-minute business needs that allow little flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   For now, I agree with Consumer Reports Travel Letter's
suggestion that the Internet would be an ideal mechanism for a new
system in which you specify the trip you want to take and the
airlines submit competing bids to you.
</P>
<P>
   That may well be the next venture in the online ``price is
right'' game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
