<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FTC-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC CRACKS DOWN ON FOREIGN-LANGUAGE CIGARETTE ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Federal Trade Commission has ordered that
cigarette advertising include the surgeon general's warning in the
same language as the ad.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a victory for a Vietnamese-American man who
sought the requirement. In the past, cigarette ads aimed at ethnic
communities were printed in languages such as Vietnamese, Chinese
or Spanish, with health advisories in English.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was deliberate, it was part of a continuing effort to
mislead and deceive the public, and to recruit new smokers,''
health worker Anh Le said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Le launched a local grass-roots effort to force
tobacco companies to change this advertising practice. His
ammunition: letters sent by health officials and Asian-American
youngsters urging an advertising crackdown by the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will affect ethnic communities across the country,'' said
Le, who works with the Vietnamese Community Health Promotion
Project at the University of California at San Francisco. ``People
are puffing away _ if they are literate only in their native
language, they don't know the dangers. They have been deliberately
kept in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the notice published Friday in the Federal
Register, the FTC said some advertisers had ``subverted'' the
original intent of a 1973 mandate for ``clear and conspicuous
disclosures'' in foreign language ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FTC is clarifying the original intent ... that all
American consumers, regardless of the language they speak, have
access to important information regarding the products they
purchase,'' the FTC said.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, which took effect immediately, applies not only
to the surgeon general's warning but to other required disclosures,
such as vehicle leasing ads or home mortgage ads, Matthew Gold, an
FTC lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC amendment applies not only to advertisements in
magazines and newspapers, but to any sales material, including
posters, videotapes or store awnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are on notice that this is how the commission will
interpret the law,'' Gold said. ``Its goal is to ensure that
whatever is being disclosed in the ad be effectively communicated
to the audience. It's a common-sense policy _ if you are talking to
Chinese people, you talk in Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This will reduce smoking habits. People will think twice about
smoking with the warning in their language,'' says Philip Nguyen,
executive director of the Southeast Community Center in San
Francisco and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to change the ads was spearheaded by the
Vietnamese-American community in large measure because of the high
incidence of smokers among male Vietnamese, estimated to be 35
percent _ about 1.5 times that of the general population _
according to the Vietnamese Community Health Promotion Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people in my clinic with lung infections ... they
don't know that smoking could affect their health,'' said Kim Phung
Nguyen, a San Francisco pediatrician and member of the Vietnamese
Tobacco-Free Community Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cigarette ads are everywhere _ the ad is beautiful, slick,
the people in them have beautiful teeth,'' she said. ``The ad is in
Vietnamese but the warning is in English. People don't have any
clue what it means.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-AFFLECK-PROFILE-     06-29 1596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AFFLECK-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN AFFLECK STRIKES WHILE SUCCESS IS HOT IN `ARMAGEDDON' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last fall he roamed among us almost unnoticed. Now
he's starring in a blockbuster, dating Gwyneth Paltrow, sporting an
Oscar and posing shirtless for the cover of GQ magazine.
</P>
<P>
   For Ben Affleck, it's been ``one weird transition'' _ and it
started between trips to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck first came to Houston last October for three weeks of
shooting ``Armageddon,'' a splashy sci-fi film due in theaters
Wednesday. When he returned for more work in January, things had
changed.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst was ``Good Will Hunting,'' a film Affleck co-wrote
with boyhood pal Matt Damon. Damon starred as a troubled young
Boston genius, with Affleck as his best friend.
</P>
<P>
   The drama drew rave reviews upon its release in December, then
earned $136 million in theaters. It also won Oscars for Affleck and
Damon for best original screenplay and for Robin Williams as best
supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life really changed between those Houston trips,'' Affleck
said, kicking back in baggy clothes in a hotel suite on what would
have been a rare day off _ if he didn't have interviews to do.
</P>
<P>
   During his first trip to Houston, filming was done at the
Johnson Space Center, and Affleck stayed at downtown's Four Seasons
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out to dinner at a bunch of places, hit the bar scenes
on nights off, and everywhere I went, people were great,'' said
Affleck, a tall, gangly guy whose fast-talking intensity is
tempered by an aw-shucks cordiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd heard Houston's rough, but it's a fun, friendly town _ and
as close to L.A. as I've seen in terms of freeways.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the only folks who recognized him ``were
record-store clerks with nose rings and tattoos who knew me from
`Chasing Amy,''' a small, raw sex comedy in which Affleck had his
first starring role.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the ``Armageddon'' set, ``one driver thought I was just
there for a day or two,'' said Affleck, who turns 26 on Aug. 15.
``But by the end of the shoot, I was winning the Academy Award. It
was quite a jump.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew returned to Houston in January to film on an offshore
oil rig. ``That's when I started getting recognized,'' Affleck
said. ``It was a weird transition.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast ribbed him _ especially top-billed star Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd say, `I don't know what you did that little movie for,'
and I'd say, `My little movie made more money than `The Jackal,'
Bruce,''' Affleck said.
</P>
<P>
   Willis still teases him. Earlier this day, he claimed the
younger actor had a nervous breakdown and was crying while filming
scenes in the Neutral Buoyancy Lab, an astronaut training facility
at the Johnson Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lie,'' Affleck said, laughing. ``It's a lie
perpetrated by an older man who's envious and obviously running low
on Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   But wearing a heavy spacesuit in a huge tank of water was
unsettling, he said. ``If it leaked, it would drop like a rock.
That was scary.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Armageddon,'' Willis and Affleck play offshore oil drillers
whose expertise is needed when NASA detects a Texas-size asteroid
on a collision course with Earth.
</P>
<P>
   A crew of roughnecks is quickly recruited to take specially
equipped shuttles to the asteroid, drill holes in it and plant
nuclear bombs to blow it off course. Otherwise, humanity is doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the crew are Steve Buscemi (``Con Air'') and Texas-born
actor Owen Wilson, who co-wrote ``Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   Liv Tyler plays Willis' daughter, who's in love with Affleck (to
Willis' chagrin), while Billy Bob Thornton plays NASA's chief at
Mission Control, shot on a set in Culver City, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon's'' world-ending plot parallels that of Deep
Impact, which originally was considered the lesser film.
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``Deep Impact'' cost $75 million to ``Armageddon's''
$100 million and lacked a major star. Yet ``Deep Impact'' has made
a surprising $120 million-plus since its May 8 release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armageddon'' producer Jerry Bruckheimer _ the action maestro
behind ``The Rock`` and ``Con Air'' _ isn't sure if that's good or
bad for his movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The positives are that I hope everybody who saw `Deep Impact'
will want to compare it to ours,'' he said. ``The negative is they
may be fed up with asteroid movies. But they are very different.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement is more truth than spin-doctoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Impact'' delves weightily into the emotions of diverse
people reacting to impending doom. ``Armageddon's'' high concept is
``The Dirty Dozen in Space.'' Driven by action and humor, it
concerns a single adventurous mission.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck was thrilled to get to play such a space-farer, although
his point of reference wasn't NASA. It was ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be an astronaut as a kid,'' he said. ``I
wanted to be like Han Solo _ an astronaut with a laser gun. I kept
asking (director) Michael Bay on the set, `Where's my NASA
pistol?'''
</P>
<P>
   Affleck credits Bruckheimer and Bay for hiring him when ``my
name didn't mean much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew me from `Chasing Amy' and had seen some tape from
`Good Will Hunting.' I was surprised the way they greeted me. I
thought I was going to have to beg for this role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Jerry was able to sign me cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruckheimer has launched other actors to huge salaries via hit
action films such as Tom Cruise (``Top Gun'') and Eddie Murphy
(``Beverly Hills Cop'').
</P>
<P>
   Now Affleck, after watching friends Chris O'Donnell and Brendan
Frasier make millions, welcomes his shot at megabucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who says there's no such thing as professional
jealousy is a liar or a fool,'' he said. ``But I always wished
people the best. Maybe I'm naive, but I felt if I just kept
plugging, it would work out for me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked out first for Damon, who earlier starred in ``The
Rainmaker.'' Now both are not just stars but also business
partners. They just signed a deal with Miramax, which gets first
shot at their screenplays.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the big money comes from starring in big pictures, and
Affleck makes no apology for wanting to ``strike while the iron is
hot,'' much as Nicolas Cage has done since winning his Oscar for
``Leaving Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No actor forgets the times he couldn't get a job,`` he said.
``I think everyone operates from that fear. It keeps you driving.
You don't want that momentum to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The momentum started in Boston, where Affleck and Damon grew up.
Affleck's family had moved there soon after he was born in
Berkeley, Calif. Both were bitten by the acting bug at a young age
(Damon, a Boston native, is two years older), and as young men they
hit Hollywood to seek fame and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come all that quickly, despite their image now as an
``overnight'' success story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always me and Matt in some house with a couple of other
guys,'' Affleck said wryly of their early struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by meager roles, the two wrote ``Good Will Hunting''
``out of desperation.'' When selling it, they then insisted on
starring, just as an unknown Sylvester Stallone had done with
``Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the model for us _ the inspiration,'' Affleck said.
``It took five years between writing ``Good Will Hunting'' to
getting it made, but it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Affleck is now starring with Sandra Bullock in ``Forces of
Nature,'' a romance filming in Savannah, Ga., that is due next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   His real-life romance is with actress Paltrow. She's the reason
Affleck splits time between L.A. and New York, where Paltrow lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking together is tough for actors who work apart on
location. They have to take time when they can find it. On this
weekend, Paltrow was seen entering the hotel where Affleck was
holding interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Affleck's next release will be director-writer's Kevin Smith's
``Dogma,'' due later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a satire on the Catholic Church,'' said Affleck. (Damon
also appears in the film.) ``It's Kevin's take on the perils of
dogmatic beliefs and being inflexible.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Forces of Nature'' wraps, Affleck plans to take a
breather. Since last August, the longest time he's had off from
work is five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too much,'' he said. ``I'm taking the fall off.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps from acting. But he'll still be writing with Damon, as
they finish their follow-up screenplay to ``Good Will Hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel an enormous amount of pressure,'' Affleck said. ``Once
you win an Academy Award, there's no way to live up to the
expectations. You're going to take some shots, and people will say,
`This isn't `Good Will Hunting.'' Then I'll say, `Thank God _ I
didn't want to write that movie again.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since writing is such a lonely, unglamorous job ``it helps to
have a partner to bounce stuff off of,'' Affleck said. ``But it
only gets fun when you start shooting the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   As for off-duty fun, if he had the time, the 6-foot-2 Affleck
would ``take a road trip on my motorcycle or drive around the
country with my brother (actor Casey Affleck, 22) in our Cadillac.
Or I wouldn't mind sitting home and watching TV for a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Affleck is well aware that success ``comes and goes, and even
the biggest stars have peaks and valleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the valleys come for me, I hope to look back and say, `I
never believed the hype, I believed in myself, I always kept my
head, I never treated anyone badly and I tried to be a good
person.' Then I'll be able to live with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
