<SLUG> BC-BORDER-VIDEO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO FOR ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS HIGHLIGHTS SNAKES, DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ High-tech equipment and helicopters haven't
scared illegal immigrants from crossing the border, but officials
hope images of rattlesnakes, dead bodies and broiling summer heat
will.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens of Mexico and other countries captured by the U.S.
Border Patrol throughout the Rio Grande Valley soon will be shown a
video that chronicles such dangers.
</P>
<P>
   The video shows footage of snake-infested brush as well as the
body of an immigrants who drowned earlier this month trying to wade
across the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   There also are shots of railroad boxcars that can feel like
ovens in the intense heat and are used to smuggle dozens of people
over the border at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to live poor than to die trying to be rich,''
Letty Garza, a Border Patrol spokeswoman, warns in Spanish at the
end of the video.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 illegal immigrants have died this month of apparent
dehydration on treks into the United States in torrid heat. It's
not uncommon for some undocumented immigrants to walk for days
through the brutal heat as they try to elude agents.
</P>
<P>
   Bodies of people who died of heat-related causes have been found
throughout the region. Several people have drowned trying to cross
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this will make a strong impression,'' said Garza, a
former television news anchor who appeared on the video.
</P>
<P>
   ``It educates and warns illegal aliens about the dangers of
crossing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 300 immigrants die along the Texas-Mexico border each
year, according to a 1996 University of Houston study.
</P>
<P>
   Rogelio Nunez, executive director of Proyecto Libertad, an
immigration and civil rights group in Harlingen, said he doubted
the video would do much good because it doesn't address the causes
of immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like: Say `no' to immigration or bad things will happen
to you,'' Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen all these pictures of what drugs do and alcohol
does, and we haven't reduced it,'' Nunez said. ``I think people
know what they're up against.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is a part of Operation Lifesaver, a U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service initiative.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the effort, Mexican radio and television stations
also are playing 30-second public service announcements warning of
the dangers of crossing the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
