<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: That good old mountain dew
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in which readers share
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, at
least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Marcus Gross, an Alabamian who found his way
to Texas, has vivid memories of ``them old cotton fields back
home.'' Here's his story:
</P>
<P>
   ``How often do we hear `the good old days.' Well, here is what I
remember of the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our parents. We had our brothers and sisters. We had
our youth. What we didn't have was electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lived on a farm that wasn't all ours. It was called the old
Gross farm. We were dirt-poor cotton farmers. We plowed with an old
Ford tractor as well as horses and mules, mostly mules.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother got up early every morning to cook our breakfast,
and we were at work by daylight. When my mother cleaned up from
breakfast, she started dinner. What was left over from dinner was
our supper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a spring with water so cold that you couldn't stand in
it barefoot. That's where we kept our milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of being cotton farmers, we raised such grains as
corn, barley and soybeans for feed. We planted sweet potatoes and
Irish potatoes, cantaloupes and melons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had several head of cattle, though not enough to count as a
herd. We had an old sow and raised pigs. What we didn't sell we'd
slaughter, salt down the middling and smoke-cure the hams and
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good smokehouse, and that wasn't all that went on in
the smokehouse, as I will tell you later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised up in a very religious family in the foothills of
the Appalachian plateau of north Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours was a small community. We had two churches, Methodist and
Baptist. We were Methodists in good standing. My daddy served as a
steward, something like the Baptists call a deacon, and our family
attended services and revivals religiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, more about that smokehouse ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with all the vegetables we raised, we also had an
orchard consisting of apples, peaches, plums, pears and grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We canned the fruit and vegetables and made jelly and jams,
and thrashed the peas that were dried.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Daddy and my two brothers and I picked the grapes,
muscadines and berries.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy had three five-gallon churns. We'd mash the fruit and
put it into those churns, also adding sugar, malt and yeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``After it had properly fermented, my daddy would take us boys
to the smokehouse after work and we'd all have a dipper of that
good old mountain dew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I will admit without question that I was the black sheep
of the family, and I still am.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister, my two brothers and I all served in World War II. I
was a paratrooper in the Southwest Pacific, but have nothing to
brag about as a hero. I was lucky to get, and probably didn't
deserve, the good conduct badge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no regrets of how I lived my life and if I had it to do
over I wouldn't change it one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dreamsville,'' c/o
Joe Murray, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915. E-mail address
is awew18a(at)prodigy.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
