<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2102 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADET-TRIAL-840(2Take     06-29 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADET-TRIAL-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL OPENS NEW CHAPTER IN CADET MURDER CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ At 21, David Graham would be entering his
third year at the Air Force Academy, by now learning to fly and
moving closer to becoming a fighter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   His former fiancee, Diane Zamora, would be on the same track at
the Naval Academy, her goal of being an astronaut still intact.
</P>
<P>
   And for Adrianne Jones, senior prom would be fresh in her mind
as she prepared to leave Mansfield for her first year at Texas A&AMP;M,
where she hoped to study psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four months after Zamora was sentenced to life in prison
for her role in Jones' death, the next chapter in what has become
known as the cadet murder case begins next week with Graham's
capital murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   Their teen-age goals seemed so certain in December 1995, before
Jones was found beaten and shot to death beside a remote road in
southwest Grand Prairie. Nearly three years later, they're just
well-publicized but unfulfilled memories.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is accused of being the trigger man in a plot spawned by
jealousy and a personal code of honor that the couple valued more
than a young girl's life, according to police reports and testimony
from Zamora's trial.
</P>
<P>
   And although they professed to be in love at the time of their
September 1996 arrests, Zamora defended herself against capital
murder charges by smearing Graham, a tactic that proved
unsuccessful with jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Graham watched from jail on Court TV as Zamora and her attorneys
painted him as a sadistic, gun-loving, sex-crazed tyrant who
listened to cult music and forced Zamora to go along with the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's mother, Janice Graham, testified that she warned Zamora
about his temper and potential for violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That defense to me was remarkable _ `David is Satan, but I
love Satan,''' Graham's attorney, Dan Cogdell, said in an
interview. ``It's always difficult to demonize a co-defendant
without putting yourself in hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicity from Zamora's monthlong Tarrant County murder trial
was so extensive that Graham's case has been moved 200 miles south
to New Braunfels out of concern that unbiased jurors could not be
found within the county. Jury selection is scheduled to begin July
6, and the trial is expected to last a month.
</P>
<P>
   In Zamora's trial, prosecutors presented testimony from close
friends of the two defendants, as well as the gun used in the
shooting and detailed confessions written separately by Graham and
Zamora. Prosecutors have said that evidence and core testimony in
Graham's trial will mirror much of Zamora's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a very difficult case to win? I'm not naive enough to
say that odds are in my favor of getting David an acquittal,'' said
Cogdell, a Houston lawyer who has gained a reputation in legal
circles, first as a protege of Richard ``Racehorse'' Haynes and
later for representing one of the Branch Davidian cult members who
was acquitted of murder charges. ``I recognize that it's an uphill
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining Graham's confession will probably be the most
difficult obstacle for the defense, legal experts say. Cogdell
already tried unsuccessfully to throw out a statement that Graham
gave to investigators while in Air Force custody, arguing that
Graham was held against his will and not informed of his
constitutional rights before he sat down at a computer screen and
began typing his four-page statement.
</P>
<P>
   The confession, which was leaked to the media before it was read
during Zamora's trial, is vivid in its description of Jones' death,
as well as the obsessed and consuming relationship between Graham
and Zamora. That relationship spun out of control when Graham
claimed he had sex with Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always being told by Diane that our relationship was so
perfect and pure. The love we shared would never be broken and no
one would never come between us,'' he wrote. ``No one, that is,
except that one girl that had stolen from us our purity.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Zamora's jealousy and Graham's desire to resolve the betrayal
combined to create the plan to kill Jones, a popular and active
Mansfield High School sophomore who ran track with Graham but had
never met -)mora, Graham wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The request of Adrianne's life was, not for a second, taken
lightly by me. ... Well, Diane's beautiful eyes have always played
the strings of my heart effortlessly. ... I didn't have any harsh
feelings for Adrianne, but no one could stand between me and Diane.
... I regret it now, for never did I imagine the heartache it would
cause my school, my friends, Adrianne's family, or even my
community. I guess I just shut it all out of my mind in that
instant when I convinced myself that Diane was even worth murder.''
</P>
<P>
   According to police reports and testimony from Zamora's trial,
Graham lured Jones out of her house on a Sunday night. With Zamora
hiding in the car trunk, Jones and Graham drove to a winding
country road near Joe Pool Lake. There, Zamora emerged from the
trunk, confronted Jones and struck her on the head with a weight.
</P>
<P>
   Dazed from the blow, Jones tried to run away, but Graham
followed her with a 9mm semiautomatic handgun. When she collapsed
on a barbed-wire fence, Graham stood over her and fired two shots
into her head, according to testimony from Zamora's trial.
</P>
<P>
   Police interviewed hundreds of high school students in the area,
including Graham, but didn't solve the case for more than nine
months. During that time, Graham and Zamora graduated from high
school _ he from Mansfield and she from Crowley _ and received
appointments to prestigious military academies.
</P>
<P>
   Once separated at the two military academies, the secret was
quickly revealed. Zamora told a fellow midshipman no fewer than 10
times about her involvement, according to trial testimony. That
midshipman _ who said he was romantically involved with Zamora _
never turned her in because he said he didn't believe her. She then
told two academy roommates about the killing, and they brought
their concerns to military officials within a day.
</P>
<P>
   In jail for nearly two years since his arrest, Graham has made
the transition from model cadet to model prisoner, adapting to the
highly structured schedule and rarely complaining, Cogdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Along Cedar Street across from City Hall, in an older part of
Mansfield, neighbors on the street of single-story homes with thick
grassy yards have only good things to say about the former
high-achieving student and his family. None of those residents
wanted to be identified for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in junior high, Graham displayed a single-minded
determination to pursue a military career, with the goal of winning
an appointment to the Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs. At
Mansfield High School, Graham wore his hair high-and-tight,
military-style, and served in the school's ROTC program.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the Civil Air Patrol squadron at nearby
Spinks Airport in Fort Worth, a common step for youths who want to
join the military and especially those who want a leg up at getting
into the academy. He rose to the rank of lieutenant colonel in the
squadron and learned about flying and rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appeared to be an outstanding young person, very sharp and
very knowledgeable,'' said Jim Gates, a lieutenant colonel and
emergency services director for the Civil Air Patrol. ``He had a
goal. He was going to go to the Air Force Academy and get his
wings.''
</P>
<P>
   That Graham faces capital murder charges still seems surprising,
Gates said. ``It just didn't seem like he was capable of something
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
