<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY, GOING ON THE ATTACK, RALLIES TO DEFEAT MEXICO, 2-1  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELLIER, France _ At the end, after two hours of playing in
temperatures above 90 degrees, exhaustion replaced celebration.
Juergen Klinsmann raised his arms, but could not keep them above
his head. Andreas Kopke, the German goalkeeper, collapsed on his
back, and defender Christian Worns writhed on the ground as his
muscles cramped in protest. But, until the whistle blew, Germany
had been as relentless as the heat.
</P>
<P>
   The European champions play for long periods where they appear
vulnerable and eminently beatable. But this is only a mirage.
Theirs is a pitiless style. For 90 minutes they play with a
merciless determination. They fall behind but they do not quit. A
Mexican goal two minutes into the second half did not unnerve
Germany Monday _ just the opposite _ it liberated the Germans to
begin a charge of their own.
</P>
<P>
   When this riveting game was over, Klinsmann and his partner at
forward, Oliver Bierhoff, had each delivered their third goals of
the World Cup, and Germany had prevailed 2-1, earning a berth in
the quarterfinals on Saturday against the winner of Tuesday's match
between Romania and Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play according to our strength, our fighting spirit,''
Klinsmann said. ``We keep going and going and fighting and
fighting. You must be physically prepared especially when it is so
hot. You must be tough. We have to fight for 90 minutes, and we try
to instill fear in the other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico was not afraid, but it did let a 1-0 lead fall away like
dripping sweat as defender Raul Lara made two critical errors. In
the 74th minute, Germany went to three forwards, as Coach Berti
Vogts inserted Ulf Kirsten, the leading scorer in the Bundesliga,
alongside Klinsmann and Bierhoff. A minute later, Dieter Hamann
sent a long diagonal pass into the penalty area, but Lara could not
trap the ball. Klinsmann, waiting, punched the deflection into the
net as Jorge Campos, the Mexican goalie, made a futile slide to
disrupt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always expect to get a pass and score a goal,'' Klinsmann
said. ``Even when it was 1-0, we never lost our trust and
confidence. It freed the team, gave us energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Four minutes from the end, Germany scored again, this time on a
play that was beautifully precise in the way it unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Lothar Mattheus, starting again at sweeper, pushed through the
middle of the field and sent a pass to Michael Tarnat on his left.
Tarnat chested the ball and lifted it across the field to Kirsten,
who left-footed a pass for Bierhoff in the penalty area. Bierhoff
led the Italian League in scoring this season with great
reliability in the air. He had hit the crossbar in the first half,
but this time he headed Kirsten's pass just inside the right post,
and Mexico had been clinically dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   For Mexico, this will be forever remembered as a chance missed.
</P>
<P>
   In the 47th minute, the Mexican forward Luis Hernandez finally
eluded Markus Babbel, who had been a late addition at starter in
the German defense. For 41 minutes, Hernandez had not touched the
ball. But now, he escaped Babbel in the penalty area, took a pass
from Cuauhtemoc Blanco and kept drifting, drifting to his right.
</P>
<P>
   Tarnat stumbled and both Worns and Kopke went to the ground,
attempting to block the shot, but Hernandez knifed it between them
for his fourth goal of the World Cup and a 1-0 lead for Mexico. In
the first round, Mexico had fallen behind three times before
catching up. This time, it scored the first goal but could not hold
on.
</P>
<P>
   The game may have turned on a wild scramble in the 62d minute,
when Mexico's energetic replacement in midfield, Jesus Arellano,
stole a pass from Babbel and sprinted toward Kopke in the German
goal. Mattheus caught up, but in kicking the ball away from
Arellano, he nearly scored an own goal. Kopke dived and seem to
rake the ball with his fingers, sending it into the left post. The
rebound was passed to Hernandez, but his shot was fired directly at
Kopke. With that escape, Germany began to grow stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first Mexican goal was a shock,'' Klinsmann said. ``But
we were never worried about getting back into the game, because we
have an instinctive fighting spirit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
