<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-POET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORT WORTH POET JESSE F. GARCIA GIVES ROCK 'N' ROLL DREAMS A VOICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesse F. Garcia, Fort Worth's rock 'n' roll poet, is a
mild-looking 46-year-old graphic artist who sports a trim mustache
and short, neat hair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the combination of avocation and appearance would seem to
be a contradiction. But there's no questioning Garcia's allegiance
to the music of the Rolling Stones, Beatles, Jimi Hendrix, the Who,
the Grateful Dead and dozens more _ right up to R.E.M. and Rage
Against the Machine _ the minute one starts reading ``Rock 'N' Roll
Dreams,'' his slim, self-published first volume of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dreams,'' the images _ of the Beatles, of Hendrix playing
Fort Worth in 1970, of the sad waste that was John Lennon's death _
spill off the pages in classic Beat style.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia takes us back to the days of teen-agers cruising
drive-ins, of the chaotic '60s and right on up to Generation Xers
who only want to move to Seattle and become grunge wannabes. And in
conversation, the light of a true fan still shines as brightly as
that of, say, a kid who has just heard ``Stairway to Heaven'' for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to really find out about music, not just what
they hear on the radio,'' he says by way of explaining one of his
reasons for assembling the poems, all of which have been written in
the past eight years. ``I want them to see if a guy really has
talent. Like in the '70s, when disco was so popular _ there were a
lot of good New York bands nobody knew about, like the New York
Dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe _ no, probably _ Garcia has remained a fan all these years
because rock 'n' roll literally, he says, saved his life. Born the
son of migrant workers and raised in Devine, just south of San
Antonio, Garcia first heard R&AMP;B via a wind-up Victrola that
belonged to the only black family in the barrio where he lived.
</P>
<P>
   He'd go over and listen to Big Joe Turner doing ``Shake, Rattle
and Roll,'' and then he graduated to records by Little Richard and
Chuck Berry. And when the Beatles exploded, he was the only
Hispanic kid with a Beatle haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other Chicanos threw rocks at me,'' he says. ``They
thought I was trying to be white.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 10, he was picking cotton alongside men and
women as his family worked in the fields around South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so poor we couldn't afford cockroaches,'' he says.
``I'm serious. What saved me from committing suicide was a
transistor radio, Top 40 rock 'n' roll.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, in a bookstore in San Antonio, Garcia bought
Allen Ginsberg's ``Howl'' for $1 and immersed himself in the world
of the Beat writers. And he began writing, although his early
stuff, he says, was horrible ``self-centered, `feel sorry for me'
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, when he was a high school sophomore, his father got a
much better job as a warehouse laborer in Fort Worth, and his
family moved to the north side.
</P>
<P>
   This was a boon for a longhaired kid who wanted to hear as much
music as possible and talk about counterculture icons like Chairman
Mao, Angela Davis and John Sinclair. Garcia spent a lot of his time
at Panther Hall, where he saw the Dead and Bob Seger; at Will
Rogers, where he saw Hendrix; and at the Convention Center, where
he saw the Stones, Led Zeppelin and Neil Young.
</P>
<P>
   He kept writing, too, and doing readings of his work, even as
the music began to turn stale. During the past few years, Garcia
has been published in the local literary magazine ``Nothing
Shocking,'' the Colorado poetry journal ``Red Dirt,'' and in
``Unsettling America: An Anthology of Contemporary Multicultural
Poetry,'' alongside Quincy Troupe and Beat hero Lawrence
Ferlinghetti.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's rock 'n' roll anymore,'' he says.
``Everybody's gotten repetitive. R.E.M. and Rage Against the
Machine are the only really good bands keeping rock 'n' roll alive.
I think it started when New Wave started coming out with
synthesizers. Other than guitar, saxophone and piano, you cannot
have rock 'n' roll. The only inspiration I look to now is Bob
Dylan.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, this year, he gathered his favorite poems about music
and published them, in no small part, he says, because ``all the
poets now are putting out these horrible, repetitive books. All
they write about is themselves. They're not good, and they're not
saying anything, and it's because they haven't experienced hard
times. In my day, if you didn't work, you didn't eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia is proud of where he has come from, but he's also proud
that he got out of the hard barrio life of his parents. Rock 'n'
roll and poetry _ coupled with a fierce desire to be educated and
not to work in the fields like so many people he grew up with _
were what got him to this place, where he has a decent job that
affords him some free time to listen to Dylan on his CD player and
to write.
</P>
<P>
   And some day, he says, he'll find a publisher for a second
volume of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people write to amuse their ego or their libido or
their intellect _ I write to amuse myself,'' he says. ``I'm
selfish. I want to keep the issues alive _ the government, ecology,
social injustice. And once in a while, I write a mushy love poem.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
