<HEADER>
A2151 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-WOMANPASTOR-     06-29 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-WOMANPASTOR-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
 
WACO CHURCH HIRES STATE'S FIRST FEMALE SOUTHERN BAPTIST SENIOR
PASTOR (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KRISTIN N. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a new seminary student, Julie
Pennington-Russell often knelt before her 8 o'clock classes ``to
pray for all the poor women who thought they were being called to
become pastors.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, as she delved into studies in theology, philosophy
and languages, she said she found biblical evidence that a woman
can lead a church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think deep inside I had always thought, `This is a crock.
God loves us the same,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Pennington-Russell became associate pastor of 19th
Avenue Baptist Church, a 90-member congregation tucked between San
Francisco's crowded row houses. In 1993, she agreed to become the
church's senior pastor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Pennington-Russell is preparing to come to Texas as the
state's first female senior pastor of a Southern Baptist church,
stoking a debate that has divided Baptist conservatives and
moderates since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington-Russell, who turns 38 on July 4, will give her first
sermon as senior pastor of Waco's Calvary Baptist Church on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1,300 women have been ordained as ministers in
churches affiliated with the Southern Baptist Convention, the
nation's largest Protestant denomination. Only 85 are senior
pastors or co-pastors, and most of them work in North Carolina,
according to Baptist Women in Ministry, a support organization
based in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington-Russell's appointment is controversial, coming as it
does on the heels of this month's Southern Baptist Convention
resolution advising women to ``submit graciously to the servant
leadership'' of their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   But even as interview requests have poured in from the ABC and
Fox TV networks, radio talk shows and other media,
Pennington-Russell has downplayed her newsworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to serve as pastor of the state of Texas,'' she
said. ``I'm going to serve this one church that I care deeply
about. And I think they care about me. And we'll walk together a
while. Hopefully, a long while.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Purdy, chairman of Calvary Baptist's pastoral search
committee, called Pennington-Russell ``an extremely gifted
preacher'' whom members hired after agreeing not ``to put any
limits on the leadership of the Lord.'' She won the job on a 190-73
vote among members.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the secular world, that'd be a landslide,'' Purdy said.
``We're excited to have her.'' Pennington-Russell said she has
enjoyed 16 years of ``being completely unselfconscious'' since she
enrolled in California's Golden Gate Baptist Theological Seminary
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Ohio, Pennington-Russell moved a lot during her
childhood because her father served in the Air Force. She said her
mother became a Christian at age 21 and raised her daughter and son
in a variety of Baptist churches _ American, Southern, Independent
and conservative _ until the family settled in Orlando, Fla., and
joined the city's First Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition at First Baptist held that ``women were not allowed to
preach, read Scripture or speak from the pulpit at all,'' although
they could sing, Pennington-Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Her father wanted her to be a dentist. But Pennington-Russell
earned a degree in speech pathology from the University of Central
Florida. With a desire to study Christianity outside the Bible
Belt, Pennington-Russell said, she moved cross-country and enrolled
in Golden Gate Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   She became convinced that women could lead in the church in her
first year of studying the Bible and the original languages of
scriptural text.
</P>
<P>
   In her view, the Bible's many examples of women prophesying and
teaching validate the role of women in the ministry. Church elders
and overseers are usually referred to in groups, a fact that
Pennington-Russell said does not exclude women from being senior
pastors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot think of any reason, except for a quest for power or
a wielding of authority, for anyone to limit what God can do in the
lives of men and women in the church if it's going to further the
church,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many conservatives, however, believe that her argument is off
base.
</P>
<P>
   They point to passages in 1 Corinthians in which Paul writes
that women should be silent in church and to Paul's letter to
Titus, in which Paul instructs older women to teach younger women.
Others hold up New Testament definitions of bishops and deacons
calling for such leaders to be the ``husband of one wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely believe in the total equality of men and women.
Men and women equally bear the image of God,'' said Daniel Akin,
dean of the school of theology at Southern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Louisville, Ky. ``But God has given men and women
different assignments in the home that beautifully parallel the
church.''
</P>
<P>
   Akin added: ``Anything you do to get to women being senior
pastors, you have to extrapolate.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Lea, dean of the school of theology at Southwestern
Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, said he interprets
Paul's prohibition against women teaching men or having authority
over men in 1 Timothy to mean that women shouldn't hold the office
of senior pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some would carry it so far to say a woman shouldn't teach
Sunday school. But I don't carry it that far,'' he said. ``Because
there are differences in opinion, I am hesitant to make it an
article of faith or test of fellowship. It is possible to differ at
this point and still be a Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Creed, dean of the George W. Truett Seminary at Baylor
University, said that as he listened to Pennington-Russell preach
her tryout sermon at Calvary Baptist, his Bible fell open to Acts
2:17, in which Peter predicted that in the last days ``your sons
and your daughters shall prophesy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not be right for every church culturally, but I don't
think Scripture disallows it,'' said Creed, who is serving as
interim pastor at the Waco church until Pennington-Russell starts.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Becca Gurney of Austin, president of Baptist Women in
Ministry, said she finds the continuous arguing over female pastors
``tiresome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not getting the Gospel told,'' she said. ``Anyone who
commits their lives to the Gospel and sharing the good news, we
should welcome them and say, `You go, girl!' or, `You go, guy!'''
Pennington-Russell doesn't appear rattled by the debate. The only
time she recalls her gender being an issue in her San Francisco
church was when she became pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Congregation leaders developed a maternity leave policy and gave
her 12 weeks' paid leave with Taylor, now 7, and Lucy, who is 3.
Church members and visiting professors filled in as interim
preachers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Twice, in 1993 and 1997, 19th Avenue members were denied voting
and speaking privileges at the California Southern Baptist
Convention because the church was led by a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently have some 19th Avenue members confided to
Pennington-Russell that they had briefly questioned whether they
could be comfortable with a female pastor.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she said, ``An inordinate amount of women
have said, `I feel so free to talk about things with my pastor'
that they might not have discussed with a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Comfortable sitting cross-legged on the floor of her office in
bluejeans or breaking sourdough bread at the pulpit for The Lord's
Supper, she said she's looking forward to the transition to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Pennington-Russell and her husband, Tim, won't
have to spend 2 1/2 hours driving back and forth across the Golden
Gate Bridge getting Lucy to preschool.
</P>
<P>
   Tim, who met his wife while studying at Golden Gate Seminary, is
a free-lance Web site developer who has already been contacted for
a new job. And the couple has purchased a 2-story, brick home ``on
this beautiful tree-lined street'' for the same amount a friend
paid for a one-bathroom studio apartment in San Francisco,
Pennington-Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   With Waco's Baylor University nearby, Pennington-Russell said,
she hopes to brush up on the Spanish she learned in college,
particularly because Calvary Baptist's 300 members include a number
of Spanish-speaking families as well as African-Americans and
Anglos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living in a smaller town where people know each other and you
really feel tied in to the community was very attractive to us,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Pennington-Russell's new church was the site
of a protest staged by East Texas followers of the
ultra-conservative Rev. W.N. Otwell, leader of the God Said
Ministries of Mount Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters, who are not affiliated with the Southern Baptist
denomination, held signs saying that Pennington-Russell ``needs to
go home and be a wife and mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennington-Russell said, however, that Waco and the Baylor
campus have been a haven for ministers who share her beliefs,
particularly since the 1994 opening of Truett Seminary as a
moderate alternative to Fort Worth's more conservative Southwestern
Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support network that I knew would be in Waco was a huge
attraction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Baptist leaders say it is unlikely that Calvary Baptist will be
penalized in any way for hiring a women pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Baptists, we believe in the congregational form of
government in most of our churches. As they make their decisions,
we honor the autonomy of each local church,'' said Paul Stripling,
executive director of the Waco Baptist Association. ``I would hope
that each of our sister churches would honor that concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvary Baptist, along with many other nominally Southern
Baptist congregations, is affiliated with a moderate group separate
from the convention, the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship. About 85
percent of Calvary Baptist's members this year earmarked their
contributions for the fellowship, while 15 percent of the members
designated their money for the convention, said Purdy, of the
Calvary Baptist pastoral search committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Merrell, a vice president for the Southern Baptist
Convention, said he expects Calvary Baptist to continue to
``distance themselves more and more'' from the convention under
Pennington-Russell's leadership. He added that the New Testament's
rules for church governance cannot be dismissed ``without great
harm to the people of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such criticism, Pennington-Russell said she's not going
to leave her religious heritage ``in the hands of a few who I think
have grossly skewed what it means to be a Baptist Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're free to do that, and I don't wish them ill,'' she
said. ``But I'm not going to abandon my tradition to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Leland Harden, song leader at 19th Avenue in San Francisco, said
he's confident that Pennington-Russell will handle whatever
adversity comes her way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julie is a trailblazer without being a femi-nazi,'' said
Harden, referring to talk show host Rush Limbaugh's label for
feminist activists. ``She's a leader focused on the calling of God.
If she's blazing trails, so be it. But she has Christ's agenda, not
her own.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
