<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-MAIN     06-29 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-MAIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT THE RAILWAY STATION: CHINESE MULL CLINTON'S DEMOCRACY MESSAGE
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _At the old Beijing train station Monday people were
playing pool, tending fussy kids, buying snacks. And a few dozen
followed a very abnormal pursuit: listening raptly to President
Clinton talk about freedom and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   What they and perhaps half a billion other Chinese heard was
Clinton's unprecedented argument on behalf of freedom and changes
that are seldom even whispered about today.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese enthused. Many thought Clinton was meddling. But
even among the latter, thoughts lingered that some good might come
of his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some day China becomes more open, we should remember and
mark this visit of Clinton,'' said Lai Zheng Xing, 26, a computer
programmer in the special economic zone of Shenzhen, who watched
Clinton in the shabby waiting room. ``He was excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't draw huge crowds to the station waiting rooms
where televisions beamed out his speech. But then again, entry into
the waiting rooms cost from 62 cents to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
   A cook, a cop and a waitress slipped in and out to catch a few
words between their duties, and several travelers who strayed in
from the cafeteria quickly got entranced by Clinton and anted up
the payment when spotted by a curt attendant.
</P>
<P>
   The White House scored a second diplomatic success Monday, by
airing live on national television Clinton's 57-minute speech and
question-and-answer session at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   Winning Chinese permission for a nationwide television broadcast
had been a priority goal for Clinton, who wanted to present his
vision of a free China. This was his second live broadcast in three
days. The first was an unprecedented televised news conference cum
debate between Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither appearance was an undiluted victory.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese listeners raised widespread complaints about the
less-than-fluent translation of Clinton's university speech, which
was done by a White House-supplied translator. And the bad quality
audio transmission meant parts of the event couldn't be understood
at all, including the questions from students, most of which were
barbed and critical of U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Michael McCurry said the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs complained about the translation because ``they had
wanted to interpret it,'' but the train station listeners also
objected that it was hard to understand.
</P>
<P>
   And last Saturday's news conference with President Jiang also
was a mixed blessing. Some Chinese were disconcerted and even
embarrassed by the direct nature of Clinton's critiques of human
rights practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Chinese feel very unhappy and many people watching with
me were very angry about that. He went a bit too far,'' said Wan
Yihua, a factory manager from Jiangxi province interviewed at the
train station. Wan found the Monday speech ``more friendly'' than
the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   How Clinton's comments will resonate over future months and even
years is impossible to gauge. His visit could spur demands for
democratic change or bring out a nationalistic backlash, as seemed
to be the case among young questioners at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one student asked Clinton how he would like it if
China sent arms to Hawaiian leaders in a hostile frame of mind,
paralleling that with America's sale of arms to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States policy is not an obstacle to the peaceful
reunification of China and Taiwan,'' Clinton responded, repeating
America's stand in support of one China, undivided.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton got little more than polite applause during his speech,
in which he not only challenged the students to work to alleviate
worldwide ills such as pollution and drug abuse, but also made a
case for opening China's political system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (Americans) believe and our experience demonstrates that
freedom strengthens stability and helps nations to change,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   How Clinton's nine-day sweep across China will change the power
balance within China's inner leadership is something his deputies
shied away from addressing. ``We can't predict,'' said McCurry.
``This is not a transparent regime and there's still, and will
remain, aspects of the Chinese leadership that remain opaque to
U.S. decision makers.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Susan Shirk, deputy assistant secretary of
state for east Asia, said that previously taboo subjects, like
repression in Tibet and the crushing of the 1989 democracy
movement, have been brought into the open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be possible to bury those subjects again,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   China's reticence to embrace democracy is not simply a matter of
autocratic leaders refusing to give over power to the masses.
Plenty of average Chinese also fear how the masses might wield
power.
</P>
<P>
   Even the computer programmer Lai, who heartily endorsed
Clinton's comments, cautioned that change must come slowly to China
and with some restraints. He cited the cultural revolution, that
decade of pandemonium from 1966 to 1976 when mostly young people
smashed vestiges of authority across the nation, as an example of
``democracy and freedom out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Chinese are even more reluctant to accept the kinds of
changes Clinton proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked a lot about freedom. But Chinese people are mostly
concerned with economic problems,'' objected Wan, the factory
manager who had early lunch as he awaited a train and watched
Clinton. ``They don't have a very strong demand for freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Wan said he feared ``too much democracy'' would cause chaos
among Chinese who tend to solve problems ``with their fists and
their feet.'' Yet he gave an unexpected summing up when asked what
is the best result Clinton's visit might have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might make politics and freedom of speech more relaxed,''
said Wan, 32. And he thought that would be okay, if it didn't go
too far and too fast.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
