<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVERS-SENIORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVE THE DRIVING TO THE SENIOR SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Murray Wallace checked over his coolers of ice
and dry ice and his clipboard filled with lab reports, grabbed his
car keys and headed for the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   It's the routine the 79-year-old Woodland Hills man follows
three days a week as a courier for Endocrine Sciences, an Agoura
Hills medical research and testing laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   He's one of a dozen of the company's part-time drivers _ all of
them over 60 years old and a few pushing 80 _ who negotiate the
freeways throughout Southern Calfornia, retrieving blood and tissue
samples from doctors' offices and hospitals. After testing is
complete, the drivers deliver lab reports that can provide a
reassuring diagnosis for a worried patient _ or lead doctors to the
right course of treatment for a newborn baby with a
life-threatening condition.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement? These guys have been there, done that. And they
didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, for example, went back to work 2{ years ago after
ending a 40-year career selling maps and globes _ and getting bored
sitting around the house. His part-time job gives him a reason to
get up in the morning, a sense of responsibility, a feeling that
he's helping somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I've been told what I was delivering could save
somebody's life,'' Wallace said. ``It's a good feeling that the job
you're doing is that important.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many companies are pushing older employees into
retirement or downsizing them out of a job, it's these older
drivers' maturity, self-reliance and reliability that make them
valuable employees, said Endocrine Sciences operations manager
Kevin Crane.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're an amazing crew,'' he said. ``The only problem I've
had with them is that they'd be here at 5 o'clock in the morning if
I'd let them. Everybody should have that problem, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Reliable, sure. But what about their driving skills?
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Jan and Dean recorded ``The Little Old Lady (From
Pasadena),'' the stereotypical older driver has been either ``the
terror of Colorado Boulevard'' from the song or the poky codger
doing a tentative 20 mph in the freeway's fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   But not these couriers, their boss says. Besides undergoing an
interview, during which their alertness and agility were
scrutinized, each had to submit state Department of Motor Vehicles
proof that they were safe drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our insurance company is not going to insure somebody who's
not,'' Crane said.
</P>
<P>
   The dozen couriers combined drive more than 200,000 miles a
year, and _ although they've had occasional fender-benders _ have
racked up only a fraction of the accidents and other problems
caused by younger drivers the company employed in the past. They
take such good care of company vehicles, in fact, that most autos
are still operating well when the odometers hit 200,000 miles,
Crane said.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old firm _ perhaps the only one in the state that
has a staff of senior-citizen drivers, according to California
Department of Aging spokeswoman Jo Raysbrook _ began hiring older
couriers just a few years after it opened for business, after
younger drivers _ most of them in their 20s and 30s _ wrecked cars,
didn't show up for work, failed to deliver samples on time or made
other major mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had younger drivers, we had repair bills like crazy _
worn brakes, burnt-out clutches,'' Crane said. ``Older drivers,
we've found, are much better drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   The last young driver the firm employed ``got into a running
yelling match with another driver, driving crazy and flipping him
off,'' Crane said. The man was fired after only a few days on the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Crane said he's careful to advertise for ``mature, reliable
people with good driving records.'' Most applicants are older
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't just hire older drivers,'' said sales manager Ron
Darrow. ``That would be discrimination. But we're looking for
people who are reliable and have experience _ and these older guys
are it.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior-citizen couriers, who earn $6.50 to $11 per hour, say
the job gives them some extra money as well as a way to feel
useful, to be outdoors, to be pretty much on their own. And it's
very different from the way they earned a living for years.
</P>
<P>
   David Bullock, 63, of Woodland Hills said he's had a lot more
fun being a driver the past five years than he had teaching
chemistry and biology to indifferent students at Taft High School,
a job he retired from nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And Peter Smart, 68, of Calabasas said the courier job he's held
for three years, since retiring as a program manager for Litton,
leaves him plenty of time to play golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part-time, and it's easy,'' he said. ``And there's nobody
to supervise you, and you don't have to explain anything to
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Butler, 73, is glad to demonstrate that older workers can
be a boon to a company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of companies are realizing that just because
somebody's 65, it doesn't mean he should be put in the trash,''
said the Chatsworth man, who's been a medical courier for eight
years, since retiring from overlapping careers as a motorcycle
salesman (15 years) and an auto mechanic (25 years).
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said he and the other drivers offer what no young person
can _ a lifetime of experience, which gives them good judgment, and
an awareness of their own mortality, which keeps them from taking
unnecessary chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think older people make fewer errors because they take their
time,'' he said. ``When you're a kid, you think you're going to
live forever. When you're older, you don't have much life left to
live, so you want to make the most of it. You're a lot more
careful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
