<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-PROBLEMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNERSHIP FUZZY IN DIGITAL WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the gap between the computerized world and
the real one shrinking quickly, the implications of virtual actors
become more interesting. And so do the accompanying problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as you can kidnap real people to make money, you can
kidnap virtual people to make money,'' said Joseph Beard, a St.
John's University law professor who specializes in intellectual
property issues.
</P>
<P>
   By kidnapping, Beard means swiping the virtual re-creation of a
person, living or dead, and using it for profit. And that will get
easier and easier the more powerful and accessible the technology
becomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers tend to lag (behind) technology,'' said Beard. ``I
really thought we would have longer than we do have. But the
technology's really taken off. The goal is to be indistinguishable
from real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Swiss researcher Nadia Thalmann's MIRALab at the
University of Geneva can take two digitized photographs of a person
and spit out a pretty good 3-D computer copy that talks and makes
appropriate facial gestures and interactions.
</P>
<P>
   Given the burgeoning business of celebrity porn on the Internet,
particularly where a star's face is digitally pasted onto someone
else's nude body, the implications for digital theft can be
dizzying, and troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm W.C. (Field)'s grandson,'' said Ronald Fields, a
television writer whose grandfather has been rendered into a
digital character that cracks jokes, looks at questioners and
twirls his cigar. ``He's a real guy in our family. I feel, even if
I were a teetotaler, a Mormon, and Southern Comfort came and wanted
to do a commercial with him, I'd say yes because that was his
image. But if someone wanted to do a nude poster, I'd stop it.
That's my grandfather. I want to protect his image.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Rosenthal, who represents many celebrities' estates in
trying to stop improper use of their images, said copyright and
trademark laws are far from clear in what can be done to stop
digital kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain and New York have virtually no prohibitions on the
use of a dead celebrity's image, Rosenthal said. California gives
the estate control for 50 years, while Indiana has a tough 100-year
rule and other restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to happen,'' Beard said. ``If an
unscrupulous producer can take a couple of on-line stills and marry
them to a body double to make a porn flick, they will. The same
thing with overseas piracy of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But Beard and others said serious work needs to be done to
update laws governing intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the laws were created with the analog world in mind, and
now we're dealing with the digital world,'' Beard said. ``I
personally think the laws need some tweaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The laws assume, for instance, that once a celebrity is dead,
his or her works are ``frozen in time; no more films will be
made,'' Beard said. ``Now, that's no longer the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The current widely differing patchwork of state laws begs for
some national legislation providing ``sufficient postmortem
protection,'' Beard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem I have is you can only control this so much,''
Fields said. ``There are thieves out there, and it is going to
happen, and we have to try to stop them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
