<HEADER>
A2185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-KELLY-BOS &LR;      06-29 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KELLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KELLY LOVES TONY' PERSONALIZES ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
KELLY LOVES TONY 
Produced and directed by: Spencer Nakasako 
On: PBS 
Date: Tuesday6/30at 10 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When A-student Kelly Saeteurn graduates from high school, she's
already pregnant by her 22-year-old boyfriend Tony Saelio. But
she's resourceful and optimistic, set on marrying the ex-gang
member and school droput, Tony, going to college, and attaining her
dreams of success, American-style.
</P>
<P>
   Thus begins ``Kelly Loves Tony,'' a highly personal, rawly
crafted video diary covering 18 months in their strained and
culturally divided life. Kelly and Tony are both Iu Mien, a Laotion
hill tribe, but have grown up in Oakland, Calif., straddling
American society and their families' tribal traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Their story, full of potential drama and revelation that is too
rarely realized, will be aired Tuesday at 10 p.m. as part of the
independent non-fiction PBS film series, ``P.O.V.''
</P>
<P>
   Supplied with a camcorder by director Spencer Nakasako, the
young couple shot the video themselves. The advantage of the
approach is an intimacy and occasional honesty, especially when
Kelly's alone addressing the unmanned camera, perhaps otherwise
unattainable.
</P>
<P>
   In one monologue, Kelly, whose cheer and grit begin to ebb after
she moves in with Tony's big, demanding family, vents her
frustration. She has been caring for her infant, laboring for the
family's approval so she can marry Tony, commuting to a community
college, and worrying about Tony's possible deportation to Laos.
``It's like 10 loads of dirty laundry,'' she says, ``and it all
piles up, and I have to finish it in two hours.'' The homeliness of
Kelly's metaphor and her easy, striking directness cut to the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   But assigning this couple to shoot all their own video footage
has almost overwhelming disadvantages. The most obvious is that,
while Kelly and Tony separately interrogate each other from behind
the camera, they can't both interact visually (or very easily,
since one of them is always filming). This is, at best, a
cumbersome way to dramatize the documentary's central relationship;
at worst, impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Tony, whose speech can often barely be understood, has
little feel for using the camera. For example, on his way to work
at a local Asian youth center, he films the sidewalk while
typically mumbling his narration.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, there's pathos in his awkwardness, which can perhaps
be read as pained self-consciousness, and in his stilted
declarations of love for his ``dream lady'' and infant son. But
Tony doesn't grow or change, and while his underdevelopment is part
of this sad chronicle, it is also a large part of its undoing. On
camera and behind it, Tony, the film's ``co-star'' if you will, is
neither interesting nor dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   This could have, perhaps should have, been a searing story of
young lives overwhelmed, hopes tragically smothered. But neither
the director nor the camcorder couple can fully awaken, much less
shape, their dormant narrative or its promising themes about
immigration and the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   It takes art to universalize personal experience _ without it,
banality beckons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
