<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA BAR DUMPS INVESTIGATIVE TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Californians who feel cheated or neglected by
their lawyer now have only one recourse: Get another lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a political fight in the state capital, the State Bar
of California has cut all but 20 of the 283 employees who
investigate consumer complaints against attorneys and who prosecute
bad lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 140,000 attorneys in the state of California _ more
than any other country _ and now there is no oversight and no
disciplinary process,'' said Clothilde Hewlett, one of the few bar
employees who was not terminated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Now the only way consumers can get back at an attorney who
cheats them is to find another lawyer willing to sue for
malpractice or take the case to a district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The bar receives about 140,000 complaints a year and opens files
on 15,000 cases. The vast majority do not end in discipline, said
Steven Nissen, State Bar executive director. But the mere existence
of a complaint often leads to the parties working out their
differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're not opening any new cases,'' Nissen said. ``There's
no buffer for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   There will no longer be a hot line for consumers _ a person can
only mail a written complaint to the State Bar, Nissen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the staff to investigate it; we'll time-stamp it
and warehouse it'' until some undetermined future time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Gov. Pete Wilson vetoed funding for the State Bar,
calling it bloated, arrogant and too political. Since then,
legislators have been unable to craft a deal to authorize the
agency to continue collecting annual license fees from the state's
lawyers, the agency's primary source of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has presented a reasonable offer that allows for
the continuous operation of the State Bar and protects the judicial
evaluation and discipline process,'' Wilson spokesman Ron Low said.
``As we have stated from the beginning, we are willing to listen to
reasonable proposals from the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   The laid-off State Bar investigators said the general public
does not care about squabbles in Sacramento. But they want to see
attorneys, who have the power to interpret and possibly manipulate
the law, regulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel like I've provided a valuable service to the
public and it's the people of California who are the real losers
here,'' said J.D. Pickering, who spent 12 years investigating
complaints against attorneys. ``I love this work. I think the
people of California will be worse off without us.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could give exact numbers, but it is believed that only a
handful of attorneys have been prosecuted in criminal courts for
cheating clients.
</P>
<P>
   Membership in the bar is mandatory but many attorneys are
uncomfortable that their dues have been used for lobbying and
political advocacy. Wilson spokesman Sean Walsh said recently that
every time the governor gets on a plane, ``every lawyer gets on a
conga line to high-five him for his efforts to reform the (State)
Bar.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Bar asked the state Supreme Court earlier this week to
grant an interim order that would immediately have set attorneys'
licensing fees at $364 for 1998, but the court denied the request
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wilson's veto, the State Bar collected $458 per year from
each attorney to pay for most of its $61 million annual budget. But
critics have noted the annual fee is more than twice the national
average, which they say is too high.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's issues with the State Bar date back to at least 1982
when, as a U.S. Senate candidate, he was censured by a bar group
for threatening to lead a recall of the state Supreme Court if it
overturned a crime initiative. More recently, the Republican
governor got angry when a bar commission that evaluates candidates
for the bench gave an unqualified rating to his most recent Supreme
Court nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a month ago, Wilson announced his terms for saving the
State Bar. Among them: reducing dues to $295 per year and
transforming the policy-making board into a body appointed by the
governor. Wilson said the State Bar's functions should be limited
to admissions, discipline and education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1613EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
