<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV05-NY     06-29 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAME THAT NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 5.)  
 (Eds., items in boldface should be set in italics.)  
 (HLW)  
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On this Independence Day weekend, it is fitting and timely to
ask: Who coined the name  &UR; United States of America &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   In the year before independence, many in the colonies went with
the name used by Benjamin Franklin in his July 1775 draft of an
articles of confederation:  &UR; United Colonies of North America &LR; .
Another name, however, most famously appeared in print on July 4,
1776, in the Declaration of Independence, which was drafted by a
committee that assigned the task to Thomas Jefferson: its last
paragraph referred to ``the Representatives of the United States of
America, in General Congress Assembled.''
</P>
<P>
   In our first exploration of this mystery a few months ago, it
was reported that the widely accepted Jefferson coinage (written by
Young Tom between June 11 and June 28, 1776) might have been
antedated by two other citations: the first in a letter from
Continental Congress member Elbridge Gerry to Gen. Horatio Gates
dated June 25, and the second in a letter to The Pennsylvania
Evening Post published on June 29, from the pseudonymous writer
``Republicus.''
</P>
<P>
   This is important; it's our country we're talking about, and we
ought to try to pin down its namer. Two letters have come pouring
in. One is from a biographer of Thomas Paine, Professor Jack
Fruchtman Jr., of Towson University, in Maryland, who insists that
Paine's usage two years after the Declaration in his widely read
``American Crisis'' publicized the name. Call me a summer soldier
or sunshine patriot, but common sense tells me that a popularizer
is not a coiner.
</P>
<P>
   Comes now Ronald Gephart, last of the editors of the Library of
Congress' 25-volume ``Letters of Delegates to Congress,
1774-1789.'' He searched his new CD-ROM of all that correspondence,
then dug around in the Journals of the Continental Congress, and
alerted me to his findings just in time for the nation's 222nd
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Henry Lee of Virginia was the Founder who made the
motion on June 7, 1776, to declare ``that these United Colonies
are, and of right ought to be, free and independent States.'' His
resolution led to the formation of three committees: one, starring
Jefferson and John Adams, to draft a declaration of independence;
another, including John Dickenson, the conservative Pennsylvanian,
and Roger Sherman, to draft articles of confederation, and a third,
including Dickenson, Adams, and Franklin, to draft a treaty plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three committees began deliberating simultaneously,''
writes Gephart, ``and continued to do so until the end of June.
Jefferson accepted the responsibility for drafting the declaration,
Dickenson the articles, and Adams the treaty plan. But as many as
18 members of the three committees were working together to create
these three fundamental documents in which  &UR; United States of
America &LR;  was used for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   So who came up with the catchy name for which the initials are
not UCNA but USA? We know that Dickenson had by June 17 prepared a
second draft _ all that survives _ of the articles, which includes
the flat statement: ``The name of this Confederation shall be the
` &UR; United States of America &LR; .''' Nothing tentative about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jefferson, on the other hand,'' writes Gephart, ``did not ask
Franklin to review his draft of `A Declaration by the
Representatives of the  &UR; United States of America &LR; ' until June 21.
It is not known when Adams drafted the preamble to the plan of
treaties.''
</P>
<P>
   The historian concludes cautiously: ``The term was first coined
by one or more members during the early deliberations of the three
committees _ between June 11, when Jefferson's committee began
work, and June 17, when it appeared in the second draft of
Dickenson's Articles.''
</P>
<P>
   Coinagists would give the edge to the conciliatory Dickenson
(who refused to sign Jefferson's Declaration), partly because the
first recorded surfacing of the phrase was his, and partly because
he's not as famous as Jefferson and can use the recognition.
</P>
<P>
   I'd still like to see Dickenson's first draft, with date. Keep
looking, historians; it's not as if he were working on a word
processor that obliterates first drafts. It would be of great
interest to all of us here in the good old UCNA, or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   CHILLING EFFECT
</P>
<P>
   ``A chilling sweat o'er-runs my trembling joints,'' says the
frightened Quintus in Shakespeare's ``Titus Andronicus.'' Such a
flush of fear stimulates the sweat glands, which then cool the skin
with perspiration, metaphorically dampening ardor and freezing
action. In underworld lingo, the verb to chill is to change a warm
body into a cool corpse.
</P>
<P>
   When it was discovered last month that City College of New York
had installed a surveillance camera inside a smoke detector outside
a student meeting room, three graduate students sued the school on
privacy grounds. Brad Sigal, a graduate student, said: ``It
definitely has a  &UR; chilling effect &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   This phrase has now become the great cliche in First Amendment
and libel law. Chief Justice Warren Burger used it 15 times in a
1972 opinion. A  &UR; chilling effect &LR;  is one that intimidates, makes
timorous and turns timid (all from  &UR; timere &LR; , ``to fear'') the
ordinarily gutsy journalist, causing the sin of self-censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Who coined it? Forget early cases about coolants. According to
Bryan Garner, editor of the Dictionary of Modern Legal Usage, the
earliest metaphoric use found so far was in 1899, by
Vice-Chancellor Henry Cooper Pitney, of New Jersey: ``This letter
the wife swears she interpreted as one of intentional
discouragement to her return, and that it had a  &UR; chilling effect &LR; 
on her.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus are we coming up to the centennial of  &UR; chilling effect &LR; .
Break out the very cold Champagne, and toast the phrase good-bye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2197 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     06-29 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUS CHAT WORTH MORE THAN TOKEN IN TEREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - I'm not one of those folks who never met a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   You know the type. They smile easily, laugh loudly and strike up
conversations anywhere _ on airplanes, in grocery stores, even in
the bathroom at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Like many newspaper and media types, I'm a little shy around
people I don't know. An editor once told me he thought most of us
were, and that's why we go into the business. It forces us to talk
to people, to overcome our aversion to chatting up a total
stranger.
</P>
<P>
   When a deadline looms and you've got to know (begin ital) right
now (end ital) why a person decided to set fire to a row of
oleanders, it tends to increase your assertiveness level
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   I've always admired people who could make that kind of
conversation naturally, even if countless of their number have
annoyed me on airplanes while I tried to nap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to St. Louis?'' they'll grin, as if more than one answer
were possible. I've always wanted to shriek and bolt from my seat
and start screaming, ``St. Louis? STOP THE PLANE! I thought we were
going to Cleveland!''
</P>
<P>
   It's all a matter of whether being banned by the airline for
life would be worth the look on the person's face.
</P>
<P>
   I came across one of these easy talkers the other day. I had to
run to catch a bus. As I fumbled for change, the driver told me I
needn't have hurried, that she always checks for stragglers before
pulling back into traffic.
</P>
<P>
   She started this train of thought as I paid my fare, and
continued as I took the only available seat, just behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough, I thought as I nodded. Then she started in with
general chitchat about how traffic wasn't bad for a Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   This was casual, bartender-type chatter. I felt no obligation to
do anything more than nod or mumble the occasional ``um-hmm.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, from out of nowhere, she got personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first day back,'' she said. ``My sister just had
surgery and I had to be there for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The casual eavesdropper would have thought that we were related,
that she was filling me in on how a cousin was faring after an
appendectomy. She talked as if she were resuming a conversation we
had been having minutes before. Only we had never seen each other
in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   We had reached that crucial point. She had engaged me and waited
for a response, even as she made stops for disembarking passengers
and greeted new ones.
</P>
<P>
   This is where I usually drop the ball. If I just sat there and
fidgeted with my glasses or scratched an imaginary itch on my arm
or something, that would be that.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if she knew me. A couple more stops and we would be
done, both gone our separate ways, the story she had tried to start
a pleasant-enough, though fleeting, memory.
</P>
<P>
   But she had been nice and clearly wanted to continue, so I bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, just what she wanted to hear. She launched into a nearly
perfect spiel about her sister: She caught me up on her condition
(she was OK) without ever actually telling me what exactly was
wrong with her.
</P>
<P>
   She did give some details. She and her sister are identical
twins, she explained. She had donated a couple of pints of blood,
just in case.
</P>
<P>
   This led to a rather touching revelation on her part of how
lucky she felt to have an identical twin, to have a guaranteed
donor on hand, if it came to that.
</P>
<P>
   Other business captured her attention from there. She helped a
man in a wheelchair board the bus and explained routes to a couple
of passengers trying to wend their way to Apache Junction. A
handful of stops later, and I was on my way.
</P>
<P>
   As I walked from my stop, I again thought about how reluctant I
would have been to launch into a conversation like that with a
stranger.
</P>
<P>
   And how glad I was to have run into someone who wasn't. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  CHINA-HISTBOX-COX &UR;      06-29 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 CHINA-HISTBOX-COX    
 &HT;     TAIWAN _ WHERE A CRISIS IS ALWAYS WAITING TO HAPPEN
 &HT;     With CLINTON-CHINA-MAIN 
 &HT;     For Use Tuesday, June 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ History suggests that Taiwan is the issue most
likely to lead to a world flashpoint between the United States and
China in the 21st Century. And as President Clinton learned Monday
from questioning by students at Beijing University, reunification
with the mainland is an important issue even among young Chinese.
Here is the background:
</P>
<P>
   1885 - Poor Province. The backward, thinly populated island of
Taiwan, or Formosa, becomes a province of imperial China. Most of
the 3 million inhabitants are Malayo-Polynesian ethnics.
</P>
<P>
   1895-1945 - Japanese Colony. Taiwan falls under Japanese
colonial rule. The economy flourishes. Education and income levels
inch upward. As China bogs down in civil war, Taiwan becomes more
developed than the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   1947 - Nationalist Redoubt. China's ruling Nationalist Party
forces are losing the Chinese civil war. They begin retreating to a
military base camp on Taiwan and assert control over the local
population.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 20, 1947 - Taiwan massacre. Local Taiwanese riot against
brutal measures by the mainland newcomers. Some Nationalist Chinese
troops open fire into a Taiwanese crowd, killing many and fostering
decades of resentment.
</P>
<P>
   June 1949 - Promise to Return. Nationalist Chinese leader
Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek retreats to Taiwan but promises to
return some day to take over the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   January 1950 - Crucial Omission. Declarations by the Truman
administration define a new Pacific ``defense perimeter'' that does
not include Taiwan. Truman said the U.S. ``will not provide
military aid or advice to Chinese forces'' on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Summer 1950 - Truman Reversal. With the outbreak of the Korean
war, China transfers a large military force to coastal Fujian
province, 120 miles from Taiwan. Truman decides to protect Taiwan
against a Chinese invasion, and the island becomes an ardent U.S.
ally
</P>
<P>
   1950-55 - On the Brink. Chinese troops shell the
Nationalist-held islands of Quemoy and Matsu, lying within 15 miles
of the Chinese coast. This spawns a running conflict that verges on
U.S.-China war. The U.S. and Nationalist China (Taiwan) sign a
mutual defense treaty.
</P>
<P>
   May 1955 - China Recedes. China decides to let the Nationalists
keep Quemoy and Matsu. With artful ambiguity, Chinese statesman
Zhou Enlai says China will strive to liberate Taiwan ``by peaceful
means so far as it is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   October 1971 - Taiwan Isolated. Diplomatic support for Taiwan
evaporates following news that President Richard Nixon plans a trip
to mainland China. The U.N. General Assembly grants China's U.N.
seat to the mainland government and expels Taiwan delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 28, 1972 - One China. President Nixon finishes historic
visit to China by declaring that ``there is but one China and
Taiwan is part of China.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan 1, 1979 - Breakoff. President Jimmy Carter ``normalizes''
relations with China, which means ending diplomatic recognition
with Taiwan and exchanging ambassadors with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Spring 1979 _ Congress Intervenes. To protect Taiwan, the U.S.
Congress passes the Taiwan Relations Act obligating the U.S. to
defend Taiwan from Chinese aggression. Carter signs the bill in
April, and arms sales to Taiwan continue.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 31, 1979 _ Treaty canceled. As part of ``normalization''
with the mainland, Carter abrogates America's 1954 mutual defense
treaty with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 17, 1982 - Arms Sales. President Ronald Reagan pledges
gradual reduction in sales of U.S. weapons to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   1991 - Olive Branch. Taiwan renounces force to retake the
mainland, and informal talks begin with China.
</P>
<P>
   June 1995 - New Friction. Taiwan president Lee Teng-hui makes
``private'' trip to the United States for a Cornell University
reunion. China blasts this as a plot to promote Taiwan independence
and accuses Clinton administration of reneging on 1978 decision to
break Taiwan ties.
</P>
<P>
   July-October 1995 - Missile Test. China ratchets up pressure by
firing unarmed nuclear-capable missiles, then staging a live-fire
naval exercise off the Chinese coast.
</P>
<P>
   March 1996 - U.S. Carriers. China holds televised live-fire war
games in Taiwan Strait. Clinton responds by dispatching two
nuclear-armed carrier battle groups to waters near Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   1997-98 - De-escalation. Taiwan and China mend fences through
family visits, business deals and informal negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Early June 1998 - Congress Demands. By 411-0, U.S. House of
Representatives adopts resolution demanding that China abandon its
threat to invade Taiwan if the island declares its independence.
China refuses.
</P>
<P>
   June 18, 1998 - Taiwan Suspends. Taiwan suspends summer war
games to avoid being ``troublemaker'' during Clinton visit to
China.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
