<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2239 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ANCIENT-FAKE-ROCK     06-29 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANCIENT-FAKE-ROCK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLIEST KNOWN FAKE STONE IS DISCOVERED IN SOUTHERN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: Photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
212 556-4204.) 
 (The Science Times) 
(HLW) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On broad plains layered with silt from the Tigris and Euphrates
Rivers, the people of ancient Mesopotamia managed to build the
first cities and spreading empires without local sources of such
raw materials of civilization as timber, metal ores, and stone.
What they could not import, they had to do without, or, as
archeologists have now discovered, learn how to make synthetic
substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, archeologists and geologists reported finding the
first evidence of artificial stone in the ruins of Mashkan-shapir,
a city that existed about 4,000 years ago in what is now southern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Artisans had apparently heated fine-grained alluvial silt to
melting temperatures, then slowly cooled it to produce rock-hard
slab resembling a type of volcanic rock called basalt.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elizabeth C. Stone, an archeologist at the State University
of New York, at Stony Brook, described the discovery in the current
issue of the journal Science and in interviews. The findings were
based on a recent geological analysis of 17 pieces of stone
collected before the Persian Gulf war in 1991, and more soil and
stone samples borrowed from a museum in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stone's excavations in the late 1980s established
Mashkan-shapir as a relatively large city of 15,000 people in the
early second millennium B.C., after the collapse of the city of Ur
as the center of power. After a brief period of glory,
Mashkan-shapir declined and was abandoned in 1720 B.C. Its ruins
disappeared in the desert until archeologists began digging there
in this century.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the synthetic rock slabs, which measure about 30 inches
long, 16 inches wide, and 3 inches thick, were found in ruins near
one of the city's temples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they looked right,'' Dr. Stone said in an
interview. ``I thought, ah, this is just bad basalt.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her colleagues, Dr. Donald H. Lindsley, a Stony Brook
geologist, tested the slabs and linked them to local soils and to
several hundred fragments of rock found across the site. He and
other researchers satisfied themselves that the slabs were not
merely slag from metal or pottery furnaces.
</P>
<P>
   The synthetic basalt, Dr. Stone and her colleagues reported,
``appears to have been manufactured in some quantity as a
substitute for the natural basalt that had been used for grinding
grain in all parts of the ancient Near East since the beginning of
agriculture.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the coincidence of a scholar named Stone from a
university in Stony Brook finding the earliest known fake stone,
the discovery is noteworthy because it should provide new insights
into the history of ancient technology, especially the innovative
uses of fire in transforming raw materials into pottery, metal,
plaster, and glass.
</P>
<P>
   Such early production of synthetic stone was previously unknown
to historians, but its discovery suggests the existence of a
creative collaboration between metallurgists and ceramicists in
Mesopotamia about 4,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stone and her associates said that the deliberate production
of synthetic rock suggested that Mesopotamian artisans had learned
the technology from their experience in smelting metals and baking
pottery. The intense heats applied in those processes produced a
byproduct of slag that bore similarities to volcanic rock.
</P>
<P>
   The new evidence, the archeologists said in their conclusion,
``suggests that the potentialities of those byproducts as a
substitute for imported grinding stones was perceived and that the
pyrotechnologies developed by potters and smiths were pooled in an
experimental process that eventually yielded a consistent
product.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dr. Vincent C. Pigott, a specialist in ancient
technologies at the University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archeology
and Anthropology, who participated in the artificial-stone study,
said he doubted that this was a true example of need being the
mother of invention, even though Mesopotamians clearly needed
scarce stone for building and grinding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know the pathways by which these people came
to artificial basalt,'' Pigott said. ``But most innovations in
technology proceed from experimentation and esthetics, not need.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Iraq is again open to archeological work, Dr. Stone said,
many questions about the artificial basalt will remain unanswered.
She would like to return to Mashkan-shapir to search for the
furnaces that were used for making the stone. They were at least
three feet in diameter, judging by the size of the largest slabs.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the furnaces could reveal much about the actual process
of making artificial stone some 4,000 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
