<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D'AMATO-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS D'AMATO FACING LESS-THAN-EASY CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARVY LIPMAN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Two of the three times Alfonse D'Amato has won
elections for the U.S. Senate, he has eked by with less than 50
percent of the vote. If the latest poll numbers hold up, he's
headed for a similar squeaker in November.
</P>
<P>
   Despite aggressive early advertising and weeks of campaign-style
public appearances, D'Amato holds only a slight edge over his
closest Democratic challenger, former congresswoman and vice
presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro, according to a new Albany
Times Union-Syracuse Newspapers poll conducted by Zogby
International in Utica, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 707 registered voters also showed that after three
terms in office, more voters had a negative view of D'Amato than a
positive view.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al D'Amato was `Candidate A' and I looked at his numbers, I
would say he's dead in the water,'' said pollster John Zogby.
``He's an incumbent under 50 percent and he's leading by less than
10 percent. Under normal circumstances, that's a sure defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Zogby said, ``this is D'Amato.''
</P>
<P>
   Zogby was referring to the senator's history of overtaking
opponents who lead him early in the race, despite low approval
ratings in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago he had a 26 percent positive job performance
rating. Now it's in the 40s. All his indicators are up.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Zogby noted, D'Amato also has already raised about $17
million for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro led her two competitors for the nomination in the
September primary, with nearly 40 percent of those Democrats who
said they were likely to vote favoring Ferraro. That's
two-and-a-half times the number who support Rep. Charles Schumer of
Brooklyn, and four times more than support New York City Public
Advocate Mark Green, who lost to D'Amato in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But Zogby said those poll numbers could be misleading, because
the poll also shows most voters don't yet know who Ferraro's
opponents are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like Ferraro's support is thin,'' he said. ``It's
name-recognition support.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that either Schumer or Green has made up much ground in the
past couple of months. Schumer has gone from 12 percent to 16
percent since April _ while spending a couple of million dollars on
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schumer's problem is that he just doesn't seem to connect with
the voters,'' Zogby said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro was leading by tremendous margins in upstate New York
and the New York City suburbs, where Schumer and Green aren't
well-known. Nearly three of four upstate voters said they were not
familiar enough with Schumer and Green to voice an opinion about
them. More than half those in the New York City suburbs said the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   That unfamiliarity is reflected in which candidate people
support. Nearly half the upstate Democrats said they supported
Ferraro, while Schumer and Green pulled in a combined seven
percent. In the New York City suburbs, Ferraro carried about 40
percent to Schumer's 10 percent and Green's 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Her big lead disappears in New York City, however, where voters
recognize her challengers' names. Only about 25 percent of New York
City residents said they were unfamiliar with Green, and about 33
percent did not know Schumer. Ferraro took 30 percent of the city
vote, to Schumer's 27 percent and Green's 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If she's looking for a big edge among women voters, however,
Ferraro may be in for a surprise. Her lead is noticeably bigger
among men _ 3-to-1 over Schumer and nearly 4-to-1 over Green _ than
it is among female voters. Among women, her lead over Schumer drops
to 2-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever emerges from the Democratic primary will face an
incumbent whose numbers, while not overwhelmingly positive, are
heading up. In a Zogby poll last month, more than half of those
polled gave D'Amato a negative job performance rating. In the
latest poll, the negative number was down to 48 percent _ still
high for a candidate seeking re-election, but lower than figures
D'Amato has registered at this point in previous races.
</P>
<P>
   His positive rating, meanwhile, rose from 38 percent in May to
44 percent in the latest poll.
</P>
<P>
   But that figure relates to his job performance. D'Amato enjoys
higher numbers when voters are asked whether they view him
favorably or unfavorably. By a 2-to-1 margin, those polled said
they have a favorable opinion of the senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This poll shows that working middle-class families of New York
know they've never had a stronger and more effective fighter than
Al D'Amato,'' D'Amato spokesman Harvey Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted June 14-15. It has a margin of error of
plus or minus 3.8 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
