<HEADER>
A2283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     06-29 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, June 30. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-RUBIN (Bangkok, Thailand) _ After a whirlwind visit to
Malaysia, in which he defended the International Monetary Fund's
harsh prescriptions for healing Asia's economies, Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin arrived on Monday evening in the place where
the financial contagion first began. Rubin will meet on Tuesday
with Thailand's prime minister, Chuan Leekpai, and other officials
to discuss their efforts to climb out of a recession _ nearly one
year to the day since Bangkok floated its currency, prompting a
devastating devaluation from which it has yet to recover. Rubin's
tour of Asia comes as the IMF is under growing attack from
politicians and businessmen here, who say the fund's formula of
high interest rates, rigorous fiscal policy, and stable currencies
is strangling the region's economies and worsening the pain of the
crisis. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TV-COVERAGE (Undated) _ When a Beijing University student
asked whether Americans have a distorted view of China, President
Clinton answered by pointing to a gallery crammed with lights and
cameras. ``As you can see, a few people come with me from the news
media,'' he said. ``I hoped that my trip would help show a full and
balanced picture of modern China.'' He almost got his wish. Though
intensely focused on human rights, television has depicted a
country so complex and changeable that reporters can hardly keep
up. One minute they are wondering why dissidents were arrested
during Clinton's trip (deliberate insult or public relations
gaffe?). The next, they are wondering why President Jiang Zemin
allowed his joint news conference with Clinton to be televised live
(sign of freedom or public relations coup?) By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Belacevac, Yugoslavia) _ Thousands of Serb special
police units and troops, backed by artillery, heavy armor, and
tanks, launched a series of attacks against separatist rebel
positions on Monday morning. Heavy armored personnel carriers
unleashed volleys at trenches and checkpoints held by lightly armed
Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas in the mining town of Belacevac,
six miles west of Pristina, the provincial capital. Serb gunners
also attacked Lapushnik, where rebels have barricaded the main road
leading from Pristina to Pec. Trucks and jeeps, packed with
soldiers in green camouflage uniforms that lacked unit insignias,
sped to the two battle fronts. There was no word on casualties. By
Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Issuing the strongest signal yet
of his frustration with the government's peace policies, President
Ezer Weizman on Monday publicly urged Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to call early elections. Weizman's largely ceremonial
office does not give him the power to dissolve the government or
call elections, and Netanyahu immediately responded that he had no
intention of so doing until his four-year term concludes in 2000.
But the unusual statement placed the popular and outspoken
president squarely in opposition to the prime minister, and gave
new credibility and strength to the notion that if Netanyahu is
unable to progress on the long-stalled peace with his two-year-old
coalition, he should take it to the voters. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-SOLDIERS-U.N. (United Nations) _ As a measure of how
dramatically the face of modern warfare has changed in the last
decade, the Security Council spent its day on Monday debating the
rapid increase in the number of child soldiers worldwide and what,
if anything, can be done to keep children out of war. Experts say
that from 250,000 to 300,000 children in at least 50 countries are
directly involved in conflict around the world _ as soldiers,
porters and frequently as all-purpose camp slaves _ in violation of
international treaties. Children are conscripted, cajoled, or
tricked into volunteering and sometimes sold to armies and
guerrilla groups by families thrown into poverty by ethnic
conflicts that now kill more civilians than troops. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-YEAR (Washington) _ The Supreme Court aimed for clarity
and, to an unusual degree, achieved it in the term that ended on
Friday after a final week's deluge of important rulings. The
justices spoke forcefully in drawing a coherent rule on sexual
harassment from a jumble of confusing precedents and vague
congressional language. They established a framework for applying
the new federal disability law's protections to people with
asymptomatic HIV infection and other conditions that may not at
first glance appear to qualify as disabling. They quickly put to
rest Congress' experiment with the line item veto as well as the
independent counsel's effort to pierce the shield of the
attorney-client privilege. These decisions, and nearly all the
others of the term's 91 rulings, were supported by clear
majorities, free of the ambiguities that often plague the court's
efforts to wrestle with highly charged subjects. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Appeals court hears arguments on
whether White House lawyer Bruce Lindsey can be forced to testify
about his discussions with President Clinton. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Nothing at this hour.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   URANIUM-PRIVATE (Washington) _ Trying to privatize the
government factories that process uranium for nuclear power plants,
the Treasury announces that it will make an initial public
offering, selling shares to the public, because it was unable to
get decent bids from corporate buyers. Prospects for this business
are poor. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   FOX-NETWORK (Undated) _ Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. plans to
sell as much as 20 percent of the Fox Group, which will include the
Fox television network, 20th Century Fox movie studio, and the Los
Angeles Dodgers, in a public stock offering. The stock offering may
give the News Corp. a way to unlock the value behind the media
assets by separating them from the company's publishing businesses.
Murdoch has been under pressure from investors to increase the
stock price of his company. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
</TEXT>
