<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2289 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIER1-GIROUARD-960(2T NEWPIER1CEO MAD 06-29 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIER1-GIROUARD-960(2Takes)-TA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADE HIS MARK BY TRAVELING THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 MARVIN GIROUARD, NEW PIER 1 CEO,(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Marvin Girouard is probably not your
father's idea of a chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's newest CEO, who took over last week at Pier 1
Imports, likes to talk about his rock 'n' roll days as a teen and
the time he hitchhiked to New Orleans with Janis Joplin.
</P>
<P>
   He traces his sense of style to a maverick grandfather who ran
gambling and prostitution houses during the Texas oil boom. He is
so tickled by celebrities that he decorates his office wall with
autographed photos of Meg Ryan and Katie Couric.
</P>
<P>
   But Girouard (pronounced Gerard) has substance as well as
sizzle. He was senior class president at Texas A&AMP;M, a member of the
cadet corps and later a Navy commando in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In the business world, he has been a globe-hopping merchant who
knew which village in Malaysia could produce 10,000 inlaid boxes in
time for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   And he has been a loyal corporate employee, shunning offers to
lead other retailers and keeping his composure when an outsider was
once picked to run the company instead of him.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is not widely known outside his industry, for 23
years Girouard has worked in key roles for Pier 1, the Fort
Worth-based retailer that does more than a billion dollars in
annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Girouard initially oversaw the worldwide buying that came to
define the home furnishings retailer. For t`e!past decade, he has
been the No. 2 executive who kept operations on track.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, less than two months shy of his 59th birthday,
Girouard finally grabbed the brass ring: He was named chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pier 1 had everything I wanted,'' Girouard said, explaining
why he hung in so long. ``It's like falling in love with a woman or
a beautiful car. Once you find the one you want, you'll wait
forever to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Girouard's climb up the corporate ladder is a tribute to
patience, persistence and loyalty, traits that may seem at odds
with a country-singing Aggie who collects German sports cars and
Rolex watches.
</P>
<P>
   But Girouard often seems to be an odd mix of flash and
conservatism. He made his mark by traveling the world, but once
refused to take a job _ even though he had children and was
unemployed _ because it would force him to move from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He owns three Porsches, wears Italian suits and buys custom-made
shirts in Hong Kong. But his favorite reading includes the National
Enquirer and the Star tabloids, and a top hobby is collecting
baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   Girouard is not physically imposing and admits that he was never
a great athlete. But he led a Navy commando unit in Vietnam,
parachuting onto beaches and swimming up rivers.
</P>
<P>
   In his early days at Pier 1, he was known as ``The Night
Fighter.'' During an uptempo moment at one meeting, an executive
challenged everyone to a push-up contest. Girouard blew away the
competition when he sprang to the floor and started doing them
one-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a quiet man,'' said Bob Bolen, the former Fort
Worth mayor and Hallmark store owner who frequently swaps retailing
tales with Girouard. ``His nature is to make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When Girouard applied to Pier 1 in 1975, he had to fill out a
standard job form, and one line asked how he would get to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my Porsche!'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, he was overseeing the company's worldwide
buying, which had him scouring the globe for the trinkets,
housewares and rattan furniture that became Pier 1's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   As Pier 1 began to improve in the early '80s, his role became
increasingly important. With the company adding stores and
upgrading its product line, Girouard not only had to find
interesting, low-cost items, he also had to build the Asian supply
connections that could keep the inventories full.
</P>
<P>
   When Pier 1 picked a new top executive in 1980, Girouard had
hoped to be the choice. He wasn't. Five years later, when the chief
executive left, Girouard made a pitch directly to the board. Again
he was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Although Girouard said he felt like the builder and owner of
Pier 1, he conceded, ``Now I know that I didn't have the vision or
the experience that this job demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. For the past decade, Girouard has been Pier 1's
strong second-in-command, earning more than $1.2 million last year
and serving as a complement to top executive Clark Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who led Pier 1 for 13 years, stepped aside last week
and became nonexecutive chairman. The two were not close friends
away from the office, but they made a strong team, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was Mr. Outside, a smooth, formal executive who refined
Pier 1's public persona and sharpened the strategy that made it one
of the country's leading speciality retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Girouard was Mr. Inside, a scrappy operations man who can find
almost any item almost anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Among Pier 1 colleagues, Girouard's foreign expertise earned the
nicknames, ``Marco Polo'' and ``Tai-Pan,'' and he was one of the
early American merchants to visit China.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Camp, who led Pier 1 before Johnson and said his
management team was responsible for the company's turnaround,
recalled a visit to a Philippines village after Pier 1 stopped
buying a rattan trunk. The village depended heavily on Pier 1
orders, and people lined the dirt road as Camp and Girouard drove
up, hoping that they could persuade Girouard to order a replacement
piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like MacArthur's second coming,'' Camp said. ``They had
made about 800 different items, and they lined them up,
side-by-side on the grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Girouard sloughs off such memories now, saying that he and the
company have come a long way. In fact, he concedes that he still
holds a grudge against Camp, even though Camp urged him to join
Pier 1 initially.
</P>
<P>
   The rift came in 1985, when Camp unexpectedly left the company
and recommended that another colleague, not Girouard, replace him.
Girouard was so incensed that he went to the board meeting and
asked to be considered for the post.
</P>
<P>
   The directors tapped Johnson, who had been a board member for
two years but had never worked at Pier 1. Then Johnson extended an
olive branch to Girouard, offering him a promotion to senior vice
president and asking him to remain with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Girouard's condition: Johnson had to keep him aboard, not just
use him to train a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson agreed, and Girouard said he thought to himself, ``Maybe
I can learn a lot from this guy. If I wait it out, one day I'll get
my chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That chance was almost delayed again this year. Four months ago,
Girouard said, Johnson suggested that he might want to remain as
CEO until 2000. According to Girouard, the succession plan had
already been approved by the board, and the CEO-in-waiting
threatened to challenge any delay.
</P>
<P>
   After considering the issue for a few days, Johnson agreed to
leave as scheduled, Girouard said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Johnson congratulated his successor at the annual
shareholders meeting and joked about his persistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to give Marvin a hand,'' Johnson said. ``Marvin's
gestation period as president was about the longest on record.''
</P>
<P>
   Girouard attributes his determination and flamboyance to his
background and his family, especially his mother and maternal
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy Ben,'' as he was known, was from Spain, and Girouard
said he was one of Port Arthur's most colorful characters during
the early 1900s oil boom. He said his grandfather ran gambling
houses and prostitution rings, drove fancy cars and wore fine
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real bon vivant man,'' Girouard said, ``and he had a
big influence on my taste and style.''
</P>
<P>
   When Girouard was in junior high, Elvis Presley played in Port
Arthur, and he and his friends were hooked by the beat. Janis
Joplin, a classmate, and several friends and cousins began playing
music and dreaming about the entertainment business.
</P>
<P>
   But Girouard's mother insisted that he become the first person
in the family to attend college. His father, an electrician, urged
him to become an electrical engineer, which could land him one of
the best jobs at the Port Arthur refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Girouard listened to his parents and went to Texas A&AMP;M
University. But it tore at him when a good friend, Johnny Preston,
wrote a hit song, ``Running Bear,'' and other friends made it to TV
dance shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from playing rock 'n' roll to being a freshman fish in
the corps _ shaving my head and marching on weekends,'' he said.
``God knows I wanted to leave A&AMP;M.''
</P>
<P>
   He stuck it out, blossoming when he switched from engineering to
marketing. He became a class president, an ardent Aggie and a firm
believer in fate. How else, he said, to explain the coincidences
that led to his big breaks?
</P>
<P>
   He insists, for example, that he landed his first job as an
advertising manager because he and the boss shared three things:
They were Navy men, they each wore a Rolex, and each owned a
Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I drove a Buick, who knows how different my life would have
been?'' Girouard said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
