<HEADER>
A2304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-OWEN-NYT     06-29 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-OWEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BRITISH STAR FACES MAJOR TEST AGAINST DEFENSE-MINDED
ARGENTINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY, SOC-WORLDCUP-NETHERLANDS,
SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S.)  
 (JT)  
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There is the same pace, the same explosive acceleration,
the same readiness to take on defenders and leave them groping at
shadows, the same killer instinct in front of goal. No wonder,
then, that Michael Owen of England is already being compared to the
star Brazilian striker, Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons are premature, of course. Owen is a novice at
top international level. His coach, Glenn Hoddle, still calls him
``the young lad.'' But at the ripe age of 18, the Liverpool lad has
emerged during the World Cup here as perhaps the most exciting new
talent in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Skill such as Owen's _ the ability to go straight at a defender
and beat him _ has never been at such a premium as in the modern
game. Defenses are so tight, pressing in midfield so intense, that
the only way to find space is often to get past someone. America
had no player here who could that. But Owen _ head down, ball
seeming tied to his foot _ injects a tempo that can disarm the best
defender.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ronaldo at the last World Cup in the United States, Owen
started here as a substitute. But unlike Ronaldo, who was 17 then
and did not not play in America, Owen has already claimed a place
in the starting lineup for England's clash with Argentina on
Tuesday, a match that will test any player's temperament.
</P>
<P>
   He did so in just 17 minutes on the pitch against Romania a week
ago. Coming on as a substitute, Owen took six minutes to score,
sweeping in a cross from fellow-striker Alan Shearer. The goal was
taken with such cat-like speed that the Romanian defenders were
left gaping. A few minutes later, he hit the post with a rasping
right-footed drive from the edge of the penalty box. England still
lost 2-1 to Romania, but even Hoddle could no longer deny that
Owen's time had come.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, the England coach had been insisting that Owen, for
all his talent, was too young. ``He still faces the hurdle of
proving he can take on the best defenses in the world,'' Hoddle
liked to say. He has stopped saying that. ``Frankly,'' said England
captain Alan Shearer, ``Owen brings a pace that nobody else, myself
included, can bring.''
</P>
<P>
   Owen, who still lives at home with his parents and four brothers
and sisters in a modest family home near the northwestern English
town of Chester, has already made a habit of breaking records.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, aged 18 years and 59 days, he became the youngest
player to appear for England, making his debut against Chile. Three
months later, aged 18 and 164 days, he became the youngest player
to score for England, beating Tommy Lawton's 60-year-old record
with a goal against Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   In the World Cup, he is now the third-youngest play ever to
participate, behind Norman Whiteside of Northern Ireland and a
young talent from Brazil named Pele, who was 17 when he played in
the 1958 World Cup in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Owen is not the talkative kind, preferring, in the phrase of
former Scottish striker Kenny Dalglish, ``to let my boots do the
talking.'' Here in France, Hoddle has generally kept his young
protege under tight wraps. But Owen is already known for an unusual
level-headedness and a single-minded dedication to achieving his
ambition: becoming the best player in the world. From the age of
15, he has talked with a deadpan assurance of how we will one day
be the world's best. Extraordinarily assured for his age, he seems,
for now, to be on course toward his objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't look at players' strengths,'' he observed during his
one appearance before the press here. ``You look at their
weaknesses and try to see where you can hurt them most if you get
the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Owen had already done a lot of hurting. Having scored a record
97 goals for Deeside Schools at the age of 10, he was signed up by
Liverpool the following year. Playing in the Liverpool youth team
at the age of 15, he had already established a reputation that
sometimes lured first-team players to go out and watch him. There
was a buzz at Liverpool, that of a special talent that was
emerging. At the age of 17, he became a professional and made his
debut for the club last year, scoring within ten minutes of coming
onto the field as a substitute. He finished last season as joint
top scorer in the English league, an extraordinary achievement for
a player in his first year at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   Owen, naturally, has weaknesses. His skills at shielding he
ball, essential for a striker, and his passing are average. But
like Gerd Muller, the legendary German striker who could be
invisible for long periods before bursting into a match with a
goal, Owen has an extraordinary eye for the target. It is this
clinical determination in front of goal, allied to his pace, that
makes Owen so exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   Against Argentina, Owen will face his greatest test. Hoddle, who
was in the England team that lost 2-1 to Argentina in the World Cup
quarterfinal in 1986, a match when Maradona scored a goal with his
hand, has talked of the opportunity to get a grievance ``out of our
systems.'' Owen was all of six back then, but if England is to
break an Argentina defense that has not yet conceded a goal here,
he will have to rise to the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Lined up against him, Owen will find two other young talents _
although, by his standards, they are already veterans. Amaldo Ariel
Ortega, aged 24, has already shown here that he is one the finest
aggressive midfielders in the game. He scored two goals against
Jamaica with an insolent ease _ chipping the ball over the
goalkeeper first with his left and then with his right foot _ and
has been an inspiration to his side.
</P>
<P>
   Marcelo Gallardo, aged 22, may start as a substitute, but it is
not for nothing that he has already been compared to Maradona. Like
the great Argentine star of the 1980s, he has a low center of
gravity and can move past players as if they did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Owen, with one goal in the tournament so far, has a long way to
go if he is to catch up with the top scorer, Christian Vieri of
Italy. While scarcely a newcomer, Vieri, aged 25, has burst on the
scene with a new authority, scoring in every match and placing even
Italy's star strikers, Roberto Baggio and Alessandro Del Piero, in
his shadow.
</P>
<P>
   Vieri, who grew up in Australia and speaks modest Italian, has
five goals so far. If Owen wants to get anywhere near that, and not
return home on Wednesday, he knows what he has to do against
Argentina. Facing him will be perhaps the best defense in the
world, but Owen has lived and thrived by surprising people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
