<HEADLINE>
GREATEST SOURCE OF DANGER IN NATIONAL PARKS IS NOT NATURE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where are you more likely to be injured: climbing down a rock
face or sitting around the campsite? The rock face may seem like
the obvious answer, but a new study of the hazards of national
parks has found that injuries at campsites _ from fist fights to
substance abuse _ outnumber those sustained during rock climbing by
more than 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, a University of California at San Diego study of eight
national parks in the state found that the greatest source of
danger is not nature. Only 3 of the 78 fatalities recorded were
attributed to ``purely environmental'' causes _ 1 apiece for shark
attack, avalanche, and inhalation of volcanic fumes.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the bulk of the fatalities stemmed from the same
weaknesses of the human heart and head that make life chancy in
civilized locations. Heart disease was the leading cause of death
(16), followed by drownings (12), falls (12), and motor vehicle
accidents (8). Men accounted for 80 percent of the fatalities,
including all 5 suicides.
</P>
<P>
   Animal attacks did show up on the list of injuries. But insects
were the most fiercesome group, accounting for 78 illnesses or
injuries, compared with 8 bites by larger creatures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
