<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT &LR;      06-29 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOGNIZING WHAT'S REAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If scientists are too rigid in ignoring phenomena that cannot be
explained by standard theories, they risk ignoring hints that may
lead to new and better theories. But chasing every ``X-File''
anomaly guarantees wasting a lot of time.
</P>
<P>
   How can one tell the difference between real science and
pursuits that may have the form, but generally not the content, of
science, like parapsychology?
</P>
<P>
   One test is having a good theory to explain the alleged
phenomena, writes philosopher Paul M. Churchland, co-author of ``On
the Contrary,'' a book of essays published by the MIT Press. The
articles in parapsychology journals report many studies of strange
mental powers imputed to humans or animals, but offer little
explanation of why such properties should exist.
</P>
<P>
   Another test is whether the field's usually rare claims of
success were repeated in a second laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   These rules might be worth the attention of the Society for
Scientific Exploration, which last week issued a report on
unidentified flying objects. The document, written by a panel of
nine scientists chaired by Von R. Eshleman of Stanford University,
concluded that ``it may be valuable'' to explore UFO sightings in
the hope of extracting ``information about unusual phenomena
currently unknown to science.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors discuss several mysterious encounters in which
pilots and others have noticed glowing lights, gigantic disks and
other perplexing objects.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists conclude that some episodes can be explained by
known natural phenomena but that others, which are harder to
account for, are worth investigating further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there are unexplained observations, there is the
possibility that scientists will learn something new by studying
those observations,'' the report states. But in terms of
Churchland's test, the authors offer no theory to account for the
unexplained sightings, and according to a press release issued by
Stanford University, they are ``not convinced'' by the theory that
would explain the alleged episodes, the thesis of extraterrestrial
visitations.
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UFOs aside, there seem to be enough weird goings on within the
portals of accepted science. Take the method of dating ancient
Indian rock art, known as petroglyphs, by means of the pollen and
other carbon-containing dust said to be trapped beneath the rock
varnish.
</P>
<P>
   Several paintings, which bear on the timing of the first
colonization of the Americas, have been dated by Dr. Ronald I.
Dorn, a pioneer of the rock varnish method at Arizona State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the method write in the current issue of Science that
they found particles of coal and charcoal in samples prepared by
Dorn but not in samples from the same sites that were collected
independently. The coal and charcoal grains were of different ages,
raising a question as to how both had been incorporated into the
same rock varnish.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy reply, Dorn adamantly denies that he tampered with
his samples and states that his critics ``failed to replicate my
results because they did not duplicate my techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorn states that coal and carbon are found together under rock
varnish. It would be absurd for anyone intent on cheating to mix
together carbon-bearing materials of different ages, he writes,
``instead of just using homogeneous materials with desired ages.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some mysteries, of course, have robust, scientific explanations
but depend on the human propensity for self-deception to be seen as
supernatural. The trick in fire-walking, Churchland notes, is that
there is no trick.
</P>
<P>
   The coals are red-hot and the fire-walkers tread on them,
usually without injury. People expect to be burned by anything
incandescent, but the coals, if carefully prepared and at a late
stage of combustion, have the density of styrofoam and hold too
little heat to burn the skin if touched quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle depends on expert preparation of the coals, and on
indoctrinating the walkers to swathe their feet in bio-magnetic
energy that repels the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Do not try this trick at home, Churchland warns. Careful
preparation is a necessity, as much in science as in the delicate
art of deceiving others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
