<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEATING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEATING ON DRIVER'S LICENSE TEST COMMON 
</HEADLINE>
 DRIVERS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHASHANK BENGALI  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Silently and in seemingly one swift
movement, two uniformed officers of the Missouri Highway Patrol
surrounded the perpetrator.
</P>
<P>
   An officer shook the man's hand free of pencil and paper and
revealed the crime: test answers scrawled between his left index
and middle fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The twentysomething offender had joined the swelling ranks of
those caught _ some red-handed _ cheating on their driver's license
test.
</P>
<P>
   Every week at testing stations throughout Missouri and Kansas,
cheaters of all ages are caught and their tests confiscated. Unlike
in school, however, where such an offense might warrant detention
or worse, the penalty for cheating in either state is little more
than some embarrassment and a slap on the wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Officials insist that the punishment fits the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should be arresting people because they
cheated,'' said Fount Foushee, a chief examiner with the Missouri
Highway Patrol, which administers the test.
</P>
<P>
   Foushee points out that the written test is only part of the
licensing process. First-time drivers, and those with expired,
suspended or revoked licenses, also must take the road test, which
three-quarters of Missouri applicants passed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A poor score on the written test doesn't necessarily equate with
a poor driver, Foushee said. Many applicants have gone from a
barely passing score on the written test to nearly perfect results
on the road test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The written test tells you that you have the knowledge to
drive. The road test shows that you actually can drive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the testing station, where the cheating incident occurred
last Monday, supervisor Ethel Mae Caldwell said applicants who did
not take the test seriously might not take driving seriously,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good indication for you if you cheat. I really
don't think we're letting bad drivers fall through, but I wish more
people took the time to study the rules,'' said Caldwell, who
catches ``a couple'' of cheaters each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like it if there would be a stiffer penalty for
cheating,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Test administrators also say security procedures haven't kept
pace with increasingly creative cheaters. In a new twist on the
age-old methods _ writing the answers on a crib sheet or the bill
of a cap _ one recent culprit programmed his calculator watch with
the answers but gave himself away, Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would check the time every few seconds,'' Caldwell said,
``so we knew something was up.''
</P>
<P>
   Other states are cracking down. In California the number of
English-language test versions recently was doubled to 10 and the
number of Spanish versions increased to five from three.
</P>
<P>
   California's new measures resulted from several undercover
operations by the state's Highway Patrol. Some troopers said they
cited about a dozen cheaters a month. And state officials reported
a black market for crib sheets that cost as much as $500.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, where an applicant can take the test twice in a
day, cheaters are barred from taking the exam again that day, but
they are allowed to return the next day with a clean slate. They
can take the test as often as they need until they pass.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas laws limit the number of times an applicant can take the
test at four. After that, they must wait six months before they are
eligible to take it again.
</P>
<P>
   No formal records of cheaters are kept in either state, and
officials acknowledge that many get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't catch 10 percent of the cheaters,'' said Foushee.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas officials say cheating isn't a significant concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't believe we have a problem here,'' said Alan
Anderson, chief examiner with the Kansas Division of Vehicles,
which administers the test. ``I've been here for 17 years, even
worked in the testing stations, and never saw that it was a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said Kansas testing protocol discourages cheating. Test
answers aren't allowed out of the office, which he said makes
memorizing them more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But no security measures will entirely deter cheating, Foushee
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started here in 1970, and people cheated then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Missouri and Kansas update the 25-question, multiple-choice
tests about every 12 months to account for changes in driving laws.
Missouri's current versions date to December 1997. Kansas will
introduce new tests the first week of July.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, four English versions of the test exist, and one
for each of 10 foreign languages, including Spanish, Chinese and
Russian. Kansas has two English-language versions, and none in a
foreign language. Kansas has bilingual examiners who will translate
for Spanish-speaking applicants and also offers a nonverbal picture
test for those who speak other languages.
</P>
<P>
   In California's attack on cheating, the tests will be changed
four times a year, but officials in Missouri and Kansas don't think
that's practical, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're changing the test that often, it becomes a
management issue and a question of logistics, and in our state it
can get very difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the limited number of versions makes it easier to cheat.
Repeat test-takers can memorize answers or share them with others.
The offender caught Monday said he got the answers from ``a
friend'' who had come in a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same test,'' he said in Spanish. ``Last time I made
too many mistakes. This time, less.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. Missouri's failure rate seems remarkably high.
</P>
<P>
   In Foushee's 16-county region last year, 48 percent failed the
test and Kansas City's rate is usually several points higher.
Anderson estimated that the passing rate in Kansas, however, hovers
steadily about 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Kansas City testing station, some applicants this
week said that passing the test _ answering 80 percent of the 25
questions correctly _ just requires a little effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty easy test,'' said David Ulett, 26, who said he
didn't study but passed his renewal examination anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell, a 25-year veteran of the testing office, said: ``I
honestly believe that if they took the time to prepare themselves,
and didn't just come in blindly, they'd all pass.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the man caught cheating said he had been
embarrassed into reform: ``I did a bad thing. I won't do it next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   On his way out of the office, he grabbed a copy of Missouri's
80-page driver's manual.
</P>
<P>
   ``To read,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
