<HEADER>
A2376 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     06-29 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS FOR SUPER-LINKED FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By ROB FIXMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the planet becomes increasingly networked, shrinking the
globe and redefining age-old concepts of community, all this
digital connectivity has so far bypassed our most fundamental
social unit, the family. Now, a rapidly emerging new industry is
betting that the next ``killer app'' will be a network in your
home.
</P>
<P>
   Already, according to the Dataquest research firm, two or more
computers are being used in an estimated 15 million American
households, a number that is expected to more than triple by 2002.
The assumption that people will want all those computers to talk to
each other, from bedroom to den to living room, kitchen, deck and
patio, has touched off a race for a chunk of a what Wedbush Morgan
Securities of Los Angeles estimates will be a $4 billion market
within four years.
</P>
<P>
   My own family contributed a few hundred dollars to the
beginnings of that market last month when it became clear that
installing a home network would cost a lot less than buying modems,
Internet access and printers for each the four computers
accumulated by three students and two increasingly Net-dependent
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding factor, though, was the introduction of a cable
modem into the household. Always connected and delivering incoming
data at better than 60 times the speed of today's fastest modems,
it quickly made the Internet the children's primary reference
library as well as a social and entertainment hub.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a bottleneck. The cable modem is connected to the
same multimedia PC that runs the color printer, the scanner and,
most importantly, a CD-ROM changer with an encyclopedia, an atlas,
a dictionary and other reference books.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the vast majority of our digital resources were
available only to the family member who happened to be using that
one machine. Simple efficiency, not to mention domestic harmony,
demanded that they be shared.
</P>
<P>
   That, says John W. Todd, Wedbush Morgan's vice president for
research, is a typical set of reasons for installing a home
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely shared Internet access that will drive the
home networking market,'' said Todd, who recently released an
investment analysis on the subject. ``But in addition, people are
quickly realizing that they can't afford to equip every computer in
the house with a complete set of peripherals.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapidly falling prices for network cards and ethernet hubs, the
equipment needed for the kind of high-speed network typically used
in corporate environments, now make it possible to connect two home
computers for less than $200 _ but only if both machines happen to
be in the same room.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest expense faced by would-be home networkers today is
the cost of running ethernet cables through walls, floors and
ceilings. Wiring a typical home can easily cost several thousand
dollars. I took this route because I am comfortable doing my own
wiring, but by the end of this summer, consumers will have a choice
of several easier, less costly alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   The best features of all these new schemes is that they will
require no new wiring and most will configure themselves _ a
significant breakthrough, since setting up a network is a more than
daunting challenge for most weekend warriors.
</P>
<P>
   While none of these new systems will deliver the 10 to 100
megabits per second bandwidth of a cable-connected ethernet (at
least not yet) they will offer speeds up to 1.6 megabits per
second, about 30 times faster than today's fastest modems.
</P>
<P>
   They will arrive in three basic flavors: wireless, phone-line
systems and power-line systems.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless networks use a high-frequency radio signal to connect
computers equipped with tiny two-way radios, or transceivers. While
these are prone to interference from other radio sources, they will
be by far the most attractive options when the technology is
mature.
</P>
<P>
   One system is already on the market, but faster, more reliable
systems will be introduced later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   For the foreseeable future, systems that use a home's existing
telephone lines _ without interfering with normal telephone use _
will be the most dependable and among the fastest and lowest cost.
The most developed of the home network technologies, they inspired
the creation earlier this month of the Home Phoneline Networking
Alliance, a standards group that includes industry giants like
AT&AMP;T, Compaq, Hewlett-Packard, IBM and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, it also includes 3Com, Lucent Technologies and
Rockwell Semiconductor Systems, indicating that these three
companies learned a hard lesson when their years of sparring over a
standard all but destroyed the market for 56K modems.
</P>
<P>
   Systems that use existing electrical wiring employ the oldest
technology and, to date, are the more expensive and least
dependable of the home networks under development. But they are
also the most promising because of the ubiquitous nature of
electrical wiring in every room in most homes. Look for systems of
this type by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   None of these systems is likely to be really mature and
glitch-free for several years, but even in their primordial stages,
they will nurture the emergence, for better or worse, of the
super-connected family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
