<SLUG> BC-AT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO WORDS FOR JUSTICES: GET REAL 
</HEADLINE>
 WORK COLUMN-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Supreme Court justices understand a lot of things, but
teen-agers aren't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   In the same week that the court strengthened the position of
employees in sexual harassment lawsuits, it made it extremely
difficult for youngsters to win damages from school districts even
if ``reprehensible'' abuse has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled in a 5-4 decision that school districts cannot
be forced to pay damages to a student who was sexually abused by a
teacher because officials did not know of the abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students essentially have no protection because the (legal)
standards are so high,'' said Neena Chaudhry, a staff attorney with
the National Women's Law Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is almost impossible for students to win
monetary damages unless someone ``with authority'' knew about the
harassment and was ``deliberately indifferent.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teen would say: ``Get real.''
</P>
<P>
   Many adults have difficulty recognizing harassment, so how can
we expect teen-agers to be even better informed? In a survey of 83
high schools for the Iowa Commission on the Status of Women, focus
groups found that many students do not have a well-formed idea of
what constitutes sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked about specific examples of sexual harassment, the
same survey found that 83 percent of young women and 62 percent of
young men had at least one exposure to a sexually harassing
incident at school.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that 19 percent of the young women and 8
percent of the young men were experiencing ongoing harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Did most of the youngsters tell their parents, teachers or
school administrators about the harassment? Of course not. The
average teen-ager doesn't even want to talk about sex with an
adult, let alone describe a personally humiliating experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of courage, whether the student is male or
female, to come forward,'' said Charlotte B. Nelson, executive
director of the Iowa Commission on Women.
</P>
<P>
   The National Women's Law Center is working with other
organizations to persuade Congress to remedy the high court's
ruling by revisiting Title IX.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds great, but we know that legislation takes months, if
not years.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, we should follow Iowa's example. We should
educate our teachers and teen-agers so they can recognize and
prevent harassment.
</P>
<P>
   After completing its survey, the Iowa Commission on the Status
of Women produced the film ``Stop It! Students Speak Out Against
Sexual Harassment.'' The film, which is available to schools, is
designed to encourage discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The courts obviously won't protect our children, so we must.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
