<HEADER>
A2385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S.-NYT     06-29 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPSON RESIGNS AS U.S. SOCCER COACH  
 (SEE ALSO SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY, SOC-WORLDCUP-OWEN,
SOC-WORLDCUP-NETHERLANDS, SOC-WORLDCUP-ARGENTINA0  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELLIER, France _ Four days after his divided team
unceremoniously exited the World Cup after three losses and and a
32d-place ranking out of 32 teams, Steve Sampson resigned Monday as
coach of the U.S. soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   In his three years as head coach, Sampson became the first
American ever to qualify the United States for the World Cup and he
provided some of the country's most important victories, including
a 1-0 win over Brazil in February.
</P>
<P>
   However, he radically changed the lineup in the months leading
up to the 1998 World Cup, dropped captain John Harkes and drew
severe criticism from veterans who had been benched.
</P>
<P>
   After the Americans lost all three first-round matches in the
World Cup and scored only one goal, Sampson was lambasted by such
players as Alexi Lalas and Tab Ramos, who said they would never
again play for the national team while Sampson was coach.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. soccer federation announced that it hoped to find a
replacement for Sampson within a month after the World Cup ends in
mid-July. The list of potential candidates includes two coaches
whom the federation attempted to hire before Sampson _ Carlos
Alberto Parreira, who led Brazil to the 1994 World Cup title and
was fired last week by Saudi Arabia; and Carlos Quieroz of
Portugal, who just left the U.S. team as head of player development
to coach the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   Also likely to be available is Bora Milutinovic, who coached the
Americans in the 1994 World Cup and is not expected to stay with
Nigeria now that it has been eliminated in the second round of the
1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Before the World Cup, many of the U.S. players said they liked
Sampson because he was an American and understood the mentality of
American players. If that preference leads the soccer federation to
hire another American coach, it would likely be Bruce Arena, coach
of D.C. United, the two-time champions of Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at the federation thank Steve for his tremendous service to
our national team program and to soccer in the USA,'' Alan I.
Rothenberg, president of the United States soccer federation, said
in a statement. ``His tireless work has helped advance our sport
and, on balance, it was an era of growth. I compliment him on his
achievements with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who was hired on Aug. 2, 1995, coached the American
team to a 26-22-14 record. This spring, Harkes was removed for a
lack of leadership and discipline and such veterans as Lalas and
Marcelo Balboa were benched, while David Regis of France, who was
naturalized only three weeks before the World Cup, stepped in as a
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   After the team failed miserably in the World Cup, Sampson was
criticized for wrecking his team's cohesiveness and for using such
inexperienced players as Chad Deering and Brian Maisonneuve in
midfield. In truth, it was Sampson's most experienced players who
let him down most - Claudio Reyna in midfield and Eric Wynalda at
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the criticisms of Sampson were valid. He did not
recognize that Reyna was incapable of leading the team. And he
played with no defensive midfielders against Iran, which
contributed mightily to a 2-1 defeat. But it was the players, not
Sampson, who came out tentative against Germany and who hit the
post repeatedly without scoring against Iran. As much criticism as
he deserved, the players largely failed to take responsibility for
their own ineptitude.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
