<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAD-ART-ART-645&AMP;ADD-     06-29 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAD-ART-ART-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASE DON'T EAT THE TOMATOES: THEY'RE GLASS BEADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By ANITA AMIRREZVANIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ Liza Lou takes off her shoes and steps
gingerly into her neat back yard, careful not to disturb the
exuberant flowers. It has all the trappings of almost any other
well-tended patch of suburbia, with its meticulously groomed lawn,
its barbecue grill stoked with coals and its picnic table groaning
with food.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes this life-size yard unique is that the lawn
itself, along with everything on it, is formed by millions of tiny
glass beads.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Ms. Lou grabs the salad bowl off the table and
offers up a glimmering carrot (covered in orange beads, of course).
There are 80 items in the salad bowl alone, from jeweled garden
mushrooms to sparkling ruby-red tomatoes. Fat sandwiches, corn on
the cob and Bud beers, all beaded. The Sunday afternoon fare is, in
fact, like a shimmering hallucination of the suburban dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back Yard,'' which is on display through July 5 at the Santa
Monica Museum of Art, is the latest beaded project created by Ms.
Lou, 29, a Los Angeles artist who has been working with bugle beads
for about a decade. Her first installation was a beaded kitchen
that drew attention for its quirkiness, its love of detail and its
feminist critique of suburban life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back Yard,'' a companion piece, is a look at the more public
side of suburbia. It is, the artist says, ``a sugar-coated dream
turned toxic.''
</P>
<P>
   The new piece was partly financed by the Santa Monica Museum of
Art for its opening exhibition at its new location in the Bergamot
Station Art Center, a complex of art galleries on a former
industrial site. The museum's executive director, Thomas Rhoads,
became interested in Ms. Lou's work after seeing a bead-covered
vanity she made a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What amazed me about Liza is the merging of both fine art and
craft,'' he said. ``Her work is accessible to the kinds of
individuals who would go to the state fair to see craft projects,
and yet it has a real conceptual grounding in feminist art. It's
the bringing together of these two worlds that makes it so
appealing and successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The beads are normally used to decorate clothing, and Ms. Lou
describes her work as ``three-dimensional paint'' with the ability
to create ``an explosion of color and light.'' But when she started
as an artist, many people disparaged her choice of materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look like art to anyone,'' she recalled. ``I had
artist friends asking me, `How's the life of a jeweler?' People
made the most unbelievable comments. It was horrible, but it also
encouraged me in a lot of ways, because I thought it must be
something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Although other contemporary artists have incorporated beads into
their work, only a few have used them on such a large scale. ``Back
Yard,'' which covers 528 square feet, required two years of work.
The installation is landscaped with 250,000 blades of bead grass in
varying shades of green and yellow. Hundreds of volunteers
fashioned the grass out of wire and beads, at what they called
weekend lawn parties.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lou constructed many of the objects, like the picnic table
and the leaves of the tree, out of old newspapers, and then glued
on beads and even sequins. ``The work takes so long that you don't
have a sense of achievement or accomplishment on a daily basis; you
feel like a failure every day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lou has been accused of being obsessive or even a bit loopy,
because she works so intensively with small materials. But she
disagrees with these labels. ``The practice of sitting and doing
your work every day is the opposite of obsession _ it's more like
devotion or a prayer,'' she said. ``The fact that it takes a long
time is just unfortunate. It's the price that one has to pay. When
you try to do something like this, you realize that you're going
against the grain of culture.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Lou attended the San Francisco Art Institute, but dropped
out to pursue her own projects, in part because of the criticism
she received over her use of beads. ``When people hated my work, I
wanted to do it bigger,'' she said. ``I left in order to develop
and grow.'' Cheryl Haines, who represents Ms. Lou out of the Haines
Gallery in San Francisco, describes her as a real contrarian.
</P>
<P>
   But having seen the grand mosaics and cathedrals of Italy, Ms.
Lou said, she wanted to create a work that was large, resplendent
and labor-intensive. One day she had a brainstorm in her mother's
kitchen: Why not bead the entire room?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kitchen,'' her first major piece, took five years to complete,
and it is also on display at the Santa Monica Museum, as a tribute
to the unacknowledged housewife.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fully beaded environment, complete with stove,
refrigerator, sink, cabinets and a table set with a bountiful
breakfast, all done in psychedelic patterns and colors. On a side
of the stove, a beaded poem by Emily Dickinson reads, ``She rose to
his Requirement, dropped/ The playthings of her life/ To take the
honorable work/ Of Woman and of Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   In between ``Back Yard'' and ``Kitchen,'' Ms. Lou completed
``Portrait Gallery,'' a series depicting all the American
presidents. She painted the portraits and then beaded them in
black, white and shades of gray, making them resemble old
photographs. ``Portrait Gallery'' is on display at the Aspen Art
Museum in Colorado through Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lou is now completing her first major commissioned work for
a private collector, a piece called ``The Closet,'' which will be
shown at the Aldrich Museum of Contemporary Art in Ridgefield,
Conn., starting on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Even after all the time she has spent working on major
installations, Ms. Lou's fantasy is to create a beaded chapel.
``All my pieces are, in a way, a kind of chapel,'' she said, ``so
it makes sense to get right to the source.''
</P>
</TEXT>
