<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, June 30, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-SHUFFLE _ Atlanta's biggest corporate employer continues
to shuffle top management. Delta said Monday that Vicki Escarra, a
company veteran who started as a flight attendant, has been
promoted to executive vice president-customer service, making her
the highest ranking woman in management. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   DHCOL30 _ The Securities and Exchange Commission says that all
publicly traded companies with substantial Year 2000 expenses will
have to disclose them. (Herubin, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERNCO-CHINA _ HONG KONG _ The company that has called
itself the ``900 pound gorilla'' of American electric utilities is
finding Asia a cruel and trackless jungle. Thorns in the form of
generator glitches continue to torment the reliability of Southern
Co.'s giant Shajiao C power plant here in China's booming southern
industrial strip. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERNCO-CHINA-SIDE _ GUANGDONG PROVINCE, China _ ``The people
who run power plants are exactly alike all over the world,'' says
Jim Webber, a 39-year Southern Co. veteran who left retirement to
help knock the kinks out of Atlanta-based utility giant's first
power plant in China. ``This is all a very large family, if you
will. We all have the same purpose in life, and that is to produce
power.'' At 57, Webber is one of five Southern Co. engineers and
technicians assigned to monitor operations in the new Shajiao C
coal-fired power plant in Guangdong Province, about 50 miles north
of Hong Kong. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-ONLINE30 _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth.Net and its sister
telephone companies offering Internet access have unique problems
to deal with as technology slowly but steadily advances toward
cable modems and high-speed access. Their options are limited by
reliance on the telephone network. Whether that will help or hurt
long term is still uncertain. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ Airline executives respond to questions about
government regulation the way the Scarecrow gave directions to
Dorothy after she landed in Oz. They point in two opposite
directions at once. When airline honchos think regulations might
help consumers, they point vigorously toward libertarianism. But if
the regulations help their profits, they point toward legislation.
This month, industry leaders displayed their schizophrenic
tendencies while trying to influence Congress. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (k, f) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ One of the greatest challenges facing
any automaker today is bringing the right product to market. Few
would argue that Mercedes-Benz is doing an exceptional job: the
E-Class, sporty SLK and M-Class sport-utility vehicle are all
blessed with exceptional customer demand. Just how does a carmaker
make the right decision at the right time? Many rely on research
groups, previous sales data and managerial skills. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE_ ATLANTA _ It's not going to happen, but wouldn't it
be nice if all pickups came with extended cabs and a third door? Of
course, there'll always be buyers for two-door, regular-cab models,
but it's amazing how much convenience and utility the extra space
and door add, particularly to a compact like the Chevrolet S-10.
(DeValt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE30 _ Just about the coolest thing a person can do on
the Internet at this time of the year is to find ways to get out of
the heat. There are plenty of Web sites that suggest ways to stay
cool during the hot summer. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
(f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MACNEWS30 _ For the uninitiated, Microsoft's Excel spreadsheet
program has always been an 800-pound gorilla _ powerful and
intimidating. That's too bad, because the program can be very
useful if you're not scared off by its impenetrable appearance and
seemingly endless list of features. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH30 _ Tomorrow is another day. It's also another day to
see the 1939 classic ``Gone With the Wind'' on the big screen the
way it was meant to be seen. A generation of mothers and
grandmothers will be taking their teenage daughters and
granddaughters off to see their generation's ``Titanic.''
Meanwhile, a generation of daughters and granddaughters can take
the opportunity to check out ``GWTW'' on the World Wide Web and
maybe teach mom and grandma a little bit about cybersurfing at the
same time. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY30 _ Once upon a time, folks sat open-mouthed at
their first sight of a television set. When radio was first
invented, some people seriously thought it might be the work of
devils. And nowadays we have computers that can read handwriting,
understand human speech and translate more languages than a platoon
of U.N. translators. So _ compared to all that _ I have my work cut
out for me when I tell you that the most magical technological
device that I know is an antenna. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS30 _ This column is dedicated to the literati among you
who run computers despite an innate loathing of them; consider it
your reward for reading this column even when it bewilders you. And
now ... Computer Haiku. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f,
l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-WATCH30 _ The federal Cooling-Off Rule, passed by
Congress in 1972 to protect vulnerable consumers from unscrupulous
door-to-door salespeople, is one of the nation's best consumer
laws. But it still remains one of the most misunderstood, which
often causes problems. Rarely a week passes that we don't receive
calls from readers who say they have purchased some item, usually a
car, and they want to return it. ``Don't I have three days to
change my mind?'' they ask. Usually the answer is no _ and nearly
always no with the purchase of a car, unless the seller agreed to a
return period. (Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THARPE-COLUMN30 _ Fraudulent credit card offers are the kudzu
vine of consumer cons. They keep coming back, despite constant
efforts to eradicate them. Kudzu will thrive almost anywhere where
there's a little bit of dirt. Fraudulent cards thrive on the need
for credit _ and consumers who have difficulty obtaining credit are
prime targets for the bogus offers. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT30 _ Dueling formats _ you know the story.
</P>
<P>
   It could be VHS against Betamax. Or compact discs against vinyl.
Fax vs. e-mail, vs. the Postal Service. Among wireless phones, it
could be traditional cellular against personal communications
services, or analog against digital. In connecting to the Internet,
there is a coming battle between phone lines called Asymmetric
Digital Subscriber Lines, known as ADSL, and cable modems running
over cable lines. And for them to succeed, they must both overcome
the slower but more entrenched modems. The formats clash. Sometimes
one dies, and sometimes they coexist. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
