game. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MARTINEZ-BROTHERS30 _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jesus Martinez is
jealous of his brothers not because they are famous big-league
pitchers but because of the money success brings them. He is not a
greedy young man. The millions he craves are not for himself. He
doesn't want a fancy car or diamond jewelry or a stylish wardrobe.
Rather, he sees what his older brothers contribute to their
hometown of Mano Guayabo in the Dominican Republic and he feels
left out. (Rosenberg, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TWO-PLAYERS30 _ DAYTON, Ohio _ For a natural left-hander,
learning to throw strikes right-handed is about as simple as
shooting a basketball in a strait jacket, except if you are Matt
Witt, the 13-year-old who throws a baseball ambidextrously. One
young man, two pitching arms. It's no mirage. (Jackson, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOHLS-COLUMN30 _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Ricky Williams returns this
fall as the nation's leading rusher in college football, but his
chances of winning the Heisman Trophy are hardly etched in stone.
Stone, no. Ash hardwood, yes. Rob Sellers is the guy doing the
etching. According to the Waco, Texas pharmacist, a part-time maker
of baseball trophy bats, Williams will win the Heisman. Says so
right there in black and white. Black script and white ash on a
33-inch, 27- ounce bat that has Williams' authentic signature
laser-engraved alongside a Longhorns logo. The words ``1998 Heisman
Trophy winner'' will be emblazoned on the barrel. (Bohls, Austin
American-Statesman) (s) MOVED.
</P>
