<HEADER>
A2399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-RUBIN-NYT &LR;      06-29 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-RUBIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBIN BACKS IMF AHEAD OF TALKS WITH THAI LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ After a whirlwind visit to Malaysia, in
which he defended the International Monetary Fund's harsh
prescriptions for healing Asia's economies, U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin arrived Monday evening in the place where the
financial contagion first began.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin will meet Tuesday with Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai of
Thailand and other officials to discuss their efforts to climb out
of a recession _ nearly one year to the day since Bangkok floated
its currency, prompting a devastating devaluation from which it has
yet to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's tour of Asia comes as the IMF is under growing attack
from politicians and business people here, who say the fund's
formula of high interest rates, rigorous fiscal policy and stable
currencies is strangling the region's economies and worsening the
pain of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, Rubin offered a measured endorsement of the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, on balance, the IMF has had it about right,'' he said
at a news conference in Kuala Lumpur after meeting with Malaysian
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad. ``I think if you loosen interest
rates, it runs the risk of eroding the currency.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said he had a ``very good discussion'' with Mahathir,
though he would not divulge details. Mahathir has been a
vituperative critic of the West, blaming the crisis on currency
traders and accusing the U.S. government of attempting to profit
from the economic misery.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear that Rubin and Mahathir had a meeting of the
minds. On the question of whether the United States should
intervene in the market to support Malaysia's currency _ a measure
Mahathir has called for but which the United States has rebuffed _
Rubin said, ``The views of the prime minister are well known. And I
think our views are well known.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rubin's aides said the tone of the meeting was
constructive and that Mahathir did not make any inflammatory
remarks, which he has been known to do in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Rubin met with Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim, who made waves recently by publicly disagreeing with
Mahathir about whether Malaysia should lower its interest rates to
jump-start its economy. Mahathir said they should be lowered, while
Anwar favored keeping them high enough to maintain the stability of
Malaysia's currency, the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a meeting Monday with Rubin, Anwar sounded more like
his boss _ declaring that interest rates were ``prohibitively
high'' and that the financial crisis was putting a severe strain on
Malaysian society.
</P>
<P>
   The pain of the Asian crisis has reached even Malaysia's
prosperous neighbor, Singapore, which announced a $1.2 billion
package of measures Monday to stimulate its sluggish economy.
Acknowledging that its economy will grow far more slowly in 1998
than it had forecasted, the Singaporean government said it would
increase public spending and offer tax rebates to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The social and political cost of the Asian crisis has been a
recurring theme of Rubin's tour, which began in China on Friday and
concludes Wednesday in South Korea. In a meeting with American
business executives in Kuala Lumpur, several people warned Rubin
about Indonesia, which they said could easily slide into disarray
in the wake of President Suharto's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a discomfort in Indonesia that the U.S. and
the West aren't taking Indonesia seriously,'' said Peter Woicke,
the managing director and chief executive of J.P. Morgan's Asia
Pacific division.
</P>
<P>
   Although the economic crisis precipitated a change in
governments here, Thailand has so far avoided the kind of social
unrest that hit Indonesia or the political dissension that has
afflicted Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the United States has praised the Chuan government for
faithfully carrying out the IMF plan, which it says has helped
Thailand regain the confidence of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   By most yardsticks, though, Thailand's economy is in parlous
shape. Exports are falling, unemployment is soaring and economists
say the country's output could shrink by 5.5 percent this year.
After a binge of borrowing from foreign banks during the Asian
economic boom, Thailand's bad debts may total as much as $25
billion _ a figure equal to 20 percent of its gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bangkok's notorious traffic jams have subsided _ a
barometer, say residents here, of how much the city's commercial
life has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Business executives here say the public's patience with
IMF-style solutions is wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is deteriorating, with no end in sight,'' said
James Stent, the senior executive vice president of the Bank of
Asia, Thailand's 11th-largest bank. ``It's time for emergency
measures.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lipton, the U.S. undersecretary of the treasury for
international affairs, said the IMF had made ``sensible''
adjustments to take account of Thailand's worsening condition _
allowing it, for example, to run a budget deficit instead of a
surplus. He said Rubin would urge the government to continue to
reform its banks, to strengthen its bankruptcy laws and to allow
more foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   But Stent said that as the crisis has dragged on, some people
here are coming to believe that Thailand's political and financial
institutions are not strong enough to tolerate the pressures of
being fully open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's increasing skepticism that opening up to foreign
investment is a panacea,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
