<P>
   CONSUMER-WATCH30 _ The federal Cooling-Off Rule, passed by
Congress in 1972 to protect vulnerable consumers from unscrupulous
door-to-door salespeople, is one of the nation's best consumer
laws. But it still remains one of the most misunderstood, which
often causes problems. Rarely a week passes that we don't receive
calls from readers who say they have purchased some item, usually a
car, and they want to return it. ``Don't I have three days to
change my mind?'' they ask. Usually the answer is no _ and nearly
always no with the purchase of a car, unless the seller agreed to a
return period. (Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   THARPE-COLUMN30 _ Fraudulent credit card offers are the kudzu
vine of consumer cons. They keep coming back, despite constant
efforts to eradicate them. Kudzu will thrive almost anywhere where
there's a little bit of dirt. Fraudulent cards thrive on the need
for credit _ and consumers who have difficulty obtaining credit are
prime targets for the bogus offers. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT30 _ Dueling formats _ you know the story.
</P>
<P>
   It could be VHS against Betamax. Or compact discs against vinyl.
Fax vs. e-mail, vs. the Postal Service. Among wireless phones, it
could be traditional cellular against personal communications
services, or analog against digital. In connecting to the Internet,
there is a coming battle between phone lines called Asymmetric
Digital Subscriber Lines, known as ADSL, and cable modems running
over cable lines. And for them to succeed, they must both overcome
the slower but more entrenched modems. The formats clash. Sometimes
one dies, and sometimes they coexist. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) (f, l) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
