<HEADER>
A2417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ARGENTIN     06-29 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ARGENTINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINA COACH IS A MAN ON A MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY, SOC-WORLDCUP-OWEN,
SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S., SOC-WORLDCUP-NETHERLANDS)  
 (JT)  
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ He is clearly a man on a mission: so much so that it is
easy to forget that Daniel Passarella already has won two World
Cups for Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   But the first came at home in 1978, when Gen. Jorge Rafael
Videla, head of the military junta that was responsible for the
disappearances and deaths of tens of thousands of Passarella's
countrymen, triumphantly handed him the trophy. ''If I'd known then
what was happening, I wouldn't have played at all,'' Passarella,
the captain of that team, has said.
</P>
<P>
   The second came in 1986, when he was on the Argentine roster,
but because of an illness, only got to watch from the bench as his
teammate Diego Maradona worked wonders with his feet and, in one
infamous instance against England, with his fist.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps that helps explain why Passarella, now national
technical director and coach, has erected an eight-foot fence
around Argentina's French training base in L'Etrat and decided to
keep distractions, including interviews, to a minimum. This
Argentine team, in every sense his team, has a chance to give him a
title without an asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   First it must get past England in the second round on Tuesday in
what is viewed as a grudge match by the English, who will never
forget nor entirely forgive Argentina for Maradona's handball that
became a goal in the 1986 quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sleep for four days afterward,'' said England coach
Glenn Hoddle, who, unlike Passarella, played in that match.
</P>
<P>
   Passarella has been less forthcoming with his reminiscences, but
his team, a foreboding mix of polished veterans and gifted
youngsters, is clearly the favorite against England. It has not
given up a goal in its last eight matches, and with midfielder Juan
Veron who excels at organizing, midfielder Ariel Ortega who excels
at creating and striker Gabriel Batistuta who excels at scoring,
its strengths are hardly on the back line alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are gathering strength,'' Passarella said after his team
defeated Croatia to win Group H.
</P>
<P>
   Only two other men have won World Cups as players and coaches:
Mario Zagallo of Brazil, and Franz Beckenbauer of Germany, but
Passarella already shares a continent with Zagallo and a nickname
with Beckenbauer. At home, the stocky, stylishly dressed Passarella
is known as ``El Kaiser,'' and at 45, he is as focused and
unflinching a coach as he was a central defender in a fine career
that took him from Argentine club River Plate to the Italian first
division. He was a high-scoring defender, in part because he often
took penalty kicks, but he is best remembered for his intensity,
and it is telling that he received a red card in the club match
that was intended to honor his career.
</P>
<P>
   Passarella has experienced personal tragedy: the death of his
18-year-old son, Sebastian, in an automobile accident. He has had
to live with regrets: the 1978 World Cup and the junta it helped
legitimize. But if he adopted a hard line with Argentina, it is
also because of timing. When he took over the national team in
1994, it had just been through a convulsive, divisive experience at
the World Cup in which it had started brilliantly and then
self-destructed after Maradona tested positive for epehedrine and
suspended from the tournament. Passarella, who already had coached
River Plate to three Argentine titles, took over with the intention
of emphasizing rigor and professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   Practices became more structured and players were required to
undergo nasal examinations to ensure that none was using cocaine.
But what would become the biggest conversation piece at home and
abroad was Passarella's decision to ban long hair. His public
explanation was that long hair was a distraction during matches,
but for Batistuta, one of those who trimmed his locks, that was not
Passarella's only reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cut mine because there was a project to to change the image
of the Argentinian player,'' he said. ``It was a question of
helping out Passarella.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone acquiesced. Fernando Redondo, one of the world's
finest defensive midfielders, refused to cut his hair for the
cause, and though Passarella has since ended the ban, he and
Redondo have yet to reconcile. Passarella has said part of the
problem is that Redondo did not want to play a different position
on the national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I select a player who thinks he's doing the team a favor by
joining us, then I not only irritate myself but my players, as
well,'' Passarella said.
</P>
<P>
   Passarella did irritate Batistuta, Argentina's all-time leading
scorer with 46 goals, by leaving him off the team for much of 1997
and choosing to rely on Hernan Crespo and other young players he
had coached at River Plate and at the Olympics in 1996, where
Argentina won the silver medal. Passarella also had coached
Batistuta at River Plate in 1989, and had benched him then, too.
This time, he explained that integrating Batistuta properly into
the national team required more than the few days allotted by FIFA
for teams to prepare for World Cup qualifying matches.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping Batistuta ignited a thousand arguments in the streets
and cafes of Argentina, but there was no arguing with the results.
With its star striker, Argentina had only 10 points in seven
matches and was in third place in the South American qualifying
race. Without him, it would go on to defeat Colombia in Colombia
and finish first. But Passarella did not leave Batistuta off his
World Cup team, and ``Batigol'' has responded with four goals in
three games in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has worked very hard, and he deserves his success,''
Passarella said. ''I hope he finishes leading scorer, but I know
that his first desire is that the team go as far as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``El Kaiser,'' as it turns out, can also be kind, but however
far his fine team goes, he does not plan on trying again in 2002.
The day after Argentina's last match in France, he will resign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
