<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, June 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms will erupt across sections of the East on
Tuesday as a potent jet-stream disturbance rotates through the
region. During the morning, one cluster of showers and
thunderstorms will move through New York and eastern Pennsylvania,
affecting New England by afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As the jet-stream disturbance intercepts a fast flow of sultry
air from the southwest, an area of showers and strong thunderstorms
will form in portions of the Ohio Valley on Tuesday morning. These
storms will advance east to the Middle Atlantic States by
afternoon. A few of the storms will produce hail and flooding
rains, though the fast movement of the storms will preclude
widespread flooding.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, winds changing direction and increasing with
altitude will cause a few of these storms to rotate. These rotating
storms, known as supercells, are capable of producing tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Uncomfortably hot and humid air will cover the southern Plains
and Southeast. As the sun heats the sultry air, rising currents of
moistened air will produce scattered afternoon cumulus clouds, a
few of which will yield to afternoon thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   An expansive high-pressure system at 20,000 feet will bring
sunny skies and blistering heat to the valleys of the interior
Southwest and eastern New Mexico. Farther northeast, isolated
afternoon thunderstorms will develop near a front over western
Kansas and eastern Colorado. Elsewhere, the West Coast will be
mainly sunny and seasonably warm, though patchy morning clouds will
cling to the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Warmth Returns
</P>
<P>
   The mercury hit 80 degrees at Elko, Nev., on Sunday for the
first time since October 4, 1997. The streak of 266 days with
temperatures below 80 degrees broke the previous record of 255
consecutive days set in 1970-1971. Sunday's milestone also marked
the latest date for 80 degrees to be observed at Elko, surpassing
the previous latest date of June 16, 1971. The lack of heat in the
Far West has resulted, in part, from the absence of warm
high-pressure systems over the region, allowing cloudy low-pressure
systems from the Pacific to regularly tamp down daytime
temperatures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
