<HEADLINE>
SAYING IT SMALL  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Inspired perhaps by the tiny gold cross that Agent
Dana Scully wears, women have been snapping up delicate chain
necklaces with crosses or other diminutive drops.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany &AMP; Co. has an 18-karat gold cross on a chain ($200) and
Elsa Peretti's cross on a chain in gold ($290) or sterling silver
($60), as well as Ms. Peretti's minuscule bird or teardrop in
silver ($60 each).
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Roberts has designed what he calls ``floating''
necklaces of nearly invisible fishing wire with tiny dangles that
appear to float at the base of the throat. Barneys New York has his
``floating'' diamond cross ($450). Neiman Marcus has his three
diamond crosses on invisible wires ($675) and M &AMP; J Savitt's cubic
zirconia cross on a silver chain ($115).
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's has Fantasia's cubic zirconia solitaire on a
silver chain ($125) and Judith Jack's marcasite cross ($48).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
