<SLUG> BC-SOC-WYNALDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEAM IN FRANCE: `LES MISERABLES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JILL R. DORSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Eric Wynalda sat in the shadows beneath the
bleachers at Spartan Stadium Saturday night, sporting a freshly
buzzed head and showing a tremendous amount of restraint.
</P>
<P>
   After much prodding, Wynalda finally said what anyone who
followed the U.S. national team during the World Cup already knew:
``It was just miserable. The whole World Cup experience was
miserable. We just felt so helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   So Wynalda did the only thing he knew to do _ he hightailed it
back from France in time to start for the Clash (5-11) against Los
Angeles (14-2).
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda had an assist to Richard Gough in the 15th minute but
the Clash lost, 2-1, thanks to Galaxy goals by Paul Caligiuri in
the 64th minute and Harut Karapetyan in the 85th minute. The
outcome extended San Jose's losing streak to five games and Los
Angeles' winning streak to four.
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda, who along with New England's Joe-Max Moore and Mike
Burns were the first national team players to play in MLS games
since the U.S. team was eliminated Thursday, came back for two
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, ``the World Cup effort is over,'' and second,
``I wasn't playing that much anyway. I wanted to play in France and
I wasn't given that opportunity and I want to play now. ... I've
got a lot to prove to this club and to myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've taken a lot from this club with regards to the national
team ... that I was more involved with the national team than with
this club and that I saved myself for national team games and that
wasn't fair to me. ... I think this is my way of proving that my
heart was always here because it has been.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, Wynalda's World Cup experience was disappointing. At
worst, it did nothing to showcase his skills at the international
level. In his third World Cup appearance, Wynalda started against
Germany, was benched against Iran and entered the Yugoslavia game
as a substitute in the second half. In all, he played less than 90
minutes and barely got a touch on the ball during the two weeks.
But the experience led him to at least one decision about the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made my mind up after the Iran game that I am going to go
for my fourth (World Cup) because there is no way I'm going to let
my WC career end like that,'' Wynalda said.
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda was slow to point a finger at national team coach Steve
Sampson. Wynalda did say that Sampson's lack of experience in the
international arena was apparent and that any relationship that
Wynalda had with Sampson is virtually over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve and I used to have a very good relationship and we used
to talk but somewhere along the line, there just wasn't a dialogue
anymore,'' Wynalda said. ``Since (Sampson cut captain) John Harkes,
I think that he made up the mind that he wanted to sever the cord
there. The people who were most honest with him got hurt the
most.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda's quick return to the Clash was greeted with enthusiasm
by the organization and 22,694 fans, who offered a standing
ovation. But, as has been rumored, Wynalda's time in San Jose may
be short. Wynalda's contract runs out at the end of this season and
he has a one-year option.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rumors were true, I did have an opportunity to go back to
Europe but I can't be specific because then you get in trouble,''
Wynalda said. ``My contract ends this year and it has an option. If
MLS can convince me, I'll stay. But either way, by the time I'm 30,
I'll be free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
