u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PEONY-NYT &LR;      06-29 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATE OF `PEONY' MAY HANG ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ With barely a week to go before the scheduled
opening of ``The Peony Pavilion'' in New York City, Lincoln Center
Festival director Nigel Redden said Monday there was still a slim
chance that intervention by President Clinton would persuade
Chinese authorities to allow the opera's actors to fly to New York
in time for opening night, July 7.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright
arrived in Shanghai on Monday night after three days in Beijing
that were characterized by remarkably open public discussion of
issues like freedom and human rights. Redden said he was planning a
news conference on Tuesday to urge the president to extend that
spirit of openness to artistic freedom while he was in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time when President Clinton, or Secretary of State
Albright, should speak out,'' Redden said. ``My hope is that
somehow the timing of his visit will help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Redden flew here a week ago, after Shanghai's Bureau of Culture
suddenly blocked shipment of the elaborate sets, costumes and props
for the classic Chinese opera, raising objections to the innovative
staging of the production and calling it too feudal, superstitious
and pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of getting nowhere in negotiations, and a
confrontation with Shanghai officials at Shanghai's Hongqiao
International Airport, Redden left for Hong Kong. But he came back
the next day after the authorities agreed to allow the sets,
costumes and props _ all paid for and technically owned by Lincoln
Center and its co-producers _ to be shipped.
</P>
<P>
   The shipment left Shanghai on Sunday and arrived safely in New
York, Redden said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the actors of ``The Peony Pavilion,'' members of the Kunqu
Opera Company who had never before performed this refined
16th-century opera in its full, 55-act form, have not been given
clearance to go to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the actors were taken by the authorities to a country
guest house outside Shanghai to rehearse a revised script of the
opera, Redden said, apparently to keep them far from the White
House press corps, which descended on Shanghai Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Two censors were there monitoring the rehearsal, Redden said, as
well as a new director, replacing Chen Shi-Zheng, who was born in
China and moved to the United States in 1987. He was hired by
Lincoln Center to direct a groundbreaking new version of the opera.
</P>
<P>
   Redden said he and Chen attended rehearsals on Sunday and Monday
and were surprised to find that the revisions seemed minor, in some
cases virtually inconsequential. Yet an official from the Bureau of
Culture told Redden that more discussions were needed and that
there was no guarantee that the actors would be allowed to leave
Shanghai this week in any case.
</P>
<P>
   Redden has said from the beginning of his negotiations that
Lincoln Center would be prepared to accept minor changes but not
anything that would alter the artistic integrity of Chen's
production or that did not have Chen's approval.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's version of the opera, a novel interpretation that takes
more than 20 hours to perform, met great response and received a
rave review in People's Daily, the Communist Party's principal
newspaper, when a dress rehearsal was performed here this month.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it brought objections from Ma Bomin, director of Shanghai's
Bureau of Culture, who called ``The Peony Pavilion'' a national
treasure that needed protection from unorthodox interpretations.
She also seemed angered when Chen refused to accept all of the
officials' suggested changes, as directors in China are usually
required to do.
</P>
<P>
   With Shanghai officials convening one long closed-door meeting
after another to discuss the opera over the last week, it appears
that ``The Peony Pavilion'' became a major political issue within
the local government, particularly with the timing of Clinton's
arrival. The nature and details of that internal debate have
remained secret.
</P>
<P>
   Redden, admittedly a neophyte in Chinese politics, said he
remained mystified by the way the opera's fate seemed to be tied up
in local political concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects so well on Chinese culture,'' said Redden,
referring to the production. ``I just don't understand why they
don't want to let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Summing up, he said he was not optimistic: ``It's a game of
chicken, and I'm not sure we're going to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
