<SLUG> BC-NAACP-HOTELS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP RATES HOTEL CHAINS TO FORCE CHANGES
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Conceding he aims to ``intimidate'' the lodging
industry into ``doing the right thing,'' NAACP President Kweisi
Mfume released the civil rights group's ratings of hotel chains on
Monday and urged travelers not to check in at those that scored
low.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the NAACP's ``economic reciprocity initiative,'' the
hotel chains were graded on their ``diversity and minority business
development'' in categories such as employment, vendor relations ,
equity and ownership in hotels, advertising, marketing and
philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hotels that receive a 'D' will not receive NAACP business
dollars,'' explained Mfume. ``And, we will take every opportunity
to inform consumers of our decision and urge them to make similar
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas-based Omni Hotels chain received the lowest grade, a
'D-minus,' and Mfume said the NAACP has purposefully avoided the
Atlanta Omni in booking rooms and events for its annual convention
there next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, you often get what you can get when you can get
it'' because conventions must compete for space, he said. ``But we
were able to extract some punishment (by avoiding the Omni), if not
distribute some rewards'' by booking hotels that scored highest on
the NAACP report card.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the report, Omni Hotels released a statement
saying its 1997 report to the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission showed that ``minorities, including African Americans,
represent a majority of the company's employees.'' Omni said 64
percent of its employees were minorities, including 25 percent
African-American, and 58 percent of its managers were minorities,
including 13 percent African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Omni said this represented an increase in the number of minority
managers, including African-Americans, over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In the NAACP ratings, Omni did score ``excellent'' in minority
employment of division managers and clerical and administrative
workers on their hotel staffs. But Omni rated ``poor'' in the
percentage of properties owned by minorities and in doing business
with minority vendors. Omni also rated ``poor'' in the use of
minority-owned advertising firm, expenditures in minority-owned
media and marketing campaigns aimed at minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Bennett, the Omni Corporate Communications Director,
said the firm's rating was at least partly because it is a private
firm and didn't answer many of the NAACP questions, deeming the
information ``proprietary.'' Its employment statistics came only
from the firm's 25 owned and managed hotels and not its 17
franchised operations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mfume said the hotel industry must realize that
minority workers ``can do something other than carry bags, make
beds and wash dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP gave its top grade, a ``B,'' to Cendant, a chain that
includes Days Inn, Howard Johnson, Travel Lodge and Super 8 Motels.
Next came a B-minus for Promus, with properties including
Doubletree, Embassy Suites, Hampton Inn and Guest Suites and
Resorts.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving a ``D'' the previous year, Memphis-based Promus
said it formed a ``diversity committee'' and tried to bring
African-American companies into its advertising, community
relations and vendor support programs.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott, Westin and Choice, which includes Comfort Inns and
EconoLodges, all received ``C-pluses.'' Holiday Hospitality,
Wyndham, Hilton, and Radisson got ``C's.'' Hyatt and ITT Sheraton
got ``C-minuses.'' Best Western got a ``D-plus'' and Adam's Mark
got a ``D.''
</P>
<P>
   Answering questions at a press conference, Mfume said the
ratings are ``designed to intimidate'' hotel chains into being fair
to the minorities who he said spend over $5 billion a year in
travel and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe, quite frankly, that our corporate friends ought to
be rewarded with our business,'' he said. ``We are looking for
evidence that companies are taking steps to create opportunities
for African Americans and other people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is based on industry responses to an NAACP survey.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Hospitality, based in Atlanta, is a subsidiary of Bass
Hotels and Resorts, and includes Holiday Inns. Responding to the
survey, the company said, ``Bass Hotels and Resorts will continue
efforts to address diversity across its hotel system and corporate
offices, including bringing more diversity to senior managment
ranks, sales and customer service teams.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
