<SLUG> BC-BBN-HOMERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 SOSA, GRIFFEY HOMER HAPPILY IN McGWIRE'S SHADOW  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN SHEA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mark McGwire might feel like a caged animal, but
Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr. feel as free as birds. That's
because McGwire is doing all the dirty work, drawing unprecedented
attention to his awesome batting-practice displays, majestic home
runs and legitimate pursuit of Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa and Griffey are simply waiting in the wings, silently but
effectively keeping within striking distance of Maris without the
pressure and headaches that seem to plague McGwire, even though he
plays in a tiny media market.
</P>
<P>
   In any other season, Sosa and Griffey would be smothered in
national publicity and daily updates on The Chase. But this year is
different because McGwire is so far ahead of Maris' 1961 pace that
anything fewer than 62 home runs would now be a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire entered the weekend, which signaled the halfway point of
the season, with 35 home runs. A 70-homer pace. Sosa, thanks to his
monster June _ a record 19 blasts so far _ checked in with 32
homers, a 64-homer pace. And Griffey had 30, on pace for 60.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of comparison, Griffey also had 30 homers at the
midway point last year, but he was getting gobs of attention
because his Mariners were leading the American League West and
McGwire, who was going nose-to-nose with Griffey, was a member of
the last-place A's.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, McGwire has become an event, and others are sitting
comfortably in the back seat willing to wait until September to hop
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' Sosa said, ``I'm not thinking about
it. I'm not Mark McGwire. Mark McGwire is the man. I'm just trying
to do my job and help the team. Maybe I'll think about it at the
end of the year, but not right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey usually refuses to address any questions relating to
Maris, simplifying things with his standard line: ``I'm not a
home-run hitter.'' It may be true, because Griffey can do so many
other things. But a guy like McGwire would never get away with such
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In the days Griffey was talking about the record, he said,
``It's surprising it's lasted that long with (Jose) Canseco,
McGwire, Cecil (Fielder), Al  &LR; (Belle) and Frank (Thomas) around.
Hey, I'm the little guy in that group. Maybe that's why I don't
have a statue at home with 62 on it.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems as though Griffey's father walked out on the Reds last
week because of problems that date back to 1975. Ken Griffey Sr.,
who doesn't forget much, is still miffed that Sparky Anderson
pulled him for a pinch hitter two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was treated with no respect in 1975 when he pinch-hit for me
in the eighth inning of a game with the bases loaded and no outs
when I was hitting .300,'' Griffey said. ``And nobody knows the
full story of 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Griffey said he was asked by then manager Lou Piniella
and GM Bob Quinn to fake an injury so the Reds could replace him
with Bill Doran. Griffey refused and was placed on the involuntary
retired list. He later signed with Seattle to play with his son.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey also chided the current manager, Jack McKeon, by saying,
``I'm out of the loop because I don't drink whiskey, smoke cigars
and listen to old stories.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
