   MLK _ Janet Reno is expected to announce a limited
re-investigation of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s assassination.
(Brice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-EDUCATION _ The South is making steady progress in a
number of areas of education, but is still clearly behind other
states in the nation, according to a report by the Southern
Regional Education Board released Monday. Georgia is in the middle-
to upper portion of southern states on 11 benchmarks that include
children in pre-k, immunizations, dropout rates and National
Assessment of Education Progress tests. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HIGHWAYS _ Now that there's a new transportation bill that
brings lots of extra money to Texas, what should the state do about
priorities? Senator Phil Gramm meets with Texas Transportation
Commission Chairman David Laney and other transportation leaders to
talk about what the state needs to do. This develops from a 12:30
p.m. meeting/press conference. (Hiott, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ABORT30 _ TALLAHASSEE _ After a yearlong political battle, a new
law banning some abortions could go into effect Tuesday. But
opponents are still waging a legal campaign to block enforcement of
the law. The abortion law bans a procedure that opponents say is
performed late in a woman's pregnancy when a fetus is partially
delivered and then aborted when only its head remains in the birth
canal. Opponents say the procedure, which they call ``partial-birth
abortion,'' is tantamount to infanticide. But abortion rights
advocates say there's no medical term ``partial-birth abortion''
and the law is so broadly written that it will ban abortions
performed in the first trimester. (Date, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   UFO _ A panel of respected scientists says UFOs need to be
looked into. Most of the public would go along with that. According
to an AJC Southern Focus Poll, 59 percent of Southerners and 66
percent of the rest of the nation believe UFOs are real or can't
say for sure. More than half believe extraterrestrial aliens have
visited Earth or might have. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. inches.
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA-VOTE _ Incumbent Alabama Gov. Fob James and his
Republican opponent Winton Blount race around the state to win
votes for Tuesday's runoff. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
