<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END IN SIGHT FOR DEBACLE OF DAVIS LAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTOLA, Calif. _ The continuing saga of Davis Lake has turned
into a giant monkey that the California Department of Fish and Game
just hasn't been able to shake off its back.
</P>
<P>
   But the inside word is that the DFG will try to shed the nemesis
over the July 4 weekend, and the immediate weeks that follow.
That's when the DFG hopes to make the first in a series of trout
plants that will add up to more than 700,000 fish, including tons
of 5-to 15-pound trout, the biggest trout plants in the history of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   There's never been another story quite like this one anywhere in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Lake, in the Sierra Nevada northwest of Reno, Nev., had
been one of the nation's most aquatic-rich mountain lakes. That is
why it produced a strain of wild rainbow trout that were huge by
mountain standards, with 16-to 24-inch trout quite typical, with
the brightest spots and the fightingest fight you've ever seen.
They added special sizzle for place always enticing to camp, see
wildlife and enjoy outdoor adventure.
</P>
<P>
   All that changed when two locals reportedly caught some pike at
Winnemucca Lake in Nevada, then illegally transported the fish into
Davis and plunked them in. The habitat was perfect for pike, and in
two years, they wiped out both year classes of young trout. From
the start, DFG biologists feared that the pike would slip
downstream and wipe out other fisheries, so they poisoned the lake
last fall, against intense protests by residents.
</P>
<P>
   You probably have heard the rest: Despite all kinds of promises
that everything would be fine, the poisoning was screwed up so
badly, with lax monitoring, overkill on poisons and lingering toxic
readings, that the State Water Resources Control Board made the
lake off limits to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Water Board fined the DFG the equivalent about $500,000
(in the form of trout plants at nearby Frenchman Lake and Grizzly
Creek), the Plumas County district attorney tried to arrest the DFG
people who were responsible for the foul-ups, and business owners
are lining up for lawsuits. If you took a vote in Plumas County
right now, I bet they'd vote 95 percent or higher to secede from
California.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the tests finally came in clean. The Department of
Health Services will have one last series of tests, then the DFG
plans to hold a public hearing in Portola to discuss hopes of
opening the lake for the July 4 weekend holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of fish planned to be stocked is staggering. 700,000?
In comparison, Lake Merced in San Francisco, which is within 20
miles of 3 million people, gets only 15,000 pounds of trout per
year from the DFG. In addition, the DFG will be buying many loads
of bigger fish from outside vendors, and provide fish from many
different year classes.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is the planted fish will quickly take on the
characteristics of the previous wild strains that made Davis so
popular among anglers.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is that the true future of this once-great
fishery will be the progeny of those planted fish _ fish that will
be born wild and learn to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information on Davis Lake and Plumas County, call
800-326-2247).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
