<SLUG> BC-TV-BIKER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIKER BROTHERHOOD: THE SOFTER SIDE OF A MOTORCYCLE GANG 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Broadcast details appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The home life of the ``Ching-a-Ling,'' a subspecies of the genus
``Biker Brotherhood,'' is inspected Tuesday night on a new series
unoriginally titled ``Inside Story'' and presided over by the
ubiquitous Bill Kurtis. Known to some as a motorcycle gang, the
Ching-a-Lings are here described as ``Road Warriors,'' dedicated,
they announce, to ``family, freedom, honor.'' The black-garbed,
ferociously decorated fellowship (they go in for Nazi symbols on
their jackets and tattoos everywhere) is tracked to its home lairs
and revealed to have a domestic side.
</P>
<P>
   The Ching-a-Lings are a mostly Hispanic group of perhaps 30
Bronx motorcycle enthusiasts: ``a religion, a brotherhood, a
family,'' Kurtis croons. There are intimations of a violent past
involving drugs, rape, even murder. These days heroin is strictly
forbidden, and members hint that persons who do not live up to
their present standards can count on retaliation. (``We ain't no
saints here,'' one confesses or boasts.) Details of what they mean
by ``taking care of business'' we are left to imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Most of this hour, which can be enjoyed as a takeoff on pop
sociology (``the Ching-a-Ling culture is steeped heavily in the
past,'' says Kurtis), is given to the softer side of the tribe. One
female companion proclaims, ``I'm his property,'' and the men
report that their bikes attract too many girls to handle. Family
values receive their due. We travel with one biker (on foot) as he
escorts his little daughter around the neighborhood on Halloween
night; his hefty presence gives a certain imperative to trick or
treat.
</P>
<P>
   You can also see the comrades partying, posturing (``Win it all
or lose everything'' is their slogan), hanging out and making an
annual visit to the cemetery to pay homage to a fellow member
killed in a shootout. There are flowers and candles, and cocaine
fumes are blown and beer is spit reverently over the tomb of
another departed. ``The Ching-a-Lings have seen a need to evolve,''
Kurtis says unsmilingly, to pictures of them riding their machines
on behalf of Toys for Tots, but not on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INSIDE STORY: ROAD WARRIORS: THE BIKER BROTHERHOOD'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Tuesday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kurtis, host; produced by BNN for A&AMP;E; Steven Rosenbaum,
executive producer for BNN; Michael Cascio, executive producer for
A&AMP;E; Gayle Gilman, supervising producer for A&AMP;E.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
