<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2480 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK30-COX     06-29 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers ready to return to game
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Wohlers graduated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves closer will be joining the Richmond Braves, Atlanta's
Class AAA affiliate, tonight after working out in Orlando for the
past 10 days to regain his control. He is expected to be in
Richmond's bullpen in Durham, N.C., for the R-Braves' International
League game with the Durham Bulls, which this season beame a Tampa
Bay farm club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a matter of his delivery and mechanics and his
confidence in all those things,'' Atlanta general manager John
Schuerholz said. ``He'd gotten to the point where he had complete
confidence and consistency with all the pitches he was throwing. We
all just feel like it's time to go out and face some competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz took that recommendation in a Monday-morning
telephone call from special assistant Guy Hansen, who has been
working with Wohlers the past week at the team's minor-league
complex. Hansen will stop working with Wohlers, who now will pitch
for highly respected Richmond coach Bill Fischer, a long-time
fixture in the system who coached Wohlers during his minor-league
career.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves still have no master plan for Wohlers' return nor
will they estimate how long he will remain with Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``No general plan but to go pitch,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-20 club
</P>
<P>
   Both Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine will get one more start before
the All-Star break but with 11 wins each, both have a leg up on
twin 20-win seasons. It may not a rarity for them _ both reached 20
in 1992 and 1993 _ but it remains a rare feat in the National
League. Over the last 27 years, only two other clubs have had two
20-win pitchers _ San Francisco in 1993 with Bill Swift and John
Burkett and St. Louis in 1985 with Joaquin Andujar and John Tudor.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine has had three 20-win seasons, Maddux has had two but
neither has one since 1993. Maddux has subsequently twice won 19
while Glavine has topped out at 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty wins as a pitcher is the same thing as a hitter hitting
.300,'' Glavine said. ``It's kind of the number that's out there
all the time. I guess that defines a great season, rather than just
a good one. I still feel I can have a good season and not win 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Over his career, Glavine's winning percentage has dipped
slightly in the second half of the season (.635 to .574) while
Maddux's winning percentage has increased in the second half (.605
to .659).
</P>
<P>
   Simon says
</P>
<P>
   Batting .254 at Richmond when the Braves re-called him, Randall
Simon was hitting for his lowest average since his first season of
rookie ball (.254 at Danville in 1993). After hitting a career-high
.308 at Richmond last year, Simon explained the fall-off as a
combination of the International League's decision to pitch him
more cautiously and his own inability to lay off pitches off the
plate. Then he begain listening to Richmond hitting coach Max
Venable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been giving me the advice to go take more walks and give
my teammates an opportunity to do the job,'' Simon said. ``I've
started doing that more they they're starting to pitch to me a
little more.''
</P>
<P>
   That advice may have been lost in handling when he reported to
the Braves on Sunday. The first pitch he saw in his first at-bat,
he singled.
</P>
<P>
   Hot and cold
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko and Andruw Jones are swinging the hottest bats as
the Braves take their last road trip of the first half. Klesko
enters the Tampa Bay series with nine multi-hit games in his last
16 starts, while Jones is hitting .356 in June. Javy Lopez, who
takes an eight-game hitting streak into tonight's game, has 18 RBIs
in his last 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Tony Graffanino is in a 1-for-22 slump, followed
closely by Chipper Jones at 1-for-20.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
