<HEADER>
A2481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOORE-COLUMN30-COX     06-29 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOORE-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In latest sports labor dispute, siding with owners is most
logical
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just like their brethren in baseball, those on both
sides of this NBA labor fight between players and owners will bleed
forever. Nobody really wins these things. But if forced to make a
choice, take the owners in something like a second-round TKO.
</P>
<P>
   The players simply don't have a Joe Bugner of a chance during
this struggle for power of a sport that owns the best potential for
turning billions into trillions sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   With NBA arenas already filled at 91 percent capacity in recent
years, bigger and fancier arenas are on the way (translated: higher
ticket prices and more bucks for the league). Television gave the
NBA a $2.6 billion deal before last season. There also is the
foreign market. Given President Clinton's initiative with China,
who's to say buying Bulls' paraphernalia in Beijing won't become
more popular than visiting Mao's corpse?
</P>
<P>
   So, after the owners voted Monday to use an option in the
collective-bargaining agreement to impose a player lockout to get
more of the NBA's total revenue, the bell was rung. Although the
players continue to stick and move while saying they won't budge on
any of their gains through the decades, they eventually will rush
into a straight right along the way to what will be the ugliest of
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Steve Woods, the Atlanta-based Jerry Maguire of
an NBA agent, ``This is like Iraq against the United States. For
the sake of negotiations, Iraq has to talk tough, but for everybody
looking in from the outside, it is futile for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the NBA players, and it starts with this: Of
the 400 players who ended this past season, 211 are free agents.
Among other things, the lockout prohibits teams from negotiating
player contracts. That means more than half of those in the league
will be without NBA-related income until this labor fight is over.
The players union says it has a fund to help those in need, but I'm
guessing that fund won't match the vast resources of their Muhammad
Ali counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   To worsen matters for the players, the NBA's new television deal
is guaranteed to pay the owners for an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   End of bout.
</P>
<P>
   This is disturbing in a way. Because this is America, we
shouldn't have salary caps or any of those other socialistic
controls that owners employ in professional sports to save
themselves from themselves. The last I checked, there wasn't a
report of Kevin Garnett shoving a knife against the throat of
Minnesota Timberwolves owner Glen Taylor to get that $126 million.
Still, the owners want the players to agree to an even tighter cap
that would keep salaries from rising at a rate dictated by supply
and demand. You know, one of our basic principles in the land of
the free.
</P>
<P>
   But here's why I'm not totally troubled by the owners winning
this fight in a romp: Everything else. In addition to keeping the
status quo financially, the players want the right to smoke
marijuana, to choose their coach, to choke their coach, to wear
shorts to their ankles, to miss practice, to ignore the media and
to ignore the fans.
</P>
<P>
   That's for starters. Given the lesser of both evils here, maybe
socialism isn't that bad.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore's column appears in the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
