<SLUG> BC-TV-KELLY-560-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG LAOTIANS' TROUBLED LIFE CAPTURED ON `P.O.V.' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kelly Saeteurn is a Dr. Laura kind of person _ the kind of
person Dr. Laura likes to tee up and smack down the fairway every
day on her radio show.
</P>
<P>
   A Laotian born in a refugee camp in Thailand and raised in
Richmond, Calif., Kelly was pregnant and unmarried when she
graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Her boyfriend, Tony Saelio, was also Laotian and had served jail
terms for burglary and robbery. Kelly gave birth to their son and
began living with his family in Oakland. Things got drearier when
her family responsibilities interfered with her junior college
classes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where Dr. Laura reminds Kelly that she's been shacking up
and scolds her for having one child, then another, out of wedlock.
Then Dr. Laura goes into her backswing, pivots her hip and tells
Kelly to quit whining and sleep in the messy bed she's made for
herself.
</P>
<P>
   That would be about a 300-yard drive in Dr. Laura-land. But for
filmmaker Spencer Nakasako, Kelly and Tony are documentary film
subjects of the first order. The result is ``Kelly Loves Tony,''
airing Tuesday night on PBS' ``P.O.V.'' series.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's not even Nakasako's film. He arranged for Kelly
to get a camcorder when she graduated from high school, then let
Kelly and Tony record their own lives for the next year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Kelly Loves Tony'' is gritty, authentic and finally
mesmerizing, whether it's Tony training the camera on the
understandably moody Kelly as they squabble through another day, or
Kelly wearily holding a mike and unburdening herself in front of
the lens.
</P>
<P>
   It's a film in which Kelly is gripping American culture with a
desperate handhold, while the Iu Mien tribal culture of Laos pulls
at her ankles.
</P>
<P>
   She's painfully isolated in Tony's home, where custom dictates
that she assume an expanded domestic role. She feels she's getting
little help with the baby, and practically no understanding from
Tony, as she copes with schoolwork. Education isn't Tony's strong
suit. And Kelly wonders why neither Tony nor his family seems in a
hurry to get the wedding done.
</P>
<P>
   Tony comes across as jolly but clueless. In one exchange with
Kelly, he blithely starts a sentence with, ``If you were a real
woman ...'' She shoots him a laser look in return. Tony wonders _
(set ital)doh!(end ital) _ ``Did I jump into some stuff, or what?''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a coin laundry, Kelly angrily hits Tony with her
opinion of the moment that he is a ``stupid dumb ass.''
</P>
<P>
   She might as well flog a sack of flour. The pudgy Tony simply
isn't equipped to receive bulletins. Alone afterward, he chirps
into the microphone, ``Our relationship right now is kind of not
perfect, you know?'' Yes, we noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Then Kelly finds out that she's pregnant again. You can imagine
Dr. Laura reaching for her putter to tap Kelly into the hole. But
to listen to Kelly, ruminating again about her in-laws, is to hear
the truth about the bicultural predicament of a young Asian
American woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they found out that I was pregnant, they were happy,''
she says. ``They didn't understand what the big deal is, having to
quit school and everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``To them, a kid should always come first. It's not like I
disagree with them or anything like that. It's just that I feel so
disappointed in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
