<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: VERDI OUTDOORS; FRENCH CULTURE ABROAD; WOUNDED
PIANIST; MEMORIALS TO IRISH IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For opera lovers and especially for Verdi
aficionados, Wednesday night at 7:30 is the time and the Central
Park Summerstage at the Rumsey Playfield at 72nd Street near Fifth
Avenue is the place.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Vincent La Selva and his New York Grand Opera
Company will begin their 25th successive season of free, fully
staged opera and the second half of their Viva Verdi! Festival,
which is offering all 28 Verdi operas in chronological order. The
attraction is ``Luisa Miller,'' Verdi's 15th opera, based on a
Friedrich von Schiller play and first performed in December 1849,
when the composer was 36.
</P>
<P>
   Wasteland
</P>
<P>
   Warning that France's cultural influence is waning, Jack Lang,
the former culture minister, on Monday proposed the creation of a
Ministry of Foreign Cultural Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In comments in the newspaper Le Monde, Lang, now a leader of the
Foreign Affairs Committee in Parliament, cited the decline of
French cinema and cuts of 15 percent in three years in the budget
to promote French culture abroad. A lack of action, he said, ``will
threaten our political influence and compromise our economic
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Slice of Life
</P>
<P>
   The bagel and hand wounds go together like the bagel and lox.
Just ask emergency-room physicians and the pianist Andre-Michel
Schub, who sliced his right palm while slicing a bagel on Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Schub was scheduled to be the soloist
that evening with the Rochester Philharmonic in the demanding
Tchaikovsky Concerto No. 1 at the opening of the Vail Valley Music
Festival in Vail, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Eugenia Zukerman, the festival's music director, thought he
might have to cancel. Schub refused to hear of it. Having declined
treatment, he played, won a standing ovation and then, still
bleeding, went off to the emergency room. The prognosis is for full
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, through Aug. 5, continues Wednesday when Robert
Bernhardt leads the Rochester in a program of arias and other music
from operas.
</P>
<P>
   Memorial
</P>
<P>
   Two new statues commemorating the Irish famine were dedicated on
Sunday in a $1 million, 6,000-square-foot downtown Boston park. The
sculptures by Robert Shure depict an anguished, starving family on
the Irish shore and a more hopeful one landing in Boston, where
more than 100,000 Irish immigrated as a result of the famine, which
began with a potato blight, led to the dispossession of farmers and
claimed an estimated 1 million lives from 1845 to 1851.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
