<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2547 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     06-29 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORAN ON GORAN: IDIOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The tall blackbearded man is cursing Goran Ivanisevic.
The tall blackbearded man is Goran Ivanisevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things I say to myself are terrible,'' he confesses, but
doesn't wish to tutor me in Croation naughtiness. ``No, I will not
tell you.'' Kind man, he wishes to spare my ears, if not his own,
and the others in Wimbledon's hazardous Court 2 who may not be deaf
to his native tongue.
</P>
<P>
   I know one word in Croation: idiot. Same as English. He directs
it at himself a lot. ``The rest is very bad, the adjectives, the
phrases,'' says a Croation journalist named Petar Radovic. ``Lucky
for him the umpire doesn't understand Croation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody understands Goran Ivanisevic, who lately has played
tennis more like an idiot than the incendiary he can be. Least of
all Goran. ``I am a movie ... interesting to watch ... a thriller
... but you never know how it will end,'' he says in his bass
voice, much deeper than his concentration.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like another unhappy ending for this 26-year-old,
6-foot vertical monument to erraticism for a couple of reels. A
burly Czech, Daniel Vacek, slugged away with Goran, toe to toe, for
the first 75 minutes of a 2-hour-13 minute shootout saga, and came
within a point of a two-set lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get two sets down, bye-bye,'' Goran is recalling after
his 6-7 (6-8), 7-6 (7-4), 6-3, 6-4 triumph that raised him to a
fourth-rounder against Todd Martin. ``But now is different.''
</P>
<P>
   The way he escaped wasn't. At 5-6, 30-40 _ the set point _
Ivanisevic, his mien as dark and menacing as the clouds that
shortly would deliver almost two hours of rain, raised his left arm
and blugeoned his 24th ace of the afternoon. Crash! Then, blam!
Along came No. 25, and trouble flew away with it. Let it rain. He
could _ and did _ finish up later.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, I know one other Croatian word: as. Ace. This should be
Goran's first name. The ace is for Goran what the knuckleball is
for Tim Wakefield _ life blood _ but a ton or two faster. Without
aces he is Bill Clinton minus lawyers, Milosevic without an army,
Keith Richards lacking a guitar, Michaela Larsen deprived of a
stove.
</P>
<P>
   Goran has so many aces up his short sleeve that if he were a
gambler in his movie, he would have been shot or run out of town.
Nobody has ever served as many at the Big W. He trumped Vacek with
44 of them, two short of his tournament record that he set last
year against Magnus Norman _ while losing the match. He holds the
season record, 1603 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it is with him. Even flocks of them winging past
foes aren't always enough protection. He riddled Andre Agassi with
37 in the 1992 final _ and still lost.
</P>
<P>
   After six years in the top ten he has skidded to No. 25, a first
round fade-out in nine of 13 tournaments. After falling at the
opening hurdle of the Australian and French, he had an excellent
chance for a Grand Slop (first-round defeats in all four majors).
Goran blew it by beating Grant Stafford, And has kept going, the
forgotten guy looking better all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Goran can win this,'' says Pete Sampras. ``If he gets
going he can beat anybody. His serve can get very scary. You just
have to guess on it, and mostly you're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can beat them all, and maybe I will,'' Goran says. ``This is
the tournament I have the best chance of winning. Is really
different now.''
</P>
<P>
   What's different?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is new six months, a new time. I cannot play worse than
the first six months. I start to feel sorry for myself. Really
disgusted. I try to be cool. I'm not a cool guy. I have to explode,
yell at myself. I don't throw rackets _ but I should start again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not easy for me to hear all the talking that he's gone _
me _ can't play any more. Hurts. So I stop feeling sorry for
myself, and play, just enjoy no matter what happens. I'm happy
again, playing good again.''
</P>
<P>
   London bookmakers agree. His price has dropped to 6-to-1, same
as 1996 champ Richard Krajicek, behind Sampras's even money.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his growls and glares, Ivanisevic is a teddy bear of
great charm who never hides his feelings. When he lost to the
forgettable Dinu Pescario in _ of course _ the first round at the
1997 US Open, he declared, ``I should enter the women's tournament.
Maybe I can win first round. Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wimbledon's grass has been his foremost platform. Finalist
in 1992 and 1994, he's made $16 million and change in prize money,
and never won an important tournament. Is this a wonderful game or
what?
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, when it's raining they show the 1992 final on
TV. I watch. I can't lose the way I'm playing ... but I do to
Agassi in five,'' Goran sighs.
</P>
<P>
   But he's still here, as impossible to figure as the weather, a
cloudburst of aces, and returning well, too. ``I have to win this
someday.'' If he holds the trophy on high Sunday, the tall
blackbearded man can call himself a ``pobjeda.'' That's success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
