<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS PREVAILS AFTER LONG HAUL AGAINST ENQUIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Let's just say that it took a while to declare a winner
in the Pete Sampras-Thomas Enquist match. Four days, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   The players warmed up Friday, but rain forced a postponement to
Saturday. The match was then suspended by showers, and Sunday is a
mandatory off day.
</P>
<P>
   Monday they tried again and, after still another rain delay _
this one nearly three hours _ MondaySampras finally prevailed, 6-3,
7-6 (7-4), 7-6, (7-3). The top seed relied on old reliable, his
serve, which produced 29 aces.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras led, 6-3, 1-0, when play was suspended Saturday, but
Monday Enquist was playing better, holding serve fairly easily.
Sampras controlled the tie-breakers, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tough,'' said Sampras, who has won only two
tournaments this year, at Philadelphia and Atlanta. ``Thomas is,
obviously, not as used to the grass-court surface compared to hard
court, but he serves very, very big (eight aces), especially his
second serve. And if he's going to serve that big, he's going to
hold serve on grass, and it came down to a couple of breakers.''
</P>
<P>
   During rain delays, players are given a 20-minute notice when
play is set to resume. ``Then, when it stops raining, you have to
get yourself emotionally keyed up again, get ready for the match,''
Sampras said. ``It's the same for everybody. It's not easy; you've
just got to try your best, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the rain delays, Sampras added, ``It's part of
Wimbledon, it's part of the aura about this place. You're going to
have a lot of rain delays, and we certainly had our fair share.
There's a lot of hanging around, a lot off dead time, and there's
nothing really you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been only been a so-so year for Sampras, to the point
where Richard Krajicek called Sampras only the ``10th player on the
tour'' a few days ago. Marcelos Rios overtook Sampras for the
world's No. 1 ranking for four weeks in late March, ending the
American's 102-week reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff doesn't really faze me,'' Sampras said. ``I know my
capabilities. I know how I'm playing this week. That's really my
main concern. The year has been a little bit up and down, but this
point last year, my year was pretty similar, except I won
Australia. So, whatever, it doesn't really faze me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was power against power in the Tim Henman-Patrick Rafter
outing, as Henman reached the quarterfinals with a 6-3, 6-7 (7-3),
6-3, 6-2 decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted to be through to the quarterfinals, but I do
feel very, very relaxed about the whole situation,'' said the
Englishman, the 12th seed. ``I surprised myself how relaxed I was.
I felt very loose in my whole game, the way I was serving. I wasn't
really trying to hit my serve particularly hard, but sometimes when
you've got good rhythm, that's when you serve best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Likewise on my returns, I was keeping it simple, and I think
that's when I do play best, when it's instinctively.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, the 1996 champion and ninth seed, had to go through a
couple of tie-breakers in defeating Nicolas Kiefer in straight
sets, 6-4, 7-6 (7-2), 7-6 (7-4). Krajicek has faced only four break
points in three matches, two against Kiefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the two break points, I served very good first serves and I
played a very good tie-breaker, especially in the second set,''
said Krajicek. ``I never return well, but if the serve and volley
is there, and if it's sharp, then I can still win these matches in
straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play a good returner like Nicolas, I think it's important
to mix it up, in the body, the speed, and the slice. So I think
that was maybe even more important than my first serve. I varied it
pretty well, and he couldn't see where I was serving my second
serve, so he was always guessing, and I think that is a good
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
