<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-BANKS-300&AMP;ADD-N     06-29 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-BANKS-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 WEAK KOREAN BANKS TO BE MERGED WITH `AMBULANCE BANKS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ The government's decision to close five
small weak banks has drawn a tepid response from economists, who
regard the move as a symbolic but largely ineffective start to
fixing the nation's ailing financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give them credit for making a first move,'' said Lee
Jeung-hoon, a banking analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in
Seoul, after the plan to merge the five banks into bigger,
healthier competitors was announced Monday. ``This is the
first-ever closure of any Korean bank, so it was a very brave thing
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Daedong Bank will be closed and merged into
Kookmin Bank, Dongnam Bank into Housing and Commercial Bank,
Dongwha Bank into Shinhan Bank, Kyonggi Bank into Koram Bank and
Chungchong Bank into Hana Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In real terms, the closings will have little significance. The
five banks being closed hold only 7.2 percent of all the bad debts
in the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   The plan gave seven other shaky banks a reprieve and foisted new
problems onto the banks that will be forced to swallow their
cousins, nicknamed ``ambulance banks'' by an analyst, James Han, at
Jardine Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Supervisory Commission, the new regulatory agency
established to police the financial system, plans to spend 17.5
trillion won, or $12.65 billion, to buy nonperforming loans from
the five banks, add capital to the acquiring banks and establish a
reserve fund to buy whatever unforeseen problem debts arise in the
six months after the mergers.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts like Han worry about what will happen after six
months, especially when most market strategists see no end in sight
to the bankruptcies that are happening at the rate of between 2,000
and 3,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the longer term, there's likely to be greater costs for
the good banks than they would have had otherwise,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not even the bank regulators are completely confident that they
have accounted for all of the problems at the five banks, or that
further problems will not arise. Indeed, reports in the local media
Monday said executives at Chungchong Bank met late Sunday night to
formally resign so that they would be eligible for severance
packages that cost the bank $35.7 million. The commission said they
would be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   This was the government's first move to solve the banking
crisis, which has hindered efforts to restructure the broad
economy. By some estimates, the South Korean banking system is
staggering under as much as $500 billion of soured loans
accumulated during years of state-directed lending that emphasized
relationships rather than credit quality.
</P>
<P>
   The process of forcing mergers in the banking sector reduces the
need to use the taxpayers' money for a bailout, a prospect the
government has dreaded at a time when the social safety net is
underfinanced and an average of 2,000 people a day are losing their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, foreign investors may end up bearing more of the cost
of cleaning up the banking system than they anticipated, a lesson
investors might bear in mind when considering a stake in any bank
in this region. Foreigners who have bought into the financial
system here have largely bought into those banks that are
considered relatively sound _ in other words, those banks forced to
merge with the worst banks.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Grand National Party on Monday accused the
government of playing favorites in determining which banks would
survive and which would die. Park Jie-won, President Kim Dae-jung's
spokesman, said that the selection process was ``very fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the federation of trade unions representing bank
workers promised to strike if the bank closings were carried
through. Several thousand people are likely to lose their jobs when
the banks are merged.
</P>
<P>
   More than 8,600 police officers were dispatched to each of the
five banks' headquarters and branch offices, but at some locations,
union demonstrators tried to prevent officials from the ``ambulance
banks'' from entering the banks scheduled for closing.
</P>
<P>
   At other sites, teams entering the banks to do the work of
merging computer and back office systems found that computer
passwords had been changed and doors to rooms housing computers
locked without any sign of a key. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
