<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-PARADE-BOS &LR;      06-29 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PARADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY ORDERS PROTESTANT PARADE IN ULSTER REROUTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ The Northern Ireland Parades Commission Monday ruled
that a Protestant parade will not be allowed to march through a
Catholic neighborhood in Portadown next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order, a fraternal group that organizes the parade,
vowed to defy the rerouting order, and violent confrontations are
expected.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three months of political progress that includes
the Good Friday agreement, its overwhelming endorsement by voters,
and the election of a new assembly last week, Northern Ireland's
fledgling spirit of accommodation will face its biggest test this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   There have been standoffs in Portadown over this parade in each
of the last three years, and widespread violence has flared the
last two years after nationalist protestors were forcibly removed
by police from blocking the Garvaghy Road, the disputed part of the
route.
</P>
<P>
   The decision creates a divisive Catch-22 in what recently has
been a more politically harmonious Northern Ireland. Many
Protestant unionists, already bitterly divided over the wisdom of
the Good Friday agreement, say they have compromised enough and see
the rerouting of the parade as a further erosion of their rights
and British identity.
</P>
<P>
   But Catholic nationalists see this as a test of whether the
British government and the overwhelmingly Protestant police force
are serious about treating their concerns equally.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the sensitivity of the situation, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, are
scheduled to hold talks today about Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   Orangemen are named for King William of Orange, who in 1690
defeated the Catholic forces of King James II, establishing the
Protestant hegemony in Northern Ireland. They hold nearly 3,000
parades each year to celebrate that heritage. But most Catholics
consider the parades triumphalist and offensive, and they don't
want them passing through their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   David Jones, a leader of the Portadown Orange lodge that
organizes the parade, pointed out that his group has been marching
the same route since 1807 and sees no need to alter it. ``We don't
recognize the Parades Commission,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alistair Graham, the Parades Commission chairman, said the
decision to block the Orangemen from marching down the Garvaghy
Road was unanimous. It came after parade organizers refused to meet
with the local residents group that opposes the route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the absence of any positive move towards accommodation,
we cannot see at this stage how a parade could proceed again this
year without having a very serious impact on community
relationships, both locally and more widely across Northern
Ireland,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   According to him, the commission has also imposed restrictions
on a planned protest by Garvaghy Road residents that was to
coincide with the parade. Resident leaders said they would also
defy that ban.
</P>
<P>
   Both Graham and the British secretary of state, Mo Mowlam, said
they hoped that parade organizers and resident leaders could reach
an accommodation before Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But there seems little chance of that. The Orange Order
maintains that the residents group is a front for Sinn Fein, the
party that is linked to the Irish Republican Army, and refuses to
talk to its leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Garvaghy Road leader, Breandan Mac Cionnaith, who served
time in prison for IRA activity but denies any links with the IRA
or Sinn Fein, said his group still fears that the police chief,
Ronnie Flanagan, will overrule the commission and allow the march
to proceed as planned through his neighborhood. Flanagan has vowed
to uphold the commission's decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
