<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2597 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-INJUNCTION-B     06-29 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-INJUNCTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE EXTENDS INJUNCTION AGAINST WOODWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Louise Woodward can sell her story to tabloids,
television or the movies, but she won't be able to spend any of the
money until the wrongful death suit filed by the parents of Matthew
Eappen is resolved this fall.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Boston issued a preliminary
injunction &UR;  &LR; Monday against the former au pair which bars her from
spending any money she gets for her story and forces her to notify
the court and the Eappens' lawyer of any deals she makes.
</P>
<P>
   Agreeing that the Eappens are likely to convince a jury that
Woodward was responsible for the death of their eight-month-old-son
-- as the state's highest court ruled two weeks ago, Judge William
G. Young took steps Monday to freeze Woodward's assets so money
will be available should the Eappens win their wrongful death suit
in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an overwhelming likelihood that (Sunil) Eappen will
succeed in establishing Woodward's civil liability for the death of
Matthew Eappen,'' Young wrote in a 21-page decision released
Monday. Sunil Eappen, Matthew's father, is administrator of his
son's estate and sued on its behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But since Woodward is a young woman of ``modest means,'' her
only potential asset is the value of her celebrity, which Young
termed ``a tragic irony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever their protestations,'' Young wrote, ``these parties
need each other in the most practical sense: absent insurance, if
Eappen is to have any chance to collect his expected judgment,
Woodward must amass the necessary funds, and the only potential
source appears to be the same media that all parties agree are most
morally repugnant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens have said that any money received from the wrongful
death suit would go to a foundation they've set up in Matthew's
name to fight child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is questionable whether a British court will enforce
the injunction if Woodward violates it.  &UR;  &LR; While British courts
traditionally have upheld judgments from foreign courts _ such as
damages won in a lawsuit _ they are less likely to find a British
citizen in contempt of an American court order, legal experts have
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fredric L. Ellis, the attorney representing the Eappens, was out
of town Monday and could not be reached for comment. Woodward fired
the lawyers representing her in the civil case last week and they
have not been replaced, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Following her conviction, Woodward and her parents insisted her
story was not for sale, calling any such deal ``distasteful and
inappropriate.'' She said she has turned down six-figure offers and
proclaimed, ``I have no intention of profiting from this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   But 10 days ago, the Daily Mail newspaper, a British tabloid,
admitted it paid Woodward's parents $60,000 for an interview last
November. Since returning to England two weeks ago, Woodward's most
highly-publicized interview was with a BBC television news
magazine, for which she was not paid.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward went home after the state Supreme Judicial Court upheld
her conviction for manslaughter in the death of Matthew, who
prosecutors say died after Woodward violently shook him and struck
his head against a hard surface.
</P>
<P>
   A Middlesex jury convicted Woodward of second-degree murder last
fall, &UR;  &LR; but Superior Court Judge Hiller Zobel reduced the verdict to
manslaughter and freed her on the 279 days she served in prison.
The SJC upheld Zobel's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two hours after the SJC ruling, attorneys for Sunil
Eappen filed the wrongful death suit in federal court. At the same
time, they asked Young to issue two orders: one requiring Woodward
to notify them and the court if she signed any contracts to sell
her story, and a second one barring her from spending the money.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's lawyers argued that such conditions would violate her
First Amendment rights but Young rejected that argument, noting
that Woodward is free to speak or write about her experiences and
sell her story.
</P>
<P>
   Young initially granted a temporary order which expired Monday.
The current injunction will remain in effect until the lawsuit is
concluded; the case is set for trial Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Although Woodward firing her lawyers ordinarily might delay
the case, Young said in his ruling Monday that he would not grant
any continuances.
</P>
</TEXT>
