<SLUG> BC-MISSISSIPPI-BALLET-605(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG DANCERS POUNCE INTO BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Del., Denmark)  (lb) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. _ It is a marvelous anomaly that many of the
world's finest young ballet dancers have just spent two weeks
performing in this otherwise somnolent capital city of some 200,000
people. Jackson, after all, can lay claim to some cultural
sophistication as the home of Eudora Welty, but it is still small
and rural enough that the lead newspaper article one recent day was
about vandalism at a hog farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some irony in a relatively obscure Southern town
hosting this event,'' the mayor, Harvey Johnson, acknowledged in an
interview. And virtually everyone in town agreed it felt sort of
odd to have the dancers here, though they have been to Jackson
before.
</P>
<P>
   The event was the sixth U.S.A. International Ballet Competition,
which ended last weekend. Every four years or so since 1979, it has
brought ballet coaches, company directors and choreographers from
five continents here to view dancers they might not have a chance
to see anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a time when international competitions are
proliferating around the world _ there are now about 15 of them,
including the triennial one in New York, the sixth of which will
occur in June 2000 _ Jackson's, astonishingly enough, may well be
the best attended, most fiercely contested of them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is now the world's premier competition,'' said Bruce
Marks, artistic director emeritus of the Boston Ballet, implying
that in ballet these days, even the competitions compete.
</P>
<P>
   Marks has a bias; he has served as chairman of the jury for the
last three competitions in Jackson. But he isn't necessarily wrong.
Past grand prix winners in Jackson have included Jose Manuel
Carreno, the Cuban dancer who is now a principal at American Ballet
Theater, and Andris Liepa, the former Bolshoi and Kirov star.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, for many ballet companies, it is their best
opportunity to fill openings. And for many dancers, in the United
States and overseas, it is their best opportunity to be seen, to
assess their standing in the world of dance, perhaps to earn a
little prize money and, most important, to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 87 dancers from 26 countries (including New Zealand,
Australia, Mongolia, Cuba and South Korea, as well as Eastern and
Western Europe and South America), all selected from applications
and videotapes, joined the competition. There were three rounds,
with dancers eliminated after the first two. By round three, 37
dancers remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to me to get to the third round, so I would
get to perform all the solos I prepared,'' said Lenaig Guegan, 22,
a French dancer who is a member of the Royal Danish Ballet in
Copenhagen, and was hoping, with her boyfriend and fellow dancer,
Bernard Courtot de Bouteiller, 24, to attract the attention of
other artistic directors. ``We're a bit bored where we are,'' she
said. He added, ``If we could get a contract somewhere, that would
be great.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a provocative thing, throughout the week, to hear the
dancers routinely referred to as ``competitors,'' to see the
women's senior gold-medal winner, a 24-year-old Russian dancer,
Anna Antonicheva, burst into tears like a beauty-pageant winner at
the announcement of her triumph, and to see Ms. Guegan so obviously
despondent after winning a merit award but not one of the main
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   She and Courtot were among many at the event who decried the
idea of applying the numerical standards of sport to an art form,
though everyone conceded that the audition was no less competitive
in its way and that all performers needed a competitive spirit to
match their expectations of themselves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Competing, but With Whom?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that in dance you should compete for a
title,'' said Elisabeth Carroll, a coach and former dancer with
American Ballet Theater and the Joffrey and Harkness ballets. ``You
compete with the audience, and in that sense you have to win every
night. The difference is you make your competitors happy. Here you
want to make them sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitive events discourage the expression and feeling that
are the main business of art, the argument goes, and encourage
dancers to be sensational and superficial, to rely on the
gravity-defying athletic leaps and diverse turns on toe that draw
gasps from an audience _ ``the flash and bash,'' in the words of
the prominent dance coach David Howard _ but have little to do with
the evocative grace of the art; jumping, after all, is not dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've often wondered if we lived in outer space, would we be
trying so hard to get to earth?'' Howard said. For the audience,
too, a competition is an odd experience.
</P>
<P>
   What was presented in Jackson was not a finished ballet
performance, with its arcs of narrative and music and variety of
choreographed passages. Rather, the evenings consisted of
individual dancer after individual dancer (with the occasional pair
thrown in), each offering a few minutes from the 19th-century
classical repertory (solos from works like ``Esmeralda,'' ``Don
Quixote'' and ``Paquita,'' and pas de deux from ``Sleeping Beauty''
and ``Le Corsaire'') and later, something contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   They were bite-size ballet nuggets filled with leaps and turns,
the dance equivalent of a football highlight film or an Olympic
gymnastics event. And when Renata Pavam Maia, a 16-year-old from
Brazil who would win a silver medal, danced the final round with a
bandaged ankle, wincing through her performance and weeping as she
took her bows, it seemed an echo of Kerri Strug.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, everyone acknowledges that the competitions
are effective professional tools, clearinghouses where dancers'
talents can be displayed, discussed and bartered. And for all their
ambivalence, dancers do want to win, because with winning comes the
imprimatur of supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   All this puts an unusual burden on the judges, who must try to
see beyond the flash and bash of each dancer in order to assess his
or her artfulness. The 13 judges, all from different countries,
awarded no grand prix this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that means is that we didn't think anyone was ready to
leap onto the stage at the Metropolitan Opera at just this
moment,'' Marks said. ``We definitely saw the potential for that,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   They did award some $60,000 in prizes and scholarships to 21
dancers, including Ms. Guegan (a merit award in the name of Robert
Joffrey, the jury chairman of the first competition), Courtot (who
won a silver medal) and Rasta Thomas, from Washington, who won the
top prize in the senior men's division, though he is only 16. (The
junior division was ostensibly for dancers 15 through 18; the
senior, 19 through 26.)
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a principal with the Hartford Ballet, doesn't even want
to be a dancer. A student of martial arts with aspirations to
attend the Yale School of Drama, he exhibits a supernaturally
flawless charm (``The pleasure is all mine'' he is wont to say
after a handshake), and he intends to be the next Hollywood action
hero. ``I want to inspire, I want to be a legend, I want to be
president of the United States, I want to be so much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Begun With Energy and Fund Raising
</P>
<P>
   Major international competitions date back to 1964, when the
first one was held in Varna, Bulgaria; it and eventually expanded
into a series of contests that rotated annually among Varna, Moscow
and Tokyo. (When Tokyo withdrew in the early 1980s, it was replaced
by Helsinki, Finland.)
</P>
<P>
   It was in the mid-1970s that a well-known New York ballet
teacher named Thalia Mara, who has just turned 87, moved to Jackson
to run the local ballet company. It was her fund raising and
energy, along with the efforts of Joffrey and the dance critic
Walter Terry, that brought the American version of the event to
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The event pumps some $6 million into the city's economy, and it
has remained here because Jacksonians volunteer by the hundreds,
provide accommodation for dancers in their homes and generally
treat the visitors with a hospitality that is downright, well,
Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the practice in other competitions, for instance, dancers
eliminated in the early rounds are invited to stay, at no cost, to
participate in classes and workshops, to attend all performances
and to dance in a choreographed group performance at the closing
gala.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is so nice here,'' the foreign dancers said last
week, again and again, often with noticeable incredulity. And some
of them even liked the early-summer heat, which had stunned the
city torpid. ``It keeps my muscles warm, so that's good,'' said
Anna Ivanova, who is the principal dancer at the Russian Ballet
Theater of Delaware, in Wilmington. She was born in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   For admittedly sports-minded Jacksonians, the event was clearly
an opportunity to mix the culture of the concert hall with the
culture of the stadium. (White Jacksonians, anyway. In a city that
is half black, the homogeneity of the crowd was striking.)
</P>
<P>
   Night after night, they filled the 2,400-seat Thalia Mara Hall
downtown, whooping for their favorites in mid-dance and launching
``bravos'' and ``bravas'' from the mezzanine.
</P>
<P>
   They even seemed to like the contemporary offerings of the
dancers, though most of the professional dance observers found
them, with a few exceptions (like Courtot's performance of his own
choreography of ``The Rite of Spring'') poorly chosen at best,
ponderous and pretentious at worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a serious taste problem with the contemporary stuff,''
said Marks, adding that next time he might well have all the
dancers prepare a piece selected in advance by the jury. For all
the complaints, in the end, almost everyone found the event
gratifying, with Ms. Ivanova giving a particularly measured
assessment of her experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first round was kind of scary, but now I like it,'' she
said after her final performance in round three. ``It's different
from dancing with a company. This is a little harder. You don't get
a second chance to try again another night, with a different
preparation. And you have more responsibility, because with a
company you have their support. It's difficult for everyone to
compete, but if you don't want to compete, you don't come.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused. This was before the results were announced, before
learning she had not won a prize. ``Of course it matters if I win,
but it's more important that I performed well, that I did my
best,'' she said, realizing that at 25, she may have come too late
to the joys of competing. ``This is my first competition, and I'd
like to come back. But now I'm too old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
