<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON GETTING HIGH MARKS FOR CHINA PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China -- A week ago - even a few days ago - White
House officials viewed President Clinton's foray into China with
near palpable fear. The trip began so dismally that President
Clinton's most senior foreign policy adviser stood in a roomful of
reporters in Xian and pleaded for them not to hastily declare it a
failure.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as Air Force One left Beijing for Shanghai on the third
leg of the trip, those same officials were ecstatic, filled with a
sense that Clinton's performance in the televised news conference
and his Beijing University address helped him realize his most
important goals: He spoke directly to the Chinese people,
coherently articulated a strong view on human rights and developed
a closer relationship with Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared ebullient Monday. He was relieved enough to
take the afternoon off in his Chinese government guesthouse in
Beijing to play cards and board games with family and friends
before flying here for a fresh round of speeches on the Chinese
economy. He took a quick limousine ride Monday night to see
Shanghai's city lights before retiring early to his hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Aides spoke in unfiltered awe about Clinton's performance. White
House spokesman Michael McCurry called it ``an important moment of
transformation in China.'' Stanley Roth, the ranking State
Department official on China, said it would have ``profound
reverberations.'' Even Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, in an
unusually impolitic assessment, said she was surprised by the
degree of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of raising issues by both presidents, and their
interchange with each other, I think is something that frankly was
not expected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, administration officials were puzzling Monday over the
long-term impact that the weekend summit would have on the future
relationship between the United States and China, and most said it
would take weeks and even months to find the answer. It is a
relationship, they cautioned, that moves forward not in yards or
even feet, but in inches -- when it moves forward at all.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, they said, the trip would probably not lead to any
sort of post-Tiananmen Square phase in US-Chinese relations, and
they warned that the political climate in Beijing today should not
be compared to Moscow before the fall of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to what happens next, we don't know,'' conceded Susan
Shirk, the deputy assistant secretary of State for East Asian and
Pacific Affairs. ``I don't think it would be wise to say this opens
up a whole new era in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear was why Jiang decided to air the news conference
Saturday on national television, allowing Chinese citizens the
unusual -- if not unprecedented -- chance to see a foreign leader
criticize the government and offer a pointed condemnation of the
1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Most aides believed Jiang felt confident enough with his
domestic standing in China to allow the two broadcasts, and he
wanted to help Clinton address critics at home who had chided the
White House for his China mission and policy of engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech Monday, and the subsequent question and answer
session with hard-line students, was also aired live. But much of
the broadcast was inaudible on China's state-run television
network. White House officials Monday said they believed the
problem was unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the students' questions were particularly pointed. One
student was applauded when he asked if there were problems with
democracy and human rights in the United States. Another asked
Clinton how he would feel if students protested his appearance at
Beijing, as students protested against Jiang when he appeared at
Harvard last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, analysts said Clinton rescued his policy with his
weekend performance, at least for now. They added that critics
would still charge that Clinton failed to meet with dissidents
during his trip, and that his official welcoming ceremony on
Tiananmen Square, where a 21-gun salute eerily echoed off nearby
walls, was a potential public relations disaster. But they added
that his pointed lectures on human rights Saturday and Monday would
help him gain support on Capitol Hill for his approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Clinton and Jiang Zemin took risks, and the gambles paid
off for both of them,'' said David M. Lampton, director of China
studies at Johns Hopkins University and the Nixon Center. ``One
doesn't want to exaggerate the accomplishments, but this was
certainly a step forward, whether your priority was human rights or
economic concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stephen Yates, a China scholar with the conservative
Heritage Foundation: ``His press conference was extraordinary. The
only thing that limited it was that it took place in the middle of
the night back home.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, some administration officials conceded that the
summit failed to yield the substantive gains by which these affairs
are usually measured. Little progress was made,for example, in
helping China gain admission to the World Trade Organization and
the other fair trade issues that are pegged to that -- a main
concern of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship with China deals with a whole host of
issues,'' said Albright, in a session with reporters. ``The trade
agenda was not one that was particularly moved forward during this
summit.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, China made little movement toward signing a pact that
would severely limit its ability to send missiles to its allies.
Chinese leaders also deferred signing its endorsement of an
international human rights accord.
</P>
<P>
   But aides and analysts said this was a summit about
communication, not treaties, and the most important victory came in
the image of Clinton, beamed to a potential audience of some 600
million viewers in a country of 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody had any expectation for blockbuster agreements,'' said
Nicholas Lardy, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institute in
Washington. ``A lot of the issues outstanding are very fundamental.
China is not going to totally transform their human rights
practices. We are down to some very hard issues that are not going
to be resolved fully, and the best one can hope for is a candid
airing of views, and that each side understands the other's
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Said McCurry: ``No one's necessarily naive that we've seen a sea
change in behavior'' on the part of Chinese officials. He rattled
off thorny issues where little progress was made, such as trade and
political dissidents. Then he added, ``But these differences have
to be seen in a new light. There's a much more engaged strategy for
dealing with them on both sides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
