<HEADLINE>
RENO LASHES OUT AGAINST VIOLENCE, URGES HEALTH CARE FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno went on the offensive
Monday against violence that involves children, urging schools to
train teachers to confront conflict and calling for children who
are victims of domestic disputes to receive counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are perpetuating domestic violence from one generation to
another. If we cannot end it in our homes, how can we expect to
keep it off our streets,'' Reno told students from the Presidential
Classroom Scholars, sponsored by the Presidential Classroom civic
and education organization.
</P>
<P>
   Reno told some 300 high school students from 46 states, Canada,
Cuba and Russia that 40 percent of homicides in America result from
violence in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child who watches his father beat his mother comes to
accept violence as a part of life,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she hoped to see programs that offer counseling for
children who witness domestic violence, and a program that would
require every certified teacher to take a course on helping
children resolve conflict ``without knives and guns and fists.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, schools need to teach about the perils of
drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to change the rhetoric of America, which politicizes
drugs,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Raising an issue that haunted President Clinton during his first
two years in office, Reno called for improved health care for
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is wrong with a nation that says to a 70-year-old
person, you can have an operation to extend your life expectancy by
three years, but turn to a five-year-old who has a ... disease and
say, sorry, your parent makes too much money to be eligible for
Medicaid, and she doesn't have enough money for insurance,'' Reno
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration proposed an extensive overhaul of the
national health care system in 1993, but it failed the following
year when the issue foundered in Congress. The administration
sought to build a network of health care providers for the 38
million Americans not covered by private insurance; Medicaid, the
program for poor people; or Medicare, which provides coverage for
the elderly and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In her address to the students, Reno never explained how such
programs would be paid or whether the federal government should
take the lead in paying for violence counseling and anti-drug
programs in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Reno urged the students to focus on the future and be positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we can't make this world a better place,'' she said,
``but if that be the case, unless I fight as hard as I can, it's
going to get a lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Korona, a student from Bishop Ireton High School in
Alexandria, Va., said Reno had good ideas, but she omitted
specifics about methods of changing educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``She mentioned paying teachers well ... where is that money
coming from?'' Korona said after the attorney general's speech.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based Presidential Classroom has sponsored
educational programs for high school students since 1969.
</P>
</TEXT>
