<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-NETHERLANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTCH `PITBULL' SCORES GOAL TO DEFEAT YUGOSLAVIA, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SOC-WORLDCUP-ARGENTINA, SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY,
SOC-WORLDCUP-OWEN, SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S.) 
(JT) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOULOUSE, France _ Edgar Davids, the man Holland knows tenderly
as ``the pitbull'', is back, lifting the Dutch side to a 2-1
victory over Yugoslavia with a magnificent last-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
   In Davids' elation after his 20-yard left-footed shot nestled in
the corner of the net, there was more than the average happiness of
a goal scorer. There was the heady fury of vindication after a long
spell in the cold. And in his joyous post-match embrace with coach
Guus Hiddink, there was reconciliation at last.
</P>
<P>
   In a country that produces talented soccer players with the same
regularity as it grows tulips, Davids stands out as an unusually
gifted midfield player. Mobile, tireless and tremendously
aggressive, he was such a force of nature at Ajax Amsterdam that
Louis Van Gaal, the great coach of that great club, dubbed him
``the pitbull.''
</P>
<P>
   The name stuck. But Davids' aggressive nature was not confined
to the pitch. Born in Surinam, raised on the wrong side of the
tracks in Amsterdam, black in a predominantly white country, he was
easily riled. When Hiddink dropped him from the Dutch during the
European Cup in 1996, Davids accused him of racism. Hiddink told
him to pack his bags and go home.
</P>
<P>
   Davids' international career seemed over. Moving to AC Milan, he
was dropped. Last year, he broke his leg. But then, six months ago,
came redemption. Signed by Juventus, Davids suddenly clicked back
into form, lifting the Italian club to the championship this year.
Hiddink simply could not ignore him.
</P>
<P>
   The coach told David the rules. He told him what he expected
from him. And he put the 25-year-old player back in the heart of
the Dutch midfield, where it is now hard to imagine the team
without him.
</P>
<P>
   Davids was flanked Monday by Clarence Seedorf of Real Madrid and
together they gave the Dutch midfield an authority that held
through much of a see-saw match. But the Yugoslavs are maddening
opponents. They can seem utterly mediocre for long spells, and
entirely defensive, before springing to life. More a collection of
stars than a cohesive team, Yugoslavia could nevertheless have won
this game.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was all Holland, but the team found it hard to
create clear chances. The Yugoslav goalkeeper, Ivica Kralj, saved
well from Seedorf in the 29th minute, after good work by
right-winger Ronald de Boer.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the 38th minute, one of Holland's many world-class
players, center-forward Dennis Bergkamp, struck. Latching onto a
long pass from Frank de Boer, he controlled the ball and shot
right-footed in a single movement. Surprised, Kralj could only get
a hand to it and the ball bounced off him into the net.
</P>
<P>
   But three minutes into the second half, Yugoslavia equalized,
when left-back Slobodan Komljenovic rose at the far post to head in
a free kick. Two minutes later, Yugoslavia had a penalty, when
Dutch center-back Jap Staam fouled Vladimir Jugovic, tugging his
jersey as he prepared to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   There are few better penalty shot-takers than Predrag Mijatovic,
the Yugoslav striker who plays for Real Madrid. But with the
pressure on him, Mijatovic blasted his shot against the underside
of the bar and it bounced out.
</P>
<P>
   With the night humid, and the players tiring, it seemed the
match would go into ovetime. But with seconds remaining, Davids
collected a corner kick on the left edge of the penalty box. He
pushed the ball forward and blasted an unstoppable shot into the
lower left corner of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Holland, which twice reached the final of the World Cup, in 1974
and 1978, with one of the greatest teams never to win soccer's
supreme tournament, was through to the quarterfinal, where it will
meet the winner of Tuesday's England-Argentina game.
</P>
<P>
   After the match, Hiddink said he had thought of taking Davids
off with ten minutes to go because the midfielder had strained a
muscle. ``It was a happy non-decision that I left him on the
pitch,'' he said. Hiddink did not say it, but it was also a happy
decision that he had brought his ``pitbull'' in from the
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
