u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEESON-BROADWAY-ART-N     06-29 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEESON-BROADWAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIAM NEESON'S EMOTIONAL JOURNEY, OUT AND BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Liam Neeson is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Liam Neeson didn't look so scary. The large, almost
lumbering screen presence from films like ``Schindler's List'' and
the current ``Les Miserables'' just seemed tall and slim in person,
with more delicate facial features than those of the lovers and
fighters he has played.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was just tired. Understandably. It was a Friday
afternoon, roughly halfway through a 14-week Broadway run of ``The
Judas Kiss'' (it closes Aug. 2) in which he plays Oscar Wilde in
two conditions: doomed and drained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, you know,'' said Neeson, seated in a back booth at
Cafe des Artistes in Manhattan. ``It's such an emotional journey
for me every day. He's practically a broken man, which two years'
hard labor did to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeson becomes that broken man eight times a week, portraying
Wilde in 1895 (Act I), just as he makes the decision not to flee
England but to stay and face imprisonment for homosexual acts, and
in 1897 (Act II), just after his release. ``You just have to go
there,'' he explained, referring to the psychological demands of
the role. ``Otherwise there's no point in doing it, you know. And
sometimes it pays off, and other times it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   And after you do it, the challenge is in leaving behind the
character's mind set when the curtain goes down, in order to live
as a sane person at least a few hours of the day. Neeson has
developed a system for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm helped by a wonderful dresser called Helen Toth,'' he
said, ``and a glass of the best French red wine I can get.''
</P>
<P>
   What exactly does Ms. Toth do to help? Neeson made the motion of
twisting a corkscrew. ``A lovely ceremony whereby she pops the cork
as I'm just reaching for the towel; we've got it all totally
synchronized,'' he explained. ``One glass of that gets rid of Oscar
Wilde.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Neeson was drinking only Pellegrino, with a
salmon omelet and vast quantities of brown bread. He was dressed in
a casual, very un-Wildean way _ navy jacket, gray shirt, black
jeans, rimless glasses _ and was eager, he said, to get home to
spend time with his two sons, who are at that ``running about''
stage (ages 3 and almost 2.)
</P>
<P>
   The children are the focus of his weekends, when he and his
wife, Natasha Richardson, take them to the country. One recent
exception, however, was the weekend of the Tony Awards (June 7) at
Radio City Music Hall, where he presented an award and Ms.
Richardson was honored as best actress in a musical for her
portrayal as Sally Bowles in ``Cabaret.'' Later that evening, the
two embraced and kissed for the cameras during a brief appearance
at the post-awards supper.
</P>
<P>
   It was a subject of much discussion when Neeson didn't receive a
Tony nomination for ``The Judas Kiss.'' His New York reviews had
been all over the place, describing his work as astonishing,
enthralling and ``the performance of the year'' on one end of the
scale, and as actorly and ``a bit of a snooze'' on the other.
Reviews also sometimes included comments on his having been cast in
the role at all (``boldly against type,'' ``slightly perverse,''
``a calamity''). The play, by David Hare, elicited equally mixed
adjectives (from brilliant, luminous and ``cleverly elliptical'' to
static and ``mind-numbing'').
</P>
<P>
   Neeson laughed off the Tony controversy (``I'm always joking
with Natasha,'' he said. ``I'm not concerned about the Tonys, but
I'm very upset about the Fanys,'' a group of New York
people's-choice awards) and complimented his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York audiences are so responsive, you know, incredibly
interested,'' he said. London theatergoers, he explained, sometimes
``came with a preconceived idea of who Oscar Wilde was, hoping to
see this dandy, this fop who would come out with one-liners, and
that's not what David Hare has written.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neeson does see Wilde as a colorful, fascinating
character. In fact, he professes a certain national possessiveness
about the man and ``his love of words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The English tend to claim him as their own, but he wasn't,''
said Neeson. ``He was very, very Irish, brought up in a very strong
tradition of Irish storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mother was this huge, outrageous Irish nationalist and was
a bit of a cult hero,'' continued Neeson, who is from Ballymena,
Northern Ireland. ``She always had an open door to visiting artists
and lecturers. So he grew up in this extraordinary educated world:
of books, yes, but of people coming from all walks of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilde's father, he pointed out, was a noted eye and ear surgeon
who died in Oscar's youth. In what Neeson called ``one of these
strange twists of fate,'' Wilde died of an ear infection, one that
his father probably could have cured.
</P>
<P>
   Before portraying Wilde, Neeson paid a visit to the Off Broadway
production of ``Gross Indecency: The Three Trials of Oscar Wilde.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I wanted to cut down on my research,'' he said. ``I
thought, `Well, if I see this play, and it's taken from the
transcripts, it's going to save me really a lot of boring books.' I
loved it. I thought it was a wonderful production. It was sort of
like a fascinating documentary, but I was moved by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeson said he believed there had been some negative reaction to
his having taken on the role. ``I sensed that there was a kind of a
gay thing, of a heterosexual playing Oscar Wilde,'' he said.
``There were some actors, some very well-known actors, who came
backstage who didn't even deign to say, `Congratulations, well
done,' which is the basic you should always say, even if you hate
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeson finds the concern puzzling. ``We're not talking about a
different species,'' he said, looking amazed that anyone could
consider playing a person of different sexual orientation that
great a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   When Neeson wants to get away from opinions like that, and from
pretty much everybody, his passion is fly-fishing and has been for
the last four years or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very absorbed in that,'' he said. ``There's incredible
paraphernalia. Each rod is totally different and has a different
action, action being the sway of the rod and how it throws the line
out. There's an art form in casting. Basically what you're trying
to do is imitate a fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not terribly successful at catching fish,'' he added,
``but that's not why I do it really.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled a day last year during the filming of ``Star Wars:
Part 1.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to this little bed-and-breakfast hotel very near
Stonehenge,'' he said. ``And it had a lovely river running beside
it, and I took a rod out. It was the most gorgeous, idyllic day.''
He described having seen a kingfisher flying, moorhens and
butterflies, like a Walt Disney movie come to life, he said. ``And
I got a couple of great bites on that line, which was thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   He is familiar with the book ``Fly Fishing Through the Midlife
Crisis,'' he said, but contended that he wasn't fazed by his recent
birthday, his 46th, which fell on Tony Awards night. And, he said,
he had made it through his 40th birthday without incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I freaked out at 30,'' he recalled. ``I was actually doing
what I always dreamed I'd be doing. I was on location doing a film,
in the Dolomites in the middle of Italy. I wasn't working that day,
so I stayed in my room and went through this miserable depression.
This was my little exorcism.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was romantically unattached at the time (which might
have contributed to his gloomy outlook), he said: ``No, I wasn't.
But she wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeson was linked with a number of famous women (including Helen
Mirren, with whom he had a long relationship) before he and Ms.
Richardson fell in love as co-stars of the Roundabout Theater's
1993 production of ``Anna Christie.'' They were married in July
1994.
</P>
<P>
   She is leaving ``Cabaret'' at the same time Neeson completes his
run in ``Judas Kiss.'' Then it's back to London to finish the
``Star Wars'' film. Nobody seems to have a problem with his playing
a Jedi knight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
