<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES MORE INTENSE SCIENTIFIC UFO STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine scientists from major universities and research
institutions in the US and Europe have carefully reviewed a variety
of UFO reports and concluded that no, there's no proof the reports
have anything to do with extraterrestrial intelligence, but yes,
the subject deserves far more attention from scientists than it has
had.
</P>
<P>
   The first such review by a scientific panel in 28 years, the
report, published Monday, was critical of scientists for their lack
of curiosity about a subject that has attracted such widespread
public interest, and of scientific journals for their reluctance to
publish research papers on the topic. But the report had high
praise for the French government, which for 21 years has had a
panel devoted to collecting rigorous scientific evidence related to
new sightings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there are unexplained observations, there is the
possibility that scientists will learn something new by studying
those observations,'' the panel wrote in its report, which was
published in the Journal of Scientific Exploration.
</P>
<P>
   The journal specializes in publishing reports by legitimate
scientists on topics that are considered too controversial for many
other scientific journals.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the panel pointed out, many phenomena that are now
recognized and understood, including the fall of meteorites and the
existence of ball lightning, were known from anecdotal eyewitness
reports but were rejected by the scientific community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be valuable to carefully evaluate UFO reports to
extract information about unusual phenomena currently unknown to
science,'' the group wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which met last fall for four days to hear various UFO
investigators present their ``best case'' evidence, focused on
reports where there was some kind of physical evidence:
photographs, radar recordings, damaged soil or plants, or physical
symptoms suffered by witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The report's conclusions were in contrast to the last major
independent review of UFO cases, conducted by Edward Condon of the
University of Colorado in 1970, which suggested there was unlikely
to be anything of value to be learned by further study.
</P>
<P>
   This panel was led by Peter Sturrock, professor emeritus of
physics at Stanford University, and included scientists from the
University of Arizona, the University of Virginia, the German
Aerospace Center and several other institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists said they were ``not convinced that any of the
evidence involved currently unknown physical processes or pointed
to the involvment of an extraterrestrial intelligence. A few cases
may have their origins in secret military activities.''
</P>
<P>
   But many cases, while intriguing, simply did not have enough
hard evidence to be able to provide a definitive explanation, they
said. They hope to spur greater efforts at scientific data
collection, and collaboration between scientists and UFO
investigators in future incidents, in hopes of being able to
pinpoint the nature of the phenomena involved.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, they cited reports of serious physical symptoms,
including some that resembled radiation sickness, and said the
medical community should be alert to the possibility of health
risks from some UFO events.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more interesting cases the panel examined, where there
were both physical evidence and trained, reliable witnesses, were
these incidents:
</P>
<P>
   _ Three hundred witnesses, most of them officers and crew aboard
two French submarines and personnel of a weather station, all
observed a 1965 incident near the Caribbean island of Martinique in
which a large luminous object arrived silently and circled the
craft twice before vanishing ``like an extinguished light bulb.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The three-member flight crew of a commercial jet flying near
Paris on January 28, 1994, saw a luminous disk they estimated to be
3,000 feet across, with fuzzy edges. The object was observed by
radar stations on the ground for 50 seconds, during which it slowed
from a speed of 110 knots to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   _ Six employees of an Air Traffic Control Center in Switzerland
saw a large, silvery disk on June 5, 1996, rotating and wobbling.
Three separate radar systems also recorded the object.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dozens of people saw unexplained lights over a valley in
Norway called Hessdalen in the early 1980s, and less frequently
right up to the present. Some of these also produced magnetic
disturbances that were recorded by instruments.
</P>
<P>
   In cases such as that in Norway of repeated sightings from the
same location, the panel noted, ``it is difficult to understand why
no rational explanation has been discovered, and it would seem that
a small investment in equipment and time should produce useful
results.'' They recommended the development of small, automated
packages that could be set up in such places to provide continuous
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The panel concluded that ``the UFO problem is not a simple one,
and it is unlikely that there is any simple universal answer.'' But
it added that ``...there is the possibility that scientists will
learn something new by studying these observations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
