<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI PRESIDENT URGES NETANYAHU TO CALL EARLY ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Dealing a stunning and unusual slap to the
government over its indecisive peace politics, President Ezer
Weizman on Monday publicly urged Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
to call early elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peace process is limping, and we had a few pitfalls in
recent months,'' Weizman told surprised reporters after a routine
meeting with the state comptroller. ``If I were in his place, I
would move for early elections. The sooner we go to early
elections, the sooner we'll know what the public thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's largely ceremonial office does not give him the power
to dissolve the government or call elections, and Netanyahu
immediately responded that he had no intention of holding a new
vote until his four-year term expires in 2000. The initial reaction
among politicians and commentators was that Netanyahu would weather
this jolt, as he has so many others.
</P>
<P>
   But the unconventional action placed the outspoken president _ a
73-year-old former air force chief and defense minister who has
great popularity _ squarely in opposition to the prime minister.
The call gave new credibility and strength to the idea that if
Netanyahu is unable to make progress on the long-stalled peace with
his two-year-old coalition, he should take it to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman is notorious for stepping out of his ceremonial role to
speak his mind. Yet officials and reporters close to him said
Monday's comments were not spontaneous, but a deliberate decision
to make public his dismay and his sense that he was deceived by the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The frustration is shared by many on both left and right _ as
well as in Washington, among the Palestinians and in Europe. Week
after week a breakthrough has appeared imminent, only to dissolve
for reasons that are never made fully public.
</P>
<P>
   The growing sense among some politicians and diplomats is that
Netanyahu is simply too unsure of the response of his Cabinet to
commit himself to ceding more West Bank land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The National Religious Party has repeatedly said it will quit
the coalition, and so bring it down, if he does so. At the other
end of the political spectrum, the Third Way party has threatened
to leave if no agreement is reached soon.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has repeatedly insisted that progress is being made,
and has blamed the Palestinians for any and all delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am working day and night for one thing _ to bring a good
agreement, an agreement that will be based on peace and security
for Israel,'' he said Monday at a joint news conference with
visiting Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu pointedly avoided referring to Weizman by name or by
office, evidently looking to avoid a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of pressure, nothing, no one, will sway me from
this,'' Netanyahu said. ``For those who are interested in the
facts, I have one thing to say: Peace is very, very close. It's
very close if the Palestinians do their part.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But after more than a year of such statements, there is little
reason to believe that Netanyahu is right this time.
</P>
<P>
   After direct Israeli talks with the Palestinian Authority of
Yasser Arafat collapsed 16 months ago, the United States began
negotiating directly with Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Several times in the last seven months, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright set deadlines and indirectly threatened to go
public against Netanyahu, but he has countered by mobilizing
support in the U.S. Congress and among American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The basic outline of the package deal under discussion is for
Israel to withdraw from 13 percent of the West Bank, apparently in
increments of 10 percent and 3 percent, with the pullbacks linked
to a timetable for Arafat to fulfill his obligations under the Oslo
accords, including a roundup of illegal arms, the detention of
terror suspects and another revision of the Palestinian Charter.
</P>
<P>
   According to Israeli officials, the latest problem is that
Arafat is balking at those demands, though he has said in the past
that he accepts the American proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Netanyahu offered the idea of holding a national
referendum on a withdrawal. The issue was debated furiously, then
abruptly dropped several days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Next, over the last weekend, during meetings with Aznar,
Netanyahu proposed convening a new Madrid conference, the talks
that began the current peace efforts in 1991. This idea was
immediately denounced by Arab leaders, and soon abandoned by the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's comment was evidently prompted by his feeling that he
had been deceived by Netanyahu. Last month, when indications were
strong that a deal really was imminent, Weizman tried to drum up
support for Netanyahu in the Labor opposition and from Jordan's
King Hussein and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak _ only to find
that there was no deal. Weizman said Monday that he had not talked
to Netanyahu for four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When talk arose about a referendum, Weizman supported the idea,
until that was dropped. ``If he isn't going to call a referendum, I
think the next solution should be elections,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
