<SLUG> BC-BKN-BIRD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRD AMONG SIX NAMED TO HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To today's beeper/cell phone/entourage set, Larry Bird may be
more identifiable as either the stoic coach of the Indiana Pacers
or the guy whose name is attached to a key provision of the
Collective Bargaining Agreement that makes a lot of players
excessively wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   He is both of those, of course, but his election to the
Basketball Hall of Fame Monday was due to his nonpareil playing
career for the Boston Celtics. It resulted in three world
championships, three MVP awards, 12 All-Star selections, a Rookie
of the Year award, and a spot on the 1992 Olympic team. His
election to the Hall was as much of a lock as a Bird free throw
down the stretch in a close game.
</P>
<P>
   Bird was one of six individuals chosen Monday. Former Harlem
Globetrotter and Magician Marques Haynes was named as was Alex
Hannum, coach of the 1957-1958 St. Louis Hawks and 1966-1967
Philadelphia 76ers, the only teams to ever defeat Bill Russell in a
playoff series. Hannum also coached the Oakland Oaks to an ABA
title and told the AP he was in ``utter and complete shock'' after
hearing of his selection. ``I think it's a tremendous honor and
it's something you can only dream about,'' Hannum added.
</P>
<P>
   Arnie Risen, who spent the last three years of his 13-year
career with the Celtics (1955-58), Jody Conradt, the coach of the
University of Texas women's team, and ex-Yugoslavian coach
Aleksandar Nikolic. In addition, Lenny Wilkens joined John Wooden
as the only two-time inductees last week. Wilkens was honored as a
coach, having already been selected as a player.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first year Bird was eligible, having been out of
basketball for the minimum five years. While the Hall does not
release vote tallies, its public relations director, Robin Deutsch,
said he'd be ``surprised'' if the 24 voters did not all include
Bird on their ballots. In recent elections, both Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and Julius Erving were both first-time inductees as
well as unanimous selections.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 24 voting members are 10 members of the media (a 5/5
split among professional and college writers), and 14 who really
know something about basketball. The voters are rotated, sometimes
on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Bird released a statement Monday which sounded a lot like it
came from the file cabinet folder marked `Grateful Acceptance
Speech.'' He thanked his family, his friends, his fans, his coaches
at high school, college, and the pro level, and basically everyone
but Marc Iavaroni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, it's a great honor,'' the statement said. He
said all those who helped him along the way should share in the
award, ``because, like the other awards I received, this is as much
a team accomplishment as an individual accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird presumably will have other basketball bonbons to disperse
this afternoon at a news conference at Market Square Arena in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Bird has been out of the NBA since 1992, when a bad back forced
him to retire at age 35. He spent five restless seasons working for
the Celtics as a consultant, but never felt he was being heard. He
eagerly returned to the NBA last year as the coach, future general
manager, and part-owner of the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   His name also is held in vain by most owners because of the
so-called ``Larry Bird Exception,'' which is at the heart of the
impending lockout. When the NBA instituted the cap in 1983, it
wanted a device that enabled teams to exceed the cap to re-sign its
own players. Bird's contract was up and it was deemed by everyone
to be a good thing for the Celtics to keep him in Boston. Thus was
born the Larry Bird Exception.
</P>
<P>
   As is always the case, there were some deserving nominees who
did not get selected. Among those were former coach and player
Larry Costello, Adrian Dantley, Sidney Moncrief, Chet Walker, Artis
Gilmore, and Gus Johnson. Coaches who fell short included
Georgetown's John Thompson and Bulls assistant Tex Winter,
architect of the triple-post offense as well as a longtime college
coach. Former Wayland Baptist coach Harley Redin (women's
category), shoe company executive Grady Lewis (veterans), and
Ubiratan Pereira Maciel of Brazil (international) also were not
selected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
