<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-HOLLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLAND EDGES YUGOSLAVIA, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOULOUSE, France _ Two years ago, Edgar Davids hailed a taxi in
the England countryside and left the Holland national team amid
accusations of racism.
</P>
<P>
   He did not return until last month, after peace talks with coach
Guus Hiddink, and after an impressive season with Juventus in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Davids' comeback had been quiet _ he was boycotting the media _
before last night, when he launched the winning goal in the last
minute of Holland's 2-1 win over Yugoslavia. The Dutch will meet
either Argentina or England in the quarterfinals in Marseille
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the goal, Davids, nicknamed ``Pit Bull,'' had stifled
Yugoslavia's creative midfielders, except for the period at the
start of the second half, when the Yugoslavs nearly took the lead.
In fact, had Pedrag Mijatovic not missed a penalty, the Yugoslavs
might have won. But after Mijatovic's shot bounced away, the Dutch
regained the momentum and deserved the victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch team has been divided into two camps _ young players
such as Davids and Clarence Seedorf, of Surinamese descent, and the
veterans whose families have been in the Low Countries for ages.
They had blended well, especially in the '80s with Ruud Gullitt and
Frank Rijkaard, but the new generation has had clashes which
culminated in a disastrous 4-1 loss to England in the 1996 European
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions were already high for this match, as Yugoslavia was
making its first appearance in an international tournament since UN
sanctions had banned it for 33 months, and they were inflamed by a
proposal from a deputy in Holland's Socialist party that the Dutch
players turn their backs while the Yugoslavian national anthem was
played to protest Belgrade's policies in Kosovo. Miljan Miljanic,
president of the Yugoslav football federation, made a formal
protest. The Dutch Minister of Sport, Erica Terpstra, boycotted the
match, and the ruling Labor party urged Dutch fans to turn their
backs.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, conflicts started in a section of Yugoslavs, and
riot police entered.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the attention was focused on the field, as two of
the most explosive, highly-skilled teams battled. The Dutch,
though, were the more proactive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the feeling we couldn't lose,'' striker Dennis Bergkamp
said. ``We were the stronger team. But I hope we can do better than
we did before if we play England.''
</P>
<P>
   They controlled midfield and pressured Yugoslavia into mistakes.
The Yugoslavs simply backed off into a defensive shell and launched
some speculative long balls toward Mijatovic in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Bergkamp finally converted the first goal, the indirect result
of the constant pressure. After several close calls following
intricate buildups, Bergkamp converted a simple, long clearance, by
holding off defender Zoran Mirkovic, controlling the ball with the
outside of his right foot, and drilling a low shot which glanced
off the hands of 6-foot-6-inch Ivica Kralj in the 38th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bergkamp's goal was mostly the result of the goalkeeper's
error, Holland had several near-misses. By the 16th minute, the
Yugoslavs appeared on the verge of panic as Slobodan Komljenovic
headed away for a corner _ after the Dutch had backed off and given
up on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Holland's became more confident, and increased its attacks.
Apparently, they had become overconfident, traditionally a bad
habit for the Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it drives me crazy because this team can play so
well,'' Hiddink said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia changed its tactics at the start of the second half.
Dragan Stojkovic livened up the midfield, despite the close pursuit
of Davids.
</P>
<P>
   A Stojkovic advance led to a throw-in, and Mijatovic was tripped
by Michael Reiziger on the left edge of hte penalty area. Stojkovic
curled the free kick to the far post, where Slobodan Komljenovic
headed to tie in the third minute of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Yugoslavia penetrated again, and Vladimir
Jugovic's shirt was pulled by Jaap Stam. Jugovic's strength
rendered the pull inocuous, but referee Jose Garcia-Aranda called a
penalty. Goalkeeper Edwin Van Der Sar dove to his right as
Mijatovic smashed the penalty into the underside of the crossbar.
The Dutch countered quickly, and Bergkamp and Mihailjovic collided
in the right corner.
</P>
<P>
   Dejan (Il Genio _ The Genius) Savicevic replaced Stojkovic early
in the half, but could not share his ideas as the Dutch played
keepaway.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia retreated to play for overtime, and the Dutch
capitalized. Marc Overmars lined up two shots in the 45th minute,
both resulting in corner kicks. Then, Davids was left unmarked just
outside the penalty arc on the left, and he sent a low shot into
the right corner.
</P>
<P>
   Had the match gone into overtime, Davids would have been
benched, according to Hiddink.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest I was planning some things in extra time,''
Hiddink said. ``Edgar Davids had lost his muscle in the last six or
seven minutes, and I was preparing a subsitution. It was a happy
non-decision to let him go to the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
