<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-GENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENE MAY NOT EXTEND LIFE OF NON-HISPANIC WHITES WITH AIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DON FINLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A gene mutation previously found to extend the
life and health of HIV-infected people appears only to work in
African Americans and perhaps Hispanics, but not non-Hispanic
whites, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the study _ which examined 1,090 HIV-infected Air
Force personnel _ found that another gene mutation earlier believed
to delay disease progression actually caused patients to sicken and
die faster.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, appearing Tuesday in the journal Nature Medicine,
suggest that developing treatments around the relatively new
science of genetic resistance to AIDS may be more difficult than
many had hoped, said Dr. Sunil Ahuja, assistant professor of
medicine at the University of Texas Health Science Center in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though non-Hispanic whites and African Americans have the
same gene mutation, it's only protective in one group,'' Ahuja
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the findings suggest that other, yet-undiscovered
gene mutations are also at work in one group but not the other.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, it was known that the virus that causes AIDS
latches onto a receptor called CD4 to enter and infect immune
cells.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, researchers confirmed the virus also locks onto a
second site, or co-receptor. That co-receptor varies depending on
the stage of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the infection, the virus latches onto a receptor called
CCR5. A mutation in both copies of the CCR5 gene _ found in 1
percent of non-Hispanic whites, but rare in other groups _ makes
people resistant to becoming infected in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   As the disease runs its course, it binds to other receptors.
Mutations in those receptors have been linked in earlier studies to
longer, disease-free lives among people infected with the human
immunodeficiency virus.
</P>
<P>
   One is the CCR2 receptor. The San Antonio researchers found the
mutated CCR2 twice as often in African Americans, Hispanics and
American Indians than in non-Hispanic whites.
</P>
<P>
   But even in those non-Hispanic whites who have CCR2, there was
no delay in disease progression. A significant delay was found in
African Americans, and Ahuja said some effect was seen in
Hispanics, but there was too little to make a statistical
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   In January, researchers with the National Cancer Institute
announced a protective effect linked to people with mutations in
the gene SDF1. That gene was associated with a seven- to 10-year
delay in the onset of AIDS from infection.
</P>
<P>
   But the San Antonio study found those with the SDF1 mutation in
the study group actually died three years sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why there's this discrepancy in the reports from our group and
the previous group aren't clear,'' Ahuja said. ``We repeated this
analysis several times and we feel confident in our data.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Ahuja, the researchers include his wife, Dr.
Seema Ahuja, also an assistant professor of medicine at the health
science center; and Air Force Lt. Col. M.J. Dolan with the
infectious diseases service at Wilford Hall Medical Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
