<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2649 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-650&AMP;ADD-     06-29 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS LARGELY OVER, CLINTON IN SHANGHAI TO SEE CHINA'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-DAY, CHINA-BOEING, CHINA-TV-COVERAGE,
CHINA-PEONY) 
(th) 
 By SETH FAISON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ With the heavily political, issue-laden leg of
his China trip now behind him, President Clinton and his entourage
came to the nation's largest and most cosmopolitan city Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   To put his finger on the vibrant pulse of modern China, his
aides said, Clinton will spend two days and three nights here
talking to regular people.
</P>
<P>
   Driving down the winding avenues of neon that advertise a
distinctly commercial sensibility in this city, Clinton's motorcade
went directly from the airport to Shanghai's thriving waterfront,
the visual climax of any tour of this megacity of 14 million.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of a dark and brooding river, a long row of stately,
colonial bank buildings were vividly lighted as if in celebration
of Shanghai's swanky past. Across the river, in a newly-developing
area known as Pudong, a crowd of shiny new skyscrapers seemed to
play to this city's boast of being the future of China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to meet entrepreneurs, community leaders
and home-owners in Shanghai, to try to accentuate the dynamic,
fast-growing economic side of China. And to address ordinary
Chinese people, as he did by speaking on live television in
Beijing, Clinton will also host a live radio call-in show that his
Chinese hosts have promised not to censor.
</P>
<P>
   As he stepped out of his limousine at the Portman Ritz-Carlton
Hotel, located on a busy street in downtown Shanghai that was lined
with crowds of people craning their necks for a glimpse of him,
Clinton waved to acknowledge the roar of cheering that greeted him.
</P>
<P>
   Then he went inside for the evening, passing up the chance to
peek at Shanghai's boisterous nightlife at any of the bars and
supper clubs that self-consciously fashion themselves after the
styles set in the 1920s and '30s, when Shanghai was the most
cosmopolitan city in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   On Clinton's daytime itinerary in Shanghai are three landmarks
that, in an indication of how this city is coming alive, have
opened in just the past two years: a technologically advanced stock
exchange, a world-class museum with inventive display techniques
and the nation's most modern and accessible public library.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides have portrayed his itinerary as one that traces
China's history. In Xian, the first stop, one sees relics of
ancient China. In Beijing the largest icons of Communist China are
on view. And Shanghai is clearly the most forward-looking city in
the country. Of course, that neat description does not account for
Guilin, the pleasure spot, or Hong Kong, which both lie ahead on
the presidential travel plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, Shanghai is the future of China,'' said Mike
McCurry, the White House spokesman. ``The changes that are taking
place in China are reflected in the very dynamic growth,
economically, and the changes taking place in South China.''
</P>
<P>
   To Shanghai residents, actually, the rate of economic growth is
palpably slowing. The real estate boom of the mid-1990s has now
created a bubble of supply that seems poised to burst, but has not
done so yet.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison with much of the rest of Asia, however, Shanghai
looks healthy. Round-the-clock construction continues on
skyscrapers throughout the city, if on fewer than before. The
unemployment rate is rising steadily, as state-owned factories
downsize, yet average family income is still climbing marginally.
</P>
<P>
   There are relatively few formal events planned during Clinton's
stay here, and officials doing advance planning work say that
offers the Clinton family the flexibility for shopping and walks,
or quiet time away from their 1,000-member entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's itinerary includes only three events, leaving almost
the entire afternoon free for shopping or something unscripted.
Wednesday's plans are almost as relaxed. On Monday, after speaking
at Beijing University, Clinton and his family took it easy. They
stayed in, at Diaoyutai Guest House, playing cards and board games,
McCurry said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton also has a modest handful of visits
planned in Shanghai. To combine her long-standing interest in
health care and the welfare of children, Mrs. Clinton is scheduled
to visit the Shanghai Children's Medical Center, a new hospital
that was built by Project Hope, a U.S.-based foundation, and
Shanghai's Second Medical University.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first hospital in China devoted to treating children,
and it was created by nongovernment entities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not in any five-year plan,'' said William Walsh,
president and chief executive of Project Hope, which has been
active in China since 1983, training and advising medical personnel
about public health. ``It reflects the kind of volunteerism that is
starting to grow in China today.''
</P>
<P>
   And it also has helped, Walsh said, that two of Shanghai's
former leaders who welcomed Project Hope to the city were later
promoted to the country's top positions: President Jiang Zemin and
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is also planning to visit a women's education and
training center, and the Shanghai No. 3 Girl's School. On
Wednesday, she will visit the Ohel Rachel Synagogue, a place of
worship for Jews who lived in Shanghai before the Communist-led
army arrived in 1949, inducing most foreigners to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is expected to join her husband at a roundtable
discussion on Tuesday morning at the Shanghai Library, titled
``Shaping China for the 21st Century,'' which is expected to
highlight the way an information-driven age will affect all
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the world we live in, this global information age, constant
improvement and change is necessary to economic opportunity and to
national strength,'' Clinton said Monday at Beijing University.
``Therefore, the freest possible flow of information, ideas and
opinions, and a greater respect for divergent political and
religious convictions will actually breed strength and stability
going forward.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
