<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-COX     06-29 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expensive anti-AIDS drugs for pregnant women now being made
available to developing countries
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geneva _ Thousands of unborn babies in the Third World soon will
have a better chance at dodging AIDS, because of a new program that
will make expensive anti-HIV drugs available to HIV-positive
pregnant women in some developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) and the
World Health Organization announced Monday at the 12th World AIDS
Conference that it plans to launch pilot drug therapy programs in
several developing countries where mother-to-child HIV transmission
is a serious problem. One in three babies born to women with HIV
contract the virus from their mothers during pregnancy or birth, or
through breast-feeding, according to the WHO.
</P>
<P>
   Through this initiative, about 30,000 HIV-infected women in
about 30 different locations will receive treatment with AZT
(zidovudine), for about a month during late pregnancy and delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``To save the life of a child costs $50,'' said Bernard
Kouchner, France's health minister. ``The effort, of course, must
be implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the per-person cost of AZT treatment for this program
nor the program's total cost has been determined, said Peter Young,
vice-president of Glaxo Wellcome, which manufactures AZT.
</P>
<P>
   But $50 per person is the estimate used by the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta. Monday the CDC presented
the results of a study in Bangkok, Thailand,that found AZT cut the
risk of mother-to-child infection by half, when given to
HIV-positive women in the last weeks of pregnancy. ``The challenge
now is how to translate these findings into practice,'' said Dr.
Nathan Shaffer of the CDC.
</P>
<P>
   The standard course of treatment for HIV-positive pregnant women
in industrialized countries is longer and more complex than the
regimen used in the Bangkok study. It is also more effective,
reducing mother-to-child transmission of HIV by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The chances are even better for babies born to mothers who not
only receive this higher standard of anti-viral therapy but also
opt to deliver via elective Caesarian section performed before
labor begins. Research has shown that infants can be infected with
HIV during labor contractions as well as when they pass through the
birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Denison, an HIV-positive American who gave birth to
twins two years ago, credits this treatment with keeping her
children free of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absolutely a result of the access to care I have
in the United States,'' said Denison.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, nearly 600,000 infants were not as fortunate as
Denison's twins. The longer drug regimen costs $600-$800. In
countries such as Tanzania, where the annual health care
expenditure per person is $4, this form of treatment is out of
reach.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to receiving AZT therapy, the women who are selected
for the UNAIDS/WHO program will receive prenatal counseling and
treatment, better care during labor and delivery and support in the
form of infant formula if they opt not to breast-feed their
infants.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participating nations: Botswana, Burkina, Cambodia,
Faso, Honduras, Rwanda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   The UNAIDS/WHO program highlights the enormous disparity between
treatment and prevention efforts in developing and developed
countries, AIDS experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Many have asked what will happen to the HIV-positive mothers who
participate in this and other similar programs once their drug
therapy ends.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say they do not expect the mothers to develop
resistance to AZT after ending a short course. But they shy away
from directly answering questions about the possible fate of these
women. As they know, drastic improvements in economy, health care
and the basic quality of life must occur for the face of AIDS to
change in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pregnancy lasts nine months,'' Denison said. ``But motherhood
lasts the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
