<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-NEWDRUGS-COX     06-29 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-NEWDRUGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conference discusses making AIDS drugs easier to take
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geneva _ It may take a decade or more to determine if the most
potent AIDS drugs now available can eradicate the virus from the
body, one of the world's top AIDS researchers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the 12th World AIDS Conference, Dr. David Ho said
understanding how HIV hides from drugs within the body in
``reservoirs,'' such as brain cells, is a major hurdle to curing
the disease. ``This is the major documented obstacle to virus
eradication,'' said Ho, of the Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center
in New York. ``The task ahead is to try to understand this
reservoir.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho suggested that it may not be necessary to completely
eliminate the virus, but to reduce it to a point at which a
patient's immune system could keep the virus in check, without
assistance from drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Until a more effective treatment is discovered, patients must
continue taking their current drug regimens, typically involving
dozens of pills a day, said Ho. A challenge for researchers is to
make it easier for patients to adhere to these drug regimens, or
HIV will swiftly develop resistance to them.
</P>
<P>
   Ho and other scientists spoke about advances and challenges in
anti-HIV drug therapy at a conference symposium Monday. While the
researchers emphasized how much progress has been made in the last
few years, they also stressed that no new drug advances shine as
brightly as did protease inhibitors, the most effective class of
drugs available, when they were first introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single magic bullet . . . doesn't exist,'' said Dr. Joep
Lange of the University of Amsterdam. ``It's biologically
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   But making drugs at least easier to take is important for
patients to follow dose regimens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Therapy must go toward once-a-day (drugs),'' said Dr. Julio
Montaner of the University of British Columbia. ``It's not whether
we like it or not, that's the direction we have to go in if we want
patients to benefit over a long-term basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Efavirenz, also known as Sustiva, is a once-daily
investigational drug that has shown excellent results in
large-scale tests, DuPont Pharmaceuticals announced Monday. But the
best results are from combinations of efavirenz with other
anti-viral drugs, such as AZT and Crixivan, which must be taken two
or three times per day.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont applied this month for efavirenz to be approved by the U.
S. Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Murphy of Northwestern University, who spoke at
Monday's symposium about numerous combinations of drugs, said the
dozen or so drugs now in the testing pipeline will offer patients
and doctors many more options for treatment. But for those for whom
the existing options don't work, time is running short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things do look encouraging, but these things are pretty far
away,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
