<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEZELL-COLUMN30-COX     06-29 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEZELL-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:Finding closed-end funds
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the stock market gets this high and unruly, a lot of people
want to shop for bargains.
</P>
<P>
   That sometimes brings to mind closed-end mutual funds,
particularly the ones that trade at a discount to the true value of
the stocks they hold.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, closed-end funds can be a bargain. But they aren't for
everyone and all occasions. If they were, more people would be
actively selling them, and more people would be buying them.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the field is dormant. As the chart shows, total
investment in closed-end funds between 1991 and 1998 has grown
every year but one, registering a decline in 1994. Still, the funds
have only a small fraction of the $5.05 trillion invested in all
mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   A closed-end fund is a special critter. Like the regular,
open-end funds, the closed-end ones are portfolios of stocks or
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But there are differences. You buy shares in a regular fund
directly from the fund, at a price that is always pegged to the net
asset value of the stocks it owns. By contrast, a closed-end fund
issues a set number of shares, which then trade on the exchanges,
like stocks.
</P>
<P>
   That means in periods of high demand, closed-end funds may sell
for a premium _ more than the value of the stocks they own. But
more often than not, they trade at a discount, meaning you get the
underlying shares for less than their face value. That's what
brings out the bargain hunters.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, you get more securities for your buck. That's
particularly attractive for bond investors. If you buy at a lower
price, yield automatically goes up.
</P>
<P>
   Another attraction is the possibility that your fund could move
back into favor. ``If it performs well, you could make even more
money, because you get the extra kick from the narrowing
discount,'' pointed out Gregg Wolper, the closed-end fund editor
for Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If the market tanks, on the other hand, you get a certain kind
of stability by owning a closed-end fund. Its price will presumably
go down, of course. But a closed-end manager doesn't have to do
what open-end managers are sometimes compelled to do _ sell stocks
in a panic if a lot of shareholders want out.
</P>
<P>
   The main attraction, however, is the discount. A warning comes
with it: Today's 8 percent discount, compelling as it may be, could
go to 10 percent or 12 percent tomorrow, if the fund goes out of
favor. As with any other investment, there may be a very good
reason why the fund was out of favor to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Some very bright people warn against closed-end funds if you
want a general-purpose stock fund. ``Among diversified equity
funds, prefer open-end over closed-end,'' writes Sheldon Jacobs in
his ``Guide to Successful No-Load Fund Investing.''
</P>
<P>
   His reasoning is this: ``As a generality, we believe the
open-end funds have more aggressive management, since they can be
penalized for poor performance. The managers of closed-end funds
know that their funds can't be redeemed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolper agrees, especially among large-cap stocks. ``Closed-end
funds are beneficial for areas that are more volatile or less
liquid,'' he said. They could include funds that invest only in one
country's stocks, or only in narrow industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that general warning, a diversified U.S. stock fund was
the first he mentioned on a short list of closed-end funds worth a
look:
</P>
<P>
   -- Central Securities, which invests in midsize U.S. companies,
``has a tremendous record over a long period,'' Wolper said. At the
end of May, Morningstar gave it five stars, the top risk-vs.-return
rating. It had a five-year annualized return of 23.7 percent, based
on net asset value, and a discount of 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Europe Fund, which Wolper said matches its peers over
time. It had five stars, a five-year return of 26.8 percent and a
discount of 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Templeton Emerging Markets Fund, one of several run by
the widely admired Mark Mobius. Its numbers were not as high,
however: Four stars, a five-year return of 11.5 percent and a
premium _ rather than a discount _ of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:hezell(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
