<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2656 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-LAYOFFS-BOS &LR;      06-29 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-LAYOFFS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ BEGINS TRIMDOWN IN WAKE OF DIGITAL ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp., which completed its $9.5 billion
acquisition of Digital earlier this month, Monday said it will lay
off 5,000 manufacturing workers worldwide and close eight plants
and distribution centers.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first part of a previously announced massive
restructuring that will eventually claim 17,000 jobs, including
15,000 Digital workers.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring will leave Compaq with a total of 67,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
   But the shake up is about much more than Compaq's effort to
absorb Digital. It's also part of a year-old plan to completely
overhaul the way Compaq makes computers _ an effort to keep up with
one of the industry's most successful companies, Round Rock,
Texas-based Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The single biggest job cut &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; 1,000 workers &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; comes at
Compaq's manufacturing facility in Houston. Compaq will cease
production of printed circuit boards for computers &UR;  &LR; and some
consumer products. The company will also reorganize its Houston
warehousing and distribution operations.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the overhaul of US manufacturing operations, Compaq
began laying off 600 administrative workers at the Marlborough,
Mass., facility that formerly served as headquarters for Digital's
manufacturing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Another 3,400 jobs will disappear as Compaq closes facilities
worldwide, or merges them with Digital facilities. Digital's
operations in Taiwan will be phased out. Digital &UR;  &LR; operations in
Australia, Scotland, Brazil and Singapore will be closed, with
operations moved to Compaq sites in those countries. In Japan,
Compaq will consolidate operations at a former Digital center which
assembles computers for delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Shannon, publisher of a newsletter on Digital, notes that
Massachusetts got off lightly in this round of layoffs beecause of
the focus on manufacturing. ``There's precious little of it in this
state,'' he said. ``It could be an awful lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Digital's workers in Massachusetts are concentrated in sales,
customer service and hardware and software engineering, as well as
corporate administration.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many more cuts still to come. Greg Petsch,
Compaq's senior vice president for manufacturing, said that further
layoffs were being planned in staffing for specific product lines,
the company's sales organization, and in corporate administration.
</P>
<P>
   Along with helping Compaq to absorb its Digital acquisition, the
changes are part of the company's year-old plan to adopt more
efficient methods of getting computers to customers. Compaq was the
darling of the computer industry last year, but has stumbled in
recent months. The company manufactured computers faster than its
distributors could sell them. That led to slower orders for new
machines and forced drastic price cuts that have weakened profit
margins throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of 1998, Compaq reported profits of $16
million, down from $414 million a year earlier. And the company
predicts that it will just break even this quarter. Meanwhile,
cross-state rival Dell Computer has seen its earnings grow
steadily. In its first quarter ended in April, Dell earned $305
million, up 54 percent from the year before. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dell sells virtually all its computers by telephone or over the
Internet, assembling them only after an order is received. This
dramatically reduces the company's costs, leading to stronger
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Now Compaq is trying to embrace a similar model. The company has
launched an Internet site to sell directly to consumers. It's
cutting back on production &UR;  &LR; of some electronic components, opting
to buy them instead. At the same time, it's trying to keep good
relations with its traditional distribution channels that bring in
most of Compaq's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very delicate balance,'' said Roger Kay, an analyst
with International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass. ``They have to
maintain their channel balance because they can't withstand the
hiccup in revenue ... At the same time, they have to get their cost
model in line with Dell's.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq stock closed up 3/8 at 29 5/16 on the New York Stock
Exchange. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1924EDT &QL; 
