<HEADER>
A2661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STINKYFLOWER-COX     06-29 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STINKYFLOWER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A really clever headline needs to go here
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--With suffocating heat, strangulating traffic and
choking smog, it only makes sense as the next big summer
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-foot-tall flower that smells like rotting human flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Starting today Atlantans can drop in _ and maybe drop over _ at
the Atlanta Botanical Garden and catch one of the rarest events in
horticulture: the blooming of the exotic Amorphophallus titanum , a
plant with the double distinction of being both the world's largest
and the world's foulest-smelling flower.
</P>
<P>
   Just how bad does it stink?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's a cross between fresh cow manure and a dead
animal,'' says Ron Gagliardo, the Garden's curator of tropical
plants, who's spent the last few weeks nurturing the bud to
maturity with a diet of chicken manure.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday workers moved the flower in its 250-pound pot from the
greenhouse to display in the lobby of the Dorothy Chapman Fuqua
Conservatory. Gagliardo said he expects it to bloom by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The flower only stinks when it's in blossom. Botanists theorize
that's because in the wild of its native Sumatra the flowers are
pollinated by stench-loving carrion beetles.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Titan arum'' will stay in bloom for two or three days.
Then its phallus-like center stalk, or ``spadix,'' will topple, and
the yearslong regeneration process will begin again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it survives, it's hard to say when it will bloom again,''
said Gagliardo. ``We've had this plant since 1994, and this is the
first time it's bloomed. They're highly unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no special plans to ventilate the conservatory to
offset the flower's stench. Visitors can expect to have a pretty
rotten time.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can take the advice of Madeleine Groves, the Garden's
coordinator of conservation programs, who worked at a London garden
when its Titan bloomed _ and people started gagging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just looked around the Army surplus stalls for a few gas
masks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
