<HEADER>
A2667 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-HISPANICS-     06-29 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-HISPANICS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS TRY TO RESTORE THEIR TRADITION OF DEVELOPING HISPANIC
PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JORGE L. ORTIZ  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Peter Magowan became a Giants fan during the
days when such Latin luminaries as Orlando Cepeda, Juan Marichal,
Jose Pagan and the Alou brothers populated the team's roster in the
late '50s and early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   When the ownership group he heads acquired the club in December
1992, Magowan vowed to reawaken the long-dormant tradition of
homegrown Latin American players on the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't just driven by a pang of nostalgia. Magowan was aware
of the growing presence of Hispanics in the major leagues _ they
make up nearly 20 percent of the rosters today _ and he wanted the
Giants to get their share of the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks after he took over, the Giants named Luis Rosa
as their coordinator of Latin American operations. The move seemed
like a coup at the time. Rosa had discovered such talented players
as Juan Gonzalez, Roberto and Sandy Alomar, Carlos Baerga, Ivan
Rodriguez, Ozzie Guillen and Wilson Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   Yet more than five years after Rosa's hiring, the Giants still
haven't developed a front-line Hispanic player, a streak of
futility that dates all the way back to Elias Sosa in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   And now they find themselves with a legal mess on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa resigned from the Giants _ he says the team forced him out
_ on June 13, 1997, the day before eight former players went on
Dominican television and said Rosa had demanded sexual favors as a
condition of employment. They also accused Rosa of embezzling part
of their signing bonuses and salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Seven more players later joined the complaint, but since then
three of the original players have retracted their story and said
it was all part of a scheme to extort money from Rosa and the
Giants. Rosa traveled to the Dominican voluntarily to face the
charges and spent four months in a San Pedro de Macoris jail before
being let out in March on $40,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal and civil charges against Rosa are pending. The 12
remaining players have also sued the Giants in civil court in the
Dominican Republic, as well as both Rosa and the Giants in U.S.
District Court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Team vice president and legal counsel Jack Bair said: ``If the
allegations are true _ and there's considerable dispute over
whether they're true, obviously, with three individuals retracting
_ but if the allegations are proven to be true, then Rosa will have
violated our policy and have acted clearly out of bounds with
respect to conduct of an employee. Certainly the Giants would never
sanction such behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the hint of such behavior could have severely damaged the
team's Latin-American efforts, which haven't borne much fruit
anyway. But the quick parting of the ways between the Giants and
Rosa appears to have prevented further harm.
</P>
<P>
   Several scouting directors from competing teams indicated the
Giants' reputation in the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico,
Rosa's base of operations, has not been hurt appreciably.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first they got hit hard with all the TV commotion and all
the newspaper articles,'' said Raymond Abreu, the Oakland A's
director of operations in the Dominican. ``But since it has died
down and everything's back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a couple of kids who have signed with the Giants
without any problems. I mean, if the problem was Luis Rosa _ which
I'm not saying he was _ but he's gone anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he would have stayed, it would have been way different,
after all these testimonies and after all these court dates here in
the Dominican. If he would have stayed, it would have impacted the
Giants.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Julian Perez, the Braves' scouting supervisor in the
Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico: ``I haven't heard any prospect
say, `Damn, I hope it's not San Francisco.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants retrenched and hired John Dipuglia from the St. Louis
Cardinals organization to take over Rosa's old duties, and they
named Ozzie Virgil manager of their summer-league team in San Pedro
de Macoris, site of their baseball academy.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Ragazzo, the ~Giants' coordinator of international
operations, said the team now has five instructors and two trainers
at the academy, plus a head scout who scours the island along with
five other scouts under him.
</P>
<P>
   Ragazzo added that prospects receive English training and even
go on trips to the States so they get exposed to the different
coaching, language, culture, weather, food, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot,'' Ragazzo said. ``Other than maybe the Dodgers or
possibly the Blue Jays of five years ago, we do as much as
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a number of years that wasn't the case. At one time the
Giants had only one scout in Puerto Rico and none in Venezuela.
Although the team has since taken steps to increase its presence,
it still lags behind other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Money has been _ and continues to be _ a major factor. For a
while the Giants had a baseball academy in the Venezuelan city of
Barquisimeto, but they have since closed it and are pondering
whether it will be cost-effective to open another one elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime Houston has become the dominant team in the
Venezuelan market. The Astros are one of several clubs spending
heavily on Latin prospects, along with the Braves, Diamondbacks,
White Sox, Dodgers, Rangers, Yankees and Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the economic wherewithal to compete with those
major-market clubs on a per-player basis,'' Ragazzo acknowledged.
``However, if we're a little more selective in how we spend our
money, then yes, I think we can be as competitive, if not more in
certain situations.''
</P>
<P>
   That selective approach has worked for the tight-fisted Pirates,
who are benefiting from their investment and contacts in Mexico.
Pitchers Francisco Cordova, Jose Silva, Esteban Loaiza and Ricardo
Rincon all come from south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of the steadily increasing number of Latin
Americans in the big leagues. According to Major League Baseball,
Latinos represented 17.5 percent of the players on Opening-Day
rosters, including players on the disabled list. That figure grows
to nearly 20 percent when U.S.-born players of Hispanic parents _
including such stars as Alex Rodriguez, Edgar Martinez and Alex
Fernandez _ are included.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants don't seem close to cashing in on the bonanza. In
early '93, a couple of months after joining the organization, Rosa
said he had signed two infielders ``who are going to have people in
San Francisco dancing in the streets in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Unless they were involved in Carnaval festivities, that
prediction hasn't come true. The Giants' media guide shows only two
players signed by Rosa were included on the preseason 40-man
roster: Triple-A outfielder Armando Rios, 26, and third baseman
Pedro Felix, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best prospects Rosa left behind _ Felix, catcher
Yorvit Torrealba and infielder Raul Marval _ were having so-so
years at Double-A Shreveport as the halfway point of the season
approached. Torrealba has been demoted to Single-A San Jose, where
his hitting has picked up. All three are still a ways from getting
to the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The only player Rosa signed for the Giants who has reached the
majors is Dominican shortstop Deivi Cruz. The Tigers stole him away
in the Rule V draft. Two other promising prospects, pitchers Fausto
Macey and Lorenzo Barcelo, were packaged in the trades that brought
in J.T. Snow, Alvarez and Roberto Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, 52, blames the lack of production on the Giants' inability
to develop the players he delivered them and on poor management at
the minor-league level. He also accused the club of stifling the
progress of Latin players and of turning its back on him at a time
of need.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Giants forced me out with some irregular tactics to get to
the point of resigning, to get to the point where mentally I wasn't
in position to make the best decision,'' said Rosa, who denies the
charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided to throw me overboard and let me swim on my own.
They didn't realize my situation affected them too. They totally
abandoned me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Bair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team's obligation is to look into the matter in a
fair-minded way,'' he said. ``I'm sure he would like us to say,
`Regardless of what the claims are, we stand behind you.' We didn't
do that. We took the responsible approach to the matter and I'm
sure he was disappointed that we wanted to look into the matter
prior to making any assessments.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Brian Sabean said: ``He was hired before I got
here, and if you look at his track record with other organizations,
you'll understand the reason he was hired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
