<HEADER>
A2670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-MENS-FASHION-AR     06-29 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-MENS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASCULINITY MEETS ROMANCE IN MILAN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (JT)  
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Romance has come to menswear here, an apt
development in the age of Viagra. Designers like Jil Sander,
Donatella Versace, Dolce &AMP; Gabbana and Issey Miyake have been
careful, though, as they infuse their spring clothes with soft,
fanciful touches, to preserve the swagger of masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   Stefano Gabbana, half of the Dolce &AMP; Gabbana design team, said
that he and Domenico Dolce discarded two looks from the collection
because they were too feminine. ``This is a strong romantic,''
Gabbana said. ``It's always masculine. I don't like for a man to be
feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   Flesh rippling through sheer sweaters, embroidery twisting down
trousers and sequins dancing across jackets have the ominous ring
of clothes for girls. But if there was one bar that designers here
were able to hurl successfully, it was the challenge of making
softer clothes manly.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that one can see Ms. Sander's influence on runways
other than her own seems to spur her forward. Using the word
``cheerful'' to describe her clothes, as she did in the program
notes for the collection that she showed Monday, is using the word
creatively. Ms. Sander has never strayed from her austere fashion
vision. What was new here was the effortlessness of sportswear and
even suits.
</P>
<P>
   The relaxation of menswear begins with the basic teaming of a
shirt and a pair of trousers, offered as a man might wear a suit.
Ms. Sander showed elastic-waist trousers in cotton and white
zip-front shirts in Egyptian cotton. A navy tubular sweater was
paired with below-the-knee dark teal shorts cut like parachute
pants.
</P>
<P>
   Many jackets were unlined and rolled easily over the shoulder
with a modified raglan cut. They evoked the same zephyrlike feeling
as the white or khaki trousers that the models wore rolled up
slightly at the ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Are men ready to free themselves from the restriction of suits?
To some degree, yes. Certainly, not all the time. Ms. Sander's
proposal of the suit without its traditional constriction is
timely, and it is not as difficult as Ms. Versace's use of sequins
and embroidery as decoration for men's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting a slimmer suit jacket than her line Gianni Versace has
shown in the recent past, Ms. Versace sensualized sweaters with
bands of matte sequins across the torso. A tiny feathered white
stripe ran down one leg of tuxedo pants, and embroidered dragons in
baby blue fire-breathed their way across the chest of gray suit
jackets. She paired white-leather fitted vests with pants
embellished with tiny appliques of feathery fabric, a traditionally
feminine textile.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Versace adapted ideas on display on runways of emerging
designers, like the cutaway jacket, and she added many of her own:
a leather shirt whipcorded with thin silver chain; smoothly
finished burned-out shirts, and a black lace lining for a sheer
black cutaway jacket. She replaced last season's rhinestone
embellishments with more sophisticated clear matte sequins on
sleeves and jackets. Her attempt to add some excitement with small
harness straps was less successful. They dangled from otherwise
appealing jackets and a white lab coat like misplaced participles.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Versace and Dolce &AMP; Gabbana have always served the
adventurous dresser, these collections have elements for a meeker
customer, as well. It was more than coincidence that both design
houses turned to the macho spatter prints of Jackson Pollock for
stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   Dolce and Gabbana enlivened black sweaters and white shirts with
colorful injections of paint, and that was mostly where the color
ended. The wonderfully limited palette _ black, gray and white,
mostly _ was fashioned into uniformlike jackets that had little
extraneous seaming.
</P>
<P>
   For suits, there were Mao-style jackets of cotton topping
relaxed pants. Designs were cast in a gray melange cotton that
Steffano said is used for the uniform for Milan's sanitation
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Pants paired with skinny sweaters bore seams at the points of
movement: the knee, the ankle. The inspiration, Gabbana said, was
the anatomical work of Leonardo. A bit of fashion chauvinism,
perhaps. In fact, the soft, blousy pants, like much of the
collection, seemed Asian at root.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Asian influence has seeped back into menswear.
Barneys New York, for instance, is making Japanese designers like
Yohji Yamamoto, Miyake and Rei Kawakubo centerpieces of its fall
season.
</P>
<P>
   Even Vivienne Westwood had, among her romance-gone-awry pieces,
some artfully draped shorts and trousers and long nylon coats
tucked and folded in the Japanese tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sensing his moment again, Miyake moved his show to Milan
from Paris, where he has shown for more than a decade. The idea,
said Nancy Knox, a spokeswoman for the designer, is to be closer to
the source of manufacturing and at the same time to create stronger
ties with the powerful Italian manufacturers, particularly in the
area of knitwear. Miyake's defection is yet another blow to the
French, who see the number of important menswear designers who
choose to show in Paris dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Naoki Takizawa, a member of Miyake's studio, the
Miyake collection was more cohesive and comprehensible than it has
recently been. Clothes were made and then shrunk to size, enabling
Takizawa to achieve an ethereal quality in his designs despite the
preponderance of suits.
</P>
<P>
   The secret lay in the butter-soft color palette and the unlined
jackets of cotton, which resembled refined calico. Here, too,
Chinese worker suits seemed paradoxically liberating. Brawny
straw-colored crocheted sweaters paired with heat-pleated pants cut
like sweat pants achieved a balance of traditional maleness with
pliability.
</P>
<P>
   More restless designers have realized that men may be ready for
some dimension in their clothing, and the traditional tools valued
in women's wear are being brought into play. Women have had little
problem defining themselves with male dress when it suits them, and
while men have not moved as far, designers are to be applauded for
trying to nudge them along.
</P>
<P>
   There is no pat on the back, though, only sure dollars, for
houses like Cerruti 1881, where numbing good taste is paramount.
Steadily evolving into a label known more for a kind of generic
avant-garde than for innovation, Cerruti, with its' khaki-colored
cotton suits and perfectly acceptable sheer sweaters, has put
itself firmly in the safe-and-not-sorry camp in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
