<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM-GUILFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE COMPANY TO ACQUIRE PAN AM ASSETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With three airplanes left to its name, one of the best known
names in aviation, Pan Am, got a new owner Monday _ a Massachusetts
railroad holding company.
</P>
<P>
   Guilford Transportation Industries Inc., which owns the Boston &AMP;
Maine and Maine Central railroads in New England, won approval from
a US bankruptcy court in Miami to buy the assets of the former Pan
Am Corp. _ two airplanes, flight certificates, spare parts, and the
trademarks _ for $24.5 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Guilford, which had earlier put up $1 million to acquire the
airline's third plane, also agreed to make an additional $4 million
infusion of operating capital to keep Pan Am alive.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Pease, executive vice president of Guilford, said in a
telephone interview that the resurrected Pan Am will continue
operating as a charter carrier, flying primarily to Caribbean
tourist destinations, while the new owners decide whether to expand
or add scheduled routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to build a base, and then see what we are going
to do next,'' Pease said in a telephone interview. ``The airline
today as a charter airline is doing well ... but we are not in a
position today to expand into a regular route system.''
</P>
<P>
   Guilford Transportation is privately held and controlled by
Timothy Mellon, 56, a reclusive financier and heir to the Mellon
banking fortune, and David Fink, 62, who as president oversees
railroad operations.
</P>
<P>
   The new corporation, Pan American Airlines Inc., will be legally
based at Guilford's offices in Billerica, Mass., but will maintain
its operational headquarters in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Memories of Pan Am past rang out as bankruptcy Judge A. Jay
Cristol, who holds a private pilot's license, approved the sale
plan Monday. ``We're all praying you'll keep the Pan Am logo
flying,'' the judge said, according to the Associated Press.
``Let's get 'em in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellon also is a licensed pilot and regularly flies a small jet
between his home in Connecticut and airports near Billerica, Pease
said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1927 as Pan American World Airways, the original
airline operated globally for 65 years, including as the first air
service to cross the Pacific Ocean. It filed for bankruptcy in 1991
in the wake of a terrorist bombing aboard one of its planes over
Lockerbie, Scotland, that killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
   New investors bought the Pan American name and familiar
blue-globe trademark in 1996, hoping to rebuild Pan Am as a
discount carrier. They failed, and the airline filed again for
bankruptcy protection last February, listing $94 million in debts.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,300 of Pan Am's 1,450 employees were laid off,
leaving only enough personnel to continue charter service.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank, the largest secured creditor, will get $20.5
million from the settlement approved Monday. Shareholders will get
nothing. Another distribution is expected, however, after $4
million worth of real estate in Miami is sold.
</P>
<P>
   People who still hold tickets on canceled Pan Am flights will be
entitled to $100 each in refunds. They have until Aug. 11 to make
claims. Lawyers said proof-of-claim forms are available from
Poorman-Douglas Corp., Box 4390, Portland, OR 97208-4390. The forms
also can be requested by telephone at 1-503-350-5938.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
