<HEADER>
A2675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      06-29 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, ITALY _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ruffo's Newest Talent &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The spate of large companies hiring young talent has speeded up
the rate at which designers move from newcomer status to
establishment insiders. Ruffo, a second-generation Italian leather
company, has hired Raf Simons and Veronique Branquinho as design
consultants for the Ruffo Research collection.
</P>
<P>
   The menswear, by Simons, is to be introduced here on Thursday.
The women's line, by Ms. Branquinho, will be shown in October,
during the spring 1999 presentations, said Joy Yaffe, the head of
sales and marketing for Ruffo.
</P>
<P>
   Simons and Ms. Branquinho replace Antonio Berardi, the British
designer whose meetings with executives at Versace in the last year
attracted considerable attention in the fashion world. Berardi
seemed about to join the Versace team, but that has not happened.
</P>
<P>
   Even more talked about than Berardi, Simons and Ms. Branquinho
burst onto the international scene from Belgium, their home base.
Linked romantically, they separately represent progressive design
voices in the postminimalist mode, with an emphasis on precise,
inventive cut.
</P>
<P>
   They were designers to watch as they appeared poised for a long
climb. But with the Ruffo contract, they have immediately become
more of a force, wielding influence on two separate collections and
collecting that valuable second paycheck, which can go a long way
toward developing and marketing their own lines. The impact that
progressive designers can have on classic lines is well documented,
but the effect goes both ways, giving the designer immediate
establishment status for a signature collection.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffo has a one-year contract with the designers. Hiring them is
part of the company's plan to raise its profile. A line of
accessories, Ruffo Origami Express, is being introduced for fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to continue to hire the designer of the moment,''
Ms. Yaffe said. ``We chose Raf because he basically represents the
fashion statement of today's man. His work is based on the Bauhaus
school and a strong influence from street culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruffo, a classic line, and Ruffo Research, its more avant-garde
counterpart, are carried in stores like Barneys New York, Bergdorf
Goodman, Louis of Boston, Neiman Marcus and Fred Segal in Los
Angeles. Most jackets in the Ruffo line cost between $1,800 and
$1,900; Ruffo Research between $2,500 and $2,800.
</P>
<P>
   Simons' own collection is scheduled to be presented in Paris on
July 3, during the French spring 1999 men's shows.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dolce &AMP; Gabbana Nights &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Forget the power lunch. Italians in the fashion business
consider the power dinner and power party a serious extension of
the business day, so the only unusual aspect of the Dolce &AMP; Gabbana
party held here on Sunday night was that, instead of being just a
celebration, it signaled the designers' entry into the club
business.
</P>
<P>
   Stefano Gabbana and Domenico Dolce are co-owners of the new
nightclub and restaurant where their post-show party was held.
Called Postgarage, it is at 5 Via Castello in Legnano, about a 30-
to 40-minute drive from the center of Milan.
</P>
<P>
   The club is an opportunity to extend Dolce &AMP; Gabbana without
using the designers' names, Gabbana said. They began searching for
a location two years ago at Dolce's insistence.
</P>
<P>
   But though their names are absent, their design insignia sets
the club's mood, Gabbana said. Huge leopard ottomans, red velvet
cushions, gold-leafed chairs, gold-colored floors and lamp shades
of Venetian glass were designed or chosen by the designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like home, or one big Dolce &AMP; Gabbana showroom,'' Gabbana
said. ``I want to open more shops, but this is like another form of
communication. Everything is Dolce &AMP; Gabbana style but nothing has
the label. I don't want to build the club with the label. It should
feel like home.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff members wear black, designed, of course, by Dolce and
Gabbana. While clubs and restaurants now routinely sell clothing
and other club-brand paraphernalia, there are no plans to offer any
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana merchandise at Postgarage. And there are no plans
to turn away patrons not dressed in the same.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
