<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PLUMPING PILLOWS AND BAKING BAGELS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In preparation for the arrival of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  and traveling
companions, employees of the Portman Ritz-Carlton in Shanghai
``scoured the local area'' for baking ingredients for bagels and
low-fat muffins, says an official release from the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, hotel staff members competed by answering
presidential trivia questions _ ``What is the name of the Clintons'
new dog?'' ``Which musical instrument does President Clinton
play?'' _ to ``help our Chinese employees understand a little more
about the first family,'' said hotel general manager
 &UR; Mark DeCocinis &LR; . Six winners were presented with Washington
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The summer issue of the art journal Coagula, an irreverent and
gossipy handout at New York art parties, takes aim at  &UR; David &LR; 
 &UR; Ross &LR; , the incoming director of SFMOMA, criticizing both his
``reign as Whit czar'' and his ``awkwardly bowling'' at a recent
benefit for New York's Frick Museum. Coagula predicts that Ross
won't get an easy ride in San Francisco, ``a city with six Super
Bowl rings,'' but (a) Personals, a terrible bowler, promises to
leave him alone on the gutterball score; and (b) We're not so
tough; it's five Super Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   _ The  &UR; Duchess of York &LR; , in New York discussing with Simon &AMP;
Schuster a self-help book for women trying to get it together _ but
hasn't Ivana already done that? _ put in a phone call to ``her
friend, best-selling author  &UR; Danielle Steel &LR; ,'' reports the New
York Post.
</P>
<P>
   _ After noticing Friday's Separated at Birth juxtaposition of
 &UR; Clement VI &LR;  and  &UR; Pete Rose &LR; , a hunch made Iris Brooks turn to her
reference books. There it was: Clement VI's pre-papal name was
 &UR; Pierre of Rosier d'Egleton &LR; . Honest.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Chastity Bono &LR;  reveals in her forthcoming book, ``Family
Outing,'' that soon after she realized she was gay, at 13, she
began fantasizing about her mother's friend  &UR; Kate Jackson &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bruce Willis &LR; , who proved to be a man on the verge of
divorce, talks about his marriage in the August issue of Playboy.
``It's the same for everybody,'' says Willis, whose wisdom is
quoted in the New York Daily News. ``... Time goes. Wake up and
realize that you are going to die some day. So live your life. Live
it completely.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; David Grenley &LR;  passes along a new word being tossed about in
Silicon Valley: ``careabouts,'' a noun having nothing to do with
caribou but meaning ``things we care about.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Commemorating the 50th anniversary of the Berlin airlift,
 &UR; Jerry Matters  &LR; faxes from Berlin that Harry, the bartender at his
hotel, said it would have been much worse ``had the Americans been
blockading and the Russians running the airlift.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR;  was in the lobby of a City of Berkeley office
building when he saw an employee arriving for work on his bicycle,
which he rode up to the front door. Without dismounting, reports
Finacom, the fellow pushed the handicapped access button, thereby
opening the automatic door, rode through, &LR;  and ``pedaled off down
the corridors right into his cubicle entrance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHOPPING LIST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sheikh Abdul-Aziz bin Baz &LR; , Saudi Arabia's top cleric, has
told the newspaper Okaz that Viagra is OK for Muslims, ``provided
it does not contain ingredients that may harm health or
intoxicate.'' The drug has been selling on the black market in
Riyadh for $80 a pill.
</P>
<P>
   _ The connection between Nantucket Nectars and gay pride is
probably strictly business, but  &UR; Mark Woodworth &LR;  thinks it wasn't
accidental that the yellow-and-blue plane towing the company's
banner over Sunday's parade was a biplane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Peering at his package of Vidalia Onion Cheese Biscuits _
``quite good'' in his opinion _  &UR; Ted Kreines &LR;  was fascinated by the
educational tidbits printed on the outside of the box: ``Folks down
South have been knotting up Vidalia Onions in pantyhose for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Shopping at Ross in Dublin, Calif., the other day,  &UR; Nancy &LR; 
 &UR; Ubaldi  &LR; saw a sign that read, &LR;  ``Jackets, sport shirts, active
bottoms, &LR; '' and wondered if there are qualifying tests for
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest issue of Architectural Digest, mined by  &UR; William &LR; 
 &UR; Whitney &LR; , reveals that  &UR; Gustav Stickley &LR; , the highly collectible
designer of Craftsman furniture, designed the first electric chair
in New York State.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Films are made taking money into consideration above all. It's
a business. Whereas, in theater it seems everyone knows you're not
really going to make any money, so they actually try and make
something memorable. ... The plays that I've done in the past
couple of years have been so rich that you could basically do them
in a clown suit and the story would still resonate. I would say
most films are unwatchable and most theater is unseen.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eric Stoltz in SOMA magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
