<HEADER>
A2682 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ELHAUGE-BOS     06-29 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ELHAUGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW PROFESSOR IN MICROSOFT CASE SAYS HE WAS MISINTERPRETED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal antitrust lawyers aren't the only ones who have taken
issue with &UR;  &LR; last week's federal appeals court ruling in favor of
Microsoft Corp. The decision has also drawn fire from a Harvard Law
School professor who says the court based its ruling in part on a
misinterpretation of his writings.
</P>
<P>
   Einer Elhauge said that the court last week erred in throwing
out an injunction ordering Microsoft to provide computer makers a
version of its Windows 95 operating system that does not contain
the Microsoft Internet Explorer Web browser. A federal judge in
Washington had issued the injunction at the behest of the U.S.
Justice Department. Federal attorneys argued that Microsoft had
violated a 1995 antitrust consent decree by forcing computer makers
to use Internet Explorer in order to obtain Windows 95. The decree
barred Microsoft from forcing companies to buy one Microsoft
product as a condition for buying another product, a practice known
as ``tying.''
</P>
<P>
   But a three-judge appeals panel ruled 2-1 that Microsoft's
actions did not violate the consent decree, because Internet
Explorer is an integrated part of Windows 95, and not a separate
product.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court based its ruling on a standard treatise in
antitrust law, written in part by Elhauge. In an op-ed piece in
Monday's New York Times, Elhauge said the court had misread his
analysis in deciding whether Microsoft had violated the consent
decree.
</P>
<P>
   Elhauge argues that since any consumer can combine Windows 95
and Internet Explorer as well as Microsoft can, the two should be
treated as separate products. The appeals court said Microsoft, by
combining the two products, created a new integrated product that
was better.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got wrong the interpretation of the legal standard,'' he
said. ``It's a fairly subtle misinterpretation,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   He noted Microsoft faces a similar antitrust complaint in a
larger case filed last month by the US Justice Department and 20
states, thus giving the federal courts a chance to rethink the
issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-29 0827
