<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-NEWBORNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM TO OFFER AZT PROTECTION TO INFANTS IN THIRD WORLD
COUNTRIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Since 1994, pregnant women infected with the AIDS virus
in the United States and Europe could take the antiviral drug AZT
and reduce the risk that their children would be infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a pilot project that would extend similar protection
to 30,000 infants of the Third World was announced by leaders of
the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS, the World Health
Organization and UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   The programs will begin within the next 12 to 18 months for
HIV-positive pregnant women in 30 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to reduce the pain suffered by people like Mercy
Maklehemena, who described during a speech at the 12th World
Conference on AIDS what it is like to experience the loss of an
infant to HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Maklehemena knew she was HIV-positive when she gave birth to her
second child, a daughter, in Soweto, South Africa, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Because her health care providers knew she was infected, she was
virtually abandoned in the hospital after birth. And her baby was
kept from her. When the infant proved infected, she was given AZT,
but no one told Maklehemena about side effects. No one told her
that she could infect her child through breastfeeding.
</P>
<P>
   As the side effects increased, Maklehemena and her doctor
decided to take the child off AZT. Her baby died in the hospital
after developing a bad cough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This experience and the pain have not gone away,'' she said.
``But the painful experience has taught me how important it is for
a woman to demand to know and to get the fullest possible
information for themselves and for their babies.``
</P>
<P>
   The death of Maklehemena's child is an example of the gap
between treatment in the industrialized northern sections of the
world and the largely developing south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perinatal (mother-to-child) HIV infection is now a preventable
disease,'' said Dr. Lynn M. Mofenson, an associate chief for
research in the pediatric, adolescent and maternal AIDS branch of
the National Institute of Child Health and Human Development.
</P>
<P>
   However, the treatment plan used in the United States is
complicated with the mother receiving AZT 16 weeks before birth and
during labor. The infant receives medication for six months
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In the Third World, where such treatment is impractical, a
shorter course of treatment seemed ideal.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study in Thailand showed that giving AZT for three to
four weeks before birth, orally during labor and to the infant for
a month afterward reduced the rate of infection in infants by 50
percent, said its lead researcher Dr. Nathan Schaffer, chief of
epidemiology at the federal Centers for Disease Control. (By
comparison, the longer treatment used in the United States reduced
infection by almost 70 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   It is not a perfect solution, but it is a possible one in a
world where 32 percent of women receive no prenatal care and 40
percent give birth without an attendant, Mofenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Saving children will still cost money _ more than most nations
spend on health care for their citizens annually on a per capita
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``To save a child costs $50,'' said Bernard Kouchner, minister
of health for France. He said his government is prepared to start a
study on the value of preventing mother-to-child transmission in a
developing country by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The nations of Cote d'Ivoire, Tanzania, Thailand and Uganda,
participants in studies of the short-course AZT therapy, will be
part of the new pilots. Other countries participating will be
Botswana, Burkina Faso, Cambodia, Honduras, Rwanda, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Young of Glaxo Wellcome Inc., the drug company that makes
AZT, said his organization already has reduced the cost of the drug
for the pilot study. ``It will cost three-fourths less than it
would in a Western setting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also negotiating to provide initial start-up
supplies for the pilot projects free, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   But Maklehemena warned that women in the poor countries must be
part of the solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What of the new trials and costing of services, including AZT
and other new therapies for women and babies _ what services and
follow-ups will these include?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   That is unclear, although there are indications that the
international agencies setting up the 30 pilot studies would like
to have continuing treatment as part of their work and hope to
persuade two other drug companies to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women will move mountains to have a healthy child,''
Maklehemena said. But women have not been involved in the design of
trials and they must be before they will enroll, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In other studies:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dr. Wafaie Fawzi of the Harvard School of Public Health along
with researchers in Tanzania found that multivitamins reduced
stillbirths, prematurity and low birthweight in children born to
mothers infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new experimental drug called abacavir in combination with
two commonly used anti-AIDS drugs reduced the level of HIV in the
blood to undetectable levels _ even though it was not one of the
potent protease inhibitors. Dr. Neil Graham, director of HIV
programs for Glaxo Wellcome Inc., said the new drug could be useful
for people for whom protease inhibitors do not work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Half of young gay men in a University of California at San
Francisco study said they were engaging in high risk sex
activities, often when they did not know the HIV status of their
partners. Yet, said Dr. Dennis Osmond, an associate professor of
epidemiology and biostatistics, the activities have not yet led to
an increase in infection rates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
