<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHER-TESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITIGATION FOLLOWS TEACHER TESTING IN MANY STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Budgeted as Student-Tests)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Efforts to test the competency of teachers have touched
off courtroom battles from New York to California, and
Massachusetts almost certainly is next, specialists said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Education will meet again Wednesday, when it
is expected to reverse its decision earlier this month to lower the
passing score for would-be teachers.
</P>
<P>
   If it does adopt the tougher standard, it will mean that 59
percent of 1,800 candidate who took the two-day examination in
April flunked _ a number which, some educators contend, would
invite a lawsuit on the grounds that the test was too tough.
</P>
<P>
   But a return to the stricter standard would reflect top
education officials' conclusion that even while it may be easier to
defend the lower standards in court, lawsuits over the teacher
competency tests are nearly inevitable in any case.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what the standard is we're going to have a high
failure rate, either 44 or 59 percent,'' said Deputy Education
Commissioner David Driscoll. ``I think there will be a legal
challenge. Just like in other states we're going to be
challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   California's state certification test wound up in federal court
in 1996 when 50,000 Latinos, blacks and Asian-Americans charged it
was to blame for keeping minority applicants out of the classroom.
A judge upheld the exam.
</P>
<P>
   When more than 1,200 New York City teachers last year failed an
examination that was a prerequisite for state certification, the
teachers' union sued the Board of Education on the grounds that the
teachers had not been properly notified _ legal turf likely to be
replowed in any Massachusetts challenge.
</P>
<P>
   In a conciliatory move, the New York board agreed to seek
temporary licenses for 900 of the teachers who failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts is vulnerable on the issue of notice,'' said
Roger Rice, a Boston attorney who has been involved in several
testing cases. ``They just sprung this on people at the very last
minute. I've never heard of a later test imposed than the one
Massachusetts pulled. These people were just getting measured for
their cap and gown and the state said, `Guess what? You've got to
take a test.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this year, Massachusetts was one of only seven states
that did not test teachers for certification. The tests drew
criticism in April after college students found out the scores
would count toward certification only a week before the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test development process seems to have been extremely
hasty and badly planned with little notice of either the nature of
the testing or the consequences of the testing,'' said Walter Haney
of Boston College's Center for the Study of Testing. ``It seems to
me that regardless of whether they're going to raise or lower the
passing score, there is ample ground for legal challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Some minority groups scored substantially lower than whites on
the test, raising the possibility of a discrimination lawsuit, even
though officials said the test was reviewed to eliminate any
cultural or ethnic biases.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, after deadlocking twice on the matter, the
Massachusetts Board of Education voted to lower the passing score
for teacher candidates, touching off an election-year debate about
how to get the best and the brightest in front of Bay State
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   After first saying he could do nothing about the falling
standard for teacher certification, Acting Governor Paul Cellucci
last Friday called for competency testing for all teachers and
pledged to fire those who flunked those exams.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also said he had asked John Silber, chairman of the
Board of Education, to reconvene this week to take a fourth vote to
raise the passing standard on certification for new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Silber said he had assured Cellucci that the vote to lower the
standards for the test would be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Schaeffer of FairTest, a Cambridge, Mass. monitoring
group that opposes teacher certification tests, said he believes if
the state opts this week for the tougher standards, it will
increase the likelihood of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer said a certification test for new teachers in Alabama
was eliminated in 1985 after critics of the exam sued, claiming
that its standards were arbitrary and based on politics not merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more this plays out as being driven by politics and not by
educational measurement, it makes them more open to litigation,''
Schaeffer said. ``The tests are based on the unproven belief that
you have to know this kind of stuff in order to function well in
the classroom. And that link is unproven.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
