<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-PREGNANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN MOVES TO HELP WOMEN CUT RISK OF HAVING AIDS BABIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Opening a new front in the global fight against AIDS,
UN officials said Monday they would offer 30,000 pregnant women in
developing nations access to a drug regimen recently proven to cut
their risk of transmitting the AIDS virus to their babies.
</P>
<P>
   The $4 million program, which will treat its initial patients
late this year, marks the first concerted effort to extend
sophisticated AIDS treatments to the world's poorest countries,
home to 90 percent of the 30.6 milion people who harbor the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV), which causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The program _ which US Surgeon General David Satcher said the
Clinton administration would support with a level of funding he
would not disclose _ will prevent only a tiny fraction of the
540,000 new cases of newborn HIV infection that arise each year in
the developing nations of Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   However, UN officials and health officials from various nations
see the program as an opening wedge in an effort to bring the
benefits of AIDS research to the nations most grimly beset by the
17-year-old epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the crucial point,'' Bernard Kouchner, France's health
minister, said. ``We must start on the issue of HIV transmission
from mother to child.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, Satcher and Kouchner said, the new program will
go beyond the attempt to chip away at mother-to-child transmission
of HIV. It will also make a start at providing infected mothers
with long-term anti-HIV drug treatments of the type that have
recently transformed AIDS care in rich nations.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher said the Clinton administration is consulting with the
Ivory Coast in West Africa to mount a program that would offer
sophisticated antiviral treatments to infected women there after
delivery. He said he hopes such US-funded programs will be launched
in several nations.
</P>
<P>
   Without sustained treatment for HIV-infected mothers, critics
say, programs aimed merely at preventing newborn HIV infections
could turn into ``orphan factories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to let the mother die after she has
delivered her baby,'' Kouchner said. ``We will take care of women
after delivery, starting with a few hundred in the first three
sites'' of the mother-child prevention program.
</P>
<P>
   The new program to prevent mother-child HIV transmission will be
funded by an International Solidarity Fund spearheaded by France,
with the support of European Union nations, and possibly the US and
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner said he is increasingly optimistic about raising the $4
million in start-up funds even though ``some nations are very
reluctant'' to contribute. ``I talked last week to Donna Shalala,''
the US secretary of health and human services, Kouchner said. ``She
said she was interested but I haven't gotten any dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the pregnancy-focused program will be set up in 30
sites around the world, including Ivory Coast, Tanzania, Thailand,
and Uganda. In those countries, recent studies showed that
mother-child HIV transmission can be cut in half with a short
course of the drug AZT administered in the final three weeks of
pregnancy and during labor.
</P>
<P>
   With price cuts for AZT announced in March by its manufacturer,
Glaxo Wellcome, the short course will cost about $50 to provide the
drug to each expectant mother. By contrast, the longer-duration
treatment that has become standard in North America and Europe runs
$600 to $800.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost of treatment in developing nations will be about
$120 per case, including the cost of HIV testing to identify which
pregnant women carry the virus, counseling women about the
implications of testing and treatment, and access to infant formula
to avoid the risk of infants' infection through breast feeding.
</P>
<P>
   It might cost $180 million to treat the approximately 1.5
million HIV-infected pregnant women in developing nations each
year. Such a program, if it could reach every infected woman, might
prevent HIV infection in 270,000 infants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
