<SLUG> BC-FED-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED EXPECTED TO HOLD BACK ON A RATE INCREASE FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The most militant inflation fighters at the Federal
Reserve Board will have plenty to fret about when the central bank
meets Tuesday and Wednesday to consider whether to raise interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew at a sizzling 5.4 percent annual pace in the
first quarter. The unemployment rate, at 4.3 percent, is the lowest
since 1970. Consumer price inflation, while still low, is
increasing, and the Clinton administration's decision to help prop
up the Japanese yen could ameliorate the inflation-fighting effects
of the strong dollar, which has helped keep import prices down.
</P>
<P>
   The strength in the stock market has left consumers feeling
flush and confident. On Monday the Commerce Department reported new
home sales in May hit a record.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, such signals of strong growth and rising
inflation pressures might normally be enough to lead the Federal
Reserve to nudge rates up. But they will almost certainly be
overshadowed during the Fed meeting by a patient, pragmatic
approach championed by Alan Greenspan, the central bank's chairman.
After the meeting adjourns, the Fed is expected to announce it is
holding interest rates steady, at least until its next meeting on
Aug. 18, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the pragmatists' argument is the belief that
growth is already slowing towards a noninflationary rate because of
the financial crisis in Asia and perhaps the strike that has nearly
shut down General Motors. Moreover, raising rates now could further
destabilize Asia and emerging economies from Russia to Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the American economy has exhibited a surprising
ability for several years to grow at robust rates without setting
off inflationary wage and price spirals. Greenspan himself even put
aside the dour mien that has long been his trademark and a few
weeks ago proclaimed the economy to be just about the best he had
ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   David Orr, the chief economist at First Union Corp.'s capital
markets group, said the economy was shifting from a Goldilocks
stage _ neither too hot nor too cold _ into a Dr. Jekyll and Mr.
Hyde stage in which it exhibited contradictory characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's crisis has had a substantial impact on farmers and
manufacturers that export chemicals, electrical equipment, lumber
and textiles, he said, helping to slow the overall economy's growth
to 2 percent or less this spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, he said, consumer spending remains strong,
incomes continue to grow and business investment in computers and
other equipment remains heavy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Alan Greenspan raising rates unless the
manufacturing sector shows some rebound, which I don't see
happening this year,'' Orr said. ``On the other hand, the
fundamentals of private sector domestic demand are just so solid
that demand is really exceeding supply in areas like housing, an
awful lot of service and retail areas and commercial construction.
So inflation is going up in those areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, Orr said, is to keep the Fed trapped between
conflicting forces, with monetary policy on hold until inflation
becomes a clear threat or the economy becomes so sluggish that it
needs to be reinvigorated by a rate cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bet is that the strength of underlying U.S. domestic
demand prevails, and that by spring of next year, or something of
that order, they do raise rates,'' Orr said. ``But it's a close
bet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The best clues to how the Fed is handling the situation could
come not in the expected terse announcement Wednesday that the
Federal Open Market Committee has left rates unchanged, but in the
minutes, to be released on Thursday, of the committee's May 19
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   At the previous meeting, on March 31, the Fed left rates
unchanged but formally signaled that it expected the next move on
interest rates to be upward _ in essence an early warning to the
markets that if the expected slowdown in growth did not happen it
would probably tighten policy.
</P>
<P>
   The May 19 minutes will reveal whether that policy bias was left
in place. It will provide a synopsis of the debate between the
pragmatists on the committee and those members who see inflation as
more of an immediate threat.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among the inflation hawks is Jerry Jordan, the
president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, who alone among
the committee's 12 members voted to raise rates at the March 31
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's vote was based in part on his concern about the rapid
growth in the money supply, a development that has a number of
other Fed officials worried. Money supply growth has fallen out of
favor in the last decade as a proxy for inflation pressures, but
some economists are now arguing that the link has been at least
partly re-established.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said they would be closely watching Thursday's
employment report, which will provide the clearest look yet at
whether growth began slowing in earnest in June.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists expect a slight uptick in the unemployment rate,
to 4.4 percent, and a slowdown in job creation, to a little more
than 200,000 in June from 296,000 in May. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
