<HEADLINE>
TAINTED GALVESTON BAY OYSTERS SICKEN 107 PEOPLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif., Colo., Fla., La., N.M.) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ The number of people reported to be ill from
bacteria in raw Galveston Bay oysters had more than doubled Monday,
and state health officials said more cases were being reported.
</P>
<P>
   The total was up to 107 cases, 18 of them involving people who
had eaten the raw Galveston Bay oysters in Florida restaurants,
said Texas Department of Health spokesman Doug McBride. The other
89 cases involved people who had eaten them in Texas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials had recorded 51 cases Friday after issuing
bulletins about the oysters, tainted by a bacterium called Vibrio
parahaemolyticus. Wholesalers were tracking down shipments _ to
restaurants around Texas and in California, Colorado, Florida,
Louisiana and New Mexico _ and warning them not to serve the
shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak of illness is the second-largest of its kind in the
nation's history. Last year, 208 people in the Pacific Northwest
fell ill from eating oysters tainted with the bacterium and one
person died, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The bacterium's development is attributed to warm, unusually
salty water around oyster beds in Galveston Bay. Officials said
they hope the infusion of fresh water from last weekend's rains
will help prevent more oysters from becoming contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen who lease state-controlled oyster beds in the bay have
stopped harvesting oysters there at least until next week while
tests are conducted to see if the oysters are contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   Oysters from seven of the 43 beds where oysters have been
harvested recently are known to have caused illnesses since early
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms from consuming foods tainted with Vibrio
parahaemolyticus include diarrhea, abdominal cramps, nausea, fever,
vomiting and headache, health officials said. The bacterium rarely
causes death, they said, but it can be dangerous to people who have
liver problems or weakened immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   The state health department still was receiving calls Monday
from health officials who have treated people who appeared to be
suffering from the illness and people who have heard about the
outbreak and believe they were victims, McBride said.
</P>
<P>
   People who have suffered symptoms within a day or two of eating
raw oysters are asked to report the illness to state officials by
calling 1-888-883-9997.
</P>
<P>
   People who develop such symptoms after eating oysters should see
a physician, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
