<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2712 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-SAMPSON-BOS &LR;      06-29 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-SAMPSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPSON RESIGNS; QUEIROS SEEN AS POSSIBLE SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS   AND FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Sampson, who directed the US men's soccer team to a
contentious last-place finish in the World Cup, jumped before he
was pushed Monday morning, resigning as head coach after three
years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at the federation thank Steve for his tremendous service to
our national team program and to soccer in the USA,'' US Soccer
Federation president Alan Rothenberg said in a statement after
Sampson told him he was leaving during a breakfast meeting in
Paris. ``His tireless work has helped advance our sport and on
balance it was an era of growth. I compliment him on his many
achievements with our team.'' Neither Sampson, who was returning to
the United States with his wife and son, nor Rothenberg were
available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who was an assistant under Bora Milutinovic on the 1994
team, was the fifth coach (along with Saudi Arabia's Carlos Alberto
Parreira, South Korea's Cha Bum Kun, Tunisia's Henri Kasperczak,
and Japan's Takeshi Okada) to resign or be fired during the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   One strong candidate as a possible successor to Sampson is
Carlos Queiros, who was hired by the US Soccer Federation to
evaluate the system. At the time, many believed he was being
positioned to take over for Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   But Queiros, formerly national team coach of Portugal, said
Monday from Florida that he has not been offered the position.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would be interested, Queiros said: ``To be
interested in something is one thing. For that thing to be a
possiblility is another.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the 41-year-old Sampson had the best winning percentage
of any coach in US soccer history, directed the team to its third
straight Cup appearance and produced an historic victory over world
champion Brazil in this year's Gold Cup, his tenure had always been
marked by uncertainty. He was given the job after Milutinovic was
let go in 1995 because the squad had played well under him as
interim coach but also because more experienced foreign coaches
were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson was on thin ice after the US was tied by Jamaica at home
in a critical qualifying match last fall and wasn't reaffirmed
until the squad had already qualified. Though a number of veteran
players had pushed to have him kept on for the Cup, their attitude
changed after Sampson dumped captain John Harkes from the squad in
April and began plugging promising but inexperienced players into
the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   After the Americans were eliminated from the tournament after
losses to Germany and Iran, several veterans, including Tab Ramos,
Eric Wynalda, and Alexi Lalas who were seeing reduced or no playing
time made no secret of their unhappiness with Sampson. After the
final loss to Yugoslavia, when Ramos never got off the bench, he
vowed he would never play for Sampson again.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who had said repeatedly that he would start whomever he
felt were the best 11 players, had refrained from answering the
veterans' criticism in public. But he lashed back after Ramos and
others blamed him for the squad's poor showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's a sense of frustration that international
careers are coming to an end and they needed a scapegoat,'' Sampson
had said last week. ``It's unfair it was pointed at me, the
individual who stuck with them for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   New England Revolution coach Thomas Rongen, who served as an
assistant on the US team, feels that Sampson is being made a
scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a very unfortunate chain of events which lead up to
this,'' Rongen said. ``Something I don't think Steve deserves.
Considering his track record, he has been the most successful coach
in the national team's history. He put a team on the field that we
can all be proud of, something that we can build from. For us to
think that we had a great chance to go to the second round was
unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at who's still playing. Not one team from the CONCACAF
region, not one from the Oceanic region, not one African team. It's
all European and Latin American teams still playing. To say that
Steve failed because of those three losses was grossly unfair. We
didn't take a step back, it was just a lost opportunity to showcase
our talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Rothenberg had said he wouldn't decide on Sampson's fate
for another month and Sampson had said he had no intention of
quitting (``I worked too hard for this. I'm not going to let one or
two individuals control my own life.''), he resigned just three
days after the players left for home.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg said in his statement that a ``thorough process for
hiring a national team coach'' would be launched but gave no
timetable for naming a successor. ``We have a clean blackboard, so
to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Rongen, Sampson's successor should have long- term
vision that coincides with Project 2010, whose aim is to have the
United States positioned to host and win the World Cup in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has got to be someone that the players respect,'' Rongen
said. ``Someone that understands the American athlete, and the
American environment. That coach needs to be someone along the
footsteps of Steve, who was always concerned about the youth
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Queiros has long had connections with the US. He coached
Portugal in the US Cup in 1992, then went to Sporting Clube de
Portugal, and in 1996 to the New York/New Jersey MetroStars. He
also coached Portugal to World championships in the Under-17 and
Under-20 categories. He has been evaluating the USSF and the MLS in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This article was reported in Montpellier, France, by John
Powers and in Toulouse, France, by Frank Dell'Apa; correspondent
Omar Kelly contributed from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
