<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2715 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNKNOWN-COX     06-29 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNKNOWN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tests reveal identity of remains from Unknowns tomb
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Pat Blassie of Marietta, Ga., a long and painful year of
uncertainty about her brother lost more than 26 years ago in
Vietnam appears to be over.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon would not officially confirm Monday that remains
exhumed May 14 from the Tomb of the Unknowns in Arlington National
Cemetery and subjected to rigorous DNA testing are those of Air
Force 1st Lt. Michael Blassie.
</P>
<P>
   But a telephone call to the family of another serviceman
officials thought might have been in the tomb indicated the remains
are Blassie's.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official ``just said they had got the results back
and that the body was Blassie's,'' The Associated Press quoted
Althea Strobridge, mother of Army helicopter pilot Capt. Rodney
Strobridge, as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said an announcement on the identification is
expected today.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Pat Blassie, a communications specialist, nor members of
her family in St. Louis, could be reached for comment Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But Blassie said last month that family members, all of whom
pushed for exhumation and DNA testing, had agreed if the remains
proved to be those of Michael they wanted him buried in a national
cemetery in St. Louis rather than in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring him home. We believe he deserves that,''
Blassie said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Blassies believed for more than a year that the remains
buried in the tomb since 1985 were Michael's. Government documents
and other information they obtained last year through the efforts
of a North Carolina veteran activist helped convince them.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Blassie's A-37 attack jet was shot down in May 1972 in a
battle about 80 miles north of Saigon. He was originally listed as
missing in action, but his status was later changed to killed in
action, body not recoverable.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to family members, however, a search team recovered
physical evidence and partial remains from near the crash site that
were labeled ``BTB (Believed to Be) Blassie.'' The physical
evidence included his identification card and a piece of his flight
suit.
</P>
<P>
   But for reasons that are still unclear to the Blassies, the
``BTB Blassie'' designation was removed in 1980 and the remains
were among four from the Vietnam era later considered for interment
at the Tomb of the Unknowns.
</P>
<P>
   Several family members, including Michael's mother, Jean,
provided DNA samples for the test comparison.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how long it might be before the Pentagon replaces
Blassie's remains with those of an unidentified serviceman from the
Vietnam War. Although several sets of remains are still
unidentified in a laboratory in Hawaii, advances in DNA testing
might render the term ``unknown'' obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
