<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALABAMA-VOTE30-COX     06-29 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-VOTE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Religious conservatives may decide Alabama runoff for Governor
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY _ In today's Republican runoff, incumbent Gov. Fob
James will learn whether bearing the cross of religious freedom is
enough to defeat hard-charging challenger Winton Blount.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Fob James is elected, it shows that religious conservatives
are alive and well and will remain dominant even though the party
has become more diverse in general,'' said William Stewart, chair
of the political science department at the University of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Elected as a Republican in 1994, James has crusaded to return
prayer to Alabama schools, which endeared him to religious
conservatives nationwide. James was elected governor as a Democrat
in 1978 and served one term. Blount, a Montgomery businessman whose
father was postmaster general under President Nixon, says James has
wasted time on religious grandstanding instead of focusing on
economic issues that have caused Alabama to lag behind its Southern
neighbors. ``This is probably a referendum on Fob James and the
image he's brought to the governor's office,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout will be crucial, especially with the GOP runoff allowing
Democratic crossovers. Blount was endorsed by Birmingham Mayor
Richard Arrington, who heads a coalition of black voters typically
pledged to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The race appears close. In a poll published Sunday, Blount drew
48 percent, James 47 percent. The poll was taken June 23-26 by
Southern Opinion Research and had a margin of error of plus or
minus five percentage points. In a five-man primary June 2, James
took 48 percent of the vote. Blount won 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sunday, however, at least one poll has shown James opening
a lead over Blount, a potential backlash to the Arrington
endorsement, said Gerald Johnson, who has been contracted to
conduct polling for the Alabama Education Association. The AEA's
president has endorsed James.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly will be some of that'' backlash, said Johnson,
formerly a political scientist at Auburn. ``At some level, there's
a racial reaction. ... Over the last three days, there's been a
significant move in the likely vote for Gov. James. But what is not
known is the size of the Democratic crossover vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2719 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-29 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A DELICATE BALANCE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Two months after Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright laid down an ultimatum to Israel to decide on a further
redeployment from the West Bank or else, neither the decision nor
the ``or else'' has appeared. Last week, in fact, Israeli papers
were running polls on whether there should be a national referendum
on whether Israel should accept the U.S. proposal for a 13 percent
withdrawal. It was like asking Israelis for their opinion about
whether the government should ask their opinion before it gives its
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, I was left with
the impression that he is ready to do a deal _ provided he can get
from the Palestinians all the political and security concessions he
feels he needs to insulate himself from the crazies in his
coalition who oppose any accord. (Polls show 63 percent of Israelis
favoring the withdrawal, so the public is ready.)
</P>
<P>
   But no deal is going to give Netanyahu, or Yasser Arafat,
everything they want. If in the end the deal on the table satisfies
Israel's basic security needs, but does not satisfy every political
need, will Netanyahu risk his coalition to push it through, or risk
the peace? No one here knows.
</P>
<P>
   I believe Netanyahu will do this deal, but only when he feels he
has no other choice. What is unusual about today, though, is that
there is a temporary equilibrium of forces that is making it
difficult for any party to force that choice. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The United States: &LR;  Back in the 1970s, Henry Kissinger was
ready to twist Golda Meir's arm to accept the 1973 disengagement
accords, and in the early 1990s James Baker was ready to twist
Yitzhak Shamir's arm to accept the Madrid peace conference. Why?
Because clear-cut overarching U.S. strategic interests were at
stake _ a global struggle with the Soviet Union and a global
struggle with Iraq. Today there are still some U.S. interests in
the peace process. But the Clinton team, because it has not
articulated any coherent post-Cold War strategic framework, can't
convincingly link any particular regional conflict with U.S.
national security, and therefore can't counter domestic pressures
to do nothing. Without a strategic logic, the Americans look like
naive do-gooders trying to break up a street brawl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Israel: &LR;  The Israeli economy today is OK, there has been no
serious Palestinian terrorism in many months and the Labor Party
opposition has all but collapsed, so for the Israeli public there
is no urgency to make a decision. Sure, every week some senior
Israeli political figure denounces Netanyahu as a liar and
manipulator. President Ezer Weizman did it last week, and on Monday
even called for new elections. But it has no effect. It seems that
some part of Israelis likes the idea that Bibi is such a bad boy.
Better, they say, to have an Israeli bad boy deal with the bandits
on the Arab side.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jordan: &LR;  King Hussein, who has more influence with the Israeli
public than any other Arab leader does, complains privately about
Netanyahu but won't break with him. This is because the king is
worried about triggering an explosion that will scare away the
foreign investors he needs. He is worried about a Palestinian
state. And he doesn't want to admit to his domestic and Syrian
critics that his Israel alliance might have been wrong. So he stews
privately and writes Netanyahu angry letters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Palestinians: &LR;  Also paralyzed. Arafat doesn't want to
unleash the Palestinian ``street,'' because he could lose control
and it could torch him. He also doesn't want to give a green light
to Hamas suicide bombers, because this will turn the United States
against him. So he stews and writes letters to Albright.
</P>
<P>
   So what you have, for the moment, is a negative equilibrium. But
its stability is an illusion, because it is not built on any
positive understandings, but rather on problems not solved,
promises not kept, decisions not taken and anger not vented.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, what you feel here is that even if there is a deal,
things won't really improve. Netanyahu's whole approach to the
Palestinians is based on the notion that there is no Palestinian
people, with its own interests and politics. That's why he
negotiates with America and gives the Palestinians a choice of
accepting what he is willing to offer America or taking nothing.
Even if Netanyahu is able to engineer a deal on those terms, it
will not be stable because there will be no real Palestinian
consensus underlying it, only an Israeli diktat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
