<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-FIRES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VP visits scorched Florida
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM COAST, Fla. _ Surrounded by the burned-out ruins of several
homes and acres of blackened pine trees, Vice President Al Gore
promised federal help is on its way to fire-ravaged Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``A joint federal and state disaster recovery center will be
established in this neighborhood tomorrow,'' Gore said Monday after
visiting residents of Seminole Woods, where nearly two dozen homes
were lost in early June. ``My heart goes out to the families who
have lost their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit came as Florida officials said they believe
firefighters are gaining the upper hand against the blazes, which
have blackened more than 230,000 acres across the state since late
May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out of the woods yet, but we're getting the kind of
equipment we need to go on the offensive in attacking the fires,''
said Gov. Lawton Chiles, who accompanied Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fires have been sparked by lightning, although some
are the work of arsonists. Fires have flared in all but one of the
state's 67 counties, with the northeast section hardest-hit.
</P>
<P>
   The flames have feasted on bone-dry acres of timber and scrub,
parched by a three-month drought and some of the hottest
temperatures in Florida weather-record history. Weather forecasters
say there is no immediate help on the way. Conditions for the week
appear likely to remain dry, with some afternoon thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   The storms and accompanying lightning sometimes do more harm
than good, sparking new fires and dropping only isolated patches of
rain.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, fires threatened Jacksonville and Waldo, a small
town outside Gainesville. Now those blazes have abated and the
biggest inferno is raging in pine woods west of Daytona Beach.
Thick smoke has filled the air over parts of several surrounding
counties, obscuring roadways and leaving some people with coughs
and stinging eyes.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, though, a moderate sea breeze off the
Atlantic blew most of the smoke away from Daytona International
Speedway, which will host the Pepsi 400 stock car race on the
Fourth of July, an event that is expected to attract hundreds of
thousands of racing enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Gore toured fire-scarred parts of Volusia County, where 80,000
acres have burned but no homes or lives have been lost. He also
traveled to Flagler County, where several dozen homes burned in
early June.
</P>
<P>
   Residents were heartened by the attention, which included an
hourlong private meeting with the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It touched me,'' said Bob March, who took Gore on a tour of
the burnt-out remains of his home. ``I really believe his heart is
in the right place and he will do all he can to see we get some
help.''
</P>
<P>
   But March and several other residents of Seminole Woods
complained that firefighters were slow to respond and only gave
last-minute evacuation orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw one firetruck in here,'' said Shawn Wilson, 35,
who saved his home with a garden hose. ``Three hours before the
fire, they told us everything was OK, and then they gave us 10
minutes to get out. Something was definitely wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore promised more federal help for fighting the fires,
including $35 million that the Federal Emergency Management Agency
has already committed for equipment, overtime and disaster
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Residents welcomed the promises, but said they hope the words
are followed by deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been made so many promises already,'' said Jim Jones,
who lost his home and his business. ``We want to see if the end
results match his words.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
