<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Tampa Bay Devil Rays
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Tonight and Wednesday at 7:05 p.m., Thursday at 12:35
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV, radio: TBS will telecast tonight's game. Fox Sports South
will telecast Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, LHP Denny Neagle (8-6,
3.48; first appearance vs. Devil Rays) vs. LHP Tony Saunders (1-8,
4.75; 3-0, 1.65 lifetime vs. Braves). Wednesday, RHP John Smoltz
(5-2, 3.77; first appearance vs. Devil Rays) vs. RHP Julio Santana
(2-1, 5.11; first appearance vs. Braves). Thursday, RHP Greg Maddux
(11-2, 1.64; first appearance vs. Devils Rays) vs. TBA.
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: This is the first meeting between the two
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Braves visited Tropicana Field in spring
training and lost. Since then, Atlanta has gone 5-0 against
expansion teams.
</P>
<P>
   _ Devil Rays leaders: Avg.: Aaron Ledesma (.317); HR _ Paul
Sorrento (12); RBI _ Fred McGriff (41); SB _ Mike Kelly and Randy
Winn (9). W _ Luis Arrojo (10); ERA _ Scott Aldred (2.19).
Strikeouts _ Arrojo (92). Saves _ Roberto Hernandez (17).
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: Tampa Bay is coming off a 2-3 road trip, scoring just
15 runs and 10 of those came in the last two games, both victories
in Philadelphia. At 37-46, the expansion Devil Rays have a better
record than seven clubs. With its 10th win of June coming Sunday,
Tampa Bay joins Florida as the only expansion teams to win 10 games
in each of their first three months of existence. . . . The D-Rays
are 5-8 in interleague play. . . . The team's 40 errors are
second-fewest in the majors only to Baltimore. . . . Tropicana
Field has not been kind to the Rays' pitching staff, which has
posted a 4.93 ERA and given up 45 home runs in 38 home games. In 42
road games, Devil Rays pitchers have a 3.84 ERA and 36 homers
allowed. . . . Ex-Brave Fred McGriff, with 10 hits in his last 23
at-bats, is breaking out of an extended slump. His home run Sunday
off Philadelphia's Mark Portugal was only his second in 52 games.
He is still batting just .234 this month. . . . The Braves last
faced lefty Tony Saunders in Game 3 of the NLCS. He had no decision
in that game, leaving in the sixth with Florida trailing 2-1, but
his 1998 performance against the Braves was extraordinary. In four
starts against Atlanta, he was 3-0 with a 1.65 ERA. Against
everyone else, he was 1-6 with a 5.57 ERA. With 54 walks in 15
starts this year, he has allowed 148 men to reach base in just 89
innings. . . . The D-Rays will not name Thursday's starter until
Thursday. Manager Larry Rothschild will choose either Luis Arrojo
or Jason Johnson. . . . On the DL: LHP Wilson Alvarez (left
shoulder tendinitis), LHP Vaughn Eshelman (left shoulder surgery),
RHP Eddie Gaillard (strained right elbow), RHP Rick Gorecki (right
bicep tendinitis), 1B Herbert Perry (knee surgery), RHP Bryan Rekar
(lower back) and LHP Terrell Wade (left shoulder surgery).
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's hot: DH Paul Sorrento has six homers in 11 games with 14
RBI. OF Mike Kelly has six hits in his last 15 at-bats (.400) after
opening the month 0-for-21. Closer Roberto Hernandez has not
allowed a run in his last 23 innings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's not: 3B Wade Boggs is hitting .154 in his last 26
at-bats, after going hitless in three games in Philadelphia. OF
Rick Becker is in a 3-for-30 slump.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
