<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta promotes former flight attendant to executive post
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines is elevating a homegrown executive to
a top position in which she'll oversee the carrier's efforts to
improve service and more efficiently handle heavy passenger loads.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Escarra, a native Atlantan who started with Delta as a
flight attendant in 1973 and rose into upper management, was named
Monday as executive vice-president-customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Escarra becomes the highest-ranking female executive at
Atlanta's biggest corporate employer. Her appointment also bucks a
recent trend at Delta of filling top positions with outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   They include a new chief executive, chief financial officer and
marketing chief, all brought in over the past 10 months. But the
new chief executive, Leo Mullin, appears content to leave daily
operations in the hands of Delta veterans such as Escarra and her
immediate superior, Chief Operating Officer Maurice Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Escarra, a 45-year-old Georgia State University graduate, had
been senior vice president-airport customer service. She takes on
the broader role as Delta struggles to reverse a decline in its
once-lofty service image, a problem magnified by heavy passenger
loads generated by a strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Delta announced the move Monday, the American Society of
Travel Agents issued a Traveler's Bill of Rights calling for ``bare
minimum standards'' of cleanliness, courtesy and comfort for
airline passengers.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Air Transport Association, an airline trade
group, said the agents' group is upset over commission cuts and
denied wholesale service problems.
</P>
<P>
   Escarra said she believes Delta has made more progress than it
is credited for in repairing service problems created by cost cuts
in 1994 and 1995. She added the airline has accelerated plans to
refurbish aircraft interiors and has set a goal of having the best
on-time rate of any hub-and-spoke airline by 2000, which would mark
a vast improvement over its poor historical ranking. She also said
Delta soon will introduce new technology to streamline passenger
processing and cut down on long lines at airports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding ways we can manage crowds efficiently is where we will
win as far as service goes,'' Escarra said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Delta confirmed Monday that Gayle Bock, vice
president for consumer marketing, is leaving the company. No reason
was given. Bock, who'd previously worked at United Airlines, was
hired in late 1996 and was involved in Delta's switch to a new ad
agency and the ``On Top of the World'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   She also headed the SkyMiles program and other promotions. No
successor has been named.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
