<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookie Brookings ready to get to work for Falcons
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The one concession to Keith Brooking's new status, a
sports utility vehicle loaded with all the options befitting a
soon-to-be millionaire, actually was delivered in April, two weeks
before the Atlanta Falcons made him the 12th overall selection in
the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   That the former Georgia Tech and East Coweta High School
linebacker is tooling around town these days in a Navigator seemed
appropriate on Monday afternoon. During a press conference to
announce his contract, Brooking again demonstrated that he has
carefully plotted a course for success and that money won't alter
his work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to play football and when I'm done doing that, maybe
I can sit back and think about the money I've made,'' said
Brooking, who looked as if he would readily swap his dark suit for
a pair of shoulder pads. ``I probably have more passion for the
game now than I've ever had. I think I can start, but my first goal
is just to get on the field as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves, whose playing career came at a time when not
even Pro Bowl caliber veterans earned seven-figure salaries,
suggested that Brooking's disdain during contract negotiations for
dollar-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves lauded Brooking, agent Gary Wichard and general manager
Harold Richardson for accomplishing one of the earliest first-round
deals in club history. He also revisited a ``throwback'' theme
started shortly after Atlanta chose Brooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's the first play of the first quarter or the last
play of the fourth quarter,'' Reeves said, ``Keith is always going
full speed.'' Before leaving for a mandatory three-day rookie
symposium in Denver, Brooking said he will begin looking for two
things upon his return _ a roomy apartment and a bank with a big
vault. He'll invest most of his team rookie-record signing bonus of
$3.8 million and seek some tangible way to help his parents, Brenda
Hembree and Harvey Brooking, both of whom attended the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Brooking's voice wavered slightly when he thanked his parents
for their sacrifices and guidance. Like her son, Hembree said the
magnitude of the ``camouflaged'' five-year deal had not yet
registered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people,'' she said, ``claim they'd play for free.
Keith loves football so much, I believe he just might.''
</P>
<P>
   That will hardly be the case. Unlike last year's 12th overall
choice, tailback Warrick Dunn of Tampa Bay, Brooking's signing
bonus is non-deferred. Of the $3.5 million bonus paid Dunn, $1.5
million was deferred to '98. Also, Dunn's contract did not include
any escalator clauses. Brooking can more than double his 2002 base
salary to $2.5 million by being voted to one Pro Bowl game.
Multiple appearances could push his salary that year to as much as
$4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
