<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NOMAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA'S HITLESS NUMBERS NUMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So, maybe we have this hitting streak stuff all
backwards with Nomar Garciaparra, who has hit in 20 straight games
entering Tuesday night's interleague contest against the Montreal
Expos in Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of counting the consecutive games in which he has
collected at least one hit, the conventional way baseball
record-keepers do business, maybe we should be calculating how many
games Garciaparra has gone without a hit.
</P>
<P>
   As you would guess, the number is a low one. Garciaparra has
played in 63 of the Red Sox 79 games this season. He has had at
least one hit in all but eight games in which he has played. Only
once this season, in back-to-back games against the Mets in Fenway
Park June 5 and 6, has he gone hitless in consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, incidentally, he doubled off Mets pitcher Masato
Yoshii, beginning the streak that has continued through Atlanta,
Chicago, St. Petersburg, Philadelphia and Miami and remains alive
Tuesday, when he is scheduled to face Expos ace Carlos Perez, the
lefthander who last September beat the Red Sox 1-0 and held
Garciaparra hitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can hit a lot of different pitches,'' Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams said when asked why hitting streaks are so commonplace
with Garciaparra. ``He can hit a lot of pitches that are maybe not
in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys chase pitches that are out of the zone, and
can't handle those pitches. Nomar doesn't chase those pitches. He
hits them hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, of course, Garciaparra set an American League
rookie record by hitting in 30 straight games. He already has had
seven streaks of 10 or more games, three this season, and his
current streak makes him just one of five Red Sox players all-time
to have more than one streak of 20 games or more.
</P>
<P>
   No Red Sox player, including Hall of Famer Tris Speaker, who
holds the club record with four streaks of 20 or more, ever did it
in his first two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a viper with that bat _ (itals)shoop,
shoop,(unitals)'' Williams said, making a sound intended to
recreate a snake's tongue flickng out of its mouth with lightning
speed. ``He's a lot of fun to watch. He's an exciting player.''
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie, Garciaparra went hitless in 36 of his 153 games,
and had just one streak in which he went more than two consecutive
games without a hit. That was last May, when he went four straight
games without a hit, at a time when he was playing with a strained
left hamstring and eventually was forced to sit out a few games.
</P>
<P>
   He is coming off a weekend series in which he absolutely wore
out Marlins pitching: his first four-hit game of the season Friday
night, two more hits plus a walk and hit by pitch on Saturday, and
a double on his first at-bat Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his outs were loud, too. He flied out to the
center-field track on Friday, lined out to right on Saturday, and
lined a 420-foot out into the center-field triangle of Pro Player
Stadium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Marlins manager Jim Leyland joked that Garciaparra is on his
second life as a big leaguer. Reincarnation is not a typical topic
of conversation in big-league clubhouses, but Red Sox manager
Williams made exactly the same observation last season.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland was impressed at the way Garciaparra took a pitch in the
back from Marlins pitcher Matt Mantei Saturday night and went to
first base without saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he was ticked off,'' Leyland said, ``but he didn't do
any of that finger-pointing stuff. He just ran down to first base,
like an old-fashioned player.
</P>
<P>
   ``And his next time up, he hit an absolute rocket. He's a
baseball player.''
</P>
<P>
   During his current streak, Garciaparra is batting .400, raising
his overall average 38 percentage points, from .278 to .316, which
ranks him third on the team, behind Mo Vaughn (.327) and Reggie
Jefferson (.323). Of his 34 hits, 16 have been for extra bases: 10
doubles, two triples and four home runs.
</P>
<P>
   And he has struck out just seven times in 85 at-bats. After
striking out 92 times in 153 games last season, Garciaparra is on
pace to drastically reduce that number this season, to just 65, a
remarkable number for such a free swinger.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Sox veterans like Vaughn and John Valentin warned
that Garciaparra would be a marked man. Last season, pitcher still
challenged him with fastballs because he was a rookie. This season,
they said, Garciaparra would see everything in a pitcher's
repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   They were right, of course, but Garciaparra adjusted. Sliders
off the plate, he has driven to right and right-center. Big-bending
curveballs, he has kept his hands back and driven them, too. Inside
fastballs on the hands, Garciaparra has fought off, and when
pitchers fail to hit their spots inside, Garciaparra has made them
pay dearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is about adjustments,'' Garciaparra said. ``First of
all, understanding the adjustments, and once you get through the
understanding process, you go through the `doing' part.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why the game is so difficult. Sometimes those
adjustments can take an awful long time.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes they don't. Any talk of streaks, and there is one
magic name: Joe DiMaggio, whose 56-game hitting streak is often
cited as baseball's unbreakable record. DiMaggio's brother,
Dominic, holds the club record of 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   Then again ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I was talking to Ted Williams,'' Red Sox GM Dan
Duquette said. ``Ted said, `I keep trying to think of who
Garciaparra reminds me of, and the one guy I keep coming back to is
Joe DiMaggio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
