<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-LOCKOUT-COX     06-29 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-LOCKOUT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA to lock out players at midnight
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several NBA teams are in such financial straits under the
current collective-bargaining agreement that not having a 1998-99
season would benefit them more than having one, commissioner David
Stern said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If Stern was being dramatic, he also was outlining the reason
why the league owners will lock out the players starting at
midnight tonight. The move, also used three years ago, will prevent
teams from performing business functions _ trades, contract
negotiations, free-agent signings and summer or preseason camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners can't afford, in effect, to play the season under
the current system,'' Stern said during a teleconference. ``That's
the reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners exercised their right to reopen the current deal when
it was determined that money paid out to players eclipsed by six
percentage points the 51.8 percenttrigger figure the sides agreed
on three years ago. However, nine negotiation sessions have
produced little in the way of agreement on the major financial
issues, including a revision of the rookie pay scale.
</P>
<P>
   And it stands to reason that neither side will bend much until
late in the summer, making the threat of the NBA's first work
stoppage quite realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential revenue-generating capacity is healthy,'' Stern
said. ``The system is not.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of matter is the so-called Larry Bird exception,
which allows teams over the salary cap to re-sign their own players
no matter how far it would take them over the cap.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Bird exception that allowed Shaquille O'Neal, Alonzo
Mourning, Kevin Garnett and Juwan Howard to ink pacts at or
exceeding $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go back to the owners and have a situation where
there is an open-ended (contract-signing system),'' deputy
commissioner Russ Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting rid of the Bird exception is something we will not
allow,'' said New York Knicks center Patrick Ewing, president of
the NBA Players Association. ``That can't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What could happen is no NBA action when no November arrives.
``That's fair and accurate,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Granik said basketball-related income for the players _
including salaries and benefits _ exceeded $1 billion for the
'97-98 season. The average salary was $2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in 14, 15 years, all 29 teams taken
together will (not turn a collective profit),'' Stern said. ``About
$1 billion have gone to the players and virtually nothing to the
owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik contends that the owners made four proposals in talks
``that all involved players' salaries going up, just hopefully not
as fast,'' he said. ``The players made one proposal on April 1 and
haven't moved off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern added that arrangements have been made with TV contract
money that would allow teams to survive an entire season without
games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
