<HEADER>
A2731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY-     06-29 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-GERMANY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY OUTCLASSES MEXICO, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELLIER, France _ Germany's grandpas were running on vapor,
their shirts and tongues hanging out in the 90-degree heat at the
Stade de la Mosson, down, 1-0, and 15 minutes from being out of the
World Cup. We've seen this movie before, of course, and we know the
ending by heart. Goal, goal, whistle, triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``This victory confirms our way of playing,'' captain Jurgen
Klinsmann said Monday &UR;  &LR; evening, after he and his mates had torn the
heart out of the valiant Mexicans, 2-1, and advanced to the
quarterfinals. ``Going and going and fighting and fighting for 90
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   And once again it was Klinsmann, the old prancing horse playing
in his third Cup, who carried the Germans, poking home the goal
that tied the match in the 75th minute and set the stage for Oliver
Bierhoff's winner in the 86th.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some moments when we thought, yes, we will win this
game,'' sighed Mexican coach Manuel Lapuente, whose squad had taken
the lead on Luis Hernandez's goal two minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the French thought in 1982, when they had the
Germans down two goals in overtime in the semis _ and lost on
penalty kicks. That's what the Yugoslavs thought in the first round
here, when they had the Germans down two goals with 17 minutes to
play _ and got tied, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Germans, who'll meet tonight's Romania-Croatia victor
Saturday in Lyon, didn't win three Cups and reach five of the last
eight finals by not knowing how to play knockout games. They know
how to use a clock, know how to substitute, know how to turn one
lapse, one turned head, one misplaced foot into a dagger.
</P>
<P>
   So it was again Monday. Just when the Mexicans were daring to
hope, German midfielder Dietmar Hamann played a ball into the area.
Mexico's Raul Lara saw it bounce off his foot. And Klinsmann, the
33-year-old striker playing his 106th international match, pounced
on the ball like a spider and knocked it past keeper Jorge Campos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always expect to be able to get a pass and score the goal,''
said Klinsmann, who has now scored 11 in his Cup career. ``Even
down 1-0, we never lost trust and confidence. The goal freed the
team completely and gave us a new energy and dynamism.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the clock was running down and the Mexicans were hoping
to push Germany's band of 30-year-olds into 30 dehydrating minutes
of overtime, the Germans coolly went for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   They began by stripping the ball from Jesus Arellano in their
own end. Now came Lothar Matthaus, the 37-year-old defender playing
in his fifth Cup, cruising up the middle, ready to pull the plunger
on a little Teutonic pinball. A long, looping pass to the left side
to midfielder Michael Tarnat. Now, back across the field to striker
Ulf Kirsten, who'd come on in the 74th minute. Now, into Bierhoff
in the box for an unstoppable header, the fatal stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Thus did Mexico's magic ride end after a gallant fortnight. The
``Tris'' had arrived here a laughingstock back home after a dismal
spring tuneup series that included a four-goal loss to a Chilean
college team. Their own newspapers dubbed them the `Tritanic'. But
after they came from two goals down to tie the Belgians and the
Dutch, nobody was laughing. Certainly not the Germans, who
remembered their last meeting with the Mexicans _ 120 scoreless
minutes in the 1986 quarterfinals before the Germans won on penalty
kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Germans had only lost once before the quarterfinals
since 1938. They dominated Monday's first half, but missed two
golden chances when a diving Campos knocked aside Tarnat's blast
with one hand in the 38th minute and Bierhoff hit the crossbar with
a header with nobody home in the 40th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost, but we did our very best,'' Hernandez said, after
German keeper Andreas Koepke had gloved his last-hope header. ``We
did the utmost.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, did Germany's grandpas, some of whom lay exhausted on
the ground after the final whistle. Going and going and fighting
and fighting for 90 minutes may be productive, but it's damned
depleting. ``The objective has been implemented,'' Berti Vogts was
saying, ``but I don't want to go through this kind of situation
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-TAILWIND-COX     06-29 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-TAILWIND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News integrity at stake in flap over nerve gas
 &HT;    (EDS: Story moving on (e) Entertainment and (a) General News
categories.)
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``There's something happenin' here/ What it is ain't
exactly clear.''
</P>
<P>
   So sang Buffalo Springfield in its hit ``For What It's Worth,''
the song that was used as background music on the controversial CNN
report on Operation Tailwind _ and a song that describes life
inside CNN today.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening is an investigation into the accuracy of
``Valley of Death,'' the report that kicked off the much-ballyhooed
``NewsStand'' magazine June 7. CNN reported that in Laos in 1970, a
covert U.S. military mission called Operation Tailwind used nerve
gas to kill American defectors and civilians. Such serious doubts
were raised about the report from many quarters _ including CNN's
own military adviser, who resigned in protest _ that Tom Johnson,
CEO of the CNN Newsgroup, hired noted First Amendment attorney
Floyd Abrams to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   As Abrams does that, no one at CNN will talk publicly about the
Tailwind report. Johnson, in his first public remarks about the
case since the controversy erupted, said Monday that Abrams' report
is due to him by July 8 and that he hopes to resolve the
controversy soon after.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams ``is guaranteed complete independence. All notes, all
files, all source materials are available to him,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact that Johnson went outside his own company _ the
first time he's done that in his eight years leading CNN _ is not a
signal that CNN thinks its original report can stand on its own
merits.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on what Abrams finds, Tailwind could be the biggest
embarrassment to CNN in its 18-year history. Johnson, known for his
integrity, will certainly order a retraction or clarification if
one is warranted, and it could be a devastating one.
</P>
<P>
   What's more likely is that the truth about whether Tailwind used
nerve gas or tear gas (as many have countered) will not be
absolutely verifiable; we're talking about a secret mission 28
years ago that people could have reason to lie about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't like there's a piece of paper we can refer to,'' was
how CNN anchor Jeff Greenfield put it.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it got the story right, CNN may not have lived up to
its own journalistic standards. There are credible allegations that
interviews with key witnesses in the Tailwind report were
selectively edited to make them seem more supportive of the nerve
gas angle than they were.
</P>
<P>
   It also appears that CNN interviewed some key players, such as
the pilots who dropped the gas, and did not include them in its
report. In fairness, CNN had evidence that nerve gas was used, but
it also had contradicting evidence that tear gas was used instead.
Several people involved in Tailwind _ the pilots, a medic _ say
they told CNN that and that CNN chose not to present it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, CNN did not include information that might have
compromised the credibility of its main source: Lt. Robert van
Buskirk, who wrote a detailed book about Tailwind in 1983 but never
mentioned nerve gas. He now says he repressed the memory for 24
years, something viewers should have been told.
</P>
<P>
   All of that would have weakened the story. But in 20/20
hindsight, it would have made CNN's position stronger today.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer covers television for the Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
