<HEADER>
A2742 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-UNPROTECTED-BOS &LR;      06-29 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-UNPROTECTED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE GAYS IN SAN FRANCISCO HAVING UNPROTECTED SEX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A 50 percent increase of high-risk sex among gay men in
San Francisco has surprised and puzzled AIDS experts there, because
it has so far not shown up in higher rates of human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection.
</P>
<P>
   Half of San Francisco gays who are 29 to 35 years old _ the
``second generation'' of the epidemic in a city among the hardest
hit by AIDS _ are engaging in unprotected anal intercourse,
according to a study being presented here today at the 12th World
AIDS Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The new trend is all the more striking because San Francisco's
gay community has often been cited as a model of responsible
behavior change and resulting drop in HIV transmission. Although
some studies in the early 1990s documented an upturn in risky
behaviors among younger gay males, the new data show a much higher
surge within the wider community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary that so many men in a city with such high HIV rates
are taking these risks,'' said Maria Ekstrand of the University of
California at San Francisco. ``It's riskier than Russian
roulette.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently between 30 and 40 percent of San Francisco gay men are
HIV-positive, down from about 50 percent in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Ekstrand said she and her colleagues were stunned to discover
that the proportion of gay men 29 to 35 years old reporting
unprotected anal sex went up 50 percent from 1992 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The men were in a study of 510 gay and bisexual San Franciscans
randomly selected from the 21 census tracts in the city most
affected by AIDS. The group has been followed since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Data since 1996 show the tendency toward risky sex has
continued. A separate analysis from the same group which considers
only men who were uninfected at the beginning of each year, found
that 14 percent were engaging in unprotected receptive anal
intercourse in 1993-94, but 26 percent reported this riskiest of
behaviors this year.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, however, the rate of new HIV infections within
the study group has not been rising _ and it appears to have fallen
recently, from 1.3 percent in 1995-96 to 0.9 percent in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers can only speculate about why riskier behaviors
have not yet translated into higher infection rates.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, said Dennis Osmond of the research group, may be
that HIV-infected men who are taking potent antiviral therapy may
be less likely to infect others because there is less virus in
their blood and seminal fluid.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible explanation, Osmond said, is that gay men are
reportedly asking prospective sexual partners if they are
HIV-positive before deciding what kind of risks to take, a practice
known as ``negotiated safety.'' However, the study shows nearly
half of those who engaged in unprotected sex did not know their
partner's HIV status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
