<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV05-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER TRAVEL ROAD WARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 5)  
(Eds: The words ASTERISK and NUMBER in parentheses have been used
twice each instead of the symbols, which are non-transmittable to
many newspaper systems.) 
 (JT)  
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about traffic jams! This summer's hot spots on the national
traffic-jam roster include a couple at least a year old. Several
new repair projects are creating major delays, up to two hours. As
resurfacing and widening of the middle-aged Interstate system
continues, long-distance drivers who have been barreling along may
find themselves trapped in a maze of overheating cars.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also good news. Some states have created phone
systems and Web site reports with up-to-date traffic and transit
information. In addition, there are slick databases for Boston,
Philadelphia, Washington and Cincinnati. Details on this system,
called Smartraveler, are below.
</P>
<P>
   But first, here is a quick view of national traffic knots
assessed by the AAA, state highway departments and other safety
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tennessee.  &LR; The problem bringing the most driver reports, the
AAA says, is on I-24 south of Nashville. Between Exit 53, the link
to I-440, a perimeter road, and Exit 81 at Murfreesboro, the road
is being widened and the ramps are being improved, with blasting
involved, which requires the stopping of traffic. If debris will
cause traffic to be blocked for 15 minutes after a blast, the
Tennessee Department of Transportation says, a detour is posted.
The state says that two lanes in each direction must be kept open
from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. Monday to Friday; blasting and lane
reductions take place on weekends, which may affect vacationers.
The AAA reports that delays of two hours are possible.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, the 60-mile detour around a blockage on I-40
near the Smokies at the  &UR; Tennessee-North Carolina &LR;  line is now but
a memory. Repairs of the road after last July's rock slide were
complete at Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee provides traffic information by phone and on a Web
site, both updated weekly, usually on Fridays. A call to (800)
858-6349 provides a menu of Interstate numbers so drivers can
listen to information on a specific route. The Web site,
www.state.tn.us/transport, gives the same information, with a map.
This site, among others, provides links to other state
transportation departments _ some valuable, others not really
intended for drivers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Connecticut. &LR;  Work on I-95 continues. The repair concentration
this year is in the western portion, from the New York
State-Connecticut line to New Haven. Picking up the Merritt Parkway
at the Cross Westchester avoids this work as far east as Milford.
Sue Reynolds of the State Department of Transportation says
construction is scheduled around the rush hours, with work going on
from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. and after 10 p.m. During construction hours,
there are lane restrictions for long stretches, Ms. Reynolds says,
so an extra hour of travel time should be allowed then. There is
also some construction on the link between I-91 and I-84 in
Hartford. It goes on between 9 a.m. and 3 p.m. and after 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Q Bridge work over the Quinnipiac at New Haven is complete,
and the Saltonstall Bridge in East Haven nearly done, Ms. Reynolds
said. ``There is as much work as last year,'' she added. ``It's
normal maintenance.'' Despite its position as a gateway to New
England vacation areas, Connecticut does not have a number to call
for information on construction delays.
</P>
<P>
   There are also problems on I-95 farther south.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; Pennsylvania, &LR;  repairs required after a tractor-trailer
accident on Memorial Day are almost complete in the Chester area.
Charles Metzger, a spokesman for the State Transportation
Department, said that the restriction to two lanes was expected to
end about July 15, when the concrete has cured. At first, the delay
was an hour, but detours have kept it to half an hour, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; Virginia, &LR;  I-95 is under construction on the 20 miles
between the North Carolina border and Exit 22. Traffic is down to
one lane each way, and the state says ``serious delays'' are to be
expected. The seven miles closest to the state line are nearly
done; the rest will take two years. Bridge repairs at Exits 58, 64,
67 and 69 are bringing lane restrictions in both directions.
Virginia has information on its Web site: www.vdot.state.va.us. But
it is not updated very often.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to  &UR; Yellowstone National Park &LR;  again face restrictions
as needed roadwork continues. Kerry Taylor at the visitor office at
Mammoth Hot Springs said that the Northeast Entrance and the East
Entrance were both being worked on, as well as Routes 14, 16 and
20, which link the East Entrance to Cody, Wyo. Driving in the park
is slow anyway _ allow an hour, for example, for the 16 miles on
the loop road between the Old Faithful Inn and Madison Junction.
But Ms. Taylor said 30-minute delays at the entrances should be
expected 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The East Entrance will be open only between 9 a.m. and 9 p.m.
until Labor Day; the Northeast Entrance only from 5 a.m. to
midnight. The South Entrance road from Jackson, Wyo., and the West
Entrance from West Yellowstone, Mont., will be coated with a
sealant one lane at a time, she said, causing lane restrictions.
Information is available from the Visitor Office, (307) 344-2109.
The Park Service has a Web site with pictures and maps at
www.nps.gov, but road projects are not included.
</P>
<P>
   Mud slides this year have given  &UR; California &LR;  difficulties along
the coast. But Jim Drago, a spokesman for Caltrans, the state
transportation department, said that Route 1, the coastal road,
which had 70 washouts in 40 miles south of Carmel, was fully
reopened at the end of May from San Luis Obispo north to Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   The state has a wide-reaching Web site, brought up to date
daily, with links to highway numbers, maps and grids:
www.dot.ca.gov.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How to Get Travel Updates &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The new Smartraveler system marks a major step forward in
getting information to drivers. The Massachusetts Highway
Department and a company called Smartroute Systems created it in
1992; the Web site for eastern Massachusetts began to operate in
1996. Since then, Cincinnati, Philadelphia and Washington have
signed on; their Web sites went into operation in 1995 and 1997.
The information is gathered by people with cellular phones and
using radio reports, camera surveillance and helicopters. The
information is made available three ways: on the Web site,
www.smartraveler.com, which offers access to data collected in all
four areas, by touch-tone phone and by cell phone in the area. Here
are the numbers:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Boston:  &LR;  Call (617) 374-1234; on a cell phone in the area,
call (ASTERISK)1. Be prepared to punch in the route number you want
to use and the exit numbers you will travel between.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Philadelphia: &LR;  Call (215) 567-5678; on a cell phone, punch
(NUMBER)211.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Washington: &LR;  Phone (202) 863-1313; on a cell phone, punch
(NUMBER)211.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cincinnati:  &LR; Call (513) 333-3333; on a cell phone, punch 211.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web site, the user clicks on the medallion for the
highway number and gets a report on the situation. According to
Katy Wallace of Smartroute Systems in Boston, New York, Detroit and
Minneapolis are coming aboard later in the year. Smartraveler works
closely with the AAA, Ms. Wallace said. People using the cell-phone
information service can be switched to the local auto club, for a
tow or other help, by dialing AAA(ASTERISK).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
