<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE, STARR TAKE JABS OVER ATTORNEY-CLIENT CONFIDENTIALITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With ``possible impeachment'' lacing their
arguments, the White House and independent counsel Kenneth Starr
sparred Monday over whether President Clinton's longtime friend and
confidant _ who also happens to be a government lawyer _ must
disclose his conversations with the president about the Monica
Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of Linda Tripp's appearance before his federal grand
jury, Starr told a three-judge appeals panel that deputy White
House Counsel Bruce Lindsey's status as a government-paid lawyer
precludes using attorney-client confidentiality to avoid
testifying.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that Clinton's private attorneys could not be
forced to testify, Starr said government lawyers like Lindsey have
a duty to report evidence of wrongdoing that eclipses any
attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Neil Eggleston, who represents the White House,
dismissed Starr's argument as exceeding ``the boundaries of
imagination'' and said it could deprive the president of effective
legal counsel in ``a run-up to possible impeachment,'' proceedings
by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Woven through the appeals court arguments were hints of a
broader examination of Lindsey's role as Clinton's most trusted
adviser. Lindsey, whose relationship with Clinton dates back to the
1960s when they were in Arkansas, has declined to tell the grand
jury about his talks with the president concerning the Lewinsky
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson ordered Lindsey
to answer Starr's questions, saying the needs of his criminal
investigation outweigh the president's right to confidential
communications with his government-paid lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The White House appealed, which prompted Monday's two-part
hearing before appeals court judges Raymond Randolph, who was
appointed to the court by President Bush, and Judith Rogers and
David Tatel, who were appointed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Under Starr's direction, grand juries in Washington and
Arlington, Va., are investigating whether Clinton or any of his
associates tried to cover-up alleged sexual encounters with
Lewinsky and with Democratic activist Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has indicated privately to congressional leaders that he
plans to submit his findings to the House of Representatives, the
body with the power to impeach a president.
</P>
<P>
   Eggleston said Starr wants information from meetings in which
Clinton, Lindsey and the president's private Whitewater lawyers
discussed a strategy for the president to follow in the Lewinsky
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Randolph, alluding to grand jury information available to
the court but not to White House lawyers, twice cautioned Eggleston
against assuming that Starr's investigation was focusing only on
Lindsey's role since the Lewinsky investigation became public in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Randolph asked Starr if it was proper for White House
lawyers to provide advice to the president on the Paula Jones
sexual harassment case and the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Starr responded that his office was not taking a position on
whether Lindsey's role in advising the president on private legal
matters was a ``misuse'' of government funds.
</P>
<P>
   When Starr argued that government lawyers are not allowed to
withhold information from a federal grand jury, Judge Tatel asked
if the same would be true if the information was being sought ``not
by the grand jury, but by the House impeachment committee?''
</P>
<P>
   Starr paused, then acknowledged that conversations between a
deputy White House counsel and the president could remain
confidential if impeachment were in the offing. Starr quickly
added: ``It is premature for this court ... to be looking down the
road and to be worrying about impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Eggleston, himself a government official, maintained that
attorney-client confidentiality should be absolute and must extend
to Lindsey and others who have sworn a U.S. oath of office.
</P>
<P>
   Without attorney-client confidentiality, ``the president of the
United States is completely deprived of counsel,'' Eggleston said.
A president must know his government lawyers cannot be forced to
testify about their confidential conversations, or he will not
confide in them, Eggleston argued.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's hearing comes on the eve of an appearance by Tripp, a
former White House employee who secretly tape recorded Lewinsky
allegedly discussing an affair she had with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp also allegedly received so-called ``talking points'' from
Lewinsky suggesting ways Tripp could provide misleading answers
when questioned about the encounter between the president and
Willey, who has testified that Clinton fondled her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Lewinsky have said under oath that they never had
sex. Clinton has said publicly he never asked anyone to lie and
that his behavior during the November 1993 meeting with Willey was
not improper.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, a former White House intern, has not testified before
the grand jury, and her lawyers are negotiating with Starr's staff
to protect her from prosecution in return for cooperating with the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
