<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR SEPARATIST ACCEPTS PARTS OF AUTONOMY OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The East Timorese independence leader, Jose
Ramos-Horta, said on Monday that he would accept an offer of
limited autonomy within Indonesia now and a five-year delay on a
referendum on the territory's permanent status. But he would not
agree to a recognition of Indonesian sovereignty in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference here, Ramos-Horta recommended that
the question of who owns East Timor, which Portugal abandoned and
Indonesia seized in 1975, be frozen while changes in the territory
take place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is progress on the ground that would be beneficial to the
people of East Timor and beneficial to the Indonesians,'' he said,
responding to proposals made on June 10 by President B.J. Habibie.
Ramos-Horta defined that progress as a reduction of Indonesian
troops in East Timor and the release of all political prisoners,
including Jose Xanana Gusmao, a guerrilla leader who has served
five years of a 20-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos-Horta had earlier seemed to rule out any compromise, even
in the short term, and he remains committed to East Timorese
independence. Habibie has already said that independence is not
possible, and has linked even limited autonomy to an international
recognition of Indonesian sovereignty over East Timor, which has
been denied.
</P>
<P>
   Under President Suharto, who resigned in May after more than 30
years in power, a special administrative status for East Timor's
800,000 people had not even been considered, and Ramos-Horta said
he welcomed Habibie's gestures.
</P>
<P>
   The new president also recently met Bishop Carlos Ximenes Belo
of East Timor, with whom Ramos-Horta, who lives in exile in
Australia, shared the 1996 Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos-Horta cited changes in both Indonesia and South Korea,
where longtime dissident and opposition leader Kim Dae-jung assumed
the presidency this year. He said the changes amounted to ``a
collapse of the Berlin Wall in East Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   In this atmosphere, Ramos-Horta said, there is room for
compromise if Indonesia does not insist on conditions.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the East Timorese had been asked not to indulge in
violence against Indonesians. There have been scattered incidents _
like a reported shooting of a Timorese man Monday after a crowd of
Timorese attacked a vehicle carrying security officials assigned to
protect European diplomatic visitors. But such episodes are
probably provoked by government agents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There have not been any clashes between Timorese guerrillas and
Indonesian troops since April, he said, adding that Timorese have
told him the troops are not being paid regularly during the
country's financial crisis and may have begun to lose heart.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos-Horta said he had not been asked by Indonesian officials
to join in talks about the territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
