<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONSANTO-CARGILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONSANTO SET TO ACQUIRE CARGILL'S FOREIGN SEED UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., Mo.)   (af)  
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Monsanto Co. will buy Cargill Inc.'s international
seed operations for $1.4 billion, the two companies said Monday, in
one of the clearest signs yet of expectations that biotechnology
will play a pivotal role in agriculture's future.
</P>
<P>
   The deal furthered an alliance the two companies formed this
spring, when they set up a joint venture to meld Monsanto's
biotechnology prowess with Cargill's huge stake in grain
processing, feed production and other parts of the food chain. It
signaled that Cargill's confidence in Monsanto's future had not
been shaken Monsanto's pending sale of itself to American Home
Products Corp., a huge deal intended to exploit the links between
biotechnology research in all of what are known as the life
sciences from food to drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's deal also reflected Cargill's weakening strategic
position with biotechnology beginning to overtake traditional plant
breeding as the key to developing valuable new crops.
</P>
<P>
   Cargill, a privately held conglomerate based in Minneapolis, has
profited from having overseas operations that are among the largest
in the fragmented global seed market. The strains of corn and other
plants Cargill has developed through traditional breeding are
popular in Latin America and among the world leaders in tropical
climates. But the company conceded that it has been too slow to
invest in biotechnology to remain a major player going forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't have the biotech capability and cost effective
access to biotech is now critical,'' said Fredric Corrigan,
president of Cargill's agricultural group.
</P>
<P>
   For Monsanto, the deal is intended to speed up the process of
penetrating overseas markets with such popular products as corn
engineered to create its own insecticide and soybeans that can
tolerate being sprayed with Monsanto's Roundup herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for our existing biotechnology traits outside
North America is roughly double the acreage potential within North
America,'' said Hendrik Verfaillie, president of Monsanto, which is
based in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest in a string of seed company acquisitions
by Monsanto, culminating in its double-barreled announcement in May
of agreements to spend well over $4 billion in stock and cash for
DeKalb Genetics Corp., a leading corn seed company, and Delta and
Pine Land Co., the United States' largest cotton seed company.
</P>
<P>
   The technology and the hefty valuations on the seed companies
were expected to encourage still further consolidation. Monday's
deal left the fate of Cargill's domestic seed business hanging. And
rumors continued to swirl about potential mergers or alliances to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clearly heading down to three companies or groups
of companies in grains and oilseeds,'' said Bonnie Wittenburg, who
follows agriculture for George K. Baum &AMP; Co. One group would be
built around Monsanto, another around the alliance of Pioneer
Hi-Bred International and DuPont, and the third around Novartis,
the Swiss company that is Europe's largest entrant, Ms. Wittenburg
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology critics fear the first generation biotech crops
will eventually backfire by encouraging the development of even
more devastating insects and weeds. But commercial farmers have
embraced them rapidly because they produce higher yields and, for
now at least, reduce reliance on harsher chemicals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
