<HEADER>
A2762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-DAYCARE-COX     06-29 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-DAYCARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day care centers, camps more alert for child illnesses
 &HT;    By Ellen Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When three toddlers who attended the same home day
care center became ill with E. coli, health officials thought the
center might be a common link.
</P>
<P>
   It was a likely suspect. Though investigators soon shifted their
focus to whether the bacteria might have spread when the youngsters
played at Marietta, Ga.'s White Water Park, the cluster of cases
underscores the potential for infections at day care centers and
summer camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you group children in diapers together, that is a high
risk group for the spread of infectious diseases and that's why we
have very specific regulations to address it,'' said Jo Cato,
director of the child care licensing section of the office of
regulatory services for Georgia's Department of Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Children playing with each other at day care centers or summer
camps can pass along the E. coli bacteria when children or staffers
do not properly wash their hands after using the bathroom or
changing a child's diapers. Though E. coli is among the most
serious infections that can spread through feces, an infected child
might expose others to hepatitis A, salmonella, pinworms and polio.
</P>
<P>
   State officials closely monitor day cares to prevent such
transmissions, Cato said. If there is a health concern or an
outbreak of an infectious disease, day care centers are required to
call in health officials.
</P>
<P>
   They also must follow the state's health and safety regulations,
including strict infection control practices. Day care staffers
must make sure to wash their hands with anti-bacterial soap before
handling children, food or toys. They also should help kids wash
their hands after using the bathroom; they also disinfect toys and
clean surfaces where diapers were changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of diligence to apply (preventive measures) is
greater in a day care just because more people are involved,'' said
Mel Ralston, public health adviser for the Georgia division of
public health. ``But the practices are just the same. The things
you would do to prevent diseases of the gut would be the same as
the preventions in any household.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, children at day care centers and summer camp programs
have a greater chance of catching and spreading such illnesses,
simply because they're in a group, health officials say.
</P>
<P>
   That fact led White Water to ban small children in day care or
summer camp groups from the amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and day care operators also are on alert. Elaine
Kamienny, owner and director of a Kids R Kids in Marietta, said
concerned parents have approached her about the possibility of
their children catching E. coli. The center is about 20 minutes
away from White Water, but she told parents that kids don't go
there on outings.
</P>
<P>
   Kamienny said that she and her staff make sure that the
environment the children are in _ whether it is at a neighborhood
swimming pool or within their own center _ remains safe and
sanitary. ``If a toy goes into a kid's mouth, we immediately
disinfect it,'' she said. ``We do normal things to keep children
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
