<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0450 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-MAIN30-COX     06-29 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-MAIN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The White Water E. coli outbreak has widened,
public-health authorities confirmed Monday, taking in more cases,
more states - and more days on which children might have been
infected.
</P>
<P>
   Four additional confirmed cases were added to the tally Monday
by the Georgia Division of Public Health: a 7-year-old from Bartow
County, Ga. who is not sick enough to be hospitalized; one child in
Illinois; and two children in Alabama. In total, 17 children - 10
in Georgia and seven from five other states - have been sickened by
E. coli O157:H7 infection that is believed to have been spread at
the waterslide themepark in Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the cases have been proved by genetic fingerprinting to
have been caused by one strain of bacteria, showing that they
belong to the same outbreak. Results of tests on the other 12,
being performed by DPH and the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, are pending.
</P>
<P>
   All four of the children added to the list Monday have been
proven by laboratory culture to have been infected with
life-threatening strain of E. coli O157:H7. Their genetic
fingerprinting will not be completed for a week, said DPH
spokeswoman Joyce Goldberg, all four of the new cases visited White
Water.
</P>
<P>
   In a troubling development, officials said four of the 17 - the
two Alabama children, a Georgia case discovered last week, and
Matthew Addison, a 3-year-old in critical condition with hemolytic
uremic syndrome in Louisville, Ky. - visited the water park not on
June 11 or 12, when the other children were presumably infected,
but six days later, on June 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have wracked our brains, and we can't come up with any
other possible exposure,'' Randy Addison, 38, said in a phone
interview from his son's hospital room. ``My wife has always been
paranoid about E. coli; she won't even allow our kids to have
fast-food hamburgers.''
</P>
<P>
   DPH epidemiologists theorize that the White Water kiddie pool
was contaminated three separate times, Goldberg said, adding that a
child infected on one of the first two days could have spread the
infection on the third day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense that a child in the early stages of infection
could have come back before showing symptoms,'' she said. ``It
could be the original child, but that child might have been so
symptomatic that a parent wouldn't have taken them back to the
park.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the widening of the outbreak from two days to six, state
officials said Monday that they believe the danger has passed.
Because the incubation period for E. coli - the time between
infection and the development of noticeable symptoms - is no longer
than nine days, any child who was infected would be sick by now,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your child was at White Water from June 11-17 and has not
shown symptoms, there is no cause for concern,'' said Dr. Kathleen
Toomey, Georgia's public health director.
</P>
<P>
   But to others viewing the outbreak, that assurance may have been
issued too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it highly unlikely that the same sick child is coming
back and contaminating the wading pool day after day,'' Randy
Addison said in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Glyn Caldwell, state epidemiologist for Kentucky, not long
ago investigated a similar swimming pool outbreak of viruses that
infected a swim team even though their pool's chlorine levels were
adequate. It turned out, he said, that the pool's chlorinating
equipment was broken; instead of metering pool chemicals through
the equipment, employees added them to the water once a day by
hand. Tests done in the morning read within legal limits; but by
evening, he found, the chemicals were almost gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you wind up with pieces that don't fit the pattern,'' he
said of the newly discovered June 17 infections, ``you have to ask
whether they're part of what you're looking at - or whether there
are other sources that you need to test.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
