<SLUG> BC-VOTER-TURNOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNOUT CONTINUES TO DROP IN PRIMARIES THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Continuing a downward trend in voter turnout, fewer
than 17 percent of those old enough to vote have gone to the polls
in statewide primaries this year, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate said the decline may be a prelude to the lowest
general-election turnout ever this November.
</P>
<P>
   Of 16 states with two statewide party primaries, only three
recorded increases from the last comparable primary, while 10
states recorded their lowest turnout ever, the report showed. This
despite recent efforts to make it easier for people to vote.
</P>
<P>
   While measures like the National Voter Registration Act,
commonly known as the motor-voter law, have increased
registrations, they have failed to increase turnout at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that fewer voters turned out in states
that made an effort to increase participation with programs like
Election Day registrations and simplified absentee voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem we have is not procedural but motivational,'' said
Curtis Gans, director of the committee. ``There is no quick fix for
what ails the American political system.''
</P>
<P>
   Gans said that the decline in primary voters was not an
aberration, but a trend that has driven down participation by 25
percent in the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing this year,'' Gans said, ``is a
continuation of the disaffection, disinterest and disengagement
from politics.''
</P>
<P>
   One notable exception in the trend, the study found, was in
California. With contentious propositions on the ballot and the
state's first ``blanket'' primary, in which voters were allowed to
choose candidates without regard to party, voters turned out in
greater numbers, suggesting that they can still be motivated by
important issues.
</P>
<P>
   The study shows a sharp decline in turnout after a peak of more
than 32 percent in 1970. In 1974, the figure dropped to 24 percent.
This year only 17 percent of the voting-age population turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Gans said he saw two problems: a lack of motivation and
education for young people about the political system, and the
unregulated use of advertising on television.
</P>
<P>
   Of 87,531,000 people of voting age, derived from the 1990
census, 14,757,247 have voted in primaries so far this year. The
voting-age population includes aliens, convicts and those ruled
mentally incompetent, overstating the actual number of eligible
voters. But Gans said it is the only figure that can be compared
from election to election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
