A2770 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAMPOUT-AZR &LR;      06-29 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAMPOUT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUCSON GROCERS FEAR WELFARE DEBIT CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (TUCSON, Ariz.) - Tucson grocers worry the fireworks could get a
little too close this Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It's the third-busiest weekend for food retailers and it's also
the week that the state of Arizona chose to replace food-stamp
coupons and welfare checks with plastic debit cards for 20,000
people in Pima County.
</P>
<P>
   Grocers fear the program could leave confused and embarrassed
food-stamp shoppers in front of checkout lines with no way to pay
for their groceries and people waiting behind them ready to
explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told them it wasn't a good time, but they said it was too
late to change it,'' said Dwayne Richard, president of the Arizona
Food Marketing Alliance, who expects grocers to bear the brunt of
people's frustrations as the new card owners learn how to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Grocers and state officials say this switch from paper to
plastic is giving them the jitters.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big change for many food-stamp shoppers who are
unfamiliar with plastic's personal identification numbers and
activation dates. And the state's system isn't simple.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients access both cash benefits and food benefits on the
same debit card. Cash benefits are available through the new card
Wednesday (July 1).
</P>
<P>
   But the July date to access food-stamp money is different for
each recipient, depending on the first letter of the recipient's
last name.
</P>
<P>
   Grocers fear this detail will not be clear to many food-stamp
shoppers until after they've stacked their carts for holiday
picnics, stood in line and had their groceries tallied by cashiers.
</P>
<P>
   Cashiers are prohibited by law from asking a shopper how he or
she intends to pay for groceries until after the order is tallied,
Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   So cashiers who suspect there may be a problem can't keep it
from happening.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare recipients in 32 states are already using the card
system, which government officials say saves taxpayer money, is
less vulnerable to fraud, and is more convenient for users.
Food-stamp shoppers in Maricopa County, the greater metro Phoenix
area - make the change in February, and the entire state will be
converted to plastic by August 1999. All states are expected to be
using the system for food stamps by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the new system's technical glitches, educating card
users has been the most common problem in all states, said Carole
Throssell, spokeswoman for the national Food Marketing Institute,
the grocers' lobbying group in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Users frequently assume the debit card works like a credit card
and will permit them to exceed the amount the government credits to
their card each month, Throssell said.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona Department of Economic Security officials have
assured grocers that Arizona's technical system is well-tested and
sound and that 95 percent of Pima County's food-stamp shoppers have
visited their DES office to receive personal training, including a
12-minute video, before picking up their card.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona initiated the thorough, personal training after some
states experienced problems when they simply mailed debit cards to
each welfare and food-stamp user, said Dayne Coffey, DES program
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who got the card in the mail didn't realize they had
to call a number to activate the card or failed to understand the
importance of memorizing PINs and activation dates.
</P>
<P>
   Food-stamp shoppers in Pennyslvania, which began using debit
cards in November, received similar face-to-face training given in
Pima County. But Pennsylvania grocers report many of their
food-stamp shoppers are still lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our retailers have hired additional staff persons to stand by
and assist customers,'' said David McCorkle, Pennsylvania Food
Merchants Association president.
</P>
<P>
   And many new Pima County card owners who received their training
as early as May, immediately went out and tried to buy groceries
with their new but unactivated card, Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   The new system also could leave some hungry people behind.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 Pima County food-stamp recipients still haven't
responded to their letter instructing them to visit their DES
office to pick up their card, Coffey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little concerned with the inner-city homeless. We
didn't get a good show up,'' Coffey said. Some homeless could be
mentally ill, alcoholics or drug users, or just haven't been able
to collect their mail, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to realize they're out of food stamps,'' Coffey
said, ``and go wandering into their (DES) offices sometime this
month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
