<HEADER>
A2771 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TV-COVERAGE-NYT     06-29 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TV-COVERAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: CLINTON'S TRIP AIDED BY TV COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-DAY, CHINA-TRADE, CHINA-PEONY) 
(th) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a Beijing University student asked whether Americans had a
distorted view of China, President Clinton answered by pointing to
a gallery crammed with lights and cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can see, a few people come with me from the news
media,'' he said. ``I hoped that my trip would help show a full and
balanced picture of modern China.'' He almost got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Though intensely focused on human rights, television has
depicted a country so complex and changeable that reporters can
hardly keep up. One minute they are wondering why dissidents were
arrested during Clinton's trip (deliberate insult or public
relations gaffe?). The next they are wondering why President Jiang
Zemin allowed his news conference with Clinton to be televised live
(sign of freedom or public relations coup?).
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Clinton got a television gift that is a
politician's dream. In two dramatic appearances, he talked directly
to millions of people without those pesky reporters and producers
getting into the act. His news conference with Jiang and his
question-and-answer session after his speech at Beijing University
came as close to television verite as we are likely to see in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   For moments at a stretch (an eternity in television time) it was
just Bill Clinton and the camera. He talked spontaneously about
ideas, appeared relaxed yet in command, and sent home an image far
different from the tense, beleaguered one that has haunted him for
months. Because of such transforming moments, television helped
shape the meaning of this summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   And while all the reporters rightly emphasized how rare the live
television broadcasts were in China, the trip has been just as
revealing about American television.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage in the last few days has offered a rare chance to
experience surprising, live, sometimes leisurely news as it
unfolds, and it has affirmed the primacy of the 24-hour news
channels over the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Those two things clearly go together. The 24-hour channels (CNN,
MSNBC and Fox News Channel) carried the post-summit news conference
and the Beijing University speech live.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the news conference began just before midnight
Friday in the Eastern United States (no expensive, prime-time
programs to disrupt), among the major networks only ABC carried it,
halfheartedly and because it happened to coincide with
``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   After 45 minutes, ABC bailed out (about 25 minutes before the
end, it turned out), with Ted Koppel thanking viewers for their
patience and sounding apologetic as he explained that the network
had expected simultaneous translation, which would have cut the
time in half.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference did start off in a stiff, logy way, with
Clinton and Jiang reading statements and then stopping for
translations. But as it unfolded, it was possible to watch this
supposedly predictable appearance transform itself into an
electrifying debate.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton diplomatically ticked off the historic events that
had taken place in Tiananmen Square, his statement built in tension
as he headed toward 1989, finally saying, ``Nine years ago, Chinese
citizens of all ages raised their voices for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point you could sense Clinton speaking past the
reporters in the room, directly to people at home, especially those
who had criticized him for going to China in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   As the two presidents civilly disagreed on volatile issues (the
Dalai Lama, Tiananmen Square in '89), the exchange acquired a
fascination and suspenseful rhythm that were not recaptured in the
snippets played back later. In a world of scripted performances,
there was high drama in watching two political leaders thinking on
their feet, well coached though they must have been.
</P>
<P>
   There were many such television moments, revealing because they
were unplanned and unfiltered. At Beijing University (on Sunday
night, Eastern time), the students presented Clinton with skeptical
questions. Was his commitment to working with the Chinese sincere,
or ``Do you have any other hidden face behind that smile?'' one
young man asked, generating applause from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did, I would mask it behind a smile,'' Clinton said, then
assured the students that his position was genuine. All were
equally telling: the question, the applause, the glib human
reaction followed quickly by the political response.
</P>
<P>
   When the cameras strayed from the president, they captured some
startling, wordless images that added to the sense of a China in
which the old repression maintains its hold. Every network and
cable channel carried film of Chinese people being led away by the
security police.
</P>
<P>
   There were several incidents: two people protested by lying down
in front of a bus filled with American journalists; in other cases
people were led away when approached by American reporters on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   However wide and complex its potential reach, television tends
to speak with a single voice. Reporters declared this trip a
political success beyond the White House press office's wildest
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's critics were given their moments on the Sunday news
shows. And Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the national
security adviser, Sandy Berger, who seemed to be everywhere at
once, were presented with the tough issues that had been expected
to overshadow this trip: why Clinton did not meet with Chinese
dissidents; accusations about illegal Chinese campaign
contributions to the Democratic Party; the selling of satellite
technology to China. The questions, answers and even the Republican
disagreements had a perfunctory tone.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even China couldn't completely dispel interest in the
juicy prospect of Linda Tripp's testimony before the grand jury,
scheduled for Tuesday. Without China, imagine how the talking heads
would have been salivating. More depressing, imagine the lurid,
wall-to-wall Tripp coverage we have in store. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
