<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAMPSIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROCERS DECRY WELFARE DEBIT CARD AS COSTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Arizona grocers say the state's new program that
converts welfare checks and food-stamp coupons into a plastic debit
card is costing them money, and they want to be reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should it cost us money to do the work of the state?''
asked Dwayne Richard, president of Arizona Food Marketing Alliance.
``The state is saving money and the retailers are picking up the
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona grocers say the program costs them in several ways:
</P>
<P>
   - Most large chains must train their floor and office staff to
handle the new debit card system.
</P>
<P>
   - Most say the one or two free debit card terminals the state
system is willing to provide are worthless in a store with five,
eight or 12 check-out counters.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure their customers are not inconvenienced, large
stores must be ready for food-stamp shoppers in all lines. That
means the state is forcing them to readjust their existing software
at a cost of up to $750 a store or $30,000 per large chain, Richard
said.
</P>
<P>
   - Using the old food-stamp coupons is similar to a cash
transaction, with little cost involved. But the new state system
sharply increases debit card purchases, which costs retailers from
2 cents in the largest stores to 20 cents in the smaller ones each
time they swipe a card through their cash register computer,
Richard said. Some states have agreed to reimburse retailers,
including Maryland, Texas, New Jersey and Illinois. Arizona has
not.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely these new costs will be coming out of the grocer's
profits, which average a razor-thin 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that kind of profit margin, any new costs will be passed
on to the customer,'' said Debra Albery, a spokeswoman for Safeway,
which has 10 stores in Pima County.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers in Arizona and across the country like the concept of
debit cards for welfare shoppers, but similar complaints are being
heard around the country, said Carole Throssell, spokeswoman for
the Food Marketing Institute in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fairly widespread,'' Throssell said. ``We've been
frustrated by efforts of state and federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has not demanded uniformity in operating
systems from state to state, forcing some merchants to accommodate
two different systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a patchwork quilt system that is cumbersome,'' Throssell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last session, legislators failed to make the changes in the
program the grocers wanted but agreed to fund a study on the
program's financial impact on Pima County retailers, who begin the
program July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The state official running the program said he would support
legislation to give retailers a tax break for documented start-up
costs they incur, but he's not prepared to ``subsidize'' retailers
and deplete $300,000 annual savings for the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to enhance their revenue,'' Dayne Coffey, a
Department of Economic Security manager, said. ``If you don't want
to pay it, don't participate _ or use the state (computer)
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Grocers already absorb the cost of debit card use for other
customers, so they should do so for welfare customers also _ or
charge all customers a fee for using any debit cards, Coffey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting they raise prices,'' he said, ``but if they
provide a service to one class of debit card holders they should
provide the same service to all customers who present a debit
card.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
