A2784 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SAMPSON-QUITS-HNS     06-29 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SAMPSON-QUITS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MONTPELLIER, France _ Steve Sampson, who came to France with much
fanfare, high hopes and what he called the best United States
soccer team ever, quietly resigned as U.S. coach Monday morning at
a breakfast meeting with U.S. Soccer federation president Alan
Rothenberg.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I made mind up my mind last night,'' Sampson said, when
contacted Monday night at a friend's home in Paris. ``Three losses
is not an acceptable result. Maybe it's time for someone else to
see what they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson previously said he would not resign after the team's
dismal World Cup showing, but apparently the reality of a
last-place finish and lingering bad feelings from players who
harshly criticized his coaching were too much to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I feel like we're playing a better brand of
soccer, I'm deeply hurt by the results,'' Sampson said. ``I think
we were dramatically unlucky. We probably wouldn't be having this
discussion if we were more precise in front of the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was a victim of my own success and the team was a
victim of its own success. We raised the expectations of a lot of
Americans by some of the results we had (before the World Cup).''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sampson nurtured U.S. Soccer through the crucial years
after the United States played host to the 1994 World Cup. Under
Sampson, the U.S. qualified for the World Cup for the third
consecutive time and posted several significant victories before
France '98, including wins over Argentina, Brazil and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I'm very pleased with Steve,'' Rothenberg said. ``The
extent of the criticism (against Sampson) was very unfortunate and
very unfair. It's unfortunate that in sports when you lose, you
lose your job. The hazard of the coaching profession is that you
usually lose your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who said he would be willing to coach another nation or
take an administrative position with U.S. Soccer, forever will be
remembered for the hugely disappointing 0-3 World Cup experience.
</P>
<P>
   Among the three losses, the U.S. team fell to underdog and
political rival Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, to play well and dominate is not enough,''
Sampson said, referring to the Iran game. ``You have to play well,
dominate and win.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team also scored just one goal at France '98, the
lowest total of any nation in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous U.S. players who said they quietly questioned Sampson's
style before the World Cup began speaking up loudly in the days
after being eliminated. Tab Ramos described the experience as ``a
mess,'' and Alexi Lalas said Sampson had no master plan.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more questionable decisions Sampson made for the World
Cup were leaving veteran midfielder John Harkes off the team and
benching all-time leading American scorer Eric Wynalda for the
final two games. Sampson also ditched his much-hyped 3-6-1 game
plan after only one game in France.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson was hired as coach in August 1995 and led the U.S. team
to a 26-22-14 record overall.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the players speaking so harshly against him, Sampson
said, ``I just wish that people would look at themselves at the
same time they're looking at the coach. I'm prepared to take my
fair share of the blame. I'm not sure if some of the players are. I
can sleep easy. I'm not happy with the results, but I can sleep
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg said he would not make a hasty decision in trying to
find a replacement for Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   Two names already mentioned among the candidates are Carlos
Quieroz, a highly respected Brazilian coach, and Carlos Alberto
Parreira, who led Brazil to the 1994 World Cup championship in the
United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
