u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS     06-29 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   All in a fortnight's &QL; 
work for Sampras
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ More rain. More waiting. Far more anticipation
than action until midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, there would be more Pete Sampras, too. For all
his recent troubles elsewhere, Sampras' victories at Wimbledon
remain as inevitable as the drizzle. Which is to say, pretty darn.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's being dissed in some circles, particularly the one
in the shape of Richard Krajicek's large mouth, there seems to be
nothing wrong with Pistol Pete's tennis. Maybe we should call him
Postal Pete because, rain or shine, he keeps making his appointed
rounds on Church Road.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras needed four days to dispose of Thomas Enqvist in three
sets, but dispose of him he finally did Monday, winning two
tiebreakers sandwiched around another weather interruption, the
fourth of their match. He and the Swede were on the court far less
than the 2{ hours they had to sit around twiddling their thumbs in
the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   But such is life here in Waterworld.
</P>
<P>
   ``You expect it,'' Sampras said. ``That's Wimbledon. It's part
of the aura of the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years, one blemish
</P>
<P>
   As is he. Except for Krajicek two years ago, nobody has beaten
Sampras on these sodden lawns going on six fortnights. He is 35-1
with four titles, as sparkling a record as anybody has compiled
over a similar span during the Open Era save for Bjorn Borg's 41-0
from 1976 through his loss to John McEnroe in the 1981 final.
</P>
<P>
   It was Borg, the inscrutable Swede, who begat a passion for the
sport in his country that would produce another dozen world-class
players in his stead, Enqvist among the latest. It was also Borg
who defined cool under fire. And rain.
</P>
<P>
   Once the showers came, as they always did _ and still do _ he
pulled out a deck of cards. When it was time to return to battle,
he gathered up his rackets and his lunch pail and, without changing
expression or his groundstrokes, churned out five successive
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras prefers to ``just shoot the you-know-what'' during the
incessant hiatuses. But informed of Borg's means of staving off
boredom when the weepy patches blew in from the West Country, he
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must have worked,'' Pete noted.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras admits he doesn't suffer the stoppages gladly. He
believes the overnight suspension of his quarterfinal against
Krajicek in '96 proved fatal _ never mind that he had gone home
trailing two sets to love. He's a huge believer in rhythm, and the
Wimbledon experience isn't theoretically conducive to maintaining
any. ``It's the same for everybody,'' he said, ``but it's not easy.
It changes the look of a match.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was supposed to play Enqvist on Friday. They finally got
onto the court late Saturday, and although Pete started with six
aces in a row en route to a 6-3 first-set victory, at 1-0 in the
second they were chased off the court. Thereafter, he found himself
hanging on with both hands.
</P>
<P>
   He came out with guns blazing Monday, yet the afternoon's second
restart saw his serve suddenly falter. After smacking three of his
29 aces in the 10th game for 5-all in the third set, he was plagued
by faults in the 12th game, leaving him obliged to stave off three
set points.
</P>
<P>
   The Sampras second serve is the finest ever, however, so survive
he did, ultimately blowing Enqvist away in the tiebreak.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek takes off kid gloves
</P>
<P>
   Thus Pete advances to the round of 16 today against French
qualifier Sebastien Grosjean. But just once in Sampras' last seven
tournaments, starting with Indian Wells in early March, has he
advanced beyond this point, creating speculation that his lengthy,
rarely interrupted run as the world's solid No. 1 was kaput.
</P>
<P>
   Krajicek, for one, opines that Sampras has become a pigeon on
more surfaces than just clay. Having defeated Pete in their last
two meetings, plus that '96 showdown in the quarters here, the
Dutchman recently pronounced Sampras no better than the 10th-best
player on the ATP Tour today.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting words?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that stuff doesn't faze me,'' Sampras said. ``I know my
capabilities. I know how I'm playing this week. My year has been a
bit up-and-down. I've had some bad days; that's all. I feel pretty
good, and I'm serving well here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has a ways to go before he'll get the chance to make
Krajicek dine on his verbiage. After Grosjean, he figures to run
into Mark Philippoussis _ no picnic on grass _ then encounter No. 3
seed Petr Korda, the Australian Open champion. Krajicek, in turn,
should have to beat twice-Wimbledon runner-up Goran Ivanisevic, who
hammered 44 aces in his two-part mini-series against Todd Martin.
</P>
<P>
   You strongly suspect, though, that Sampras badly wants a piece
of Big Richard. There's a score to be settled. If not for Krajicek,
Pete might be trying to make history this fortnight, instead of
spending most of it merely marking time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
