u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-WARCRIMES-NYT &LR;      06-29 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB ON TRIAL FOR ALLEGED 1991 MASSACRE IN CROATIA COMMITS
SUICIDE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ A Serb being tried for his role in a
massacre of more than 200 people in Croatia in 1991 has committed
suicide, the U.N. War Crimes Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The body of the Serb, Slavko Dokmanovic, 48, the former mayor of
Vukovar, was found early on Monday morning hanging behind the door
of his cell. A spokesman for the tribunal said that Dokmanovic had
hanged himself from a door hinge.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoner was reportedly on medication for depression and,
according to tribunal officials, had tried to kill himself before
during the year he had been held in the detention center, in
Scheveningen, near The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   The suicide abruptly closes the case against Dokmanovic just as
it was approaching its end. The trial, which began on Jan. 19,
ended last Thursday; the verdict was due on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no verdict now and the case is herewith
terminated,'' said Christian Chartier, the tribunal's spokesman.
``It must be very frustrating for the family, for the relatives of
the victims, for the prosecution and the defense, and maybe for
historians.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Chartier, Dokmanovic's lawyer had asked to increase
his client's medication on Friday. The prisoner again complained
that he was not feeling well on Sunday afternoon, and the prison
doctor who saw him ordered that he be closely monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Guards checked on him every 30 minutes and kept his cell lights
on. He was last seen alive at about 11:30 p.m. on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that, Chartier continued, Dokmanovic apparently
managed to short-circuit his cell lights and then killed himself in
the dark. On the next guards' round, just after midnight, he was
found hanging behind his cell door.
</P>
<P>
   Dokmanovic, a quiet graying man with a droopy mustache, had been
charged with war crimes for his role in one of the first
well-documented atrocities by Serbs during the Balkan war. He had
served until mid-1991 and from November 1991 to 1996 as mayor of
Vukovar, a town of 85,000 people on the Serbia-Croatia border and
the site of savage fighting after Belgrade ordered the Yugoslav
army to attack it.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment against Dokmanovic, in the final
days of the siege several hundred people sought refuge at Vukovar
Hospital because they had been led to believe that an orderly
evacuation with international observers had been worked out between
the warring parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army, which is dominated by Serbs, took control of
the hospital on Nov. 19, 1991. The next morning, Yugoslav and Serb
paramilitary soldiers pulled most men from the hospital, among them
``wounded patients, hospital staff, soldiers who had defended the
town, Croatian political activists, and other civilians,'' the
indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 300 men were taken to a farm just outside Vukovar and
there they were ``forced to run between two lines of soldiers'' who
beat them and later took them in small groups to a ravine where
they were shot and buried. More than 50 people are still missing.
The bodies of 198 men and 2 women have been found and identified.
At least two men died from the beatings.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dokmanovic was not charged with shooting anyone, his
indictment said that he helped organize the massacre. It says: ``At
all times, he aided and abetted or otherwise participated in these
events.''
</P>
<P>
   Three officers of the Yugoslav army have been indicted in the
same case but Belgrade has refused to hand them over.
</P>
<P>
   Dokmanovic was caught through a trick. He was invited to meet
U.N. officials at the Serbia-Croatia border in June 1997. He showed
up, not knowing that he had been indicted, and was immediately
arrested and flown to The Hague. That arrest was the first signal
that the tribunal had changed its strategy and was keeping
indictments secret.
</P>
<P>
   Dokmanovic had denied all the charges against him and his lawyer
has argued that he was the victim of mistaken identity. The lawyer
said his client had been very distraught and confused and was
arranging for a psychiatrist from Belgrade, who had come to see him
before, to travel once again to the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate investigations _ one by the tribunal and one by the
Dutch police _ have begun to determine how the suicide could have
happened in the closely watched detention center. The U.N. cell
block is a part of the Scheveningen Penitentiary Complex.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal is now holding 27 people indicted for war crimes.
One prisoner, a Serb general, Djordje Djukic, was released without
trial for health reasons in March 1996 and died of cancer two
months later in Belgrade. Only two have been sentenced by the
tribunal since it opened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Dokmanovic's trial, which began in January 1998, was one of the
fastest on record. During 35 days of hearings, 85 witnesses were
heard, in almost equal numbers for the prosecution and the defense.
Some legal experts argued that convincing and detailed evidence
against Dokmanovic was scant, while others believed he might face a
life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal's investigations of the Vukovar killings can now
continue only if and when prosecutors can arrest one or more of the
three other men indicted in the case. While the Vukovar massacre is
well documented, Chartier, the spokesman, said, ``the tribunal can
try people only on the basis of their alleged individual
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The three others indicted in the Vukovar massacre are the
commander of the Yugoslav army unit, Col. Mile Mrksic; his
subordinate, Maj. Veselin Sljivancanin; and the commander of a
special infantry unit, Capt. Miroslav Radic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
