<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-CONFERENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. PLANS TO TREAT 30,000 HIV-INFECTED PREGNANT WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ In a new attempt to slow the transmission of AIDS from
mothers to their babies, the United Nations is launching a pilot
program to treat 30,000 pregnant women infected with HIV in 11
countries where the infection is spreading rapidly, U.N. officials
said at the 12th World AIDS Conference here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which will focus on developing nations, mainly in
Africa, will offer testing to pregnant women and short-term therapy
with the drug AZT during late pregnancy and delivery.
</P>
<P>
   A number of studies have shown that short-term AZT therapy can
dramatically reduce the risk of a woman transmitting HIV to her
baby. Each year an estimated 2 million HIV-infected women worldwide
become pregnant, officials of the U.N. AIDS program said. About
680,000 babies were born with AIDS last year, thrusting
mother-to-child transmission to center stage at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   But as the U.N. program was announced at a news conference,
ACTUP-Paris, a French activist group, strongly attacked it as
unethical. Protesters argued that the program is far too limited,
because it provides treatment to women only during pregnancy and
not afterward.
</P>
<P>
   They also criticized organizers for not addressing the fate of
the children who will be born uninfected by HIV, but whose mothers
may soon die of AIDS. About 1.6 million children worldwide lost
their mothers to the disease in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. will be an orphan factory soon,'' Marie de Cenival of
ACTUP-Paris said. Ms. de Cenival and Gaelle Krikorian of
ACTUP-Paris charged in an interview that the United Nations was
submitting to pressure from the industrialized world to expand
their market for AZT and other drugs in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to limit spread of the epidemic but we think it is a
political strategy and we want people to understand that,'' Ms. de
Cenival said. ``It is a wrong and cheap choice, and it is not going
to strengthen the health system in Africa,'' where 21 million of
the 30 million HIV infected people live.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Piot, who heads the U.N. AIDS program, other U.N.
officials and Dr. Bernard Kouchner, the French minister of health,
strongly defended the project against ACTUP-Paris' criticism.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the United Nations did not have enough money to
treat all HIV-infected pregnant women and had to act now, even if
the program created some orphans in the face of what Piot said was
a ``runaway epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS program has negotiated with AZT's manufacturer, Glaxo
Wellcome PLC, for a substantial reduction in the cost of the drug:
$50 for the course of AZT and $20 for testing. A short course of
treatment typically costs $800. Participants will receive free AZT
starting at the 36th week of pregnancy and during labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're off track,'' said Gregg Gonsalves, a spokesman for
Treatment Action Group, a New York City AIDS activist group, in
reference to ACTUP-Paris' position. ``We think it is a great
project.''
</P>
<P>
   In choosing project sites, the United Nations targeted areas
where women of childbearing age have high HIV infection rates and
where the local health system is strong enough to deliver a number
of measures needed to reduce mother-to-child transmission of the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   The projects will be in four countries (Ivory Coast, Tanzania,
Thailand and Uganda) where AZT trials showed that short-course AZT
treatment can reduce the risk of infection in newborns by about
one-half. In Thailand, such therapy reduced the risk to 9.4 percent
from 15.9 percent, Dr. Nathan Shaffer of the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention said.
</P>
<P>
   The projects will also be conducted in seven other countries:
Botswana, Burkina Faso, Cambodia, Honduras, Rwanda, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Program officials must still overcome a number of hurdles,
including the spread of the AIDS virus through breastfeeding. A
third of HIV transmissions from mother to child in developing
countries are passed via nursing. The program, Piot said, will
offer counseling for infected women who choose not to breastfeed.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy E. Maklehemena, an HIV-infected South African woman whose
baby girl died of AIDS, inserted a personal note to the debate.
While not addressing the U.N. AIDS program directly, she criticized
doctors and drug companies for ignoring the impact of research
trials on women's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women will move mountains to have a healthy baby,'' said Ms.
Maklehemena of Durban. ``Women will be motivated to enroll if they
are told the trials can save their baby's life. But, how do trials
protect or prolong women's lives?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
