u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORT30-COX     06-29 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confusion reigns over new Florida abortion law
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ As of midnight, a form of late-term abortion
called particularly gruesome by foes became illegal in Florida. Or
perhaps most abortions became illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion heralds the effective date of the state's
so-called ``partial-birth abortion'' ban, which finally is law
after lawmakers overrode Gov. Lawton Chiles' veto of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights activists say the law is worded so vaguely that
it could reasonably be interpreted to ban any number of abortion
methods in even the first three months of a pregnancy, when a woman
currently has an absolute right to seek an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really trying to get rid of all abortions,'' said
Patricia Baird-Windle, who owns abortion clinics in both Melbourne
and West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the new law _ the first restriction on a Florida
woman's right to an abortion in nearly a decade _ say that type of
argument was to be expected from abortion supporters and their
defenders, who will not brook even reasonable restrictions on
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the law specifically targets a method known as
dilation and extraction _ in which a fetus is partially delivered
before it is killed by collapsing its skull _ that they call
tantamount to infanticide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a smokescreen to try and take the issue to something that
it is not,'' said state Sen. Anna Cowin, the Leesburg Republican
who sponsored the measure in the Senate last year.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, however, do agree that the legal arguing over the
law that would put imprison a doctor for five years for performing
a partial-birth abortion is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy it's becoming law,'' said House sponsor Randy Ball,
R-Mims. ``But the battle certainly is just beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   No court has yet evaluated the law on its merits _ a status that
changes today when abortion-rights activists will argue before a
federal judge in Miami that the law violates federal guarantees of
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the legal machinations over the law have centered on how
it passed the legislature. House and Senate overwhelmingly approved
it in 1997. Chiles vetoed it, only to see both chambers override
him this spring.
</P>
<P>
   In between was the special session on school construction, which
Chiles now argues should have been the time for any veto overrides
to come up. By waiting until spring, Chiles argued to the Florida
Supreme Court, the legislature waited too long.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's failure to rule on that question by Monday
meant 60 days have passed since the end of this spring's session
and, under the state constitution, the overridden law takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   Cowin argues that she meant for her bill to apply only to
partial-birth abortions in the last three months of pregnancy, when
most abortions are illegal anyway. As to banning other forms of
abortion? ``That was never the intention,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That, Baird-Windle said, is nonsense. ``They've never acted in
good faith in anything, ever,'' she said of abortion opponents,
many of whom blockaded her Melbourne clinic in years past. ``This
wording was part of their stealth attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Ball said there is no stealth attack: it is all out in the open.
Part of the strategy for banning partial-birth abortions, he said,
was to bring to the public a vivid description of what is done,
which isn't too much different than what is done in some other
abortion methods.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he'd like all abortions to be banned because he
believes they are murder. ``That's why there cannot be a
compromise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether the partial-birth is the proverbial foot-in-the
door: ``I hope so,'' Ball said.
</P>
<P>
   And that is precisely what abortion-rights activists fear, and
why they plan to argue in court today that the partial-birth ban,
by its broadness, takes away some of the abortion rights guaranteed
by the U.S. Supreme Court Roe vs. Wade decision 25 years ago. The
law is the first abortion restriction in Florida since the parental
consent law that lasted two months before it was overturned in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Charlene Carres, a Tallahassee abortion-rights lawyer who will
ask the federal judge to stop the new law from taking effect, said
most of the bans in the other 17 states that have passed them have
also been struck down by judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those judges can't all be reading it wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Coalition of Florida director John Dowless disagrees
with Carres' spin but agrees that a judge or judges somewhere,
state or federal, is liable to strike down the law. ``It's the last
bastion of liberalism left. And that's our courts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
