<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2802 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-MACKAY-COX     06-29 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MACKAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MacKay extends offer to Dantzler in hopes of unification
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hoping to unify the party and avoid a
costly primary fight, Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay has asked his opponent,
former state Sen. Rick Dantzler, to become his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, barring any last minute glitch, is expected to
be made today at a news conference in Tallahassee, according to
senior Democrats knowledgeable about the decision.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay met with Dantzler for dinner Monday night in the state
capital to formally ask Dantzler to join the ticket. Early reaction
to the ticket was largely positive. One notable exception was state
Rep. Keith Arnold of Fort Myers who now finds himself MacKay's lone
opponent for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful,'' said state Sen. Tom Rossin, D-West
Palm Beach, a Dantzler supporter. ``It makes an awful lot of sense
to do this. Rick is liked by an awful lot of people who are
concerned about the future of the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Diffenderfer, MacKay's Palm Beach County organizer, said
adding Dantzler to the ticket ``should quiet some of those factions
in the party who thought MacKay could not bring the party
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Dantzler, 42, is 23 years younger than MacKay and three years
younger than Jeb Bush, the likely Republican nominee. Supporters of
Dantzler, a quiet, soft-spoken lawyer from Winter Haven, say he
represents a new generation of Democratic leaders who can
aggressively challenge the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1997 Dantzler has tried to sell that image to party
leaders, hoping they would embrace his candidacy for governor.
During his year-long campaign Dantzler said he liked and respected
MacKay but was convinced that MacKay would be unable to energize
the party and defeat Bush in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Despite early support from a number of his former Senate
colleagues, Dantzler's campaign was never able to hit its mark.
Hoping to raise $1 million early in his campaign to prove he would
be a strong candidate, Dantzler had just over $600,000 nine months
later with more than $400,000 of it spent.
</P>
<P>
   In attempt to prove his determination to win, Dantzler quit the
Senate in January, promising to campaign full time. Renting an
apartment in Broward County, a key Democratic area, Dantzler spent
much of his time there.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his efforts, however, Dantzler continued to have
difficulty raising money and recent polls showed him far behind
MacKay. By last week Dantzler, who had often said he was not
interested in being a running mate, began publicly saying he would
be willing to consider the job if it was offered.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party leaders are now hoping to convince Arnold to
quit the race and perhaps consider a bid for secretary of state
instead. Arnold had been counting on a three-way primary. He had
hoped that he could win enough votes in September to pass Dantzler
and force MacKay into runoff in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been planning a runoff strategy and this announcement
obviously changes all that,'' said Arnold, who must find his own
running mate by the July 17 deadline. Arnold had raised more than
$300,000 as of March 31 and has spent nearly all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smartest thing Keith Arnold could do right now is work
with the party to find something that would help him stay in public
life,'' said one top Democratic official. ``If he wants to help the
party he should let MacKay begin the job of campaigning against
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Arnold is determined to stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been pretty clear for the last few weeks that
MacKay and Dantzler were thinking about doing this,'' Arnold said.
``It makes it harder for me but the only way I'm certain to lose
this race is by getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cory Tilley, Bush's campaign spokesman, was dismissive of the
MacKay-Dantzler ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever Buddy MacKay picks is not going to hide the fact that
Buddy MacKay is out of touch with Florida voters,'' said Tilley.
``Having Rick Danztler on the ticket is not going to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley is a political editor for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
