<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2803 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-BAUGHMAN-LADN     06-29 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BAUGHMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE INITIATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The conversation bordered on intense as both
sides stood firm in stating their cases.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the consultation with Angels third-base coach Larry Bowa
was just another day in the on-the-job learning process for Justin
Baughman, the Angels' 23-year-old rookie second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so, so much to learn,'' Baughman said, ``and I have a
lot of questions sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowa _ known for his feisty ways as a shortstop with the
Philadelphia Phillies and the Chicago Cubs _ has been a key figure
in Baughman's rise to the big leagues. Just last season, Baughman
was playing shortstop at Class-A Lake Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin had some merit to his thoughts,'' Bowa said of
Baughman's recent pregame tutoral. ``You want a player to stand up
and not just shake his head all the time in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like a guy who is intense. Justin has all the tools to play
at this level for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Baughman's climb through the Angels' farm system has been swift
and surprising. The fourth-year pro jumped from Class-A to Triple-A
this season and was promoted to the majors last month.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman has solidified a position that was a big question mark
when Randy Velarde couldn't make it back from an elbow injury.
Veterans Carlos Garcia and Norberto Martin failed in their bids to
start.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman, regarded as the quickest player in the Angels'
organization, has hit .274 and has fielded his position well,
making just three errors in his first 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into the spring thinking that I'd be playing shortstop
at the Double-A level,'' Baughman said, ``so yes, you could say I'm
ahead of my timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during spring training that Baughman grabbed the
attention of manager Terry Collins and Bowa. With Gary DiSarcina
set at shortstop, the Angels coaches' moved Baughman to second base
in the final week of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing just fine over there,'' Collins said. ``He's earned
the chance to play there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked his play at shortstop in the spring and then we
decided to take a look at him at second base for a couple of games.
We liked what we saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what they liked about Baughman was the way he attacked
the position change, trying to learn as much as he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listen to Larry a lot and I watch a lot of things that Gary
DiSarcina does as well,'' Baughman said. ``If I can do some of the
things that Gary has done in his career, I'd consider myself a
successful person.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, who has played alongside a number of second basemen
since coming up to stay in 1991, likes Baughman's potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of upside,'' DiSarcina said. ``As far as being
an example for him, that's up to him. I go out and do my job every
day and if he watches what I do, then that's fine. I appreciate
that if he sees me in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the toughness from Bowa and DiSarcina must have rubbed
off on Baughman. Earlier this season, Baughman took a line drive
off his face that required 60 stiches. He missed just five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys might have missed two, maybe three weeks,'' Bowa
said. ``He didn't want to come out, and who could blame him? He
wants to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't see any need to sit out,'' said Baughman. ``I
didn't suffer any serious damage or anything and my instinct is to
play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as he has accomplished in his short time in the major
leagues, Baughman admits that playing baseball at the highest level
can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say it's intimidating, that's not the right word,''
Baughman said. ``But there is a lot to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence is such a huge thing up here and I'm still trying
to build my own. It's an everyday thing. You could say I'm glad to
be here. Who wouldn't be? But the last thing I'll do is rest on it
and take it for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
