u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NL-STARS-COX     06-29 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NL-STARS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   National League All-Stars announced
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Stinson
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 COX NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves have never had a shortstop voted
onto the All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss had gone 10 seasons without a sniff of the Mid-Summer
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   What a perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss will join third baseman Chipper Jones to comprise the
starting left side of the National League infield next Tuesday,
when the 69th All-Star Game is played in Denver. St. Louis first
baseman Mark McGwire was the league's top vote-getter with 3.38
million votes, according to final NL balloting released by the
league Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the rest of the NL lineup are New York catcher Mike
Piazza, Houston second baseman Craig Biggio and outfielders Tony
Gwynn of San Diego, Barry Bonds of the San Francisco and Larry
Walker of Colorado. American League starters will be annouced this
afternoon, with pitchers to follow Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in 1970 have the Braves had two players voted to start
in the All-Star game, with Hank Aaron and Rico Carty sharing the
outfield with Willie Mays that year. Former Brave shortstop Jeff
Blauser started in the 1997 All-Star game but was subsituting for
the injured Barry Larkin of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ''They only way you feel you belong is if the fans want you,''
said Jones, who made the NL team for the third time and started in
1996 for the injured Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, who only once finished as high as second in the voting
(1989 in Oakland), drew 1.2 million votes to beat out Larkin by
162,389. Weiss was with ailing son Brody Monday night and
unavailable for comment, but around the league there was an
appreciation for an accomplishment made under duress.
</P>
<P>
   ''For this to happen in a year of crisis for his family is
rather ironic,'' said Colorado owner Jerry McMorris, a Weiss fan
from his Rockies days. ''Maybe this can be the start of a positive
period him. Most important, maybe Brody can start to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
