<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Krajicek to Sampras: Wake up
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Richard Krajicek wants to recommend a few
things to world No.1 Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to start working, to wake up,'' Krajicek said after
both reached the fourth round of Wimbledon Monday. ``He has to
start winning some tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has been in a slump most of the year, compiling just a
25-8 record with just two titles while acting lackadaisical about
his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the road to Hanover, which is the ranking Jan.
1, he is the No.10 player,'' Krajicek said. ``He knows it himself,
that he has not done so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras bristled when asked about Krajicek's opinion that
Sampras rates 10th among players this year, although his words
don't reveal that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff really doesn't faze me. I know my capabilities. I
know how I'm playing this week,'' Sampras said. ``My year has been
a little bit up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   His coach, Paul Annacone, also doesn't mind what others say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately for Pete he really only makes news when he
loses,'' Annacone said. ``The most important thing for me and for
Pete is accumulation of the 12 months. He's got plenty of time to
have a very high standard year.''
</P>
<P>
   He took another step toward a fifth Wimbledon title by advancing
to the fourth round despite the frustration of waiting for three
days to play. He defeated Thomas Enqvist 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 7-6 (7-3)
in a match originally scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long, long weekend,'' Sampras said. ``It's an
emotional roller coaster. You get up for playing, and you come off,
and you have a 20-minute delay. You come back, play a game. You
have (Sunday) off, which was kind of bizarre (that) they don't play
on middle Sunday. So you get the highs and lows.''
</P>
<P>
   Petr Korda (third seed), Goran Ivanisevic (14) and Tim Henman
(12) also advanced in the men's draw. Korda and Henman move to the
quarterfinals and Ivanisevic goes to the fourth round with
Krajicek, the ninth seed.
</P>
<P>
   Morariu loses: Corina Morariu, the St. Andrew's graduate now at
a career-high ranking of 37, made her best Grand Slam showing of
her career, despite losing to third seed Jana Novotna, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Other seeded women advancing were Lindsay Davenport (2), Monica
Seles (6), Irina Spirlea (10), Dominique Van Roost (15) and Natalie
Tauziat (16). Seles is the only player to advance to the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sampras, Novotna said rain delays upset her schedule.
``Nevertheless, after the rain delay I thought that I had started
to play much better and I have enjoyed myself very much and just
played a wonderful match.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Clarke writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
