</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIMBLEDON-WILLIAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Injury forces Serena Williams to retire from match
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Serena Williams glared at the grass on
Court 13.
</P>
<P>
   It already had felled her once, straining her left calf, and she
wasn't happy with its slickness.
</P>
<P>
   Forty minutes later, the 16-year-old decided to bag Wimbledon,
retiring from her third-round match trailing 47th-ranked Virginia
Ruano-Pascual 7-5, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The move raised eyebrows because Serena said the injury came
early in the first set, but she didn't call a trainer for several
games and didn't retire until clearly getting in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about her sister's ``loss,'' Venus Williams might
have summarized what happened best.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't lose. She retired,'' said Venus, who advanced to
the fourth round by defeating Chanda Rubin 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Serena said she had hoped the injury would improve as the match
continued, but it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at that moment in time, I could have carried on if I
wanted to, but I have to think about the future,'' said Serena, who
is ranked 20th in the world. ``I don't want to hurt myself over
something silly and be out for maybe two months just because I
didn't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Her loss eliminated the inviting sister-sister fourth-round
matchup that many had hoped to see today. Seventh seed Venus, 18,
now plays Ruano-Pascual instead.
</P>
<P>
   The elder sister leads the rivalry 2-0, but they've never played
on grass. Monica Seles was among several experts who gave Serena
the edge on this surface because she moves better and plays a more
varied game.
</P>
<P>
   Serena was disappointed not to play her sister. But when Venus
was asked whether she was disappointed or relieved, she just
smiled, saying, ``I think I can't change what happened. So I have
to go on and just make sure that I do what Serena didn't do
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Serena's worst fall on the grass came when she was up 40-30 at
1-1. She was running behind the baseline near the edge of the court
when both feet slipped out from under her. She managed to get up
and hit a few more balls before sending a lob long.
</P>
<P>
   Ruano-Pascual won the next two points to break Serena's serve
for a 2-1 lead. Serena continued to slip and slide throughout the
match but the players held serve until Serena called for a trainer
after the ninth game.
</P>
<P>
   A WTA trainer examined her left calf just below the knee and
applied tape. Serena won the next game when Ruana-Pascual had been
serving for the first set, but the Spaniard won the next eight
straight points to take the set 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Serena played well using a strong backhand slice and hitting the
lines often.
</P>
<P>
   Serena disagreed that Ruana-Pascual was a difficult opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think she played a good day (game) today,'' Serena
said. ``but I think that if I were in better shape it wouldn't have
been happening at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second set Ruana-Pascual stayed strong while Serena moved
little but didn't limp or look to be in pain. Ruana-Pascual won the
first four games before Serena held a service game for 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   As she left the court for the changeover, though, Serena told
the chair umpire she couldn't continue, which he announced.
</P>
<P>
   She then gathered her racquets and bags and walked off the court
without acknowledging her opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Ruana-Pascual looked around and shrugged, then stood up and
raised her arms. The crowd gave a quick round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot,'' Serena said. ``I never really had to quit during a
match.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rain and the late doubles match, Ruana-Pascual
was not available for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Serena and Venus also had to withdraw from doubles competition
because WTA rules prohibit players who withdraw from singles to
play doubles in the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Serena can remain in mixed doubles because the match wasn't
scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Serena expects her leg will be fine soon. ``It's already feeling
a little better,'' she said. ``I don't think (the pain) was that
intense. Just maybe a little tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Clarke writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
