u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-AGREEMENT-SPI &LR;      06-29 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-AGREEMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B.C. PREMIER BLASTS SALMON AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Canada-Washington state salmon conservation agreement is
``inequitable'' and will be ``devasting for British Columbia
fishermen,'' B.C. Premier Glen Clark said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He said in an interview that British Columbia may renew legal
action in American courts against U.S. fisheries interests. He
hinted that the province could reconsider costly investments to
restore salmon habitat if the only result is fish for Americans to
catch.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was cut out of the accord that was announced Friday. It
was negotiated by Canada's federal fisheries minister, David
Anderson, and Gov. Gary Locke.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said Monday he has discussed but not yet concluded a
similar short-term agreement with Alaska Gov. Tony Knowles.
Alaska-based fishermen have first crack at salmon bound for both
Pacific Northwest and British Columbia river systems.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Clark predicted that Canada will accept whatever Alaska
offers.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson defended the accord, under which U.S.-based
fishermen will ease pressure this year on coho salmon bound for the
Fraser River, while Canada takes measures to preserve chinook
salmon bound for Puget Sound waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fish move together, they swim together,'' Anderson said.
``If you do something to save your own salmon, you may benefit your
neighbor's stock. So be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark vowed to resist the accord, which he called ``a
travesty.'' The British Columbia government does not have authority
over fisheries. But Clark hinted that the province may seek redress
in American courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will examine any legal means available to us,'' he said.
``It may include reviving the court case we had in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The province filed suit in federal court last year, seeking
damages for alleged overfishing of B.C.-bound salmon by Alaska
fishermen. The case was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Angry British Columbia fisheries interests were talking about
more direct action. At a news conference in Victoria, they
threatened to disrupt a U.S. Navy torpedo testing range located in
Canadian waters at Nanoose Bay north of Nanaimo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to drop anchor for a little while and have a
little picnic,'' said John Radosevic, president of the United
Fishermen and Allied Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second hint of a possible hot summer on the B.C.
coast. Last month, Radosevic talked about possible delays against
passenger liners that use Vancouver as a takeoff point for cruises
to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The Anderson-Locke accord was reached after Anderson took
drastic action to save dwindling coho salmon runs of the Fraser
River, and the Skeena River in northern British Columbia. He cut
off the sport fishery for coho and curtailed both the commercial
and recreational fishing off the west coast of Vancouver Island.
</P>
<P>
   A byproduct of Canada's actions was to ease pressure on Puget
Sound chinook salmon, recently listed under the federal Endangered
Species Act. Locke was encouraged to approach Anderson with
proposals for additional conservation measures.
</P>
<P>
   Under the conservation deal, Washington will reduce by 22
percent the U.S. catch of Canadian coho. The cutback will allow an
additional 7,000 to 8,000 fish to spawn, although only at most 500
of the most endangered run in the Thompson River tributary of the
Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Canada will cut back by 50 percent its catch of
U.S.-bound chinook. The cutback will save an estimated 14,000
chinook, a quarter of them from endangered wild salmon runs, said
Curt Smitch, Locke's chief fisheries adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Canada will undertake additional conservation measures next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They agreed next spring to restrict the Georgia Strait sport
fishery, one of the plums they have left, which affects our chinook
stocks in the Nooksack and Stilliguamish rivers,'' Smitch said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said Canada needed to save its coho runs, whether or
not the U.S. wanted to join in a conservation move. ``In so doing,
we substantially improved chances of survival of your Puget Sound
chinook,'' he said. ``The governor recognized this. He made a
gesture to help us, which he was not required to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The first gesture of peace in the four-year U.S.-Canada salmon
dispute has rekindled a war of words between the British Columbia
and Canadian governments.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said his province has committed to restoring
logging-ravaged salmon habitat, only to see Canadian fishermen bear
the brunt of sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government of British Columbia is spending $150 million
(Canadian) on watershed restoration and rebuilding salmon
streams,'' he said. ``If the taxpayers are spending that amount of
money, it is hard to justify if the Americans _ particularly in
Alaska _ are simply catching the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Smitch said the state of Washington curtailed fishing for coho
and chinook long before the Canadian government took similar moves.
``We have already shut down our fishery (while) this is the first
year they've done it,'' he said. ``The consequences to the special
interests are wrenching.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the salmon war between the Canadian and British Columbia
governments, added Smitch, ``We don't understand politics up there
and we're not going to get in the middle of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the state may already be in the middle of it. U.S. and
Canadian negotiators are trying to work out an agreement to share
the relatively abundant sockeye salmon runs of the Fraser River.
Many of the salmon swim through U.S. waters en route to the
Canadian river.
</P>
<P>
   Canada offered last week to allow Washington and Oregon to catch
as mcuh as 25 percent of Fraser River sockeye _ or an estimated
1.25 million fish. Clark has denounced the offer as excessive.
Canadian fisheries officials say the premier will be to blame if
there is no agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators have until Wednesday to work out a sockeye
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran Victoria politician and conservationist, Anderson has
been on the firing line since he announced in May that stern
conservation measures were coming.
</P>
<P>
   He said Monday that while his policies have provoked furious
protests from Clark and fisheries lobbyists, the Canadian public
supports the need to protect weak salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a wide understanding,'' he said. ``The
understanding extends to fisheries interests. It does not extend to
the paid leaders of interest groups, who relish conflict. It does
not extend to the British Columbia government, which believes that
confrontation with the federal government is good politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
