<SLUG> BC-MA-LOTTERY-DISPUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD CLAIMANT APPEARS AT HEARING OVER $21 MILLION TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAINTREE _ The most confused and contentious fight in Lottery
history _ with a $21 million jackpot at stake _ took an incredible
twist Monday when a third claimant to the prize emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Bardakjian, 52, of Watertown, appeared at a hearing at
Lottery headquarters that had been scheduled to resolve the dispute
between 72-year-old Paraskeve Kantges and Nick Havan.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kantges, Bardakjian said she also telephoned in the winning
bet to Watertown Provisions, owned by Havan, along with 36 other
bets last Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   And like Kantges, Bardakjian said that when she went to the
store to pick up her tickets the next day, Havan gave her all the
tickets except the winning one.
</P>
<P>
   Havan has maintained that although Kantges may have telephoned
in the winning bet to Havan's store, she called back later to
cancel the bet and he purchased it for himself. He is appealing a
finding favor of Kantges by former Lottery executive director
Samuel M. DePhillippo.
</P>
<P>
   Bardakjian, a native of Lebanon, appeared at the hearing without
a lawyer, but accompanied by her daughter and a friend. Lottery
officials said she had filed a claim to the Mass Millions jackpot
on Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Bardakjian made an opening statement in which she said she
``jumped up'' with joy when she discovered her number had been
picked.
</P>
<P>
   She said she went to Watertown Provisions to pick up her
tickets, but Havan said she did not have the winning ticket. ``I
was so crying, I went home,'' said Bardakjian.
</P>
<P>
   Havan maintains that he, and neither Kantges nor Bardakjian are
the rightful owners of the Mass Millions ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Steadman, a retired Supeior Court judge, is hearing the
testimony and will make recommendations to the full Lottery
Commission. The dispute is likely to end up in the courts, however.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Bardakjian's appearance, Havan testified Monday that he
did not come forward and publicly claim the jackpot for several
days because he feared Kantges would cause dispute his claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she would be very upset and demand the ticket from me,
I was not ready to disclose,'' Havan testified.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges, who is scheduled to testify Tuesday, denied she
canceled the bet. She said she had played the same number daily for
years. She claims it was one of about 90 lottery bets she made that
day, but it was the only one Havan did not turn over to her.
</P>
<P>
   When Havan told two lottery officials, who came to his store
several days after the drawing that Kantges had canceled the bet.
``They looked at me like I came from Jupiter,'' Havan said
</P>
<P>
   Havan also described an earlier dispute with Kantges over loud
music.
</P>
<P>
   When Kantges asked him to turn off disco music he was playing
because it was disturbing customers, Havan replied: ``What
customers? You are the only one here.''
</P>
<P>
   `I am a customer,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You call yourself a customer. You spent an hour in the store
and bought only a head of lettuce,'' Havan said he told her.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the exchange, he said Kantges boycotted the store
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, attorney R. Robert Popeo, representing
the Lottery, tried to show that Havan lied at a earlier hearing and
at a depostion when he claimed to have a bachelor's degree in civil
engineering from Wentworth Institute of Technology. Popeo presented
an affidavit from Wentworth stating the Havan had only an
associate's degree.
</P>
<P>
   Havan insisted he had a bachelor's degree and said he had given
it to his lawyer. Popeo demanded it be produced.
</P>
<P>
   Havan's lawyer, Laurence Johnson, dramatically parried the
attack by producing both the associate's and the bachelor's degree
from his briefcase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
