<SLUG> BC-FOX-MARKETPLACE-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NEWS CORP. TO SELL SHARES IN NEW UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ News Corp. said Monday that it planned to sell to the
public as much as 20 percent of its American film, television and
sports businesses _ including 20th Century Fox, Fox Television and
the Los Angeles Dodgers _ in an initial stock offering. The sale is
aimed in large part at bolstering the price of News Corp.'s shares,
which have lagged behind those of other media giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Murdoch is putting a window on some of the more developing
assets that may not earn very much but undoubtedly will have
considerable growth,'' said David Londoner, an analyst with
Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   A sale could also help News Corp. pay down some of its $8
billion in debt. And it would give the company a new stock that it
could use to make acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to say how much 20 percent in the new company,
Fox Group, would be worth, analysts said, because the amount of
debt it would carry is not known. The businesses that make up the
Fox Group accounted for nearly $7 billion of News Corp.'s $11.2
billion in U.S. revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were enthusiastic about the planned offering, sending
the American depository receipts of News Corp. up 12 percent. The
ADRs _ each representing four shares of the Australian company _
closed up $3.5625, at $33.0625, after earlier touching a 52-week
high of $33.25.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. ADRs have been trading at about eight times cash
flow, compared with rivals Time Warner, Viacom and Walt Disney, for
example, which are trading at roughly 12 times cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's caution over News Corp. stems largely from the
fact that the company, which also owns HarperCollins, The New York
Post and newspapers in Britain and Australia, is seen as a
publishing and newspaper company as much as an entertainment
company, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is up 40 percent over the past 18 months, but that compares
badly with Time Warner at 127 percent and Viacom at 73 percent,''
said Ed Hatch of UBS Securities. ``This will let investors directly
own News Corp.'s fastest-growing and most highly valued businesses
and remind investors that News Corp. owns 80 percent of those
businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The market for new stock issues has cooled in the last month.
Still, News Corp.'s sale is expected by the end of the year, when
investors could be more receptive. More important, the move follows
several years of debt-paring by the company and could set the stage
for more acquisitions. Earlier this month, News Corp. sold TV
Guide, one of the crown jewels of its 1980s buying spree, for $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lyon, president of Institutional Capital, which manages
$12 billion and owns News Corp. preferred stock, noted that an
advantage of the Fox Group offering is that it frees News Corp. to
use the new stock for acquisitions. Analysts expect that the new
stock will trade at a higher multiple, and if that proves the case,
it would be a cheaper currency for making acquisitions. Moreover,
they note, Murdoch has always been an empire builder.
</P>
<P>
   And because News Corp. is selling only 20 percent to the public,
it will continue to be able to consolidate the Fox Group's profits
or losses at the parent company for tax purposes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As part of the deal, News Corp. is keeping its largest
money-loser _ Star-TV, its Asian cable-programming service _ at the
parent company. That operation is believed to have lost about $80
million in fiscal 1998, which ends Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Its more recent start-up operation, Fox News, which is still
losing money _ about $75 million a year, by Lyon's estimate _ will
be part of the new venture, along with Fox's 50 percent stake in a
host of regional sports services.
</P>
<P>
   Investors do not know the full value of the sports networks
because they are part of a joint venture that is 50 percent owned
by Liberty Media, a cable-programming company. Neither parent
reports the joint-venture numbers separately from other operations.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch estimates that the film studio, the television
production company and the 22 television stations are likely to
have 1999 cash flow of about $1 billion. If the company does trade
at a 12 multiple, like other media companies, 20 percent of that
would be $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox's recent record has been stamped by the huge
success of ``Titanic,'' the $200 million budget for which was
financed by Fox and Paramount, which put in $65 million. So far the
film has grossed over $1 billion worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Its new release, ``Dr. Doolittle,'' opened unexpectedly strong
over the weekend, taking in $29 million at the box office.
``Bulworth'' was a disappointment, but ``Hope Floats'' and ``The X
Files'' have been somewhat successful. Still, forecasting cash flow
from the unpredictable film business is always difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
