<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHYSIO-MERGE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHYSIO-CONTROL IS MERGING WITH MEDTRONIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a merger that could one day make life-saving defibrillating
devices available for home use by people at risk for heart attacks,
Redmond, Wash.-based Physio-Control Corp. has joined forces with
Minneapolis-based medical giant Medtronic Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, which is not expected to result in any layoffs for
Physio's 950 employees, could mean bigger markets for both players.
</P>
<P>
   Physio-Control is the market leader in automated external
defibrillators, devices that shock the heart back into normal
rhythm using an external shock applied through paddles. Medtronic
is the world's leading maker of pacemakers and other implantable
heart devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good move for both companies,'' said Dr. David Gruber,
a physician and stock analyst with Vector Securities International
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The more patients who survive sudden cardiac arrest, the more
candidates there are for Medtronic's implantable devices, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The $538-million stock merger gives Physio-Control the financial
resources to put its life-saving instruments into the hands of more
``first responders,'' those people that arrive first when someone
suffers a sudden heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   First-responders could be anyone from security guards in office
buildings, to family members at home with heart patients.
</P>
<P>
   The market for external defibrillators has traditionally been in
hospitals and emergency response vehicles, but advances in
technology have made it possible for even lay people to administer
the life-saving shocks.
</P>
<P>
   Physio-Control, which does about $173 million in sales with all
its product lines, has sold between 15,000 and 20,000 of its
Lifepak 500 devices for use by first-responders. But that only
scratches the surface of a market analysts estimate could be worth
in excess of $425 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're poised with the technology, but what has to happen is
the infrastructure to deploy it,'' said Richard Martin chairman and
chief executive officer of Physio-Control. ``By virtue of this
merger, we'll be able to accelerate the development of that
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   The devices could one day be used anywhere people gather, or
emergency treatment might be needed, such as police cars, stadiums,
schools, commerical airlines, hotels and office buildings.
Eventually, it might also be used in homes for patients at high
risk for coronary artery disease.
</P>
<P>
   The survival rate for people who suffer sudden cardiac arrest
outside a hospital is currently less than 5 percent, but it's
highly time dependent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed is critical,'' Gruber said.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden cardiac arrest is usually caused by ventricular
fibrillation, which is when the heart muscle starts quivering and
fails to pump blood to the brain and vital organs. The chance of
survival drops about 10 percent for every minute before the patient
can be ``defibrillated'' or shocked back to a normal rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   There are between 350,000 and 400,000 deaths from sudden cardiac
arrest each year in the United States and about 1 million
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association is pushing to increase the
survival rate from such heart attacks to 25 percent within the next
decade, through increased use of automated external defibrillators
and better public education.
</P>
<P>
   News of the merger sent Medtronic and Physio stock spiking
upward. Medtronic stock closed Monday at $115, up $3. Physio stock
closed at $26.25, up $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the merger, Physio-Control shareholders will
receive $27.50 _ a 20 percent premium over Friday's close _ in the
form of Medtronic stock for each share of Physio-Control they hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a positive development for Physio and its employees,''
said Andrew Jay, analyst with Bankers Trust New York.
</P>
<P>
   The deal follows another recent acquisition in the heart market.
Last December, Hewlett-Packard Co. bought out Seattle-based
Heartstream, which also makes automated external defibrillators.
</P>
<P>
   The Physio-Control merger was unrelated to that acquisition,
analysts said. It grew out of an inquiry from Medtronic, which has
a history of growing through mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Physio-Control, which was founded in 1955 and is one of the
Seattle area's largest medical instrument makers, had been looking
at acquisitions of its own to try to find
</P>
<P>
   ways to expand its markets, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Merging with Medtronic, which has strong international sales,
will also help build Physio's market overseas, analysts said.
Medtronic, which has about 13,500 employees worldwide, does about
$3 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   The merger isn't expected to affect Physio-Control's
manufacturing facilities in Redmond. About 70 percent of the
company's employees work on the Eastside.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two companies' products are complementary and don't
overlap, there will not be any consolidation, said Art Collins,
president and chief operating officer of Medtronic. If the merger
is approved, Martin will report to Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Physio-Control already has done much of the basic streamlining
that frequently accompanies mergers, Collins said. ``The company
has been operating profitably and very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
