u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKWELL-CHIPS-NYT &LR;      06-29 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKWELL-CHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKWELL TO CUT 3,800 JOBS AND SPIN OFF CHIP UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rockwell International Corp.'s transformation to
commercial electronics from the military business suffered a
setback Monday when the company announced that it would spin off
its semiconductor division to shareholders, cut 3,800 jobs and take
a pretax charge of $625 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell, which made the B-1 bomber and the Space Shuttle, had
been counting on the electronics business, which it saw as fast
growing and glamorous, to carry it into the future. Rockwell had
sold its military and aerospace businesses to Boeing Co. in 1996
for $3.2 billion and spun off its auto parts business last year
into a publicly traded company, Meritor Automotive Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But while fast-growing, electronics, particularly
semiconductors, can be extremely volatile. Rockwell, which is based
in Costa Mesa, Calif., had been buffeted by plunging prices and
slower than expected sales growth for personal computer modems, for
which it is a major supplier of chips.
</P>
<P>
   Losses in the semiconductor division and pressure from
shareholders led Rockwell to conclude that it did not have the
stomach after all for boom and bust cycles and that the chip
business did not mesh that well with its other, somewhat more
predictable, businesses _ industrial automation equipment and
avionics.
</P>
<P>
   ``These really are different businesses,'' Don H. Davis,
chairman and chief executive, said today in an interview. Asked why
Rockwell had not seen that a year ago, he pointed to the modem
market. ``We saw prices drop significantly more than we ever
thought they would at the time and that changes the dynamics of the
whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the losses in its chip division, Rockwell's
largest business, it is experiencing flat sales, in part because of
the economic problems in Asia. While its avionics business remained
strong, Rockwell said it would report lower than expected profits
for the third fiscal quarter, which ends Tuesday, the second
consecutive quarter in which it has had earnings below estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the special charge, Davis said, earnings for the
quarter were expected to be 30 cents a share, including the
semiconductor business. But counting only continuing operations,
earnings will be 45 cents a share compared with 56 cents in last
year's third quarter. Analysts had expected earnings of about 68
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for continuing operations will be about $1.7 billion, up 5
percent, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year, the company expected earnings a share from
continuing operations of $2.30 compared with last year's $2.12, on
sales of about $6.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the sluggish earnings, Davis, a company veteran
who took over as chief executive last October and as chairman in
February, Monday announced a major corporate overhaul, which he
predicted will result in pretax savings of $100 million in fiscal
1999 and $200 million annually starting in 2001. Investors greeted
the announcements with cautious optimism as the stock, which has
fallen much of this year, climbed 56.25 cents, to $49.
</P>
<P>
   Lior Bregman, an analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer, said that
Rockwell resisted divesting its chip business at a time when it
could have been sold for a high price. Now, ``they are doing it out
of weakness rather than strength.'' He also speculated that the
avionics or automation business might be divested at some point in
the future because they did not seem to fit together well either.
</P>
<P>
   The worker cutbacks, primarily in the automation business,
amounted to more than 9 percent of the 41,000 Rockwell employees
not in the semiconductor business. The chip division, which has
7,000 employees, is likely to have its own revamping later, though
officials said there will not be too many layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The $625 million charge included $275 million of intangible
asset writeoffs and goodwill mainly related to the company's
Reliance Electric motor business and $160 million for severance
costs.
</P>
<P>
   The new semiconductor company, which does not yet have a name,
will have revenues of about $1.3 billion, making it a midsized chip
company.
</P>
<P>
   The chip division had been a part of Rockwell for about 30
years. But it became a significant part of the company only in the
last few years, with the divestiture of the aerospace and auto
business, and with the boom in the sale of modems because of the
popularity of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in the semiconductor division tripled from $530 million in
fiscal 1993 to $1.59 billion in fiscal 1996 before leveling off in
1997. Modem chips account for about half the division's sales.
</P>
<P>
   But consumers had been hesitant to buy modems because of a
format battle that erupted last year between Rockwell and a rival,
U.S. Robotics, which is now part of the 3Com Corp. Even though they
have now agreed on a standard for the new modems, operating at 56
kilobits a second, sales have not fully recovered and prices have
remained weak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
