<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-NYT &LR;      06-29 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL SUCCESSES IN KOSOVO WORRY EUROPEANS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The surprising strength of ethnic Albanian rebels
fighting for independence in the Serbian province of Kosovo is
putting strains on international efforts to keep the violence from
spreading, European and American diplomats said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a major shift of emphasis after weeks of European and
American threats to use NATO military power to stop Serbia's
attacks on the rebels, the 15 countries of the European Union
called on the Albanians on Monday to reject ``violence and acts of
terrorism,'' too, and commit themselves to a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
   European Union foreign ministers meeting in Luxembourg also
repeated European and American threats to use force if the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, continued to flout international
demands to halt his attacks and withdraw military and police units
that have inflicted heavy casualties on civilians.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany, a key player in efforts to keep the fighting from
spreading, said it was no longer insisting on withdrawal of Serbian
troops from the combat zones as a condition for resuming talks
between the rebels and Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were suspended after the Serbian offensive began early
last month. As recently as two weeks ago, a key demand on Milosevic
for getting the talks restarted was withdrawal of security units
used against ethnic Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The change in emphasis reflects the rebels' rapid seizure of
more than a third of Kosovo's territory, partly with arms and
soldiers moved in from Albania, according to European officials.
</P>
<P>
   French and German diplomats said that they were taken by
surprise by separate meetings last week with people claiming to be
representatives of the Kosovo Liberation Army by two American
special envoys, Richard Holbrooke and Robert Gelbard.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable American officials said that Holbrooke's decision
to talk with the Kosovo fighters last week reflected the rapidly
changing military situation there. ``The Europeans didn't act fast
enough to get Milosevic to stop the attacks, so the rebels poured
troops and arms in,'' a U.S. official said. ``Now we have a new
situation to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   An official in Bonn said on Monday that his country would push
the United States, Russia and the other European countries
monitoring the situation in Kosovo to make clear to both the rebels
and Milosevic when the international group next meets in Bonn on
July 8 that the only real condition now for restarting talks should
be a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep insisting on a Serbian troop withdrawal before
political talks resume, that could lead to a mass exodus of the
Serbian population,'' the official said. Reports from Kosovo say
the rebels have kidnapped and fired on Serb civilians there and
have tried to drive them out of rebel-controlled territory.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the European foreign ministers made their most direct
appeal yet to rebel military leaders to stop the fighting. Even now
they prefer to deal with the ethnic Albanian leader, Ibrahim
Rugova, who supported a nonviolent approach in Kosovo while
fighting was raging in nearby Bosnia. But, European diplomats said,
Rugova's authority has been undermined as fighting spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those in a leadership role in the Kosovar Albanian
community should unite responsibly in making clear their commitment
to dialogue and a peaceful resolution of the problems of Kosovo,
and their rejection of violence and acts of terrorism,'' the
foreign ministers said.
</P>
<P>
   They also reminded both the rebel leaders and Rugova that Europe
was opposed to independence for Kosovo, instead supporting ``a
large degree of autonomy'' for it within Yugoslavia. Although 90
percent of Kosovo's population is ethnic Albanian, it is
historically Serbian territory. Serbia dominates what remains of
Yugoslavia, and Milosevic, a former president of Serbia, remains
its paramount leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, unsettled by the American meetings with rebel
military leaders, have also taken initiatives of their own. After a
meeting between Rugova and a German foreign ministry official,
Wolfgang Ischinger, in Bonn last Thursday, Rugova agreed that he
could start talks with the Belgrade leaders again provided there
was a cease-fire, a German diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Russia, France, Italy, Britain, and Germany,
joined by Japan and Canada, agreed in London on June 12 that Serbia
could find itself threatened with NATO military action if it did
not call off the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia is not yet ready to let the U.N. Security Council,
where it has a veto, give NATO the go-ahead. And France, a NATO
ally, has indicated it might block military action by the alliance
unless the Security Council gave its approval.
</P>
<P>
   France joined other NATO defense ministers early this month in
calling for military contingency plans for a range of operations,
including air strikes against Serbian strategic targets in Kosovo
and beyond, to step up pressure on Milosevic to call off the
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
