<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-840&AMP;ADD     06-29 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGUING ATTORNEY-CLIENT PRIVILEGE, STARR AND WHITE HOUSE CHANGE
COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The issue of the potential impeachment of President
Clinton served as the backdrop Monday to a historic legal fight
over the attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from the independent counsel, the White House
argued that the potential impeachment of the president made the
privilege a crucial matter, while while Kenneth Starr argued that
the possibility of impeachment was too remote to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   While the competing views put forward by the two sides in a
federal appeals court hearing Monday on the immediacy of
impeachment appeared at first-blush to be counter-intuitive, they
made sense in the framework of the legal fight that has arisen in
the Lewinsky inquiry over the parameters of the lawyer-client
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The White House maintained that because Starr had recently told
the Supreme Court that he might file an impeachment report to
Congress, President Clinton was entitled to receive confidential
advice from his government lawyers in the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But in an unusual twist, Starr walked away from what he had said
about an impeachment report, telling the three-judge panel that the
president was not entitled to keep the advice confidential because
impeachment was too remote an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The case focuses on the issue of whether Clinton can receive
confidential advice from government lawyers in a criminal inquiry.
Since both the White House and the independent counsel maintained
Monday that Clinton could use such lawyers to defend himself in an
impeachment inquiry in Congress, the argument focused in part on
the likelihood and timing of such a prospect.
</P>
<P>
   The White House lawyer, W. Neil Eggleston, contended that since
Starr had raised the prospect of an impeachment proceeding, the
president had every right to rely on government lawyers to defend
himself, as a matter of the constitutional principle of separation
of powers.
</P>
<P>
   As it became clear in the argument that the president stood on
firmer legal ground in a congressional inquiry, rather than in
grand jury proceeding, Starr told the appeals court there was no
need to consider impeachment issues. Instead, Starr urged the
judges to focus on whether they really wanted to put their
endorsement on the White House's position, establishing a rule that
every federal government lawyer would have a legal obligation to
forward evidence of a crime to investigators, except for White
House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The case arose when the president appealed a lower court
decision ordering one of his closest aides, deputy White House
counsel Bruce Lindsey, to answer questions before a federal grand
jury about conversations that he had with Clinton and other
witnesses, including Vernon Jordan, who helped Ms. Lewinsky to find
a job in New York. Clinton, Jordan and Ms. Lewinsky are involved in
the independent counsel's investigation trying to determine if
there was an attempt to cover up the President's relationship with
the former White House intern when her deposition was sought in the
sexual harassment lawsuit brought by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In the public phase of Monday's hearing, the judges sharply
questioned both sides, invoking lessons from the Watergate and
Iran-Contra scandals but giving few hints about their positions.
The panel, which also held a closed hearing on the more sensitive
grand jury aspects of the appeal, consisted of A. Raymond Randolph,
Judith W. Rogers and David S. Tatel. To each lawyer, Tatel asked
whether the President had any special rights to confidential advice
from White House lawyers in impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Eggleston, the president's top lawyer for privilege issues,
replied that ``in a run-up to possible impeachment,'' it was beyond
question as a matter of Constitutional law that the president
should be able to rely on the confidential advice of government
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independent counsel has said in his Supreme Court brief
that a referral of impeachment is certainly under consideration,''
Eggleston said. ``Impeachment involves an official function. It
would be incumbent on the President to defend himself if he
believes it appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Starr replied that the prospect of impeachment was too
remote a possibility to be considered by the court, and that the
judges should only focus on the fact that the White House was
seeking to limit grand jury testimony, not testimony in a
congressional proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   In a concession that surprised some White House lawyers, Starr
told the judges that government lawyers ``could actually represent
the president in an impeachment setting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's not where we are,'' Starr hastened to add. ``It is
premature for this court to look down the road and look at
impeachment. It is beyond the compass of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The position of the office of the president misunderstands the
vision of what it means to be a government lawyer,'' Starr told the
three-judge panel, citing a federal law that requires federal
employees to report any evidence of a crime to the attorney
general. ``If there is wrongdoing, it must be exposed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Starr first raised the prospect of an impeachment proceeding
four weeks ago. In a brief asking the Supreme Court to bypass the
appeals court and take the case on an expedited basis, Starr wrote
of the urgency of a final decision so that he could quickly proceed
with possible indictments and possibly send an impeachment report
to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The court turned down Starr's request and suggested that the
appeals court consider the matter quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Under the independent counsel law, Starr must report any
``substantial and credible information'' that ``may constitute
grounds for impeachment'' to the House. The Constitution then gives
the House the authority to decide whether to recommend an
impeachment trial, which would be held in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments over impeachment and the attorney-client privilege
were unusual in part because the Justice Department has broken
ranks with the White House, and in a friend of the court brief,
taken an intermediate position between that of the president and
the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has argued there is no privilege for government lawyers to
withhold evidence from a federal grand jury. The White House argued
that there is an absolute privilege. The Justice Department, in a
brief signed by Attorney General Janet Reno, asserts that there
should be a qualified privilege which a federal judge should
balance against the needs of investigators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
