u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-1STLD-WRITETHR     06-29 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIANS UNLEASH SERIES OF HEAVY ATTACKS AGAINST ALBANIAN
SEPARATISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct town's location in 8th graf; south is correct)  (ART ADV.: a map locating Belacevac is being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
212 556-4204.) 
(ps) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELACEVAC, Yugoslavia _ Thousands of Serb special police units
and troops, backed by artillery and tanks, opened a series of
attacks against separatist rebel positions on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy armored personnel carriers unleashed volleys at trenches
and checkpoints held by lightly armed Kosovo Liberation Army
guerrillas in the mining town of Belacevac, six miles west of
Pristina, the provincial capital. Serb gunners also attacked
Lapushnik, where rebels have barricaded the main road leading from
Pristina to Pec.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks and jeeps, packed with soldiers in green-camouflage
battle dress sped to the two fronts.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbians reported that an 8-year-old ethnic Albanian boy had
been killed and a man wounded. More than 8,000 people were forced
to flee their homes in Belacevac and take refuge in nearby woods.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats say the attacks end the latest diplomatic
effort to negotiate a cease-fire and could see the fighting spread
to new areas, including Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs believe this is the final offensive,'' said a
Western military observer. ``But this is the third attempt since
March by the Serbian security forces to wipe out the rebels. Each
attempt has only brought an escalation of the fighting. So will
this one.''
</P>
<P>
   From the top of a 50-foot slag heap at the southern edge of
Belacevac on Monday drifting clouds of charcoal-colored smoke could
be seen spiraling up from burning houses in the neighboring village
of Hade. Armored vehicles could also be seen moving swiftly along
the town's deserted streets. Rifle fire and mortar rounds
reverberated across hay fields.
</P>
<P>
   At a Serb police checkpoint about a mile outside Lapushnik, a
hamlet a mile south of Negrovce, houses were afire and explosions
could be heard. A barricade of cars and cement blocks at Lapushnik,
manned by rebel fighters with rocket-propelled grenades, blocks the
road to Pec and has cut off the Serb-held town of Kijevo for seven
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   American envoy Richard Holbrooke, who spent four days last week
trying to broker a cease-fire in Kosovo, called Kijevo ``the most
dangerous place in Europe,'' warning that a Serb effort to push
into the town and free it from rebel encirclement could lead to ``a
general war.''
</P>
<P>
   The police closed the main road from Pristina to Pec soon after
dawn. Policemen on the road to Belacevac near Obilic, northwest of
Pristina, were joined by an angry collection of heavily armed Serb
civilians, many of whom said they had been pushed out of their
homes by the rebels in recent days. The Serbs, who jeered foreign
reporters, appeared to be gathering to enter the mining town after
the assault by the military and the police. Streams of residents
were fleeing the fighting on foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is war,'' said one elderly woman, who did not want to give
her name, as she clutched a small nylon bag with a few belongings.
``We have become Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Belgrade to make a push against rebel positions
follows efforts by the United States to broker a cease-fire accord
and halt the fighting that erupted in the Serbian province in
March. But neither Belgrade nor the rebel army, which controls
about 40 percent of the province, were willing to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has threatened to carry out air strikes if Belgrade does
not withdraw its forces and end attacks, but there was no immediate
indication that this latest assault would lead to intervention.
There is also a concern among diplomats that continued fighting
could set off a wider regional war that would draw in Albania and
Macedonia, which has a restive ethnic Albanian minority.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In March, Serb forces surrounded an area known as the Drenica
triangle where rebel bands, numbering no more than a couple of
hundred, operated with impunity. The special police shelled
villages like Prekaz into rubble and killed over 80 people, more
than half of them women, small children, and the elderly. The
attack produced a province-wide rebellion, ending the peaceful
resistance movement led by the ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim
Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of fighters have since flocked to the rebel movement
and tons of weapons and ammunition have been ferried by pack horses
over the border from northern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago Serb forces moved again in force against villages
along the border with northern Albania, pounding homes into rubble
and displacing some 80,000 people. Streams of refugees fled into
Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. ambassador to Montenegro, Christopher Hill, who is
trying to negotiate between the ethnic Albanian leadership and
Belgrade, met on Monday with the president of Yugoslavia, Slobodan
Milosevic, and with ethnic Albanian leaders in Pristina. Hill and
Holbrooke had hoped to get the rebels to remove barricades along
main roads and use the move to hold off a massive Serb assault. The
rebels, however, refused to consider the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that after the rebels suffer some serious losses
they will be in the mood to negotiate,'' said a Western diplomat,
``but for now they seem to want to fight. There is little we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   There were signs over the past few days that a huge
counter-insurgency sweep was being planned. The Serbs, who are
spending over $2 million a day to keep forces deployed in Kosovo,
moved about 50 tracked armored vehicles into positions around
Belacevac on Saturday morning and have deployed hundreds of
reinforcements in the province. Serb soldiers have also set up
anti-aircraft batteries around the airport and on hilltops in case
of a NATO air attack.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, tense groups of Serb soldiers fired at a
barricade made out of old, rusted mine equipment set up and manned
by rebel soldiers in Belacevac.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels took over the huge open pit coal mine last week and
kidnapped several Serb mine workers, halting all mine production.
</P>
<P>
   Belacevac and a neighboring mine, Dobroselo, provide the coal to
power two massive electric generating plants at Obilic. The plants
supply power to Kosovo, parts of Serbia and Macedonia. Huge
conveyor belts, now idle, channeled the coal to the plant from
Belacevac.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure of the mine was one of the most flagrant challenges
to Belgrade's authority. It saw guerrillas, often in berets and
black uniforms, checking documents of passing cars within a half a
mile of a sprawling army base with the city skyline behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there is an attack coming,'' said a bearded rebel on
Sunday night, ``and we have moved our forces into the hills to
respond. Don't worry, the war is far from over. This is only the
beginning. We will see you in Pristina.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
