<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2827 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-MEXICO-GERMANY-HN     06-29 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MEXICO-GERMANY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MONTPELLIER, France _ Suddenly and shockingly, Mexico found itself
in the most uncomfortable and precarious position it had known in
this World Cup tournament.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was winning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the attacked, not the prideful attacker. Thanks to yet
another memorable goal by Luis Hernandez in the opening moments of
Monday's second half at Stade de la Mosson, Mexico was the team in
control, and mighty Germany was forced to the brink of elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world thought we would be overwhelmed,'' Mexican
goalkeeper Jorge Campos said. ``We had the Germans running. We had
them running in circles.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, Germany started running like the smooth machine the
world has come to know.
</P>
<P>
   The team that prides itself on never being denied wasn't, as
veterans Juergen Klinsmann and Oliver Bierhoff each punched in a
well-placed late goal and knocked out Mexico 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in with high expectations, and it looked like we would
achieve them,'' said Mexican coach Manuel Lapuente, whose team came
from behind in all three of its first-round World Cup games. ``But
just when we were flying, they clipped our wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Klinsmann, in his third World Cup tournament, finally broke
through Campos' great game in goal and set the large flag-waving
contingent of German fans partying in the 75th minute. After
Mexican defender Pavel Pardo misplayed an entry pass by the
Germans, failing to clear the ball as Klinsmann charged forward,
Klinsmann popped in the tying score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only mistake we made in front of goal,'' said
Campos, who otherwise had probably his best game of the tournament,
knocking away at least two first-half shots that looked like
certain goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not an easy game for us,'' German coach Berti Vogts
said. ``Mexico had an excellent plan, and their players gained
confidence when they got the 1-0 lead. But our first goal got us
going.''
</P>
<P>
   And the second goal, which came more because of Bierhoff's
excellence in the air than a mistake in the Mexican defense, came
in the 86th minute, sending the Germans to the quarterfinals and a
game against the winner of today's Romania-Croatia match.
</P>
<P>
   Bierhoff made a terrific play on the game-winner, giving Campos
no chance as he ripped a header in off a well-placed long pass from
Ulf Kirsten.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock when Mexico scored and we were losing, but we
tried to keep the fighting spirit,'' Klinsmann said. ``We never
lost confidence, but we were in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Vogts: ``I've played against Mexico quite a bit in my
career. I knew what to expect from them. I knew they would be very
tough. But I have never seen a Mexican team play with that kind of
passion. I never want to go through that kind of game again.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mexico, the only questions after the long, entertaining game
were what-ifs.
</P>
<P>
   After Hernandez gave his team the surprising lead in the 47th
minute when he blasted in the goal off a nice pass from Cuahtemoc
Blanco, Mexico had at least two more legitimate chances to score.
Just one more goal would have given Mexico the luxury of dropping
into defense to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   The best opportunity came in the 65th minute, when Jesus
Arellano made a terrific sprint through the middle of the German
defense and fired a shot that hit the post. The ball ricocheted to
Hernandez, who had an open net to his right but wheeled and hit the
ball directly at German goalkeeper Andreas Kopke.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you turn and shoot, it's just reaction,'' Hernandez said.
``If I would have reacted differently, I would have hit it to the
open side. I just hit it to the wrong place. I think if it was 2-0,
we would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mexican team goes home after clearly exceeding all
pre-tournament expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very sad in the locker room after the game because it
was a game we could have won. But we knew we did everything we
could,'' Mexico's Luis Garcia said. ``Germany always is going to
fight to the end, and they did that today. They went 90 minutes and
won it at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hernandez, one of the surprise stars of France '98 with
four goals scored: ``We leave with pride, but we don't leave
satisfied. If we had the trophy, we would be satisfied.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
