</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CLINTON, STARR PLAYING SAME GAME ... WAITING FOR MONICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CLINTON-STARR) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BENNETT c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year ago Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel, insisted that he was not out to dig into
President Clinton's ``personal life.'' That, of course, was then.
</P>
<P>
   Before a grand jury last week, one of Starr's prosecutors asked
Sidney Blumenthal, a senior White House aide, if he had ever
discussed with Hillary Rodham Clinton whether her husband had a
``sex addiction,'' Blumenthal said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By Blumenthal's account, the jurors, who have no doubt heard a
great deal of titillating testimony by now, did not bat an eye at
the question, to which, he said, he answered no.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's new interest, if not its intensity, can be explained. A
year ago, after all, he had surely never heard of Monica Lewinsky
and had no inkling of the accusations of perjury and obstruction of
justice that would transform his green-eyeshades investigation of
an Ozarks real estate deal into a tabloid television sensation.
</P>
<P>
   More than five months after the Lewinsky accusations were
disclosed, head-snapping and sometimes baffling swerves in
direction have become the norm in this investigation, as well as in
the press accounts of it. Even the broadest contours of the story,
as publicly glimpsed in grand jury appearances and press accounts,
keep shifting.
</P>
<P>
   The recent spate of news accounts has trended in the president's
favor, but those most closely involved in the investigation and the
president's defense tend to roll their eyes at incremental press
reports. For them, only one game really matters here now.
``Everybody's waiting for Monica,'' is how one of the president's
allies summed it up recently, referring to nervous anticipation
over what agreement for testimony she might negotiate with
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   No one outside Starr's office knows if his investigation is
floundering or bounding ahead, although it is easy enough to spot a
former White House official or a former prosecutor on television
describing it one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Linda Tripp, the famously hidden hand on the
``record'' button, has her first day here before the grand jurors,
who have already listened to the 20 hours of covert tapes she made
of her conversations with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes, several press accounts suggest, demonstrate that
Clinton tried to obstruct justice by covering up his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky, getting her a job in New York among other
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Or else they demonstrate no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News &AMP; World Report said last week that Ms. Tripp's tapes
might actually protect the president from charges of obstruction,
rather than implicate him as Newsweek had previously reported. U.S.
News said it had ``reviewed the contents'' of tapes suggesting that
Ms. Lewinsky was hoping for help in finding a job from Clinton two
months before she was subpoenaed to testify for Paula Jones' sexual
misconduct suit. It was that subpoena that supposedly motivated
Clinton to find her a job, to keep her on his side.
</P>
<P>
   As the magazine's publicity people went to work (even some
lawyers here have publicity people now, by the way), Washington
began buzzing with the supposition that Starr was having trouble
proving his obstruction case. But the magazine's article did not
quite deliver the goods. Newsweek, U.S. News sniffed, had had
access to only 90 minutes of the tapes. But U.S. News did not get
much more. It said that it had ``reviewed the contents'' of
``roughly two hours of new tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves roughly 16.5 hours of tapes whose contents have gone
unreviewed by any publication. Goodness knows what Ms. Lewinsky may
have said. As U.S. News acknowledged in its report, the two hours
of tapes that it reviewed were silent on some of the central issues
of obstruction, such as who wrote the ``talking points'' that Ms.
Lewinsky is said to have provided to Ms. Tripp to coach potential
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the article did provide revelations, of a sort. U.S. News
said the source of its portion of tapes ``had no ideological or
commercial motivation to favor the president, the independent
counsel or any other party in the dispute.'' In the news business,
that is known as ``burying the lead.'' In this city of inveterate
ax-grinders, the discovery of such a person with ties to the
Lewinsky imbroglio would have made a compelling man-bites-dog
headline.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton tried to obstruct justice is not the only issue
that is being regularly reinterpreted, or guessed at. There is also
the matter of what kind of sex he and Ms. Lewinsky had, if any.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Dale Young, a businesswoman from Scarsdale, N.Y., who
is a friend of Ms. Lewinsky and her mother, Marcia Lewis, paid a
visit to the grand jury here in response to a subpoena. She
provided an account of conversations she had had with Ms. Lewinsky
about the president that was reported this week by Newsweek and
confirmed by her lawyer, John Verni _ who dryly observed Monday
that he now understood what this ``media frenzy'' was that he kept
hearing about.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Young concluded from a conversation with Ms. Lewinsky that
she had had an intimate relationship with Clinton that amounted to
foreplay and nothing more, Verni confirmed. Both Ms. Lewinsky and
Clinton have denied a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Young's version is a far cry from some of the early reports
about sex in the Oval Office. But it is of course hearsay, and not
definitive.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, her testimony does not seem to have deflected
Starr from his inquiry into the president's sexual behavior and
attitudes, judging from Blumenthal's account of his testimony.
Starr's office did not respond to a phone message today but in the
past has declined to comment on Blumenthal's testimony or any
other.
</P>
<P>
   In two recent visits to the grand jury, Blumenthal said, he was
asked, ``Does the president believe that oral sex is sex?'' and
``Does the president's religion include sexual intercourse?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
