<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENMAN UPLIFTS LOCALS; SERENA WILLIAMS BAILS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Tim Henman kept the hopes of the British
brotherhood alive and well Monday by reaching the quarterfinal
round at Wimbledon for the third consecutive year with a smooth
upset of sixth-seeded Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   But sisterhood turned solitary when Serena Williams succumbed to
a leg injury and left it to the seventh-seeded Venus to forge ahead
alone.
</P>
<P>
   She called it ``those slipping blues at Wimbledon,'' but the
16-year-old Serena Williams was not singing a torch song. She was
making her excuse for bailing out against Virginia Ruano Pascual of
Spain after the rain-slicked lawn of Court 13 behaved more like a
banana peel.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Williams sister, whose Wimbledon debut was supposed
to feature a much ballyhooed Round of 16 confrontation with her
18-year-old sister, strained her left calf muscle midway through
the first set of what turned out to be a 7-5, 4-1 victory for the
astonished Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
   Though Williams later admitted she could have completed the
match, she opted to default just after improving a 4-0 second-set
deficit by holding serve. And then, instead of plopping herself and
her bandaged leg in her changeover chair, she sauntered over to the
umpire and announced that she was through for the day.
</P>
<P>
   The 47th-ranked Ruano Pascual did not realize what had
transpired until the crowd began to clap and drift away. At that
point she stood up, gave a sheepish shrug and raised her arms to
celebrate a strange victory that sent her into a Round of 16 date
with the other Williams sister.
</P>
<P>
   Ruano Pascual later said it was the first time she had won _ or
lost _ a match in which her opponent failed to shake her hand in
acknowledgment. Williams said the oversight was not intentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, I forgot,'' she said. ``I never had to quit during a
match before.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the 24-year-old Ruano Pascual, who converted four of five
break opportunities and racked up winners on 19 of her 22 forays to
the net, was obviously more of an all-court player than Williams
anticipated, the teen-ager denied that she was outplayed or
outclassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She played pretty good today, but if I was in better shape, it
wouldn't have been happening at all,'' Williams said. ``I could
have carried on if I wanted to, but I have to think about the
future. In the future I definitely see myself as one of the
champions. I don't want to hurt myself over something silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to be pretty excited about facing each other
again,'' she said of facing her older sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to give something exciting to England for once,''
she said jokingly, apparently unaware that between Henman's 6-3,
6-7 (3-7), 6-3, 6-2 triumph against Rafter, the U.S. Open champion,
and the British soccer team's second-round stand just across the
English Channel in the World Cup, that the home nation has all the
excitement it can stand.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Serena Williams, whose future is ahead of her,
third-seeded Petr Korda, who finally won a Grand Slam title this
year at the Australian Open, is 30 and less assured of his
tomorrows. That is why Korda soldiered on Monday evening despite
taking a slip on Court 2 that caused him to sprain his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Leading John Van Lottum of the Netherlands, 6-3, 6-4, 5-5, when
he fell and did an inadvertent rendition of the splits, Korda had
the offending ankle taped up and hung on for a 6-3, 6-4, 7-6 (7-4)
victory that sent him into the quarterfinals against the
12th-seeded Henman.
</P>
<P>
   It took Pete Sampras, the defending champion, three days and
four rain delays to do it, but he arrived in the fourth round with
a 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 7-6 (7-3) ouster of Thomas Enqvist of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who began the match with six consecutive aces on
Saturday afternoon and wound up with 29, said this year's grim
weather has put everybody ``on an emotional roller coaster.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras figures to encounter minimal resistance from his
next opponent, Sebastien Grosjean, a 117th-ranked French qualifier
who reached the Round of 16 by ignoring the near three-hour rain
delay that interrupted play in the third set of his 6-0, 7-6
(10-8), 6-2 upset of 16th-seeded Felix Mantilla of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams advanced to the fourth round without complication
by overpowering Chanda Rubin, 6-3, 6-4, and said she is convinced
she can win this Slam, particularly with Serena out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serena is definitely the toughest player out there,'' Venus
Williams said. ``She didn't lose. She retired. I have to go on and
just make sure I do what Serena didn't do today. I'm definitely at
the point where I can do this now.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Goran Ivanisevic, seeded 14th and convinced his career is on
the mend, used 44 aces to overwhelm Daniel Vacek, 6-7 (6-8), 7-6
(7-4), 6-3, 6-4. ``If I keep my mind and play like this, I can beat
anybody here,'' said the Croat, a two-time finalist, who next plays
Todd Martin, a two-time semifinalist.
</P>
<P>
   _ There were no surprises among the top-seeded women who
performed Monday. Second-seeded Lindsay Davenport reached the
quarterfinal opposite 16th-seeded Nathalie Tauziat with a 6-1, 6-0
demolition of Spain's Magui Serna, and sixth-seeded Monica Seles
earned a quarterfinal clash with unseeded Natasha Zvereva by
dispatching last year's Wimbledon nemesis, 14th-seeded Sandrine
Testud, 6-3, 6-2. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
