<SLUG> BC-NBA-LOCKOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA TO BEGIN LOCKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes issues sidebar)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA will close down at midnight Tuesday night and not
re-open for business until its labor problem is resolved,
Commissioner David Stern announced Monday. The lockout, the second
in three years, could extend into next season, the commissioner
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that is fair and accurate,'' Stern said of possibly
losing games to a work stoppage for the first time in NBA history.
``There are a number of clubs that will do better not operating
than operating. That's something the players don't seem to
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Billy Hunter, the executive director of the NBA
Players Association: ``Until the owners abandon their posture of
one-sided concession bargaining, and show some willingness to
compromise, it is difficult to expect any progress. The owners
continue to demand unprecedented concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   The lockout was agreed upon after a conference call of owners.
Stern said that while there was no formal vote, the league's Labor
Relations Committee had voted unanimously to impose a lockout. The
current Collective Bargaining Agreement expires at midnight
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the provisions of the lockout, the players will not be
paid, nor will they be allowed to have any ``basketball'' contact
with management. Team facilities will be closed, negotiations and
trades are not permitted, and any summer exhibitions or camps are
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   The league did say it would allow previously scheduled charity
games to go forward and would not object if a member of a team's
medical staff met with a player with a rehabilitative need to
monitor recovery. The meeting would have to be somewhere other than
the team's training facility, however. Teams also will forward a
player's mail and the league won't prevent players and management
from co-mingling in social situations, such as weddings.
</P>
<P>
   Stern and deputy commissioner Russ Granik outlined the basic
problem, which has not changed since the league voted 27-2 in March
to re-open the current Collective Bargaining Agreement. In the
agreement, the owners agreed to pay 48 percent of all basketball
revenues to the players and felt that they could live with 51.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   This past year, Stern said the league paid out more than 57
percent to the players. Thus, even though the league is generating
record revenues, more than the agreed-upon amount is going to the
players. Granik said the league as a whole will lose money this
season for the first time in 15 years while profits have been
steadily decreasing since peaking at around 20 percent in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to continue to play next season under the
current conditions,'' Stern said. ``It's the system that doesn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said, ``The owners' demands are especially unreasonable
in light of the continued acknowledgment by the commissioner that
the league continues to generate healthy and increasing revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Since April 1 there have been nine negotiating sessions, most of
them of three to five hours, Granik said. The last session last
week, however, took only 30 minutes. Granik said the league has
made four different proposals, all of which he said guarantee that
salaries continue to rise, but at a slower rate. The union, he
said, made one proposal on April 1 and remains adamant that it will
not give up the Larry Bird exception, a provision which allows
teams to exceed the salary cap to sign their own players.
</P>
<P>
   According to an agent familiar with the negotiations, the
league's proposals were ``rigid, hard-line and extreme.'' The
agent, who asked not to be identified, equated the league proposals
with someone trying to buy your house for well below market value.
``You don't even bother to make a counter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The average NBA salary is around $2.6 million and roughly 55
percent of the players make $1 million or more, Stern said.
However, the league insists more than half of its teams lost money
last season; the union says their auditors found four teams in the
red. Teams will receive television money regardless _ it will be
repaid if there are no games, but NBC doesn't start an active
schedule until after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money has to be repaid to the network,'' Stern said. ``It
was arranged that in the event of a work stoppage, teams will be
able to survive the season without suffering dire economic
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the third lockout in league history. A lockout in
the summer of 1995 lasted well into September and produced the
current collective bargaining Agreement, which was for six years.
However, the agreement contained a re-opener clause for the owners
after three years. The other lockout came in 1996 and lasted only a
couple hours and was due to disputes over modifications to the
agreement from the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout already caused USA Basketball to remove the 12 NBA
players from its roster for this summer's world championships in
Athens. The players had decided that participating would, in
effect, be akin to marketing the NBA. Instead, USA Basketball will
field a team likely composed of collegians and, possibly, Americans
playing professionally overseas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE ISSUES IN THE LOCKOUT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We should just put a large dollar sign here because _ surprise _
that's what's at the heart of the latest NBA lockout. The league
wants to salaries to rise, but not as fast as they are rising. The
union wants the stars to continue to get theirs while also getting
better deals for the lower-paid players.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Larry Bird Exception: This is the big issue. It allows
teams to re-sign their own veteran free agents to any salary. There
are some exceptions to the exception, but it applies to most
everyone. The original concept was sound; it allowed teams to keep
their own players. But lately it has been used by teams to re-sign
players to exorbitant deals, the latest being Kevin Garnett's
six-year, $126 million deal. The NBA wants to either eliminate the
Bird exception altogether or modify it. The union wants it to stay
the way it is and says it won't budge on that.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rookies: All first round draft picks the last three years
have signed three-year guaranteed deals. The league wants to move
that back to four or five year deals. In addition, rookie wage
scale players can extend their contract by any amount (see Garnett)
after just the second year and, if they don't, become free agents
after their third year. The league wants to make the rookies
restricted free agents after the first contract expires, giving
teams the right to match any offer.
</P>
<P>
   -- Salary Cap: It's part of the fabric now. The league would
love to institute a hard cap, such as football has, which would
prevent teams from spending wildly. The players don't like any cap,
including the one that's already in place which is a soft cap.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--PETER MAY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
