<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DAVID CONE'S LITTLE WAR WITH HIMSELF  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The conflict within the game matches a career-long
personal tenet against a newly embraced view of medical fact.
Halfway to 20 victories before the season is mathematically half
over, David Cone also finds himself in the middle of a juggling
act, trying to strike a proper balance between cockiness and
caution, emotion and ambition.
</P>
<P>
   The unfortunate truth of the matter is, some days that is easier
said than done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I feel like the best is still ahead of me,'' Cone
said recently. ``And then I shake myself into reality and say,
`Just take what you can get.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So many games, so much temptation, and the playoffs do seem so
far away. But the memory of his dead arm contributing to the
Yankees' playoff demise last season lingers far more than his right
shoulder's dull throb.
</P>
<P>
   Cone pitches to get back to the postseason, a place he believes
he evicted himself from last time around by ``failing to make the
distinction between pain and injury.'' By letting the tough guy in
him decide he could ``pitch through anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The riddle for Cone these days is to not get blinded by his own
success, swayed by his own inner strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Cone is an innings guy, and he knows no one can have a
big year without pitching through some pain,'' said his pitching
coach, Mel Stottlemyre. ``But those innings take a toll. He has to
recognize when to back off.''
</P>
<P>
   If he were given a choice of selecting from a menu of
opportunity, of course, Cone would take a couple more electric
autumn nights at Yankee Stadium over beating the likes of the
Philadelphia Phillies Tuesday night in the Bronx. What he wouldn't
have given to have his turn come up against the Mets. He has Jordan
in him, Cone does. The bigger the game, the hungrier he is for the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of athletes are really fearful of failure,'' he
said. ``I used to have some fear, but now, the only thing I fear is
a missed opportunity, not pitching in a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   He also happens to be a 35-year-old pitcher who has taken
surgical shoulder hits in consecutive years. He knows that
Stottlemyre is right, that physiology is not dictated by
psychology, and that when his body speaks now, he had better
listen. Then again, when the messages are mixed just what is he
supposed to think?
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, he was pitching to an earned run average
over 6.00, and began to think he would never again be more than a
five- or six-inning pitcher again. He said he was ``starting to
feel old.''
</P>
<P>
   This was in the visitors' clubhouse at Shea Stadium last
Saturday morning, and from the locker stall next door, Darryl
Strawberry chimed in. ``You're still old,'' he said. ``We're both
old.''
</P>
<P>
   Except this season has suddenly become something of a romp
through a Disney cartoon. Since his slow start, Cone has
dramatically improved his pitch-per-inning count while lasting
deeper into the game. His walk-strikeout ratio is actually better
now than ever. He recently dominated Cleveland's and Atlanta's
imposing lineups. The way the Yankees produce runs, make few
defensive mistakes and close out games, Cone, at 10-2, has a chance
to win 20. The last time he did that was also the first time, a
decade ago with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is to pitching what George Steinbrenner is to owning, and
none of this regular-season prosperity would matter if this season
ends like last season, with the mound feeling like the Boston
Marathon's Heartbreak Hill. He left a game one day against Texas
because he couldn't get the ball to home plate. Cone forced himself
back too soon, and later talked his way into Manager Joe Torre's
heart and Game 1 against Cleveland, another mistake. By early
winter, doctors had surgically cleaned out his shoulder, and he was
embracing rationalizations of the end.
</P>
<P>
   He told himself he was lucky, ahead of the game, that his arm
had given him more pitches than anyone except maybe Randy Johnson
these last 10 years. This was all pre-emptive, premature. He was
back in the rotation before Torre and Stottlemyre expected him. Now
Cone and Strawberry, who already have World Series rings from 1996,
have quiet talks about what a joy it to be granted renewed baseball
life on a team as good as this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitch in a pennant race, get a post-season start, that's the
ultimate,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no race, really, but there is the long season to
survive. Cone said he has always ``pushed the limit,'' but now he
knows there has to be a time to walk away, off the mound. Live to
pitch another October.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
