<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: J. WALTER THOMPSON AGENCY WINS MERRILL LYNCH ACCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch is bullish on J. Walter Thompson New
York, an agency that has suffered a spate of bearish news in the
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. has ended one of the most closely watched
recent reviews by selecting the flagship New York office of the J.
Walter Thompson Co., a unit of WPP Group PLC, to handle its
worldwide account, with estimated billings of $85 million. Thompson
New York will serve as the lead office on the account, involving
Merrill Lynch operations in 45 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, made Monday, was a delight and a relief for
Thompson New York after a period of tumult that included account
losses, executive reshufflings and shortfalls in other high-profile
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here is very thrilled,'' said Bob Jeffrey, who joined
Thompson New York as president on March 31 and attended his first
account pitch meeting two days later. ``It's a big win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Merrill Lynch account had been handled for 12 years by
Bozell Worldwide in New York, a unit of True North Communications,
which resigned rather than take part in the review as it began in
February. The decision came after the review had been narrowed to
Thompson and one other finalist, D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles
Communications in New York, a unit of MacManus Group.
</P>
<P>
   The shift by Merrill Lynch is emblematic of the ferment in the
financial services field as a growing number of marketers rethink
agency relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, for instance, Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. consolidated
its brand advertising, with billings estimated at $50 million, at
the BBDO New York unit of Omnicom Group, while the Dreyfus Corp.,
part of the Mellon Bank Corp., narrowed a review on its account,
with estimated billings of $30 million, to six contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition is intensifying with a lot more entrants into
the financial services world,'' said Paul W. Critchlow, senior vice
president for marketing and communications at Merrill Lynch in New
York, ``so we thought it was timely to begin differentiating the
Merrill Lynch brand and put some additional advertising resources
against our businesses, in the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``A third of our revenue comes from outside the U.S.,'' he
added, ``and that's growing rapidly'' because of ventures like
Merrill Lynch Japan Securities Ltd., a private-client operation
being opened in that country tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Both Thompson and DMB&AMP;B strove mightily to land Merrill Lynch as
a client, partly because of the prestige associated with the firm
and partly because of the cachet Wall Street has as the stock
market trades in near-record territory. Martin Sorrell, chief
executive at WPP in London, and Roy J. Bostock, chairman and chief
executive at MacManus in New York, both took active roles in their
agencies' pitches.
</P>
<P>
   And both agencies were hoping that winning the review would
offset some recent problems.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil at Thompson New York included the abrupt departure
of Jeffrey's predecessor, Susan Giannino; the loss of a longtime
client, the Eastman Kodak Co., to a sibling WPP agency, Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather Worldwide in New York, and failure in reviews for
assignments from marketers like the First Brands Corp. and the
Pepsi-Cola Co. unit of Pepsico Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``This weekend was the first I've had off in two months,'' said
Jeffrey, who came to Thompson New York from Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS,
part of the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies,
where he had been president and managing director of the San
Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   And DMB&AMP;B had been hoping to help compensate for the loss in
late March of a top client, the Gateway computer company, after
handling its worldwide account for only a year. The account, with
billings estimated at $50 million to $70 million, had been one of
the 10 largest at DMB&AMP;B; the agency is now suing Gateway for $9
million in connection with the dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Haney, a spokesman for DMB&AMP;B in Troy, Mich., said that the
agency was ``very disappointed'' at the Merrill Lynch decision.
</P>
<P>
   The decision had been expected around June 1, but that week
executives at Merrill Lynch asked both agencies to flesh out ideas
offered at what were to have been final presentations in late May.
After that, the executives split into two camps, one advocating
Thompson New York, the other DMB&AMP;B.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tough choice,'' Critchlow acknowledged, ``but in
the end we felt Thompson really was better suited to help build our
brand on a global basis.'' The initial campaign from Thompson New
York will be based on the agency's previously submitted ideas, he
said, after they are ``refined and adjusted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's premature to say what form the ads will take since we
have some more work to do,'' Critchlow said, ``but it will be
different from what we currently have.'' The present Merrill Lynch
campaign carries the theme ``The difference is Merrill Lynch.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the familiar ``Bullish on America'' theme was created by
a previous agency, Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, Bozell also used bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the new campaign, which will probably begin sometime in
September, will feature bulls in some form, Critchlow replied:
``The bull is our icon. The bull will never disappear; it will
always be somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The creative team at Thompson New York that worked on the
Merrill Lynch pitch was headed by Bill Hamilton, a former executive
vice president and co-creative head at the flagship New York office
of the Thompson sibling Ogilvy &AMP; Mather, who served as a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Bill from when we both worked at Chiat/Day together,''
Jeffrey said, ``and at Ogilvy he worked on IBM, American Express
and a lot of other blue-chip assignments.'' Merrill Lynch
executives ``saw that experience,'' he added, ``and appreciated
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton will now join Thompson New York, Jeffrey said, with
some title that would reflect his role as ``the global creative
director on Merrill Lynch.'' J.J. Jordan is the executive vice
president and executive creative director at Thompson New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Merrill Lynch review started with five agencies. The others
were: Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding in New York, which is also owned by
True North; Grey Advertising in New York, and the New York office
of Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS. Foote, Cone and Grey were eliminated in
April and Lowe was eliminated in mid-May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
