<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT PLANS TO SELL SHARES IN URANIUM BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   The government will try to privatize its uranium enrichment
business by selling stock to the public, with proceeds expected to
be $1.36 billion to $1.65 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The entity to be sold, U.S. Enrichment Corp., operates aging
factories in Piketon, Ohio, and Paducah, Ky., and had sales of $1.6
billion last year. It is also developing a laser-based enrichment
system at laboratories of the Energy Department, of which it was
once a part.
</P>
<P>
   NO CHANGE EXPECTED AT FED MEETING
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board's policy-making committee begins a
two-day meeting Tuesday to consider whether to raise interest
rates. Despite signs of a strong economy and rising inflationary
pressures, the Fed is expected to leave rates unchanged. Economists
said the predominant view among Fed policy-makers, led by Alan
Greenspan, the chairman of the central bank, is that the economy is
already slowing because of the Asian crisis and perhaps even the
strike that has crippled General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   MONSANTO ACQUIRING A SEED UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto is buying Cargill's international seed operations for
$1.4 billion in one of the clearest signs yet of expectations that
biotechnology will play a pivotal role in agriculture's future.
</P>
<P>
   BUYING SPREE PUSHES MARKETS UP
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 52.82 points, to 8,997.36
in an end-of-quarter buying spree. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index increased 5.29 points, to 1,138.49, and the Nasdaq composite
index gained 21.55 points, to 1,891.08.
</P>
<P>
   Investors poured an estimated $21.1 billion into stock mutual
funds in June.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-HOME SALES ROSE 0.3 PERCENT IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new homes rose 0.3 percent in May, to an annual rate of
890,000 units, fueled by low interest rates and high consumer
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   POWERGEN OF BRITAIN TO BUY UTILITY
</P>
<P>
   Powergen, Britain's second-largest generator of electricity, has
agreed to buy East Midlands Electricity for $1.4 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL NAMES J. WALTER THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has selected the New York office of J. Walter
Thompson to handle its worldwide advertising account, with
estimated billings of $85 million. The Merrill Lynch account has
been handled by Bozell Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   LSI LOGIC IN A DEAL FOR SYMBIOS
</P>
<P>
   LSI Logic has agreed to acquire Symbios, a maker of chips, from
Hyundai Electronics America for about $760 million.
</P>
<P>
   BANK PLAN VIEWED AS NOT ENOUGH
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the government of South Korea to merge five
small banks into bigger, healthier competitors has drawn a tepid
response from economists, who regard the move as largely an
ineffective start to fixing the nation's ailing financial system.
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR OF U.S. NEWS DISMISSED
</P>
<P>
   The editor of U.S. News &AMP; World Report, James Fallows, was
dismissed. He will be replaced by Stephen G. Smith, the editor of
National Journal, the political weekly. Harold Evans, the editorial
director and vice chairman of Mortimer Zuckerman's publications,
said the dismissal was his decision.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN CORPORATIONS ARE PESSIMISTIC
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan said corporate sentiment had deteriorated to
its worst level in four years, with most companies saying they have
seen economic conditions worsen over the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN DEVALUES ITS CURRENCY
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan devalued its currency, the rupee, by 4.4 percent after
its nuclear tests prompted foreigners to pull investments from the
country.
</P>
</TEXT>
