<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH WAYS TO GET TRAFFIC DATA TO PHOENIX MOTORISTS UNVEILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The route out of traffic tie-ups may be through your
cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Or your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Or your TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, members of a high-tech consortium unveiled the many
ways they've devised for Phoenix-area motorists to get traffic
information before driving into a traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   The most advanced method _ and the most costly _ is the
``Traffic Angel,'' which dials a motorist's cell phone whenever
something happens to slow traffic on the commuter's usual route.
The service will be available to Phoenix-area residents by fall.
</P>
<P>
   A special television traffic channel already is available to
Tempe cable users. And an Internet service provides
up-to-the-minute traffic conditions on freeways and streets
throughout the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time after time, people tell us transportation is the No. 1
problem and the No. 1 concern in our community,'' explained Tempe
Mayor Neil Giuiliano.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding traffic information through technology developed by the
AZTech consortium may help put an end to transportation
frustrations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't put the radio traffic reports out of business. Some
of the information provided through the new television, Internet
and phone service comes from Metro Networks, the largest
traffic-reporting system in the nation. &UR; Other data is gathered from
the Arizona Department of Transportation's freeway network, as well
as traffic information from cities and Maricopa County.
</P>
<P>
   The services showcased Monday are the latest wrinkles in
Arizona's move toward intelligent-transportation systems. Fueled by
a $7.5 million federal grant, metropolitan Phoenix is one of four
regions in the United States experimenting with ways to use
technology to move traffic faster and more safely. The technology
is seen as a less-expensive alternative to expanding freeways or
building new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix will be one of 10 cities where the cell-phone service
will be launched in September, said Craig Lynar, a vice president
at Etak, one of the private companies working with officials of
ADOT, Maricopa County and Phoenix-area cities as members of the
AzTech consortium. The California-based Etak, a subsidiary of Sony
Corp., publishes digital maps.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to feed traffic information through an AT&AMP;T
PocketNet cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists can use the display screen on the phone to read
current traffic information, Lynar said. &UR; Or they can take it
several steps further and have the ``Traffic Angel'' call them with
details of traffic jams that would affect their commutes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, for a monthly fee, subscribers would enter their
driving routes, such as from home to office or to school, and then
specify what times they plan to use the routes. If the service
detects a problem at those times, Traffic Angel calls the driver's
cell phone. The information would pop up on the phone's display
screen.
</P>
<P>
   The service will be available only through AT&AMP;T's PocketNet
phone. The phone is specially equipped to receive data similar to a
miniature computer browser, Lynar said. The service costs $29 a
month; an additional $5 fee would buy the notification service.
</P>
<P>
   As for the television and Internet services, officials said they
hope motorists would tap into those before leaving home or work.
Armed with up-to-date information, they could adjust their
commutes &UR; for the fastest paths to their destinations.
</P>
<P>
   The television information is only available to Tempe cable
users. Other Phoenix-area cities want to see how the service works
out before committing time on their own cable stations, Giuiliano
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe also will use the service to post traffic information for
special events, such as football games. &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at 444-8963 or via e-mail at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
