<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-LVMH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EN GARDE: A VERY DIFFERENT COSMETICS RETAILER IS COMING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(af) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Standing in the middle of the first floor of Saks
Fifth Avenue in Manhattan is a little like arriving in Tangier on
the ferry from Spain. Peddlers with exotic wares are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies, new fall colors,'' beckons a woman from Estee Lauder,
running her hands over a display case of violet-toned shadows and
blushes. ``Need some help?'' asks a woman from the Stila counter
over the head of the customer whose makeup she is applying. ``Try
Bulgari,'' announces an immaculately groomed saleswoman, gripping a
bottle of perfume, poised to spray.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way expensive makeup has been sold in this country
for decades, with cosmetics company representatives sitting at
counters or wandering the aisles throughout department stores,
hoping to ensnare women looking for a new eye shadow and getting
them to buy a nail polish or astringent to go with it.
</P>
<P>
   But a French luxury cosmetics emporium is coming to town,
betting that women will be willing to try an entirely different
experience. In this store, perfumes will be arranged in
alphabetical order, with nary a sprayer in sight.
</P>
<P>
   While some products will be displayed by brand, often a mix of
lines will be placed together by product classification _ say, a
shelf of mud masks or a rack of anti-aging creams.
</P>
<P>
   The salespeople will work for the store owner itself _ Sephora,
a unit of LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton _ and not the cosmetics
companies. Of course, if anyone asks, they will be happy to make
strong recommendations, and large advertising displays will be
omnipresent.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be none of the gift-with-purchase deals _ the
bottle of perfume, the box of scented powder and the odd teddy bear
that come free with a $59 purchase _ that are the backbone of
cosmetics retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Sephora's new 9,000-square-foot store _ opening next month on
Broadway in SoHo _ will join other independent stores like Make-Up
Forever, Aveda and Origins, a unit of Estee Lauder, that are also
trying to grab new business outside traditional industry formats.
</P>
<P>
   But those upstart chains of smaller stores sell only their own
wares. No retailer is making as big a bet as Sephora, which was
purchased last July by LVMH, a luxury holding company that also
sells Champagne and other high-end goods. With 11,000 products for
sale, Sephora is a sort of luxury cosmetics general store, and SoHo
is just its port of entry into America.
</P>
<P>
   The company is negotiating to acquire a site in Rockefeller
Center. About 15 other stores are scheduled to open this year
throughout the United States, in such cities as Los Angeles, Miami,
San Francisco and Seattle. And smaller versions will appear in
upscale American malls soon after, Sephora executives said.
</P>
<P>
   The company already runs 54 stores in France, with a
14,000-square-foot flagship on the Champs-Elysees in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Sephora's arrival in the United States will be closely watched
by competitors, as the retailer pushes up against several
presumptions that have long dominated the industry. Will women buy
as many products if they are not heavily pushed by sales clerks?
Will customers appreciate the freedom to wander and try things out
at whim?
</P>
<P>
   ``We find that 40 percent of mall visitors don't go into
department stores,'' said Howard Meitiner, chief executive of
Sephora. ``That means there is a huge audience out there looking
for new outlets for beauty shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   But will small makeup companies that have developed strong,
exclusive relationships with certain department stores jeopardize
that by jumping on board with Sephora?
</P>
<P>
   And will large suppliers be satisfied with being sold like
cereal on an alphabetically arranged shelf? Cosmetics companies
have considerable teeth: their products often account for more than
10 percent of a department store's total revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most vendors realize we are making the market bigger,'' said
Myron E. Ullman III, chief executive of the DFS Group, the LVMH
subsidiary that operates Sephora, and a former chief executive of
Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   The cosmetics industry has several top players that own most of
the market and are widely distributed, with dozens of little
companies trying to make a go in fewer venues. Sales of cosmetics
and perfume reached $14.5 billion in the United States last year,
with about one-third of the sales in department stores, said Allan
Mottus, editor of The Informationist, a trade publication for the
beauty industry.
</P>
<P>
   Another third came through drugstores, with the rest split among
mass merchants and various other outlets, including Cosmetics Plus,
a chain of off-price beauty products in New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly 2,300 department stores that carry prestige
cosmetics, almost all carry Estee Lauder, Clinique, Lancome and
Elizabeth Arden. By comparison, smaller lines like Bobbi Brown, MAC
and Christian Dior are found in about 700 stores, and in a few of
their own small shops.
</P>
<P>
   Sephora, while focusing on many of the brands offered in upscale
stores, also carries some lines found in drugstores, like Nivea. It
sells its own private label line, too, which includes 365 shades of
lip color. Customers can freely test samples, and the sales help,
dressed in black Nehru suits, are supposed to know something about
all the products.
</P>
<P>
   Have dry skin and don't want to chat about it? Simply pop a
description of the problem into a computer and it will recommend a
variety of products from different companies, instead of, say, an
entire skin care line by Chanel.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a display that breaks down scents to their key
ingredients, so if a shopper is in love with lavender, she can find
out which perfumes are infused with it.
</P>
<P>
   American retailers are taking note. Bloomingdale's, a unit of
Federated Department Stores Inc., sent a team to explore the
Champs-Elysees Sephora store last year and has been furiously
remodeling its flagship's first floor, all the while maintaining
that the changes have nothing to do with Sephora. Nonetheless, it
is freshening the floor's look, adding more interactive displays
and retraining the staff _ its most extensive face lift of the area
ever.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
