<SLUG> BC-FINBUDGET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business section
plans to move for Tuesday, June 30, on the New York Times wire. For
questions, please call Marcus Chan at 415-777-8443.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SIEBEL  &LR; _ If you have a brokerage account, if you hold shares in a
mutual fund, if you are a bank customer _ indeed, if you are
anyone's customer at all _ chances are you are being closely
watched.
</P>
<P>
   As computers grow exponentially faster and disk-drive capacities
approach infinity, companies are finding it easy to quickly sort
through huge customer databases. They can pull together every scrap
of information they collect and figure out the shrewdest way to
increase their sales.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel Systems of San Mateo is the leader among a half-dozen or
so companies that make software that helps companies read the
wishes of individual and corporate customers. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LSI _  &LR; Chipmaker LSI Logic Corp. said yesterday it will acquire
Symbios Inc., a Hyundai Electronics America unit that makes
high-end data storage and adapter cards, for $760 million in cash.
By Amy Doan
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNET  &LR; _ Rule 101 of Internet start-ups: The window of
opportunity to cash out for big bucks is open only briefly before
it abruptly shuts.
</P>
<P>
   Take the cautionary examples of PointCast and Marimba, a pair of
Bay Area companies that pioneered technology to broadcast, or
``push,'' customized information to computer screens over the
Internet. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIGITAL &LR;  _ Tom Abate's high-tech column.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PERSONAL TECH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDCHAT &LR;  _ &LR;   &LR; Getting answers to medical questions has always
been one of the prime reasons people go on the Internet. But while
the Web is full of health-related chatter, it's rife with
misinformation and hype about unproven treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of the nation's top medical educators are wading
gingerly into the mess, hoping to add some long-needed quality
control and at the same time garner a little online visibility for
their institutions. By Carl Hall
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A  &LR; _ David Einstein answers your computing
questions.
</P>
