<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSMETICS-LVMH-ART-2N     06-29 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-LVMH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: area ever.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Department stores are obviously nervous,'' Mottus said.
``Sephora gives the consumer the opportunity to take a whole line
apart, and in Europe, some consumers like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many American consumers may, too. ``So many times you get a
makeover and it never looks the same at home,'' said Wendy Gabriel,
an accountant from Orlando, Fla., who was dodging some perfume mist
in Saks the other day. ``I'd rather experiment myself, to see if I
can really make liquid eye liner work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sephora may find the United States a very different market
from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For openers, department stores play a much bigger role in the
cosmetics business in America than they do in Europe, so
competition is much tougher. Ten percent of all cosmetics purchases
in France are made in Sephora stores; no single department-store
chain in the United States can boast anywhere near such a share.
</P>
<P>
   And although many women hate having to fend off the spraying
masses of perfume pushers, they do like to see the same face at the
same makeup stand. ``I go back to the MAC counter again and again
because I know there will be that same person there to help me,''
said Stacey Wiener, head of promotions for a cable television show.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, American department stores frequently carve out
their own special deals with suppliers _ especially among
cutting-edge brands _ securing exclusive rights to a line.
</P>
<P>
   Barney's Inc., for instance, has such a hold in its New York
stores on Philosophy, a hip brand sold in little plastic containers
with black lids. It is also the only outlet for Make-Up Forever _
known for its bright palettes _ and several other lines outside
those companies' own stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focused on keeping our distribution limited,'' said
Joyce Avelon, who runs retail operations for Philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Fifth Avenue frequently gets perfume companies to introduce
a new scent on its sales floor, with the understanding that once
the brand has been out a while its maker can start selling it
elsewhere. Often, the deals are broken down by location, with a
retailer insisting on exclusive distribution rights in, say,
Houston but not Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Department stores are not going to give up those arrangements so
easily, and will almost certainly lean on cosmetics makers _
especially small ones whose business they have more or less
created.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is reminding vendors,'' said one department store
executive who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``Everybody
knows the game here. Cosmetics sales per square foot are the
highest of any department in department stores, and people are very
protective of it. We are not going to stand by while another
competitor comes in.''
</P>
<P>
   The hottest lines in recent years are the signature lines
produced by makeup artists themselves, like Bobbi Brown, which
Sephora does not carry. Another is Nars, named for the makeup
artist Francois Nars, which is sold in Barneys New York, 24 Saks
stores and one Fred Segal store in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like Sephora to be part of our future,'' said Kate
Sullivan, director of marketing and sales for Nars, adding,
however, that her current clients might be upset with the move.
``Most small vendors base their business on their relationships,''
she said. ``When you enter into a store when you're new, you make a
commitment to grow together.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ullman of DFS said that Sephora would have no trouble
securing the brands it wanted. ``Ultimately, if the customer
decides this is a more enjoyable way to shop,'' he said, ``vendors
will migrate to where the customer is.''
</P>
<P>
   Every major brand will be in the store _ Giorgio Armani, Chanel,
Clarins, Clinique, Calvin Klein, Lancome, Estee Lauder, Yves Saint
Laurent, L'Oreal and Versace will all be in stock. Prices will be
the same as in department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason LVMH bought Sephora was to have another home
for the many cosmetic brands in its own portfolio, like Christian
Dior, Givenchy and Guerlain. Some cosmetics executives in the
United States have grumbled that they are not keen on being
displayed in a democratic fashion, and have wondered whether
Sephora's American stores will give more prominence to its parent
company's brands. Ullman says that will not happen, citing equal
treatment at the company's stores in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``DFS is run very autonomously,'' he said. ``We maintain a
Chinese wall with LVMH. Those brands will be handled no differently
than other brands. It would be foolish for us to do something that
helps 10 percent of the business at the expense of 90 percent of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, American department stores are studying the
newfangled European competitor intently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about Sephora is that it has made us stop and
think, `Are we running the business as well as we can?''' said
Michael Gould, chief executive of Bloomingdale's. ``They have made
us take a look.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
