<HEADER>
A2853 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS &LR;      06-29 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unable to reach what National Basketball Association
Commissioner David Stern called ``the promised land of agreement''
with the players union on a new collective-bargaining agreement,
the NBA announced Monday it would enact a lockout of its players at
midnight today.
</P>
<P>
   League owners, who had voted 27-2 to reopen the existing
collective-bargaining agreement in March, met Monday via conference
call and decided to lock out the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expired collective-bargaining agreement between the NBA
and its players did not work,'' said NBA Deputy Commissioner Russ
Granik. ``We have made a series of proposals to the players under
which salaries would continue to increase but at a slower rate than
under the expired deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably, the players have rejected all of these proposals.
The NBA will not operate until we reach a new agreement that is
fair to both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the percentage of what is called basketball-related
income (BRI) _ revenue from such things as tickets, broadcasting,
arena concessions, luxury suites, premium-seat licenses and
merchandising _ that is divided up between the players and the
owners.
</P>
<P>
   The owners reopened the collective-bargaining agreement when
player salaries climbed above 51.8 percent of the BRI. Owners, who
claim players got closer to 57 percent of the BRI, are saying that
salaries are rising faster than the league's income and that the
NBA is treading on dangerous financial ground.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did half of the NBA's 29 teams lose money, owners
insist, but the league itself did not turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   So the NBA, the only major pro sports league that has not lost a
regular-season game to work stoppage, is fully prepared to go an
entire season without playing a game.
</P>
<P>
   From promised land to potential wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our deal (the last bargaining agreement) had some risk in
it,'' Stern said. ``What we needed was an opportunity to reopen and
renegotiate if that risk turned out to be a reality. Needless to
say, 57 percent is not an economic model that works. They (the
owners) just simply wanted a deal that works.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons salaries have been climbing so quickly is the
so-called ``Larry Bird exception'' to the salary cap, which allows
teams to re-sign their own free agents for any amount, regardless
of the salary-cap figure. It was the Bird exception that allowed
the Chicago Bulls to pay Michael Jordan $33 million this season,
despite the $26.9 million-per-team salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly because of the Bird exception, 38 of the 372 NBA players
made $323.4 million _ the lion's share of the $1 billion in salary
and benefits the league doled out last year.
</P>
<P>
   The owners would like to eliminate _ or severely curtail _ the
Bird exception and install a ``hard'' salary cap, which teams could
not exceed. That would be the best way, they feel, to get salaries
under control.
</P>
<P>
   This is reportedly the biggest sticking point in the
negotiations. While other peripheral issues like the drug policy,
player conduct and expanding the rookie wage scale beyond the
current three years have been pretty much agreed upon, the Bird
exception is something the players are loath to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   The union feels owners are victims of their own poor business
decisions and are now looking for the players to bail them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try not to focus on the Larry Bird exception,'' Granik
said. ``We need an agreement that is not totally open-ended, like
the current agreement. If there's a way to that, and there may (be
a way) that keeps the Larry Bird exception _ or some element of
that _ in there, then we're prepared to talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can't have a situation where we go back to the owners
again and say, `Look, we have a system that is totally open-ended.
We hope it will work a little better.' We can't do that again. It
didn't work very well.''
</P>
<P>
   So the NBA won't go to work at all.
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, players will not be paid, teams cannot trade or
negotiate with players, free agents cannot be signed, team workout
facilities will be shut down and teams cannot conduct or help with
summer camps, exhibitions, practices, workouts, coaching sessions
or team meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently unable to learn the lessons provided by Major League
Baseball, which went through a strike in 1994 and 1995 that proved
disastrous, the NBA is chancing a similar public-relations fiasco,
hoping to force the players, whose average salary is $2.2 million,
to blink first in the standoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to play the season under the current system,''
Stern said. ``That's just a reality. Certainly the primary
beneficiaries of the current system are the players, so as an
economic matter, their risk is greater here than the owners.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the owners have the money amassed from a $2.6
billion television contract _ a war chest that will tide them over
should the lockout spill over into the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stern, the lockout could last the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be fair and accurate (to say),'' Stern said.
``Unfortunately, there will be a number of clubs that will do
better not operating than operating. And that's something the
players don't yet understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2147EDT &QL; 
