<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIEBEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Siebel Systems makes software that may smack of Big Brother   By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
If you have a brokerage account, if you hold shares in a mutual
fund, if you are a bank customer _ indeed, if you are anyone's
customer at all _ chances are you are being closely watched.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As computers grow exponentially faster and disk-drive capacities
approach infinity, companies are finding it easy to quickly sort
through huge customer databases. They can pull together every scrap
of information they collect and figure out the shrewdest way to
increase their sales.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel Systems of San Mateo is the leader among a half-dozen or
so companies that make software that helps companies read the
wishes of individual and corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Siebel and its competitors, it has never been easier
for big companies to manage their sales and marketing. The
downside, privacy advocates contend, is that the information
customers provide to companies might be used for purposes of which
the customers disapprove.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel's software has a bulky name _ enterprise relationship
management application _ and a hefty price.
</P>
<P>
   Using powerful new software such as Siebel's, designed to make
the fullest use of increased computer power, companies can deftly
weave all their information about you into a tailor-made scheme to
sell you more goods or services.
</P>
<P>
   A brokerage firm, for example, can scan your portfolio, all your
buy or sell transactions and all your account deposits and
withdrawals. It can review all your requests for information and
examine all your complaints. It can stir in what it knows about
your age, income and family status.
</P>
<P>
   It may conclude that you are an affluent, fast-trading
speculator who regularly throws large new sums of money into the
market, mainly into marginal high-technology stocks. It then might
call you and offer you a chunk of its next high-tech initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel's one-time licensing fee to use the software ranges from
$1,500 to $5,000 per user, depending on how complex the customer's
needs are. At Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities, the San Francisco
investment bank, 400 people use the software, which carried an
upfront fee in the neighborhood of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most customers also pay for a service contract, which can add 15
percent to the basic cost. For this, they get a chance to meet
regularly with Siebel technicians and are entitled to free product
upgrades and debugging.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel's customers include a broad selection of large industrial
and financial companies, including Compaq Computer, Digital
Equipment, Bank of America and Prudential.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all customers require outside help to install the
software, pull fragmented data together into a single database,
test the product and mold it to their needs. Those services can
cost considerably more than the software itself.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel doesn't do much of that work itself, but rather farms it
out to Andersen Consulting, with which it has a cozy relationship.
Andersen's managing partner, George Shaheen, sits on Siebel's board
of directors, and his firm owns 8 percent of Siebel's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Siebel, the company's chairman, president, chief executive
and co-founder and a former Oracle Corp. vice president, owns 28
percent of the stock _ more than $600 million worth.
</P>
<P>
   The other co-founder, Patricia House, a former Frame Technology
executive vice president who serves as executive vice president and
chief operating officer of Siebel, has a $60 million stake in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   As expensive as Siebel's software is, the company's customers
evidently find it worth the price. Siebel, which didn't exist until
five years ago, posted operating income of $7 million on revenues
of $119 million last year, and expects revenues to triple this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery's chief executive, Thom Weisel, says Siebel software
has added $40 million to his own firm's annual revenues by helping
his investment bankers and marketing people focus more efficiently
on their best opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Montgomery people contact customers or potential
customers, they enter a record of the conversation in the database,
where it is accessible to all users.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that one of the equity bankers talked to the chief
financial officer of a software company last week,'' says Doug
Kline, a Montgomery vice president who manages technology for the
corporate finance division.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be helpful to a merger-and-acquisitions banker
trying to find a partner for one of our other customers in the
software business. Before we put the Siebel system in two years
ago, there were communications problems. To get the same kind of
information we get off the computer now, you had to call everybody
in the department.''
</P>
<P>
   Some privacy advocates say enterprise software has a Big
Brotherish tinge.
</P>
<P>
   Even though companies may be drawing strictly from data they
gathered legitimately, and are using it for internal purposes only,
they have no automatic right to use it for high-pressure sales,
says Robert Ellis Smith, publisher of Privacy Journal in
Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information gathered for one purpose should not be used for an
incompatible purpose without the consent of the individual,'' Smith
remarks. ``Up front you have a responsibility to tell your customer
what you plan to do with the information you get from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Siebel customers are reluctant to say exactly how they use
the company's products.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco discount broker Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. tried to
avoid the question at first. Eventually Schwab spokesman Tom
Taggart disclosed that employees use the Siebel system in part to
determine which customers requested Individual Retirement Account
applications but never sent them back. Schwab employees then place
follow-up calls.
</P>
<P>
   A Schwab competitor, Boston-based Fidelity Investments, also
uses Siebel software. It declined to discuss the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Seibel stock, which trades on Nasdaq, closed at a record high of
$32.19 yesterday, up $2.06 for the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
