<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 2 Bay Area `Push' Firms Shoved Aside   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Rule 101 of Internet start-ups: The window of opportunity to cash
out for big bucks is open only briefly before it abruptly shuts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take the cautionary examples of PointCast and Marimba, a pair of
Bay Area companies that pioneered technology to broadcast, or
``push,'' customized information to computer screens over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, both were anointed the Next Big Things on the Net.
Marimba's photogenic chief executive, Kim Polese, radiated from the
cover of major high-tech publications and &UR;  &LR; Time magazine named her
one of the 25 most influential people in America. And executives at
PointCast _ which was being touted as an overnight success story _
spurned a $400 million buyout bid from media mogul Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the push companies have been shoved aside. Yahoo and
Excite _ whose Web-search sites have been made over into ``portal''
sites that combine free e-mail, message boards, news and shopping _
are all the rage on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Sunnyvale-based PointCast reportedly is seeking a buyer, even
though it filed last month to go public in July. The company hopes
to sell 4.3 million shares of stock for about $10 to $12 a share.
At $11 a share, PointCast would be worth $235 million _ about half
of the Murdoch offer.
</P>
<P>
   Marimba hardly made a peep for months until it announced a major
software upgrade last week. The Mountain View company _ which is
backed by the powerful Menlo Park venture capital firm of Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers _ still has plans to go public, possibly
in 1999, but sources say it too is on the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Marimba's VCs) saw any exit, I can't believe they wouldn't
have taken it by now,'' said David Simons, managing director of
Digital Video Investments in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The plight of PointCast and Marimba highlights the fickle nature
of the Internet market, which has careened from one concept du jour
to another, industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``The Internet is full of fads, and I think push was the
biggest of them,'' said Jim Clark, chairman and co-founder of
Mountain View-based Netscape Communications, the mother of all
Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun shines brightly on a select place for a concerted
moment and then it passes. If you don't cash in, you're f_,'' said
Michael Wolff, author of ``Burn Rate: How I Survived the Gold Rush
Years on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in this market is timing, timing, timing,'' Wolff
said. ``It's all about promise, hype and heat _ not about business
performance. PointCast and Marimba's time came and went.''
</P>
<P>
   The time apparently is now for companies with portal sites. In
the past month, Walt Disney Co. has bought 44 percent of Infoseek,
NBC made substantial investments in Cnet, and AOL shunned a $30
billion takeover offer from AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But Marimba CEO Kim Polese vehemently disputes the notion that
Marimba is passe. In fact, she claims the company is at the center
of ``the next great wave on the Internet _ distributed enterprise
applications.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been quietly kicking serious butt,'' said Polese in
discussing the company's new software program, Castanet 3.0, and
its expanding customer list, which now totals 800 _ including
Federal Express, Ford Motor and Intuit.
</P>
<P>
   Castanet 3.0 lets corporations ship software programs and
upgrades over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Marimba has nearly doubled its workforce over the past year, to
130.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to do a pile-on or an IPO rush,'' Polese said.
``It's not about an immediate payoff, but about building a
substantive company that will be consistently profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Polese admits Marimba ``could have done a better job defining
what we do.'' Because it didn't, she said, ``we were lumped into
the push category. We've always been much more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Marimba's problems are over its identity, PointCast's stem
from stiff competition.
</P>
<P>
   Both Microsoft's Internet Explorer and Netscape's Communicator
Web browsers offer free ``push'' features. And PointCast has lost
subscribers amid complaints that the service was delivering too
much unwanted content and slowing down internal corporate networks.
</P>
<P>
   PointCast CEO David Dorman has said the company is making a
transition from strictly broadcasting news to consumers. PointCast
wants to become the de facto information conduit for employees at
Fortune 500 companies, delivering companywide messages, sales
updates, employee news and a calendar of corporate events, as well
as traditional news.
</P>
<P>
   PointCast officials, who are in the midst of a legally mandated
quiet period before the company goes public, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, PointCast's and Marimba's overheated hype machines
and willingness to talk may have led to their current predicaments.
</P>
<P>
   One Silicon Valley venture capitalist said, ``These guys
trumpeted themselves loudly, but didn't do a good job of explaining
who they were. They set themselves up for a fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
