<SLUG> BC-LSI-HYUNDAI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LSI TO BUY CHIP SUBSIDIARY FROM HYUNDAI ELECTRONICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ LSI Logic Corp. said Monday that it had agreed
to acquire Symbios Inc., a Silicon Valley-based subsidiary of
Hyundai Electronics America, for about $760 million in cash,
including assumption of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Symbios, which had 1997 sales of $620 million, is a leader in
Small Computer System Interface, known as SCSI and pronounced
scuzzy, chips used to connect to networks and peripheral devices,
like disk and tape drives.
</P>
<P>
   LSI, which is based in Milpitas, Calif., is best known for its
system-on-a-chip technology, used in products like Sony's
Playstation video game player, but has also been a participant in
the market for disk-drive controllers.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes four days after Hyundai, a unit of
Hyundai Motor Co., and Adaptec Inc., the leading producer of SCSI
devices, ended an earlier accord in which Adaptec planned to buy
Symbios for $775 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Adaptec said it had learned that the Federal Trade Commission
was unlikely to approve that merger because of the combined
companies' apparent domination of the SCSI market. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
