<SLUG> BC-BKN-BIRD-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARRY BIRD ELECTED TO BASKETBALL HALL OF FAME  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He could not jump and he could not run, especially when his
aching back acted up. But Larry Bird could play basketball, and
Monday he received the ultimate confirmation of that when he was
elected to the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people were elected. Three were players: Bird in his first
year of eligibility; Marques Haynes, who played more than 40 years
with the Harlem Globetrotters and then the Harlem Magicians, and
Arnie Risen, who played 13 seasons for three teams in the National
Basketball League and then the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Four new members were coaches: Lenny Wilkens, now with the
Atlanta Hawks, who was elected as a player in 1989; Alex Hannum,
who coached 13 seasons for five teams in the NBA and the American
Basketball Association; Jody Conradt, who compiled a 592-146 record
with the University of Texas women's team, and Aleksandr Nikolic,
who coached Yugoslavia to the 1977 European championship and the
1978 world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Bird, a 6-foot-9-inch forward, played 13 seasons with the Boston
Celtics and led them to NBA championships in 1981, 1984 and 1986.
He was voted the league's most valuable player three times and an
All-Star 12 times. He retired in 1992. Last season, he became coach
of the Indiana Pacers, led them to the Eastern Conference finals
and was voted the NBA's coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, it's a great honor,'' he said. ``I am very
honored to be part of the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird's election was anticipated. It was also warmly received.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a guy who got the ultimate out of his own abilities,''
Oscar Robertson, another Hall of Fame player, told the Associated
Press. ``Because Larry, as far as having all the great athletic
ability, didn't have that. But he had a tremendous knowledge of the
game of basketball, and he was settled in the way he played. He was
a great basketball player, and he deserves to be in the Hall of
Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird quit early in his freshman year at Indiana University
before he ever played for Bob Knight and had to be talked into
transferring to Indiana State and playing again. Mel Daniels was an
assistant coach at Indiana State when Bird led the team to the NCAA
final in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``His love for the game and how effective he was at playing
basketball kind of made him understand that basketball had to be a
big part of his life,'' Daniels said.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bird's election to the Hall of Fame, Daniels said simply,
``That's where he's supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
