<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Doctors Make Online House Call  
   
 By Carl T. Hall  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Getting answers to medical questions has always been one of the
prime reasons people go on the Internet. But while the Web is full
of health-related chatter, it's rife with misinformation and hype
about unproven treatments.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, some of the nation's top medical educators are wading
gingerly into the mess, hoping to add some long-needed quality
control and at the same time garner a little online visibility for
their institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to find junk on the Internet,'' said Dr. Tom
Ferguson, an Austin, Texas, physician and online-medicine expert.
``There's a lot of variability, but in many cases you can get stuff
now that's better than what you get from a doctor's office.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at San Francisco has begun
collaborating with Oregon-based Sapient Health Networks, a
for-profit company that sponsors medical chat rooms for people with
certain chronic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, nurses and other UCSF experts regularly log on as
moderators during discussions of subjects including weight control,
depression, heart disease, diabetes and cancer. A segment on
women's health includes topics such as menopause and uterine
fibroids.
</P>
<P>
   Chat rooms let people message each other online in real time.
Unlike Internet bulletin boards, chat rooms offer the advantage of
live conversation, but the content cannot be censored, and the
conversation gets confusing when multiple participants are all
typing at once.
</P>
<P>
   Other credibility-conscious Web sites include
 &LR; www.intelihealth.com &LR; , sponsored by Johns Hopkins University and
Aetna U.S. Healthcare. The site includes an ``Ask-The-Doc'' feature
that lets you post questions to Johns Hopkins physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. C. Everett Koop, the former U.S. surgeon general, will have
his own site _  &LR; www.koop.com  &LR; _ &LR;   &LR; in about two weeks. Plans include
online support groups monitored by Koop and a panel of medical
experts.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the UCSF venture say the Internet is ideal for
consumer health research if the quality problems can be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides a level of support you can't get in any other
medium,'' said JoAnne Saxe, a nurse practitioner and associate
clinical professor at the UCSF School of Nursing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Teresa Wright, an expert on liver diseases, helps guide a
burgeoning group interested in hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some risks, but I think it's also a good opportunity
to get some information out to people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sapient chats, generally an hour long, are open only to
registered participants, but there's no fee to sign up and the
sponsors promise never to divulge your identity. Registration
forms, technical details and a schedule of the discussions can be
found at  &LR; www.shn.net,  &LR; which also includes transcripts of past
chat sessions arranged by subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   The site has about 100,000 registered users and is signing up
about 2,000 newcomers a week, said James Kean, Sapient's president
and co-founder &LR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; The goal, he added, is to create a useful ``community
experience'' for people going through the intensely personal
experience of a chronic illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want a framework to help assess all the information
that's out there,'' Kean said. ``They want a reliable source for
all the breaking news that might concern them, and there's a real
urge to be connected to a community _ but it's got to be a
high-quality community.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no sure way to keep out fad promoters and disguised
commercial interests. But advance registration seems to help keep a
semblance of control.
</P>
<P>
   The moderators, backed by a cadre of well-informed patients and
family members, try to keep the discussions on point, frequently
challenging those making unsubstantiated claims or adding caveats
where needed.
</P>
<P>
   Sapient is relying on a business strategy that does not hinge on
building huge collections of eyeballs for advertisers, as is the
case for the big health-discussion groups on AOL and other online
services.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sapient frequently conducts online surveys of its
customers, compiling answers into closely targeted consumer
research reports for drug companies and device makers.
</P>
<P>
   Such surveys are hot commodities given the quick turnaround time
and high degree of ``purity'' in the populations being sampled. A
single report can sell for $10,000 to $100,000, Kean said.
</P>
<P>
   Sapient guarantees to keep your identity _ and e-mail address _
private. Participants select an online pseudonym.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are suspicious of health care companies. We consider
ourselves an intermediary,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
