<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0505 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2874 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILTON-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      06-29 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILTON-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILTON GAMBLING SPLIT-OFF SEEN, THEN MERGER WITH GRAND CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Nev., N.J., Miss.)  (10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET EMBARGO for
electronic media.) 
(af) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hilton Hotels Corp. is expected to announce on
Tuesday that it will split its hotel and gambling operations into
separate companies and will merge the gaming company with the
Mississippi gambling operations of Grand Casinos Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton shareholders are expected to receive one share in each of
the gaming and hotel companies for each share they now own,
according to executives close to the situation. Grand Casinos is
expected to spin off its Mississippi operations into a separate
company. The Hilton gaming unit and Grand Casinos' Mississippi
spinoff would then merge in a pooling of interests.
</P>
<P>
   The price for Grand Casinos will depend on the value of the
stock in Hilton's gaming company and the value of the stock in
Grand Casinos' Mississippi operations and on the ratio in which
they are exchanged in the merger. Grand Casinos has a market value
of $780 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton executives have said in the past that splitting the
companies will benefit shareholders by freeing the hotel business,
which is doing well, from the gambling business, which is under
pressure because of a glut of hotel rooms in Las Vegas, Nev. Now,
officials and analysts have said, Hilton's stock price is being
held back by its association with the gaming business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the gaming business is kind of the Rodney
Dangerfield of the stock market,'' Hilton's chief executive,
Stephen F. Bollenbach, told securities analysts in April in a
conference call to discuss earnings. He said that splitting the
Beverly Hills company was a high priority because Hilton's shares
were trading at ``a conglomerate discount.''
</P>
<P>
   Combining Hilton's gaming business with that of Grand Casinos
would create a gambling giant with a presence in the nation's three
largest gaming markets. The two companies have little overlap, with
Hilton strong in Las Vegas and Atlantic City, while Grand is the
largest operator of casinos in Mississippi. Grand also manages
three Indian casinos, but that part of its business will not go to
Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Hilton and Grand Casinos said Monday that it was
their policy not to comment on rumors.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, if it goes through, would make the third time a charm
for Bollenbach, who has faltered in two previous attempts at
mergers and is under shareholder pressure to achieve some deal.
``Our shareholders expect us to be a transactional company,'' he
told analysts earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Hilton failed last year in a protracted attempt to buy the
ITT Corp., which owned the Sheraton hotel chain and Caesars
casinos. ITT was taken over instead by Starwood Hotels and Resorts
Trust.
</P>
<P>
   This year, merger talks between Hilton and Circus Circus
Enterprises broke down. The companies were negotiating a split of
Hilton to be followed by a combination of its gaming business with
Circus _ a deal similar to what is expected on Tuesday. But the
talks fell apart over price and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Those missteps have slightly tarnished the reputation Bollenbach
had earned as a savvy deal maker for his major roles in splitting
the old Marriott Corp. into two companies, rescuing Donald J.
Trump's troubled empire and engineering the Walt Disney Co.'s
acquisition of ABC.
</P>
<P>
   He was recruited to run Hilton in early 1996 by Barron Hilton,
the son of the founder and now the company's chairman, and promptly
bought Bally Entertainment for about $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the timing of the latest deal could raise some eyebrows.
Tuesday is the deadline for Hilton to enter into a major
transaction that would entitle Bollenbach to accelerated vesting of
his stock options under his employment contract. But a Hilton
spokesman has said that Bollenbach voluntarily waived those rights
so as to avoid the appearance that he was pushing Hilton into a
transaction for his own gain.
</P>
<P>
   Hilton has been wanting to split into two companies but decided
it also needed a merger to provide a business purpose that would
bolster the deal's chances of qualifying for tax-free status. In
addition, the combination with Grand Casinos would add some heft to
the gaming company, although Hilton by itself is already among the
world's largest gambling companies.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected that Arthur M. Goldberg, the head of Hilton's
gaming operations, will run the combined gaming company, though
Grand Casinos management is also expected to be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Grand Casinos slipped 6.25 cents Monday, to $18.50,
and Hilton shares rose 81.25 cents, to $31.50, both on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   There was an extraordinarily high volume of trading in Grand
Casinos Inc. options last Friday as rumors of a deal spread.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Casinos has grown quickly from a start running one Indian
casino in 1991. In 1997 it had net income of $66.1 million on
revenue of $607.4 million. Most of the revenue came from its three
Mississippi casinos. But Grand Casinos stumbled badly in its
investment in the Stratosphere hotel in Las Vegas, which filed for
bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Casinos wrote off its entire investment. Its contracts to
manage Indian casinos, which will be the main business of the
company that is not spun off to merge with Hilton, are set to
expire by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Of more concern to Hilton is that next year Mirage Resorts,
generally considered the builder of the nation's most spectacular
casinos, will open a major resort near Grand Casinos' operations in
Biloxi and Gulfport. That could draw business away from Grand
Casinos, although it could also attract more gamblers to the area
and actually help Grand Casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have speculated that once Hilton's hotel
operations are free from its gaming business, it could be an
acquisition candidate or make an acquisition on its own. Hilton has
had some discussions with Ladbroke Group PLC, the British company
that controls the Hilton brand outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although talks on a merger do not seem to have gone very far,
the companies have agreed on a common, worldwide logo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
