<P>
   (NYT12) GREENWICH, Conn. -- June 29, 1998 -- STANTONS-RIGHTS,
6-29 -- In 1848, an upstate New York housewife named Elizabeth Cady
Stanton assembled a convention in a Seneca Falls church and made
the radical demand that women be allowed to vote. The fourth, fifth
and sixth generation of descendants of Elizabeth Stanton: from
right, great-great granddaughter Coline Jenkins-Sahlin, 46; her
mother, Rhoda Jenkins, 77; and her daughter, Elizabeth
Jenkins-Sahlin, 13. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- June 29, 1998 -- SCI-CHU-PHYSICS,
6-29 -- Dr. Steven Chu discusses an experiment with graduate
students Joel Hensley, center, and Kurt Franke. Chu, the master of
manipulating atoms and molecules who shared the most recent Nobel
Prize in Physics with two other researchers, alternates taking
phone calls with bantering about projects that combine conceptual
simplicity and a faint air of unbelievability. ``I'm drawn towards
the wilder, science-fiction-type stuff,'' he says. (Susan Spann/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOMBAY, India -- June 29, 1998 -- INDIA-BUSINESS-LUNCH,
6-29 -- The intricate trade of the tiffin-wallah has changed little
in 130 years. Jaganath Adav pushes a handcart filled with
home-cooked lunches through Bombay's business district. By all
accounts, the system is virtually fail-safe, aside from train
strikes or accidents, or the unreported sickness or death of a
carrier. Ask a tiffin-wallah when he last failed a customer, and he
will scratch his head. ``Never, that I remember,'' says Adav. (John
F. Burns/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MILAN, Italy -- June 29, 1998 -- MILAN-MENS-FASHION-2,
6-29 -- Romance has come to men's wear here, an apt development in
the age of Viagra. From left, a gray Mao-inspired suit from Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana; Jil Sander's white jacket with rolled-cuff pants; Issey
Miyake's chartreuse and black shirt and mauve pants. (Dan Lecca/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MILAN, Italy -- June 29, 1998 -- MILAN-MENS-FASHION-1,
6-29 -- Romance has come to men's wear here, an apt development in
the age of Viagra. From left, Jil Sander's sheer green sweater and
parachute shorts; At Versace, a pale blue sweater with embroidered
pants; Dolce &AMP; Gabbana sweater inspired by Jackson Pollack; (Dan
Lecca/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 29, 1998 -- FOWL-THEATER-REVIEW, 6-29 --
Susan Vitucci working a puppet in her comedy ``Love's Fowl'' Q
essentially the tale of Chicken Little as told by puppets made of
wooden clothespins. The production uses three screens. One carries
an English translation of the Italian lyrics. The two others carry
the magnified images of the puppets manipulated by Ms. Vitucci, who
wrote the canny and clever libretto and sings to the sprightly
music (and occasional voice) of Henry Krieger. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SANTA MONICA, Calif. -- June 29, 1998 -- BEAD-ART, 6-29
-- Liza Lou in her new installation, ``Back Yard,'' on display at
the Santa Monica Museum of Art through July 5. What makes this
life-size yard unique is that the lawn itself, along with
everything on it, is formed by millions of tiny glass beads. ``The
work takes so long that you don't have a sense of achievement or
accomplishment on a daily basis; you feel like a failure every
day,'' she says. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 29, 1998 -- NEESON-BROADWAY-2, 6-29 --
Liam Neeson as a countryman, Oscar Wilde, in ``The Judas Kiss:''
``He was very, very Irish,'' says Neeson, who has developed a
system by which he exorcises the character when the curtain goes
down, in order to live as a sane person at least a few hours of the
day. ``I'm helped by a wonderful dresser called Helen Toth, and a
glass of the best French red wine I can get.'' (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 29, 1998 -- NEESON-BROADWAY-1, 6-29 --
Liam Neeson is starring in ``The Judas Kiss.'' He plays Oscar Wilde
in two conditions: doomed and drained. ``It's hard, you know,''
says Neeson. ``It's such an emotional journey for me every day.
He's practically a broken man, which two years' hard labor did to
him.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LONDON -- June 29, 1998 -- BRITAIN-U.S., 6-29 -- John
Tusa, managing director of the Barbican Center in London, where
``Inventing America,'' a $4.8 million, 10-month festival of
American culture is being held. The Barbican has called it the
biggest festival of its kind ever held outside the United States.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) FLORENCE, Italy -- June 29, 1998 -- SCI-PIETA, 6-29 --
Michelangelo's Florentine Pieta in the Museo dell'Opera del Duomo.
One day, without explanation, the artist took a sledgehammer to it,
nearly destroying the work before one of his servants dragged him
away. Eventually it was patched together by one of his less
talented assistants. Now, scientists, armed with special
photography equipment, lasers, X-ray machines and powerful
computers, will try to unravel the statue's mysteries. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) IRAQI DESERT -- June 29, 1998 --
SUB-SCI-ANCIENT-FAKE-ROCK, 6-29 -- Dr. Elizabeth Stone in the Iraqi
desert, where she found artificial stone in the ruins of
Mashkan-shapir, a 4,000-year-old Mesopotamian city. It was a
relatively large city of 15,000 people in the early second
millennium B.C., which, after a brief period of glory, declined and
was abandoned in 1720 B.C. Mashkan-shapir's ruins disappeared in
the desert until archeologists began digging there in this century.
(Dr. Elizabeth Stone/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
