<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NY-IMMIGRANTS-N     06-29 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NY-IMMIGRANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE PRACTICAL, SAY CHINESE-AMERICANS IN BACKING CLINTON'S TRIP
</HEADLINE>
   (See related stories: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-DAY, CHINA-TRADE,
CHINA-TV-COVERAGE, CHINA-PEONY) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As President Clinton deflects criticism from both
politicians in the United States and students in Beijing over his
trip to China, he is finding unwavering _ and somewhat surprising _
support from Chinese immigrants in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether they originally hailed from mainland
China, Taiwan or Hong Kong, immigrants in the New York metropolitan
area have applauded Clinton's trip, saying his mission benefits
both the United States and China for economic, political and
cultural reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, critics in Washington accused Clinton of kowtowing to
a government with a human rights record that only brutal regimes
would envy. Monday, Chinese students at Beijing University grilled
Clinton as well, questioning whether the United States was secretly
trying to isolate China politically.
</P>
<P>
   But as Clinton continues his trip to the world's largest
totalitarian state, interviews with more than two dozen Chinese
immigrants interviewed over two days revealed a more practical
assessment: Human rights are secondary to economic progress and
Sino-American relations. And anyone who disagrees with that, they
say bluntly, simply does not understand China, or the Chinese
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think most Americans understand why Clinton's trip is
so good,'' said Daniel Chao, 35, of Edison, N.J., who grew up in
Shanghai and was eating Sunday at Joe's Shanghai in Flushing,
Queens. ``It's very important for the long-term Sino-American
relationship that Clinton have a chance to get first-hand
information, and talk about the real issues with the Chinese
leaders and the Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the immigrants say, Clinton's trip has
tremendous symbolic value for people who, invariably, place a lot
of meaning on symbols and gestures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all Chinese, and this raises the profile of all Chinese
people,'' said Johnson Wang, 67, of Jersey City, N.J., a
Taiwanese-American who was purchasing lottery tickets at the Port
Authority Bus Terminal in Manhattan on Sunday. ``We are especially
proud of the fact that this trip is nine days _ the longest ever by
Clinton!''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, it might appear that Chinese immigrants would
have disparate views. After all, Chinese immigrants in New York
include the old guard from Taiwan and Hong Kong, who have been
major backers of Taiwan's Nationalist government, and political
arrivistes from Fujian province in southern China, who have been
partial to China's Communist Government. Throw in smaller segments
of people whose modus operandi range from Taiwan independence to
Tibetan independence, and the result is a fluid, vibrant community
that, more often than not, agrees to disagree.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to matters of national or ethnic pride, many
Chinese immigrants cast typical allegiances aside. Blood, not
politics, prevails.
</P>
<P>
   So it went with the return of Hong Kong to Chinese sovereignty
in 1997. So it went with President Jiang Zemin's visit to New York
in December. And so it has gone with Clinton's trip.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of the immigrants interviewed failed to mention the
eminence of economic reform and Sino-American trade relations when
asked about the vital points of Clinton's trip. It is through
economic reform, they say, that China will become a freer society.
</P>
<P>
   Political reform, they added, is a consequence of economic
reform _ and should be treated accordingly. Even the 1989 massacre
in Tiananmen Square _ considered by many Americans to be the symbol
of the Chinese regime _ is viewed by most Chinese-Americans as an
incident that, while tragic, should be consigned to history.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened, happened,'' said Jane Eng, a Hong Kong
immigrant and manager of the Nancy Wedding Center, a bustling
bridal shop on the Bowery. ``We cannot just sit here and wait for a
conclusion. We have to take the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason why Chinese-Americans may appear to be
relatively blase about human rights is that their definition of
what a person's basic rights ought to be is different from what
other Americans usually think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human rights are the ability to have enough food, clothing,
education and shelter,'' said Chunde Shi, 36, a former urban
planner in Beijing who now works as a computer consultant in the
New York area. ``Only after you have these can you think about
things like democracy and freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0512 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NIRELAND-NYT &LR;      06-29 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NIRELAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW ALLIANCES IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 30:
</P>
<P>
   The week ahead contains two important events in Northern
Ireland. Wednesday the region's new assembly will meet for the
first time, and Sunday marks the date of the most explosive of the
yearly parades. In both cases, a small group of determined
opponents can thwart the desire for peace expressed by the great
majority of voters.
</P>
<P>
   The parades, celebrating Protestant victories of 300 years ago,
are an annual source of tension. This year the British government
took the smart step of forming a bipartisan commission to rule on
the routes marchers may take. Monday the commission decided that
the Orange Order may not take its Drumcree march through the
Catholic Garvaghy Road in Portadown. The Orange Order has refused
to comply. Catholic residents, equally intransigent, vow to greet
the march with a protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary must uphold the parade
commission's ruling, which is the law, and do so without the heavy
use of plastic bullets and other violent measures. Britain has
wisely sent reinforcements, in the form of 1,000 soldiers. But the
best solution would be a compromise between local Catholics and
Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   While the parade season looks dishearteningly familiar, the
opening of the new assembly shows that things are changing in
Northern Ireland. The 108 members elected last week meet for the
first time Wednesday. The assembly can work only if politicians
break out of their sectarian thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Members will choose a first minister, who is expected to be
David Trimble, leader of the Protestant Ulster Unionist Party. His
deputy is likely to be John Hume, head of the largely Catholic
Social Democratic and Labor Party. Trimble will find himself
governing a body and heading a cabinet that includes Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the Irish Republican Army. He still does not
speak to its members. But he is now Sinn Fein's ally in making the
assembly work, against the hard-line Protestants whose views he
once shared. That journey took courage and vision.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-liners oppose the peace agreement, especially because
the assembly will get no powers until a body linking its members
with Irish legislators is in place. They have nearly enough members
to sabotage the assembly on key votes, so a few defections from
Trimble's party would be fatal. That threat makes Trimble very
vulnerable to pressure from the small anti-accord group.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein's president, Gerry Adams, like Trimble, faces a
paradox. He badly needs to prevent those Ulster Unionists from
defecting. He could help by joining Trimble in pressing the IRA to
begin giving up its arms. The idea of cross-community alliances is
startling and strange for Northern Ireland. When they happen, we
will know that the peace process is working. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0513 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2884 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-DAY-1STLD-WRITE     06-29 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DAY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(950)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS SEE LIVE ACCESS TO CHINESE TV AS HIGHLIGHT OF SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Changes ``his Oxford-educated Chinese counterpart'' to ``his
Cambridge-educated Chinese counterpart, Yang Jiechi'' in 2nd graf
of 2nd take. No other changes.)  (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-TRADE, CHINA-TV-COVERAGE,
CHINA-PEONY) 
(ps) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ It was not until minutes before the Saturday
news conference by President Clinton and President Jiang Zemin that
the Chinese leader decided to allow the event to be broadcast live.
</P>
<P>
   And Jiang did not inform the United States that he would permit
the broadcast of Clinton's Beijing University speech on Monday
until less than an hour before the address was to begin.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said Monday that they were elated at both
decisions, which had been a central demand of the United States and
gave an American President unfiltered access to the Chinese people
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   American officials also said that progress at the summit on the
spread of weapons technology and the joint agreement not to aim
nuclear weapons at each other's cities were important, though
largely symbolic. It was the live television access to the Chinese
audience that made the summit meeting a breakthrough, according to
American officials.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials were still puzzling over just what
prompted Jiang to make the call.
</P>
<P>
   One theory they put forward to reporters as Clinton flew from
the Chinese capital to Shanghai was that Jiang used Clinton as a
sort of ventriloquist's dummy to raise the most sensitive topics in
Chinese society and then to defend his position to the Chinese
people and to reactionaries in his own government.
</P>
<P>
   Another school of thought was that Jiang knew how much the
American side valued access to the Chinese audience, and was not
willing to risk harming the relationship by denying that access.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that these decisions were made at the
highest level, by Jiang himself,'' said a senior American official.
``One can only speculate about his motivation. They recognized that
the price of engagement with us was giving us access to their
people. Jiang knew he needed to do that to make this a successful
summit.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained uncertain how deep or lasting an impact these events
would have on Chinese politics and society. Nor was it likely that
Clinton had silenced his critics at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real answer is going to come not from American officials,
but, of course, from the people of China,'' said Stanley Roth,
assistant secretary of state for East Asia. ``And we've seen
repeated quotes in the press from people indicating that it will
have profound reverberations from here. I think this will be
percolating within China for quite some time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's aides were unreservedly crowing Monday about the
``extraordinary,'' and ``historic'' summit meeting, and they
arranged a briefing for reporters by a senior official to talk ``on
background'' about all the 18 months of preparation Clinton and his
staff had made to pull off the event.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day meeting in Beijing was the fruit of a risky decision
in November 1996 to conduct reciprocal summit meetings in
Washington and Beijing without any conditions, and thus no
guarantee of success, the official said, giving this account of
what happened:
</P>
<P>
   The first of the two summit meetings, in Washington in October,
was judged a success by both sides. The meeting produced a handful
of substantive agreements, including China's pledge to stop sending
missiles to Iran and aiding Pakistan's nuclear program, and a
deepening of the personal relationship between Clinton and Jiang.
The two countries set up a bug-proof hotline between their
capitals, a link that was used for the first time in May after the
Indian nuclear tests. It was the first time that an American
President and a Chinese leader had spoken by telephone, according
to American officials.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere for the meeting in Beijing was more difficult,
the official said, with controversies swirling in the United States
over allegations of Chinese meddling in the 1996 Presidential
election and the suspected pilfering of sensitive American
technology through the launch of American satellites on Chinese
rockets.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials turned the difficult domestic
climate to their advantage, according to an account by a
high-ranking participant. The crescendo of criticism and a series
of congressional hearings on Chinese missiles and money put Clinton
in a quandary. He could cancel the summit meeting _ as 151 members
of Congress demanded _ or he could travel to Beijing without any
assurance that the meeting would bring results.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the president's national security adviser, went to
Beijing the first week of June with two messages for Jiang. He told
the Chinese leader that Clinton was ``unshakable'' in his
determination to make the summit meeting. But, he added, the
meeting had to produce a positive outcome or risk giving Clinton's
critics new ammunition and setting back United States-China
relations for months, or longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was not a summit that moved the relationship forward,
it would feed the critics back home,'' a senior administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions boiled down to one central concern on the
American side, which they believed would nurture the relationship
while quieting domestic critics: Clinton must have access to the
Chinese people, through television, radio and public appearances
that were not unduly restricted by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese leadership was noncommittal on the access question,
as well as the substantive matters still under discussion _ the
targeting of nuclear missiles, the spread of weapons technology and
human rights. Berger returned to Washington uneasy about the
meeting, then less than three weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``As always with the Chinese, nothing much happens before the
end game,'' a senior White House aide said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Berger's deputy, James Steinberg, flew to Beijing on June 22,
four days before Clinton was to arrive in China, to try to nail
down progress on the nuclear targeting plan and China's membership
in an international non-proliferation agreement known as the
Missile Technology Control Regime.
</P>
<P>
   After hours of word-by-word negotiation of the statement on the
missile agreement, Steinberg and his Cambridge-educated Chinese
counterpart, Yang Jiechi, agreed that the two nations would
announce that China would ``actively consider joining'' the missile
accord. American officials consider that a significant step that
will ultimately lead to China's acceptance of international rules
governing sales of medium- and long-range missiles capable of
carrying nuclear, biological and chemical warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The talks on the targeting of nuclear missiles went down to the
wire. On Friday, American officials expressed doubt that a deal
could be reached, because the Chinese insisted that the United
States renounce any first use of nuclear weapons, a policy change
the United States was unwilling to make. Agreement was finally
reached late Friday night, and was announced Saturday morning at
the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   One large question remained: Would Jiang permit the live
broadcast? Although American officials did not indicate in advance
that Clinton intended to criticize the Chinese crackdown on
pro-democracy protesters in Tiananmen Square in 1989, Jiang
appeared prepared for the rhetorical broadside. And he in fact
invited Clinton to respond to his comments on Tibet and other human
rights issues, rather than curtailing the news conference, as he
easily could have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
