<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ABORTION-FOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A DEVIOUS ATTACK ON CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 30:
</P>
<P>
   The Republican effort to curtail abortion rights took a stealthy
and dangerous turn last week when the House voted 223-202 to
prohibit the Food and Drug Administration from testing or approving
any drug that induces abortion, including RU-486, a drug that the
FDA has approved for use in controlled studies. For several years
now, anti-abortion forces have tried to win public support by
focusing their rhetoric on late-term abortions. This latest move
shows that they want to block all methods, including the earliest
and least invasive forms of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents say the measure, which is attached to a $56
billion agriculture appropriations bill, merely prevents taxpayer
money from being used to facilitate abortion. But unlike bans on
federal funding for abortions, which are already in place, this
measure goes a step further.
</P>
<P>
   It directly attacks the ability of the FDA to review abortion
drugs, and would essentially outlaw this method of abortion even if
it is safe and effective. Moreover, the House sets a terrible
precedent by loading ideology on the drug approval process. If this
is allowed to stand, the public's access to effective drugs will
become a matter of politics, decided by members of Congress rather
than clinical research.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate should reject this measure as a dangerous intrusion
into the functions of the FDA as well as an attack on the
constitutionally protected right to choose abortion. President
Clinton must also make clear that he will veto the agriculture
appropriations bill if it arrives on his desk containing this kind
of limitation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
