<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0520 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NBA-LOCKOUT-NYT &LR;      06-29 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NBA-LOCKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SEASON WITHOUT A DUNK? 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, June 30:
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association, unlike professional
football, baseball and hockey, has never had its games disrupted by
a labor dispute. That may be about to change.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA owners say they are paying the players so much that the
league is no longer profitable, and so they will lock out the
players, beginning at midnight Tuesday night, until the players'
union agrees to a method to hold down the growth of salaries.
</P>
<P>
   For basketball fans, the first impact of this dispute will be in
the world championships this summer. The team of NBA stars that was
to play for the United States will now stay home, to be replaced by
a team chosen from players either in college or not good enough to
be in the NBA. That will make for a more competitive tournament
that the American team will be unlikely to win.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA now has a ``cap'' on total team salaries, but that cap
has done a better job of holding down the salaries of rookies and
of journeymen players than it has of halting the escalation of star
salaries. The rules allow a team to pay any amount it wishes to
re-sign its own players, enabling the Chicago Bulls to pay $33
million to Michael Jordan last season, when the supposed cap for an
entire team was $26.9 million. Younger stars try to maneuver their
way onto richer teams that will be able to pay cap-busting
salaries. The owners want a new contract that will bar them from
throwing so much money at the best players.
</P>
<P>
   Under the league's current contract, salaries of rookies and
journeymen players have been reined in to some extent. More players
now make something close to the league minimum _ currently $272,000
for veterans _ than once did, and young stars are limited to less
than $3 million a year until their fourth year. The fact that stars
cannot truly cash in until their fourth year has encouraged college
undergraduates and even high school players to turn pro as soon as
they can, so that the fourth year will come when they are still
relatively young.
</P>
<P>
   Each side appears to be entering this lockout convinced that the
other will cave. The NBA's television contracts will keep money
coming in all season even if no games are played. The players think
they have a legal trump card, which they could play by dissolving
their union and then arguing that antitrust laws bar any limits on
salaries in the absence of a collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   It is obviously in both sides' interests to make a deal. But
rationality does not always prevail in labor talks, and this could
be a confrontation in which no one blinks until a large part of the
season _ or even all of it _ has been canceled. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
