</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES CHINA'S ECONOMIC FUTURE IN SHANGHAI 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Midway through his nine-day journey, President
Clinton ventured Tuesday into China's financial capital to view
first hand the rapid economic changes in this nation's largest
city.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his entourage of 1,000 left Beijing Monday night
after a series of historic sessions with Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and the unprecedented live broadcast of his address to Peking
University students.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials touted the president's speech and a
series of economic agreements as proof that a new relationship
between the United States and China was well underway.
</P>
<P>
   No where is the new China on better display that in this city of
13 million where entrepreneurs are becoming millionaires as this
communist country turns toward a more market-oriented economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, Shanghai is the future of China because of the
changes that are taking place in China are reflected in the very
dynamic growth, economically, and the changes occurring in South
China,'' said White House spokesman Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president ``will see that and literally be a
part of that over the coming days.'' Clinton's visit mirrors
Jiang's visit to the United States last October when he visited New
York and Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to tour the Shanghai Library and meet with local
community leaders to discuss the shaping of China for the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   The new Shanghai Library houses more than 1 million volumes and
contains the latest technology, including Internet access. The tour
and discussion afterward will help Clinton underscore a major
message here: that the new information age will require China to
have a more open society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, touring the library is an opportunity for him to
make vivid the argument he made today, that information
technologies and the flow of information will inevitably produce
change in China. And touring the library will be a dramatic part of
that,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's two-day stay here, he will appear on a radio
talk show and take questions from callers as well as meet with U.S.
business executives and Shanghai's young entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the size of Clinton's entourage, the delegation contains
no business executives, who usually make up a portion of the group
accompanying the president. Clinton already is under fire from
critics for emphasizing trade over human rights and from
Republicans who accuse him of altering U.S. export policy to China
to benefit a business executive who contributed money to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   However, McCurry said a business delegation was not as critical
as it was when Clinton toured Africa earlier this year. ``This is
not a case of the president needing to bring business with him to
China; they are literally already here, and they're interested in
what we can do to further the relationship and to be of
assistance,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials were thrilled by China's decision to air
Clinton's remarks to Peking University students live on television
and radio. The live broadcast followed a similar decision to air a
news conference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what it is is evidence of the way in which the
president's policy has worked and has been successful in terms of
engagement,'' said Sandy Kristoff, the Asian affairs expert at the
National Security Council. ``What engagement really means is that
you can work through your differences, continue to agree to
disagree and continue to fight, not pull any punches, and at the
same time, produce results and cooperate in areas where you do have
shared interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Shirk, deputy assistant secretary of state for East Asia,
said it would not be possible for China to bury the controversial
subjects of the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre nor the issue of
Tibet following the Clinton-Jiang news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, as to what happens next, we don't know. I don't think it
would be wise to say this opens up a whole new era in China, but it
was a very self-conscious decision on President Jiang's part to
allow this kind of open discussion on previously taboo ideas,''
Shirk said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also touted a series of agreements, such as
opening China to Peace Corps volunteers and initiating new programs
to help China strengthen its legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic controversy in the United States caused by
Clinton's decision to allow U.S. companies to use Chinese rockets
to launch satellites also is reverberating here. Critics contend
Loral Space &AMP; Communications Ltd., owned by a major Clinton backer,
illegally passed on missile information that allowed China to
improve its rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an urgency for us to tell the Chinese we need to
talk to them, we need to engage them and talk about these issues.
The tack we've been taking with the Chinese is that it is very
important that we have transparency and dialogue in our
relationship, so that we can work together to clear up
misunderstandings and provide information to the people in the
United States who have concerns about these issues,'' said Alan
Turley, a commercial affairs expert based at the U.S. Embassy in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the openness displayed during the president's visit,
Chinese police continued their close watch on dissidents, detaining
yet another democracy activist who was attempting to set up an
opposition political party. It was the sixth dissident rounded up
during President Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
