<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS LOOKING FOR TRADE OPPORTUNITIES BEFORE LOCKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks were still talking to teams about making a
trade before Tuesday night's midnight deadline while waiting for
the Charles Oakley trade to become official.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley was traded to Toronto for Marcus Camby last Wednesday. To
complete the deal, Oakley was supposed to arrive in Toronto for his
physical Monday at noon, but he was not on his scheduled flight.
One league official said the deadline for Oakley to report was
extended to 5 p.m. Tuesday. If Oakley fails to show up, according
to the league official, the Raptors have to either void the deal or
waive the physical for the 34-year-old forward.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Raptors and Knicks said they expected Oakley
to arrive and pass his physical, clearing the way for the deal to
go through before the league's lockout is scheduled to begin at
midnight Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, all player-related business between teams will
cease. That leaves the Knicks with a small window of time to
complete a deal for a point guard. As of Monday, there was no trade
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything can pop up,'' the team president, Ernie Grunfeld,
said. ``But in all likelihood, this is what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have shown interest in Milwaukee's Terrell Brandon,
the former Laker Nick Van Exel and the former Sun Steve Nash.
However, Van Exel was traded to the Nuggets and Vancouver acquired
Nash last week, and their new teams appear eager to hold on to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon is still a possibility. But a deal for him would be a
better salary-cap fit for both teams after the lockout ends and
players are under next year's salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Once Brandon's balloon payment of $7 million for next year kicks
in, the Bucks, if they are under the salary cap, would be able to
take back multiple players in a deal. In such a scenario, the
Knicks could send Milwaukee Chris Childs, John Starks and Chris
Mills. Under his current pre-July 1 salary, Brandon, a base-year
compensation player, makes just $1.6 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
