r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-COLUMN-LA     06-29 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BRUISED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Tex. _ Gary Sheffield emerged from the pile Sunday
night bloody and defiant. That was the problem.
</P>
<P>
   His fight with Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall in the sixth inning
and the Dodgers leading by three runs was not a call to arms. It
was an massive error in judgment that reaches far beyond the
Pirates' eventual comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of heading on the road hoping to put behind six weeks of
chaos, the Dodgers dragged Sunday along with them. And the mess
didn't just stop at Sheffield. Eric Karros, Wilton Guerrero, Adrian
Beltre, Roger Cedeno and manager Glenn Hoffman all sat at the table
of baseball's most dysfunctional family. And it is certain to get
worse before it gets better.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield set the tone when he went after Kendall, the Pirates'
best player. First he knocked off Kendall's helmet during a near
collision at home plate, then didn't like what the catcher had to
say.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield already had a two-run homer, an RBI single and his
foot on the neck of the Pirates, who were 10 outs from getting
swept in a three-game series. Why he didn't walk away and let the
team move onto Texas feeling good is a strange call for the
Dodgers' best player.
</P>
<P>
   Victories bring their own swagger. Going after the only name on
the other team doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   It could be argued that Kendall is a hothead who has had run-ins
with other top players. It also could be said that last season's
brawl with the Angels after Chan Ho park hit Tony Phillips helped
ignite the Dodgers and get them back in the race. But emotionally
that team was like the '27 Yankees compared to this one. Walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield has been the most productive Dodger on the field since
the May 15 Mike Piazza trade. Off the field he has been even
better.
</P>
<P>
   There are children's groups and scholarships that seldom get
mentioned. But Dodgers fans didn't get a World Series ring like he
did last year in Florida. They just want him to help the team win.
</P>
<P>
   After the lowly Pirates rallied with five runs in the final
three innings, everybody in the visiting clubhouse huddled around a
tiny television, looking for clues to the mayhem. More than the
punches thrown, they wanted to see what made the Dodgers come
unglued.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheffield/Kendall play began when Cedeno was picked off
first base by reliever Mike Williams. The Pirates pulled one of
those fake-to-third, throw-to-first plays that never work. Scouting
reports all over baseball are being rewritten. Cedeno, who the
Dodgers projected as their Opening Day center fielder, has been
responsible for a half dozen blunders this season. He has dropped
fly balls, tried to take third on ground balls to short and been
picked off in critical situations.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno had a nice little six-game hitting streak, but he is not
the answer, except for maybe some bad Dodgers trivia.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the Sheffield play, Karros set another bad tone.
Some might say he had good reason. But when the team is 39-42,
saving a season should be all that matters. Karros came in batting
.385 during a 10-game hitting streak. More important, he was
batting .345 with runners in scoring position during the streak and
.311 since returning to the cleanup spot.
</P>
<P>
   This is a guy who had three consecutive 30-homer, 100-RBI
seasons batting fourth. Sunday, he was dropped to fifth behind
Sheffield after the team had just won two straight.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who rehabs his left knee for hours before and after
games, wasn't around to talk about the move. He didn't have to. His
slumping body language said it all. The move was very questionable,
but Karros needed to show the kids he is on board.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of kids, Beltre no longer looks like the player who had
an RBI single on the first pitch he faced in the big leagues. He
looks like what he is, a Double-A third baseman with great
potential. Beltre is bright and composed. He also is 3 for 19 at
the plate and threw away a ground ball that led to the eventual
winning run.
</P>
<P>
   If this seems like picking on the Latin youngsters, nothing
could be further from the truth. Management needs to put them in
situations to succeed, not rush them into situations where they
can't help.
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't be the first time Hoffman is second-guessed as
a manager, having Guerrero at shortstop in the ninth inning when
the Dodgers had a chance to stop the mess.
</P>
<P>
   During Ismael Valdes' near perfect game on Saturday, Hoffman put
Juan Castro at short in the late innings. Sunday, he stayed with
Guerrero, who is a gifted hitter but moved from short to second
because of defensive problems. Now he was back at short and booted
Tony Womack's grounder that led to the Pirates final run.
</P>
<P>
   Just one game. But oh, what a story it told.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
