<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR CALLS KING A LIAR WHO DEFRAUDED AN INSURER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal prosecutor described Don King on Monday as
a liar who fraudulently collected $350,000 in insurance after a
1991 fight was canceled and then repeatedly deceived the boxer
Julio Cesar Chavez to perpetuate the scam.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments in U.S. District Court in Manhattan,
Christine Chung, an assistant U.S. attorney, told the jury that
King ``had the motive, means and opportunity'' to submit a phony
contract to a Lloyd's of London syndicate calling for repayment of
$350,000 in training expenses to Chavez, to backdate a $30,000
check to Chavez after the cancellation, to direct accountants to
file a fraudulent claim and to not pay Chavez when Lloyd's paid the
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have had help, but Don King did it,'' Chung said in her
three-and-a-half-hour summation. ``When you intersect all the lines
of proof, only one man is standing _ Don King.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 trial in the case ended in a mistrial. King was the only
defendant then; this time King and his company, Don King
Productions, were indicted on nine charges of wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Citing King's testimony in the 1995 trial, Chung said, ``He took
the stand and told lies, about things big and small.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Fleming Jr., one of King's lawyers, said in his closing
argument: ``I heard in the last five minutes the word `lie' as many
as 15 times. Do you see a single count of perjury against Don
King?''
</P>
<P>
   In his two-hour summation, Fleming tried to distance King from
any wrongdoing. ``In 1991, Don King Productions had revenues of $61
million,'' he said. ``And Mr. King is running around trying to
defraud Syndicate 370 of $350,000? Where lies the fraud? In the
United States? In London?''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming criticized the prosecution for hiding crucial facts from
the jury, which he said he had to bring out in cross-examination;
excoriated the testimony of government witnesses like Joseph
Maffia, King's former accountant and chief accuser, who was granted
immunity; and belittled insurance officials for giving depositions
on videotape in London but refusing to testify in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming also argued that the prosecution misinterpreted the
phrase ``maintenance non-refundable training expenses.'' The
prosecution contends that the $350,000 in expenses that the Lloyd's
syndicate reimbursed did not exist. Fleming said it consisted of
$80,000 paid in two checks to Chavez (which, he said, King took as
a loss) and $270,000 in what he called maintenance, to pay off
$736,000 that King had advanced Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming never addressed the prosecution's accusation that King,
or his company, submitted a phony contract to the Lloyd's
syndicate, one that Chavez did not sign, with the rider calling for
payment to Chavez of the $350,000 in non-refundable expenses.
Instead, Fleming asked, ``Is it a crime that the insurance company
wasn't told that the contract was modified?''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming continued, ``They want to convict because the insurance
company wasn't told this wasn't the original contract Chavez
signed.''
</P>
<P>
   King continued to look at ease, reading during the session and
greeting courtroom guests. During breaks, his roaring laugh was
easily heard. Among his supporters Monday were former Mayor David
Dinkins and Rabbi Shea Hecht, the chairman of the National
Committee for the Furtherance of Jewish Education. Hecht
distributed fliers announcing a dinner in November at which King
would be honored with the committee's humanitarian award.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming was scheduled to finish his statement Tuesday morning,
and then Billy Murphy Jr. would give a summation for Don King
Productions. Baruch Weiss, a second prosecutor, was to deliver the
rebuttal argument.
</P>
<P>
   The jury could begin deliberations Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
