<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERGEN-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERGEN TO BUY UTILITY FOR $1.4 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Powergen PLC, Britain's second-largest generator of electricity,
said Monday that it had agreed to buy East Midlands Electricity for
$1.4 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   East Midlands, one of 12 regional distributors and sellers of
electricity in England and Wales, is being sold by Dominion
Resources Inc., an American utility company, which said it had been
frustrated in its attempts to grow in Britain, even though the
utility industry is being deregulated.
</P>
<P>
   Dominion bought Midland, which serves 2.3 million mostly
residential customers, in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   For Powergen, the acquisition, which also includes the
assumption of $1.8 billion in debt, will help it achieve its goal
of integrating its power business with a distributor. The British
government separated the businesses when it privatized electricity
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Powergen, Edmund Wallis, has said that his
company is looking for an acquisition in the United States.
Industry executives said Monday that Powergen had been in talks
with Houston Industries, a major utility, over a possible merger.
Such a combination would be one of the largest ever in the industry
and the first where a British company was an equal partner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
