<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio man faces music to unusual protesting
 &HT;    By Jennifer Inez Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Carl E. Lenhof, accused of defecating in books at
Miami (Ohio) Valley public libraries will have to pay more than
$500 for the damage and will likely lose his library card.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lenhof pleaded no contest in Dayton Municipal Court
to two counts of criminal damaging and one count of telephone
harassment. He must pay $518 in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 known cases of vandalism centered on books dealing with
homosexuality, the United Nations and the Federal Reserve. The
books were found in the men's toilet or in the book return area in
Dayton, as well as neighboring Kettering, Huber Heights, West
Carrollton, Centerville and Englewood, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dayton's Wright-Patterson Air Force Base, where
Lenhof works as an electrical engineer, said Monday, ``appropriate
action'' will be taken against Lenhof,'' but officials declined to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Greene County Public Library officials said the Yellow Springs
and Beavercreek branches were hit by the vandalism in 1997. Three
books relating to homosexuality were damaged. Officials said they
would seek restitution but not charges.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting Lenhof's plea, Dayton Municipal Judge Bill Littlejohn
said, ``I certainly think he should not go to the library.'' A
sentencing date has not been set. Lenhof faces up to six months in
jail for each count.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton police Detective Dan Hall said the vandalism happened at
libraries between 1994 and1997.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Lenhof nor his attorney, Larry Greger would comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lenhof has worked at the base since 1970. He also owns Verita's
Catholic Books on Burkhardt Road.
</P>
<P>
   Lenhof, 49, of Riverside was originally charged with four counts
of criminal damaging and one count of telephone harassment.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the plea, other municipalities in Montgomery
County will not prosecute him.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Lenhof made harassing phone calls to the Dayton
Lesbian and Gay Center and the Dayton chapter of the National
Organization for Women.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Inez Ward writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
