<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HIGHWAYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Transportation bill brings extra money to Texas
 &HT;    By Debbie Hiott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hoping an early start will mean more highway
money for Texas, state and local leaders vowed Monday to begin
angling for part of $700 million set aside in a national
transportation bill for border infrastructure and trade corridors.
</P>
<P>
   That money comes on top of the $1.9 billion per year the state
already expects for highways in the new six-year bill.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm, in Austin as part of a three-city tour to
discuss state highway needs, urged state leaders to begin pursuing
the trade corridor money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to be successful, we're going to have to do our
homework,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Highway Administrator Ken Wykle said the federal call
for projects will come in the fall. In the Central Texas region,
transportation planners are likely to ask for trade corridor money
to build Texas 130, the 89-mile proposed Interstate 35 alternate
that would run from Interstate 10 in Seguin to I-35 just north of
Georgetown. Supporters say the highway is needed to relieve
congestion on I-35, where traffic has increased 25 percent since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes the drive through Austin one of the busiest
stretches of I-35,'' said Austin Mayor Kirk Watson. ``It is nothing
to brag about when it means we've got more traffic, bigger
congestion and more deaths than any other stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas 130 is expected to cost $1 billion, and although
transportation planners have said it will be a toll road, tolls are
expected to pay only 40 percent of the cost. It will be five to 10
years before it is built.
</P>
<P>
   Although the project has received widespread support from
Central Texas politicians and business leaders, not everyone thinks
Texas 130 will solve traffic problems. While about 200 Texas 130
boosters listened to Watson and Gramm in the state Transportation
Department headquarters, about two dozen people outside protested
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Ascot of Commuter Choices Coalition, a group formed to
opposeTexas 130, said it would rather see the $1 billion spent on
passenger rail, a better bus system and other alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to create sprawl,'' she said. She said Texas 130
won't reduce traffic on I-35 or solve traffic problems created by
the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by state consultants, Texas 130 would
relieve I-35 traffic by 6 to 8 percent downtown. In Williamson
County it would reduce I-35 traffic more than 20 percent. The state
has not said how much Texas 130 would relieve I-35 traffic as a
toll road.
</P>
<P>
   The highway is expected to be built in phases, with the first
phase extending from just north of Georgetown to U.S. 290 east. A
second phase would go through the rest of Travis County, and a
final phase would extend to Seguin.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the highway will be most convenient for Williamson
County residents and will encourage suburban sprawl instead of
Austin's Smart Growth initiative, which seeks to steer growth to
less environmentally sensitive areas. But Watson said Texas 130
will help promote Smart Growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we need to do in order to have Smart Growth
is we need to have infrastructure in the area where you want growth
to occur,'' he said. Watson said Texas 130 will help direct more
growth to the less developed east side of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
