<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STANTON-RIGHTS-ART-10     06-29 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANTON-RIGHTS-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX GENERATIONS OF STALWART WOMEN MARKED BY HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of three generations of Stantons is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By ELIZABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a hot July day in 1848, a frustrated upstate New York
housewife named Elizabeth Cady Stanton assembled a convention in a
Seneca Falls church and made the radical demand that women be
allowed to vote. In that moment, she changed not only American
history but the expectations placed on the next five generations of
women in her own family.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this matrilineal line of descent: Stanton's daughter,
Harriot Blatch, became the chief strategist of the suffrage
movement in New York. Harriot Blatch's daughter, Nora Barney, was
one of the first women to become a civil engineer. Mrs. Barney's
daughter, Rhoda Jenkins, 77, became an architect. Her daughter,
Coline Jenkins-Sahlin, 46, is an elected official in Greenwich,
Conn., and last year helped move a long-forgotten statue of
Stanton, Susan B. Anthony and Lucretia Mott to the U.S. Capitol
Rotunda. Ms. Jenkins-Sahlin's daughter, Elizabeth, 13, has
contributed a chapter about six generations of Stantons in ``33
Things Every Girl Should Know,'' a book for young women published
this year by Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Elizabeth, her mother and grandmother will be among
the descendants of the 1848 participants to celebrate the
convention's 150th anniversary in Seneca Falls. Hillary Rodham
Clinton is to open four days of events with a speech on July 16.
The National Park Service will promote the Women's Rights National
Historical Park in Seneca Falls, and the National Organization for
Women will be there to advance its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But for Elizabeth, her mother and grandmother, the anniversary
is as personal as it is political _ a family reunion under the gaze
of the ``Queenmother,'' as Stanton was called in her old age. On a
recent day in Old Greenwich, at the home of Ms. Jenkins-Sahlin,
they talked about a legacy that both liberated and oppressed, about
complicated mother-daughter relationships, and about a little-known
family history that is also America's.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to know that I'm a descendant,'' Ms.
Jenkins-Sahlin said. ``And if that's meaningful to them, if that's
a means for them to connect to women's history, I will gladly serve
that role. A lot of America does not know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, Rhoda Jenkins, Stanton's great-granddaughter, has
borne the most weight from the past. She is closest to it, of
course, and also may have had the most difficult mother, at least
from her point of view. ``Either you got out of her way, or you
suffered,'' Ms. Jenkins said of her mother, Nora Barney. As for the
specter of her foremothers, she said: ``It was always there. You
had to do your best, you had to be responsible, you had to be
independent. And on and on and on. It was a heavy burden to
carry.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Ms. Jenkins said she would not have become an architect
without the strong women behind her. ``Mother believed in
pushing,'' she said. ``You don't question a hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jenkins was born in July 1920, 18 years after the death of
Stanton, but only a month before the passage of the 19th Amendment
giving women the vote. She grew up in Greenwich, where her mother
designed and built 25 houses. (Ms. Jenkins' father, Morgan Barney,
was a naval architect.) There was a nanny, a governess and a
realization only in Ms. Jenkins' later years that her mother had
been unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always could rely on her to back me up on anything,'' Ms.
Jenkins said. ``But we really didn't have those cozy times that I
read about that other girls had.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda Jenkins graduated from the University of Pennsylvania in
1941 with an architecture degree, worked with her brother building
houses in Greenwich, then married Frederick Jenkins, a landscape
architect, in 1948. She continued working after her children were
born _ a son, Morgan, in 1949 and Coline in 1951. When her husband
died of lung cancer in 1955, Ms. Jenkins struggled.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last things on her mind was women's rights. ``I
didn't really have much time,'' she said. She did not join NOW
until she was in her 70s.
</P>
<P>
   She was determined to rear her daughter in a different way than
her mother had reared her. ``I made an effort not to say, `You've
got to do this,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, Coline, agrees that ``she didn't dominate me.'' At
the same time, she heard very little from her mother about her
history until the family started making trips to Seneca Falls, when
Ms. Jenkins-Sahlin was 18. ``But I had these very strong women
around me,'' Ms. Jenkins-Sahlin said. ``Those were my role models.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jenkins-Sahlin went to public schools in Rye, N.Y., and
graduated from Earlham College in Richmond, Ind., in 1973, well
into the second wave of the women's movement.
</P>
<P>
   She married Gunnar Sahlin, a cellist with the Stockholm
Philharmonic, in 1976, and for the next 12 years lived in Sweden,
where Elizabeth and her brother, Eric, were born.
</P>
<P>
   After the family moved to America in 1988, she became president
of a park preservation group and was elected to Greenwich's
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
   One of her first acts was a resolution that made the language of
the Greenwich government sex-neutral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it unacceptable that a government body can only talk
about `he,''' Ms. Jenkins-Sahlin said. Although her foremothers
would have cheered her on, she said she acted on her own. ``I don't
feel any pressure from them,'' she said. ``But I would love to meet
them. Wouldn't it be great if they could be right here?''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ms. Jenkins-Sahlin has helped found Third Wave
Television, a production company that makes programs on women's
issues. She is also offering her daughter more information on the
family past than she was given _ not least because women's history
is more available now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want her to know things,'' Ms. Jenkins-Sahlin said. ``But I
don't want to push it on her so that she's turned off by it.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems unlikely. ``What they did was very heroic,''
Elizabeth said of her foremothers. ``They went against everything
that was typical of the time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Elizabeth will be in the ninth grade at Greenwich High School
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   She would like to be an architect or an engineer, like her
grandmother and great-grandmother. ``Anything's possible for
anyone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And what would Elizabeth Cady Stanton _ who did not live to see
suffrage _ think of the lives of American women today?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that she would be pretty delighted,'' said Ms.
Jenkins, her great-granddaughter, marveling at the inroads women
have made into fields dominated by men. ``I'm amazed myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
