<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-CHARTER-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS ASSAIL EFFORT TO CHANGE NEW YORK'S CHARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Its first public hearing does not take place until
Wednesday night, but already New York City's newly created Charter
Revision Commission is being criticized by good-government groups
and others as a cynically conceived agency with considerable power
to disturb the balance of government in favor of the panel's
creator, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the strongest blow came Monday in a seven-page letter
from Frederick Schwarz Jr., the chairman of the 1989 charter
commission, the city's last, to the new commission's chairman,
Peter Powers. Schwarz laid out several ``very fundamental
concerns'' about the commission, from the lack of diversity among
its 12 members to its plans to consider eliminating the Office of
the Public Advocate and the Independent Budget Office, both of
which have been critical of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Schwarz expressed outrage that the commission
planned to move rapidly so that it could place charter questions on
November's ballot, apparently to meet the mayor's timetable.
Giuliani created the commission two months ago, primarily as a
means to block another referendum _ on whether tax money should be
spent on building a stadium for the New York Yankees in Manhattan _
from appearing on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor has been quoted as saying a Yankee Stadium
referendum is bad government,'' Schwarz wrote. ``As the old adage
has it, however, two wrongs do not make a right. More
fundamentally, the appointment of your commission with the signal
that it should operate on this truncated and inadequate schedule is
awful government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An improper start will taint whatever this commission attempts
to do,'' wrote Schwarz, a Democrat who rarely enters the city's
political fray.
</P>
<P>
   Powers, a longtime friend of Giuliani's who was his first deputy
mayor, declined to respond specifically to Schwarz's letter. But he
defended the creation of the commission, saying it would examine
legitimate areas of inquiry, from the city's campaign-finance
system to its procurement process. ``If people feel that there's
not a diversity of view, it's all the more reason why they should
stop talking about process and start talking about substantive ways
of how we can change the charter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Giuliani administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, was less diplomatic, dismissing Schwartz's arguments as
``politically charged allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the matters at stake transcend both the mayor's
approval rating and the future home of a baseball team. The City
Charter is the document that lays out the operations of government
and the responsibilities of elected officials. Only twice in the
last 40 years have city officials opened it up for change, which
can only come by public vote.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz and others emphasized that they were not suggesting the
current charter was perfect. But they said Giuliani's approach
smacked of low-level politicking, rather than of lofty ideals.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One point of contention is the makeup of the commission, many of
whose 12 members have direct links to the mayor. Powers was his
first deputy mayor, Paul Crotty his corporation counsel, Howard
Wilson his commissioner of investigation. Vincent Marchiselli, a
former assemblyman from the Bronx, was a member of the Democrats
for Giuliani Committee in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Biderman, who was the commissioner for two agencies
under Mayor Edward Koch, was on Giuliani's transition team in 1993,
as did Herbert Rubin, a longtime lawyer to the Liberal Party.
Rubin's wife, Rose Luttan Rubin, is the chief judge for the city's
Office of Administrative Trials and Hearings, to which she was
appointed by Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be qualified, but you want that commission to have
independence,'' said Eric Lane, a professor at Hofstra Law School
who was the 1989 commission's executive director. ``They're all his
buddies, and many of them have had their only governmental
experience through him.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Schwarz did not question the integrity of the
commission's members, but contended that they did not represent
``the varied viewpoints in our city.'' And he zeroed in on the
events leading up to the panel's creation.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani created the commission in part to block the efforts of
Peter Vallone, the speaker of the City Council, to put a referendum
on the stadium proposal on November's ballot; according to city
law, a charter-related question takes precedence over other ballot
questions. The mayor's move reflected both his continuing problems
with the council and his opinion that Vallone, a Democrat, was
pushing the referendum to increase voter turnout when he is running
for governor.
</P>
<P>
   But Schwarz recalled that only a few months ago, Giuliani had
said that he saw no immediate need for charter revision. He
expressed outrage that the commission plans to hold five public
hearings, all at night and in early July, to meet time limits for
placing one or more questions on this fall's ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
