<HEADER>
A2941 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-argentina-england-HNS     06-29 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-argentina-england </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
No love lost as England, Argentina prepare to vie
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MONTPELLIER, France _ Between the ``Hand of God'' and the long arm
of the law, today's Argentina-England World Cup elimination match
figures to reach out and touch an array of emotional subjects.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of them are bitter _ the Falkland Islands War,
troublemaking hooligans, South American and European soccer pride
and memories of a crucial Argentine goal that probably should not
have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a massive game for both countries,'' English coach
Glenn Hoddle said. ``Both teams want this game very much.''
</P>
<P>
   For numerous reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First, there are the 12-year-old painfully hard feelings that
remain from the last time these soccer powers met at the 1986 World
Cup in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It was then when Argentine great Diego Maradona made a pair of
spectacular goals to eliminate England and took a huge step toward
becoming the soccer legend he is today.
</P>
<P>
   Maradona's second goal in that game, the eventual game-winner in
Argentina's 2-1 victory, remains one of the most spectacular in
World Cup history, a brilliant zig-zagging play during which
numerous English players tried to snag the ball, only to see
Maradona rocket in a score.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the first of Maradona's goals that was dubbed the
``Hand of God'' goal, after everyone in the stadium except the
referee saw Maradona help the ball into the net with his fist.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the game if he used his hand on the attempted
header, Maradona responded, ``It was the hand of God.''
</P>
<P>
   The English, including Hoddle, who played in the game, still
consider it a crime.
</P>
<P>
   One English newspaper bannered the headline, ``We can forget
(Falklands) war, but never Maradona.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very important game for everyone, and the way it was
won by Argentina left a sour taste in the mouth,'' Hoddle said.
``It was a tight game until that handball, which turned the
situation completely. This game has given us the chance to address
the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The game, which will be played at Stade Geoffroy-Guichard in
well-fortified Saint-Etienne, has so many other themes involved,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Fans from both soccer-loving nations began streaming into
Saint-Etienne on Monday, only to find a large security presence and
more bans on alcohol sales or consumption because of the hooligans
who follow the English team.
</P>
<P>
   Fans also found few tickets available, as barely more than 2,000
were allocated to each nation.
</P>
<P>
   World Cup organizers appear to be taking few chances in this
critical game, which spokesman Keith Cooper described as a
potential ``flash point'' for violence because of all the factors
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The 1982 Falkland Islands War involving Argentina and England
remains a bitter issue between the nations. Then there is the
matter of World Cup survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans will consider anything less than a place in the final
game as a failure,'' Argentine star Gabriel Batistuta said. ``And
they would be right. We need this game. We cannot lose to
England.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hoddle: ``We have a chance to right a 12-year wrong. That
feeling of injustice has stayed with us a long time. This game can
help us get that out of our system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0541 </DOCNO>
