<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-ADDRESSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BLOW IT UP? JUST TRY TO FIND IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All kidding aside, the mayor's much-maligned crisis
center is brilliantly conceived, and not just because it will be
bulletproof and bomb resistant. The genius is in its location: 7
World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   No terrorists will ever find the place. Or at least darned few
will. And if they come from out of town, forget it. Even New
Yorkers who work in that section of lower Manhattan have trouble
locating the building, which is actually on Vesey Street, across
from the main trade center complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's down there somewhere,'' said a woman on a smoking break
at Vesey and Church streets. She pointed vaguely in the direction
of the trade center. ``But I can't tell you which one it is.''
</P>
<P>
   She was hardly alone. Asked on Vesey Street how to get to 7
World Trade Center (``practice'' not being an acceptable answer),
one man shrugged, a young woman pointed the wrong way and a hot-dog
vendor jerked his head toward 5 World Trade Center. Some people got
it right. But the odds of a bum steer were exceptionally high.
</P>
<P>
   That will reassure anyone worried about the security of
officials who will take to the ``emergency control center'' when
disaster strikes. To others, though, it is a reminder of how
confusing it can be to get around certain neighborhoods, where many
buildings have highfalutin addresses that say nothing about where
they really are.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever tried to get to the Park Avenue Atrium? Its
address is 237 Park Ave., but there is no way to enter it from
Park. It is on Lexington Avenue, near East 46th Street. Park Avenue
Atrium just sounds ritzier than Lexington Avenue Atrium.
</P>
<P>
   Even weirder is 1325 Ave. of the Americas, which isn't within
shooting distance of that avenue. It is much closer to Seventh
Avenue, with entrances on West 53rd and 54th streets.
</P>
<P>
   If you can guess correctly where New York Plaza is, give
yourself a cigar. It is bounded by Whitehall, South, Water and
Broad Streets. Wall Street Plaza is not on Wall Street. It is the
fancy name for 88 Pine St. Even some workers at the post office's
Wall Street station, two blocks away, draw blanks when asked where
it is. You might think that 2 Times Square is in Times Square. Not
a chance. It sits on Duffy Square, a few blocks north.
</P>
<P>
   For near insanity, nothing tops a cluster of buildings around
Pennsylvania Station that bear Penn Plaza addresses. You
practically need a Sherpa guide to get around. Some buildings are
on Seventh Avenue, others on Eighth Avenue and still others on side
streets. Can someone please explain how No. 5 Penn Plaza came to be
two and a half blocks from No. 4?
</P>
<P>
   You may want a stiff drink after trying to pinpoint all 79 sites
designated ``plazas'' in Manhattan alone. But there is no mystery
to how the confusion came about.
</P>
<P>
   Developers love having these so-called vanity addresses. They
produce more tenants, which is good for the owners, and higher
rents, which is even better. That is nowhere more self-evident than
in pricey Manhattan. During the go-go 1980s, the borough
president's office, which had the final say, was more than willing
to play along. So were the emergency services, as long as they were
notified of changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These addresses promote value and image, no question about
it,'' said Robert Emden, executive managing director of Grubb &AMP;
Ellis, commercial real-estate brokers in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Messinger, the unsuccessful Democratic candidate for mayor
last year, tried to halt the vanity giveaways after she became
Manhattan borough president in 1990. ``They were making life in the
city harder and harder,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she always prevailed. Witness an apartment building
that the owners chose to call 62 West 62nd St. It is east of 44
West 62nd, even though the logic of West Side numbering says that
No. 62 should be west of No. 44. ``We begged them to change it,''
Messinger said, arguing both safety and common sense. But the
developers, who liked the symmetry of 62 West 62nd, held their
ground and won in court.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, it is comforting to think about would-be
burglars being so confused by the illogical numbering that they
give up in despair. Similarly, you have to smile at the idea of
terrorist jackanapes thinking they can ever master this city enough
to find the mayor's downtown crisis center.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, aren't you surprised to have read this far without
hearing it called a bunker?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
