<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE SAYS HE WANTS TO REMAIN A YANKEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Cone sat between dozens of fans on a bench
beside some softball diamonds in Central Park on Monday, stressing
that he wants to stay with the Yankees even after the guaranteed
portion of his three-year contract ends this season.
</P>
<P>
   If Cone tosses 200 innings in 1998, he could exercise the $5.5
million option or become a free agent. If the pitcher does not, the
Yankees will pay a $1.5 million option and let him go or try to
sign him for a lesser amount. Cone conceded that if he reaches 200
innings, and he is on pace to pitch exactly 200, his baseball
address will not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be hard to say anything else,'' Cone said. ``It's
obvious I enjoy playing here. I've settled here. I'm developing
charitable activities here. I think it's pretty obvious where my
heart lies. I can't think of a better situation to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a blue T-shirt, tan shorts and a maroon baseball cap,
Cone looked like just another New Yorker. That is the way he wants
it. It is one reason Cone was in the park sponsoring his charity
softball tournament on his first scheduled day off in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   So even though Cone is pitching against the Phillies at Yankee
Stadium on Tuesday night and even though it would have been very
easy to punch the snooze button at 8 a.m. Monday, the 35-year-old
pitcher who embodies New York more than any other Yankee was
signing thousands of autographs, answering hundreds of questions
and watching dozens of players who paid $1,000 each to hang out
with major leaguers for a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect fit to have a softball tournament that could
benefit a lot of charities and Central Park,'' Cone said. ``That's
about as New York as you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Cone, David's wife, added: ``If he's not back here, it's
not going to be by his choice. I think you can safely say he wants
to finish his career here.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Brian Cashman called Cone ``special'' and
bluntly said: ``In terms of the future, he has an option and we'd
love for him to stay. I got to believe he'll get the 200 innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of David Wells, Hideki Irabu and Orlando
Hernandez, who all have guaranteed contracts for 1999, and Andy
Pettitte and Ramiro Mendoza, two 26-year-olds who will be important
next season, Cashman said Cone is a major part of New York's plans.
</P>
<P>
   The general manager said there is a chance Cone and the Yankees
could announce later this season that they have agreed for him to
return in 1999 and erase the uncertainty over the 200 innings
trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're expecting David to be here,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Cone wondered if his career was finished. Lynn
revealed that David painfully lifted his right arm up near his
shoulder one day, grimaced and spoke of retirement after he had
been battered for 16 runs in his first two starts. But when she was
asked if her husband, who is 10-1 with a 3.36 earned run average in
his last 12 starts, is still pondering retirement, Lynn said ``Not
this minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre voted for bringing Cone back by saying, ``I think he's
at the point where he's proven it health-wise so now he can do it
for a few more years.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Levy, the vice president of Cone's foundation, said
Monday's event was expected to raise around $100,000 with the cash
going to the Baseball Assistance Team, the Central Park
Conservancy, the City Parks Foundation and the Children's Hospital
at Westchester Medical Center. Cone wants to hold a tournament
annually, which would be much easier if he is pitching in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 200 innings is significant because if I reach that
level,'' Cone said. ``I can control my own destiny. Obviously, it's
very important for me to stay here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
