<HEADLINE>
RESTAURATEUR ENDS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Warner LeRoy, the owner of Tavern on the Green, has
withdrawn his lawsuit against the restaurateur David Bouley, and
their partnership in Bouley Bakery and several other projects in
TriBeCa has been dissolved. LeRoy, who had accused Bouley of
misappropriating money, reached an agreement with him on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The terms were not announced, but the agreement will leave
Bouley, one of the city's most respected chefs, the sole owner of
the Bouley Bakery and other projects in TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   The former partners have signed a confidentiality agreement,
Bouley said. A spokeswoman said LeRoy had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   LeRoy was seeking more than $4 million for his share of the
partnership, for which he paid $2 million. Bouley and LeRoy also
dissolved their partnership in the Russian Tea Room restoration,
Bouley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great because now we can go our separate ways and be
more productive,'' Bouley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bouley is negotiating with Credit Suisse Bank for a $25 million
loan to finance the projects, which include Danube, a Viennese
restaurant, a cooking school and Restaurant Bouley. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
