<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WELFARE-FRAUD-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINETY ARE CHARGED IN WELFARE-FRAUD SCHEMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Government workers created identities for as many as
50 nonexistent children to bilk the welfare system, prosecutors
said Monday, announcing that the workers were among 90 people
caught up in ongoing investigations of welfare fraud in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 90 people charged by prosecutors in Manhattan, 14 are
government workers. In many cases, welfare workers filed phony
records in exchange for kickbacks from welfare recipients, and the
workers typically kept 80 percent of the money, leaving just a
small amount for the applicants, said the Manhattan district
attorney, Robert Morgenthau.
</P>
<P>
   All told, those charged stole more than $1.3 million from the
city's welfare system by creating fake cases and collecting
payments for the nonexistent children, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's case was the 11th prosecution resulting from regular
inquiries of welfare and housing assistance that the City
Department of Investigation has conducted over the last three
years. Edward Kuriansky, the city commissioner of investigation,
said the inquiries have resulted in the arrests of 622 people,
including 200 city employees, and involved the theft of $8.2
million in welfare and tenant subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Although the amount of theft represents a relatively small
portion of welfare payments _ the City Human Resources
Administration said it paid out $159 million in May alone _
Kuriansky said it showed how a small number of people could do a
lot of damage to the city treasury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost a case history in how much damage a few bad
apples can do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kuriansky also noted that only a tiny percentage of the city's
welfare cases involved fraud. The welfare office involved in
Monday's charges _ the Dyckman Income Support Center in Inwood in
Upper Manhattan _ processed between 15,000 and 16,000 cases each
year, he said, but only 80 resulted in these prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutions are part of an overall city effort to tighten
supervision of welfare programs, an effort that includes such
measures as the fingerprinting of welfare recipients to prevent
people from applying for benefits twice, a practice known as double
dipping.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday announcing the charges, Morgenthau
said the cases were important because fraud undermines an important
city program vital to helping the poor. ``What we are trying to do
here is protect the welfare system from fraud,'' Morgenthau said.
``It is an effort to protect the welfare system for people who need
it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, prosecutors described two schemes that
they say operated at the Dyckman Center. The first involved the
city's Fair Hearing program, in which welfare recipients seeking
extra money can challenge the amount they are paid.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Human Resources Administration workers at the
center filed false papers claiming that welfare recipients had won
Fair Hearing settlements, even though hearings had never been held.
They said that six current and three former Human Resources workers
were charged with carrying out the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Kuriansky said the fraud was uncovered after investigators
received a tip in 1995 that led to other arrests at the Dyckman
Center. He said that investigators discovered the fraudulent Fair
Hearing claims in part by checking whether hearings had actually
been held. Prosecutors said the hearing scheme was conducted
between 1992 and 1996 and cost the city $575,000.
</P>
<P>
   The second scheme, prosecutors said, involved the creation of
the false case files. They said that three Human Resources
employees used false birth certificates to open files on behalf of
several welfare recipients. In one case, prosecutors said, a woman
collected welfare while living in the Dominican Republic, and in
another the money was used to pay for a face lift. Many of the fake
files were opened in the names of children who did not exist, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the second scheme, which lasted from 1988 to
March of this year, cost the city $776,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kuriansky said the people involved in the scheme varied the
names of recipients and used different reasons to justify the
payments.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   City welfare officials have made efforts to change the system to
prevent similar frauds, Kuriansky said. Among the efforts are new
computer systems intended to find large or unusual payments to
welfare recipients, fingerprint checks to prevent people from
applying for duplicate benefits, and cross-checks by internal
auditors to insure that cases are not fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would likely prohibit and prevent something like this from
happening in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kuriansky said that investigators have recommended that the
Human Resources Administration tighten a potential loophole. He
said that while adult welfare recipients are now fingerprinted
before they can receive benefits, guardians of children who receive
payments on behalf of those children are not required to be
fingerprinted. Kuriansky said that only one person should be
allowed to claim benefits for a single child.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Human Resources Administration said it is
now studying whether it should make the change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
