<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEMS-SENATE-RACE-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS DIFFER SHARPLY IN SENATE PRIMARY DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. _ Sharing a stage for the first time in
this campaign, the three Democratic candidates for Senate tangled
Monday over their allegiance to the tobacco industry, fund-raising
tactics and how President Clinton should deal with China.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates _ Geraldine Ferraro, Mark Green and Charles
Schumer _ struggled to keep the focus on the Republican incumbent,
Alfonse D'Amato, and avoid the recriminations that marred the
Democratic contest six years ago. But with just one more debate
scheduled until the weekend before the Sept. 15 primary, the stakes
here were significant, and the candidates' attempts at cordiality
slipped more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Green questioned Ferraro's judgment in accepting a $20,000
speaking fee from a tobacco company. Ferraro responded by accusing
Green of taking a contribution from a tobacco industry ($50, as it
turned out), and complained about Schumer's aggressive fund-raising
effort. And the three candidates differed on some substantive
issues, including the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges came in a free-flowing debate sponsored by the New
York State Broadcasters Association at the Sagamore Hotel, a
picturesque retreat on Lake George. The hourlong late-morning
session was moderated by Gabe Pressman of WNBC-TV in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, the 1984 vice presidential nominee, who is the
best-known of the candidates and has a strong lead in most polls,
has repeatedly declined attempts by her lesser-known colleagues to
get her to share a stage with them. The debate she agreed to Monday
seemed unlikely to win particularly widespread attention. It was
situated in a relatively remote part of New York, almost 90 minutes
by car from Albany, and it was not broadcast on television.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the clashes among the Democrats were provoked by Green,
the New York City public advocate, who has less money than either
Schumer, a congressman who represents Brooklyn and Queens, or
Ferraro, and thus was arguably under the most pressure to make the
most out this setting.
</P>
<P>
   In one notable exchange, Green attacked Ferraro for accepting
$20,000 to speak before a symposium sponsored by Philip Morris Co.
in Palm Beach, Fla., last year, when she worked as a commentator on
Crossfire, the CNN program. ``I really hope that Geraldine would
rethink the honorarium and give the money back,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro defended the fee, saying it had not prevented her from
supporting tough measures aimed at tobacco companies in Congress.
``Mark, I have no intention of giving the money back,'' Ferraro
said. ``As you well know, I paid taxes on it. And high taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, seeking to turn the tobacco tables on Green, she said:
``Mark, you've taken money from an officer of Philip Morris during
your public advocate campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's that?'' Green said, sitting upright in one of four easy
chairs that had been set up on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro glanced down to the second row of the audience, where a
press aide was sitting between her husband, John Zaccaro and her
campaign manager, David Eichenbaum. ``Amanda, can _ '' but Green
cut off her attempt to seek assistance: ``No, no, no, no,
Geraldine.''
</P>
<P>
   After the debate, Eichenbaum identified the Philip Morris
executive as David Dangoor, an executive vice president who he said
had contributed $50, a minimal contribution by today's standards,
to Green's campaign in 1993. Green said he did not know Dangoor,
and would return the $50 if Ferraro returned the $20,000 she
received.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates were unified in attacking what they said were the
shortcomings of D'Amato, whom they described as conservative,
politically dishonest and a creature of his contributors. And all
three signaled that they would focus on D'Amato's opposition to
abortion rights.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I am going to take the issue of choice to Al D'Amato and show
the voters of New York he's an extremist,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro said: ``He has even supported a constitutional amendment
to ban abortion under all circumstances, even when the life of a
mother is at stake. That is an issue, I have to tell you, that
Republican women are looking at and saying, `There is no way that
we're going to allow this man to take that right away.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats disagreed with one another _ and with Clinton _ on
how the United States should handle China. Schumer said Clinton
should not have visited Tiananmen Square. ``There was such a brutal
massacre that I think you could draw the line and show the Chinese,
yes I want to come, yes I want to engage you, but there are certain
things you should not do.''
</P>
<P>
   And Green said he did not think the United States should
continue awarding China most-favored-nation trade status, given the
country's human-rights record. Both Schumer and Ferraro endorsed
Clinton's position that it would be an economic and political
mistake to exclude China from world trade markets.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also clashed on the death penalty. Green, taking
a position that is historically popular in Democratic primaries in
New York and drawing a distinction between himself and his two
opponents, strongly argued against capital punishment. ``I don't
believe it deters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer found himself defending what he has presented as one of
the bigger triumphs of his campaign: his aggressive fund raising.
He asserted he needed to counteract Ferraro's name recognition and
the fact that Green spent $2 million during an effectively
uncontested bid for re-election as public advocate last year.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who is a member of the Banking Committee, said ``very
little'' of that money came from banking interests. But Ferraro
asserted she had firsthand knowledge that Schumer was soliciting
from those sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be quite frank, the reason I know that is if I call up and
say, `Hey listen, I'd love you to get involved in my campaign,'
they say, `I can't. D'Amato is on the Banking Committee. Schumer is
on the Banking Committee. I can't give to you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Ferraro said in response to a question that the campaign
had followed a generally high road so far. Pressman looked startled
at her response, and reminded Ferraro that she had called her
rivals ``liars'' two weeks ago for denying they had strong-armed
delegates at the Democratic state convention. He asked if she was
rescinding it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know if I take that back,'' Ferraro said. ``I am
saying that that's behind us. I may have been a little tired
then.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Ferraro said it was possible she would agree to
further encounters, she also said she did not view such sessions
either as an efficient use of her time or enlightening to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you that I ran for vice president of the United
States, in case anyone forgot,'' Ferraro after the debate,
referring to 1984, when she was the running-mate of Walter Mondale.
``You know how many debates I had with George Bush? One.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
