<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOXGROUP-BUY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX IPO WOULD GIVE INVESTORS SHOT AT PIECE OF ENTERTAINMENT PIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ News Corp.'s decision to sell a minority ownership
in its Fox franchise gives investors the chance to directly own a
major entertainment firm without unrelated assets clouding the
offering, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pure play,'' said Steve Cesinger, managing director of
Greif &AMP; Co., an investment banker in Los Angeles. ``Investors may
be interested in the programming and content (of Fox) in the U.S.,
not Murdoch's newspapers in Europe and the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In a ``pure play,'' investors buy into a company in which its
core operations are in one market or category. In this case, it
would be entertainment content.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street cheered the news, driving News Corp.'s American
depository reciepts up 3 9/16 to 33 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   American depository receipts, or ADRs, are certificates traded
in a U.S. exchange to represent securities of a foreign company.
They are issued by U.S. banks to represent a certain amount of
foreign securities they hold in the foreign entity's country of
origin. ADRs make trading foreign securities in the U.S. easier by
eliminating currency exchanges, among other hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox offering likely won't be an ADR, since it represents
American operations and the subsidiary probably will be based in
the United States, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Australia-based News Corp. said it will offer to the
public its Fox Group, consisting of its U.S. filmed entertainment,
TV programming and distribution, and sports team assets. Twentieth
Century Fox, the Fox Television Group and the Los Angeles Dodgers,
among other entities, would fall under this umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 20 percent of the Fox Group will be offered to investors
in an initial public offering expected to debut on Wall Street by
the end of the year. News Corp. expects to register a filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission within three months, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the offering _ such as what price the shares will
trade at, or how many shares will be offered _ won't be available
until the filing.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp.'s plan is for an equity offering, not a spin-off,
which AT&AMP;T did with Lucent. In a spin-off, the parent company
distributes all or most of its shares of the subsidiary to its
existing stockholders. It's usually accompanied by an IPO, where
new shares are issued and sold. The subsidiary becomes a separately
traded company.
</P>
<P>
   By making the IPO announcement without an SEC filing, News Corp.
is likely testing the investment community's interest in its Fox
franchise at a time when the IPO market is lackluster from too many
offerings, said Tom Taulli, a market analyst at IPO Monitor, a Los
Angeles-area online IPO tracking service.
</P>
<P>
   If the offering is successful, analysts think that Murdoch might
consider spinning off Fox and going public with News Corp.'s other
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no guarantee that the Fox IPO will be received well,
despite its household name, Taulli said. Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's IPO
didn't perform well because of its debt load, even though the movie
studio has a well-known brand name. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980629.0551 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-CARL-NYT &LR;      06-29 0570
