<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-STOCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS STOCKS OFTEN BENCH PLAYERS RATHER THAN STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So you want to own a piece of the L.A. Dodgers but
are disappointed ``Ally McBeal'' comes with them? Consider yourself
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Sports teams that are packaged with other businesses _ as News
Corp. intends to do with the Los Angeles Dodgers baseball team and
the rest of its Fox Group division _ generally are a better value
for investors than sports franchises standing alone in the
marketplace, said analysts surveyed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the performance of the Boston Celtics LP, now a stock
market veteran, and the Cleveland Indians Baseball Co. Inc., a
newcomer to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, it turns out, has been much of a bargain for investors
as both are trading well below their 52-week highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one common denominator you find when a sports team goes
public is that the investors (in) the IPO don't make a lot of
money. The owner of the company makes a lot of money,'' said Mark
Cunningham, analyst for SQC Research Duke in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason, as in the case of the Celtics and Indians, is
that initial investors buy on emotion rather than sound finances,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Celtics went public in 1987 they valued the franchise
at $120 million and they have just announced a private transaction
that I think values the Celtics at $150 million. So over 10 years
it's not a very good investment,'' said Peter A. Russ, an analyst
at Laidlaw Global Securities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Deals that work out better for all concerned have business lines
other than sports.
</P>
<P>
   For example, The Walt Disney Co. and Time Warner Inc. are
trading near their 52-week high. Disney owns the Anaheim Mighty
Ducks hockey team and Anaheim Angels baseball team; Time Warner
owns the Atlanta Braves baseball and Hawks basketball teams.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to prove that the Angels' and Braves'
performances on the field have helped push their parent companies'
shares up. Then again, both teams are broadcast on cable channels
owned by their parent companies, and first-place teams like the
Angels and Braves draw more viewers, which increases revenue.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of diversity serves investors better, said Harry
Vinezia, an analyst at Raymond James who follows the Florida
Panthers Holdings Inc., owners of the Panthers pro hockey team and
some other properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Panthers were first a public company it was just the
Panthers,'' he said. ``But since they have diversified into lodging
and the restaurant industry, it has definitely helped the stock.
And it make the company more viable because it smooths out the cash
flow streams and takes some of the operating risk out of the
company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2320EDT &QL; 
