<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-29 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3097 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USNEWS-FALLOWS-NYT &LR;      06-29 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USNEWS-FALLOWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITOR OF U.S. NEWS &AMP; WORLD REPORT FIRED
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Fallows, the editor of U.S. News &AMP; World Report, said
Monday he was fired Monday by the magazine's owner, Mortimer
Zuckerman, after less than two years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued later in the day by the magazine's editorial
director, Harold Evans, confirmed the dismissal but gave no reasons
for it and announced that Fallows would be replaced by Stephen G.
Smith, editor of National Journal, a Washington weekly that
specializes in government and politics.
</P>
<P>
   In a 19-page memorandum that Fallows read aloud to his staff
Monday morning, he said, ``Mort Zuckerman has decided that I should
leave the magazine and that a new editor should come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallows, who declined to be interviewed, said Zuckerman was
seeking a change in direction at the magazine and that the two men
had fundamental differences over news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Fallows cited as an example the shooting death of the fashion
designer Gianni Versace. (Zuckerman felt it was given too few
pages, Fallows said in his memo.)
</P>
<P>
   ``While I do not think he has a good reason for making this
change,'' Fallows wrote, ``clearly he has the right.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the maneuvering at the magazine, Fallows issued a
clarifying statement later in the day, saying that Zuckerman
``would like it to be made clear that, on the issue of who is
responsible for deciding that I should leave the magazine, Harry
Evans has full authority to make that decision, and the choice was
in fact ultimately his.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans has an interest in establishing his authority at the
magazine. Since he stepped down as president and publisher of
Random House's trade group last fall, amid speculation that he had
been forced out, people in the media industry have been wondering
what the once high-profile Evans had been up to.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Noah, an editor at U.S. News, called Evans ``a
papier-mache boss'' who is ``frantically trying to look like he's
not taking orders from Mort.''
</P>
<P>
   But Evans emphasized Monday that he was the one in control of
the Fallows situation. ``It was my responsibility and it was my
decision,'' he said in an interview. ``I don't want to get into
details about it, but I thought it was time for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans also sent a memo to the staff reminding them that he has
responsibility for hiring and firing.
</P>
<P>
   Zuckerman, backed up his deputy. ``It's Harry's job and its
Harry's responsibility and it's Harry's authority,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fallows, 48, came to U.S. News in September 1996 from The
Atlantic Monthly, where he was Washington editor. His appointment
got the attention of the industry, in part, because of his book,
``Breaking the News: How the Media Undermined American Democracy,''
which was highly critical of the media and because he began his
tenure by making some controversial staff changes.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was his decision to remove political columnist
Stephen Roberts, whom he had criticized for using his position to
generate large speaking fees.
</P>
<P>
   Under Fallows, the magazine's struggle for a niche became more
intense, given the greater resources and later press times of its
competitors, Time and Newsweek. (U.S. News has a circulation of
about 2.2 million; Newsweek, 3.2 million and Time, 4.2 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Fallows' memorandum read in part as a defense of his record at
U.S. News, praising various aspects of the magazine's look and
coverage. ``I am tremendously proud of what we have accomplished,
and I hope you are too,'' he wrote. ``This magazine is better than
it was two years ago, and you deserve the credit _ and my lasting
gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Before becoming editor of National Journal, Smith was the
founding editor of Civilization Magazine. He has also served as
executive editor of Newsweek, held various editorial posts at Time
magazine and worked at several newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to improve the format and the design,'' Smith said
Monday. ``Give the magazine more pace, crop photographs a little
more boldly and run more boxes and shorter stories _ that way I
think we can better gain the attention of our readers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
