<SLUG> BC-NY-STATE-REP-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY VENDETTA ALLEGED BY DEFENSE FOR ASSEMBLYMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The federal corruption case against Assemblyman Dov
Hikind of Brooklyn originated with city investigators who were
pursuing a Giuliani administration vendetta against Hikind and a
social services group, a defense lawyer contended in court Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hikind, D-Borough Park, is charged in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn with illegally seeking and receiving payoffs from leaders
of the group, the Council of Jewish Organizations of Borough Park,
in return for obtaining hundreds of thousands of dollars in state
funds for the group. The 15-year veteran of the Assembly is accused
of taking at least $40,000 from the government grants that had been
given to the group, which is widely known as COJO.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments are to begin Tuesday in the trial after six
weeks of testimony. The Borough Park group's former employment and
training director, Rabbi Elimelech Naiman, is also a defendant in
the case. Like Hikind, Naiman, who is charged with fraud and other
offenses, has insisted he committed no crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The contention that the prosecution was born of hostility in
City Hall was made by Naiman's lawyer, Benjamin Brafman, who sought
unsuccessfully to call as a witness a city lawyer who had worked on
the case in its initial stages.
</P>
<P>
   Brafman told Judge Charles Sifton that he needed to call the
lawyer, Susan Ross, of the city's Department of Investigation,
because she had ``unique information'' that the initial decision to
pursue the case was ``politically motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Investigation under the current mayor of New
York City, because COJO had become too powerful, marked it for
extinction,'' Brafman asserted. He maintained that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and a top aide, whom he did not identify, ``openly spoke
of this as the end of the reign of Dov Hikind and COJO.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's press secretary, Colleen Roche, later responded that
Brafman's statements had ``no basis in fact.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really unfortunate and sad that such arguments are made
in desperation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sifton rejected Brafman's request to call Ms. Ross, saying that
the kind of information he was seeking from her would more
appropriately have been sought in pretrial discovery proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Brafman suggested in court that he knew about the purported
conversation from several Giuliani administration aides whom he
said he had interviewed but who, ``because of fear of losing their
jobs, could not come into court to testify.'' Later Brafman
declined to elaborate on his statements in court.
</P>
<P>
   Hikind's supporters have maintained that although the
assemblyman had backed the Republican mayor in his races for City
Hall in 1989 and 1993, Hikind fell out of favor with the Giuliani
administration when he supported George Pataki, another Republican,
for governor in 1994. Giuliani backed the Democratic incumbent,
Mario Cuomo, in that election.
</P>
<P>
   Hikind is accused of receiving the COJO funds in the form of
payments for items like tuition for his children and other
relatives, family trips abroad and campaign and fund-raising
activities. Sifton on Monday narrowed the charges against him by
dismissing some of the conspiracy and fraud counts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
