<HEADLINE>
JUDGE BLOCKS N.J. LAW BANNING SEX BOOKS FROM JAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ New Jersey's broad, new law banning sexually
oriented books, photographs and films from a prison for sex
offenders remained in legal limbo Monday after a federal judge
again refused to let the state enforce it and called the measure's
constitutionality into question.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Alfred Wolin, in Newark, declined to issue a
final opinion on the law, saying he wanted to give the state
attorney general's office a second chance to argue its merits. But
calling the law too broad and vague, Wolin said the burden the
state faces in convincing him of its constitutionality ``appears to
be insurmountable.''
</P>
<P>
   The law's ``plain language mandates that certain everyday
literature would be banned'' from the prison, the Adult Diagnostic
and Treatment Center in Avenel, Wolin said. Monday's decision
extends a temporary halt to the law imposed June 1 by the judge,
who said he agreed with contentions in a suit filed by two inmates
that the law would prevent them from reading the Bible and fashion
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Avenel's 750 inmates have committed sex crimes at least
twice and been classified by judges as ``repetitive and
compulsive'' offenders. The state maintains that sexually oriented
material hinders the rehabilitation of the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   But in his opinion, Wolin said a literal reading of the law
would give prison administrators the authority to ban newspapers
with sexually suggestive advertisements or copies of ``National
Geographic'' that had photographs of bare-breasted women.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Peter Verniero said he was disappointed that
Wolin had blocked enforcement of the law for a second time.
Verniero said his staff remained convinced of the law's merits and
constitutionality. The judge set a hearing for July 20 for new
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Lustberg, the court-appointed lawyer for the inmates,
called Wolin's opinion a ``terrific victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It vindicates our argument that this is unjustifiable
censorship,'' Lustberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Commissioner Jack Terhune declined to comment
because the case is still pending, said a spokeswoman, Julia
Marian-Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Materials banned by the law, passed last January, include those
containing ``any description, narrative account, display, or
depiction of sexual activity or associated anatomical area.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolin contended Monday that the law was inspired more by
``outraged'' legislators than by concern about rehabilitation. He
noted that Avenel administrators officially opposed the law before
Governor Christie Whitman signed it.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Avenel's director of psychology, Nancy
Graffin, did not testify before the Legislature about the law and
did not know the statute existed until May, one month before it was
to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates who filed the lawsuit, Richard Waterman and Michael
Curtis, are both repeat offenders. Waterman is serving a 54-year
term for sexually abusing a 9-year-old girl and had earlier been
convicted of raping an 11-year-old and fondling another 9-year-old
girl. Curtis is serving 20 years for sexually abusing a 14-year-old
boy and had been convicted in Arizona of sexually assaulting a
15-year-old boy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
