<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGER ADMITS USING VIRUS TO STEAL COMPUTER PASSWORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A teen-age computer hacker pleaded guilty in
Manhattan federal court on Monday to stealing more than 500
passwords from America Online users last year.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that the teen-ager, referred to in court papers
as John Doe, had obtained the passwords by sending e-mail messages
to America Online subscribers from February through April.
</P>
<P>
   When the clients clicked on an attachment included with the
message, a computer virus known as a Trojan horse, because it
cloaks its true purpose, was activated and secretly recorded the
users' keystrokes, including their passwords, said Mary Jo White,
the U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The passwords were then forwarded by the virus program to an
e-mail account that the teen-ager held under a false identity on
Juno, a Manhattan-based Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   It did not appear that the teen-ager was able to, or attempted
to, profit from his work. Credit cards numbers were not taken, and
thus no merchandise was purchased with them over the Internet, said
Tricia Primrose, a spokeswoman for America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager was charged with unlawful interception of
electronic communication, a felony, but because of his age he
pleaded guilty to an act of juvenile delinquency. Normally, the
sentence for that crime is six months' probation, according to
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers with the U.S. attorney's office declined to discuss the
specifics of the case, citing confidentiality. They did say,
however, that the boy had obtained the computer program used to get
the passwords through a person he had met on line.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager's lawyer declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said
that the teen-ager had been caught by the federal authorities with
the help of Juno, which alerted the authorities when the teen-ager
called into his account. The call was subsequently traced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
