A3109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-BUDGET-525&AMP;ADD-NYT     06-29 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BUDGET-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY GOVERNOR IN DEAL TO RAISE GAS TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Overcoming opposition from some Republican
lawmakers reluctant to raise taxes, Gov. Christie Whitman reached
agreement with legislative leaders Monday to increase the state's
gasoline tax gradually _ 4 cents a gallon over three years _ to
help pay for transportation projects around the state.
</P>
<P>
   The tax increase is 3 cents less a gallon than what Whitman
proposed in May. Two of those cents would have gone toward
preserving a million acres of farmland and open space, nearly half
the undeveloped land left in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers are now considering another proposal to ask voters
whether they would support a plan to borrow $1 billion over 30
years for preserving open space. The other proposed 1-cent increase
would have been spent on transportation projects.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists would not see the full impact of the 4-cent-a-gallon
gasoline tax at the pumps all at once. Under the plan, the gasoline
tax would rise by 1 cent next year, 2 cents the following year and
1 cent more in the year 2001. The increase would be contingent on
voters' approval of a referendum in November, which would ask them
whether they supported a gasoline tax increase and whether they
approved dedicating all motor vehicle tax revenues to
transportation projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this is the right thing to do,'' said the
Assembly speaker, Jack Collins, R-Salem County. ``I am sure that
this will be a bipartisan effort.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement on the gasoline tax increase came as both the
Assembly and the Senate gave final approval to a new $18.2 billion
state budget for the new fiscal year beginning July 1. The budget
raises spending by almost $1 billion over this year for public
schools, state colleges and a handful of other programs. And it
puts $661 million aside for the state's rainy day fund.
</P>
<P>
   With the gasoline tax increase, the Whitman administration
expects to spend $200 million more on transportation projects in
the next two years than had been budgeted.
</P>
<P>
   The increase would allow the state to pay the higher borrowing
costs for expanding the state's Transportation Trust Fund, the
system used to finance highway and mass transit projects.
Administration officials said spending would rise to $900 million
from $700 million in 1999 and 2000. It would increase to $950
million annually in the following three years.
</P>
<P>
   After lawmakers rejected the 2-cent-a-gallon increase for
open-space preservation, Whitman continued to push for a
5-cent-a-gallon increase for transportation projects. But
lawmakers, particularly Republican members of the General Assembly
who face re-election next year, balked at raising taxes while the
state's economic boom was pouring extra revenues into the state's
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plan will produce about $400 million less in
estimated new revenues from the gasoline tax than what the
administration first proposed, her aides said that the
4-cent-a-gallon increase would meet the administration's
transportation goals. ``It works,'' said Pete McDonough, a
spokesman for the governor. ``We can get a program large enough to
meet the needs of the state.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Collins said the Legislature would return in late July to
consider the gasoline tax increase. At the end of three years, it
would raise state taxes on gasoline to 18.5 cents a gallon from
14.5 cents. Collins also said the Legislature would consider two
other bills, asking voters to dedicate motor vehicle tax revenues
for transportation projects and support the 30-year borrowing plan
to preserve a million acres of farmland and other open space.
</P>
<P>
   The state budget, which Whitman is expected to sign into law on
Tuesday, was approved by the Legislature with bipartisan support
for the first time in almost a decade. Democrats were able to share
some of the budget surplus with their Republican colleagues for
various projects in their legislative districts. The total spending
was $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats voted against the budget because of language
that the Whitman administration had quietly inserted that would
establish a state-appointed fiscal review board to oversee the city
of Camden's finances. The city is looking for a $15 million bailout
from the state to balance its books, and the administration insists
the money would only be allocated if a state-run financial review
board is in place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
