r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAIL-AZR &LR;      06-29 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAIL SUIT DROPPED BY FEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DENNIS WAGNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sheriff Joe Arpaio declared victory Monday over the
federal government after Justice Department attorneys ended a
three-year probe of Maricopa County jails by dropping a lawsuit
over inmate abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Although a dismissal motion says the case was terminated only
after the sheriff complied with jail improvements required in a
settlement, Arpaio said the action proves that prisoners never were
victims of systemic mistreatment, as alleged in the lawsuit and a
government study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to put up with this for three years. Three years!'' the
sheriff said. ``Over what? It's been dismissed . . . Evidently, all
these allegations that have been going on for three years were not
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers in Washington, D.C., declined comment
on any aspect of the case, including what steps were taken to
determine that jail conditions had improved.
</P>
<P>
   The civil complaint was filed in U.S. District Court here in
October, along with a settlement agreement which said the case
would be dropped if Arpaio lived up to numerous reform promises for
six months.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleged not only that inmates were subjected to
mistreatment, but that sheriff's officials were ``deliberately
indifferent'' to it. The lawsuit also said Arpaio's administration
failed to discipline abusive jailers.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Arpaio and his staff insisted that dropping the case
is a tacit admission by Justice Department officials that there
never was wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio said the lengthy investigation was spawned by his
enemies, and amounted to a ``free consulting study'' that wasted
taxpayer money. He said there are occasional problems in the county
jails, but that he deals with those himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need the Justice Department or Civil Liberties Union
or Amnesty International or the Boy Scouts to come down here and
try to accuse my people,'' Arpaio said. ``If you wanna get the
sheriff, go after the sheriff. Don't take on my employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio's public information staff trumpeted the development in a
news release with the headline: ``Justice is done. Jail brutality
claims unfounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack McIntyre, an attorney with the Sheriff's Office, proclaimed
that allegations of systemic abuse were ``thoroughly repudiated.''
</P>
<P>
   When the lawsuit was filed, Janet Napolitano, then-U.S. attorney
for Arizona, characterized it as a legal formality, while Arpaio
vowed that nothing would change his management of the jails.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the motion for dismissal claims there have been substantial
jail improvements in use-of-force policies, booking operations,
Tent City conditions, grievance procedures, staffing and training,
among other things.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement agreement required all of those changes, along
with a ban on hog-tying inmates, using restraint chairs as
punishment, and using pepper spray or stun devices except on
combative prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Closure of the case ends a federal investigation that began in
August 1995 and included two evaluations of jail operations.
</P>
<P>
   Correctional expert Eugene Miller's review led Justice
Department lawyers to allege that inmates were victims of violence
without justification, in some cases after they had been handcuffed
or placed in restraint chairs.
</P>
<P>
   After Arpaio condemned that report, the Justice Department hired
George Sullivan _ another expert on incarcerations _ to review jail
conditions. Sullivan also wrote a critical report, leading to the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the investigation, Arpaio insisted that his office
appropriately dealt with isolated instances of mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's officials pointed out that one of Sullivan's major
criticisms _ the arming of all guards with pepper spray or taser
devices _ was part of a project funded by the Justice Department.
They also said reforms listed in the court case were in place
before the lawsuit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the use-of-force case is resolved, medical and mental
health care within the jails remain under a federal investigation. &QL; 
Dennis Wagner can be reached at 444-8874 or at
dennis.wagner(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
