<HEADLINE>
METS STRUGGLING TO RECAPTURE MAGIC OF '97 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets are still gamely chasing the Atlanta Braves
in the National League East and are just a step or two behind the
San Francisco Giants in the race for the National League wild-card
berth. Yet while both teams present tantalizing targets, the team
the Mets most want to emulate right now is none other than the 1997
version of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are 43-34 heading into Tuesday night's inter-league
contest against the Blue Jays in Toronto, the same record the '97
club carried into its 78th game. That team stood 6{ games behind
Atlanta after going 43-34. This year's club is 7{ games out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the perception seems to be that the Mets are struggling to
get back the magic of a year ago, when the `97 club generated its
own special excitement despite often sparse turnouts at Shea
Stadium. The Mets of a year ago led the majors with 47
come-from-behind victories. They also won 24 games in their final
at-bat, equaling the major league best.
</P>
<P>
   Such moxie assured the franchise a winning season (88-74) for
the first time since 1990. It also set a standard, one the 1998
club sometimes seems to struggle to meet, despite similar
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Take Sunday night's victory over the visiting Yankees. The Mets,
playing in a nationally televised game, won when the club's hottest
hitter, Carlos Baerga, opened the ninth inning with a double off
reliever Ramiro Mendoza. Butch Huskey, unaccustomed to having to
bunt, did so with great efficiency, moving Baerga to third. After
Brian McRae drew an intentional walk, Luis Lopez delivered a
game-winning sacrifice fly, Baerga scoring before the meandering
McRae was nearly doubled off first base.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the 11th time this season the Mets had won in their
final at-bat. Yet the number of such victories was overshadowed by
the club's desperate need to avoid a three-game sweep at the hands
of the cross-town rivals. That the victory also left the Mets
practically begging for more late comebacks showed how they are
frantic to recreate the magic touch of a year ago, not only in
reality, but perception as the team searches for its own identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much us beating the Yankees in the third game,''
said Huskey. ``It was more us not losing three games in a row.
These were three big games and those guys have experience over
there, they've experienced big games a lot. A lot of our guys
haven't. So a lot of our guys had a lot of adrenaline rushing. It's
just something we've got to control better. And the only way you
get experience with that is being in the atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the architects of the victory _ Baerga and reliever
Dennis Cook _ have the ability to show younger Mets how to get to
the next level. For Baerga, somnambulant at the plate early this
season but now batting .283, is a veteran from the winning
Cleveland Indians teams of the mid-1990s. Cook helped the Florida
Marlins win a World Series title last year.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga not only scored the game's winning run, but drove in the
Mets' first run, with a sixth-inning single. That hit was the Mets'
first off the all-but-untouchable Yankees' rookie, Orlando
Hernandez, giving the team a chance to live on until the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Another chance was provided by Cook, who remains the one
reliable reliever to set up closer John Franco. Cook, assigned to
stop the horde of Yankees' left-handed power hitters, threw two
scoreless innings, striking out three, enabling the Mets to remain
in a 1-1 tie until the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   In his last 18 games the left-handed veteran has allowed only
one earned run in 181/3 innings, lowering his earned run average
from 4.76 to 2.10. That not only gives Bobby Valentine a legitimate
response to teams that feature left-handed threats, like the
Yankees' Paul O'Neill, Tino Martinez and Darryl Strawberry. It
gives the manager a choice in tough situations, something the
struggling Mel Rojas doesn't often present.
</P>
</TEXT>
