<HEADLINE>
POLICE REPORTS PROBED IN SHOOTING OF SQUEEGEE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Police Department is investigating
whether some of the detectives who worked on the case of an
off-duty police officer accused of shooting a ``squeegee man'' in
the Bronx skewed their reports to make the shooting appear
justifiable, police officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry focuses on whether the first detectives on the scene
of the June 14 shooting tried to cover up for the officer, Michael
Meyer, by suggesting that he had fired his gun because he was being
robbed by the squeegee man, Antoine Reid, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives from the Internal Affairs Bureau took over the case
later that night and arrested Meyer on a charge of second-degree
attempted murder, saying that he had fired without provocation
after Reid put soap on his windshield without permission.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Internal Affairs Bureau is investigating why the police
reports written by some of the first detectives on the scene
contain statements by witnesses who talk about the possibility of a
robbery attempt, but the reports written by the Internal Affairs
detectives who took over the case do not, officials said. The
internal investigation was first reported in The Daily News Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a police spokeswoman, said that Internal Affairs
began its investigation last week. ``The issue is the reports and
if there is a bias in the reports,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said in an interview a few days after the shooting that
Meyer first raised the issue of robbery right after shooting him in
the chest. ``He walked, picked up my squeegee and said: `See,
everybody? He tried to rob me,''' Reid said. He said two women who
had witnessed the shooting and had come to his aid, holding his
hands, did not believe the charge. ``They said: `Aw, get out of
here. He ain't try to rob you. You just shot him,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was released from the hospital on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry began as the department announced that it would help
federal prosecutors investigate accusations that police officers
had perjured themselves and colluded to protect a colleague, a
former officer, Francis Livoti, who was convicted last week in U.S.
District Court of violating the civil rights of a Bronx man who
died in his custody in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
