<HEADLINE>
GM JOB SHOULD NOT HURT LASORDA'S HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Dodgers internist Michael Mellman wasn't
consulted when Tom Lasorda was given the stress-filled general
manager's position less than two years after being sidelined with a
heart condition. But Lasorda has the blessing of Mellman, who
monitored the former manager during two angioplasty procedures in
1996 that helped eliminate blockage in the arteries leading to the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy had a heart problem, but it has been treated and he is
well enough for his new assignment,'' Mellman said. ``The general
manager's position can be taxing, but it is far different than the
manager, who is closely involved with every pitch in each game. If
a GM is on the road and doesn't feel good, he can stay at the
hotel. The manager can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, who turns 71 in September, underwent a routine physical
exam just days before taking over for fired executive vice
president Fred Claire. Mellman said Lasorda's blood pressure and
cholesterol levels were normal. Mellman also points out that
Lasorda resumed traveling after undergoing a second angioplasty
during the 1996 National League Division series between the Dodgers
and Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking over for Claire, Lasorda traveled extensively
throughout the Dodgers' minor-league system evaluating talent. He
also maintained his rigorous schedule of charity and motivational
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has bounced back well,'' Mellman said. ``A second and even
a third angioplasty is not uncommon, but Tommy appears to be past
all that. I am very pleased with the condition he is in. The road
can be a tough place, but Tommy has made some good adjustments in
his life.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Gonzalez on pace: Rangers outfielder Juan Gonzalez leads the
majors with 96 RBI in 81 games, 26 more than any other player in
the American League. Gonzalez has the second-most RBI in
major-league history before the All-Star break. Detroit's Hank
Greenberg had 103 in 76 games in 1935. After 81 games, Greenberg
had 108. Amazingly, he did not make the All-Star team, missing out
behind Lou Gehrig and Jimmie Foxx.
</P>
<P>
   The AL-record for RBI in a season is 184 by Gehrig in 1934. The
major-league record is 190 by Hack Wilson in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick hits: Right fielder Gary Sheffield accompanied the club
here after having the cut on his left eye examined before the 11
a.m. flight. Sheffield, injured in Sunday night's bench-clearing
brawl with Pittsburgh, has been cleared to play tonight....
Shortstop Jose Vizcaino underwent an MRI exam Monday on his
severely sprained right ankle. The test confirmed a ligament tear
and he will wear a soft cast for a week. Vizcaino, who complained
of increased swelling and pain in the ankle Sunday after appearing
to make progress, hopes to be back after the All-Star break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
