<HEADLINE>
FIRED TEACHER STUNNED AT CHURCH-STATE FUROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MACARENA HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Almost three weeks after she was fired for asking
children in her Bronx classroom if they had accepted Jesus as their
Saviour, Mildred Rosario says she is stunned to find herself at the
center of a national debate over the division between church and
state.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed Sunday at her pastor's office in her Pentecostal
church in East Harlem, Mrs. Rosario, 43, said she never expected
that her response to a student's question about a schoolmate's
recent death would cause such a furor. Discussion of her case has
moved from her principal's office to City Hall, where Mayor Rudolph
W. Giuliani spoke on her behalf, to Congress, where Rep. Tom Delay,
R-Texas, the majority whip, spoke in her favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did was console my students,'' said Mrs. Rosario, who
was fired June 12 from her job as a sixth-grade bilingual teacher
at Intermediate School 74 in the Bronx. ``I answered my students'
questions and they have treated me worse than a criminal. I do not
regret what I did because God is going to give me the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Rosario, who lives in Manhattan, has filed a grievance with
her union, the United Federation of Teachers, challenging her
dismissal. On Friday, she and a union delegate met with a
representative of the superintendent's office to discuss her case,
and a union spokesman said Monday that a decision was expected this
week.
</P>
<P>
   She does not believe that what she did was wrong, she said. She
is aware of the school's policy against proselytizing, she said,
but feels obligated to talk about her faith when asked. ``To talk
about God is something else,'' she said. ``I did not talk about
religion. I don't know why the Board of Education is mixing one
thing with another. I respect all religions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, Mrs. Rosario and her husband, Hector, sat
unnoticed in the third-to-last row of the small Pentecostal church,
Abrigo del Altisimo, which they have attended for three years. When
a congregant took requests for prayers, Mrs. Rosario was the last
to raise her hand. Unlike most congregants, who asked for prayers
for the ill or the needy, Mrs. Rosario did not say anything. But
after all the requests were in and the prayers began, the
congregant leading the prayer asked God to give strength to Mrs.
Rosario.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began when a student and her guardian complained
about Mrs. Rosario's leading her class in prayer, asking if anyone
wanted to accept Jesus and laying hands on some children.
</P>
<P>
   The principal, Leroy Johnson, saw her action as a clear-cut
violation of the ban on proselytizing by teachers. ``Mrs. Rosario
comes up as the martyr and here is this little girl who has
different beliefs and she is terrified,'' Johnson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As is her habit, Mrs. Rosario met her arriving students outside
the school the morning of June 8 and walked with them to the
classroom, she said. She had not yet taken attendance when the
principal asked over the intercom for a moment of silence in memory
of Christopher Lee, a fifth grader who had drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the first question, from Luisa Corporan, 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is Christopher Lee?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``In heaven,'' Mrs. Rosario said she answered.
</P>
<P>
   Students followed with more questions about God and heaven. But
before proceeding, Mrs. Rosario said, she had announced that anyone
who did not want to listen could read a book or use the computers
in the back of the room.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving the complaint, Johnson scheduled a meeting the
following day with Mrs. Rosario, the girl and her guardian, who is
her sister-in-law. Mrs. Rosario said she asked them for
forgiveness, which they granted. She believes that the matter
should have ended there, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson asked Mrs. Rosario to write down her account of what
had happened in the classroom. She said she took the questioning
personally and felt that school officials were making fun of her
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took away my job,'' she said. ``But the joy I feel inside
because I am saved and my name from the book of life, that they
can't take away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
