<HEADLINE>
NRC GIVES FINAL APPROVAL TO RESTART OF REACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (lb) 
 By JONATHAN RABINOVITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Millstone Unit 3, a nuclear reactor in
southeastern Connecticut, is scheduled to begin transmitting
electricity by Thursday after more than two years of being barred
from operating by federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The unit is the largest of three reactors at the Millstone
Nuclear Power Station, which the Nuclear Regulatory Commission shut
down in late 1995 and early 1996 because of safety concerns. While
the other two units still are not allowed to operate, the federal
commissioners gave a preliminary approval earlier this month for
Unit 3 to restart, and on Monday it received the commission's final
blessing.
</P>
<P>
   That decision is a marked turnabout from the plant's problems of
a few years ago, which produced a fine of $2.1 million, the largest
in the history of the U.S. nuclear power industry.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Utilities, the company that operates Millstone, was
forced to take steps to ensure that it would act upon workers'
safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's commission announcement comes at a critical moment for
Connecticut and western Massachusetts, which rely on Northeast
Utilities for most of their electricity. July is when demand for
power reaches its peak, and the utility's difficulty during last
week's heat indicated that it may have trouble meeting its
customers' needs without the electricity provided by Millstone.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Brothers, the Millstone Station vice president of
operations, said the Unit 3 reactor would be started Tuesday at
noon. It would take at least 24 hours to heat up enough to provide
electricity, but he added that the company planned to take it
``slow and easy'' and probably not start transmitting electricity
until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, the unit will be at roughly 30 percent of capacity,
said Terrence McIntosh, a company spokesman. The reactor is not
expected to reach full power for two to five weeks, according to a
statement from Northeast Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of Northeast Utilities said Monday that federal
regulators were letting the reactor begin operating before all of
its problems had been resolved. They contended that the unit lacked
adequate fire prevention barriers and had flaws in the system that
detects damage to the nuclear core.
</P>
<P>
   But Diane Screnci, a federal commission spokeswoman, said the
agency had determined that the reactor could be operated safely
before it issued Monday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The approval was announced early Monday afternoon over the
public address system at the plant, and employees gathered in the
yard outside the unit to celebrate. Cake and coffee were served in
the cafeteria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
