<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CAMPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOMERS HAVE A NEW CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
Hello Muddah, 
Hello Faddah. 
Here I am at 
Camp Granada.'' 
!dtpost!!bold!_Allan Sherman, from his No. 2 hit song of 1963!off! 
!by1! By  Dave Shelburne  
!by2!Daily News Staff Writer !dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   In their youth, the early members of the baby boomer generation
might have spent their summers at some Camp Granada, scribbling
postcards to mom and dad.
</P>
<P>
   Now charging into and through their 50s en masse, those same
front-rankers have hardly given up on camping because of a few
emerging wrinkles. They've just replaced a paddle and lake with a
golf club and water hazard, often in a spectacular location. And
they don't limit themselves to the summertime.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, baby boomers and others had the opportunity for
extended, comprehensive instruction on a near-year-round basis at
270 locations in 44 states, according to ShawGuides, which
publishes an annual listing of nationwide golf and tennis camps.
</P>
<P>
   More than 750 campers have gone through one- to three-day
schools since October at PGA West, where the Jim McLean Golf School
is enjoying booming business in its first full year of operation on
the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a monster year there,'' said McLean, the 1994 PGA
teacher of the year who estimated another 5,000-6,000 golfers have
attended McClean School clinics at PGA West.
</P>
<P>
   Camp isn't cheap, even at summer-in-the-desert rates, which run
from $300 per person for a one-day school to $1,250 for the
three-day players school, which is the most popular and where
McLean students get to play on the course with their instructor two
of the three days.
</P>
<P>
   But, on a hourly basis, the cost of camp instruction is not a
whole lot more than golfers would pay over a similar period of time
in weekly lessons at their neighborhood driving range. And,
arguably, instruction in one chunk of time, offering the
opportunity for reinforcement and repetition under guidance, might
be a better investment than the newest mega-titanium,
Godzilla-sized driver _ or even a whole new set of woods and irons.
</P>
<P>
   Dorlene Kaplan of ShawGuides, which is conducting a reaction
survey of golf campers, said early response has been mostly
favorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most felt they came away with lasting results, and even the
ones who thought they didn't learn that much said they had a great
time,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Students at a recent three-day McLean camp seemed to like it.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Slinkard, owner of a manufacturers rep firm in Nashville,
was happy with the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facilities were awesome,'' he said. ``You had all the
quality practice balls you wanted. I think my pro could pick things
out in my swing just by glancing at it and tell me what I was doing
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Kolts of Danbury, Conn., who attended the same school,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with their ability in a very short period of
time to hone in on everybody's individual problem areas, or areas
where we needed improvement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McLean camps start with videotape analysis, in which the camera
shows the students the difference ``between feel and real,'' as
instructor Debra Chaumillon puts it. From that tape, instructors
zero in on specific areas _ the problems the students knew they had
and, often, ones the tape reveals to them for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of each school, students are shown an ``after'' tape
of themselves, often with notable improvement.
</P>
<P>
   McLean looks for instructors who not only can teach but can also
play the game. And they have to follow a basic philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be successful in a golf-school business, you have to have
all your instructors on the same page,'' he said. ``You just can't
be teaching different things and you can't confuse the student. But
there is a lot of room for individuality.'''
</P>
<P>
   All of his instructors look at a golf swing through its various
positions or steps. McLean is noted for his eight-step approach.
They find what's broken the most and fix it _ most of the time
without too much rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to have people work on their weakness, then help them
in those areas,'' said McLean, whose schools _ also based in
Florida and Michigan _ attract players of all levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim has a reputation for teaching tour players and good
players,'' said Greg Vincent, managing director of the McLean
Group. ``But the bulk of our business is teaching beginners and
higher-handicap players. In the last couple of years we've seen a
lot of beginners come into the game, and as golf schools have
become more popular, people realize that's a quick and easy way to
immerse themselves in the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-98 2359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
